<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS NOT WORRIED ABOUT 0-4 PRESEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith once
had a television commercial built around the theme, ``the real work
begins in the preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement is about as obsolete around the Cowboys' Valley
Ranch training complex these days as Smith's defunct shoe deal with
Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   To the Cowboys, 0-4 in the preseason this year and 1-13 in
preseason games since 1998, only the regular season matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's that critical,'' Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman said. ``There is not a big carryover once you go into the
regular season with regards to what your record was in the
preseason. The last time we had a winning record in the preseason
was in 1989, and we went 1-15 (in the regular season). We've had
losing records (in the preseason) and won Super Bowls.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys coach Dave Campo, ``What we've done in the
preseason means absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning in the preseason may not be important, but playing well
is.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys' starters on both sides of the ball have yet to
produce a performance they can be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Their play bottomed out in the game against the Broncos on
Saturday night, when Cowboys starters were dominated 24-6 in the
first half of an eventual 36-23 setback.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys failed to convert in the red zone and had trouble
stopping both the run and the pass, and after the game players
questioned their preparation and the coaches questioned the
players' focus.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make you assume that the Cowboys would point to
the preseason finale against the St. Louis Rams on Thursday to make
amends and build confidence.
</P>
<P>
   You would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, who said he overreacted after the Broncos game, said
Monday that the starters will make only a brief appearance against
the Rams. He said they are gearing up for the regular-season opener
against the Philadelphia Eagles on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two weeks we are going to zero in on the players who
will win for us,'' Campo said. ``And we want to get our legs back.
The next two weeks we are going to back off the hitting and make
sure we are not going too long in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   That begs the question: How can the Cowboys be confident that
they will be ready for the opener?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their middling play, the Cowboys have been unable
to develop cohesion on offense because of injuries and a retirement
threat. Smith (strained calf) and tight end David LaFleur (strained
groin) have not played in the preseason and will miss the Rams
game. Fullback Robert Thomas (sprained knee) will miss his second
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Tackle Erik Williams, who missed four weeks of training camp
while contemplating retirement, will play for the first time
against the Rams. Solomon Page, who had replaced Williams at
tackle, will play guard, meaning that the Cowboys' starting
offensive line will play together for the first time, albeit
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of questions at cornerback, where embattled
rookie Kareem Larrimore is starting in place of the departed Kevin
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, who claims no team has continuity in the preseason,
believes the Cowboys will be ready because ``I know these guys. I
know what they are made of. If we are healthy, we are going to be
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Campo said the Cowboys' first-team units have shown
enough, despite the absences, to foster confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that if you looked at our first units and you took
a poll around the league, they'd say we're going to have a pretty
good football team. That's what I'm looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Campo be looking through rose-colored glasses? He
acknowledges as much, but adds that ``the film doesn't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the problems the Cowboys had with discipline and
technique against the Broncos (read: Larrimore) will be corrected
before the Philadelphia game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the heat of the battle, players tend to revert back to bad
technique,'' Campo said. ``That's our job to make sure they do
things right. We will be more disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said Larrimore's struggles have an upside because it will
help him understand ``that we know a little more about this than he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said Larrimore's play will be improved by a better pass
rush, which he feels the Cowboys will get with a healthy Leon Lett
in the lineup. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
