<HEADLINE>
KICK RETURNER HALL AMONG COWBOYS CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Darran Hall left his heart _ and his future with
the Dallas Cowboys _ in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who fumbled the first two kickoffs and bobbled a punt in
the Broncos' 36-23 victory Saturday, was one of 13 players released
by the Cowboys on Monday. The Cowboys' roster now stands at 73
players. They must make two moves by 3 p.m. Tuesday to reach their
maximum of 71, which includes roster exemptions for NFL Europe
players Chris Akins, Stephen Fisher, Duane Hawthorne, Michael Lies,
Ryan Neufeld and Jeff Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have given us a lot of their time and effort out
there on the field. It's a tough situation,'' Cowboys vice
president Stephen Jones said. ``There are a lot of things that go
into cuts. You're always trying to develop players, so it's always
tough. A guy like Darran Hall is a philosophical decision. Do you
cut a player because his skill is big plays but at the same time he
can make big plays that can hurt you? Those are tough decisions
that you have to go through, but we're very comfortable with where
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The misfortune of those put on the waiver wire could be good
news for others.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free agent Micah Knorr will be the team's opening-day
punter after Barry Cantrell was released. Knorr has averaged 41.8
yards on 16 punts.
</P>
<P>
   First-year safety Jason Kaiser was released, which could open a
spot for Chris Akins to make the roster on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Third-year linebacker Brandon Tolbert, who tore his left
anterior cruciate ligament against the Broncos, will be placed on
injured reserve once he clears waivers. Tolbert was trying to
return after tearing his right anterior cruciate ligament during
the Cowboys' 1999 training camp. ELLIS FEELING GOOD
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Greg Ellis' road to recovery continued in Denver
when he saw his first game action since fracturing his left tibia
and fibula in a Dec. 12 game against the Philadelphia Eagles. Ellis
said Monday that his leg ``feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with the progress that he made,'' Cowboys
coach Dave Campo said. ``He played actually a little bit more than
I thought he was going to play. He wanted to play more. He felt
very good. He said he started thinking about the leg a little bit
early, but after the first three or four plays, he was his old
self. He's not where he needs to be football-shape-wise. Obviously,
the practice and playing a little bit in this next ballgame will
give him an opportunity to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who had 59 tackles, 7.5 sacks and 17 quarterback
pressures last season, said he will not rush his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't play as much as I did last year, I don't think,
especially in the early part of the season,'' he said. ``I'll play
a whole lot this year, I think, but probably not as much as last
year.'' SAFETY FIRST
</P>
<P>
   Third-year safety Izell Reese spent eight months rehabilitating
from surgery to repair a herniated disk in his neck only to strain
a calf muscle the first week of training camp. Saturday night
against the Broncos, he saw his first game action since Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having that calf injury kind of offset it, and I
didn't really think about my neck surgery or anything,'' Reese
said. ``I was able to stick my head in there a couple of times and
didn't have any problems. I feel confident about it, and I feel
healthy, so that's a good thing.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the Cowboys' moves Tuesday could be placing cornerback
Kevin Smith on the reserved/retired list. Smith, a nine-year
veteran, left the team two weeks ago to contemplate retirement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie cornerbacks Dwayne Goodrich (strained left hamstring)
and Mario Edwards (strained hamstring) are doubtful for Thursday
against the St. Louis Rams, Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right tackle Erik Williams, who reported to training camp last
week, will make his preseason debut against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys are no closer to signing former New York Giants
cornerback Phillipi Sparks than they were two weeks ago when Sparks
told them he would stay retired rather than return for the $440,000
minimum.
COWBOYS CUTS OL Chris Brymer
</P>
<P>
   P Barry Cantrell
</P>
<P>
   WR Drew Cone
</P>
<P>
   OG J.R. Conrad
</P>
<P>
   DE Kendrick Gholston
</P>
<P>
   WR Darran Hall
</P>
<P>
   TE Lawrence Hart
</P>
<P>
   TE J.J. Huggins
</P>
<P>
   DT Keith Jackson
</P>
<P>
   S Jason Kaiser
</P>
<P>
   OT Steve Scifres
</P>
<P>
   OT Chad Slaughter
</P>
