<SLUG> BC-GEN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JOCK KINGDOM, SAVING FACE TAKES THREE EASY STEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In today's jock kingdom, it's a shrink's paradise. No matter how
twisted, troubled or dense the player might be, help is always
available of the cerebral kind, provided by kindly team owners who
are attempting to head off the dreaded late-night phone call.
</P>
<P>
   But as you know, repeated image disasters with players still
happen. The best of counseling and information can save some but
not all. At times, a good bail bondsman and defense lawyer are as
valuable in sports as any hitting coach who taught Gabe Kapler the
leg kick.
</P>
<P>
   What is obviously missing in the jock kingdom, however, is the
``disaster specialist.'' On the executive level of the NFL,
baseball, the NBA, the NHL, etc., it's been all about overwhelming
our jock friends with preemptive-type information. Don't do this,
don't do that, and if you ever even consider doing this or doing
that, then call this number immediately. Which is fine, except what
happens after they are charged with still having done this or that,
despite all the warnings?
</P>
<P>
   Beating a rap in the court of law might prove to be impossible,
but in the long run, even the greatest of jocks, should he screw
up, will have to answer to the court of public opinion. It is much
more powerful and damning than the legal end, but also much more
forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   This message is too late for Michael Irvin, who has now blown
two careers. And also too late for the likes of Pete Rose and Leon
Lett, not to mention Roy Tarpley. What these guys needed was a
``disaster coach.'' For a minimal fee, I would have served as such,
with a money-back guarantee that each would win in the
all-important court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   All other jocks, however, should immediately listen up. You
never know when this info might come in very handy. Remember one
thing: The fans are always eager to forgive you, provided, of
course, they think you can still help the team win. Third-string
running backs should not expect much success, but for that star
jock in trouble, here's the simple three-step plan to return to
grace:
</P>
<P>
   (1) Immediately call a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Start your statement in serious tones, but then begin to
break down, emotionally. Cry real tears. This is very important.
Cry freely. Throw in a few sobs.
</P>
<P>
   (3) Deny everything, and threaten to sue. Or, maybe even better,
confess to everything, then apologize for that drug problem,
drinking problem, gambling problem, etc., that was caused by an
abusive upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, this stuff never fails. Your fans will still be
your fans, and even new fans will climb aboard your bandwagon. In
fact, this week there was yet another success story involving the
foolproof three-step plan. Denver Broncos linebacker Bill
Romanowski, come on down, give us your testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were awesome, incredible,'' said the Bronco known as
``Romo,'' after an exhibition game against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some of us Mile High Stadium press-box visitors
Saturday night, drowsy with anticipation of another NFL exhibition
encounter to sit through, were snapped out of a slumber by the
mighty howl from 69,000-plus throats during pregame introductions.
Had John Elway shown up, announcing he had unretired? No, it was
just Romo's name being called on the P.A. system.
</P>
<P>
   It had been such a bad week for the veteran headhunter who is
considered one of the NFL's dirtiest players, although it's the
same in any city; dirty only applies if he's playing for the other
team.
</P>
<P>
   But a bad summer for Romanowski got worse last week. If the
federal indictment for illegally obtaining diet pills didn't taint
Romo as a speed freak, along comes an unnamed former teammate being
quoted in ``Sports Illustrated'' as saying Romanowski used racial
statements. Something about this being a white guy who ``speeded''
for a supposed edge on the field against the black guys, except
Romo wasn't quoted as saying ``black guys.'' Granted, that's
cold-blooded for a publication to print such a thing without giving
the speaker's name, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Romo was caught in a firestorm. So how did he handle it? The
wise way, of course. He called a news conference, he cried, he
denied everything, and then threatened to sue ``SI''. After all
that, Denver welcomed him Saturday night like the season's first
snowfall on the ski slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Given this latest case, I thought of Michael, and him always
being too proud or too cool to ``work'' the court of public
opinion. And nobody could have pulled it off better than Irvin,
because Irvin is smart that way. Very smart when it comes to media
dealings. He might even have saved the Fox gig with just three easy
little steps. But no ...
</P>
<P>
   Michael will always have that
full-length-fur-coat-in-the-courtroom mentality, except now look
where that coolness got him. Go to Pete Rose _ if he had confessed
to the obvious on gambling 10 years ago, and done so under the
three-step procedure, Pete would long ago have Charlie Hustled his
way into Cooperstown. Instead, Rose has become a national fool.
</P>
<P>
   When in trouble in the jock kingdom, the solution is so simple.
For crying out loud, why are there those who still don't understand
what to do? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
