<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHR     08-22 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WOULD YOU LOOK AT WHO'S GOT THE JUICE _ THE POWER COMPANIES  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it revenge of the nerds.
</P>
<P>
   Big, boring electric and gas utilities _ once given up for dead
_ are this year's hottest stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to falling interest rates and rolling power outages, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's utilities index, which includes companies such as
PG&AMP;E and Enron, is up 35 percent, year to date.
</P>
<P>
   And the worst performing sector?
</P>
<P>
   Telecom service providers. The S&AMP;P communications services
index, which tracks long-distance, local and cellular carriers, is
down 26 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This has created an unusual situation for utility mutual funds,
which invest in two types of stocks _ this year's winners and this
year's losers.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, utility funds invested almost exclusively in
dividend-paying electric utilities. They were designed for the
proverbial widows and orphans _ people who needed a stable income
and no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   But as the telecommunications industry was deregulated, many
utility funds began buying not just Baby Bells but also
fast-growing, unregulated long-distance and wireless carriers and
even cell-phonemakers such as Nokia and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   One utility-fund manager justified an investment in AOL by
defining a utility as anything you use daily and pay for monthly.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, that strategy paid off, and telecom-heavy
utility funds beat power-hungry ones hands down.
</P>
<P>
   But that started to change in March of this year.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nasdaq crashed, investors started looking for stocks
that looked safe and undervalued. Staring them in the face were
electric utilities, which were laughably cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electric companies are still viewed as bond equivalents,''
says John Kohli, manager of the Franklin Utilities fund.
``Historically, the dividend yield (annual dividend divided by
share price) on a utility stock has been 80 to 90 percent of the
yield on 10-year Treasury bonds.'' But in early March, utilities
were yielding 6.5 percent _ or 103 percent of the 6.4 percent
Treasury-bond rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a greater yield buying electric utility stocks than
10-year Treasuries,'' Kohli says. ``That had never occurred in 30
years of looking at electric utilities.''
</P>
<P>
   So investors began buying utility stocks. That drove share
prices up and yields _ which move in the opposite direction _ down.
Today, utility yields are back to normal _ about 85 percent of the
Treasury rate.
</P>
<P>
   But utility stocks still look inexpensive by some measures.
``Traditionally, the group has grown 2 to 3 percent a year, but
analysts now expect earnings growth of 7 percent over the next five
years,'' Kohli says. The companies in the S&AMP;P 500 are expected to
grow a shade faster, at 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But utility stocks are trading at 12.5 times earnings, while the
S&AMP;P 500 is trading at 26 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   With the S&AMP;P 500, ``you're paying more than twice as much for 1
percent greater earnings growth,'' says Kohli.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of this year, electric utilities earned
21.4 percent more on average than they did in the first half of
last year. Earnings for the S&AMP;P 500 companies were up only 17.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the utilities' earnings have come from power generation
_ or more specifically, from a lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, as energy deregulation created a lot of
uncertainty, utility companies were reluctant to build new power
plants because they weren't sure how they'd pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, strong economic growth pushed demand to record
levels. Today, there is barely enough power to meet demand, and the
result has been temporary power outages and soaring energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad news for consumers, but good news for utility
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Given the speed at which new power plants are built in this
country, the supply/demand imbalance is not going to change
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Paulsen, chief investment officer for Wells Capital
Management, thinks there's another, more traditional reason to buy
utility stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities have always been interest-rate sensitive _ when
interest rates go down _ utility stocks go up, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Once the markets concluded that the Federal Reserve was finished
raising interest rates, at least until after the presidential
elections, investors decided it was safe to buy utility stocks
again.
</P>
<P>
   Paulsen sees interest rates going even lower, which means
utilities could go even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from an intense period of inflation fear to a
soft-landing euphoria. Eventually we'll move right through the
euphoria and people will start to say, ``Oops, we've overdone it.
We're heading into a recession,'' he says. ``Utilities are good
soft-landing and `oops-recession' stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all utilities will do well. As deregulation
unfolds, there will be winners and losers, just as there were in
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some utilities are scrambling to get into e-commerce
and other promising, but unproven businesses. Some are using their
pipelines into the home to sell new products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're going to follow the industry closely, buying
through a mutual fund is probably the best route. But it's
important to know what flavor utility fund you're buying.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Craib-Cox, who follows utility funds for Morningstar,
says power-oriented funds are still a better bargain, but
telecom-oriented utility funds, despite their recent woes, offer
greater long-term growth.
</P>
<P>
   Among funds that concentrate on electric utilities, he likes
no-load Vanguard Utilities Income. ``They have good managers, a
good record and below-average risk,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Among telecom-oriented funds, he likes MFS Fund Utilities, which
has ``a great track record'' but charges a commission. Despite its
54 percent weighting in telecom services, it's up 8.45 percent year
to date.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if all you want is telecom, there are many pure
telecom funds to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
