<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-REACT-NYT     08-22 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE WORK TENSIONS EASE AS STRIKE ENDS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With VERIZON-STRIKE, VERIZON-IMPACT) By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Doucette's head was spinning as he reported to work Monday
for the first time in two weeks. Like tens of thousands of other
Verizon Communications employees, Doucette had gone on strike at
the country's largest local telephone company. Now, as he returned
to his job as a customer assistance representative in Braintree,
Mass., he weighed the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   First, the walkout had gotten him a nice pay raise and more
benefits. Even stock options.
</P>
<P>
   But it had also brought a host of headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Doucette said he was expecting a flood of calls from customers
seeking repairs and services. And there were the workplace
relationships that had to be mended. Like other union workers,
Doucette had walked the picket lines and joined in calling managers
``scabs,'' jeering them as they strode into the building to fill in
on the grunt jobs. Union jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the managers was crying when she was coming out, and I
knew why,'' he said. ``She had been a rep for years and years. You
can't avoid it and you can't let it stop you from doing what you
need to do. But boy, emotionally, there is a lot of pain there. I'm
so glad that part of it is over.''
</P>
<P>
   For union workers, their managers and many Verizon customers,
Monday was a time for trying to bridge the chasms that emerged
during the emotional 15-day walkout. In those two weeks, managers
were taunted, repair vans were assaulted and two union workers were
nearly electrocuted in Long Island while trying to cut a power line
they had mistaken for a telephone cable.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, two unions representing 86,000 workers in 12
states along the Eastern seaboard reached a contract agreement with
Verizon that would cover about two-thirds of the strikers. Local
unions representing the rest, who work from New Jersey to Virginia,
were still trying to negotiate a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those workers showed up Monday outside a half-dozen or
so Verizon offices in New York, forming picket lines and forcing
other union workers to make a decision about whether to cross those
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, more than 80 percent of the strikers in New York and New
England returned to their jobs, said John Bonomo, a Verizon
spokesman. Under the settlement agreement, union workers did not
have to report to their workplaces for another three days if they
had extenuating circumstances. Of those who did show up, some
talked of managers buying them lunch, while others said they were
greeted with cold silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, after a strike, and in this situation in particular
where management was working long hours, both sides are relieved,''
said Richard Hurd, a professor of labor studies at Cornell
University. ``There's the potential to go back to work with
feelings of good will. The only situation where there may be
difficulty is if there were places where strikers were particularly
vociferous in their attacks on managers.''
</P>
<P>
   One such site was a repair-van garage on King Street in lower
Manhattan. In the opening days of the strike, a group of union
workers surrounded a manager in the street and taunted him about
his troubled marriage. The police later charged four of the workers
with harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of tension'' on returning to work, said Rob
Anderson, who spent five hours in jail last week after being
arrested for the jeering. ``Managers didn't say much of anything.
It was like, go to work, go to work. They gave us our toolbags.
They didn't give us information on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some managers at the garage said they had a right to harbor
bitter feelings. One manager, who declined to give his name, said
he had been pelted in the back of his head with an egg while out
making a repair.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, the company's backlog of repair orders had risen to
78,000 since the strike began on Aug. 6. It was unclear how many
orders were put in before the strike and how many were due to
vandalism during the walkout, Bonomo said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Belfiore, a Manhattan resident, said she had been waiting
since the strike began to get her telephone repaired. She said
telephone service was crucial because her son, Michael, has
cerebral palsy and often injures himself. ``The telephone is
vital,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For workers and managers, the return to the workplace provided
ample opportunities for occasionally tense encounters. In several
offices, union members worked alongside managers who had filled in
for strikers during the walkout. In many cases, supervisors had
asked those managers to stay on Monday in case union workers did
not show up or refused to cross some of the remaining picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unusual to see managers reporting to your desk, and you
sitting in the same cubicle with them,'' said Stephen Montgomery,
who works in a bill-collecting office in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shapiro, who usually managed computer programmers in
White Plains, N.Y., watched Monday morning as union workers began
straggling back into the customer assistance call center in nearby
Valhalla. The workers looked over the gray cubicles they had
vacated for two weeks. Then they saw the strangers. Shapiro, who
had been filling in as an operator, was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He half-expected a resentful glance or even a shouting match.
But the workers just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local management here seems like they're assimilating
everybody into the workflow without making an issue of anything,''
Shapiro said. ``And that's the way I guess it needs to be for the
business to function as efficiently as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some union workers in New York, assimilation did not
come so easily. They still had to grapple with the moral
implications of crossing picket lines. About 20 members of
mid-Atlantic local unions, which were still negotiating for a
contract, showed up Monday morning at a Verizon office tower on
Pearl Street near the Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Thompson, who tested data lines for the company, said he
walked into the building after a union steward told him to report
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to do,'' he said. ``My heart told me not to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At mid-afternoon, a manager was standing in the plaza trying to
persuade some union workers to go into the building. One
technician, John Giarrita, said he did not want to return to work
because managers were filling in for some union jobs in his
workplace. ``The management and craft, we don't work together,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the manager, who asked not to be named, offered a deal: If
five technicians went up with him, he would cut loose 15 of the
pinch-hitting managers. Giarrita mulled over this with some of his
co-workers. The five men glanced around the plaza, then followed
the manager through the glass doors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
