<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COLOMBIA-DRUGS-NYT     08-22 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLOMBIA-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN IS CHARGED IN U.S. IN WIDE SHIPMENT OF COCAINE
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Colombian man, accused of heading an international
drug cartel that prosecutors alleged shipped thousands of pounds of
cocaine to the United States and Europe, faced criminal charges in
U.S. District Court here Monday, three days after his extradition
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Alberto Orlandez-Gamboa, who prosecutors have said is
the head of the Caracol drug cartel, has been charged with
conspiring to transport the cocaine and with conspiring to launder
tens of millions of dollars in profits from drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said he was the third drug suspect extradited from
Colombia since that country amended its constitution in December
1997 to allow extradition to the United States. Mary Jo White, the
U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York, said
Orlandez-Gamboa was the first person accused of heading a drug
organization to be extradited from Colombia in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   White said the United States was seeking the extradition of 80
other suspects from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Extradition to the United States has been controversial in
Colombia, and the action involving Orlandez-Gamboa required
approval from the highest levels of Colombia's government. The
United States formally requested extradition in August 1999, after
Orlandez-Gamboa was indicted by a federal grand jury here.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, 2000, the Colombian Supreme Court issued an order
approving the extradition, and the next day the president of
Colombia, Andres Pastrana, and his Cabinet signed a resolution
providing for the action. Orlandez-Gamboa was flown from Bogota to
Miami on a Drug Enforcement Administration jet on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno issued a statement Monday commending
the Colombian government and saying the action ``sends a strong
message to drug dealers that there are no safe havens.''
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Mark F. Mendelsohn, an assistant U.S. attorney,
said newspaper ads had recently appeared in Cali, Colombia,
threatening violence against Colombia's supreme court and senior
political officials if Orlandez-Gamboa was sent to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Orlandez-Gamboa headed the Caracol
drug cartel from Barranquilla, Colombia, directing his subordinates
to carry out bribery and violence including kidnappings and
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges him with crimes dating to 1992; although
he was arrested and jailed in Colombia in June 1998, prosecutors
charged he continued to run the cartel from prison. While in
prison, prosecutors said, Orlandez-Gamboa directed the delivery of
$1.5 million from the United States to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Orlandez-Gamboa also used Caracol, which means
snail in Spanish, as a personal nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges that the Caracol organization imported
cocaine to a variety of places in the United States, and
prosecutors said the drugs went to New York, Miami, Philadelphia
and Puerto Rico. They said the organization used cargo ships, speed
boats and aircraft to move the cocaine and smuggled it in shipments
of cement, in sealed cans and inside ceramic tiles.
</P>
<P>
   After a hearing before a federal magistrate Monday,
Orlandez-Gamboa was ordered held without bail. If convicted on all
charges, he faces life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Martin Schmukler, said Orlandez-Gamboa intended to
plead not guilty to the charges against him. ``I don't think the
charges can be substantiated at all,'' Schmukler said. ``At the
very time they were committed, he was already in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmukler said that, under the extradition agreement,
Orlandez-Gamboa could be charged only with acts that occurred after
the Colombian constitution was changed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the court appearance, White said the
extradition agreement would not hurt the prosecution of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Schmukler said his client had nothing to do with any
advertisements that appeared in Colombian newspapers regarding the
extradition. He said that there had been an entrenched resistance
to extradition for many years, and that similar ads had run after
other cases.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Orlandez-Gamboa ran an automotive business in
Colombia and scoffed at prosecutors' charges that his client ran an
international narcotics cartel from a prison cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jail is not a place to conduct illegal activities,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
