r s BC-OLY-FORTNER-DREAM-TEX     08-22 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FORTNER-DREAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S OLYMPIC BASKETBALL COACH LIVING HER DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sitting at her breakfast table with the sun rising on a
hot Florida morning, Louisiana Tech assistant coach Nell Fortner
announced her master plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the Olympic coach,'' Fortner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, OK,'' was the most polite way coaching colleague Tennessee
assistant Mickie DeMoss could respond.
</P>
<P>
   What else could she say?
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't even a head coach yet,'' DeMoss said demurely.
</P>
<P>
   Fortner reflected for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said, ``then that's what I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I about choked on my eggs,'' DeMoss admits of their 1992
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Fortner and her U.S. women's basketball team
are completing their final preparations for the 2000 Olympic Summer
Games next month in Sydney, Australia. Fortner returns to Texas,
where she played in college from 1978-82, for two exhibitions _
Tuesday night in San Antonio and Wednesday night in Dallas. They
are the first of nine exhibitions for the U.S. team before a Sept.
16 Olympics opener against South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's game at Reunion Arena will mark Fortner's 100th
since she was appointed Team USA's coach in 1997. Her record is
84-14.
</P>
<P>
   In eight years, the former Texas player and Stephen F. Austin
assistant has gone from obscure Louisiana Tech assistant, to Purdue
head coach, to head coach of the WNBA's Indiana Fever to her
lifelong dream of coaching the Olympic team. With that dream comes
the weight of the-U.S.-will-win-the-gold-in-a-walk expectations,
heightened by an undefeated performance by the 1996 team, while
dealing with an entire new set of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even believe this,'' Fortner, 41, said, her eyes
widening. ``I still see friends from Texas and they run into me and
it's like, `Can you believe I'm the Olympic coach?' I always
believed I could be ... my goal was to be the 2008 Olympic coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The native of Jackson, Miss., who later moved to New Braunfels
and starred at Texas from 1978-82 in basketball and volleyball, was
considered a bright mind after Purdue hired her in 1997. She had
spent three years as an assistant at Stephen F. Austin and five at
Louisiana Tech, but it was her work with the '96 Olympic team that
moved her into the upper echelon of coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nell is totally different than (1996 Olympic coach Tara
VanDerveer),'' Olympic guard Dawn Staley said. ``Not to say that
Tara was negative, but Tara was really strict and methodical and
structured, and Nell takes advantage of the talent she has. Nell is
more modern in that she can handle the difference with all of the
distractions. Tara is pretty much cut and paste. Nell can pretty
much survive with any situation that you throw at her.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortner watched VanDerveer do it in '96 when the U.S. team went
52-0 on a pre-Olympic exhibition tour and then was undefeated in
the Olympics for the gold medal. As an assistant on that staff,
Fortner was responsible for scouting, weight training and working
with perimeter players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to sit in the stands at the Olympics and I remember
thinking, `I want to be down there'' on the bench, Fortner said.
</P>
<P>
   She's sitting there now because she relates well to just about
anything. Whether it's her easy going demeanor, soft Southern
accent or disarming smile, her success is directly correlated to
the manner in which she deals with people.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that some of her closest coaching colleagues _
Tennessee's Pat Summitt, Texas' Jody Conradt, Louisiana Tech's Leon
Barmore and VanDerveer _ are the most respected coaches in the
profession today.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this profession you have a lot of quick studies and Nell is
one of them,'' said DeMoss, a member of the Lady Vols' staff for 15
seasons. ``They move up the ladder quickly, because in our
profession it's hard to find someone who has the total package.
Someone who knows the game, how to teach it and relates to players.
She does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortner doesn't have much choice.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of the WNBA and an influx of the professional
woman's basketball player, exposure and better foreign players, the
game has arguably changed more in the past four years than in the
previous 40. With those changes, so has the face of U.S. basketball
evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Fortner has fewer practices, more outside interests and a roster
that won't come completely together until the middle of next week
after the WNBA Finals. Her team went 29-2 in exhibitions last
winter and spring before the players _ all the Olympians except
Teresa Edwards and Katrina McClain play in the WNBA _ joined their
pro teams.
</P>
<P>
   But while everything else changes, the expectations remain the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media perceives the WNBA is the NBA. It's not,'' women's
basketball analyst Ann Meyers said. ``With the WNBA and the
exposure they look at the talent out there and think, `How can they
not win?' It's, `This is their time. USA is the best. And you
better come through.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is hope that the 2000 team will have a similar impact on
the women's game and gender as the '96 team. But then, there was no
professional league, little media coverage and even less outside
interest other than the quadrennial Olympic celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see it being like '96,'' Fortner said. ``People will
care about it, but it's just different when it's in your home
country. After Sydney, I think what you will see is players
becoming better, faster.''
</P>
<P>
   That's tomorrow, and tomorrow can wait. Today is what Fortner
has to build on what she set out to do eight years ago at a
breakfast table on a college recruiting trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at the breakfast table now what do I say?'' Fortner
wondered before smiling with quick nod of the head. ``I want to win
a gold medal.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
