<HEADLINE>
FARRIS WINS A&AMP;M'S QUARTERBACK BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 A&AMP;M-QUARTERBACK-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M's Mark Farris, a 25-year-old sophomore and former
professional baseball player, will start at quarterback when the
Aggies open the season Sept. 2 at Notre Dame, coach R.C. Slocum
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Farris emerged as the coaching staff's choice after a lengthy,
tightly contested competition that included sophomore Vance Smith
and redshirt freshman Colby Freeman. The three quarterbacks entered
two-a-day practices with their roles undefined after spring drills
failed to produce a clear-cut starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked Mark because of his overall performance in spring
training and summer camp,'' Slocum said. ``We felt like right now,
with all the things we like to do with our offense, he gives us the
best chance at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were rotating three quarterbacks, and it's just really hard
trying to get all three of them equal (repetitions). It made it
hard to get any kind of continuity on offense, and I didn't want to
wait until game week and have the distraction going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris completed only 6 of 16 passes for 53 yards in limited
action as a reserve during the 1999 season, but his maturity played
a significant role in Slocum's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Farris spent five years in the Pittsburgh Pirates' organization
after being selected in the first round of the 1994 June amateur
draft.Farris learned how to cope with adversity trying to move up
the Pirates' chain. He got as high as Double-A Carolina of the
Southern League.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't learn to accept failure, but you learn to deal with
it,'' said Farris, who hit .273 in 111 games for Carolina two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum described the competition as ``very close'' and indicated
that Smith and Freeman will split time working with the second-team
offense during practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is still the same,'' Farris said. ``I do the very best
I can on the field and let the coaches decide who starts and who
gets to play. I have to keep working hard and doing my best. We've
had great competition since the spring, and we will continue to
compete. That competition has helped each of us improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the decision should help ``get the air cleared,''
Slocum said, ``so when we go Notre Dame, there's no distractions at
all about who's going to walk out there as the quarterback.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
