<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-REPORT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REPORT SPELLS OUT QUACKENBUSH MISDEEDS  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Former Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush and
his top aides deliberately manipulated the Insurance Department's
enforcement activities to benefit his own political fortunes, a
report released Monday concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The final report of the Assembly Insurance Committee _ which
held hearings earlier this year that ultimately led to
Quackenbush's resignation _ says the former commissioner ignored
his responsibilities to victims of the 1994 Northridge earthquake.
Lawmakers alleged that he allowed insurance companies to make
contributions to nonprofit foundations that he founded rather than
pay larger fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Quackenbush and his senior aides used that money to
benefit the commissioner and his associates, not the public,'' the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the committee echoed the findings as the report was
unanimously adopted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became increasingly clear in the hearings that
(Quackenbush) had abused his public trust,'' said Assemblyman Jack
Scott, D-Altadena, chairman of the committee. ``He had twisted the
powers of his own office so it served his own political interests,
instead of the public that elected him. And so, instead of
protecting consumers, he used his authority to further his own
political ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee concurred with that conclusion,
although several spent many hours Sunday night arguing for removal
of language they found too partisan. Quackenbush is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The report also makes several suggestions for possible
legislation to prevent similar abuses from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned June 28 to avoid almost certain impeachment
by the Legislature. Gov. Gray Davis has named former state appeals
court Justice Harry Low to serve the remaining two years of
Quackenbush's term.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that Quackenbush coerced insurance
companies into paying $12 million to two nonprofit foundations he
created, a move that allowed them to avoid millions of dollars in
potential fines for their handling of claims connected with the
Northridge earthquake. Those payments then were used to pay for
television commercials, polls and other outreach that aided
Quackenbush's political career.
</P>
<P>
   Three people are singled out in the report for creating and
implementing the foundation scheme: former Department of Insurance
chief counsel William Palmer; the department's former deputy
commissioner, George Grays; and Joe Shumate, a political consultant
who has run Quackenbush's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer and Grays resigned from the department. Grays has been
named by the state attorney general's office as being the focus of
a criminal investigation and having a central role in running the
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Shumate's role was not detailed until the committee's report was
issued Monday. It says Shumate helped run the foundations,
personally benefited from money paid to his company by the
foundations, and helped those tainted by the scandal to devise
counterattacks and damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we were able to spend time reviewing all the facts, it
became clear to many of us that Mr. Shumate had a very central role
in designing and implementing the `perpetual campaign,' '' said
Assemblyman Fred Keeley, D-Boulder Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The ``perpetual campaign'' was the process of using department
enforcement actions to help pay for Quackenbush's political
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Shumate could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report does not take postions on some of the key
questions raised by the Quackenbush scandal, including whether the
state commissioner should be appointed instead of elected.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the key changes recommended by the committee are that:
</P>
<P>
   -- State law should regulate any spending of enforcement
settlement funds on consumer education and outreach that feature
the commissioner or any other elected official.
</P>
<P>
   -- All money obtained through settlements of enforcement actions
should be deposited in the state general fund, or otherwise be
subject to fiscal oversight or control by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   -- Details of final settlements between the department and
insurance companies should be available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Some committee members warned against trying to pass many of
these recommendations before the Legislature adjourns at the end of
the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having these bills rushed through as a knee-jerk
reaction,'' said Assemblyman Dave Cox, R-Fair Oaks. ``The consumers
will be better served if we would consult with the incoming
commissioner and take time to make good laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But several of the ideas in the report, as well as other
suggested reforms, already are in bills moving through the
legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   A bill by Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco,
would extend the statute of limitations on Northridge earthquake
claims for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about restoring the opportunity taken away from some
of the people who were victims, that the former insurance
commissioner took away to help his own fortunes. He took that away
forever,'' Keeley said during Assembly floor debate on the bill
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed the Assembly and now moves back to the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
