<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BONDS-PRENUPTIAL-SFCH     08-22 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONDS-PRENUPTIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE'S HIGH COURT UPHOLDS SLUGGER BARRY BONDS'
PRENUPTIAL  AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a decision that could affect thousands of
prenuptial contracts, the California Supreme Court Monday upheld
Giants slugger Barry Bonds' agreement with his former spouse in
which she gave up her right to half the fortune he would earn
during their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sun Bonds did not have a lawyer, the court said she
understood the consequences of signing the premarital agreement the
day before the wedding, voluntarily giving up all her rights to
community property.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling in Bonds' favor, the court appeared to suggest that
requiring each side to have a lawyer would open up a flood of
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a majority of dissolution cases in California at least one
of the two parties apparently is not represented by counsel,''
wrote Chief Justice Ronald George in the court's decision. Having a
lawyer is ``merely one factor among several'' that a court should
consider in deciding whether the agreement was voluntarily signed,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices reversed a state appeals court ruling that required
each spouse-to-be to have independent lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is one of the first in the nation to interpret a
national law adopted by 28 states _ including California _ that
sets out the basic requirements for premarital agreements. One of
the most controversial issues in interpreting these pacts has been
whether each side must have a lawyer to make the agreement valid.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a shutout for Bonds in his six-year divorce
battle. All seven justices ruled in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds was ``ecstatic'' when he heard the news, said his lawyer
Robert Nachshin. ``I`m glad it's 99 percent over,'' said the
outfielder, who must return to the state court of appeal to decide
other issues pertaining to the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate ruling, the court upheld a Malibu couple's
premarital agreement in which each side waived all rights to
spousal support. The wife later changed her mind and upon divorce
sued her ex-husband for support. In that case, both parties were
well-educated, wealthy and had been married before. And each had
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonds case presented far different facts.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met in Montreal in August 1987 when Bonds was a
promising young outfielder for the Pittsburgh Pirates making
$106,000 a year and Sun Bonds was studying to be a beautician. They
were both 23.
</P>
<P>
   After a whirlwind, three-month romance, they became engaged and
set a wedding date for the following February.
</P>
<P>
   On their way to the Phoenix airport, where they were catching a
plane for a Las Vegas wedding the next day, they made a stop at the
office of Bonds' lawyer. Sun Bonds signed a premarital agreement
that she had seen for the first time only a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the couple divorced in 1994, Bonds was making $8
million a year with the Giants. Sun Bonds asked for support for
both herself and their young son and daughter. But a San Mateo
judge upheld the agreement, ruling that Sun Bonds voluntarily
signed it. The judge awarded Sun Bonds child support as well as
$10,000 in monthly spousal support, which ended in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds has since remarried and last year signed a $22.9-million
contract with the Giants for two years, plus an option year.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, a state Court of Appeal in San Francisco struck
down the agreement because Sun Bonds did not have a lawyer when she
signed the agreement. In cases where each side does not have an
attorney, courts must ``closely scrutinize'' the circumstances
surrounding the contract, the court said in its 2-to-1 decision.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that Bonds had two lawyers and a financial
adviser with him when he signed the agreement, while Sun Bonds was
accompanied by only a Swedish friend with no legal background.
</P>
<P>
   The justices said it would be ``unfair'' to hold Sun Bonds, a
Swedish cosmetology student with limited proficiency in English, to
what they said was a sloppily drafted agreement. The court was also
troubled by the last-minute signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But in reversing that decision, the state Supreme Court agreed
with the trial judge's interpretation of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't threatened when she signed the agreement and, in
fact, appeared happy, calm and confident, the high court said. A
lawyer for Bonds discussed the agreement with her at least a week
before she signed it, and even suggested she might want to get her
own lawyer. But she refused, the court said, agreeing with Bonds to
keep their property and earnings separate.
</P>
<P>
   The court also noted that the wedding was a small, impromptu
affair that could easily have been postponed if Sun Bonds wanted to
have a lawyer look over the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also didn't buy the suggestion that Sun Bonds was
naive and vulnerable when she signed over her rights to community
property. Sun Bonds was ``intrepid rather than a person whose will
is easily overborne,'' George said. He noted that she had emigrated
from her homeland when she was barely 20, gotten a job, made
friends and could speak two foreign languages.
</P>
<P>
   In interpreting the Uniform Premarital Agreement Act, which
California adopted in 1985, the court noted that the drafters
specifically rejected the requirement that each party have a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Although they didn't make it a requirement, the justices
acknowledged it is always a wise precaution to have a lawyer. ``The
best assurance of enforceability is independent representation for
both parties,'' wrote George.
</P>
<P>
   Nachshin, Bonds' trial lawyer from Los Angeles, said he and
Bonds felt ``totally vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the agreement has been upheld, the lawyer said he felt
confident they would prevail in the lower courts in interpreting
other provisions of the contract. The trial court ``found Sun Bonds
to be a totally noncredible witness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sherman, the Berkeley lawyer who argued the appeal for
Bonds, said it is no coincidence that the high court upheld both
the Bonds agreement as well as that in the Malibu case. ``Both
decisions reflect more of a willingness to uphold premarital
agreements,'' he said, ``and only set them aside in exceptional
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige Leslie Wickland, the San Francisco lawyer who represented
Sun Bonds, said she was disappointed that the high court gave
little guidance to the lower courts in interpreting these
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss to imagine what facts they would find that would
constitute an invalid agreement,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
