<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SFO GETS THE DISINCENTIVE PLAN  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Man, am I stupid.
</P>
<P>
   I would think that the most massive San Francisco construction
project since the Two Bridges should be constructed by construction
people in whom the city has faith and trust.
</P>
<P>
   The SFO expansion job _ I would think that you just don't want
it done half-fanny.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that kind of thinking is very naive.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's paper was a story about how a construction company
that has been indicted on charges of defrauding the city's
minority-contracting program is still a major player in the SFO
terminal project.
</P>
<P>
   The city didn't fire Scott-Norman Mechanical Inc., &LR;  because city
officials fear putting the entire airport project behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   However! Once Scott-Norman's portion of the project is finished,
the city is going to sue the contractor for its profits.
</P>
<P>
   So the city is saying, ``Please do your best work on this
crucial project for which we're paying you $89.1 million (!!), then
we're going to sue your pants off.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm so stupid that I would think this is not the ideal way to
insure quality work. Where's the company's motivation to do a
bang-up job? Wouldn't there be the temptation to phone it in?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately we're only talking about the plumbing,
air-conditioning and fire protection systems at the new
international terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Here is this stupid guy's wish: That the project will look and
perform a lot better than it smells.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN 2000: In Al Gore's stump speech (and in Al's case, is
``stump speech'' redundant?), he says proudly, ``I stand before you
as my own man!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure, but I think this means that Al Gore has made a
significant financial contribution to the Al Gore campaign and
therefore he now exerts a great amount of political influence over
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice that Al is now his own man, but most of us guys felt
that way the day we got our driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S SAD, almost, the grief some of the dot-commers are starting
to feel as a result of the backlash to their sometimes-heavy-handed
invasion of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle is enriching to the community's vocabulary. The
Wall Street Journal ran a story last Friday, ``San Franciscans
Start to Rue the Dot-com Influx.''
</P>
<P>
   In the story, one dot-commer lamented, ``They call us
dot-commies and dot-communists, even e-holes.''
</P>
<P>
   JOE BAGADONUTS overheard this exchange in a coffee shop
somewhere in North Beach:
</P>
<P>
   Yupster: ``How did your date with the receptionist go?''
</P>
<P>
   Hipster: ``Stellar. I took her to a pre-Burning Man party and
then back to my place.''
</P>
<P>
   Y: ``Did you get lucky?''
</P>
<P>
   H: ``Dude. This IPO was so hot that when we finished, the
neighbors lit up and smoked.''
</P>
<P>
   SOME WISE guy out there, name unknown, refers to that
in-the-spotlight SUV as the Ford Exploder. Cute.
</P>
<P>
   And Fred Wickham poses the legal /philosophical/constitutional
question, ``Is it wrong to yell `Firestone!' in a crowded Ford
Explorer?''
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF faulty tires, Phoenix wonders why consumers don't
have the right to information about how goods are made, especially
goods that can be fatal if they are not expertly assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't we know if products were produced by scab labor?''
Phoenix asks, referring to Firestone tires made during a plant
strike. ``What good is the union label if it's sewn on by a scab?''
</P>
<P>
   HONK IF you are a man of dubious reputation and character who
spent the night at Xiana's house just before she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects would have been easier for the cops to track if the
mom had only kept a guest book signed by the random overnighters.
</P>
<P>
   SHUT DOWN the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   That's going to be the rallying cry of the rest of baseball once
somebody puts together the evidence that makes it clear the Giants
have an unfair home-park advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: At Saturday's game against the Braves, a stirring
Giants' come-from-behind win, a key hit was a routine fly ball hit
by J.T. Snow that Braves' left fielder B.J. Surhoff lost in the sun
and wind.
</P>
<P>
   There are mysterious wind swirls out in left field that nobody
in the world understands except Barry Bonds. And maybe Barry has
cooler shades than the other guys who play out there.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the first-base ump on Saturday failed to notice
Ellis Burks running out of his legal lane to first base, causing a
key Braves' screwup. The ump wasn't available to explain, but it is
believed that he said of Burks, ``I lost him in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, left-field bleacher fans turn Giants' outs into homers by
reaching over the wall and snatching the ball before the opposing
left fielder can grab it.
</P>
<P>
   And somehow, the Giants constructed a right-field homer wall
that, with one exception, nobody else in the big leagues but Barry
Bonds can clear.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, the rest of baseball is going to demand that
the Giants play their home games at Candlestick until the visitors
are guaranteed a level playing field.
</P>
</TEXT>
