u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-1STLD-W     08-22 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIDESTEPS RACE THAT HAS STIRRED TENSIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Changes middle initial of Larry B. Seabrook in 5th graf)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Steering clear of a political struggle that has
stirred ethnic tensions in New York's Democratic Party, Hillary
Rodham Clinton declined Monday to offer her backing for Rep. Eliot
Engel, a five-term Bronx Democrat who is facing a September primary
challenge orchestrated by black and Hispanic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not getting involved in that campaign,'' Clinton said at
a news conference in Yonkers, as Engel stood, stiff and
expressionless, at her side. ``This is a local situation. I'm not
going to have anything to say about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I count both of them as friends, and I'm not going to become,
you know, involved one way or another,'' said Clinton, the
Democratic candidate for senator.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement was in keeping with a general policy of her
campaign not to take sides in any primaries, even ones that involve
incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   This congressional contest has drawn unusual attention since
Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx Democratic leader, who is also a senior
Hispanic leader in New York, announced that he was withdrawing his
support for Engel, who is Jewish, and endorsing Larry B. Seabrook,
a state senator who is black.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Engel's supporters and some Jewish newspapers have
assailed Ramirez's decision as a stark attempt to increase the
power of black and Hispanic leaders. Ramirez disputed that Monday,
saying his decision was based on what he described as Engel's
lackluster performance in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Engel, who appeared with Clinton at two campaign stops in lower
Westchester on Monday, said he was not surprised by Clinton's
statement, though he made no effort to hide his disappointment.
``I'm told that she's not endorsing any race in a contested
primary,'' he said. ``If it was solely my race, I would be more
upset about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Engel said that Clinton's decision to sit out this struggle
was likely to complicate her already unsteady position with some
Jewish voters. ``She has a lot of convincing to do in the Jewish
community, and frankly, I think the fact that she's staying neutral
isn't helping her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton discussed Engel's primary challenge on a day in which
she campaigned through Yonkers, before coming here Monday evening
to be the host of a fund-raiser on behalf of the Westchester
Coalition for Legal Abortion. At both stops in Yonkers, she
reprised her attacks her on opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, for his
support of Republican positions backing large tax cuts and against
strict regulation of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent Sunday night at her home in Chappaqua with
President Clinton and, for the first time, she said, with their
dog, Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   She expressed particular delight Monday morning at being at
Sunnyside Manor, a community center for the elderly by the Hudson
River in Yonkers. ``What a well-named, place: Sunnyside!'' she
enthused. ``Look at all these faces; it makes me feel so sunny!''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's attempts to avoid a discussion about Engel's campaign,
one of the more complicated ethnic situations on New York's
political landscape this year, suggests the experience the first
lady has gained since she came to New York more than a year ago,
when she found herself ensnared in a number of only-in-New-York
ethnic political disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has appeared at public events with Seabrook and Engel,
in a concerted attempt, her aides said, to appear to be evenhanded.
Several Democrats said that Clinton would be particularly well
advised not to take sides between Ramirez, the powerful Bronx
leader and one of the most influential Hispanics in New York, and
Engel.
</P>
<P>
   And Ramirez applauded Clinton's decision to stay out of the
race, and said his own abandonment of Engel, whom he had supported
before, reflected his conclusion that he was an ``absentee
congressman'' who had lost interest in the concerns of Bronx
residents. He chastised Engel for even complaining about the turn
of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliot Engel ought to stop that nonsense,'' he said. ``Take a
chill pill. Relax. It's just a primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton's decision was not without risks. Engel's case
has raised concern among a number of Jewish leaders, some of whom
have already been less than full-throated in their support of
Clinton's campaign. For his part, Engel placed the blame not on
Clinton but on Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept that is the position that she's taken,'' Engel said.
``Let's face it: Robert Ramirez has browbeaten the world and
threatened the world and this is the kind of boss-laded politics he
runs in the Bronx. Everyone is afraid of him.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
