<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMIT-SUPERVISORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERM-LIMIT ADVOCATE TO FILE SUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last time a Los Angeles County supervisor was
voted out of office, Christopher Skinnell was toddling around home
in Glendale north of Los Angeles, making trouble for his day-care
provider mom.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 23-year-old resident of La Crescenta, 12 miles north of
downtown L.A., is making trouble for what he calls ``the five
little kings,'' championing a ballot initiative that would limit
the five supervisors to two terms of four years each.
</P>
<P>
   Skinnell turned in 300,000 petition signatures for the ballot
initiative this spring, which only required about 197,000 valid
signatures. But County Clerk Conny McCormack initially ruled that
approximately 101,000 of the signatures were invalid mostly because
they were determined to be duplicates, illegible or signers were
not on voter registration rolls.
</P>
<P>
   After Skinnell's volunteers found 1,120 valid signatures
incorrectly disqualified, McCormack acknowledged last week there
are enough valid signatures to place the measure on the ballot. But
her reversal came a week after the deadline for placing measures on
the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Skinnell said he will file a lawsuit Tuesday to reverse the
county registrar's initial ruling and force his initiative on this
fall's ballot. The printing deadline for the November election is
Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met people who think that things are not right in Los
Angeles County,'' Skinnell said. To make them right, ``usually,
what you do is you run for that office, but in the supervisorial
seats, it's practically impossible to defeat the incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last last time that an incumbent was defeated was in 1980,
when Ronald Regan was elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Skinnell is raising the possibility that the
disqualification process might have been tainted to benefit the
supervisors, who hired Registrar-Recorder/County Clerk McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sort of smoking gun that misconduct occurred,
but it smells bad to me with that much error,'' Skinnell said,
adding that of the disqualified signatures that his six helpers
reviewed, 20 percent of them turned out to be valid. What you're
talking about was 20,000 signatures misclassified. We went in
expecting to find maybe 1 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky and McCormack vehemently denied
any attempt to thwart the initiative's certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no effort to bottle it up,'' Yaroslavsky said, adding
that he would not contest Skinnell's lawsuit to recertify the
initiative, and that ``one way of the other, it'll be on the
ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor, who opposes term limits, also characterized
Skinnell as a front man for former supervisor and term-limits
advocate Pete Schabarum, who retired in 1991 after serving 19 years
on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a grass-roots effort,'' Yaroslavsky said. ``I
think this is Pete's parting shot at the county and at Gloria
Molina,'' who initiated a voting-rights lawsuit that created a
Latino-dominated district and made Schabarum's re-election
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Schabarum could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Skinnell acknowledges that Schabarum's term-limits advocacy
group was the source of $250,000 used to finance the initiative
effort, but adds that he approached Schabarum for help, not the
other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a musician and a day-care provider, Skinnell has made
big-time politics his life at an early age, doing demographic and
other research for congressional and state legislative candidates
whom he declined to name.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to get dragged into this,'' Skinnell
explained.
</P>
<P>
   He got his start in politics after he graduated in 1995 from
Crescenta Valley High School. As a freshman government major at
Claremont McKenna College, he began working at the Rose Institute
of State and Local Government as a research assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 1999 Claremont graduate is a research associate at the
conservative institute and is diligent about noting that his
term-limits crusade is in no way affiliated with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Math Club in high school, Skinnell seems to have
an affinity for numbers. He looks at numbers of voters in a
candidates' district, how they break down into demographic and
political categories. He looks at the same sorts of numbers when
helping with redistricting for an irrigation district in Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   One number he likes to cite is 2 million _ the number of
constituents that county supervisors represent. That's considerably
more than term-limited state senators or Los Angeles City Council
members represent. It's even larger than the constituencies of most
mayors in the state, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Using the advantages of incumbency, of currying favor with
corporations and unions through awarding billions of dollars worth
of contracts and of the campaign financing such favor can easily
drum up, ``you can build your own little fiefdom, and the other
supervisors won't generally interfere,'' Skinnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky and other supervisors oppose term limits, saying
those imposed on the state Legislature in 1990 have led to a game
of political ``musical chairs'' that has left lobbyists and
bureaucrats as the only long-term establishment.
</P>
<P>
   County supervisors are some of the few politicians in L.A.
County without term limits. Many city leaders, including Los
Angeles' City Council and mayor, serve under term limits, as does
the governor, state Assembly members and state senators.
</P>
<P>
   But while the president of the United States is limited to two,
four-year terms, U.S. representatives and U.S. senators do not face
term limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 0101EDT &QL; 
