<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH'S RICKY WILLIAMS HEALTHY AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-WILLIAMS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ricky Williams took the handoff midway through the third
quarter of the season opener last September in Arizona State's Sun
Devil Stadium, he was a Heisman Trophy candidate on everyone's
preseason All-American list.
</P>
<P>
   Scant seconds later, after tearing a ligament in his left knee,
the Texas Tech running back was destined to become a name on a
surgery schedule and a fixture on the rehabilitation list posted
daily outside the Texas Tech training room.
</P>
<P>
   End of season. Dream interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part of my life was hard for me,'' Williams said. ``You
come out a Heisman Trophy candidate and an All-American, and for
that to be shot down and you suddenly have to start all over ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he feels not so much like a senior trying to
regain the form that made him one of college football's top
players, but more like the freshman who emerged in 1997 from a pack
of candidates vying to replace Byron Hanspard. He gained 894 yards
that year to set a Tech season rushing record for freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel a little like I'm an incoming freshman,''
Williams said. ``I've got to prove that my knee is OK and I can
still get out there and run like I did before. But at this point, I
feel pretty good being in pads and back out there with the team. My
knee is doing good, and most of my confidence in it is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really gotten hit in practice yet, but things are
feeling pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll get hit starting Saturday, when Tech opens its season at
home against New Mexico. Williams, who enters the season with a
2,476 yards rushing in two full seasons, will wear a protective
knee brace into October. Periodically during August, he has taken a
practice off when he experiences soreness. Though he has a hint,
Tech coach Mike Leach can only anticipate what a healthy Williams _
teamed with sophomore scooter Shaud Williams _ could mean to his
pass-happy offense this season.
</P>
<P>
   Shaud Williams averaged 5.9 yards a carry and scored seven
touchdowns last year while gaining a team-leading 658 yards. An
H-back in Leach's offense, he frequently will be on the field at
the same time as Ricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are incredible threats running and catching the ball,''
Leach said. ``We've taken care of Ricky in training camp, but he's
looked good. I had two guys in separate classes at Valdosta State
(1992-96) who both gained over 1,000 yards in this offense, but
I've never had two guys like this at the same time. We're going to
try and get them both the ball as many ways as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kliff Kingsbury relishes the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ricky looks really good,'' Kingsbury said. ``He's
going to be ready to go Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having both he and Shaud out there I think is really going to
make it tough on the defense. We spread them out and start hitting
passes and then hit them with two of the best running backs in the
country? It's kind of like, `What do you do?' from their
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   To Ricky Williams' credit, the crushing injury didn't bring him
down mentally. Red Raiders fans will recall the animated Williams
hobbling up and down the Raiders' sideline last season, urging the
team on and offering individual encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky was a motivator for us at all our games and even at
practice,'' Shaud said. ``He helped me out a great deal after he
got hurt, telling me little things that would take longer for me to
pick up and learn on my own. But that's the kind of guy Ricky is.
He was not going to let something like the injury keep him away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams said that he continued to take his role as team
captain seriously after he was injured, and that helped his mental
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't perform physically, but I was still captain and
that role called for leadership,'' Williams said. ``Playing that
role is what kept my confidence up. It let my teammates know that I
was still there, and it gave me a feeling that people still
depended on me. And my teammates helped me through rehab, letting
me know that I was still `The Man' and they were depending on me,
that they felt they could still win a lot of games with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tech coach Spike Dykes said Williams' post-injury
enthusiasm was exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an amazing young man,'' Dykes said. ``He's the most
unselfish, team-oriented guy I've ever been around. A lot of people
in his situation would have lost interest, or be down, or be
negative. He never did any of that. He took (the situation) _ even
though it hurt him badly because he loves to play the game _ and
handled it in the best light I believe I ever saw a guy do.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a senior, asked that Tech not apply for a medical
redshirt so that he can go out with the class he came in with. Once
concerned that there was little role for him in Leach's
pass-oriented attack, he approaches Saturday's first game with
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running backs are going to get the ball in a lot of
ways,'' Williams said. ``I'm enjoying getting out there and
catching the ball. I feel good about lining up one on one with a
linebacker and he having to cover me in the open field. I feel like
that's going to be one of my strong points.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as his knee holds up, that likely won't be the only one.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
