<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IOWA </SLUG>
 STATE-McCARNEY-TEX 
McCARNEY, IOWA STATE READY TO MAKE BIG NOISE IN BIG 12 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a coach with a 13-42 career record who is soon to be working
for a new set of bosses, Iowa State coach Dan McCarney acts
downright serene.
</P>
<P>
   McCarney has been the Cyclones' coach since 1995 and over the
past five years has tried to bring Iowa State's program to the
respectable level. School president Martin Jischke, who left for
Purdue in June, and athletic director Gene Smith, who recently took
a similar job at Arizona State, were McCarney believers who had
been patient with the Cyclones' zephyr-like progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any more pressure,` McCarney said about
performing for new employers. ``I've been asked that a number of
times. I know the program has improved a lot. Anyone close to it
knows that, too. We're a much better program, which is why I think
we're on the threshold of doing some great things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this coaching staff and this football team. I've never
felt as good about anything in my life. We've tried to build this
program the right way. We haven't taken shortcuts. We haven't made
excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's 4-7 record was Iowa State's best under McCarney and
17 starters are returning, plus a senior class of 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do what we can do, he won't have a problem,'' said
fifth-year senior center Ben Bruns. ``And I foresee that happening.
We will have a very successful year. It is a critical time, but
we're all ready for that and we accept it and it doesn't feel like
pressure to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Smith left for Arizona State, the feeling in Ames was
that McCarney needed a winning season to save his job. Last season,
the Cyclones showed signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-0 start was the school's best since 1981. Iowa State
posted a shutout victory at Nevada-Las Vegas, the first road
shutout since 1978. The Cyclones won at Missouri, ending a 28-game
losing streak in conference road games. But with a chance to record
the first winning season since 1986 and possibly make a bowl game
for the first time since 1978, the Cyclones lost seven of their
last eight. Four of those losses were by less than a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close,'' McCarney said. ``There were four or five
games that we should've won. We're not that far away. It's a matter
of the guys making a few more plays.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarney believes that Iowa State finally has Big 12
Conference-type players at nearly every position and enough depth
to compete. In particular, the Cyclones have improved defensively.
In McCarney's first season, Iowa State allowed an average of 458
yards and 37 points a game. Last season, opponents averaged 351
yards and 24 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, the way things have changed since my freshman
year to now, it's not even the same sport,'' senior quarterback
Sage Rosenfels said. ``I'm not ripping on the guys who played in
those early years, but we're so much faster and so much more
physical on defense now. We have a lot more depth and a lot of
quality players.''
</P>
<P>
   A few plays here, a few more points there and perhaps Iowa State
will find a way to win six or more games. The Cyclones haven't been
to a bowl game since 1978, a statistic McCarney says is
``sickening.'' Winning would cure that illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the team we have coming back, and with the things we're
going to try to accomplish, the things that Dan McCarney has said
are coming true,'' Iowa State senior defensive end Reggie Hayward
said. ``It has just taken time, but right now, it's a great time to
be a Cyclone.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
