<HEADER>
A8696 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elarton wins 14th as Astros nip Cubs
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Without actually saying so, the Astros and Chicago Cubs paid
homage to baseball movies Monday night at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Even the expected Cub-friendly gathering at Enron Field had to
give two thumbs up to the Astros after a 5-4 victory that just
reaffirmed how much better they have played over the last five
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unheralded Joe Slusarski bailed closer Octavio Dotel out of a
no-out, bases-loaded jam in the ninth inning as the Astros escaped
potential disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is not a guy who normally pitches in the late innings, but
he was the freshest guy we had and the least likely to walk
someone,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``And obviously, in
that situation, we couldn't afford to walk anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won for the ninth time in 13 games and are 11-6 in
their last 17 to go four games over .500 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a team perceived to be so bad played so well, the
Cleveland Indians were on their way to winning a pennant on the big
screen in Major League.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans, and there were plenty of them, didn't leave the
premises totally disappointed. They got a chance to see Sammy Sosa
hit one of the most awe-inspiring home runs of his career. In a
scene straight out of The Natural, Sosa launched a towering shot
into the left-field lights _ more than 100 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``That landed just south of Dallas,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Dierker: ``(Pitching coach) Burt (Hooton) and I both
agreed that we threw a lot of pitches that were hit for home runs,
but not quite as long as that one. That was pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elarton held the Cubs to three runs in eight innings to
extend his personal winning streak to five games. Elarton (14-4)
has a 3.11 ERA over his last five six starts and owns a sparkling
career winning percentage of .714 (25-10).
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bogar led the Astros with two hits, and Richard Hidalgo
drove in three of the five runs. Bogar also started a crucial
double play in the ninth inning, much to the delight of Slusarski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to keep the ball on the ground and hoping
that we'd come up with a good play behind me, and we did,'' said
Slusarski, who entered the game after Dotel walked the bases loaded
on just 13 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I didn't have to be perfect, but I had to get three
outs. Scott deserved that win; he pitched his rear off.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who got a swollen finger on his right hand _ the result
of a chopper up the middle in the fifth inning _ didn't have his
best stuff, but it was enough to beat the Cubs, who lost for the
sixth consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are games when you go out there, and you just cruise,
and you don't have to think, which makes it a lot easier,'' Elarton
said. ``But games like this take a lot more effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The first three innings belonged to the pitchers. Cubs starter
Kevin Tapani (8-10) faced the minimum number of hitters, while
Elarton danced around potential trouble to keep the visitors off
the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   That trend ceased in the fourth when Chicago's Damon Buford led
off with a double and scored on Willie Greene's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros answered with three runs in the bottom of the inning.
Julio Lugo hit a leadoff double and scored on Bogar's single
through the right side, and Hidalgo's two-run blast over the
center-field wall gave the Astros a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's 457-foot missile into the lights high above the railroad
tracks in left field tied the score in the fifth and seemed to
mesmerize the crowd of 34,248. It tied Montreal's Andy Tracy for
the longest home run at Enron Field and was Sosa's
major-league-leading 43rd on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that ball went a foot, it went 550 feet,'' said Astros left
fielder Lance Berkman, who wasn't buying the announced distance.
``There are a only a handful of guys who can hit a ball 550 feet,
and he's one of them. I can guarantee you that ball was approaching
that distance. It wasn't even on its way down.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of Sosa's homer arguably was not as impressive as the
height. According to estimates by Enron Field engineer Rob Harris,
Sosa's homer made contact with the lights 120 to 125 feet above the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't watch them,'' Elarton said. ``But when that
one came off the bat, I turned around; I wanted to see it. That's
the most impressive home run I've ever seen. It was a pleasure to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros loaded the bases with none out in the sixth and
reclaimed the lead on Hidalgo's sacrifice fly. At first glance, it
didn't appear the ball would be deep enough to score Lugo from
third base, but left fielder Rondell White made a poor throw, and
Lugo took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou followed with an RBI single, a run that proved
critical when the Cubs got one back in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   After coaxing Eric Young to hit into a double play for only the
ninth time in 483 at-bats _ as a run scored _ Slusarski got a fly
out from Mark Grace to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slu did a great job,'' Bogar said. ``If you had asked me how
we were going to get out of that (jam) without giving up the lead,
I wouldn't have too many options for you.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
