<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HN     08-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bagwell only cares about numbers adding up to wins
</P>
<P>
   By JAYNE CUSTRED
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Somewhere, in some small corner of Jeff Bagwell's
heart, there has to be a warm, fuzzy feeling for the kind of
baseball he's been playing since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the satisfaction is there, however deeply buried, for the
elite company Bagwell is now keeping thanks to his fifth
consecutive season of 30 home runs, 100 runs and 100 RBIs. Maybe at
home, in quiet moments, he allows himself to retrieve and savor his
personal accomplishments as of late.
</P>
<P>
   But not publicly, and not for long. In the confines of Enron
Field, there's only one thing that consumes Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know how bad of a season we've had,'' he said. ``That's
really all I can focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask about his becoming the first Astro ever to hit 300 or more
home runs, and he doesn't want to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   Mention joining legends like Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Hank Aaron
and Willie Mays with his fifth straight season of 30 homers, 100
runs and 100 RBIs _ making Bagwell only the eighth player in
history to accomplish the feat _ and he admits he knows but doesn't
care.
</P>
<P>
   Comment on his nine home runs in the last 11 games, and there's
no doubt Bagwell cares even less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very overrated stat,'' Bagwell said. ``My job is to
drive in runs and score runs. If I get a two-run homer or a two-run
single, it's fine by me. Run production is what I'm after, not home
runs. Wins and losses are the only stat that I really care about.''
</P>
<P>
   And that stat, unfortunately, is the hardest one for Bagwell to
live with these days. Although the Astros bested the Cubs 5-4
Monday evening, the club still owns the worst record in the majors
at 51-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not an individual sport,'' Bagwell said. ``I mean it
is, in some ways. There are individual statistics. But I've been
playing for 10 years, and the only thing I've really wanted in each
of those years is for us to get in the playoffs. With a year like
this one, those personal things just don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the bright spots few and far between for the Astros
this season, dismissing Bagwell's accomplishments leaves precious
little to cheer about. And since the team returned from the
All-Star break on July 13, Bagwell has certainly provided his share
of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell has hit 15 home runs since the break, and perhaps even
more impressive, has 39 RBIs. When the midseason break began,
Bagwell was hitting .294. He's upped his average to .313 since
then. On Sunday, he slugged the 301st homer of his career, and he
had an 18-game hitting streak snapped Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's swinging the bat real well now,'' manager Larry Dierker
said. ``It's always the same with him. When he's swinging well, he
hits it hard all over the place. But no one can explain streaks
like that. Streaks and slumps are inevitable. The great ones just
have longer streaks than they do slumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell is the first to admit he struggled a bit in May and
June. As with a majority of his teammates, things were slow at the
plate for Bagwell. But just as his success now doesn't faze him,
neither did his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't analyze streaks, bad or good, especially in
baseball,'' Bagwell said. ``There's too many things involved.
You've got to get pitches to hit; then you've got to put the ball
in play with eight players out there. A lot is luck. You've still
got to be lucky. You can't miss the good pitches when you get them.
And you can't worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a hit, I get a hit. It's too hard of a game as it is
to worry about it. I try for four good ones a night, and if I do,
then it was a good game. There's just a lot you can't control, so
you do the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bagwell, that's usually enough. His 38 homers are
third-best in the National League, and he sits at fifth in the NL
with 103 RBIs. Bagwell is second with 113 runs and third in total
bases with 287.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bagwell's sixth overall season with 100 RBIs or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing with Bagwell,'' Dierker said. ``When he's not
hitting well, he still gets walks and makes the plays and does all
kinds of things to help our team. Anyone in any career has ups and
downs, when you struggle to get the job done. But the really good
ones keep on plugging away when they're struggling and manage to
get the job done anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bagwell is one of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
