<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-2NDL     08-22 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' DEAL TO TRADE EWING TO SEATTLE FALLS THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to rewrite with additional reporting. Expands by 900 words;
story is now 2 takes.)   
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing, the stoic 7-foot center who for 15
years tried to be the player to bring a championship to the New
York Knicks, was on the brink of being traded Monday night before a
four-team, 13-player deal hit a significant obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, a 38-year-old veteran, was the centerpiece of the
blockbuster deal that would have sent him to the Seattle
SuperSonics, said a National Basketball Association official on the
condition of anonymity. But a division within the Detroit Pistons,
who were set to acquire seven marginal players, caused the team to
call off the trade Monday night; four of the players had contracts
that the team did not want to assume.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ewing's going to Seattle, the proposed trade
would have had the Knicks acquiring forward Vin Baker from the
SuperSonics and forward Glen Rice and center Travis Knight from the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would have received Chris Dudley from the Knicks and
Christian Laettner from the Detroit Pistons. The Pistons would have
added a number of role players from the three teams, including
Vernon Maxwell, Lazaro Borrell, Greg Foster, Vladimir Stepania,
John Celestand, Tyronn Lue and David Wingate.
</P>
<P>
   So the deal has been delayed for at least a day. But it seems
unlikely that Ewing will return to the Knicks next season after the
team seemed to have let him go Monday, even preparing for a
conference call to announce the trade. And Seattle remains
interested in obtaining the 12-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons executives, said one person with knowledge of the
negotiations, were strongly debating whether to take on the seven
players. One way to revive the deal may involve Detroit's asking
the three other teams to sweeten the deal with higher-quality
players and more money. The Pistons were willing to receive No. 1
draft picks from the Lakers and the Knicks in addition to an
unspecified amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the trade broke Monday afternoon, Pistons executives
said the team's offices were besieged with negative calls, and they
acknowledged that public opinion might have given them doubts.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the All-Star Grant Hill to Orlando earlier this
month, Detroit was trying to find a creative way to make itself
competitive over the next several years. The best way for the
Pistons to achieve that goal is to acquire players with one year
left on their contracts in order to free salary-cap room to bid for
free agents like Chris Webber and Dikembe Mutombo next summer.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer of monster multiteam deals that involved some of the
game's most prominent players, the proposed trade would have been
the biggest in league history. Last week's four-team, nine-player
swap, which involved Golden State, Utah, Dallas and Boston, marked
the first time four teams agreed to trade players in one package.
With salary complications, that deal took nearly a week to
complete. Prolonging the process was that the three players first
had to sign with their previous teams. One player originally
included in the trade, Utah's Scott Padgett, was eventually taken
out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   So while Ewing was still a Knick Monday night, the prospects of
his remaining in New York are over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to win it here,'' Herb Williams, a former Knick,
said Monday night at Madison Square Garden, where he was attending
the Liberty's WNBA playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dominating post players in the NBA's modern era,
Ewing was taken by the Knicks with the No. 1 selection in the 1985
college draft. They won the pick that season by winning the NBA's
first draft lottery; it was a day that sent long-suffering fans
cheering into the streets of Manhattan with the knowledge that the
Knicks would select the scowling, shot-blocking menace from
Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing would lead the Knicks into the playoffs 13 straight years.
With him, the Knicks advanced to the Eastern Conference finals
three times. In 1994, they came within a game of winning the
franchise's first title since 1973 before losing to the Houston
Rockets in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Holder of most major club records, Ewing ended last season as
the 14th-leading scorer in league history. He is fourth in blocked
shots and he played in his 1,000th game last season. Ewing is one
of seven players in NBA annals to spend 15 years with the same
team.
</P>
<P>
   If his longevity was impressive, though, his durability was
wearing thin. In the last three seasons, he missed 88
regular-season games because of injury. From a dislocated right
wrist to a partial tear in his left Achilles' tendon, his
production was severely limited by his health. He could not play in
the 1999 championship series against the San Antonio Spurs, a
series the Knicks lost in five games. He began last season on the
injury list.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ewing came back and silenced his critics for most of the
regular season. He started 62 games, and he dutifully took on a
reduced role in an offense suddenly powered by Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But as the playoffs came, the old question began to re-emerge
outside and inside the locker room: Were the Knicks better off
without their franchise center, the plodding, aging 7-footer whose
post-up, half-court style came to be viewed as a blight to the
Knicks' new high-octane outfit? He would miss two games in the
playoffs because of his Achilles' problem.
</P>
<P>
   In complete games without Ewing against the Indiana Pacers in
the past two postseasons, the Knicks went 5-1. Sprewell tried to
play down the controversy during the Indiana series in June,
saying, ``If we win the championship, Patrick has to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But privately, he, Larry Johnson and others were convinced Ewing
was slowing the offense down.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, John Starks, a former Knick, said: ``You never
know what it took for him to go in the locker room night in and
night out, to take the blame when he didn't win. He's been taking
the blame his whole career. Now there's no more finger-pointing
with Patrick Ewing gone.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
