<P>
   Forty percent of Americans define themselves as evangelical, or
born-again, Christians. That number has grown in the past 30 years,
said Michael Lindsay, Gallup Organization consultant for theology,
religion and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Gallup defines an evangelical as a person meeting three
criteria: Believes the Bible is the actual word of God; experienced
a personal conversion; and seeks to lead non-Christians to
conversion. The Religious Right is a subgroup of evangelicals that
is more political and represents about 10 percent of evangelicals,
according to Gallup.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats, 46percent would identify themselves as
evangelical. It's 53percent for Republicans and 40 percent for
Independents. The identification goes beyond conservative
Republicans and crosses denominational lines.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates pay attention to these numbers, Lindsay said, and
after Bill Clinton's impeachment trial, Americans are more
interested in how the personal beliefs of a candidate would affect
his actions in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans see morality and religion tied together,''
Lindsay said. ``For example, 84 percent in this country say Jesus
Christ is God or the son of God. That's remarkable. If you compare
it with Great Britain, about 46percent believe in the divinity of
Christ. Hence, when someone says they have a personal relationship
with Jesus Christ, that does make a difference for a sizable number
of people. They are using the language of evangelicals.''
</P>
<P>
   So, when Bush said Jesus Christ was his favorite political
philosopher, a lot of Americans nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have kids wearing WWJD? armbands,''
Anderson said. ``They're not Christian Right, but they go to
church, are concerned about the direction of the country, and they
are a little more ambivalent about where society is going. Does
faith set well with them? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is Southern Baptist and is active at a church in Arlington,
Va. He grew up in a culture where such talk comes naturally. Bush
grew up Episcopalian and is now Methodist. He had a conversion
experience at a Billy Graham crusade.
</P>
<P>
   For those people who are not in the Jesus camp, these public
professions bring mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Jesus,'' says Ibrahim Hooper, spokesman for the
Washington, D.C.-based Council on American-Islamic Relations. ``We
would hope that a leader would have a firm moral base and that most
often means a spiritual base as well. We're not particularly
disturbed that someone would express their faith openly.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Paikowsky, executive vice president of the Jewish Federation
of Greater Phoenix, worries about the next step: How political
philosophies tied to Jesus will determine how the country is run.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is thrilled that Gore has picked an Orthodox Jew as a
running mate, Paikowsky said he believes personal religious beliefs
should be kept out of public conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good from many standpoints,'' he said of Joe Lieberman,
Gore's running mate, ``but it doesn't change my general point of
view that I hope candidates continue to be disciplined with regard
to introducing their faith into the electoral campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   People want to know that candidates have thought deeply about
faith issues, and they have the right to know how religious beliefs
will direct actions, said the Rev. Dr. C.Welton Gaddy, executive
director of the Interfaith Alliance. The national organization
represents 100,000 Protestants, Catholics, Muslims, Jews and 50
other faith traditions, and promotes the role of religion in public
life.
</P>
<P>
   But people also can be suspicious about the sincerity of such
statements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you only use religious language when it is politically
profitable?'' he asked. ``If that is the case, are you being
religious or are you being political?''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing private religion into the public world has high risks
and could be in bad taste, Marty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more ample use of religion plays its part, they better
handle it with care,'' he said. ``They better know the risks, and
they better know they will be accused of hypocrisy, and they better
search their hearts. Religion is so easy to exploit. {hellip}
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, if you want to be president of all the people, you
have to watch things. I think we've had enough of the testifying.
Now, we have to see what they do with policies.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at kelly.ettenborough(a)arizona
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-7728.
</P>
