</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ANNE STEPHENSON'S NEW&AMP;NOTABLE BOOK REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Anne Stephenson(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Speical for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``THE HEAD GAME''
</P>
<P>
   By Roger Kahn
</P>
<P>
   (Harcourt, $25)
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing chess at 90 miles an hour, and that's not
boring at all,'' Kahn said when former pitcher Clem Labine asked
him if he was tired of watching baseball. Indeed, this book, due
out in early September, is just another excuse to talk about the
game, and that's OK by us. Kahn's hook is what Labine called ``the
head game: the pitcher thinking, the catcher thinking, the batter,
the anticipating and all the rest.'' There's lots of history as
Kahn talks about the intricacies of pitching and the ``armed men''
who have made their mark. When he once asked Pete Rose to name the
greatest pitcher he'd faced, Rose named three: Sandy Koufax, Bob
Gibson and Juan Marichal. Kahn ties them at second, behind Christy
Mathewson. ``Forget 1910,'' he says. ``Mathewson today would throw
splitters, circle changes and all the rest and outthink the
Griffeys, the McGwires and everyone else. Plus he looked like
Apollo - not a bad thing.'' It's something to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``BETRAYAL OF TRUST: THE COLLAPSE OF GLOBAL PUBLIC HEALTH''
</P>
<P>
   By Laurie Garrett
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $30)
</P>
<P>
   This is a formidable book in size and subject, one that's not
easy to embrace when most of us view global health as distant and
irrelevant to our lives. Newsday's Garrett admits that ``public
health is a negative - when it's at its best, nothing happens.''
But it is not at its best, and we now worry naively if what is
``over there'' might come ``here.'' Garrett visited India to study
the pneumonic plague, Zaire to focus on the Ebola epidemic that
flourished after corruption destroyed all basic elements of public
health, and Russia, where life expectancy plummeted after the
Soviet Union collapsed. Finally, she returns to the United States
to address the devastating effects of budget cuts during the Reagan
years, the rise of antibiotic-resistant diseases, the threat of
bioterrorism and the effects of HMOs and wealth disparities on
public health. It's accessible, informative reading about an issue
that affects the world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``BLUE GOLD''
</P>
<P>
   By Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Brynhild Sigurd, and you don't want to meet her in a
dark alley. She is nearly 7feet tall, which never helps, and her
heart is cold - as Cussler says with his dubious flair for
description, ``she could have sprung whole from the permafrost.''
Brynhild lives in Valhalla, her redwood castle on the shore of Lake
Tahoe, and holds business meetings aboard a life-sized Viking ship
that sits in what passes for her living room. Needless to say, she
is trouble - she is, in fact, plotting to take over the world's
supply of fresh water. Her first ruthless act is the 1991
kidnapping of a beautiful scientist who had discovered how to
purify saltwater, but things went awry and the scientist became the
captive ``goddess'' of a remote Indian tribe in the rain forest of
Venezuela. Luckily, Cussler's manly hero, Kurt Austin, is on hand
to flirt with the scientist and figure out what Brynhild is up to.
If you like action and don't want to think too hard, Brynhild and
Kurt are for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``SIN BOLDLY''
</P>
<P>
   By David R. Williams
</P>
<P>
   (Perseus, $7.95)
</P>
<P>
   Will anyone read this book? New &AMP; Notable did, waving our fists
occasionally in a show of solidarity, but then we have a soft spot
for quirky ideas. Its real target audience is college students, who
are a harder sell. Subtitled Dr. Dave's Guide to Writing the
College Paper, it tells us what professors want to see in material
submitted by their students: care with grammar and word usage,
awareness of audience, clarity of ideas and expression - in short,
a good performance. Williams, a professor of English at George
Mason University, was tired of correcting the same errors year
after year, so he wrote some ideas on how his students could make
their work better. Self-published at first, the book has come up in
the world and is attracting attention as a blunt, irreverently
philosophical and occasionally long-winded treatise on selling
yourself and your ideas. It's also a primer on that well-known path
to success: pleasing the boss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
