r e BC-SAVINGGRACE-REVIEW-AZ     08-22 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVINGGRACE-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SAVINGGRACE-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A `GRACE' PERIOD FROM NOISE OF SUMMER(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charm is an undervalued commodity in movies these days.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of sprawling, violent epics and empty special-effects
vehicles, there's not much room for whimsy. And that's too bad
because films such as (beginitalic)Saving Grace (enditalic)prove
how enchanting such movies can be.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Saving Grace (enditalic)is a small film with some
big laughs, mostly due to stellar performances by Brenda Blethyn
((beginitalic)Secrets &AMP; Lies(enditalic)) and Craig Ferguson
((beginitalic)The Drew Carey Show(enditalic)), who play residents
of a quirky fishing village on the Cornish coast.
</P>
<P>
   Blethyn is Grace Trevethen, whose late husband jumped out of a
plane sans parachute, leaving her with a manor house and a mountain
of debt. Ferguson plays Grace's gardener, Matthew, who proposes
digging Grace out of debt by growing marijuana in her spacious
greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is really secondary in this film, which is all tone and
mood, sprinkled with picturesque shots of the Cornish countryside
and cliffs overhanging the Atlantic. The score is equally
entrancing, and the humor is droll and decidedly British, keeping a
smile on your face throughout.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this is an actor's movie.
</P>
<P>
   Blethyn carries the film with an utterly convincing portrayal of
Grace, a middle-age woman who has to put aside her morals to save
her home. Ferguson, who also co-wrote the movie, slips easily into
the role of Matthew, an easygoing but rugged Scotsman determined to
settle down with his girlfriend, Nicky (Valerie Edmond).
</P>
<P>
   Nicky provides a nice moral rudder for the film, warning Matthew
that his stunt may have consequences and keeping the movie from
becoming a British version of (beginitalic)Up in Smoke(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The film is buoyed by the gang of oddball townspeople who are
determined to help Grace any way they can: the local tavern keeper,
a pair of elderly lady shopkeepers and the seemingly out-of-touch
town constable. Martin Clunes is especially effective in the role
of the town doctor, who takes a fairly relaxed approach to his
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The film is alternately sidesplitting and poignant as we watch
Grace and Matthew struggle to build their marijuana farm in secret,
with some fairly uneven results. When the greenhouse lights up the
entire night sky, the townspeople first blame aliens and then turn
the whole thing into evening entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a funny bit in which Grace, as the ultimate fish
out of water, goes to London to try to peddle her wares. There she
finds an unlikely ally and meets a French drug dealer (Tcheky
Karyo), who has a hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   While the ending is a bit too pat, by that time, we're all too
charmed to care.
</P>
<P>
   And with (beginitalic)Saving Grace(enditalic), that's really the
point.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
