<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8709 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-THECELL-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      08-22 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THECELL-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-THECELL-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `THE CELL' UNLOCKS PSYCHOLOGICAL HELL(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At times, (beginitalic)The Cell (enditalic)is really tough to
watch. But you just can't take your eyes off it.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally powerful and visually stunning, (beginitalic)The
Cell (enditalic)is a triumph of art direction, set design,
costuming and shotmaking. It is, quite simply, like nothing you've
seen before. Or would want to see again, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   The film is patently disturbing and includes gory, graphic
violence that is not for the faint of heart. Still, it succeeds
through sheer magnitude and sweep, with a clever, taut story that
keeps you guessing until the end.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Jennifer Lopez as Catherine Deane, a psychologist
who can enter a comatose mind through the use of a radically new
technique. Once inside, she attempts to counsel the other mind,
attempting to bring the person back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not quite sure what's going on. Others in the film
question whether the therapy works, suggesting that Deane is
actually seeing drug-induced hallucinations and not connecting with
the other mind at all.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the macabre dream sequences are spectacular from the
opening scene, in which Deane rides a magnificent black horse past
giant sand dunes to meet with a child she is trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, FBI agent Peter Novak (Vince Vaughn) is on the trail
of serial killer Carl Stargher (Vincent D'Onofrio), a sadomasochist
who tortures and kills women who have certain doll-like features.
The police manage to catch Stargher, but not before he slips into a
coma, leaving his last victim hidden with just 40 hours to live.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Deane and her revolutionary treatment. She volunteers to
enter the killer's mind to find the girl. From there, things get
really freaky.
</P>
<P>
   Combining computer effects with brilliant sets and costumes,
director Tarsem Singh takes the audience inside the killer's
twisted mind, creating a nightmarish dreamscape filled with
medieval torture chambers, snarling demons and opulent throne
rooms, where Stargher indulges his sick fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   We watch with fascination as Deane plays Alice, falling into a
surreal wonderland, where the White Rabbit is replaced by spiders,
snakes and other, even less pleasant, creatures - watch for a horse
of a really different color.
</P>
<P>
   Deane is constantly in danger of accepting the bizarre world as
real and perhaps never escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Those scenes are interspersed with the killer's childhood
memories, which include a sparkling 360-degree shot of an
old-fashioned baptism and an artfully shot sequence involving
Stargher's abusive father.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the movie really takes off and, at the same time,
veers into some gory violence. There's one torture scene that will
make most people uncomfortable, and the ending is also quite
bloody. But it seems that the film is trying to be true to its
nature in reflecting the twisted mind of a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez does a nice job in the leading role, portraying the
psychologist with equal amounts of sympathy and determination. She
also gets to wear fabulous costumes as she plays different roles in
the killer's fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is a standout as the obsessed, haunted FBI agent who's
struggling to find the killer's latest victim. He plays the role
with appropriate weariness, as if he hasn't slept for days.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's D'Onofrio, who portrays several characters in this
film as the killer adopts different personas inside his dream
world. He's under a lot of makeup but turns in a solid performance.
</P>
<P>
   But (beginitalic)The Cell's (enditalic)not really about acting.
It's more of a visual feast. Some of the shots are so amazing
they're really hard to describe.
</P>
<P>
   You just have to be there.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
