<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      08-22 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB SITE AND MAGAZINE REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Web site and current
magazines: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.twain2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain has been dead for a while, but that doesn't mean he
wouldn't make a boffo U.S. president. Fortunately he's running. Or
at least that's the premise of this oddball site, which appears to
be a campaign clearinghouse for fake press releases, fake polls and
campaign-related sound bites (actually uttered once by the
candidate), and it would all be very jolly if Twain's century-old
quotes about various issues weren't so much smarter than what we're
likely to hear from the actual candidates. Our favorite click at
this address allows acolytes to file their own personal campaign
endorsement. ``It is nearly impossible to be morally bankrupt when
you're dead,'' says one. Our second-favorite click is the media
resources page, which advises reporters that ``the candidate's
schedule does not allow interviews except when he can be caught on
the campaign trail {ellipsis} (but) senior advisers to the campaign
are available to respond to media inquiries.'' Run, Sam, run.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``BUSINESS WEEK''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently suffering from hernia envy caused by its upstart New
Economy competitors, (beginitalic)BW(enditalic) lays on the heft
with a double issue themed to describing the 21st-century
corporation. Big bosses will ponder the meaning of it all while
counting down the days till their golden parachutes poof open. Cube
drones, meanwhile, will enjoy the unintended hilarity of such
predictions as the dawning of the age of ``knowledge manager.''
Some companies are already giving this position a shot, writes Neil
Gross, explaining that knowledge management ``preaches that human
skills, expertise and relationships are the most precious resources
in an organization.'' We'll pause for a second until all the
laughter dies down. OK, that's enough. Other features include an
examination of Internet gambling, a look at the Gore-Lieberman
ticket's fiscal plans and a profile - on page 240 - of U.S. Olympic
Committee chief executive Norman Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``FAST COMPANY''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of backbreaking reads, (beginitalic)FC
(enditalic)pushes its total September page count above 400 by
offering a 100-page special report on ``the new realities of the
New Economy.'' (beginitalic)New (enditalic)being more or less the
key concept. Otherwise, Daniel H. Pink's page 90 review of the new
David Brooks book is something every (beginitalic)Fast Company
(enditalic)subscriber will enjoy, primarily because the book -
(beginitalic)Bobos in Paradise (enditalic)- will flatter them
stupid. Bobos, you see, are Bourgeois Bohemians, and they are, Pink
says Brooks says, ``today's emperors.'' The book's thesis:
``Dumb-looking people with great parents have been displaced by
smart, ambitious, educated and anti-establishment people with
scuffed shoes.'' We've got the shoes part down, at least.
Meanwhile, no preconceptions will be dashed by the portrait of
``photographers' rep'' Julian Richards on page 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``FORBES ASAP''
</P>
<P>
   This issue throws itself at the coming transition from the
electron-driven New Economy to the photon-driven New Economy, and
if the pace of change is driving you nuts, perhaps you should cease
reading magazines like this, bucko, and just kick back with a
(beginitalic)People (enditalic)or a (beginitalic)TV Guide
(enditalic)or whatnot. Anyway, something called optical networks
promise infinite bandwidth, and infinite bandwidth is what we live
for. We'll pause momentarily while speculation rages about our need
for infinite bandwidth. Anyway (again), ``communications guru''
George Gilder says that optical networks ``are vital to the
fulfillment of the business plans of the Internet economy and the
future of world peace and prosperity.'' And to think,
(beginitalic)you have no idea what he's talking about.
(enditalic)Adds Gilder: ``The Internet is best imagined as a
virtual point of light into which will be distilled all the
commerce and culture of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``ESQUIRE''
</P>
<P>
   Just to prove that we're not silly drunk on tech rags, here
comes the ``Big Style Issue'' of the Big E, filled with handsome
dudes modeling handsome duds. Elsewhere, the dependably brilliant
Tom Carson illuminates the dark side of prime-time game shows
(we're clipping and saving and maybe framing Roberto Parada's
sizzling Regis illustration), Billy Crudup is touted as the next
breakout movie star, Elvis Mitchell celebrates blaxploitation
soundtracks, and there's a special report on rage. Grrr. But the
highlight of the issue for us is the almost overlookable blurb
about bacon becoming the new cocaine. (Bow ties and Jersey City get
the same hey-they're-cool-again treatment in the same spread so,
you know, grain of salt.) There is evidently a Bacon of the Month
Club, and it reports a recent 500 percent increase in enrollment.
Dr. Atkins, you (beginitalic)rule(enditalic), bro! Join the Bacon
of the Month Club by calling 1-888-472-5283. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Magaine reviews
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
