<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-B-GOLDBERG-AZR &LR;      08-22 2486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B-GOLDBERG-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-B-GOLDBERG-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PHYSICIAN: SOME PATIENTS MAKE FALSE ACCUSATIONS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVID PARRISH AND JODIE SNYDER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Mark D. Goldberg has been in more trouble for more reasons
than perhaps any other physician in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He once prescribed 1,532 addictive painkillers to a woman
without examining her.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of trading drug prescriptions for sex.
</P>
<P>
   When the state sent an undercover agent to his office with a
fake injury, he appeared to coach her on how to get workers'
compensation benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his patients died when either their X-rays or tests went
unread or ignored; another died when her severe headache turned out
to be a ruptured blood vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Board of Medical Examiners has censured Goldberg,
placed him on probation and publicly questioned his competency.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of that, he is still practicing medicine in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the 42-year-old family practitioner has
owned and operated up to four clinics in Mesa and Apache Junction.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Goldberg filed for bankruptcy protection, in part
because a patient was suing him, accusing him of sexual misconduct,
and his malpractice insurance policy wouldn't pay if he lost the
case. The suit is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg had amassed debts of $434,000, according to bankruptcy
records. He listed as debts and expenses a $1,000-a-month lease on
a new Mercedes-Benz, $30,000 in credit card charges, $1,800 in
monthly child support payments and a $2,900 monthly mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg declined a request for an interview on the advice of
his attorney. In a written statement, Goldberg said he has treated
thousands of patients for years without problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say I have had no patient complaints,'' he
wrote. ``What I can say is that I have done my best to provide my
patients with the high quality care they deserve and that I
continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AN EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg never graduated from college, according to his
testimony in legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City native, he attended a community college and a
state university in Los Angeles, but left without a degree to
pursue a career in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he went to the Caribbean, where he attended
Universidad C.E.T.E.C. Escuela de Medicina in the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from medical school in 1983, and the next year, the
school closed after revelations that officials were selling medical
degrees for $5,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pay for anything you want here - diplomas,
transcripts, grades, anything,'' Roger Heil, a New York medical
student, told a reporter in 1984 when the medical school and
another in Santo Domingo were shut down by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Some students never attended classes; they just paid tuition and
got their degrees, Dominican Republic officials said in news
reports at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In his written statement, Goldberg acknowledged that his medical
school was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to point out that the school was accredited
during the period I attended there and that I spent the last two
years of medical school in an exchange program attending the
University of Maryland affiliated hospitals,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg came back to the United States and did his residency
training at South Nassau Community Hospital in Oceanside, N.Y.
Afterward, he taught at a medical and dental college, then worked
in a New Jersey urgent-care clinic. There are no records of
problems during this time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Goldberg came West to practice medicine in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, he became Anna Pauer's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   A Mesa real estate agent and grandmother, Pauer, 69, was
terrified of cancer after her husband died of the disease. She kept
asking Goldberg to watch for signs of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A radiologist read one of Pauer's routine X-rays in 1990 and
spotted what he thought might be a cancerous growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspect vascular lesion in the upper part of the right kidney.
This could conceivably be a neoplasm (possible cancer),'' wrote Dr.
M. Kirdani in his August 1990 report.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg did nothing for nearly four years.
</P>
<P>
   A May 1994 chest X-ray confirmed Pauer's worst fears: She had
cancer. Pauer died three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Her family sued Goldberg, saying he should have diagnosed the
cancer earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg testified in a deposition that he never saw the
radiologist's report, despite the fact that it was in Pauer's
medical file in his office.
</P>
<P>
   There were other indications that Pauer might have cancer.
Lesions were found in a 1992 bone scan, but Goldberg went along
with a cancer specialist's opinion that no further testing was
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The medical board reviewed the case in October 1995 and decided
against discipline. Instead, the board issued Goldberg a
non-disciplinary advisory letter. Pauer's family and Goldberg
settled the lawsuit out of court for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS WERE DYING
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, two more of Goldberg's patients died.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, a 33-year-old woman with a history of high
blood pressure and circulatory problems told Goldberg she had
severe headaches and a persistent cough. Previously, she suffered a
subdural hematoma, an enlarged blood clot in the layer of tissue
covering the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg checked her lungs but performed no other exam, although
severe headaches are a sign of a hematoma or a hemorrhage. Goldberg
noted in her file that she was doing remarkably well, according to
medical board records.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after seeing Goldberg, the woman, who is not
identified in medical board records, was examined by another doctor
who ordered a brain scan. The scan revealed bleeding on the surface
of the brain. She died shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   If treated quickly, about half of patients survive such a
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1996 hearing on the matter, Dr. Barry Weiss, a medical
board member, said the headache ``warranted a more comprehensive
examination than was noted in her chart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Specifically,'' he said, ``because she died three days later.
She probably had some significant problems during that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Another patient died of lung cancer that was clearly visible in
an X-ray that Goldberg didn't examine for six weeks, according to
the medical board.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, 1994, Goldberg ordered a chest X-ray during a
routine physical for a 73-year-old man. The man had other chest
X-rays annually for the five previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, the man, who was not identified by the medical
board, returned, reporting chills and a temperature. Goldberg still
had not read the January X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   A different doctor ordered more X-rays and found a tumor the
size of a golf ball in the man's right lung. He died May 19, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he had five sets of X-rays since 1989, there was no
evidence that (Goldberg) read these X-rays,'' Weiss said during the
subsequent board hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg told the board that he read the man's X-rays from 1989
on. He couldn't explain why the medical file didn't indicate that
he had looked at the X-rays. There must have been a mix-up, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, he didn't get to X-rays quickly when the patient
seemed to be in good health, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever the reason, we had gotten four or five weeks
behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FLOWING PHARMACY
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Goldberg also prescribed powerful drugs to at
least seven patients with brief or no examinations or without
exploring other treatments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Goldberg prescribed to one patient the equivalent
of 2.1 daily dosages of Lortab, a painkiller, from 1993 to 1995
without documenting that he conducted any examination, according to
medical board records.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Goldberg repeatedly refilled a 10-year-old's
Ritalin prescription without ever seeing the child, board records
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor is rather quick on the draw to treat people with
controlled substances and narcotics for problems that are not well
documented, and often the narcotics are used instead of or in
advance of more standard treatment. That's sort of not good
medicine,'' Weiss said in a report to the medical board.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to questions about his medical practices, Goldberg
has faced accusations of sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Two female patients accused him of preying on them when they
went to him for medical care. Goldberg has repeatedly denied any
impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some patients make false charges against physicians,''
Goldberg wrote to(beginitalic) The Republic. (enditalic)''It has
been my misfortune to have experienced the reality of that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rena Headlee, a single mother of three, went to see
Goldberg after a 1992 auto accident, she already had seen a lot of
trouble in her life. She had been abused as a child; she had been
divorced twice; and a third husband had died of cancer. She had a
history of abusing prescription drugs and had undergone treatment
for addiction and depression at a Tucson clinic.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Goldberg gave Headlee painkillers for neck and back
pain. Within a few months, she couldn't sleep without taking one or
two sleeping pills, she said in legal records. She also began
taking Xanax, a drug that eases anxiety and panic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Headlee attempted suicide by overdosing on sleeping
pills. She saw an orthopedic surgeon, who wrote Goldberg a letter
urging him to wean her from the addictive medication.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg did just the opposite, Headlee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me to know that the average doctor wouldn't be
giving this medicine due to (my) history. Basically, it's just you
do me a favor, I'm doing you a favor,'' she told medical board
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The favor he wanted? Sex, according to Headlee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets your hand and puts it on his privates,'' Headlee said
in a January 1996 interview with medical board investigators. ``He
just wants you to turn around, and it's like a minute or two and
that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Headlee said she had sex at least 20 times with Goldberg in his
medical offices in Mesa and Apache Junction.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg would write her a prescription for 20 pills, then if
she cooperated sexually, he would write a prescription for 100
more, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Headlee said, she persuaded Goldberg to postdate
prescriptions so she wouldn't have to come to his clinic as
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, nearly four years after it started, Headlee said she
felt like ``dirt because of what I was doing,'' and she went to the
Mesa Police Department. They investigated and decided there wasn't
enough evidence to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   Headlee then reported what happened to the medical board.
Attorneys associated with the case said the board is still
investigating.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Headlee fatally shot herself.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said Headlee's charge ``was both unbelievable and sad
because it was indicative of a troubled mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's attorneys also contend thatHeadlee had a history of
making sexual allegations. They cited a 1992 Mesa Police Department
report in which Headlee accused a Mesa police officer of fondling
her.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SEX ALLEGATIONS
</P>
<P>
   While Headlee's tragedy was unfolding, another woman was
accusing Goldberg of sexual advances.
</P>
<P>
   Cyndie Mathers, 41, who suffers from a brain injury and
associated behavioral problems, went to Goldberg to get referrals
to a radiologist and neurologist, mainly to pursue a lawsuit
against another doctor. She alleges in an ongoing lawsuit that
Goldberg solicited sex from her in exchange for the referrals.
</P>
<P>
   The medical board said she appeared to have a vendetta against
Goldberg, and in 1996, dismissed her complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office also investigated but could
not build a case against Goldberg, records show. Two
surreptitiously taped conversations were judged to be inconclusive
by investigators because Goldberg never directly asked for sex.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of a Dec. 9, 1993, taped conversation between the two:
</P>
<P>
   Mathers: ``Do you want to meet at a motel or do you want to meet
here or do you want to?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg: ``Either way, we'll decide. Let's get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathers: ``When? You name the time. You name the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg: ``Mmm, (pause). How about next week?''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to (beginitalic)The Republic(enditalic),
Goldberg said he never sought sex from Mathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had any poor judgment in regard to Ms. Mathers, it was
agreeing to try to help her medically when I was aware of her
history with the other doctors,'' Goldberg wrote.
</P>
<P>
   TAPED CONVERSATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the Attorney General's Office sent Special Agent
Linda Bergevin to Goldberg's office. She posed as a stripper who
had slipped on some beer at work and injured her knee and wrist.
She told Goldberg she wanted to pursue a workers' compensation
claim and a lawsuit against the bar owner.
</P>
<P>
   Transcripts of conversations recorded with a hidden microphone
during several office visits with Goldberg make it clear she was
playing up to him to see if he would proposition her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the nicest doctor I've ever met,'' she cooed to
Goldberg at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg did ask Bergevin out for a drink, but he seemed more
interested in the insurance claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was your right wrist and your right knee, right?'' Goldberg
asked Bergevin during one office visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your wrist is fine now, right?'' Goldberg asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But your knee is still bothering you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we'll just say that it's still bothering you,'' Goldberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still bothering - how long does it have to still bother
me?'' Bergevin asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another couple of weeks,'' Goldberg said, suggesting she come
for three more office visits. ``I mean, just to create a nice
picture for the whole thing. If your pain goes away completely,
well then at that point, a couple more weeks I'll see you and then
we'll dump it. That'll be the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But will I still put my claim in?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, of course,'' Goldberg said. ``They believe anything a
doctor says.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 medical board hearing, Goldberg denied he ever
meant to defraud the state with a specious workers' compensation
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg could not explain to the board why he asked the
undercover agent out for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office considered seeking criminal
charges against Goldberg, but decided not to because the state was
never actually defrauded, records show. In January 1996, the
medical board censured Goldberg in the case.
</P>
<P>
   For his other problems, over prescribing drugs and his
questionable treatment of the two patients who died, the medical
board in 1996 gave Goldberg five years of probation and ordered him
to take an exam to prove his medical competency.
</P>
<P>
   He passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
