<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT &LR;      08-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES BEAT METS ON WALK IN 10TH, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The crowd started hooting on Dennis Cook's first
ball to Dave Magadan with the bases loaded in the bottom of the
10th Monday night. The hoots became roars when ball two sailed by.
In his second inning of work, Cook had already walked four hitters.
The unpredictable Mets left-hander was about to unravel again.
</P>
<P>
   Cook got a called strike, then a fastball came in a little low.
Cook smirked _ he felt his strike zone had been squeezed by the
home plate umpire, Gerry Davis, in the ninth _ and his final pitch
was at Magadan's shoe tops. It was ball four, and it forced in the
winning run as the Padres beat the Mets, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Cook (6-3) stalked off the mound, hollering at Davis and holding
his hands close together, giving his representation of Davis'
strike zone. Cook shook his head and glanced once more toward Davis
before slipping into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mets two and a half games behind Atlanta in
the National League East, but they retained their
three-and-a-half-game lead over Arizona in the wild-card race.
Trevor Hoffman (4-4) was the winner for San Diego in relief of
Woody Williams, who pitched nine innings but lost a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres got out of the top of the ninth when Derek Bell of
the Mets was called out for interfering with Padres catcher Wiki
Gonzalez, who was trying to catch Darryl Hamilton stealing. Manager
Bobby Valentine argued unsuccessfully with Davis, and Cook came in
to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez led off the ninth with a smash to right-center, and Jay
Payton _ who is fast enough and takes good enough reads to play
shallow _ dashed back to the warning track to take away an
extra-base hit. But pinch-hitter Joe Vitiello walked, and
pinch-runner Damian Jackson stole second. With two outs and runners
at first and second, Cook fanned Ryan Klesko on a sidearm slider to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook opened the 10th with a walk to Phil Nevin. Ruben Rivera
reached on a fielder's choice, and a single by Mike Darr and a walk
to Gonzalez loaded the bases for the pinch-hitter Magadan.
</P>
<P>
   Glendon Rusch's outing had long since ended by then, but his
perseverance allowed the Mets to use their bullpen later rather
than sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Ten times in Rusch's first 13 starts this year, he pitched at
least six innings and allowed no more than three earned runs. For
only the fourth time in 10 starts, Rusch matched that criteria, and
the Mets needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch had to give the Mets innings; the bullpen worked four and
a third innings Sunday, and the long reliever Pat Mahomes is
starting Tuesday for Mike Hampton, who is being held back because
of a stress fracture in his right ribs, which forced him from his
start last Thursday. Hampton will probably need to throw two
bullpen sessions before he can start again, and the Mets are not
sure when that will be.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres jumped to a 4-0 lead, partly because of sloppy
defense but also because they wore down a control pitcher. With two
outs and the bases empty in the first, Klesko fouled off four
pitches with a 3-2 count. Rusch, who averages only two walks per
nine innings, lost the duel and walked Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Then he had Klesko picked off, but first baseman Lenny Harris,
giving Todd Zeile a day off, threw the ball off Klesko's body for
an error. Phil Nevin's bloop single scored Klesko with an unearned
run.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch threw 34 pitches that inning and 36 in the second, an
inning that began with Rivera being hit by a pitch. Darr singled,
but with two outs, Eric Owens reached on an infield single when
second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo threw late to third in an attempt to
catch Rivera off base.
</P>
<P>
   The bases were loaded, and Rusch did the unthinkable: He walked
the weak-hitting Desi Relaford to force in a run. Rusch kicked his
leg in frustration, and Klesko slammed down his bat and helmet when
he struck out one batter later to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch continued to stumble in the third, when his curveball
escaped him as Rivera bashed it for a run-scoring triple and Darr
pounded it for a run-scoring single that put the Padres ahead, 4-0.
A line-drive double play ended the inning, and there was no telling
then that Rusch would settle down as he did, allowing one hit and
striking out four over three scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could not score for him until the sixth. In the fourth,
Mike Piazza rifled a low line drive to the warning track in left
field, where the ball took one bounce off the soft wall. Piazza
could get only a single; he had hit it too hard for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   Singles by Robin Ventura and Benny Agbayani loaded the bases for
Jay Payton, who was 0 for 16 in his career with the bases loaded.
He lined out to right, where Darr caught the ball and threw to
first baseman Klesko, whose relay beat a sliding Piazza for the
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, after Ventura's third single put runners at first
and second, Agbayani blasted Williams' first pitch over the fence
in left-center field. It was his 11th home run, and probably his
most important since his game-winning grand slam in Tokyo in March.
The three-run blast got the Mets into the game, and they tied it,
4-4, in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick reached on a throwing error by the shortstop
Relaford and, with one out, Harris singled Bordick to third. Bell,
who is in the midst of another awful slump, chopped a ball in front
of first base, where Williams fielded it, wheeled and threw to
home. But Bordick slid by with the tying run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
