</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-ROCKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY DEFEATS ROCKERS, 81-67, TO REACH WNBA FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the mad-dash opening minutes of Monday night's
Eastern Conference finals, the Liberty played as if there were only
a tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The present passed in a blur, as Liberty players steamrolled the
visiting Cleveland Rockers in the first half, turning them into
wide-eyed tourists unnerved by the rush of bodies, bright lights
and brash sounds in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty launched a 30-2 run from the opening tap and held
the Rockers scoreless for 10 minutes in the first half, which was
nearly a repeat of what happened in Sunday's Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in another nightmarish repeat of Game 2 for the
Liberty, the Rockers recovered in the second half, closing within
10 points with just under three minutes remaining in the game and
introducing doubt into what had been total domination.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty players have used doubt as a weapon this year, and
in the final minutes once again turned back Cleveland to send the
confetti showering onto the Garden floor, draping an exhaustive but
eventually convincing 81-67 victory over the Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, the Liberty captured the Eastern
Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of ourselves because of what we had to go through
with nobody believing in us, and here we are again,'' the team
captain, Teresa Weatherspoon, said. ``We're happy with what we
accomplished, but we haven't accomplished anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in the four-year history of the Women's
National Basketball Association, the Liberty earned a trip to the
finals, to play the league's only champions, the Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   The two-of-three-game series opens Thursday night in the Garden,
where the Liberty has won 13 straight games, then shifts to Houston
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it got down to 10 points, I was a little bit nervous,''
said Liberty center Tari Phillips, who scored all 12 of her points
in her team's remarkable 46-point first half. ``But I already said
before the game, that was not our destiny. This is what we fought
for all season long; this is why we had 13 wins against great teams
at home, including Houston. We were going to take this win no
matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the Liberty played like a veteran team, using its
home-court advantage and experience to befuddle the much younger
Cleveland group, which could not overcome the Liberty's merciless
defense. The Rockers rode to the end the 13-point effort of Suzie
McConnell Serio, their 35-year-old veteran point guard, who is now
officially retired.
</P>
<P>
   It was her 3-pointer, her third of the game, that put the
Rockers within 10 points with 2 minutes 45 seconds remaining. ``We
lost our concentration,'' the Liberty's Becky Hammon said. ``We
just had to keep together. We just couldn't play not to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Hammon, the second-year shooting guard, scored 6
straight points three ways _ off foul shots, a 12-foot jumper and a
driving layup. That gave the Liberty a 14-point lead and sealed the
victory before a crowd of 15,173, which included Nets guard Stephon
Marbury, who celebrated with the team on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Tamika Whitmore, also a second-year player for the
Liberty, scored a game-high 19 points. ``Last year I came in and I
didn't know what to expect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, she was so prepared, she was unable to meditate as
usual, restless for the victory. ``This one feels better,''
Whitmore added about the Eastern Conference title. ``It feels
better because a lot of people doubted us in the beginning, and we
still became champs.''
</P>
<P>
   There was doubt after the Liberty dropped the first game of this
two-of-three series in Cleveland. There was doubt Sunday when the
Liberty allowed the Rockers to creep back into the game. But from
the start of Monday night's game, the Liberty made sure there was
no question who was in control.
</P>
<P>
   Signs in large type displaying confident quotes from the Rockers
hung on top of diagrammed plays in the Liberty locker room before
the game, as much motivation as New York would need.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, New York shot 55.9 percent from the floor,
outrebounded Cleveland, 17-12, and with 8:49 to play in the half,
New York already had a 33-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first half they were very emotional, just like
yesterday,'' said Cleveland's Merlakia Jones. ``We were taking
quick shots and they were taking advantage of it. You're just
trying to find some kind of a way to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hammon's desperation underhand floater found its way into
the basket at the buzzer to end the half, it was an omen, if not a
precursor to the end. New York led, 46-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have hung our heads, but we didn't,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland first closed the deficit to 13 points in the opening
minutes of the second half, but then the Liberty launched an 8-0
run that seemed to put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Johnson, playing on a right ankle she sprained in Game 2,
scored 14 points, and had 10 assists and six rebounds, an emblem
for a team that would not be denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, it was probably like 70 percent, but I told
Coach that once I warmed up it will be 110 percent,'' she said.
``It's really sore. I turned it three times, but thought I can't
dwell on that _ I couldn't let my team down.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson scored 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had tremendous passion tonight to win the Eastern
Conference championship,'' coach Richie Adubato said. ``That's why
we focused on such a great start in every phase of the game. We
were everywhere, we got rebounds, pushed the ball and made great
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers, meanwhile, made poor decisions, rushing shots. They
won only four road games this season, their last coming three weeks
ago. While the Liberty has been adequate on the road, 9-9, the team
has been virtually unbeatable in the Garden, with a 15-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty has not lost in the Garden since June 25, including
a 69-64 victory over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat Houston we have to do everything right,'' Whitmore
said. ``We can't have any slip-ups. When you go into the final we
can't have any mental lapses like we did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Just frantic runs, followed by confetti.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
