<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-IMMIG (Zagreb, Croatia) _ The chaotic lands of the Balkans
have become the latest gateway to western Europe for tens of
thousands of illegal immigrants from China, South Asia and Mideast
countries like Iran and Iraq, according to Western diplomats, local
officials and the increasing number of refugees who get caught en
route. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   (With map)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-THINNING (Flagstaff, Ariz.) _ The Clinton administration
has been sharply criticized for failing to do some things that
would have made this fire season less devastating. One
controversial measure, known as forest thinning, allows more
logging in places where forests have become too dense. But in many
places around the country, environmentalists have successfully
opposed this. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (With map)
</P>
<P>
   YOUTHS-EXECUTE (Undated) _ If the state of Georgia electrocutes
Alexander Williams on Thursday, as planned, five men who committed
murder when they were 17 will have been put to death this year in
the United States. That is more than in any year since 1954, when
six teenagers were executed in Florida and Georgia. While
proponents say such executions are justified, given the
increasingly heinous nature of juvenile crime, opponents call it
unconscionable. Most juvenile offenders on death row are in
Southern states, while most countries in the world prohibit the
practice. A Special Report by Sarah Rimer and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ POLITICS _ (Moved in `p' category.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-WORKING-FAMILIES (Washington) _ Through the four days of
the Democratic National Convention last week it was impossible get
through an hour, much less a day, without hearing the words
``working families.'' Neophyte candidates in obscure congressional
districts talked about them in their brief non-prime-time
appearances; the party's platform championed their needs; and the
presidential nominee himself took up their cause and continued to
pound the theme as his campaign steamed down the Mississippi River.
And it's not a matter of coincidence; the phrase was the result of
weeks of research and focus groups, and the campaign is making sure
that voters remember it. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ In the lexicon of the high-technology
companies that are reshaping the economy, terms like stock options,
profit sharing and overtime loom large. So it no small wonder that
the contract agreement reached by Verizon Communications and its
unions, which makes provisions on these issues and many more, has
raised eyebrows. While the direct effect is almost impossible to
gauge, the apparent consensus about the settlement is that the
unions came away as winners and, perhaps, as meaningful
participants in the New Economy that was ready to leave them at its
margins, according to analysts. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   DEBEERS-STRATEGY (London) _ De Beers has had to confront
accusations that the company has links to traffic in diamonds from
Africa's war zones. But it has also had to face a much bigger
challenge: the belief that its huge stockpile of diamonds, used to
help control the supply and keep world prices high, had become a
costly albatross. Now, De Beers is using the controversy over
so-called blood diamonds to advance a strategic switch to address
its commercial problems. The plan is to turn De Beers from a
stockpile manager into a branded, high-value diamond-trader that
would keep diamonds from war zones out of the luxury market.
Marketing, not monopoly, would make sure the company maintained its
leadership position. By seizing the moral high ground, De Beers has
already shown signs that its business is turning around. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 4,5,6)
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-AMERICA-INTERNET (Undated) _ The Internet revolution has
definitely come to Latin America. But whether the businesses and
jobs spawned by that revolution have helped the region begin to
wean itself from economic dependence on the United States and other
outsiders is considered a matter of debate. Starmedia, one of the
biggest and most successful Internet companies in Latin America,
has branch offices in seven countries and millions of subscribers
throughout the region. But its headquarters are in New York. Its
$450 million in funding came from investors in the United States.
Its stock is listed on the Nasdaq but not on any exchange in Latin
America. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAMES (Undated) _ Because virtually all of the catchy
Web addresses ending in ``.com'' have already been claimed, a
growing number of companies have begun to realize that there is
money to be made in helping owners re-sell the names that they no
longer want or need. By Sabra Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE/ENTERTAINMENT _ (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOXER-WRITER (Undated) _ Jerry Boyd invented F.X. Toole to
shield his boxing life _ which has brought him psychic fulfillment
but no riches _ from his writing, which had until recently brought
him only rejection. As F.X. Toole he writes fiction _ a craft that
he quietly pursued when he wasn't stopping blood coming from
fighters' noses in his work as a cutman. His first book of short
fiction, ``Rope Burns: Stories from the Corner,'' will be published
next month. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   JONI-MITCHELL-PAINTER (Saskatoon, Saskatchewan) _ From 500
paintings, drawings and photographs made over the last three
decades, the Mendel Art Gallery, a public museum here, has selected
87 pieces for Joni Mitchell's first retrospective show. As
recordings of her folk, jazz and rock songs echo through the
galleries, visitors explore an artistic side to the singer only
hinted at in the album covers she has painted over the years. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The new biography ``William
Shakespeare: The Man Behind the Genius,'' by Anthony Holden,
although breezily readable, offers no new facts about the
playwright's life. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE _ (Moved in `a' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RACE-GENES (Undated) _ Scientists have long suspected that
the racial categories recognized by society are not reflected on
the genetic level. But the more closely that researchers examine
the human genome, the more most of them are convinced that the
standard labels used to distinguish people by ``race'' have little
or no biological meaning. Are differences between humans only skin
deep? By Natalie Angier.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT 3 and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GSUIT (Undated) _ Many of today's military aircraft
accelerate so quickly and turn so rapidly that they meet or exceed
the physical limits of their pilots. And a new generation of
higher-performance jets soon to join air forces around the world
promises to worsen the problem, making it even harder for the human
component of these weapon systems to keep up with the mechanical.
By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 1,2)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CHINA-RICE (Undated) _ In a stunning new result from what
has become one of the largest agricultural experiments ever,
thousands of rice farmers in China have doubled the yields of their
most valuable crop and nearly eliminated its most devastating
disease _ without using chemical treatments or spending a single
extra penny. Led by a team of scientists, the farmers were able to
abandon chemical fungicides previously widely used to fight rice
blast _ the most important disease of the most important staple in
the world. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BUTTERFLIES-CORN (Undated) _ Ever since last year when
scientists reported that pollen from genetically engineered corn
could kill monarch butterfly caterpillars in the laboratory,
scientists have been battling over one central question: Are these
beloved butterflies being harmed by the millions of acres of
biotech corn being planted across the country? A new study suggests
the answer is yes. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Are there
really caterpillars that scream to protect themselves? If so, what
types? Can we hear the sound they make? By C. Caliborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PADIAN-AIDS (Undated) _ A conversation with Dr. Nancy
Padian, 48, an epidemiologist who is director of research for the
AIDS Research Institute of the University of California at San
Francisco. Padian is one of the world's foremost experts on the
heterosexual transmission of AIDS. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEXICO-MEDICINE (Undated) _ A medical doctor with a
scholarly interest in pre-Columbian art appears to have pushed back
the date of the earliest scientific medical illustration by several
centuries with his study of bizarre two faced ancient Mexican
figurines known to art historians as the `pretty ladies of
Tlatilco.'' By William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos NYT 13,14,15)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GROWING-TEETH (Undated) _ In a test of the accumulating new
knowledge about how organs are generated in developing organs, a
team of researchers at the Harvard Medical School and elsewhere has
succeeded in making chick embryos grow tooth buds. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Left on a hot
summer day, a tray of ice cubes turns to liquid water. Put back in
the freezer, the liquid water turns back to ice. But the number of
water molecules in the tray remains more or less constant. This
basic fact is the key to understanding how icy the earth got in the
last ice age 200 centuries ago. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPASSION (Undated) _ Compassion has become medically and
politically correct. Re-emerging with a vengeance among educators,
medical associations and hospital administrators, it is as though
caregivers and thier chargers have suddenly discovered humility,
mortality and goodness. By John Lagone.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WRITING-PHYSICIANS (Undated) _ Each year it seems that more
and more physicians are putting aside their stethoscopes for word
processors. Indeed, the most casual look at publishers' book lists
or major magazines and newspapers demonstrates that an increasing
cadre of doctors is writing best-selling works of nonfiction,
novels, plays, motion pictures and essays. Even professional
conferences are being held to encourage physicians with literary
aspirations. By Howard Markel, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT 10)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PERSONAL-TRAINERS (Undated) _ Although more than 4 million
Americans use personal trainers, there are few standards governing
the more than 66,000 people who make a living buffing biceps and
toning pecs. The term is not legally defined and states do not
require certification, a minimum training or licensing. Anyone who
can hoist a dumbbell and print a business card on a home computer
can call him or herself a personal trainer. By Liz Neporent.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PSYCHE-TRAITS (Undated) _ One of the many odd experiences of
being a psychiatrist is discovering that seemingly benign traits
can have a dark and even pathological side to them. A
characteristic that we would typically dismiss lightly in everyday
life _ a tendency to procrastinate, a hot temper or a
fastidiousness about details _ sends up a red flag for a
psychiatrist. At times what appears to be a minor eccentricity can
afford a glimpse into a large and unsuspected landscape of
symptoms. By Anna Fels, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Each
year, several hundred people succumb to anaphylactic attacks, the
American Academy of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology says, because
they fail to use epinephrine as a first-aid measure or fail to use
it soon enough. Further deaths result when victims fail to seek
professional medical help after using epinephrine, which suppresses
the attack, for only about 20 minutes. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Women who have had hysterectomies have a 60 percent greater
risk of being incontinent by the time they are 60, according to a
new report in The Lancet. This means the onset can be well after
the date of surgery, since most women who have hysterectomies do so
in their 40s or 50s. The operation is the second most common major
surgical procedure for women.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study suggests that when it comes to one of the
conditions for which antibiotics are often dispensed _ children's
earaches _ the treatment may be of little value. The study,
sponsored by the federal Agency for Healthcare Research and
Quality, found that almost two-thirds of children with acute otitis
media, or middle ear infection, recover from pain and fever within
24 hours of diagnosis _ without antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   _ As it stands now, millions of diabetics need to take blood
samples several times a day by piercing their fingers _ a
time-consuming and somewhat painful practice. But a recent study
suggests that things may become easier. Writing in the Diabetes
Technology and Therapeutics, researchers said diabetics may one day
be able to monitor glucose levels by just passing a beam of
infrared light through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cochlear implants have been used for almost a decade to help
thousands of profoundly deaf children, but some two-thirds of
insurance companies are often unwilling to pay, citing a lack of
evidence that the devices are cost-effective. A new study, however,
reports that over the course of a deaf person's life, the implants
can save more than $50,000 in costs associated with the disability.
</P>
<P>
   Here are Monday night's columns, other features:
</P>
<P>
   11
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Well, it took a year, but we've
finally got those presidential candidates nominated. And thanks to
the conventions, we now understand that George W. Bush likes
nothing better than to hang around with members of minority groups,
that Al Gore likes nothing better than to hang around with Tipper,
and that everybody in the Reform Party is crazy. By Gail Collins.
</P>
<P>
   EDIT-OBSERVER-PINOCHET (Undated) _ On Gen. Augusto Pinochet and
the changes under way in Chile. By Tina Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
