<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LAD     08-22 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SINKING FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Contrary to everyone's thoughts, the Los Angeles
Dodgers will be involved in a race as the season winds to a close.
</P>
<P>
   First place? Nah. But last place is attainable.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' lead over last-place San Diego could be something
to watch, especially since the Dodgers entered Monday three games
out of the National League West cellar. They pulled even closer
with a lethargic 4-1 loss to the Montreal Expos at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And what's been a taxing mental season on Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson has also brought its share of physical problems. It was
announced after the game Johnson would be having surgery to repair
a partially torn rotator cuff today at 8 a.m. at Centinela Hospital
Medical Center. The surgery will be performed by team physician Dr.
Frank Jobe.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who injured the shoulder earlier in the season by what
he thought was lifting weights, said he expected to be on the bench
for tonight's game against the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be here,'' Johnson, 57, said. ``It hurts every day
anyway, and it'll be a little more sore (today).''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Johnson was hospitalized with an irregular heartbeat.
He went to the hospital July 16 after experiencing dizziness at his
home. He missed four games before returning July 20, with the
directive to lay off caffeine, chewing tobacco and wine. In his
absence, bench coach Jim Tracy managed the club.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers trainer Stan Johnston said the shoulder began bothering
Johnson Aug. 8, and an MRI on Monday showed a partial tear in the
rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started aching pretty bad and I got a couple of
injections,'' Johnson said. ``Might as well do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder is Johnson's physical pain. The losing is mental.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the Colorado Rockies losing to Atlanta, the Dodgers
would be tied for third rather than leading fourth-place Colorado
by a game. But, hey, with 39 games to play, the Dodgers can catch
the Rockies and Padres.
</P>
<P>
   And with six of the Dodgers' last nine games against the Padres,
maybe there will be some meaningful moments in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly beats charting the Dodgers' drop from
respectability, and the playoff race, in the past two weeks. For
those who are near-sighted, the Dodgers are now a season-high nine
games behind front-running San Francisco, but that's a race not
worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough because we're definitely going through tight times
right now,'' Dodgers center fielder Tom Goodwin said. ``We have to
keep fighting and come out here every day. If it doesn't look like
it's going to happen, you still have to work like it's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With boos greeting every Dodgers mistake and disgust shown from
many in the 32,053 in attendance, the Dodgers again fell to a
sub-.500 team with a payroll that's only a fraction of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie right-hander Matt Herges (8-3) is learning the travails
of being a starter, particularly one in the No. 4 or No. 5 spot in
the Dodgers' rotation. Herges was 8-0 out of the bullpen but has
lost each of his three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the only positive I've been able to find is maybe I
held runners on,'' said Herges, who saw catcher Todd Hundley throw
out three would-be base stealers. ``Other than that, I didn't hit
my spots, didn't make the big pitches. When your offense is
struggling, you have to put up zeros.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight start, Herges pitched six innings, and he
left with the Dodgers trailing 4-0 and showing absolutely no pulse.
The Dodgers (62-61) are 29-30 at home, and with a loss today could
fall to .500 for the first time since they were 3-3 on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Expos right-hander Dustin Hermanson dominated the Dodgers, whose
sporadic offense lately has a consistency similar to oatmeal.
Indeed, that's the same Dustin Hermanson who hadn't won since July
20, and who was 0-4 with a 7.67 ERA in his past five
starts.!dlim!!dlim!
</P>
</TEXT>
