r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-22 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MIGHT BE BEST THIS SWAP WENT BUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Well, if you went to bed believing Christian
Laettner and Chris Dudley were on their way to the Los Angeles
Lakers, we hate to have to report it was only a dream. That
four-team, dozen-player trade fell apart Monday night, making it
the biggest deal in NBA history that never was.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, you're shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, you'll wake up on Dec. 25 to learn that
Christmas has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, you're crushed.
</P>
<P>
   It's too painful to think about how the Lakers will get by
without good old Chris and Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Why, oh why, do they build us up like that, only to let us down?
</P>
<P>
   Listen, apologies for the sarcasm, but something about that
proposed trade had to leave a Lakers fan cold. Maybe it was
Laettner, the veteran underachiever and lightning rod for
controversy. Or Dudley, the one professional basketball player who
could stand to take free-throwing lessons from Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Would those have been improvements over what the Lakers had for
a power forward and a backup center when they were winning the NBA
championship? Was that the best the Lakers could get in exchange
for Glen Rice?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are: yes, and yes.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   If this failed deal accomplished nothing else, it gave us a
glimpse of the kind of trade that is bound to happen between today
and the Lakers' 2000-2001 season opener 10 weeks from now. Not
exactly this trade, involving precisely these players, but
something like it.
</P>
<P>
   Something a little bit positive and a little bit flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Kupchak, the head of the front office in the post-Jerry
West era, faces the following facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have to get rid of Rice, whose performance and
attitude weren't worth the millions he could command.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers need a power forward to replace A.C. Green, who was
released almost before the championship parade float stopped
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers need a backup center better than Travis Knight and
John Salley, who did little more than keep Shaq's seat warm on the
bench, and then only if they sat side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak will accomplish all of those things, you can be fairly
sure of that. But when he does, it won't feel like an
accomplishment to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the failure of the Glen Rice experience, which
began with the trade that cost the Lakers Eddie Jones and Elden
Campbell to get him, and ended with Rice having his worst NBA
season and the Lakers winning a title anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If you sat down with a blank sheet of paper Monday afternoon,
while the big deal was still ``go,'' and diagramed the Lakers'
major transactions of the past few years, you discovered they'd
essentially traded Jones, Campbell and Nick Van Exel for ...
Laettner and Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, after he led Duke to NCAA championships in
1991 and 1992, Laettner was among the most valuable players in the
sport. He was the No. 3 pick in the draft, behind only O'Neal and
Alonzo Mourning. He had outballoted O'Neal for that spring's Wooden
Award. He had been chosen over O'Neal for the token collegian's
spot on that summer's Olympic roster.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner no longer commands such respect. Yet when the Lakers
went shopping for a swap for Rice, he and Dudley were the best they
could find. At that, it would have taken throw-ins of Tyronn Lue
and John Celistand and complicated four-way negotiations, to get it
done.
</P>
<P>
   If you were expecting a big, splashy deal this summer, something
to get excited about, let this be a lesson. As long as O'Neal, Kobe
Bryant and Phil Jackson are under contract, the Lakers will be in a
perpetual process of tinkering with the rest of the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Wake us when it's over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
