<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER ARM IN THE FOLD FOR TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC received an oral commitment Monday night
from All-American quarterback Matt Leinart of Mater Dei High in
Santa Ana. He selected the Trojans over Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Leinart is considered one of the top quarterbacks in the
country, and passed for more than 2,400 yards last season. His
other top school choices were Georgia Tech, Texas A&AMP;M and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason I wanted to go to USC was because it's close to
home and my family and brother can come to games,'' Leinart said.
``I just felt comfortable with the coaches and the program. They've
got good up-and- coming talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Leinart (6-foot-5, 215 pounds) said last week he would wait
until early September to decide, but changed his mind over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like this was the best time. I was really stressed out,
the last month especially,'' Leinart said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have received five commitments. Besides Leinart, USC
has commitments from tailback David Kirtman of Mercer Island,
Wash., defensive back John Walker of Birmingham High, quarterback
Billy Hart of Mission Viejo and defensive tackle Jason Wardlow of
Upland.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons returns: Cornerback Antuan Simmons, who underwent
surgery to remove a stomach tumor in May, made his first appearance
at UC Irvine on Monday and received an enthusiastic round of
applause from his teammates after practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling good. It's good to be back around the team. I miss
them,'' Simmons said. ``I just told them I was glad to be back and
to see everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, who was a preseason All-American, weighs 167 pounds,
about 18 less than he weighed at the end of last season. He will
redshirt this year and return next season for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to practice at least some this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work out, and if I feel healthy enough, I'll
practice with the team,'' Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has only viewed one practice, Simmons already was
critiquing the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the secondary looked young and made a lot of mental
mistakes,'' he said. ``I think I can talk to them about their
mistakes. I can be on the sidelines and lift their heads up.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons will accompany the Trojans to Giants Stadium in New
Jersey for the Penn State game.
</P>
<P>
   His presence affected his teammates, many of whom had not seen
Simmons since his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towards the end of the practice, when I was beginning to feel
sorry for myself,'' said cornerback Darrell Rideaux, ``I saw Antuan
out there and it's an extra inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen hit road: USC coach Paul Hackett said he will decide
today which true freshmen will accompany the Trojans to the Kickoff
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere between six and 10 freshmen will make the trip, Hackett
said. He has already decided strong safety Matt Grootegoed,
quarterback Matt Cassel and offensive tackle Joe McGuire will make
the travel roster. Other sure bets are tight end Alex Holmes, wide
receiver Keary Colbert and defensive tackle Kenechi Udeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that travel are people that have a chance to play,''
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
