<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-PAUS-UCLA-LADN     08-22 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAUS-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUS PICKED TO QB BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cory Paus lost the starting quarterback job twice
to injury last season, but he's never lost it on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Paus kept that record intact Monday when UCLA coach Bob Toledo
put an end to the competition for the quarterback job by announcing
that Paus had beaten out fellow redshirt sophomore Ryan McCann and
will start the season opener against No. 3-ranked Alabama on Sept.
2 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When fall camp opened nine days ago, Toledo said he'd allow
McCann and Paus to compete on even terms - the same amount of reps,
the same amount of work with the first team, etc. - and then make a
decision by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, it became clear early on that Paus was more consistent
and made fewer mistakes. While McCann improved late last week and
both played well during Saturday's scrimmage, it wasn't enough to
sway Toledo and offensive coordinator Al Borges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was all said and done, Cory at this point operates the
offense better and that was the whole key,'' said Toledo, who added
that junior Scott McEwan of Thousand Oaks High will remain the No.3
quarterback. ``Ryan is still learning and he's made great strides
and he's closed the gap a little. He just doesn't have the total
knowledge of the offense like Cory does.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo informed McCann and Paus of his decision Sunday night
after a quarterbacks meeting in Borges' office.
</P>
<P>
   In Paus' mind, the only reason for the competition was the
broken collarbone that ended his season in the 10th game and
off-season shoulder surgery that limited his participation in
spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally excited,'' Paus said. ``In the spring, I felt like
I was getting better, knowing the offense and knowing what was
going on before it was going to happen. From the first day I felt
really good about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the minute he said Wednesday (was the decision day) ...
I thought he'd do it before because I was confident I was showing
that it should be named before then. I'm excited to start the
season as the starting quarterback and get on my curve and get
going so I can be a really great quarterback in a couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus said he's much more prepared for the job than a year ago,
now that he has seven career starts. The experience is critical in
UCLA's offense, which expects more of the quarterback than
well-thrown passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it entails knowing who to throw to and when to throw
it,'' said Toledo, who added that Paus was ahead of Cade McNown at
this stage of their development because Paus had the benefit of a
redshirt year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big thing is getting us out of bad plays and into good
plays. We have checks at the line of scrimmage and he has to do
that. We give them the opportunity to put us in the right
formation. If you go watch the scrimmage and you see a guy throw
two touchdowns, you think that's all he has to do. It's not. It's a
pro type of offense and it takes some time to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus said he received congratulations from McCann, but
acknowledged that they aren't close. McCann, who practiced Monday
afternoon after missing the morning session with back spasms,
appeared to take the decision in stride and said he is determined
to work harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly disappointed, but the coach has to make a
decision,'' said McCann, the left-hander from Agoura, who began
last season as the No. 4 quarterback before leading the Bruins to
their biggest victory, an overtime win against Washington, and
starting against USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Paus) had a good camp. In the beginning I struggled. I felt
like I did well, but the gap was too big. Now I've got to work hard
to get back to being No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Toledo quickly quashed any ideas of a quarterback
controversy. Last season, he played Drew Bennett and Paus equally
in the first two games and then announced that Paus had won the
job. This year's tryout is over, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reins are now in Paus' hands, meaning he'll take two out of
three snaps in practice and he'll begin to assert the leadership
that the job requires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Cory looking behind his back and I told both of
them that,'' Toledo said. ``Because (the quarterback) throws an
interception or makes a mistake he's not out. I don't believe in
that. But I did tell him he's got to move the team, he's got to
score points and he's got to do a good job. Otherwise, eventually
we've got to make a change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 0247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
