<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN'S FENWAY RETURN IS TAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It wasn't quite the same as last year, and that was
just fine with first baseman Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn returned to Fenway Park last season for the first time
since leaving the Boston Red Sox after the 1998 season. But on
Tuesday there wasn't nearly the same hoopla that surrounded his
return last season on May 7, when dozens of reporters swarmed
Vaughn on the field during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from interviews with some local reporters and a few
catcalls from the fans, it was pretty tame.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Vaughn was hindered by a severely sprained ankle,
and went 3 for 20 with eight strikeouts and only two RBI in five
games at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurt, now I'm healthy,'' Vaughn said. ``I might not get
any hits in the series, but now at least I can walk up to the plate
and feel good in the batter's box.''
</P>
<P>
   In his second at-bat Tuesday, Vaughn hit a liner high off the
green monster in left field for a long single, but said before the
game he didn't plan to alter his approach at the plate to take
advantage of the short porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get a pitch to drive,'' he said. ``I want to
keep this game as simple as possible. It doesn't count for five
home runs if you hit one against this team. I'm not trying to get
back at them. I just want to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn even chatted with a former nemesis of his, Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette, before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to work hard not to speak to somebody,'' Vaughn
said. ``That's negative energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad wants in: Outfielder Darin Erstad did not play for the
second consecutive game because of tightness in his left ribcage.
His status is still day-to-day, but manager Mike Scioscia said
Erstad probably won't play today either and that the Angels miss
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our lineup he's the most important hitter,'' Scioscia said.
``He sets the table and drives in runs. In my estimation he's done
it better than anybody in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Not playing is driving Erstad crazy, even before games when he
goes through a regimented routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lost,'' Erstad said while sitting on the dugout steps,
watching his teammates take batting practice. ``I don't do this. I
don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight: The Angels were well-aware that pitcher Kent
Bottenfield threw a five-hit shutout against the St. Louis
Cardinals on Sunday night. Bottenfield, traded to Philadelphia for
outfielder Ron Gant on July 30, is 1-1 with a 2.89 ERA for the
Phillies. Since the trade, the Angels have released Ken Hill and
put Jarrod Washburn and Seth Etherton on the disabled list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
