<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 08:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     08-22 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS TAKES SMALL STEP TO RESTORE FREEDOM OF WORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His email address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle between Congress and the U.S. Supreme Court continues
_ over the significance of religious liberty and the right to
worship without government intrusion. Congress supports a much
broader interpretation of the constitutional protections afforded
to the freedom to worship than does the court.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's stingy interpretation of the U.S. Constitution
in Employment Division v. Smith (1990) involving the legitimate
religious use of peyote by Oregon members of the Native American
Church severely truncated traditional protections for religious
worship.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon outlawed the use of peyote in all circumstances, despite
the fact that Congress had made it legal for NAC members to use it
in religious worship. In its 6-3 decision, the high court held that
any generally applicable law could burden or even prohibit a
specific mode of religious worship. Oregon's law was a considered a
generally applicable law.
</P>
<P>
   Until that decision, the Free Exercise Clause provided
heightened protection for those involved in legitimate religious
worship or religious ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the 1990 decision, Congress passed the Religious
Freedom Restoration Act of 1993, only to have it struck down by the
high court in 1997. The court, in its decision, said that Congress
had exceeded it authority.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of July, before Congress took its August recess, both
the Senate and the House quietly passed a new religious liberty
bill _ by unanimous consent. The legislation is narrowly focused to
use the acknowledged power of Congress to regulate under the
Commerce Clause, the Spending Clause and the Fourteenth Amendment.
The bill intends to widen the protections given to religious
worship in areas where Congress has the unquestioned authority to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill didn't receive much attention in the press, it
now awaits President Clinton's signature. Clinton has already
expressed support for the bill, so there is little doubt he will
sign it into law soon.
</P>
<P>
   When Senate Bill 2869 (Religious Land Use and Institutionalized
Persons Act of 2000) becomes law, it will prohibit all levels of
government from implementing land use regulations ``in a manner
that impose a substantial burden on the religious exercise of a
person, including a religious assembly or institution, unless the
government demonstrates'' that such a burden furthers a compelling
governmental interest and that it is the least restrictive means of
achieving that compelling interest.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for a governmental agency to prove it has a
compelling interest and that the method of regulation used to
further that compelling interest is the least restrictive means of
achieving it. This strict test reinstates the traditional test for
whether a law unconstitutionally burdens religious worship _ the
test that the Supreme Court did away with in the 1990 peyote case.
</P>
<P>
   This law will apply to all programs or activities that receive
federal funds _ regardless of whether the land use regulations are
generally applicable and do not specifically target religious
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The first section of the mini-religious liberty bill is meant to
thwart zoning regulations that often harm churches and interfere
with religious ceremonies. In numbers of cities and towns, city
officials have sought to limit the number of worshippers at
churches and pressured houses of worship to shut down soup
kitchens. This bill would force city officials to have a compelling
reason to inflict a burden on religious worship.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of bipartisanship, Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., issued a joint statement to prove the need
for such a bill: ``Sometimes, zoning board members or neighborhood
residents explicitly offer race or religion as the reason to
exclude a proposed church, especially in cases of black churches
and Jewish shuls and synagogues. More often, discrimination lurks
behind such vague and universally applicable reasons as traffic,
aesthetics, or `not consistent with the city's land use plan.' ...
This discrimination against religious uses is a nationwide
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Understated but as important, the bill also gives some leverage
to American Indians who find their religious worship at sacred
sites restricted or outlawed altogether because of tourism, mining
or road building.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of S. 2869 deals with persons residing in or
confined to government institutions. The bill states: ''No
government shall impose a substantial burden on the religious
exercise of a person residing in or confined to an institution ...
unless the government demonstrates the imposition of the burden on
that person is 1) in furtherance of a compelling governmental
interest; and 2) is the least restrictive means of furthering that
compelling governmental interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill will provide protection for the religious beliefs and
worship of all those persons confined in state residential
facilities, homes for the disabled and correctional institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Institutionalized persons are often subject to the authority of
a very few local officials who don't want to go out of their way to
allow them to practice their faith. In a joint statement about this
part of the bill, Hatch and Kennedy pointed out: ``Whether from
indifference, ignorance, bigotry, or lack of resources, some
institutions restrict religious liberty in egregious and
unnecessary ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Committee on the Judiciary even learned of a case in
which prison authorities recorded the sacrament of confession
between a prisoner and the Roman Catholic chaplain. In another
prison, an inmate was allowed to attend Episcopal worship but
forbidden to take communion.
</P>
<P>
   A Wisconsin prison would not allow Christian inmates to wear
even tiny crosses. And, in the West, we are well acquainted with
prison officials who arbitrarily forbid American Indians from using
sweat lodges for their worship _ although there is sufficient room
for them to be built on prison grounds.
</P>
<P>
   As a safeguard, this bill does not amend or repeal the Prison
Litigation Reform Act which protects prisons and prison officials
from frivolous lawsuits filed by prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   A very broad coalition of religious and civil liberties groups
and conservative organizations like the Family Research Council
supported the passage of this bill. Melissa Rogers, general counsel
of the Baptist Joint Committee, successfully led the coalition in
urging for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   Until the U.S. Supreme Court can be convinced to revisit its
decision in Employment Division v. Smith and come around to an
interpretation of the Constitution that is consistent with our
nation's vision of the great significance of religious worship, we
must rely upon Congress to hack away at the court's mingy
understanding of one of America's great freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   This bill is a small step toward restoring the meaning of the
Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment, but one which will be
more difficult for the high court to gut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
