a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-22 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON IS ABOUT TO GET A LOT LESS FUNNY 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   I was very impressed, but at the
same time saddened, by President Clinton's speech at the Democratic
National Convention.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until he told me, I didn't realize Clinton was personally
responsible for 22 million new jobs, the lowest unemployment in 30
years, 8 years without a direct hit from an asteroid and no new
wars with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, I had assumed that Clinton's two terms had
mostly been spent chasing interns around the Oval Office and
renting out the Lincoln bedroom. Who knew he had time for anything
else?
</P>
<P>
   But my pride in President Clinton's accomplishments was tinged
with sadness. Soon, he will be leaving the White House. Where will
he go? What will he do? And most importantly of all, where will
humor columnists and late-night comedians turn for material?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore? Please. Gore's handlers recently torpedoed Rep. Loretta
Sanchez of California's plans to hold a Democratic fund-raiser at
the Playboy Mansion. Imagine how much fun that would have been!
There's Hef, a Benton twin on each arm, defending the right of
every American to buy soft-core porn at the convenience store of
his or her choice. There's the infamous grotto, aswim with former
Playmates, each with something to say on health care reform and the
high cost of boob jobs. And everywhere celebrities, celebrities,
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Clinton would have jumped into an event of this
sort like Billy Carter belly-flopping into a vat of Billy Beer. Al
Gore, however, wants none of it. The only time he would even
mention Playboy would be to say how much he enjoys the articles.
Gore wants to disassociate himself from the excesses of the Clinton
presidency. The image he is trying to cultivate is that of a monk:
austere, abstemious, strictly G-rated. In other words, boring.
</P>
<P>
   George W.? He and Gore seem to be trying to out-sanctimony one
another, the top prize going to the first one to sprout wings and a
halo. George W. has humorous potential in the sense that he mangles
the English language and comes across as sort of _ how can I put
this delicately? _ dumb, but there is little chance that his cadre
of handlers will allow him to be the next Dan Quayle, hard as he
might try.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton says he's really going to miss being president and
it's possible that we're going to miss him, too. But before he
begins work on his memoirs and his library, Clinton needs to take
some time off and relax. Which is why I'm inviting him to spend
some time in my adopted hometown of Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Bradenton has lots of golf courses, including one built on top
of a landfill. If your round is going badly, Mr. President, you can
always poke around and find a nice used tire or refrigerator part.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the people I play with, bending the rules is not only
tolerated, but encouraged. If you want to kick your ball out from
behind a tree or toss it out of a sand trap, feel free to do so.
Chances are the people you're playing with are cheating worse than
you.
</P>
<P>
   Bradenton also has a topless nightclub that you could
investigate periodically to make sure it is abiding by the new
county law that requires that no more than 20 percent of the breast
and 80 percent of the buttocks are exposed. Or maybe it's 80
percent of the breast and 20 percent of the buttocks. Either way,
being a smart guy, I'm sure you'd be able to grasp the situation,
so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bradenton is a small town and kind of isolated from the
rest of the world, so if Hillary gets elected to the New York
senate, chances are we won't hear about it here for several months,
if at all.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Mr. President, I think you'd be very comfortable in
Bradenton for a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't stay too long. We've got our reputation to think
about, don't you know.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
