<HEADLINE>
WHAT EVERY EXECUTIVE NEEDS TO KNOW ABOUT GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Mon., Aug. 21, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from the July-August
issue of issue of HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of
information on the art and science of business and management. For
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or about The Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By KIMBERLY O'NEILL PACKARD and FOREST REINHARDT  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The possibility that the Earth's surface temperature is rising
caught the public's attention during the brutal summer of 1988. But
it wasn't until December 1997 that global warming began to assume a
prominent position on business executives' agendas. That's when
representatives of 160 nations, convened by the United Nations in
Kyoto, Japan, adopted a plan that would limit the amounts of carbon
dioxide and other so-called greenhouse gases being released into
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto Protocol was accepted by representatives of the
industrial nations, but in most cases the full legislative bodies
each have to ratify the protocol. If ratified, the Kyoto Protocol
will require industrial nations to dramatically reduce emissions of
those gases by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts believe that human activity is contributing to an
increase in the Earth's average surface temperature. Scientists
also agree that an increase of as little as 2 degrees Fahrenheit is
likely to cause more severe storms, floods and droughts and to
accelerate the spread of disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto Protocol also sounded a warning to business leaders.
If large-scale reductions of emissions are mandated by law, many
manufacturers will have to dramatically change the way they
operate. They will also have to contend with shifts in demand, as
energy-efficient products overtake those that have long been
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Where to begin? A good place to start is to look closely at the
risks _ and the opportunities _ associated with shifts in the
weather, potential regulatory changes and the battle over public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   BAD WEATHER AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Most of the extreme effects associated with climate change have
yet to emerge. Nevertheless, companies whose assets are directly
affected by the weather must start planning now.
</P>
<P>
   For example, insurance companies should adapt their predictive
models to ensure that their prices are accurate and to prevent
large financial losses because of payouts after unexpectedly severe
storms.
</P>
<P>
   To value waterfront properties correctly, real estate companies
will have to keep up with the latest thinking on changes in flood
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   For companies that sell seeds, risk management may mean
developing crops that can deliver higher yields in drier
conditions. For timber operations, it may mean spending more on
fire and pest management: Drier conditions increase the risk of
fire and make young trees weaker and more vulnerable to insect
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, companies in a variety of industries may
experience shifting demand for their products as climate change
affects more people. For example, if tropical diseases migrate into
more industrialized nations, which is likely as temperatures rise,
pharmaceutical companies may see their markets expand.
</P>
<P>
   ANTICIPATING REGULATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Although it may be decades before people in Munich or
Minneapolis have to worry about tropical diseases, regulations
designed to curb climate change are already being proposed.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, government likely will impose additional taxes on
fossil-fuel consumption and require that cars and appliances use
less energy.
</P>
<P>
   Such regulatory programs will change asset values. Fleets of
trucks that get particularly low gas mileage will suffer. The
programs will also increase the value of goods and services such as
renewable-energy technology, process-control equipment and
telecommunications services _ for example, teleconferences that
substitute for transportation.
</P>
<P>
   As government regulatory schemes take shape, companies should
speak up and support programs that give them flexibility in
deciding how to reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
   A command-and-control approach _ in which all sources would be
required to make proportional reductions in carbon-dioxide
emissions, regardless of the cost or difficulty _ could cost six
times as much as market-based solutions, according to the White
House Council of Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, most businesses have not actively promoted market
approaches as an alternative to command and control.
</P>
<P>
   One market approach is to tax emissions of greenhouse gases.
Companies could then decide if it's more efficient to pay the tax
or invest in reducing emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Another solution would be to set up a system of tradable
permits. Under such a system, the government allocates emissions
permits that companies can then buy and sell. Businesses that would
have to pay huge sums to reduce their emissions of greenhouse gases
could instead buy permits from companies that are able to make the
required operating changes more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever regulatory systems emerge, some companies stand to make
money from the changes. Makers of industrial process controls, such
as Honeywell and ABB, may be among the big winners. They are
already investing in sophisticated thermostats, equipment that
generates electricity more efficiently and other products and
services whose value will increase in a world of higher-cost
energy.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why companies that make energy-efficient
products may support new regulations. But it's less clear why a
company such as General Motors has advocated government policies
that may make driving more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   GM and other large automakers such as Ford see climate change as
an opportunity to gain advantages over their less technologically
sophisticated rivals. That's why they are investing in cars that
run on a combination of gasoline and battery power and in fuel
cells. As the cost of driving conventional automobiles rises, Ford
and GM will dominate a new market and freeze out smaller
competitors for whom the required investments will be too great.
</P>
<P>
   Like automakers, energy companies stand to be hit hard by any
new policies that arise from the anticipation of global climate
change.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco has been a leader in supporting international efforts
to slow climate change. It has even announced voluntary cutbacks of
its own carbon dioxide output _ cutbacks similar to those required
under the Kyoto Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, BP Amoco believes that taking a leadership
position gives it a distinctive identity in the eyes of government
officials, scientists and environmental groups. That may mean
better access to government-controlled oil deposits and more
operating flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the company's experiments with emissions trading
are likely to give it clout at the negotiating table when
international regulatory frameworks are being devised. It will also
stimulate the company's employees to think more imaginatively _
and, in turn, feel valued.
</P>
<P>
   THE CLIMATE OF PUBLIC OPINION
</P>
<P>
   Probably the only thing more unpredictable than the weather is
public opinion. But good publicity can pay big dividends: As the
intensity and level of public interest increase, companies known to
have made early efforts to tackle climate change will have seats at
the negotiating table when regulations are being debated.
</P>
<P>
   For strategic reasons, some companies have chosen to be quiet
about their efforts. Honeywell and ABB would gain advantages from
more stringent emissions regulations, but they've had to be
cautious in their public statements on global warming. Some of
their biggest customers are fossil fuel and electricity companies.
</P>
<P>
   While good PR buzz on preventing or preparing for climate change
has its appeal, smart companies know it's simply bad business
practice to make investments, relocate resources or change
strategies solely for the sake of appearance. That's why David
Allen, who oversees BP Amoco's solar energy investments, is careful
to emphasize that the company's foray into solar ``is not just a
public relations sop. We would not do that. If you just paint
something, then people will in due course see it as paint.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to think steadily and consistently about a topic as
complicated as climate change is a tough test of management acumen.
Some executives are meeting it head-on. Those who are not should
wonder why they aren't _ and so should their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   (Kimberly O'Neill Packard is a consultant with McKinsey &AMP; Co. in
Boston. Forest Reinhardt is an associate professor at Harvard
Business School in Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on offerings
from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
