<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And now for the news. . .
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELEE ISLAND, Ont. - It's Canada's southern-most island in Lake
Erie - it measures 9 miles, north to south, and somewhere between 3
and 4, east to west.Year-round residents number 200 hearty souls.
</P>
<P>
   With summer's end, the pace here slackens as ferries from the
Canadian and U.S. mainlands cut back their shuttles to a sparse
winter schedule that lasts until the lake freezes over. Life on the
island slows to a pleasant walk. I know because I've been reading
all about it in some back issues of the local newspaper - The
Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   The big news in November, 1992, was that two hunters had
accidentally cut loose on one another with bird shot.
</P>
<P>
   In December there was a ``euchre shootout'' beginning at 8:30 in
the hotel,andthe LCBO (Liquor Control Board of Ontario) gave notice
that empties would be accepted during the winter months until they
ran out of room. A bingo fund-raiser sponsored by the Pelee Island
public school students raised $98,and anyone interested in a puzzle
exchange was advised to ``contact Pat at the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer, however, has always been a different story. The
following is anupdate on the latest breaking hard news as reported
in the ``Blotter''section ofThe Grapevine:
</P>
<P>
   ``July 7, 2000. R.S.C. Trenton contacted O.P.P. (Ontario
Provincial Police) Pelee Island for missing overdue boater reported
missing by concerned spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Boater (husband) located at a party in Sandusky, Ohio. Spouse
advised of findings and was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 8. Center Dyke Road. One male intoxicated on bicycle
while riding to residence at 03:00 fell on face and required
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 8. West Shore Road. One male and one female under the
influence of alcoholic beverages passed out in front lobby of
O.P.P. station. Offered free room and board with a Provincial
certificate for public intoxication. Declined. Requested an
established B&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 22. East West Road. A party of four visiting from
Michigan, inquired what O.R.R. stands for. Advised it's O.P.P. This
party thought Canada was policed only by the Mounties and was
surprised to see a police cruiser insteadof a horse (see TV show
North of 60). Visitors thought it 'cute' that officers in Ontario
are armed.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 22. At the corner of East West Road and West Shore Road.
Police officers while on duty in a fully marked police cruiser came
upon a male who was standing next to a seated female at a picnic
table engaged in an (in)appropriate behavior. This male looked over
at the police and appeared to have a 'deer caught in the light'
look on his face and continued with his activity. Officers
activated high intensity spotlight but this party continued and
only stopped when one officer yelled, 'Ahem! This is the police!'
Both parties apologized for their behavior and stated, 'This is our
first time on Pelee Island,' as if that were to make a difference.
Officers explained that this was a family island and such
activities should be limited to private quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``July 22. Two boxes of filet mignon and a case of beer reported
stolen from the hotel, and five folks from Ohio crashed into the
rocks on West Shore Road. Alcohol and poor vision were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``August 5. East Shore Road. Suspicious vehicle reported by
cottager. Police located two young males who were canvassing public
beach area for new female friends. Advised to go home and have a
cold shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``August 13. West Shore Road. Mischief complaint. Two turtle
signs found hanging from trees and appeared to be hung in effigy by
their necks.
</P>
<P>
   ``August 13. East Shore Road Lizard Point. Six people in a
26-foot boat ran aground at Lizard Point. Extensive damage to
propeller. Vessel towed without incident. Charges to follow.
Special thanks to Dave Hodare, the Rodigers, and Matt Abbey with
his boat, The Minnow. Also an anonymous male swam out twice to
rescue and assist boaters only to find out these individuals were
weak swimmers stranded in seven feet of water. Novice boaters will
make short of this new hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it folks, crime on an island.
</P>
<P>
   And a reminder: ``Steingart Septic Service is No. 1 in the No. 2
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
