r k BC-YOUNG0823-COX     08-22 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stroll down memory's hall is cavalcade of confiscations
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - Ah, the newborn days of another school year.
Welcome back, child. Now, turn right around and march that tongue
stud of yours back home.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of our town is a young lady in Lorena whose offense
isn't a body ornament but hair that is too short, or too alert. The
principal said her spiked 'do won't do. Fascinating, the age-old
process.
</P>
<P>
   And hair-styles aren't the half of it. I was reminded of this
recently by a scent in, of all places, the boys' room. Actually, it
was in the men's room.
</P>
<P>
   A cinnamon-scented air freshener had transported me back 30-plus
years _ to a time of innocence and ruby-cheeked stealth, to the
quest to smuggle something into school, flaunt it and not catch
hell.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking about cigarettes, booze or guns. I'm talking
about cinnamon toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   I never smuggled them. I didn't have the guts. Only the boldest
seventh-graders smuggled cinnamon toothpicks. Guarded like stolen
plutonium rods, the toothpicks were dipped in cinnamon oil to bathe
a tongue in eye-watering fire.
</P>
<P>
   It was guaranteed status to trot out 10 or 12 toothpicks in wax
paper. Even more impressive was he who possessed an amber vial of
oil. Its scent could sit you down.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon toothpicks were sort of a nether-vice: not food, not
gum, not drink and _ oh, no _ not drugs. They were just
delightfully mysterious, easily concealed, and of course forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   A modern-day variant among grade-schoolers is a salty substance
in a small shaker, a Mexican candy called Lucas, commonly licked
off a palm. Mmmm. Hey, kids. How 'bout a show of hands?
</P>
<P>
   Thus two examples that conjure and color an eternal intrigue: to
test in relative innocence the limits of ``off-limits.''
</P>
<P>
   These days such testing runs up against the principal's ban on
Pokemon cards or yo-yos. Laser pointers, hand-held games and pagers
are more recent nuisances.
</P>
<P>
   I asked around for adult recollections of school contraband _
odd and puny stuff that became big by being forbidden. Go ahead, I
said. Show me what was in your pockets.
</P>
<P>
   One remembered when her school banned paper clips, or at least a
certain contrivance thereof. Students who somehow felt envious of
others with orthodontal mouths fashioned paper-clip chains they
stretched over their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   One person recalled a ban on clackers, noisy tethered plastic
balls. Several remembered the confiscation of so-called paper
footballs, little triangular constructs of notebook paper made for
field-goal flicking.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a retired educator about such vices and they will come
pouring forth from her mind's confiscation closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nail polish was the worst thing girls could bring,'' said one.
The vapors from the polish would disrupt class, and their hues
could end up everywhere _ on desks, on walls, on schoolboys' noses.
Perfume was similarly disruptive, she said, with the potential of
toxic spills.
</P>
<P>
   At one school, little-girl glitter, for sparkling up eye brows
or highlighting one's locks, became a forbidden because it ended up
everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the no-no that spans the ages is food in class,
always disruptive. Always gooey.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the scene of Waco grade-schoolers who had just been on a
bakery field trip, each receiving a wrapped Twinkle or Ding-Dong or
somesuch, and the smiling principal greeting the grade schoolers at
the bottom step of the bus, holding a grocery sack into which each
cream-filled treat vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Today some grown-up is lamenting the Ding-Dong that got away.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is Opinion Page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
