<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN23-CO     08-22 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freshmen testing independence need to be taught the dangers of
credit
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Santanya Cofield graduated from college three years ago with
$10,000 in credit card debt, a camcorder and only the haziest idea
where the rest of the money went.
</P>
<P>
   Even with her diploma, the 26-year-old Atlanta native felt she
had failed. ``I was very depressed,'' she recalled. ``And I had a
lot of anxiety from those bill collectors calling me all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her story is a common one, and it will start afresh for
thousands of young people just now stepping into the freedom of
their college years.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and retailersirst card for 15 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   Parents don't necessarily have much to say about it. ``Most
college freshmen have just turned 18, which means they are eligible
to sign a contract,'' pointed out Suzanne Boas, president of the
Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Greater Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The offers certainly can look attractive. There are cash
rebates, discounted airline tickets, free long-distance phone calls
and introductory interest rates as low as 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On many campuses, recruiters offer T-shirts, coffee mugs and the
like to students who fill out an application on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   But many young people _ some of them imitating their parents _
haven't achieved an adult relationship with easy credit. College
students owe $1,843 on their credit cards, on average. Three out of
four use their cards for routine spending _ things like food,
clothes, toiletries and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Two of every five let the debts ride from one month to the next,
and as a result many will graduate with consumer debt piled on top
of their student loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A credit card is just a tool,'' said Charles Frazier, a
certified financial planner, ``but it can lead to a false sense of
security, at least until the bills arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some families have worked for years to instill financial
discipline in their offspring. Others have left it to the last
minute, or to fate.
</P>
<P>
   For worried families, here are some timely ways to corral the
credit monster.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Educate your freshman. Too many young people do not understand
the broad concepts, such as budgeting and compound interest. Even
more know nothing about details like grace periods, late payments
and finance charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most effective way is for parents to show a young adult
what a credit card statement looks like,'' said Steve Rhode,
founder and president of myvesta.org, a nonprofit organization
formerly known as Debt Counselors of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can show what it means. You can go over your bills with
them, so they can see how those casual purchases add up and how
interest does too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lilli Friedland, a family counselor, suggests bringing in
outside experts, many of whom can be found on the Internet.
``Because finances are such a delicate issue, it's really important
to show it in black and white as well as to teach it,'' she said.
``When you get it from a variety of experts, it supports what
parents are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Explain the consequences of credit abuse. ``I realized I had
to work to support my credit cards,'' said Cofield, an Atlantan who
was raised in the city's Adamsville neighborhood and now works in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse after she graduated. Her bad credit record showed
up with prospective employers, and landlords checked her out. ``I
had to explain it,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It helped when she pointed out that she enrolled in a repayment
program with Boas' CCCS.
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback: Her current lifestyle is diminished by the
$275 a month she allots to paying off the debts of long ago. She
still owes $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spell out who is responsible for debts. Frazier and others
believe parents should not make a practice of bailing out their
near-adult children. ``You have to make them responsible,'' he
said. ``If the kid knows he doesn't have to pay the bill, there are
no limits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't co-sign for a credit card. ``You're the one with better
credit, and if there is a problem, they're going to come after
you,'' said Rhode.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Treat your student as an adult. ``You have to walk a fine line
between giving advice they need and allowing them make their own
decisions and their own mistakes,'' Boas observed. ``Like
everything else in life, they will live up to our expectations of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Set a good example. If you can, show that you follow a budget
and pay your bills on time. If you can't, point out the problems
you've brought on yourself. Even a bad example can be a teaching
tool.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stay in touch. Mistakes are part of the learning process.
Parents can be part of that process, but only if they're willing to
be helpers, rather than hanging judges.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
