<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-MATCHMAKER-2ND &LR;  &UR;      08-22 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MATCHMAKER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... are heard.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all her connections to the wired sector, Plotkin's
credentials are solidly old economy. The skills she uses at work
``are people skills, not technical skills,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in Wheeling, W.Va., where her mother taught in
public schools and her father worked in advertising. After studying
radio and television at Ohio University, she moved to Boston in
1970, following a friend from high school who had a teaching job in
Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Soon she was working as an aide to John Larkin Thompson, then
president of Blue Shield of Massachusetts, the big health insurer,
and a member of the Vault, a group of top executives from companies
such as Bank of Boston and Boston Edison, which was the dominant
business lobby of its day.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson sent Plotkin to monitor debate on Beacon Hill on a bill
that set safety standards for ambulances. From that job, ``I
learned it was all about relationship building,'' Plotkin said.
``You don't usually win on your first try, but you have to build
bridges . . . and make sure you touch base with the right people.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Plotkin marketed executive programs for Harvard's School
of Public Health and ran a membership program for another
association, the New England Council, made up of businesses,
colleges, and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, at a political fund-raiser, she met Eric Vogt, founding
president of what was then the Massachusetts Computer Software
Council, who soon offered her the job she has held ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the council included executives from just 13
companies, among them Saddlebrook Corp. and MicroMentor Inc., who
were chiefly interested in trading tips on running their businesses
and didn't care much for public debate.
</P>
<P>
   Vogt said those early members ``didn't give two hoots about
politics and basically saw it as a waste of time and resources.''
But he said he hired Plotkin partly for ``her insistence that we
listen and pay attention and consider the impact of public
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of her advice became clear in 1990, when the council
helped convince the Dukakis administration to table a
loosely-written computer crime bill that would have outlawed the
teaching of computer-security courses.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Plotkin was working out of a new office in Copley Square,
arranging meetings at which executives could compare notes on new
inventions, such as spreadsheet programs and something called the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   She also invited politicians to receptions at the Newton
Marriott and other Route 128 hotels and brought in guests such as
Microsoft founder Bill Gates and Clinton administration technology
adviser Ira Magaziner.
</P>
<P>
   A poised public speaker herself, Plotkin rarely takes the podium
at such events and can usually be found making introductions in the
back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thinks her job is to make other people look good, not
herself,'' said Dan Bricklin, chief technology officer of Trellix
Corp. in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   Since many software executives aren't known for their smooth
social skills, Plotkin also makes sure speakers are ready for the
stage. ``She gives you all the material you would want if you need
to fall back on something,'' Bricklin said.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin was married in 1977 to a computer programmer. Their son
Arlen was born in 1986, the same year she started her current job
at the council. Four years later, she was divorced and began
raising Arlen as a single parent, taking him everywhere from
council strategy meetings to trade missions to Israel and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have found a babysitter, but she wanted to take
advantage of the opportunity to introduce him to new things,'' said
David Blohm, who is chief executive of SmarterKids.com in Needham
and the council's past chairman.
</P>
<P>
   She also didn't want to miss out on Arlen's upbringing. Once she
spent a Saturday morning watching him play soccer, then raced off
for lunch with the president of China.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, Plotkin married again, this time to a Sudbury
psychiatrist, in a low-key ceremony attended by just 21 people.
They live in Newton.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin won't discuss her salary, but she says she has turned
down ``friend-of-the-company'' shares as gifts from about four
companies who are council members.
</P>
<P>
   Such gifts are a common practice among technology companies, but
Plotkin says that accepting them would create conflicts of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job has to be representing all of the software companies in
the state equally,'' she said. If she were to accept shares, she
said, ``there would be an issue whenever somebody asked me to
recommend a company.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing up the payoffs is worth it to keep a job she enjoys,
Plotkin said, one that is ``all about networking.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate, Plotkin mentions a meeting several years when
John Hamill, then president of Fleet Bank, agreed to lend $1
million to a state program to finance technology companies. Plotkin
followed up with a question on a more personal note: Maybe Hamill
could help her Chestnut Hill hairdresser get a loan? Hamill called
him the next day and eventually Fleet financed a renovation for the
shop, Changes Salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I try to do,'' Plotkin said, ``is to remember people
and to connect people in ways that they may not have thought to
connect themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
