<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8847 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE23-     08-22 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher stress can lead to job burnout
 &HT;    By Hap Lecrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the beginning of the school year, I would like to encourage
you to think about a topic that is often neglected but extremely
important. The topic that I am referring to is teacher stress and
burnout.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, in our society, is expected to produce positive
results, often without the tools that are essential for success.
Since free public school is one of the cornerstones of our society,
the successful education of our children is often taken for
granted. Many parents simply enroll a child in school at the
appropriate age and sit back and wait for expected results.
Parents, and society in general, are often oblivious to the
stresses felt by educators:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Work overload _ many teachers feel compelled to take work home
in the evenings and on weekends in order to meet the
responsibilities expected of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lack of appropriate reward and recognition for their work _
teachers' salaries remain very low in comparison to other
professionals in our society.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unrealistic and/or idealistic expectations from those they
serve or those they work with _ teachers are often seen as
surrogate parents, counselors, character-builders, caretakers,
disciplinarians (often without any authority), etc.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pervasive feelings of lack of control in their profession _
positive results are expected without the tools needed to
accomplish these results.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lack of positive feedback from students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Working environments that are overcrowded, outdated or in
high-crime areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Multiple pressures from those they serve _ parents, students,
governmental agencies, administrations and the media.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal pressures _ produced by the need to take care of
their own families, health, living environments, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Often we expect teachers to have no personal problems, no
worries or concerns outside of their teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The end result can be that we want results but we don't want to
do what is really necessary to help. The problem can go even
further when parents actually retard the learning process in their
children by promoting counter-productive alternatives at home such
as too much television; letting their children stay up too late,
causing the children to suffer from fatigue the next day; lack of
support from parents regarding school regulations; and lack of
assistance with homework assignments.
</P>
<P>
   All of this puts teachers in a very stressful position and may
lead to teacher burnout, physical ailments, depression and a desire
to leave the teaching profession.
</P>
<P>
   Next week I will discuss ways that we can all assist teachers in
their extremely important wo
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
