<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE: MICROSOFT DENIES LINUX REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft? Writing software for Linux? No.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. officials last week were quick to deny a rumor
that the company had begun working on porting its popular
office-software suite to the Linux operating system. Rumors to the
contrary had enlivened the LinuxWorld trade show in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the spur of competition is making Microsoft a bit less
insular than it used to be. The company is eager to challenge
RealNetworks Inc. for dominance of the Internet multimedia
business. That's why Microsoft has ported its Windows Media Player
to Solaris, a popular version of the Unix operating system produced
by a bitter rival, Sun Microsystems Inc. There's also a version
that's compatible with HP-UX, Hewlett-Packard Co.'s version of
Unix. And Microsoft has created Solaris and HP-UX versions of its
Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not unimaginable that Microsoft might someday try to
plant the flag in Linux country. Just not this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Linux-land, VA Linux Systems Inc. has been
rearranging the furniture. And companies like IBM, Sun, Compaq,
EMC, Hewlett-Packard, and Intel are doing much of the heavy
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux is consolidating several of the Andover.net sites into
the Open Source Development Network, a service designed to
encourage and support software developers working on Linux and
other open-source software projects. The site will provide
centralized access to lots of old Andover.net services, such as
Freshmeat, a repository of interesting new open-source programs,
and Question Exchange, where visitors can get answers to complex
programming questions.
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux is also beefing up the SourceForge Web site, where
programmers publish their ongoing work on open-source projects. The
site will offer the ability to compile and run newly written code
over the Internet on a variety of different computers provided by
IBM, Sun, Compaq, Intel, and Hewlett-Packard, with EMC providing
advanced data-storage equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even amateur programmers will be able to test-drive
their code on some of the hottest machines around. VA Linux is
betting that will lead to more good open-source code and more
demand for the company's Linux computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VA Linux isn't alone in its quest to find bright new software
talent. Tucows Inc. came to Harvard Square last week from the wilds
of Flint, Mich., hoping to milk a few good programs from the code
warriors of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Tucows (www.tucows.com) is one of the Internet's biggest
distributors of shareware, programs that can be downloaded for a
tryout before purchase. The advertiser-supported service features
an index of 40,000 shareware programs, as well as product reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Scott Swiderski says Tucows is always grazing for new
products from up-and-coming programmers, and lots of interesting
stuff comes in over the transom. ``We deal with thousands of people
every month,'' said Swiderski, but most of those contacts happen
over the Internet. He wanted a chance for direct contact with
programmers. And where better to look than the land of Harvard and
MIT?
</P>
<P>
   And so Tucows set up what Swiderski called its ``casting
cowch,'' a sofa coated in Holstein-spotted leather, and a heap of
bovine squeeze toys, on the second floor of the Harvard Coop on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A number of local programmers showed up, including Sharon
Housley of Hanover's NotePage Inc., who already sells her software
through Tucows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to speak face to face with the
reviewers,'' said Housley. Her company's WebGate e-mail paging
software has a four-cow rating; perhaps a few pointers from the
critics can show Housley how to earn that fifth cow and make her
product an udder success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
