<HEADLINE>
ONE-WAY CALLING GETS A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This may sound like the beginning of a mean-spirited insurance
salesman or former lover joke but . . . did you ever wish you could
have a phone call with someone without their knowing your phone
number?
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind the latest example in a flood of
specialized Internet-based communication services. A Boston company
called Acallto.com is ramping up its service with new features this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to use the Internet as your secretary to get someone
on the phone. You send addressees an e-mail or a Web page address
asking them to call.
</P>
<P>
   They click on the message or a link on the Web page and enter
their phone number. Within a few seconds, their phone rings and,
when they answer, a call is completed to your phone number, using
voice-over-Internet-protocol connections.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Internet fuels an ever-greater number of
contacts among strangers, from people doing deals through an
auction site to lonely hearts cruising in a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to imagine a growing number of situations where we
might like to talk on the phone with someone once or twice but not
give them our phone number. (Government officials and business
executives who have been kind enough to share a home phone number
with a reporter covering a story can relate to this.)
</P>
<P>
   From the recipient's perspective, it can often be nicer to get
an e-mail proposing a conversation than to pick up your phone and
have some stranger babble at you out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers pay $6 a month, plus 19 cents a minute, for calls
anywhere in the world (the first 15 minutes are free). Besides the
privacy issue, Acallto allows subscribers to exert considerable
control over how and when they are reached.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you could send someone an open-ended invitation to
call you that would be routed to your work number during work hours
and to your home or wireless phone at other times, reducing the
chances the person you want to speak with has to play voice-mail
tag to catch up with you.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can send someone ``an Acallto,'' as the company dubs it,
that only works during a two-hour window on Thursday morning when
you feel like answering the phone, or you can shut down an Acallto
link you opened for someone you quickly realized you never want to
have to talk to again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a little mind-bending is that we are turning the phone
call around,'' said Acallto chairman and chief technical officer
Allen Razdow. Razdow is a former top executive with MathSoft Inc.
of Cambridge, a software company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as one of those old-fashioned situations where you
pick up the phone and hear a secretary say, `Please hold for Mr.
Smith,' '' Razdow said.
</P>
<P>
   One feature allows senders to check a little pop-up screen on
their computer desktops that indicates whether a recipient of an
Acallto request has received it, so they can anticipate whether a
call might be coming soon. The company is also looking into
adapting the service for sale to auction sites and chat rooms to
offer their visitors a controlled, more anonymous way of talking.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that perhaps only the marketplace can resolve is
whether some recipients might react negatively to getting an e-mail
that could be interpreted as saying: Her Royal Highness may or may
not wish to speak to you between 9 and noon tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone who might be rubbed the wrong way, there could be
more people who are glad to have the chance to make a call more at
their convenience than someone else's and with the Acallto
subscriber who initiated the call paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Gardner, research director for messaging and directory
services for consultants Aberdeen Group in Boston, said he could
see the service becoming a popular marketing tool. ``It's much more
of an opt-in, less annoying version of communication,'' Gardner
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main value to me seems to be to initiate phone calls
through e-mail,'' Gardner said. ``Making yourself private is kind
of an ancillary benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
