<SLUG> BC-TECH-ETOYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ETOYS, IT'S TIME `TO EXECUTE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a year ago, most investors cheerfully applauded Edward
``Toby'' Lenk, chief executive of eToys Inc. and the undisputed toy
baron of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But running an Internet retail business in today's dot-com
environment is no fun and games. The 38-year-old Lenk, a graduate
of Harvard Business School, has watched his company's stock price
spiral downward from a high of $86 in October to $4.0625 last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lenk managed to raise $100 million by selling
convertible preferred stock to private investors, he accepted less
favorable terms than in previous rounds of funding.
</P>
<P>
   But he was unshaken by the recent announcement that online giant
Amazon.com Inc. and bricks-and-mortar retailer Toys R Us Inc. have
forged an alliance to create what they hope will be the Internet's
biggest toy business.
</P>
<P>
   Lenk said the two rivals joined forces because they ``made the
decision that they can't compete with us alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other dot-com executives, Lenk has discovered that the bar
is much higher this holiday selling season for eToys, which is
based in Santa Monica, Calif. And like Jeff Bezos, founcer of
Amazon.com, Lenk must prove that he can continue to expand sales
rapidly while keeping a lid on expenses, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Lenk talked about his competitors, his
investors, and his strategy to keep eToys in the number-one
Internet toy position.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does the new relationship between Amazon.com and Toys R
Us impact your company?
</P>
<P>
   A. Toys R Us made the decision that they can't compete with us
alone. And Amazon made the same decision.
</P>
<P>
   Last holiday season, we had about 10 competitors, who spent $200
million in advertising and promotions to compete with us. We spent
$26 million in our core television campaign last year. We were
massively outgunned in this space. Despite that, we were three
times the size of the number-two player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you set a date when eToys will become profitable?
</P>
<P>
   A. Our target is to come close to breaking even next holiday and
then to break even in 2002. So two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How have the shakeout and the unfriendly reception on Wall
Street toward Internet retailers impacted your company?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a very interesting question, because the corollary
questions I get are: How is employee morale? How is employee
retention? The reality is that there was clearly a speculative
bubble over the last two years. Because of this crazy bubble, you
had a situation last holiday season where we had 10 competitors
spending $200 million. But here's the thing: What goes up hard and
fast crashes even harder and faster. I've been stunned by the pace
of the shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You used Fingerhut last year to help fill your orders. What
happened to Fingerhut?
</P>
<P>
   A. We fired them. Third-party relations like the one our friends
just embarked upon are very challenging.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How would you rate eToys' performance in filling orders last
holiday selling season?
</P>
<P>
   A. The piece of the business that went to Fingerhut we were not
happy with. So we weren't perfect. But we were really, really good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How is your merchandising different than a bricks-and-mortar
store?
</P>
<P>
   A. Toys R Us carries about one-tenth the selection we have. In
fact, their Web site has never gotten up to their physical store
selection. So we probably have 20 times the items they have on
their Web site. These aren't all toys. The other thing people don't
understand is we're a children's company. We have every single
children's book in print at eToys. These are the kind of things you
can do on the Web that you can't do (in off-line stores).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What will the Internet landscape look like after the holiday
season this year?
</P>
<P>
   A. Cynically, if you're Toys R Us, with this deal, you've just
taken Amazon out of the (toy) market. And they could just hope we
go away. You're darn right they hope we go away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you gotten your message out to analysts?
</P>
<P>
   A. In this climate, analysts are followers. We have to execute.
Last year, they were valuing every Internet company assuming they
were going to be successful. This year, they're valuing every
Internet company as if they're all going away. So it's a show-me
climate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
