<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MOVIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOAD WAR, THE SEQUEL: FILM TRADING STIRS NEW FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the underground world of computer hackers, he goes by the
name Dvdboy and is renowned for his skill at converting DVDs into a
format that allows movies to be shared easily _ and illegally _
over the Internet. A self-described movie buff who owns more than
300 DVDs, the 27-year-old network engineer takes great pride in his
work. ``For me, the motivation is being considered the best,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Dvdboy, who lives in the United Kingdom and requested that his
real name not be used, thinks of himself as an artist. Executives
in the film industry use another word: pirate.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the latest battleground in the download war that
began with free music and Napster, a conflict that is pitting
hackers and activists against entertainment industry executives.
While digital piracy is not as rampant with movies as it is with
music, an estimated 250,000 to 350,000 movies are traded every day
on the Internet, from summer releases like ``Me, Myself, and
Irene'' to cult favorites like ``Star Wars'' and ``The Matrix.''
And the movie industry isn't sitting back quietly. The Motion
Picture Association of America won round one on Thursday when a
federal judge ruled that it is illegal to publish DeCSS, a computer
program used to crack antipiracy features on DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be mistaken: The war has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they win, they lose,'' says Bruce Forest, director of
media and entertainment for Viant, a New York consulting company.
``The war is still raging, and the technology cannot be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the underground trading of movies is growing rapidly,
thanks to new technology. First, programmers use DeCSS to decode
the encryption used to protect DVDs from piracy. Then, they use a
compression program named DivX (which is not related to the defunct
alternative to DVDs that used the same name). Developed earlier
this year by a Jerome Rota, a French videographer, the technology
enables programmers like Dvdboy to compress huge DVDs into files
that are small enough to store on a CD or on a hard drive. With a
high-speed connection, it is now possible to download a full-length
movie in one or two hours, a process that would have taken days
without DivX. And the quality is near picture-perfect.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say it's easy. Movie trading today is where music
trading was a year or so ago: It's a byzantine process that is
still largely underground. Most of the action takes place on
Internet Relay Chat, the system of underground chat channels
dominated by hacker cliques. Films are also traded on Usenet
bulletin boards, although they are often divided into many small
files that must be retrieved separately. They are also distributed
on private sites that are restricted to insiders, and some movies
are traded on networks like Gnutella and Scour Exchange. The
process is hardly as easy as point and click.
</P>
<P>
   But a little more than a year ago, the only people who regularly
traded music online were the true tech heads and code freaks, and
now, more than 24 million people are sharing music files on
Napster, which simplifies the download process. Industry experts
expect that movie sharing will become as simple in a matter of
months, cautioning that the movie industry has a very short window
before a movie version of Napster becomes a new household word.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the movie industry has taken its case directly to the
courts, going after individuals and suing such companies as Scour,
a strategy derided by techies. ``In the worst case, you take all of
the users who were above ground and you drive them underground,''
says Gene Kan, one of the developers of Gnutella, a decentralized
file-sharing system developed after Napster was sued. ``They do
exactly what they were doing before, only now they are forced to
realize that there are more deceptive ways of doing what they
wanted to do anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders counter that they will use technology to defeat
technology. ``We are determined to put our movies online, but we
won't do so until we can dispatch them to homes in a safe and
secure environment,'' says Jack Valenti, president of the Motion
Picture Association.
</P>
<P>
   The movie industry is attempting to learn from the music
industry's less-than-successful attempts to sell digital music
online; so far, three of the four major record companies have
launched pilot programs, but they are extremely difficult to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to downloading music, it's easier to be
dishonest than to be honest,'' says Richard Wolpert, a former
Disney executive and the head of Chance Investments, a venture
capital firm that funds digital entertainment ventures, including
Scour. ``People won't put up with it. The entertainment companies
have to come up with a system that is as easy to use as Napster.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of folks vying to do just that. Rota, 27, has
teamed with several Internet entrepreneurs to found a company
called ProjectMayo.com; the firm aims to release a simplified
version of DivX that can be used for legal purposes such as sharing
home videos. The firm is also developing a database that can be
used for a digital video-on-demand system; it has yet to ink any
deals with the studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have about 9 to 12 months to lead the charge,'' says
Jordan Greenhaul, ProjectMayo's CEO. ``After that the
infrastructure will change, and it will become a slugfest between
the motion picture industry and the underground Internet world.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies are becoming more popular on the Internet every day. A
20-year-old Virginia Tech college student who runs
www.divxnews.com, a site that distributes news about DivX movies,
says that his site receives 40,000 hits a day _ and that number is
rising.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhaul goes so far as to say that a little piracy is a good
thing. Pirates, he says, are ``scum-of-the-earth types (who)
accelerate the opening up of markets that wouldn't open up without
them. Piracy may be a viable force in our social dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   Few other entrepreneurs hoping to capitalize on the
digital-movie market would go so far as to argue the social value
of piracy. But some say that piracy will not be such a big issue if
the movie industry can get its act together soon. ``There will
always be some minimal form of piracy,'' says Howard Weizman, CEO
of Massive Media Group, a digital rights management company. ``But
most consumers aren't comfortable stealing. Once they have a legal
option for digital entertainment content at a reasonable price,
piracy will be miniscule.''
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ticks, the definition of copyright is evolving and
mores are changing as consumers become accustomed to downloading
music _ and eventually movies _ for free. ``The proliferation of
information increases its value,'' says John Perry Barlow, a
founder of the Electronic Freedom Foundation. ``Information isn't
an industrial product. You can't think of movies as though they
were toasters.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the movie industry's definition of copyright has
prevailed in the courts, and some say they will win the battle for
control over content. The movie industry will eventually figure out
how to turn digital movies into a new revenue stream, the way it
did with videocassettes and DVDs. Even Dvdboy, the European
programmer, contends that DivX movies serve as samples that
increase the sales of DVDs. ``DivX is not a replacement for the DVD
itself, as the quality of the video cannot compare to that of my
home theater,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Zittrain, executive director of Harvard's Berkman
Center for the Internet and Society, predicts that a new generation
of Internet appliances will be developed, specifically for the
distribution of legal entertainment content. ``The arms race is in
earnest,'' he says, ``but it is too early to count the giants of
the movie industry down and out. You wouldn't like them when they
are angry, and they are definitely angry at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
