<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-MATCHMAKER-ART-2     08-22 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MATCHMAKER-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 JOYCE PLOTKIN: TECHNOLOGY BOOM MATCHMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Everyone makes time for Joyce Plotkin. Even as a
strike loomed at Verizon Communications earlier this month, company
public-affairs director Joe Zukowski cleared his schedule to see
the president of the Massachusetts Software and Internet Council.
</P>
<P>
   The post makes Plotkin, a 51-year-old self-described soccer mom,
the official envoy of the new economy. Each month, she visits
dozens of executives and public officials eager to do business with
the 775 booming technology companies she represents.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin was seeking funds from Verizon to pay for an advertising
campaign to draw more skilled workers and investment to the state.
Verizon sells millions of dollars of services to the software
sector, and Zukowski was ready to tell her what she wanted to hear,
even if his company isn't a member of Plotkin's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to participate at the $25,000 level,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes!'' exclaimed Plotkin, who has a made a career of her
ability to make connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give that man a T-shirt!'' she told an aide. The slogan
emblazoned on the white garment read, ``Massachusetts. The State of
Things to Come. www.dotcommonwealth.com,'' a reference to the Web
site that is just one of 20-odd projects Plotkin has helped to
dream up or operate for the Software and Internet Council.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin's organization is a lobbying and fund-raising group and
more. With a budget of more than $1 million annually, her council
hosts more than 50 meetings a year for executives and programmers
to mingle with each other and venture capitalists,
intellectual-property lawyers, and other specialists whose
deal-making keeps the software industry humming.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is the hostess for all this hobnobbing, Plotkin shuns
the spotlight. But after 14 years in the job, she has built a
network that has become an economic force in itself, encouraging
contacts that lead to new products and sales for the mostly young
companies she represents. (The council's membership roster runs,
alphabetically, from Akamai Technologies to Zoesis Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin networks constantly, referring companies, public
officials, and investors to each other. In 1998, she helped involve
labor unions in a project to wire Boston schools for Internet
access; the relationship paid off recently when the AFL-CIO
supported a proposal by Senator Edward M. Kennedy to increase the
number of visas issued to skilled computer programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Her matchmaking doesn't always involve policy. A few years ago,
she made introductions that led to the Look and Feel Band, a
rhythm-and-blues outfit of software executives, and arranged for
their first gig aboard a cruise boat in Boston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Joyce as someone who knows everybody,'' said the band's
bass player, Drew Hannah, chief executive of Fishman Transducers
Inc. of Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Church Lewis, president of the Boston investment advisory firm
Beeson Gregory International, says he has met three clients so far
at council meetings and comes back to troll for more. ``The more
people you meet, the more business you're going to do,'' Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question the sector is doing more business than ever.
According to the thick guidebook the council publishes each fall,
the number of software and Internet companies in the state has
grown from 800 firms employing 46,000 people in 1989 to 3,000 firms
employing 138,000 people last year.
</P>
<P>
   The combined revenue of these businesses more than tripled, from
$3 billion to $10.7 billion over the same period. By comparison,
computer and communications-hardware makers employed 77,591 people
in the state last year, according to the Massachusetts Technology
Collaborative, a state-funded trade group, down from more than
100,000 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the increase are myriad, but Tom Hubbard, vice
president of the Technology Collaborative, says the role of Plotkin
and her council shouldn't be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any growth industry creates a trade association sooner or
later, but I think what Joyce has done is to improve the climate,''
Hubbard said. ``She's really made it easier for people to
interact.''
</P>
<P>
   And Plotkin says she doesn't foresee any slowdown soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One spur for Plotkin is competition, both from Silicon Valley
and from a rival trade group in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   She's still vexed by a 1994 book by a California academic,
AnnaLee Saxenian, who argued that Massachusetts fell behind Silicon
Valley because local companies were too rigid and hierarchical to
keep up with new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin says the author ignored the local software sector, an
industry that was already practicing many of the prescriptions for
success _ flexibility, collaboration, and decentralization _ that
Saxenian outlined in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already had over a thousand companies at that point who
were working with a lot of energy that didn't seem to make it into
the book,'' Plotkin said. ``They already knew they had to learn new
ways of doing business, and you can see today how it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the software industry in and around Boston signals a
shift away from hardware makers such as Digital Equipment Corp. and
Data General, among the state's largest employers a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   A priority for those companies was cutting taxes. They supported
blunt representatives such as Howard Foley of the Massachusetts
High Technology Council, who once said of an opposing interest
group, ``We'll bury them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Software and Internet Council's members include many
smaller companies that worry more about finding the financing,
office space, and skilled workers needed to keep expanding. ``The
agenda is not, `Give us tax cuts,' because that's not what I'm
concerned about right now,'' said Mike Attili, president of Amaxo
Inc. in Newburyport, which sells software services for online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Plotkin's top lobbyist _ Bruce Holbein, a one-time
Digital employee _ concentrates on federal issues, such as rules
related to visas and accounting guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin's group and Foley's High Technology Council agree on
some matters. Both advocate normalized trade relations with China,
for example. Some big companies, such as EMC Corp. and IBM, are
members of both organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups seldom cooperate, however. Chris Anderson, vice
president for public policy at the High Technology Council, said he
has asked Plotkin for help in lobbying state lawmakers on issues
such as a plan to reduce the cost of unemployment insurance, but to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Software Council has taken a nonactivist role,'' which is
why it generates little criticism, said Anderson, who is slated to
become the High Technology Council's president next January, when
Foley retires. ``When you make decisions and draw lines in the
sand, people are going to be upset with you, and when you don't,
nobody does.''
</P>
<P>
   Plotkin says she has declined to help on Beacon Hill because
most of the concerns of her members relate to matters in
Washington. ``We just have different agendas,'' she said. ``They
have an economic agenda, and we have a technology-policy agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Plotkin has struck an alliance with TechNet, a
technology trade group based in Palo Alto, Calif., with similar
priorities in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to broaden the local technology industry's influence
on congressmen outside the Massachusetts delegation. Unlike the
Software and Internet Council, TechNet makes contributions to
political candidates from both parties, and its fund-raising
organization will channel funds from local contributors, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is ``the next evolution of political involvement
for us, for the Massachusetts technology community,'' Plotkin said.
``Money doesn't buy influence, but it helps to ensure that your
positions are heard.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
