<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-GARAGE-BOS &LR;      08-22 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GARAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE'S TRYING TO RIDE THE PENGUIN'S COATTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN JOSE, CALIF. _ At LinuxWorld, everyone wanted to dance
with the penguin.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations such as Dell Computer Corp, IBM Corp., Sun
Microsystems Inc., Hewlett-Packard Co., and Compaq Computer Corp.
lined up to profess allegiance to the Linux computer operating
system, whose mascot is a penguin.
</P>
<P>
   But riding on the penguin's coattails is a tricky thing.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Corel Corp. Last year, Corel placed a large bet by
selling Linux versions of its software, including its marquee
WordPerfect Office programs.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't paid off, at least not yet. The Ottowa software
company's finances are dismal. Sales of Linux-based software make
up an anemic 5 percent of Corel's overall revenues. And the
company's founder, CEO and chief Linux champion Michael Cowpland,
abruptly resigned last week.
</P>
<P>
   Corel's experience suggests the limitations of a grass-roots
software movement, i.e., Linux, in a pure corporate world where the
primary objective is not to make cool software but to make a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Corel's problems predate its Linux conversion. The
company's sales have languished for years after it lost its battle
with Microsoft Corp. in the mid-1990s for the word-processing and
spreadsheet markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Corel's victories have been sporadic and symbolic.
The US Department of Justice, which is suing Microsoft for
antitrust infringement, recently chose WordPerfect as its official
word-processing program. But Corel's word-processing and
spreadsheet software market shares remained less than 5 percent in
1999, according to IDC in Framingham. Microsoft claimed over 94
percent of both markets.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Linux. Cowpland, who founded Corel in 1985, saw Linux as a
potential key to his company's rebirth. Corel committed to making
Linux versions of its key software, including CorelDraw, just
released at LinuxWorld in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Corel also invested in a project called WINE, which is
researching ways to let Linux users run programs made for Microsoft
Windows. The company also distributes its own version of the Linux
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves gave Corel's stock a boost, at least temporarily.
Its shares hit a high of $44.50 on the Nasdaq last Dec. 9, weeks
after it started shipping its Linux products. On Friday, Corel's
shares fell 12.5 cents to close at $3.40625.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the temporary stock surge, Corel's bottom line hasn't
benefited much from its Linux efforts. In June, the company posted
losses of $23.6 million on revenue of $36.6 million in its second
quarter ended May 31. For the same period in 1999, the company
earned $9.2 million on revenue of $70.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't Corel been able to capitalize on Linux mania?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer is that Linux, while growing rapidly, is
still a tiny portion _ just 4 percent _ of the market for computer
desktop operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's making money from Linux,'' said Jean W. Orr,
technology analyst with BlueStone Capital Partners in New York.
``Ninety-eight percent of Corel's revenues still come from selling
applications on Windows and Macintosh. It simply can't be assumed
that Linux is somehow going to turn the company around. Corel has
to focus on making its core business profitable before it invests
in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   A second obstacle is price. While WordPerfect Office for Linux
sells for $139, Sun Microsystems is distributing a competing
product, StarOffice, for free. ``Even though Corel's product is
very inexpensive, it still costs more than StarOffice,'' said Dan
Kusnetzky, vice president of system software research at IDC.
</P>
<P>
   This is the crux of Corel's dilemma. At the heart of the Linux
ethos is the concept of ``free software.'' Though it doesn't
necessarily mean software should be given away for free, it does
mean companies openly share the source code, or recipe, for its
products.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most Linux companies don't make money selling
software. Instead, they rely on selling technical services to go
along with the software, services such as consulting, installing,
or maintaining the programs. It's a business model that can take
years to mature because it requires a large base of computer users
to switch to Linux from other operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Corel's problems, however, are immediate. Derek J. Burney,
Corel's interim CEO, knows this. So while Corel will continue its
Linux efforts, Burney made it clear that the company ``definitely
needs to roll up our sleeves on the Windows and Macintosh
applications.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
