<HEADER>
A8867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      08-22 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPANY TEN YEARS IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Scott Killoh received his first angel money in a duffel bag.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1990. The old Shawmut Bank, swimming in bad loans, had
just canceled the business loan Killoh had been promised. He needed
money fast to handle a $50,000 order from his first big client. He
was setting up networks of clone computers at the time and needed
to buy parts for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Just when he was starting to sweat, a friend from his class at
UMass's Isenberg School of Management came to his rescue. Killoh
says the woman convinced her father, who was living at a YMCA in
Connecticut after a messy divorce, to lend him $35,000 in cash he
had literally tucked under the mattress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was kind of crazy, looking back,'' Killoh says. But the
money was repaid within a couple of weeks, with interest.
</P>
<P>
   Most angels don't get their money back nearly so fast _ and they
expect far bigger returns. But the cash helped Killoh get his
networking and consulting business off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   He developed a niche with universities and publishers and began
building database products for news companies. That ultimately led
to the current Web strategy of his Openpages Inc., a Westford,
Mass. content management player with a large office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I joined them, they had a profitable business,'' says
Warren Huff, a lawyer Killoh asked to become Openpages' chief
executive in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself is unusual. Then, even after repositioning the
company to take advantage of the Internet, ``we operated the
company cash-flow positive in 1998 and 1999,'' Huff says. Revenues
this year should exceed $13 million, triple what they were a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists love that kind of story. In December,
Openpages raised $14 million from Boston's Matrix Partners and
Sigma Partners' Boston office. And today, the company plans to
announce a $30 million round _ $20 million from Matrix and Sigma,
plus $10 million from Wall Street's Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   What others might call a second round, Openpages is dubbing
mezzanine money. That means the company and its backers are looking
to go public in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
   Little surprise. The IPO market has come back strongly from its
spring plunge. And one of Openpages' backers, Sigma, was the first
investor in Vignette Corp., the Austin, Texas, content-management
company that many believe has seized the lead in the field.
Vignette went public in February 1999 and soared. Shares are up 284
percent over the past 12 months, despite slumping 28 percent so far
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sigma says this is not a me-too play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole space is very complicated because no one does
exactly the same thing,'' says John Mandile, managing director at
Sigma. Other competitors include Broadvision, Art Technology Group,
and Interwoven.
</P>
<P>
   Mandile describes the company as ``compatible with Vignette''
but handling a specific need: managing content on one system so it
can be distributed in a number of ways, whether printed in a
newspaper, blasted to a Web site, or broadcast over television.
</P>
<P>
   Openpages provides services to many news clients, such as
Fidelity Investments' Community Newspaper Co., which is using the
service for its townonline.com Web portal; the Miami Herald; and
Knight Ridder's RealCities.com. But the company says it can service
business-to-business and e-commerce sites, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the Web era, Killoh, 34, says, ``Everyone is really a
publisher. Even if they're selling sweaters.''
</P>
<P>
   He's spending about half his time in the company's growing
Moscow office these days. That's where Killoh's early collaborator,
Yuri Kirkel, oversees 80 of Openpages' 215 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Killoh hired Kirkel in 1994, when the Russian PhD was delivering
pizzas in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really couldn't understand English,'' Killoh says. ``But he
was a great programmer.'' And when he wanted to move home, Killoh
let him set up the office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Now the office is considered a competitive advantage, Killoh
says, because Russia doesn't face Boston's hiring crunch. The
company has tapped dozens of skilled engineers from Moscow State
University, Russia's MIT, and plans to hire many more this year.
</P>
<P>
   If he has any regrets, Killoh jokes, it's that he wishes he'd
started his business later. It's funny to have been toiling away
for a decade, he says, while more recent grads launch companies and
go public within a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he says: ``I personally prefer to actually
build value.'' He adds: ``My goal has been to build a product that
people can install. That's what I enjoy doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like the investors like it, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
