<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INCOME-CALIF (San Francisco) _ The economic picture for
Californians is not as rosy as it is perceived, despite the state's
newly minted dot-com millionaires, movie moguls and real estate
barons, according to a report released by the Federal Reserve Bank
of San Francisco. Income for California families is declining
against average family incomes for the nation, the study says. By
CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   PREMARITAL-PACTS (San Francisco) _ Barry Bonds' wife-to-be
didn't need a lawyer to understand what she was doing when she
signed a premarital agreement in 1988 giving up her right to half
his baseball salary, the state Supreme Court says. The unanimous
ruling is a strong statement in favor of the binding nature of
prenuptial agreements. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   DESERTER-ISRAEL (San Antonio) _ The former commander of a San
Antonio military intelligence unit, found by police at a youth
hostel in Israel's Negev Desert, has asked for immigrant status,
U.S. and Israeli authorities say. Army Reserve Lt. Col. Jeremiah J.
Mattysse, 49, is charged with desertion. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WAGE (San Francisco) _ After two years of hardcore
lobbying and delicate negotiating, the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors approves a broad living-wage law. The action is an
election-year victory for the board members, and it provides solace
for more than 21,500 workers in line for bigger pay checks, paid
days off and, eventually, health benefits. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   RAPID-RAIL (San Antonio) _ The Texas portion of a rail route
that carries more than 35,000 people to and from San Antonio each
year could become one of 11 high-speed rail corridors nationwide.
It might not revive talk of a bullet train whizzing across Texas at
200 mph., but it could help Amtrak's Texas Eagle, which already is
leading the national rail company out of financial troubles. By
SCOTT HUDDLESTON.
</P>
<P>
   SF-AIRPORT (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Powerful San Francisco
politicians are crafting legislation here and in Washington, D.C.,
that would pay up to $300 million to the Cargill Salt company to
buy thousands of acres of marshland in the area's South Bay and
possibly speed expansion of San Francisco International Airport. By
ROBERT SALLADAY and JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-DECOR (Undated) _ With the debut season of ``Survivor''
wrapping up Wednesday, we offer a Survivor Kit _ advice on how to
turn your den into Pulau Tiga, the castaways' home away from home.
By MELISSA WARD AGUILAR.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-FOOD (Undated) _ Since pan-fried rat is so five minutes
ago, try a recipe for Squirrels a la King. By RENEE KIENTZ.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-MUSIC (Undated) _ Here are tips that go beyond the
obvious (Gloria Gaynor's ``I Will Survive'') when providing
background music for your ``Survivor'' party. By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-DRINKS (Undated) _ Favorite recipes for tropical drinks
worthy of miniature paper parasols. By PAMELA MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-BUDGET-FILMS (Albany, N.Y.) _ With today's technology, just
about anyone can shoot and edit a movie. And just about anyone can
market it, shilling on personalized Web pages or finding
distribution on any of several burgeoning sites that screen on-line
movies for viewers. Indeed, the latest digital advances are prying
hard at the tightest seals of Hollywood. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-FALL (Undated) _ August is melting away. School is
starting. As far as American publishers are concerned, fall is upon
us. The weeks between now and Christmas have traditionally seen the
bulk of the A-list books for the year _ the novels by big names,
the controversy-provoking polemics, the fat and formidable
biographies. This year's crop looks fairly impressive. By FRITZ
LANHAM.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Nobody is eating barbecued rat
anymore. It's all about cliques and politics and manipulation, the
human drama of back-stabbing. That's why any worker with half a
brain and absolutely no social life has to watch Wednesday night's
television finale of ``Survivor.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-DISTANCE (San Antonio) _ San Antonio-based SBC
Communications Inc. has signed up more than 500,000 long-distance
customers in Texas in the six weeks that it has been allowed to
offer the service. The brisk customer growth surprised some
analysts by exceeding that of Verizon Communications, the former
Bell Atlantic, when it launched long-distance service last year in
New York. Verizon took more than three months to attract its first
500,000 long-distance customers. By SANFORD NOWLIN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-ARTISTS (San Francisco) _ Outside the Community Art
Studio in San Francisco's gritty Tenderloin district, the landscape
features decrepit buildings and scarred lives. But those who enter
the studio leave behind homelessness, addictions or criminal
records and become artists with a vision of hope. By MARIANNE
CONSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Q-AND-A (San Francisco) _ As Sydney beckons, the NBA turns
inside out and the Giants purr their way through the dog days, Ms.
Demeanor gives her mailbag an overdue once-over. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RISON (Alameda, Calif.) _ Never mind what you've heard about
Andre Rison. The wide receiver, a five-time Pro Bowl player, is
nothing like the trouble-maker you've read about, say friends and
former teammates. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ On behalf of all registered
voters, likely voters, the American people and America in general,
I'd like to ask how TV, radio and print media ``experts'' know
enough to speak for me? I mean, for us. There must be close to 2
million such political pundits on various payrolls these days _
mostly male, mostly white and mostly well-paid. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
