<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-HOMELESS-ARTISTS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-ARTISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ART CENTER OFFERS CONFIDENCE FOR THE DOWNTRODDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hearts with angel wings and a riverside oasis
with golden monkeys. A desert goddess with beatific smile and a
tusked elephant resplendent in princely robe.
</P>
<P>
   The creations of clay and on canvas are idyllic. But this art
does not imitate life.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Community Art Studio in San Francisco's gritty
Tenderloin district, the landscape features decrepit buildings and
scarred lives.
</P>
<P>
   But those who enter the studio are not just homeless or junkies
or drunks or ex-cons or any of the other labels that society brands
on them. They are artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was always `Who am I?''' said David Seiler, 47, a
Vietnam veteran beset by drug and drinking problems who has been
homeless for about 15 years. ``Here's an answer. Whoever I am out
there, I'm not that here. I walk in that door, I'm an artist. At
the very least, I'm an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this place because of the spirit of community,'' said
J.B. Saunders, 47, a former crack addict who has been homeless for
most of the past 10 years. ``You see all ages and all races.
Everybody is given their space to create what they want and be who
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Run by the Central City Hospitality House, the center that
provides counseling, job training and shelter for the homeless and
indigent, the Community Art Studio began in 1969 as a place for
hippies left over from the Summer of Love to hang out and do their
macrame, said Samantha Giles, 30, the studio director.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, however, the storefront art studio and gallery
started targeting homeless and low-income people. About three dozen
show up during the studio's hours _ noon to 5 p.m. on Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Space and art supplies and camaraderie are free to whoever walks
in the door, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love is that people don't have to give their Social
Security number or income level or who they are in the system,''
said Giles, a former social worker who joined the studio last year.
``They can just walk in and be an artist and this is who they are
for five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Donations provide about half of the studio's $109,000 budget for
salaries and art supplies. But the artists pitch in, too, donating
their art for the annual silent auction, the studio's biggest
fund-raiser. The last one, in June, netted about $55,000, Giles
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, the artists hope to raise money for themselves. An
exhibit, the People's Art Show, will showcase their sculptures,
paintings, sketches, tile mosaics, and pottery. All the proceeds
will go to the artists.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the artists could certainly use the money and ego boost
from making a sale, but that is not why they create art. Even if
they had no previous formal art training, many say they now see
their art as their salvation and the studio as their sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The karma is good. It's like a sanctuary atmosphere,'' said
Roya Bozman, 49, a drug addict and former homeless musician who has
been coming to the studio about a dozen years. ``It takes me away
from it all when I'm in here. It keeps me away from the
environment. It keeps me motivated instead of out there where I'm
just drifting around. It's like a vacation for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gem in a mudslide,'' said Dale Fiegl, 47, a former
homeless artist living in a hostel, who views the Tenderloin and
its morass of poverty and drugs as the mudslide. ``This brings an
oasis to people who have no oasis.''
</P>
<P>
   The studio looks not unlike any other, with walls filled with
watercolors and drawings, shelves filled with canvases and
paintbrushes, and bins filled with clay.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the room, where the clay artists congregate,
William Bacon, 37, an accomplished sculptor, holds court as he
creates Ganesh, an Indian deity that is a man in the body of a
four-armed elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, who said he became homeless four years ago when he
suffered dioxin poisoning while working at an oil refinery, was
advising Seiler on how to best lay out his tiles for a mosaic.
Nearby, Bozman was showing Saunders how to create shadows and tones
in his oil portrait of a nomadic African woman.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Saunders had been coming to the studio for the
better part of a decade, he had until now stuck to clay. The
portrait _ an homage to women, he said, as an apology for the
shabby way he had treated them when he was doing crack _ was his
first oil painting.
</P>
<P>
   As the men and women work alongside each other, they tell their
tales and offer advice not only on art techniques but survival.
Many share tips on the best places to go for a hot meal and a long
shower, which agency has decent job training and how to work the
shelter system.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork is also great therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Pepe Benjamin, 44, was homeless for many years when started
going to the art studio. After mastering the potter's wheel, he
felt he could master anything. He earned his high school
equivalency degree and now he has a steady job cleaning and
managing a nearby apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started from coming here,'' he said. ``Doing this is
highly inspiring. You move onto something else: `I can do that,
too.' It all starts with a little clay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This place like saved my life,'' said Thomas Carney, 46, who
said he suffered from depression. ``It's been building my
confidence. I feel like I'm finding my voice now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
