<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8884 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOW TO WIN THE GAME OF `SURVIVOR' IN THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nobody is eating barbecued rat anymore. It's all
about cliques and politics and manipulation, the human drama of
back stabbing. That's why any worker with half a brain and
absolutely no social life has to watch Wednesday night's television
finale of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   It's down to four people now, and one basically unlikable soul
will walk away with $1 million. If you watch how the ``Survivor''
people interact and really pay attention, you will learn a lot
about office politics and how to get promoted, even though these
people are on a deserted island in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   (Brief background: 16 castaways were broken into two tribes of
eight people each, called Tagi and Pagong. Once the field was
reduced to 10 castaways, they became one tribe, but former Tagi
members systematically voted out all the former Pagong members.)
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's show milks the drama and commercials for all
they're worth, the four finalists will vote to eliminate one of
their own. After more drama and lots of commercials, the three will
narrow it to two. Then all four people from this episode, plus the
last five previously cast-off castaways will decide which of the
two finalists wins $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   So who will win? The person who keeps these things in mind:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pure talent is rarely enough.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, some kind, wholesome, apolitical soul could win on
``Survivor'' by winning every episode's immunity challenge (the
person who wins the week's contest can't be voted off during that
episode). It didn't happen in ``Survivor,'' and it rarely happens
at work.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Hardly anyone is perfect for any job. The good news is that
you don't have to convince your boss that you're a perfect fit _
just that you're the best person available.
</P>
<P>
   What helps immensely is if you show bursts of talent and energy
at the right time. A brilliant idea on a $10,000 project is nice; a
brilliant idea on a $10 million project can change your life. If
you put in long hours all the time, you can get taken for granted;
if you put in long hours to help meet a crucial deadline, you can
win someone's eternal gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how good you are at office politics, you have to be
good at what you do to survive. If you let your politics write a
check that your talent can't cash, you will be in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   _ Know your place in the pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Of the final four on ``Survivor,'' let's assume Kelly has the
most support, followed by Sue and then kind of a tossup between
Rich and Rudy. That's how I see it.
</P>
<P>
   If Sue, Rich or Rudy has an inflated sense of self-esteem,
though, it could cost him or her $1 million. Anyone who makes it to
the final twosome with Kelly will probably lose.
</P>
<P>
   Workers with inflated egos are the most common casualties in
office politics. Instead of just having a gut feeling that you're
doing a good job, look for evidence that the people upstairs like
you, such as promotions, bonuses or raises. If you can't find such
evidence, you might not be as good as you think you are.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are talented, you need to find people who will
support you _ and trust you to support them. A lot of people move
up in an organization once a trusted ally has been promoted, or
they follow that person to another workplace.
</P>
<P>
   You should know your key rival's strengths and weaknesses. If
you can show strength in a rival's weak area and convince the boss
that the area is crucial, you'll increase your chances of getting
promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, too, the best thing you can do is form a shaky
alliance and help your rival land a great promotion _ with another
company, of course. That trick can work for pain-in-the-neck
bosses, too, assuming they have at least some shred of talent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take advantage of random acts of stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Rich is still in the game is because of a stupid
policy adopted by a recently eliminated contestant, Sean. Until the
last couple of weeks, Sean always voted to eliminate people in
alphabetical order because he was trying not to offend anyone.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out, though, that Sean unwittingly cast the deciding
vote to eliminate another contestant, Jenna, when he could have
wiped out the influential Rich. It was a dumb move, and Sean
eventually paid for it when the Rich-led alliance voted him off.
</P>
<P>
   In the office or on a deserted island, ridiculous twists of fate
will take place. Smart people won't attempt to explain them, but
will think about how they can benefit. If everything falls into
place, the Rich just might get richer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LOW-BUDGET-FILMS-2NDT     08-22 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-BUDGET-FILMS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALBANY, N.Y.: x x x have some pearls.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AtomFilms Web site is a case in point. On any given day, the
site offers a smorgasbord of animated and live-action shorts _
``short'' meaning anything from around half a minute to half an
hour or more. Some are ironic; some are thoughtful; some make
shrewd use of the interactive capabilities of Web-based technology;
and some of them stink.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Guinea Pig Theatre Presents Romeo and Juliet,'' a
two-minute, 34-second reduction of the Bard featuring caged
rodents, goes down easier than ``The Easter Bunny SUCKS,'' in which
the bouncing icon is cast as a potty-mouthed tobacco addict who
rebuffs kids in a park.
</P>
<P>
   Far more successful is ``Capitol Ill,'' a hands-on music video
that invites the viewer to manipulate dancing cutouts of George W.
Bush and Al Gore. Click on a turntable to add a scratch to the
tune; pull on a lever, and the presidential aspirants slide across
the stage. Other knobs and levers toss around beats, sound bites
(``I took the initiative in creating the Internet,'' boasts Al) and
other effects. After a few minutes, Bill Clinton (in boxers) and
George Bush the Elder boogie in for a cameo. It may not qualify as
Serious Art, but it sure is a kick to play with.
</P>
<P>
   And playfulness is part of the digital era. Literally. Think
Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some indie films will look more and more like games, which is
OK,'' said Ortali, a neat native of France who once chaired the
French department at the State University of New York at Albany.
``I just want to make sure that it's the scriptwriters who create
good indie films who will be the ones to do games also. ... I don't
want to leave games of the future just to programmers.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Ortali is a devout believer in Web-linked DVDs and the
interactive future of digital filmmaking: He expects, as do many,
that the new technology will permanently, profoundly alter not just
how movies are made but how we watch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The age of nitrate is over,'' announced screenwriter Paul
Schrader (``Taxi Driver'') at the Lake Placid Film Forum earlier
this year, and he was dead serious when he said it. Filmgoing, like
filmmaking, may never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, when you write a script, you're very aware of how
it's going to look. You imagine it every step of the way,'' said
the Adirondack-based novelist Russell Banks, who has seen two of
his books adapted into film (``Affliction,'' directed by Schrader,
and ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' by Atom Egoyan). Banks has just
finished a screenplay draft for a prominent filmmaker (too early to
say what, or for whom) that will likely be shot in digital. To that
end, he included in the script suggestions for ``a mix-up'' of
different visual textures, from handheld video to 35mm to grainy
black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do things differently,'' he said. ``There's an
intimacy with digital, a friendliness _ it puts you right up close
to the faces and the bodies and the locales, the close locales, of
human beings. ... So it does change how you write. It allowed me to
get much more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   The new technology ``is one of the most interesting and
promising things since the talkies came along _ and it's going to
be that revolutionary,'' he said. Banks is critical of a breed he
terms ``technobrats'' _ technological sophisticates who have little
or ``only cliched interest'' in storytelling _ but holds out hope
that someday, the art will catch up with the craft. Filmmakers will
learn ``how to use the technology for more interesting
storytelling. Because, finally, that's what film is all about. In
the end it's not a strictly visual art, it's a storyteller's art,
it's a narrative art. And I think, in time, that'll come to the
foreground.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   NEW WORLD OF EFFECTS
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Placid, Schrader cited ``Forrest Gump'' as the first
film to use computerized visuals as ``part of the everyday language
of film,'' not in cacophonous blow-'em-ups but as effective
narrative tools. The digital elimination of Gary Sinise's legs is
one such example, and one reason why ``Gump'' represents a
watershed film.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we're moving into an era where everything will be
effects,'' he said. ``It's a very big change out there, and we'll
be living in a completely different world.''
</P>
<P>
   The new filmmaking can change an actor's eye color. It can alter
the lighting in a room. It can change tint, tone, atmosphere,
aspect, the entire ``look'' of a movie. It can do just about
anything, from making live animals pucker up for dialogue to
resurrecting John Wayne for a beer commercial.
</P>
<P>
   There may even be a time, in the not-so-distant future, when
movie actors are made _ sprung from computer chips _ rather than
born. (``I have no problem with virtual actors,'' quipped Schrader.
``You know, you don't have to try to get 'em out of the hard drive
when they don't want to come to the set.'')
</P>
<P>
   For the Masuccis, at least, the future is neither remote nor
rapping at their door; they'll be using conventional actors in
their next movie, ``Judgment Time,'' a half-hour sci-fi thriller.
Every stage of filmmaking excites them _ the planning of
preproduction, the controlled mayhem of shooting, the creative
end-game of editing and post-production. ``The most exciting
phase,'' said Joe Masucci, ``is when you stumble upon the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, an idea is all they need. ``Anyone who ever wanted to
make a movie, if you're serious about it, the tools are affordable.
There's no reason not to do it,'' said Joe, and there are plenty of
young filmmakers who agree with him. Even a few from an older
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a kid today, 25 years old or whatever, it would be
really irresistible to go out there and buy $5,000 worth of
equipment and produce, make and distribute my own movies,'' Banks
said. ``And you can do it now. And there's no way you could do that
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With digital filmmaking,'' said Tugman, ``everything is about
kind of closing your eyes and seeing the images so clearly in your
head, then opening your eyes and for the first time not feeling
that lost, hopeless feeling of, `That's nice, but if only ...'
</P>
<P>
   ``The `if onlys' have changed. Now you can close your eyes and
dream what you wanna dream and open your eyes,'' he said. ``And you
will be able to realize anything in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-LOW-BUDGET-FILMS-2TAK     08-22 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-BUDGET-FILMS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TECHNOLOGY PUTS THE POWER OF HOLLYWOOD IN EVERYMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You've heard of low-budget film. You've heard of
micro-budget film. You may even have heard of people who make
low-budgeted and micro-budgeted films. At the very least, you've
heard of ``The Blair Witch Project'' (for good or for ill), patched
together by nobodies for a mere $30,000 and destined, thanks to
savvy Internet marketing, to make $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of all that. But chances are _ unless you're their
mother _ you've never heard of Joe and Dan Masucci, two guys who
make films so minutely budgeted that you'd need a microscope to
read the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   They make their movies entirely with digital equipment, on
digital tape, transferred to desktop computer and edited _
digitally, of course _ with widely available software. The end
product is stuff that looks good and costs little. And not a speck
of celluloid need apply.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the behemoths of Hollywood, about $95
million hollow men and $84 million Klumps, the mild-mannered
Masucci brothers are the real future of filmmaking. Their most
recent venture, a savvy, 50-minute mock ``X-Files'' episode titled
``Graceland'' that's part homage, part spoof, part hyperarticulate
Elvis conspiracy theory, cost less than $500 to make.
</P>
<P>
   Dan, an Apple computer technician who lives in Albany, directed
and starred as an dourly Duchovny-like Fox Mulder; Donna Hayes, a
friend, played Scully. Joe served as director of photography. Both
wrote and produced the film, in which an extraterrestrial Elvis
abducts and impregnates a humble Albany waitress.
</P>
<P>
   The end product, plugged on the Masuccis' Web site
(www.fountainheadpictures.com), has been distributed free of charge
to anyone who mails them a videotape or CD. So far, they say, about
150 copies of ``Graceland'' have been sent around the globe _ to
``Australia, Lithuania, Argentina, Belgium, Athens, Greece and all
around the country,'' said Dan, a stay-at-home dad in suburban East
Greenbush. ``When you include digital technology with use of the
Internet ... '' he begins, and his brother quickly finishes: ``...
you have a worldwide audience.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't make money off it. If they wanted to, they'd have a
few copyright holders to contend with (the Presley estate; Thirteen
Productions, which makes ``X-Files''; the Fox network). But the
project is nevertheless a masterstroke of self-promotion, a slick
business card that raises audience and industry awareness of the
Masuccis' filmcraft.
</P>
<P>
   They sent a copy to ``X-Files'' scribe Vince Gilligan, and
although nothing may come of the gesture, he replied with a
complimentary thank-you note and promised to pass on the episode to
his colleagues. It's a small victory for the Masuccis, but it
typifies the do-it-yourself mentality that drives such budding
filmmakers and points to the synergy between low costs and high
hopes that fuel the digital revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   MAINSTREAM MOVIEMAKING
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, just about anyone can shoot a movie. Just about
anyone can edit it _ avoiding the cost of hiring a traditional
editor in a traditional studio at the traditional
$100-plus-per-hour fees. And just about anyone can market it,
shilling on personalized Web pages or finding distribution on any
of several burgeoning sites (AtomFilms.com, for one) that screen
on-line movies for viewers with the proper software.
</P>
<P>
   As the Masuccis illustrate, the latest digital advances are
prying hard at the tightest seals of Hollywood. It's moviemaking
for Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmaking, in the Hollywood sense of the word, will never be
democratic, even if you go as far as Gus Van Sant shooting his next
project with Jim Carrey on digital. I don't think that means that
the industry itself is going to be more accepting of two guys from
Albany making a movie,'' said Jason Tugman, a digital filmmaker and
self-described ``Chief Idiot'' of a Chicago-based troubleshooting
Web site, DigitalIdiots.com. ``But I think what it's doing is
leveling the independent market and making the independent market
so that it is even more so _ independent in separating itself from
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Tugman's Web site helps filmmakers make sense of the new
technology, providing organized tutorials and plentiful how-tos.
The idea is to provide a digital leg up, ``to educate people in the
basics of digital filmmaking so they feel extremely comfortable
with the foundation. Because once you have the foundation, you can
take that and get in depth as much as you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   All filmmakers, he said, ``have these little ideas _ and they're
not these big, fancy ideas. They're sketches, they're bits, they're
moments, they're little things that in (traditional) film would
cost me a thousand dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new technology, ``I can literally free my mind from all
these things that are trapped in there, because I can spend _ what?
_ $15 on a DVD tape?''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FUN AND GAMES
</P>
<P>
   This is, as people in this exploding industry seem to agree, a
good thing. Inexpensive equipment (maybe $1,000 to $4,000 for a
camera; $1,600 for the computer hardware; $1,000 for the software)
is a good thing. The freedom to experiment is a good thing. The
plethora of filters and visual effects that can be applied in
post-production, at sub-sub-minimal cost, are good things. And
opening up the arcane world of filmmaking to anyone with a few
thousand bucks and the chutzpah to spend it is surely good thing.
As Joe Masucci observed, ``You can put a whole movie studio
together for $5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, there is a downside: the fact that a lot of these
new filmmakers are rank beginners, not all of them blessed with
talent. ``We will have a huge amount of bad, bad movies coming
along,'' said Ray Ortali, founder and chief executive of Prime
Technologies, a Delmar, N.Y.-based company that designs Web sites
and DVDs. ``But in this mountain of crap _ if we put it that way _
we are going to have some pearls.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
