<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-LONG-DISTANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONG-DISTANCE SERVICE IS BRISK FOR SBC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SANFORD NOWLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ SBC Communications Inc. has signed up more than
500,000 long-distance customers in Texas in the six weeks it has
been allowed to offer the service, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The brisk customer growth surprised some analysts by exceeding
that of Verizon Communications _ formerly Bell Atlantic _ when it
launched long-distance service last year in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon took more than three months to attract its first 500,000
long-distance customers. It passed the million-customer mark in
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly surprising to see SBC add this many customers
this fast,'' said David Burks, a telecommunications analyst for
J.J.B. Hilliard, W.L. Lyons in Louisville, Ky. ``The company's off
to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Burks said SBC's aggressive advertising and its good track
record with existing local-service customers contributed to the
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working very hard to get the word out that we're
offering long-distance service in Texas,'' said SBC spokesman Selim
Bingol. ``It's gratifying to see this kind of response.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC, the corporate parent of Southwestern Bell, posted news of
the customer additions in an investor briefing released late
Friday. San Antonio-based SBC also is the parent company of Pacific
Bell Nevada Bell in the West and Ameritech in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators gave final approval for SBC to enter Texas' $7.7
billion long-distance market on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Regional Bell companies such as SBC may offer long distance to
customers in their service area once they have shown state and
federal regulators their markets are open to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   So far, SBC and Verizon _ the partnership formed this year by
Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp. _ are the only regional Bells that
regulators have allowed to sell long distance in their home
territories. Both also are seeking permission to enter the
long-distance market in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Also in its investor briefing, SBC said it has more than 435,000
subscribers to its DSL (digital subscriber line) service, which
allows ultra-fast Internet access over standard phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   It wants to have 1 million DSL subscribers by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sanford Nowlin by e-mail at
snowlin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
