<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK16-COX     08-22 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online banking growing rapidly
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   That traditional but unconvincing excuse _ ``The check is in the
mail,'' has gotten even flimsier for the 10 percent of U.S.
households who bank on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10.5 million households used online banks last year
for bill-paying, checking accounts, credit cards and loans, buying
certificates of deposits or other financial services.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are many. ``People's money is something they are
always interested in following,'' said Jim Bruene, editor and
founder of the Online Banking Report newsletter. ``Online is an
easier way to do it, rather than waiting to look at a printed
statement once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors: More families have access to the Internet. Banks
have made it easier to use. And the array of services has
increased.
</P>
<P>
   More banks have rushed in to compete for that business, too.
Search for U.S.-based banks at www.onlinebankingreport
</P>
<P>
   .com, and you will find 789 listings. Some are only online. Many
more are subsidiaries of existing banks, large and small.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond convenience, some online banks also offer higher interest
rates on checking accounts and certificates of deposit than
conventional banks, no monthly fees and free online bill-paying
services.
</P>
<P>
   All those factors account for rapid growth since the first
online banking services appeared in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But there are drawbacks. You can't make cash deposits. You can
make direct deposits of your paychecks, but you have to mail in
other checks. ``Some people are really not happy with the downtime
until their money is deposited in their accounts,'' said Greg
McBride, a financial analyst at Bankrate.com.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be delays paying bills. A number of corporations,
such as AT&AMP;T, will accept electronic payment now. About half of
bill payments are made by that swift route, according to Bruene.
But the rest go from your online bank by mail.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Consumer Action, a San Francisco-based
watchdog organization, found that some online banks make it hard to
get questions answered, through the banks' Web sites or on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   True online banks have no ATMs, of course. Nor do they have
branch offices where you can talk to real people about real
problems. ``People want to work with someone they trust with their
money,'' Bruene said. ``Who do you trust more than your existing
bank?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bruene expects rapid growth to continue. He believes 15
million households will use online banks or credit unions by the
end of this year, and 20 million by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Banks will be happy with that. One recent study showed that the
cost of a full-service teller transaction is $1.07. The bank spent
27 cents for each ATM transaction _ but only 1 cent for
Internet-based transactions.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to open an online account, it pays to shop
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates differ considerably on checking accounts and CDs.
No-fee checking accounts and bill-paying are the norm, but not
universal.
</P>
<P>
   You may also want to check on what other services are offered.
The array varies considerably from one Web bank to the next.
</P>
<P>
   You can find frequently updated reports of interest rates at
www.bankrate.com and rankings of online banks at www
</P>
<P>
   .gomez.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among its rankings, Gomez says Atlanta-based Security First
Network Bank is best overall, Wachovia is the easiest to use and
USAccess Bank has the lowest overall cost.
</P>
<P>
   It will also pay to ask yourself some questions. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Am I comfortable with computers?
</P>
<P>
   Online banking requires basic computer skills and confidence to
entrust both money and financial information to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you amenable to banking with an entity you can't tangibly
see?'' asked Bankrate.com's McBride. ``The primary objection seems
to be placing your money with an institution that is more virtual
than traditional bricks and mortar, and that maybe in a different
part of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What services do I want?
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost accounts are an attractive feature, as are the
relatively high interest some online banks pay on checking accounts
and CDs. A tidy process for bill-paying attracts others.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're accustomed to meeting your money at the
neighborhood ATM, you'll have to consider how much the fees will
be. If you remember Jimmy Stewart as the infinitely kind banker in
the movie ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' rest assured you will not meet
him _ or any other real person _ on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How do I know an online bank is safe?
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Action recommends looking for ``128-bit encryption,''
the standard in the industry, and for a written guarantee to
protect account holders from losses due to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   You should also visit www.fdic.gov to check whether the bank
you're considering has deposit insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do I still want face-to-face contact?
</P>
<P>
   Most people do. At least 95 percent of online bank customers use
the online services of a traditional bank, according to Bruene.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason is the trust that comes from maintaining an
existing relationship with a bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   To check a bank's financial strength, go to www.veribanc.com.
You get an instant rating for $10. The phone number is
1-800-837-4226. You can get some basic information about a bank
from www.fdic.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Look up www.consumer-action.org for a comprehensive report on
online banking. You can also get a free copy by sending a stamped,
self-addressed envelope to Consumer Action-OB, 717 Market St.,
Suite 310, San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   For an interesting discussion of online banking, as well as
rankings by various attributes, go to www.gomez.com and click on
Banks. The essays are under ``Gomez Resources.''
</P>
<P>
   www.bankrate.com tracks interest rates from online banks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
