<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NY     08-22 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SHOULD STICK WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Aug. 22, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So far the dominant theme of Al Gore's presidential campaign
seems to be that he's not Bill Clinton. Of course, there are 275
million other Americans who are also not Bill Clinton, but there
you have it.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Biddle, for example, is not Bill Clinton. Puff Daddy is
also not Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Aguilera? Nope. She's not Bill Clinton either.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing day the Gore camp is going to more drastic
extremes to distance their man from the pants-around-the-ankles
legacy of the president. It's only a matter of time before they
make the claim that even though Gore has been the vice president of
the United States for nearly eight years, he's never actually met
Clinton in person. Not since Darva Conger fled Rick Rockwell's
clutches have I seen anyone try to desperately to shed a former
partner.
</P>
<P>
   It's ridiculous. I mean, was it really necessary for the
fabulous Gore daughters to form an alliance and vote Clinton off
the island during the tribal council portion of the Democratic
National Convention last week?
</P>
<P>
   And how about Gore's rousing refrain from ``the most important
speech of his political life,'' as 8,000 pundits dubbed it. (That's
about as insightful as calling the Super Bowl the most important
football game of the year.) In front of God and Tipper and country,
Gore proclaimed he was standing ``as my own man.''
</P>
<P>
   Well gee whiz. As a statement of independence, that's right up
there with, ``I think I deserve a later curfew, mom!'' and, ``Can I
stay at Tommy's house tonight? His parents said it was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republicans are furiously working to keep the
Clinton-Gore linkup at the forefront of the public consciousness,
like a busybody matchmaker who refuses to believe a marriage is
crumbling. As a guest editorialist reminded us in the New York
Times on Monday, Gov. George W. Bush's acceptance speech included
the line, ``After all the shouting and all of the scandal, we can
begin again.''
</P>
<P>
   Begin what, I'm not sure. But if you're a reporter and you
venture near any Bush staffer or Republican leader these days,
they'll hit you with some variation on that theme, some unsubtle
dig at Gore via Clinton. In fact if you venture anywhere near a
hardcore GOPer these days, you risk being wrestled to the ground
and told: ``Al Gore and Bill Clinton are the same guy! And Soylent
Green is people!''
</P>
<P>
   The media are also addicted to this whole
six-degrees-of-separation angle. Political cartoonists, columnists,
cable-talk yappers, even aliens like Sam Donaldson _ each day they
offer their take on the Clinton-Gore connection and whether the
candidate is doing a good enough job of separating himself from the
lame duck, scandal-tainted, yucky prez. Among both parties and the
press, it's a given that in order for Al Gore to win the general
election, he must shed that Clintonian snakeskin and stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong! Gore shouldn't be in Clinton denial, he should be riding
those Teflon coattails all the way to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   What everybody seems to be forgetting is that Clinton is a
winner. The ultimate survivor, forever prevailing over the
Republican Party. He defeated George Bush, he beat Bob Dole, he
whupped Newt Gingrich, he dismantled Henry Hyde's posse and he
could probably travel back in time and figure out a way to swipe an
election from Abraham Lincoln if he had to.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Clinton ``lost'' to the GOP in the midterm debacle of
1994, he won. Contract with America, my eye.
</P>
<P>
   We're living in a golden age of prosperity and peace. Maybe
Clinton shouldn't receive the bulk of the credit for that _ but
he's been the guy at the wheel for seven and a half years, and for
the majority of the voting public, that's always been good enough.
He's still in office because we kept him there.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore's really his own man, he'll reconsider the conventional
wisdom and stand next to Clinton as often as possible, wearing a
T-shirt with an arrow that points to the president and proclaims,
``I'm with him!'' Leave the dramatic breakup to Anne Heche and
Ellen Degeneres. Gore should stick it out with the one who brought
him to the dance in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
