<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROWING WEARY OF THE PUNDIT'S PRATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On behalf of all registered voters, likely
voters, the American people and America in general, I'd like to ask
how television, radio and print media ``experts'' know enough to
speak for me?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, for us.
</P>
<P>
   There must be close to 2 million such political pundits on
various payrolls these days. They are everywhere, at all hours. In
Pulitzer Prize-winning newspapers and the most esoteric cable
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly male, mostly white and _ it appears from the nice suits
and expensive haircuts of those on TV _ mostly well-paid, these
experts presume over and over to pronounce with unshakable surety
what the American people want with regard to:
</P>
<P>
   _ A president.
</P>
<P>
   _ A presidential candidate's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   _ The specific acceptance speech of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ The specific acceptance speech of Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   _ The behavior and speeches of all presidential candidates and
vice presidential candidates during the months separating their
nominating conventions and the national election.
</P>
<P>
   _ The behavior of Republican and Democratic presidential
candidates during the televised debates that take place over the
abovementioned time period.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any and every socio-political thing we might hear or think
about in these prosperous times, when ``everybody'' is so allegedly
fat and happy.
</P>
<P>
   How did these political analysts and observers get so very, very
informed?
</P>
<P>
   The word ``pundit'' comes from Hindu where it means a scholar
who is fluent in Sanskrit and educated in matters of law, divinity
and science.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, such qualifications are not required of the modern U.S.
version. But the easy confidence with which our pundits talk and
write about ``America's'' wants, needs and dreams sounds like an
ordinary person relaying the news to another that the sun does
indeed rise in the East.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow ventriloquist's dummies, have any of you invited any
of these people over to your house for pizza and beer or some
kebobs on the Weber?
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone tell me about the day that Tim or Chris or Morton or
George or William or Maureen _ or any of the 2 million _ knocked
upon your front door and said: ``Hi. I'd like to ask you if you
thought Al and Tipper's kiss was genuine passion or cynical
political manipulation?''
</P>
<P>
   Did a few of them send you a lengthy questionnaire along with
the U.S. Census form? Did you happen to take a long cruise or
cross-country flight with any of them? Are they calling everyone at
home during telemarketing time but me?
</P>
<P>
   Surely the pundits are not basing their omniscience on polls.
</P>
<P>
   All 2 million of them cannot seem to construct a compound
sentence without referring to ``the latest polls.'' But, I have
noticed, they all also never miss a chance to demonstrate their
consummate sophistication by dismissing the polls as ``interesting
but not at all conclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless the polls happen to support the specific point
the political expert is about to make or affirms the point he/she
made (so pointedly) the time before.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it's possible all 2 million of them are psychic.
</P>
<P>
   That would certainly explain how they can say things like,
``Americans want Al Gore to provide detail on his proposed
policies, but not too much detail.'' Or, ``America expects its vice
presidential candidates to play the role of the attack dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Americans are pretty happy in this economy; they just
can't get excited about the possibility of George Bush appointing
two anti-abortion justices to the U.S. Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   If all the experts and analysts were gathering intelligence by
spying on us with big telescopes and phone bugs, I think we'd know
it by now. William or Tim would slip and say, ``Unlike most of
America, Max and Florence Thompson in Topeka are very interested in
hearing about Hadassah Lieberman's recipe for her husband's
favorite egg dish.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what can explain it?
</P>
<P>
   How did the pundits get to be such experts? How do they continue
to get away with speaking for you and me? Won't someone solve the
mystery? America wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
