<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8921 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-VACATION-BUTLER-LIFEB     08-22 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-BUTLER-LIFEBEAT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1200-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT YOUR SERVICE, MADAM 
 SUBS TO INCLUDE PHOTO ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ''separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text.
 (ART ADV: Photos of butler Christopher and friend are available on
Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By JOAN SCOBEY  
 c. 2000 Joan Scobey  
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two minutes after I'm shown into my panelled room at the luxe
Lanesborough Hotel in London, where even the bathtub and toilet
have mahogany accents and the rugs are set flush into the parquet
floor, the doorbell rings and I meet my butler. Dark suit, pearl
gray striped tie, warm smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Christopher,'' he says pleasantly. ``May I unpack
for you?''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. I blush to think of anyone looking in my suitcase, not
least a butler who, I suppose, has unpacked at some of Britain's
stateliest homes. Inside are no ball gowns, no black satin teddies.
Instead images of my faded blue jeans, turtlenecks and sensible
walking shoes pass before my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm, thanks,'' I mumble. ``I think I can manage myself.'' I'm
already having trouble dealing with this butler concept.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher is obviously used to diffident Americans who aren't
up to being buttled. ``Here is your stationery,'' he moves on
pleasantly, pointing to some sheets of letterhead on the desk
printed: In residence, Joan Scobey. They sit next to business cards
with my private Lanesborough telephone and fax numbers. The fax
machine is hidden in a desk drawer, and Christopher shows me how it
works, along with an entertainment system tucked into a period
armoire.
</P>
<P>
   Last in my butler tutorial is the intricate panel of bedside
buttons that are control central for lights, temperature and a
variety of other earthly desires, including Privacy _ aka ``Do Not
Disturb.'' The most important button _ Butler _ seems to be
everywhere. There is hardly a corner of my bedroom or bathroom from
which I can't summon Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher is small and French. He was just promoted from room
service, and already knows discretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So who's at the hotel now?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businessmen,'' he answers smoothly. ``Entertainment people
love it. A gentleman from the Middle East is in the Royal Suite.''
That's as far as Christopher goes. But the staff still talks about
the time Madonna stayed in the Royal Suite and had the dining room
lined with mirrors and packed with fitness equipment. From her
balcony overlooking Buckingham Palace she even bestowed royal waves
on her fans below.
</P>
<P>
   After I had booked my room, I received the hotel's Guest Profile
form. It requested my choice of drinks for the bar, morning
newspapers and preferred mode of transportation (Did I want to be
picked up at the airport in the Jaguar or the Bentley?), as well as
my favorite music. I checked Jazz/Blues. Christopher was waiting
with ``Still Got the Blues,'' ``Hooked on Big Bands,'' ``Duke
Ellington'' and a long list of CDs from which I added ``The
Complete Beatles'' and Handel's ``Water Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar comes complete with a bucket of ice, tongs at the ready,
crystal decanters holding Scotch, gin and vodka, and six
Bordeaux-shaped bottles of Sparkling Blenheim mineral water. I'm
ready to settle into the leather sofa with a drink, kick back with
``Abbey Road,'' delve into the bowl of dates and strawberries _ and
contemplate life with a butler.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. I feel woefully inadequate for this
upstairs/downstairs scene. There's not only the matter of
butler-worthy clothes, but I'm not even up to speed on the business
amenities. Sure, I've stayed in hotel rooms with faxes before, but
never with anyone taking such a correct interest in my well-being.
</P>
<P>
   At the touch of the Butler button, Christopher appears in less
than a minute. Lanesborough butlers are trained to respond to their
discreet beepers within two minutes; if they don't, the call is
forwarded to another station and the butler team goes into code
blue alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christopher, I'd like to ask a friend to stop by for drinks
later.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Mrs. Scobey. I'll organize it.'' Christopher comes
from Epernay, so he knows a thing or two about champagne. I leave
everything to him.
</P>
<P>
   Lanesborough butlers are chosen for their aplomb and cool, I
later learn from Robert, the head butler. Calm, quick thinking and
a congenial personality are far more important than training.
Anthony Hopkins followed Robert around to pick up pointers for his
role in ``The Remains of the Day.'' Lanesborough butlers are not,
however, in the starchy Jeeves or John Gielgud tradition. They are
friendly, humorous, easy-mannered _ and completely correct.
</P>
<P>
   They also know when you're in your room and when you're not.
There are no hidden cameras to reveal exactly what you're doing and
where, but it's hard to escape the unnerving notion that Big Butler
is watching. Robert showed me how it's done. Sophisticated
computers register the status of motion detectors and sensors for
lights, television and air-conditioning in every room. If you
forget to turn off your Privacy button when you leave, and there's
no movement in your room for twenty minutes, the lights go out and
the staff feels free to enter.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to never disturb a guest. That works fine, unless
you happen to be quietly reading or soaking in a bubble bath and
find that the room suddenly goes dark, or that your butler has come
in to check the bar. (A regal wave of your hand will turn the
lights on at once; your butler won't blink an eye.)
</P>
<P>
   Walking dogs, buying clothes, planning menus and choosing wines,
even a 3 a.m. call to rehang a picture _ it's all in the life of a
Lanesborough butler. The Christophers, Sergios and Susans will do
just about anything that's asked of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One butler had to roll an Indian prince's turban on his head,
which took hours,'' said Robert. ``Another had to find a
thoroughbred horse for a guest to buy _ lucky one of our butlers
had been a horse breeder. Another with an economic degree wrote a
speech for a Thai banker, then trained him to give it.''
</P>
<P>
   I had far less taxing needs, and they were usually anticipated
(another mark of a good butler). With Christopher, I never had to
put my boots out. Every evening he spirited them away and returned
them polished to a fine patina and stuffed with tissue paper. One
day, a button on my jacket came loose. Of course, I could sew it on
myself, but hey, if there's a butler in your life, you might as
well let him buttle. I was beginning to get the hang of this.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of my stay I felt confident enough to ask for help
with some research. Richard happened to be on call at the time.
(You didn't think the same butler attends to you round the clock,
did you? You can enjoy three of them a day.) I was trying to find
the name of a particular restaurant a friend told me about. All I
knew was that there were no prices on the menu and you pay what you
think the meal is worth. It sounded like fun, but the concierge had
never heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a couple of hours,'' said Richard. Two hours later
there was a note on my desk with the name, address, tube station,
even the bus route.
</P>
<P>
   So that's the story. And when I leave for the airport, I hope
there'll be two of us going back to the States. Christopher and me.
</P>
<P>
   If you long to be pampered at The Lanesborough, singles start at
about $380 and doubles about $510, suites begin around $780, and
the Royal Suite, with three bedrooms for your entourage, is about
$6,000. The butler comes for free. Call 800-999-1828.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
