<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT'S MIND OVER BODY IN PURSUING TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Stands for Q-AND-A)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As Sydney beckons and the National Basketball
Association turns inside out, Ms. Demeanor gives her mailbag an
overdue once-over.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: How about the way Tiger Woods' competitors
have tried to get into better shape to deal with him? I've heard
that Colin Montgomerie lost 20 pounds, and everyone has heard about
David Duval's fitness obsession. I admire their drive. Don't you
think it will have an effect?
</P>
<P>
   _ R. Simmons, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Dear. Mr. Simmons: Well, if you watched the PGA Championship,
you saw Tiger pushed as hard as ever by a man with an extra chin.
This is not to say that tighter abs won't help golfers challenge
Tiger, who, aside from all of his other assets, maintains the
sleekest physique in the game. But the area where the other golfers
need the most help is in the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Bob May had no reason to believe that he could keep up with
Tiger in the PGA, and maybe that's the reason he did. David Duval
skipped the tournament because he has a fragile back, but his body
isn't the only reason for his inability to keep pace with Tiger.
His confidence comes and goes. His lean body doesn't look merely
fit. It looks starved, and angry, a web of misplaced passions.
</P>
<P>
   All of Tiger's passion aligns perfectly. It might make him
unbeatable, but May proved that Tiger isn't untouchable. It would
be great to see some more real challengers, if only to frame
Tiger's ability better.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: Can you explain the deeper meaning of the
big, four-way trade in the NBA that everyone's talking about? Where
would it leave my Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.N. McMurphy, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Dear J.N.: As the stylists say, the key to success is how you
accessorize. If this deal goes through as planned, the Lakers would
have details to flatter both Phil Jackson, pensive guru, and
Shaquille O'Neal, the favored canvas of cheap-shot artists
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Their frontcourt would include graduates of Yale (Chris Dudley),
Stanford (Mark Madsen) and Duke (Christian Laettner). The potential
for intellectual pretensions is boundless . . . until you consider
that they will all be flak jackets for a guy who dropped out of LSU
. . . and that the brightest Laker just might be the youngster who
never went to college at all. A gossipy item in L.A. recently
placed Kobe Bryant at a posh Italian eatery, speaking fluently in
Old Country tongue to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   As for the soon-to-be-departed Glen Rice, when he sang ``Me, me,
me, me, me,'' he wasn't tuning up for La Traviata. He never spoke
the right language for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: What do you think of this softball team that
won the Little League World Series with five 14- to 16-year-old
boys on the roster? I know it's legal to put boys in the girls
sport, but it doesn't seem fair. I can't blame the organizers for
saying they want to rewrite the rules to exclude the boys.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Riggs, Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Riggs: The winning team came from Eloy, Ariz., a small
town that couldn't put together enough players to field an entire
baseball or softball team. I'm not confident supporting a team that
could encourage other cities to transform a girls sport into a boys
one. But if girls are entitled to take spots away from boys on a
Little League baseball team, it's hard to argue that boys should be
banned from softball.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so hard to figure out that the coach of the
second-place team made a huge mistake by choosing to forfeit the
final game. His players apparently wanted to go ahead and compete.
He refused, saying that three of them had been hurt in a prior game
against the big, burly boys.
</P>
<P>
   I have a problem with his argument because his all-female team
had lost by only one run to the coeds in the prior game. In another
showdown earlier in the tournament, they actually beat them by a
run.
</P>
<P>
   What I really want to know is, given the way female athletes are
expected to promote themselves these days, when will the Eloy Five
be asked to pose naked for a calendar or crawl seductively across
the floor for a Sports Illustrated picture?
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: One question, two words: Bela Karolyi?
</P>
<P>
   _ Flip Dout in Boston
</P>
<P>
   Dear Flip: Here's my theory: Ever seen him and Bob Knight in the
same room together? The initials are the same. The attitude is
similar. The only difference is that none of the gymnasts would
dare challenge Karolyi. So he ends up looking like Knight on happy
pills.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ms. Demeanor: What have you thought of Dennis Miller so far
on Monday Night Football?
</P>
<P>
   _ Roger Nielsen, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Nielsen: He'd be marginally passable as a commentator
on professional wrestling. Give me Chris Rock, or Ellen DeGeneres,
or any of the other comics with regular gigs on HBO, Miller's
stand-up home. But Rock and DeGeneres won't do football, because
they're too good at their first jobs. Miller's blather is vapid
pretension, delivered in the most irritating voice imaginable. Come
to think of it: Pretentious, irritating? Has anyone seen Miller and
Christian Laettner in the same room?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gwen Knapp is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
