   ATTENTION SPORTS, NFL EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service/CoxNet is producing a full-color, four-page
preview of the NFL season, which kicks off Sunday, Sept. 3. The
package will be available by 5 p.m. ET on Friday, Aug. 25 for
release on Sunday, Aug. 27. A budget of the preview section follows
below.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service will also deliver a weekly NFL page throughout
the regular season every Friday by 5 p.m. ET for release the
following Sunday. It will include a feature story on a star player,
notes on top players and teams, standings and TV schedules and will
be built to accomodate strip and half-page ads.
</P>
<P>
   Both the special preview section and weekly page will be
available in three formats: Digital Technology International, Quark
XPress or PDF format from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For sales information, please call Bob Farnell at 800-535-4425
or e-mail farnellb(at)nytimes.com. Each page is available for only
$20.
</P>
<P>
   And to view the regular lineup of weekly paginated pages offered
by Cox News Service and The New York Times Syndicate, please visit:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If you have any questions, please call CoxNet in Atlanta at 404
526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NFL PREVIEW BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   PAGE ONE
</P>
<P>
   NFL-PREVIEW _ A look at the state of the NFL heading into the
2000 season. Has expansion watered down the league to the point
where teams such as Atlanta, St. Louis and Tennessee can make it to
the Super Bowl or have the teams at the bottom for so long finally
found the magic to become competitive? Is it a combination of both?
We will attempt to point out three to five major occurrences that
have had a huge impact on the league, including the institution of
the salary cap. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PAGE TWO
</P>
<P>
   NFL-NFC-CAPSULES _ A team-by-team look at strengths, weaknesses
and personnel changes. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
