<HEADLINE>
IT'S LAST-MINUTE HEROICS FOR THE RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES 
c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Perhaps, Trot Nixon suggested, it's time for the
nightly packed houses at Fenway Park _ 38 straight sellouts and
counting _ to do the opposite of the crowds in southern California,
who leave in the seventh inning to beat the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why play the first eight innings?'' Nixon said Monday. ``Let's
just go straight to the ninth. We'd finish a lot quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful thing, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast meeting with the boss? Catching the 7 a.m. shuttle to
LaGuardia? Got to make your deliveries to Kiki's Kwik Mart before
dawn?
</P>
<P>
   If that's your schedule and you're a Red Sox fan, your life has
taken on another layer of pain in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   But who's complaining? If it takes an extra cup of coffee or two
every morning for the next six weeks to survive, fire up the
grinder. The way the Sox are winning lately, with the accent on the
first syllable, you go to bed at your own peril.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Brian Daubach, hitting a home run with two outs
in the ninth to tie the score, then dumping a two-run flare over
shortstop in the 11th inning, again just one out away from defeat,
to lift the Sox to a 7-6 win over the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a whole lot of hits lately,'' said Daubach, who
had had just 10 hits and 3 RBIs in 61 at-bats this month and had
been dropped into the No. 8 hole by manager Jimy Williams. ``But
I've gotten some huge ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the last eight games, the Sox have won in their
last at-bat. Six times in the last 24 games, they have come from
two or more runs behind after failing to do so once in their first
97 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like this bring you together a little bit more,''
reliever Rod Beck said. ``Everyone remembers how much fun it is to
win. It's important to feel that from time to time, because it
reminds all of us what the goal is.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox closer Derek Lowe was one out away from being the losing
pitcher after giving up a double to Troy Glaus to open the 11th and
two successive bunts, including a suicide squeeze by Adam Kennedy,
the same player whose three-run home run had broken a 2-all tie in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was in the dugout when Daubach reached out and hit
Shigetoshi Hasegawa's trick pitch, ``the Shuto,'' a
sinkerball/forkball tailing away from him, inches off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just went `who-o-o-o-o-o-o,' '' Lowe said, the wide arc of
his smile matching the motion he was making with his hand to
describe the looping flight of Daubach's game-winner, which fell a
short hop in front of the hopeless dive of Angels left fielder
Orlando Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional swing was almost unbearable for everyone on the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the bottom of the emotional scale,'' said catcher
Jason Varitek, who had just hit into a bases-loaded, no-out double
play that almost became a triple play because of the inexplicable
delayed reaction by baserunners Troy O'Leary and Manny Alexander.
``I had just hit a ball hard, but right at somebody, exactly what I
didn't want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Brian came up big again. We were pretty much written off
in that game. Two outs, nobody on in the ninth inning. But I
happened to get a walk, and Brian hit that home run. Just a great
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, of course, first arrived here as the ultimate
replacement player, in more than one sense of the word. He was, of
course, the widely ridiculed choice of Sox general manager Dan
Duquette to replace Mo Vaughn, which was a little like asking an
accordion player to replace Seiji Ozawa as conductor of the Boston
Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   While buried in the Mets' minor league system, Daubach had been
pressed into service to play as a replacement for the striking big
leaguers during spring training of 1995. For all the underdog
stories of the minor league lifer making it to the big time last
season, there was a subtext that rubbed some people raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the whole story,'' Beck said. ``A lot of guys still
aren't over the strike. I have mixed feelings about it. I like
Dauber. He's a good dude. But that will be an issue he'll have to
deal with for the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, (ex-Sox pitcher) Mark Portugal treated him like
(expletive). It didn't matter that he was a good guy. A lot of guys
lost a lot of money during that thing, and a lot of guys lost a lot
of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm over it. It doesn't bother me so much. There were a lot of
guys lied to who were in (Daubach's) position. They were threatened
that they would never get back in the game if they didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big mess for everyone concerned. I think it was the
worst thing that ever happened to this game, but to dwell on it is
useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Better, instead, to savor the sweet taste left by Daubach's
dramatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Rico Brogna's slam,'' said first-base coach Tommy
Harper, referring to last Monday's scene stealer. ``You can't
describe those feelings. When that game is over, and you know that
you don't have to go back out there, and the fans are just
delirious when that first ball goes out, two out in the ninth, and
the same man gets the winning hit with two outs two innings later,
that's got to be an unbelievable feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you, because I never did that. But I've got to
imagine Dauber's feeling pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Nixon was pounding on Daubach in the midst of
another joyous postgame scrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's had such buzzard's luck for so long,'' Nixon said.
``You look at the scoreboard, and you think he hasn't been hitting
the ball hard at all. But he's been hitting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really happy for Dauber. I told him before he went up
there, `Show him what you can do.' That's an inside joke we have
throughout the clubhouse. And that's what he did. He got a tough
pitch, and flared it out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
