<HEADLINE>
LABOR FALLS IN BEHIND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Vice President Al Gore's huge postconvention bounce last
week, it appears that many rank-and-file union members have put
aside their disappointment over Gore's support of the China trade
bill and made his election a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's leap in the polls, which brought him from more than a
dozen points behind George W. Bush to six points ahead in one poll
and dead even with the Texas governor in other polls, is largely
attributed to his populist-oriented speech.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, whenever Gore mentioned working families _ which has
been organized labor's catchword for middle-class families
struggling in spite of the booming economy _ many union workers
felt Gore was talking to them. And, indeed, he was.
</P>
<P>
   As the polls have shown, Gore's support among males increased
significantly. No doubt much of that gain was from union workers
who had earlier expressed their displeasure over Gore's support for
the bill that would normalize trade relations with China despite
China's poor record on human and workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also expanded his lead over Bush among women (apparently
including working women) both single and married.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's ``fight for working families'' theme struck a chord
with union leaders and the rank and file. They know that a Bush
administration may try, legislatively, to weaken the strength and
effectiveness of unions. The GOP also knows union support of
candidates can make a difference not only in congressional races,
but also in the making of laws that can help or hurt unions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's bump in the polls also comes at the expense of the Green
Party's Ralph Nader. Before Gore's convention speech, Nader and his
populist approach, which included a strong stance against the China
trade bill, appeared to cut into Gore's Democratic base.
</P>
<P>
   But after Gore s speech, which included many of the populist
themes Nader has espoused, Nader's rankappeared to have temporarily
halted at 3 or 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Gore's boost among unions and working families was
helped when the UAW endorsed him almost immediately after he chose
Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as his running mate.
Ironically, Lieberman also supported the China trade bill, which
the UAW denounced as a threat to US jobs. However, Lieberman still
has a strong labor record, of which the UAW is aware.
</P>
<P>
   But the UAW, which had considered supporting Nader, apparently
decided to back the Gore-Lieberman ticket. They know that Nader,
despite his appealing themes, cannot become president. And
supporting Nader would serve only to help Bush win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's earlier endorsement of Gore, and its continued
backing of his candidacy even after he supported the China trade
bill, probably helped to keep much of the vice president's base
together up to the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has nearly his entire Democratic base intact and can now
reach out for the independents, whom he hopes will see him as the
one who best represents their views, their concerns, and their
futures. However, Gore knows _ as does Bush _ that the race is
still very close and could be decided by a few states.
</P>
<P>
   And, as former Governor Michael S. Dukakis found out in his
election battle with former President George Bush, who in turn
later found out in his battle with Clinton, that even a significant
lead in the polls during the late summer is no guarantee of a
victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past week, Gore has increased his standing in the
polls largely because rank-and-file union workers have decided to
stand with him. Now Gore can run for the White House with the
renewed and energetic wind of labor at his back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
