<HEADLINE>
BARGAINS ON CRUISE VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've thought of taking a cruise, the time to do so has
never been better.
</P>
<P>
   This year is seeing the largest influx of new ships since 1998,
and even more are expected in 2001 and 2002. With cruise capacity
growing and bookings softer than cruise lines expected, discounting
throughout the industry is rampant. It's the old story of supply
and demand: Supply is up, demand is down, and discounting is the
way to fill the ships.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're looking for a good deal, this is the year. Next
year may not be so great. ``I think the overall amount of
discounting seen in 2000 will dissipate'' in 2001, Rick James, a
Princess Cruises senior vice president, told a Florida panel
recently, according to Travel Weekly, a national trade publication.
The publication said he saw the lines promoting ``more aggressive
early-booking discounts'' as a marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   However, discounting cruise fares by one means or another should
be around for a while as long as there are more staterooms to fill
than passengers. Just as the sticker price on a new car is not the
final price, so to is the list price for a cruise. Most lines offer
early-booking discounts already that are far below the brochure
price. When shopping for a cruise, don't discount the luxury lines
_ you just may find luxury at the price of a lower-costcruise.
</P>
<P>
   While the buys on the seas are great, don't let price alone be
the reason for choosing one line or ship over another. The best
advice is to see a knowledgeable travel agent who can match your
interests and desires with the right ship.
</P>
<P>
   Many travel agencies now specialize in cruises only or have a
special cruise department with agents who have first-hand
experience on many cruises.
</P>
<P>
   World Wide Cruises in Florida offers a last-minute desk _ in the
cruise industry that can be anywhere from two days to six months
prior to sailing. To find out what some of these deals are,
consumers can call their hot line at 800-882-9000 or visit
www.wwcruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   The savings or discounting on upcoming cruises can vary greatly.
For example, Radisson Seven Seas Cruises is offering savings of up
to 50 percent off the second-guest fare and ``immediate desposit
rewards'' of up to $1,000 in shipboard credits for deposits secured
with a credit card at the time of booking on its Feb. 2, 2001 Grand
Circle South America 58-night voyage. Passengers have the
flexibility to choose one of four shorter segments or combine two
or more segments for savings up to $17,590 a couple on the full
cruise, as well as receiving complimentary first class air.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also offering two-for-one savings on fall
sailings of its Radisson Diamond from Europe and on four Caribbean
sailings as well as on its Paul Gauguin on its cruises of from
Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Victory sets sail
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To experience the newest ship in the world, one just has to head
to New York City where the Carnival Victory will be offering a
series of four- and five-day eastern Canada cruises beginning Aug.
31. In late September, the ship will sail on one- to five-night
cruises from Newport News, Va., and Charleston, S.C., followed by a
program of seven-day alternating eastern and western Caribbean
cruises from Miami beginning Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of the 102,000 ton Carnival Victory and
its 15,000-square foot health and fitness facilty, annual spa usage
on the line's 15-ship fleet is expected to top the million mark for
the first time. That means 50 percent of Carnival's nearly 2
million annual guests are expected to be using the health and
fitness facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exercising has become an important part of people's daily
lives _ even while on vacation _ and the Carnival Victory was
designed with today's health-conscious guests in mind, offering a
variety of sophisticated equipment and expansive facilites, along
with pampering treatments they otherwise might not indulge in back
home,'' said Bob Dickinson, Carnival president.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these cruises see a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Irish cruise
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 10th annual Irish Festival Caribbean Cruise will be held
aboard the Holland America line's Westerdamn departing Fort
Lauderdale Jan. 19. More than 50 hours of traditional Celtic
entertainment from music to dance and culture will be featured as
the vessel cruises to six ports of call. And there will be daily
workshops on all things Irish, from learning to dance a jig to
instructions on the tin whistle. Guests are also encouraged to
socialize with the performers. The seven-day cruise cost from
$1,299 to $2,499 and can only be booked through Irish Festival
Cruises at 800-441-HARP.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
7 days with Disney
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Cruise Line is now offering a seven-night Caribbean
cruise in addition to its three- and four-day sailings.
</P>
<P>
   While the Disney Wonder will continue to offer its combination
land-and-sea vacations that combine a three- or four-day cruise
with a three- or four-day stay at Disney World, the Disney Magic
expands the cruise experience with a cruise that offers three days
at sea, and three ports of call _ St. Maarten, St. Thomas, and
Disney's own isle, Castaway Cay.
</P>
<P>
   For its seven-day cruise, Disney has created a new show, C'est
Magique, that combines magic, stagecraft, and sensational
illusions. ``We have taken clasic magic to a level never before
seen,''said Cliff Perry, Disney Cruise's entertainment director.
</P>
<P>
   Just as on the shorter cruises, the Magic will offer rotation
dining, where guests and their waiters move from themed dining room
to themed dining room. In addition there will be special dinners
including a ``It's a Small World'' one with dishes from throughout
the world. For adults, the Palo specialty restaurant will open
during days for champagne brunch and afternoon tea. There's even a
midnight buffet behind kitchen galley doors.
</P>
<P>
   During days at sea the Magic features a new themed approach to
adult programming through conversations with experts in nautical
lore, entertaining, and Disney heritage. And for children there are
30 new programs and activities keyed to ages 3 to 4, 5 to 7, 8 to
9, and 10 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Both ships feature a visit to Castaway Cay where the ships dock
and passengers can walk ashore rather than take a tender in as on
other lines; a nighttime entertainment area just for adults, nearly
a deck of children's programming, original Disney shows, and
first-run Disney films and animated classics in the theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
