<HEADLINE>
STUDENT ADVANTAGE SAID TO BE BUYING OUT RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Student Advantage Inc. of Boston, a leading online service for
college students, is expected to announce a deal to buy most of the
assets of its troubled top competitor CollegeClub.com, according to
people familiar with the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, due this week, will make Student Advantage the
overwhelming leader in a higher education market targeted by more
than a dozen start-ups and millions in venture-capital funding over
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage's fee-based service counts 2.1 million
students as members nationwide. CollegeClub.com, based in San
Diego, is used by 2.9 million registered students at 3,600 college
and university campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Though CollegeClub managed to attract a huge student following,
it was driven to serious financial trouble in the process. The
company filed for Chapter 11 bankrupty protection Monday, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisition of CollegeClub assets will be subject to the
approval of a Bankruptcy Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage has agreed to pay about $20 million in cash
and stock to acquire CollegeClub's Web site and other intellectual
property. It also will assume some of the company's revenue
contracts, including a relationship with General Motors Corp. The
company had purchased the assets of another CollegeClub subsidiary,
eStudentLoan LLC, for $1 million last month.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage has secured a $10 million financing commitment
from FleetBoston Financial Corp. to help fund the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   CollegeClub executives could not be reached Monday. A Student
Advantage spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   CollegeClub is another example of the fast-changing fortunes of
consumer-oriented Internet companies. Though its assets are selling
at bargain-basement prices, CollegeClub had been contemplating an
$85 million initial public stock offering just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company pulled its IPO registration in June, when chief
executive and cofounder Michael Pousti resigned. CollegeClub's
chief operating officer, James DeBello, quit soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage has built a larger and more predictable
business by charging student members $20 per year and forging
relationships with big corporations and universities themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Card-carrying members pay for exclusive student discounts,
mostly available offline at stores and restaurants, as well as
access to information and services on Student Advantage's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The company has relationships with 50 national retailers,
including AT&AMP;T, Amtrak, Tower Records, and Staples Inc. It also
maintains retail discount relationships with 15,000 local
participating stores in 125 cities across the country. Student
Advantage sometimes is paid a percentage of any increase in
student-discount business the national retailers receive as a
result of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Other national sponsors, such as AT&AMP;T, buy membership cards in
bulk and distribute them to students as customer premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage, founded eight years ago by former Bain
Capital executive Ray Sozzi, was just one company in a crowd of
competitors trying to use the Internet to reach students in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation and financial struggles have whittled the field
down to just a few public competitors.
</P>
<P>
   CollegeClub became one of the young industry's leading
consolidators, acquiring College
</P>
<P>
   student.com, Versity.com, eStudentLoan.com, Izio.com, and
Campus24.com in just the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage acquired two competitors in the last year,
College411 and Scholaraid.
</P>
<P>
   Other surviving public competitors have been struggling in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of YouthStream Media Networks Inc. have lost more than 88
percent of their value so far this year. It bought Acton-based
Teen.com for $5.4 million in stock last month.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Washington-based Varsity Group Inc., which went public
at $10 each in February, traded below $1 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Student Advantage has hardly been immune from stock market
problems. It went public at $8 per share in June 1999, and the
stock peaked at $28 in December. But those shares have tumbled to
as low as $3.0625 this year and finshed Monday at $7.0625.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
