<HEADLINE>
PILOTS SAY BETTER OXYGEN MASKS COULD SAVE LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An AirTran Airways DC-9 made an emergency landing on Aug. 8 in
Greensboro, N.C., when smoke filled the cockpit about 10 minutes
after takeoff and spread into the passenger compartment.
</P>
<P>
   As the flight crew struggled to bring the airplane with 61
people on board back to Greensboro, their ability to see outside
the plane as well as to view critical cockpit gauges was hampered
by thick smoke, sources close to an investigation of the incident
say. The crew not only had to fly the plane and locate the source
of the smoke, they also had to put on cumbersome oxygen masks to
cover their noses and mouths as well as don and adjust smoke
goggles.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of time, attention, and coordination required to put
on the oxygen masks and smoke goggles has been an issue with pilots
since at least 1996, when a ValuJet DC-9 crashed in Florida,
killing all 110 on board. After the accident, ValuJet became
AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are dealing with all that, it means you can't be
doing anything else _ like flying the airplane,'' said Paul
McCarthy, the Air Line Pilots Association's safety chairman. The
union represents more than 50,000 pilots at major airlines, but not
AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent incident involving AirTran has received scant
attention in the press. But safety officials say privately it is a
prime example of the need for improved masks for cockpit crews
fighting smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots say that there is a much better safety system. Full face
masks, which are form fitting, can be put on with one hand in
seconds and provide oxygen and clear air around the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of exceptions, virtually every major carrier,
however, still uses the two-piece set with an oxygen mask for the
mouth and separate goggles for the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those masks go back to ancient technology,'' said John Mazor,
a spokesman for the airline pilots' union. ``Their primary job is
to deliver oxygen and not keep out smoke and fumes.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the two-piece set requires both hands to put on and
adjust and takes as long as 15 seconds to put on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when the cockpit is filling with smoke, seconds
count,'' said Mazor.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots say that smoke in the cockpit is the most urgent
emergency in flight because it can easily get out of control,
options are limited, and time is critical.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 2, 1998, Swissair Flight 111, an MD-11, crashed off the
coast of Nova Scotia with 231 on board. The pilot reported smoke in
the cockpit and was circling to dump fuel before attempting to land
in Halifax. Everyone on board the jet died.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, which at the time code-shared with Swissair,
announced last year that it would begin retrofitting its entire
600-airplane fleet with one-piece masks that have a communication
system inside and are large enough to fit over prescription
eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for United Airlines said its Airbus aircraft have
the full face masks, and the airline is putting the newer masks on
all of its planes, a procedure that is expected to be completed by
the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration requires equipment for
breathing and protecting eyes in the event of smoke in the cockpit,
but has not required a particular design.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, which investigates all
aviation accidents in the United States and makes safety
recommendations to the FAA and airlines based on its
investigations, concluded in the wake of the 1996 ValuJet crash
that the system of an oxygen mask and smoke goggles is cumbersome.
The safety board recommended that the FAA ``establish a performance
standard for the rapid donning of smoke goggles; then ensure that
all carriers meet this standard through improved smoke goggle
equipment, improved flight crew training, or both.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for American and Continental airlines said their
planes are equipped with the two-piece masks. A US Airways
spokesman said the airline's fleet is split with some planes having
two-piece masks and others having full face masks.
</P>
<P>
   Tad Hutcheson, a spokesman for AirTran, said the airline's 12
newer airplanes, Boeing 717s, have full face masks, but the fleet
of 35 DC-9 aircraft does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things our safety department is evaluating right
now is whether to convert the DC-9 mask to a full face mask,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The AirTran flight took off from Greensboro on Aug. 8 bound for
Atlanta. When the plane was 15 miles from the airport and climbing
through 7,000 feet, the first officer smelled smoke and seconds
later the captain smelled it.
</P>
<P>
   They declared an emergency, shut down the main electrical power,
and returned to Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, I heard the sound of the engines make like a
drastic slowdown,'' said passenger Clarence Thompson of Chicago.
``It was very unusual because we were still cimbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started banking,'' said Thompson. ``I was on the left side
of the plane, in row 20 by the window, and all I could see was
ground and I thought `we are going down.' About a minute later, the
pilot comes on and said we have to return to the airport. He never
came back on again. The next thing we heard was the flight
attendants telling us to put our heads down. I looked up one last
time and saw smoke in the front of the plane. I was sure we were
going to crash.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed and turned onto a taxiway and stopped, its tail
sticking out on the active runway. Using emergency slides and
over-wing emergency exits, everyone got out safely. The copilot was
one of four AirTran employees treated at a local hospital for smoke
inhalation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew did a good job getting the aircraft back. If the
weather was bad or they were a little further out, the outcome
would have been a lot different,'' said a federal transportation
official familiar with the investigation of the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
