<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RISON ARRIVES IN OAKLAND WITH AN ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ Never mind what you have heard about Andre
Rison. The wide receiver is nothing like the trouble-maker you've
read about, say friends and former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a guy that, despite what the media might believe, is
very much a team football player,'' said Oakland Raiders
quarterback Rich Gannon, who played with Rison on the Kansas City
Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   The two are teammates again. The Raiders signed Rison Monday,
following the 11-year player's release by the Chiefs last week.
</P>
<P>
   On his flight to Oakland on Sunday night, Rison said he turned
to a Raiders fan sitting behind him and said, ``You can't hate me
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Rison is a five-time Pro Bowl player. He has 702 catches for
9,599 yards and 78 touchdowns. He also has been involved in
questionable off-field incidents and has sometimes been accused of
causing trouble in the locker room. During training camp with the
Chiefs in Wisconsin this year, he was cited for failing to identify
himself to a police officer. He also goes on trial next month on
charges of stealing a $1,000 tape recorder. Four years ago his
girlfriend, singer Lisa ``Left Eye'' Lopes set fire to his house
after a domestic dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy that likes to do his own thing, from what I know
about him,'' said wide receiver Tim Brown, who said he and Rison
were friends. ``As long as he does his own thing on the field,
that's all I care about. And, hey, this is the Raiders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to judge him for ourselves,'' coach Jon Gruden
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a new home, a new environment,'' Rison said. ``I've got
a new lease on life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rison spent the past three years with the Chiefs. The Raiders
are his seventh team.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden would not be specific about what role Rison will play
with the Raiders, other than to note that Brown and James Jett
remained the team's starting wideouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to overstate anything right now,'' Gruden said.
``We'll see what happens in the next couple weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But players were doing plenty of speculating on how the talented
receiver might help diversify the Raiders' passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he lines up wide by himself on one side and me and James
Jett are on the other side, they can't just say that's another
guy,'' Brown said. ``That's Andre Rison over there. Of course he
has to go out and make some plays, but I think his name is going to
carry a lot of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Rickey Dudley also was pleased with Rison's addition.
``I've got to believe it's for the better,'' he said, noting the
challenge defensive secondaries will face in covering him and the
three wide receivers. ``Somebody is going to have a mismatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gannon said the Raiders were unlikely to move too far from their
basic run game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've invested a great deal of time and money into two great
football players in (running backs) Napoleon Kaufman and Tyrone
Wheatley, and you don't want to abandon that and say we're going to
start throwing the football all the time now,'' Gannon said. ``But
we threw the ball quite a bit last year and we were productive, and
we can be a little more aggressive and effective this year. But
we're still going to run the football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have been looking for another receiver since Terry
Mickens was lost indefinitely due to a bruised spinal column.
</P>
<P>
   Rison said even though he was contacted by several teams, he
knew he would become a Raider as soon as he was cut in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my mind made up,'' he said, noting the Raiders and the
Chiefs ran similar offenses. ``But they run it to perfection
here.''
</P>
<P>
   After going to the Super Bowl with the Green Bay Packers and to
the playoffs with the Atlanta Falcons, Rison said he was hoping to
add a winning edge to the Raiders. ``My biggest thing I'm bringing
here,'' he said, ``is I want this team to have an attitude. . . .
No one beats us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
