<HEADLINE>
STARS DISH IT OUT BUT CAN'T TAKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most neutral observers have absolved Tampa Bay's Mamadou ``Big
Mama'' Diallo of blame in the collision that resulted in
season-ending injuries to MetroStars goalkeeper Mike Ammann last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the MetroStars continue to accuse Diallo of ``malicious''
intent in the incident, which left Ammann with three broken ribs, a
punctured lung, and facial cuts. Though MLS has cleared Diallo,
MetroStars general manager Nick Sakiewicz threatened to take the
matter to another level _ either the US Soccer Federation, FIFA, or
the US courts.
</P>
<P>
   And after the MetroStars' 5-3 win over Colorado Saturday,
defender Mike Petke revealed a T-shirt that promised revenge.
Petke, it should be noted, had been assigned to mark Diallo, who
scored three goals in the Mutiny's 4-3 overtime victory over the
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   MLS vice president Ivan Gazidis planned to address the situation
in a conference call Tuesday. He has likely placed a gag order on
the MetroStars and should stick by the decision not to punish
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diallo might have been a little reckless or clumsy,'' a league
spokesman said Monday. ``But the intent to injure wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars' protests seem somewhat shrill. They have
reversed their on-field fortunes this season, improving from a
dispirited team to one that could contend for the MLS Cup title.
They also have developed a reputation for overly aggressive play.
</P>
<P>
   Petke, for instance, was recently spotlighted on the ESPN Extra
Time show for a dangerous, studs-up challenge. Commentator Alexi
Lalas correctly analyzed Petke's play as brainless, though it was
also destructive in intent. In fact, such tackles occur in more
sophisticated leagues only in extreme cases; yet Petke made the
tackle in the final minutes with his team leading, 4-1. Even more
alarming, Petke proclaimed his innocence after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Also disturbing are reports that Sakiewicz previously offered to
compensate MetroStars players who had been fined for overly
aggressive play. And MetroStars defenders are certainly encouraged
to be destructive; MetroStars press releases refer to the team's
``defensive backfield,'' a football term that connotes a propensity
for colliding with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern that emerges is that the MetroStars are not
uninterested in being involved in rough play, motivated partially
because they wanted to prove they would not be as dysfunctional as
in '99.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of Petke's tackles are well-timed, and his
positioning is good. Petke is a very competent defender who could
become a US national team candidate, but to encourage him to be
brutish is doing him a disservice.
</P>
<P>
   A final word about rough play, then.
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous incident in high-level soccer in the US in
recent years occurred July 4, 1994, at Palo Alto, Calif. Brazilian
midfielder Leonardo delivered an elbow that nearly killed Tabare
Ramos, who is now a MetroStars midfielder. MLS would be wise to
draw the line on gratuitous violence now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olympic choices solid
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The choice of players for the US Olympic team was made long ago
by coach Clive Charles. The team has played together for two years
and had success, and Charles was not about to break up a group that
had developed loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions about some of the choices, especially the
naming of Bayer Leverkusen's Frankie Hejduk as an overage player.
</P>
<P>
   The other over-23 players, Jeff Agoos and Chris Armas, should
bring stability.
</P>
<P>
   But Hejduk, despite being potentially more talented, does not
seem to be what the team needs. Some observers blame Hejduk for
costing the US in its first two World Cup qualifying matches last
month. In a 1-1 tie in Guatemala, Hejduk did not kill the clock and
wasted crosses with the US leading in the final minutes. And in a
2-1 loss at Costa Rica, Hejduk's wild tackle in the penalty area
led to a likely makeup call and Hernan Medford's deciding goal in
the 93d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Charles also is faithful to the central defensive duo of the
Revolution's Brian Dunseth and Tampa Bay's Chad McCarty. Chicago's
Carlos Bocanegra seems to be a viable challenger for position but
was not included.
</P>
<P>
   But a more fundamental problem with the team was noted by Soccer
America columnist Paul Gardner in a brilliant analysis that traced
the roots of Charles's selections to Portland, Ore., and East
London. During the NASL heyday, the Portland Timbers became a huge
success by importing mostly workmanlike players from England. The
Timbers had success on the field, the players were active in the
community, and general manager Don Paul (a former Cleveland Browns
player) responded to critics who said the game needed to be
Americanized:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're filling the stands with Americans _ that's how we're
Americanizing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles, who had played for West Ham United, was among those
players. Charles has been successful as a collegiate coach and he
has chosen some excellent players on this Olympic team. But, as
Gardner notes, the players who will thrive in Charles's system will
likely be heavy on physicality and light on fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   If soccer is to progress in the US, creativity must be
encouraged. There are hundreds of thousands of excellent athletic
specimens involved in soccer in the US. Unless we want to watch
them running around in circles for the next decade, they are going
to have to be placed in situations where their imagination and
intuition can thrive. For Gardner, this means encouraging Hispanic
involvement. And those aware of the changing demographics of the
Western Hemisphere would likely agree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whither Baggio?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The potential savior of MLS is currently training by himself in
the small town of Caldogno in the Veneto region of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But the league is unlikely to pursue Roberto Baggio, even though
he is not with a team and likely has no real future in Italy's
Serie A.
</P>
<P>
   Baggio, 33, is far from finished. Several European and Japanese
teams are bidding for him, and Udinese seems likely to sign him for
$2 million-$2.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Baggio was the star of the game for the FIFA
World All-Stars in Marseille, France. Incredibly, though, no
top-level Italian teams can fit Baggio into their plans, partially
because they believe he has overvalued his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Inter coach Marcello Lippi benched Baggio for nearly the entire
1999-2000 season, though Baggio reemerged to lead the team to a
Coppa Italia title, and Lippi has said he has no plans for Baggio
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Sconcerti, an admitted Baggio backer, urged him to face
reality in an article titled, ``Give Me a Half Hour of Baggio,'' in
Guerin Sportivo magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baggio is a great player but not for more than a half-hour,''
Sconcerti wrote. ``That is not faint praise. A half-hour is a very
long time on the field. Only special players can fully capitalize
on that time. In the last 30 minutes of the game, when the other
players are tired, there is probably not another player in the
world who can make the difference like Baggio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
