<HEADLINE>
JOSTLE PUSHES HER RIVALS OUT OF THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All season, the 3-year-old colts received the lion's share of
attention. While every move made by Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet
was chronicled, the sophomore fillies were all but ignored.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the real head-to-head battle in the 3-year-old
ranks wasn't between Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Red
Bullet, who met only when Red Bullet prevailed in the Preakness,
but between females Secret Status and Jostle, who fought it out
three times, with underdog Jostle emerging as the leader of the
division.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Status, a daughter of A.P. Indy, established her
credentials by winning the Kentucky Oaks at Churchill Downs, while
Jostle, a daughter of Brocco, showed promise by taking the
Black-Eyed Susan at Pimlico. Secret Status struck the first blow in
the rivalry when she defeated Jostle by more than 2 lengths in the
Mother Goose at Belmont July 1. Regularly ridden by Pat Day, Secret
Status was 3-5 in the Mother Goose, run at 1 1/8 miles, while
Jostle, whose jockey is Mike Smith, was dismissed at 18-1.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting set up the Coaching Club American Oaks at Belmont
July 22. The Coaching Club is raced at a demanding 1 1/2 miles, and
Jostle, at 5-2, went all the way in front to defeat Secret Status,
who could do no better than third (behind Resort) at 2-5.
</P>
<P>
   The rubber match came Saturday in the $750,000 Alabama at
Saratoga, and while the bettors stuck with Secret Status, off at
4-5, Jostle proved much the best, winning by nearly 4 lengths at
7-2 ($9.50 to win). The time for the 1 1/4 miles was a slow 2:04
3/5 over a track that was officially labeled ``fast'' but had been
made heavy by frequent rain.
</P>
<P>
   After Jostle, who is trained by John Servis, went gate-to-wire
in the Coaching Club, Neil Howard, who trains Secret Status,
entered a rabbit, Valleydar, especially purchased to ensure an
honest pace in the Alabama. Valleydar did take the lead (before
fading to last) under Aaron Gryder, but she established such
dawdling fractions (:24 for a quarter, :48 3/5 for a half) over the
dull surface that the tactic was ineffective. Jostle stalked the
pace for a mile, put a head in front turning for home, and ran away
through the stretch. Secret Status, who was headstrong early, also
followed the pace, but had to fight hard to secure the place by a
head over 7-1 shot Spain and Jorge Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised that she won as easily as she did,''
said Servis. ``I thought Secret Status would be real tough at a
mile and one-quarter, but Jostle just keeps getting better. As far
as the 3-year-old filly championship goes, I don't know what else
you could ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The race unfolded like I picture in my mind,'' said Smith.
``Jostle proved that she would have no problems rating off the
pace, and I actually think she's a better horse when she does
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama was a bitter blow to the connections of Secret
Status, who felt her loss in the Coaching Club was attributable
mostly to the vagaries of the pace scenario in a 12-furlong race,
which often allows front-runners to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Secret Status ran OK,'' said Howard. ``She might
have been closer to the pace than I would have wanted, but I don't
think that was any fault on the jockey's part. I really don't know
what happened. I'll have to figure it out. But Jostle is a nice
filly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Secret Status's kick was not effective because of the way she
was in the first turn,'' said Day. ``She was a little bit on the
bridle, a little bit too eager.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has not run since the Preakness in May, and Red
Bullet, who is now out of the upcoming Travers at Saratoga because
of a lingering virus, has not run since the Dwyer in July. While
the boys are being held under wraps, the girls have been fighting
it out.
</P>
<P>
   Which contender is the leading 3-year-old colt: Fusaichi
Pegasus, Red Bullet, or Dixie Union, who won the Haskell at
Monmouth? We don't know because thay haven't run enough. What we do
know is that Jostle is the top filly. That's what happens when
racehorses actually race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
