<HEADLINE>
A CANDY MUSEUM? HOW SWEET! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things weren't going well for brothers James and Gilbert Ganong
in 1873. They'd opened a grocery store in St. Stephen, New
Brunswick, but it was failing. They needed something to attract
customers, and they needed it quickly. So they added what was then
a specialty item: candy.
</P>
<P>
   Good career move.
</P>
<P>
   The candy drew plenty of customers, so the brothers decided to
eliminate the middle man and make their own sweets. Before long,
they sold the grocery and were in the candy business exclusively.
By 1930, the company was employing 700 people and selling tons of
chocolate and other candies across Canada. Among the favorite items
were chicken bones, a concoction with cinnamon candy on the outside
and chocolate on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet story of Ganong candies is told at our Museum of the
Month, the year-old Chocolate Museum in St. Stephen. Although this
is not a factory tour, some of the early and present equipment is
on display, along with chocolate-making demonstrations (and
samples!), hands-on displays, games (can you fit the big
make-believe chocolates into the properly shaped slots?), and a
unique collection of candy boxes and wrappers, including some
picturing Longfellow's Evangeline, once the symbol of Ganong
candies.
</P>
<P>
   A guide will show you early valentine boxes _ Ganong was the
first in Canada to sell them _ and will probably tell you the story
of how in 1910 Arthur Ganong, who would later become company
president, and factory superintendent George Ensor needed a
convenient way to bring candy along on their fishing trips. So they
invented what became the world's first five-cent chocolate bar.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a video that includes a delightful interview with
retired chairman of the board Whidden Ganong, known as the Candy
Man. Your guide will later tell you that he ate a pound of
chocolate a day _ and died at age 93!
</P>
<P>
   (The Chocolate Museum is on Milltown Boulevard, St. Stephen, New
Brunswick, on the US border with Calais, Maine. Adult admission is
about $2.75 US. In addition to the museum, the refurbished complex
(it was the chocolate factory until 1990) also houses a large store
that sells crafts and, oh yes, Ganong candies. For more
information, call 506-466-7848.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which state begins with an ``A'' but doesn't end
with one? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Some travelers want to go to foreign places but are
dismayed when the places turn out actually to be foreign'' _
Margaret Atwood, poet and novelist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Two Seattle television stations have the call letters
KING and KONG. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: In Hartford, you cannot cross the street while
walking on your hands. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The naked truth: According to a survey by Choice Hotels, 17.8
percent of guests surveyed wear nothing to bed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Margaret Ahearn of Concord disagrees with the use of
``America'' to mean only the United States. In response to last
week's trivia question _ what is the largest island on America's
East Coast? _ she writes: ``Newfoundland with 43,548 square miles
is more than 25 times bigger than Long Island, and even though it
is in Canada and not the US, it is still in America and on the East
Coast. . . . Why do we assume that Canada is not in America?'' She
has a point, but even Canadians refer to US residents as Americans.
The usage may have come about because, of all the countries in the
Americas, the United States of America is the only one with
``America'' in its name. &QL; 
 &QL; 
History in a hotel: The Lenox Hotel, one of the first hotels in the
Back Bay, has been added to the roster of the National Trust
Historic Hotels of America. The hotel was built in 1900 in eight
months for $1.1 million. And because the Lenox was adjacent to a
rail yard for many years, wealthy guests such as opera singer
Enrico Caruso would pull their rail cars up to the hotel and walk
right in. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Arkansas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
