<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURES IN THE AIR AND AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for an adventurous outing? How about being part of a
schooner race, or pretending you're a World War II ace in a genuine
fighter plan of that era.
</P>
<P>
   For tall-ship fans, maritime history buffs, or those who just
like to sail, the place to be on Labor Day weekend is the 16th
annual Gloucester Schooner Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Gloucester, Mass. festival features open house exhibits
aboard tall ships, a traditional fish fry, a lighted ship parade,
fireworks, and, on Sept. 3, the great schooner race.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest will be the race between the American
Eagle, a 1930 Gloucester-built schooner and three-time winner;
Alabama, a 1926-built schooner returning to the race for the third
time, and a race newcomer, the Californian, a square topsail
schooner. Would-be schooner sailors can race aboard the Alabama or
the Californian. No experience is required, just a good attitude,
and $125 (which includes a light lunch while underway). Space is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   For information on joining the race or being aboard a spectator
craft, call Boston Nautical Heritage Group at 781-344-1749 or visit
www.Advenure(at)BostonNautical.com.
</P>
<P>
   Now if you'd rather take to the air, you can fly in a genuine
North American T-6. Warbird Adventures, which has been flying from
Kissimmee, Fla., for the last three years has brought one of its
planes to Rhode Island through mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The flights are not simulated, but the real thing. Certified
instructors will take you up and teach you to fly, let you take
control, and execute an aerobatic maneuver. The fighter-trainer T-6
is the same plane that former President George Bush learned to fly.
</P>
<P>
   A basic 15-minute flight is $154. On 30- and 60-minute flights,
maneuvers are undertaken. An hour flight, recorded with three video
cameras, is $544.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island flights are out of Lincoln. For information or to
book a flight, call 800-386-1593.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Labor Day outings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's time to plan a Labor Day getaway. Here are just a few
ideas:
</P>
<P>
   The sixth annual Mount Snow Brewers Festival is Sept. 2-3. More
than 75 microbrews from 20 breweries will set up shop at this
Vermont resort. There will be live music, and Mount Snow is open
for mountain biking, h9iking, scenic chairlift rides, and golf.
Festival admission is $12, which includes a souvenir beer pint
glass and beer ticket. A weekend pass is $20. For information, call
800-245-SNOW.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston you can catch the 18th annual Boston Antique &AMP; Classic
Boat Festival at Long Wharf from noon to 5 p.m. Sept. 2, and 11
a.m. to 3 p.m. Sept. 3. Classic sailboats, power boats, and
hand-powered craft, even an 1890s steam launch will be on view.
There will also be schooner sails, a crafts market, music, and, at
3:15 p.m. Sept. 3, a parade of boats. Admission is $4. For
information, call 617-422-1703.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hudson ramble
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A weekend walking festival highlighting some of the 3,000 miles
of trails within the Hudson River Valley National Heritage Area
will be held Sept. 23-24. More than 70 guided walks will be
featured in the area that extends from just north of New YOrk City
to the state capital of Albany on terrain ranging from paved rail
trails to rugged ridge hikes on the heights of the Palisades. Many
walks are family-friendly and several walks are accessible to
people with disabilities. A highlight will be the oening of a new
section of the Hyde Park Trail to Top Cottage, President Franklin
D. Roosevelt's private retreat on the family estate.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service has called the Hudson River Valley
Heritage Area ``the landscape that defined America.'' Within its
boundaries lie the vistas that inspired the rise of America's first
school of landscape painting, estates on which American landscape
architecture took shape, Revlutionary War sites, and pristine
wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Other walks planned include a 1777 Hike into History, a geology
walk for children, sunset walks, and an architectual walking tour.
Also planned are concerts, house tours, and food events. All walks
are free except for a few where site and parking fees cannot be
waived. For a brochure on the Hudson River Valley Ramble or lodging
information, call 800-453-6665 or e-mail
ramble(at)highlandflings.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bermuda getaway
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a new, casual, natural Bermuda to discover at Daniel's
Head, the island's newest resort with some 50 freestanding cottages
along _ and over _ the water. TNT Vacations has a three-night
package at $579 including air fare from Boston. For information on
this or other ``out of the blue'' Bermuda offers, call 888-468-6846
or see a travel agent. And if you are heading for the island, check
out the Fifth Annual Bermuda Jazz Festival Sept. 15-16. For details
or packages, call 800-BERMUDA.
</P>
