<HEADER>
A8968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-RAFTING-BOS &LR;      08-22 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RAFTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWING FUN ON THE DEERFIELD RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLEMONT, Mass. _ Long known for the beauty of its
surroundings _ the Mohawk Trail scenic highway is also the town's
main street _ in recent years Charlemont has found a new claim to
fame: it's now the white-water rafting capital of southern New
England.
</P>
<P>
   From mid-April to mid-October four rafting companies _ Zoar
Outdoor, Crab Apple Whitewater, North American Whitewater and
Wilderness Plus _ run rafting trips on a roughly 20-mile stretch of
the Deerfield River that offers white-water conditions ranging from
Class I (an occasional ripple) to Class IV (lots of challenging
rapids.)
</P>
<P>
   To minimize environmental impact, the number of rafters allowed
on the river is limited to 320 a day. Zoar Outdoor and Crab Apple,
both operating on the Deerfield since 1989, can each carry 130. The
other two outfitters are allowed 30 rafters each.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I reached Zoar Outdoor's base camp just west of the
center of town, it was clear that the company would be putting a
full complement of rafters on the river this mid-week day. Scores
of people _ including a number of noisy and excited school and
summer-camp groups _ were milling around outside the red clapboard
office building, all ready to hit the water.
</P>
<P>
   We were divided into two sections, the red and blue trips. The
reds, mostly males in their teens and 20s, would be doing the
Dryway, a roughly 4-mile section of river that has Class III and IV
white water for almost its entire length. Billed as an experience
that ``keeps your adrenaline flowing'' red-trip participants are
required to be ``comfortable in the water, in good physical
condition, and ready for a fairly strenuous adventure.'' They also
have to be at least 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
   My cautious selection was the blue trip, a 10-mile run through a
section of the Deerfield that is mostly Class I and II white water
but includes the challenging (but not terrifying) Zoar Gap rapids,
which have a Class III rating. Zoar Outdoor's most popular, the
Zoar Gap trip is suitable for children as young as 7 and appeals to
family, office, church, camp, and scout groups.
</P>
<P>
   After a safety lecture (`` . . . if you fall out of the raft,
keep your feet up and point them downstream.''), we picked up
helmets, life vests, and paddles and boarded buses for the put-in
point at Fife Brook Dam. Rafting is possible on the Deerfield
through the summer and into autumn because of daily controlled
releases of water from its dams by Pacific Electric Generating Co.
Trips are timed to coincide with releases so that rafts in effect
are riding a flood tide down river.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-trip flotilla of six-person rafts was waiting for us by
the bank below the dam. I shared a raft with the O'Neil family from
Foxborough, Michael, Sue, and their sons Mike, 14; Christopher, 12
and Patrick, 10. The kids were rafting for the first time but their
mother and father had white-water rafted in northern Maine, where
more than a score of rafting companies are based.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, in effect the skipper of the raft, was Sarah Harper.
A native of St. Louis, she grew up on the banks of the Mississippi,
discovered New England rivers while a student at Marlboro College
in Vermont, and has been a guide with Zoar Outdoor for four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   After pushing off, Harper gave us _ her crew _ some basic
rafting lessons, largely a matter of paddling in unison and
responding quickly to commands to shift the raft right or left. She
also taught us how to read the river, that is to spot shoals, small
whirlpools, or eddies, and also rocks hidden just below the surface
of the water.``Eddies are fun and you can surf them,'' she said,
and took us swirling though a good-sized one. Rafting lessons
learned, the crew had to make a group decision. ``Do you want to be
a war boat or a peace boat?'' Harper asked. War boats engage in
running water fights with other rafts, using large plastic bailing
buckets as cannon. Paddlers in peace boats can avoid combat _ and
stay relatively dry _ by holding up two fingers in the traditional
V-shaped peace sign.
</P>
<P>
   As did a majority of the rafts, ours opted for war and for most
of the trip there were frequent skirmishes between ours and other
rafts, with lots of well-aimed showers of water usually accompanied
by loud war cries. However, in the interest of community relations,
sections of the river with houses on the bank were declared peace
zones and paddled through quietly.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the trip took us through stretches of the
Deerfield that flow tranquilly between steep wooded banks:
classically beautiful Mohawk Trail country. In several of these
sections, it was possible to get out of the raft and swim. But,
there was also a good sampling of Class II white water involving
teamwork and fast paddling in order to snake around and in between
rocks and even slide over a few. Not adrenaline- producing exactly
but challenging _ and a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   The high point of the trip was Zoar Gap rapids. Although not
terribly long, the rapids were serious, i.e. Class III, white water
with a sudden sharp drop into a swirl of foam that threatened to
overturn the raft. No one fell out of our raft (although I think I
came close) but a couple of people did from other rafts _ all to be
quickly pulled back in.
</P>
<P>
   The Zoar Gap trip usually takes five or six hours and includes a
leisurely picnic lunch in a state park a mile or so below Zoar Gap
rapids. The picnic this day was less leisurely than usual: In the
middle of it a fast-moving thunderstorm forecast for the evening
finally rolled in.
</P>
<P>
   Since everyone was wet already the rain didn't matter much, but
paddling home made more sense than picnicking with soggy sandwiches
and we took to the rafts. By the time the blue flotilla pulled into
the landing across from the base camp, the sun was shining again.
</P>
<P>
   Like other commercial rafting trips, this one was followed by a
slide show. A photographer stationed on the river bank had taken a
photo _ copies of which were, of course, for sale _ of each raft as
it went through Zoar Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Our raft looked pretty good. The O'Neils were clearly having a
wonderful time and Sarah Harper was professionally serene. To my
surprise, instead of appearing terrified, I just looked very
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, maybe next time I'll try the Dryway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
