u a BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      08-22 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES DNA HAVE A COLOR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What color is DNA? Are free nucleotides a different color
than nucleotides in a strand of DNA? Are nucleosides different
colors than nucleotides? J.A.S., Chelmsford, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. DNA is a long molecule made of many pieces called nucleotides
strung together. Nucleotides are nucleosides with phosphates added
on. A nucleoside, in turn, is made of a sugar molecule stuck to one
of four different nitrogen-containing molecules corresponding to
the four basic letters _ C,G,T and A _ of the genetic code. OK.
With the terminology out of the way, on to your question.
</P>
<P>
   All these things are pretty much colorless (that is, they look
white). Incidentally, you can look at DNA yourself with nothing
more than simple kitchen equipment. If you're interested, have a
look at the ``Amateur Scientist'' column in the September 1998
issue of Scientific American.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, do keep in mind that you asked about color,
which I take to mean you're asking how something will look to a
human eye. Of course, there will be small variations in how
different colors of light (including infrared and ultraviolet,
which humans cannot see) are absorbed and reflected and these are
as unique to each chemical compound as a fingerprint. If your eyes
were a lot more sensitive, you might, indeed, detect a subtle
difference in the shades of white that would lead you to say they
were different colors and, in fact, chemists can use just such
differences to distinguish things that might look just the same to
you, like sugar, salt and strychnine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to the doctor at drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send
fax to: 617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The
Boston Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107. Please include your initials and hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-SUMMER-ASSOCIATE-ART-     08-22 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-ASSOCIATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 IT'S SUMMER AND AT LAW FIRMS, A KEY WORD IS `ASSOCIATE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Not every summer job gets you a tan.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, not every summer job pays $2,400 a week.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Amanda Vamvakias and her fellow summer
associates are earning at Ropes &AMP; Gray, the prestigious downtown
law firm.
</P>
<P>
   With annual salaries for first-year associates at major firms
shooting up (at Ropes &AMP; Gray, they're currently $125,000), the pay
for summer associates has kept pace. So in the minimum-wage,
room-and-board world of the classic summer job, summer associates
can seem to belong to another universe.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Vamvakias, 24, appreciates that. The native of
Falmouth, Maine, has had among her previous summer jobs stints as a
salesclerk at L.L. Bean and a waitress in a Portland diner
(``Probably the hardest work I've ever done,'' she says of the
latter).
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the upper reaches of the legal profession, the job title
``summer associate'' is as evocative of June, July, and August as
``lifeguard'' or ``camp counselor'' is for the population at large.
``Summer,'' after all, is part of the name.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, elite law firms throughout the United States pay top
dollar, recruiting second-year students from leading law schools to
work for them during the upcoming summer. The competition is
intense. Vamvakias, for example, had upwards of 15 on-campus
interviews and seven or eight callbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Earnest, upbeat, down-to-earth, she does not come across as your
classic high-powered-lawyer-in-the-making. With her deep brown eyes
and sweet, shy smile, Vamvakias could be Sandra Bullock's nicer kid
sister. She's a graduate of Duke (``I thought I'd be a walk-on for
the basketball team,'' she deadpans) and about to begin her third
year at Harvard Law School. She has already picked out her area of
specialization, trusts and estates, and feels she's settling in for
the long haul professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that I wanted to go to law school pretty early in my
college career,'' she says. ``There's something empowering about
knowing what you can and can't do, how you can help people, how you
can solve problems. That's the biggest thing for me: helping people
solve problems. I just like that work and the satisfaction you get
from helping people in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides high salaries, major law firms dangle before 2Ls (as
second-year law students are called) the chance to add a prominent
name to their resumes, the likely offer of a job after graduation,
and the opportunity to enjoy a relatively undemanding workload.
</P>
<P>
   There are social perks, too. Among the events Ropes &AMP; Gray has
sponsored for its summer associates this year have been a private
dinner at Figs; a walking tour of Beacon Hill; a performance of
``Shear Madness''; a dinner cruise while the Tall Ships were in
town; and a visit to Fenway Park. The Red Sox game was Vamvakias's
favorite event. ``I'm a big fan, anyway,'' she notes, ``and Brian
Daubach won it in the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do the most sought-after law firms in the country go to such
trouble? For the same reason a top college athletic program tries
to attract the best high-school players: In the courtroom, as on
the field, recruiting is how to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring is the life blood of the firm,'' says Bryan Chegwidden,
one of three partners in charge of summer-associate recruiting at
Ropes &AMP; Gray, ``and the summer program probably satisfies somewhere
up to 90 percent of our hiring needs.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are 60 summer associates. About 360 lawyers
work at Ropes &AMP; Gray, and 155 of them are partners.
</P>
<P>
   The after-hours festivities are as much a part of integrating
the summer associates into a firm as departmental meetings and
training seminars (both of which Ropes &AMP; Gray offers). Top firms
are very much aware that summer associates are coming to a city as
well as a firm. If it's an attractive, lively city, the firm hopes
that doesn't go unnoticed. As Vamvakias says with only the hint of
a smile, ``They don't want us chained to our desks for 13 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much a case of catering to the summer associates as
courting them. A summer associate at Ropes &AMP; Gray is someone who
can write his or her own ticket at almost any law firm in the
country. Since such a large percentage of the associates and
partners were themselves summer associates there, they need no
reminding of this.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all play and no work can seem pretty dull _ or at
least it can to the sort of person likely to flourish at law
school. So it's not all fun and games for 13 weeks. ``We don't do
make work,'' Chegwidden says. ``We try to make sure that (summer
associates) partake in active work and productive work.''
</P>
<P>
   Vamvakias, for example, has worked in two different departments,
real estate as well as trusts and estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In T&AMP;E there's a lot of drafting to see if this is what the
client had in mind with a trust or a will or power of attorney. On
the real-estate side, there's also research. Then there's a lot of
drafting of leases and agreements, that sort of thing. You're
writing a memo one minute, then the next you're doing research for
someone else. So you're constantly juggling _ and usually a lunch
in there somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It's real work, albeit a far cry from working a cash register in
Freeport or waiting tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had an amazing summer,'' Vamvakias says. ``It's been
great. I've loved the work and I've been really excited to find out
there's something in the profession I've chosen for myself that I
really see myself doing for years upon years. I've made so many
great friends and had such a great time. It's been a lot more fun
than I think people would suppose about working at a law firm for
the summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
