<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS URGED TO SEEK RAIL IMPROVEMENTS ON AMTRAK ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT HUDDLESTON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Local officials hope the Texas portion of Amtrak's
popular Texas Eagle route will become one of 11 higher-speed rail
corridors nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The designation could help improve ridership on the Eagle, which
operates between San Antonio and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas submitted a corridor designation application, it
could apply for federal funding for projects to enhance train
speeds for its existing Amtrak Texas Eagle service,'' San Antonio
City Councilman Tim Bannwolf, chairman of the Metropolitan Planning
Organization, said in an Aug. 11 letter to the state Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the department to propose that the Texas portion of the
Amtrak route be nominated for a federal designation to improve
crossings and rail lines so trains can go faster.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation, which has named eight
high-speed corridors nationally, is considering adding up to three
more. The only designated corridor in Texas is a portion of the
Gulf Coast Corridor, which runs from Houston to New Orleans, then
continues east.
</P>
<P>
   A program run by federal railroad and highway officials lets
states apply for funds to upgrade tracks and rail crossings to
improve passenger rail service on designated corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here hope such a designation could improve movement of
the Texas Eagle, as well as freight.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, has asked cities to support
designation of the Texas portion of the Eagle route. The route
starts in San Antonio, then runs north through San Marcos, Austin,
Fort Worth, Dallas and Texarkana before continuing onto Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the improvements would increase speed along the
rails from 40 mph to 70 or 80 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine high-speed rail in Texas has not been seriously
discussed since 1994, when a French-American partnership hoping to
build an $8.4 billion system to provide 200-mph service to Houston,
Dallas and San Antonio failed to find financing.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's Eagle carried 18,676 passengers last month, about 44
percent more than the 12,960 passengers served in July 1999. July
ridership throughout Amtrak's 22,000-mile system rose 4.5 percent,
to a 10-year high for monthly ridership of just over 2 million
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amtrak is having its best summer ever, in part due to the
ongoing success of the Texas Eagle, our best performing
long-distance train,'' Amtrak President George D. Warrington said
in a recent statement.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Johnson, an Amtrak spokesman in Chicago, said there is no
time line for adding the proposed Aztec Eagle, which would run from
San Antonio through Laredo to Monterrey, Mexico, as the first
Amtrak route south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is under a congressional mandate to become financially
self-sufficient by 2003. Federal operating assistance for the
company decreased from $484 million in 1999 to $362 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The rail company was in deep red ink when it considered
eliminating the Texas Eagle in 1996. A congressional appropriation
of $22.5 million and a $5.6 million loan from the state kept the
line running.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak recently has set records with $102.3 million in ticket
revenue in June and $107.2 million in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
