<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GENTLEMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHAN, BY A FRIEND: WORTHY HISTORY LACKING IN SALT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MOONEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GENTLEMAN FROM NEW YORK 
Daniel Patrick Moynihan: A biography 
By Godfrey Hodgson 
Houghton Mifflin 
452 pp., $38 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daniel Patrick Moynihan is one of this country's most intriguing
and redoubtable public figures, certainly deserving of a chronicle
of his life's work. As the senior senator from New York prepares to
retire, he is fortunate to have as his biographer Godfrey Hodgson,
a friend, admirer, and first-rate journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gentleman from New York'' is neither hagiography nor
apologia, however. Rather, Hodgson fashions what he calls ``a
biography of a mind.'' At times he sandpapers the rough patches of
Moynihan's life, but he succeeds in supporting his thesis, stated
at the outset, that ``no one in political life in the United
States, or anywhere else . . . has thought more penetratingly or
with deeper understanding into the problems of democracy'' than has
Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson is British. He has spent much time covering politics in
the United States. He knows this ground well, and he covers it
economically because there is much to describe in the life of a New
Yorker who served not only Democratic presidents John F. Kennedy
and Lyndon B. Johnson but also Republicans Richard M. Nixon and
Gerald R. Ford, who was ambassador to India and the United Nations,
who wrote numerous books and articles, who taught at Harvard, and
who served 24 years as senator.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Moynihan managed to inject himself into the
center of national and international debates with remarkable
prescience for the course of events.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson ascribes the ``meanderings of his political course'' to
the ``chance encounters and random walks'' of a paladin who married
his own rangy intellect, and to ``high ambition and low cunning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many see him as having sailed on a great circle from classic
liberalism, by way of neoconservatism, back to a contemporary
version of a traditional Democratic liberal position,'' the author
writes. ``Moynihan himself insists that it was not he who has
moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hodgson, for the most part, portrays his friend as an
anchored vessel buffeted by the storms of the 1960s, '70s, `80s,
and '90s. He was a friend, ally, adversary or enemy of most great
figures and thinkers of the times.
</P>
<P>
   Some will have a hard time swallowing Moynihan's profession of
political constancy. After all, this is a man who claims he was
``born a Democrat'' but worked for Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan was clearly anguished by the experience, however. In
retrospect, he rued his service, at least after the 1972 election,
by which time he knew, or at least suspected, the worst about the
administration. ``What do you call such a person?'' Moynihan says
of his failure to leave. ``A Moynihan, I suppose. A term suggestive
of moral and political failing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson mounts a stouter defense of some of his friend's other
noted stumblings. The most humbling was the searing public reaction
to the so-called Moynihan Report of 1965, which, using government
data, described for the first time the breakdown of
African-American families and urged ``national action'' to end the
poverty and unemployment at its root.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh response from liberals and black leaders devastated
Moynihan, who for years was branded by some as a racist, a charge
Hodgson painstakingly rejects.
</P>
<P>
   The biographer's account of Moynihan's ideas and bureaucratic
and ideological battles is dry history at times, but Hodgson
accomplishes his task. Welfare, tax, and Social Security reform?
They're all here. Moynihan's obsession with ethnicity, the poor,
the architecture of federal buildings? Well-documented, along with
his pioneering call for automobile safety, and his fights on behalf
of highway and mass transit systems and pork for his beloved New
York.
</P>
<P>
   What is lacking in ``The Gentleman from New York'' is the
personal and the colorful, perhaps a concession to the
Moynihan-Hodgson friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's pungent wit flashes but occasionally here, though
there is a illuminating anecdote about his gallant but futile 1975
fight at the United Nations to turn back a resolution that equated
Zionism with racism. After their defeat on the vote, Moynihan
embraced the Israeli representative, Chaim Herzog, and exclaimed:
``(Bleep) 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's the exception. Moynihan's mind, not his rich and
occasionally outrageous character, is the star of this work. Except
for the impact on Moynihan of the abandonment of his family by his
father, a drinker and gambler, when Moynihan was young, the book
offers little insight into his family life. Liz, his wife of 45
years, is generously portrayed, but plays less of a role in
Hodgson's book than she has as the guardrails of her husband's life
and career.
</P>
<P>
   Any reporter who has covered Moynihan at length has a story or
two about the senator's fondness of drink, but Hodgson, who has
hoisted a few with his chum, dispatches the issue in eight
paragraphs, deep into the book. Some stories are recounted, even a
suggestion that Moynihan's habits thwarted a run for president.
Hodgson, however, relies on his own experience. ``I have never seen
him, as the phrase goes, the worse for wear,'' he writes. Whatever
that means.
</P>
<P>
   But the few shortcomings of ``The Gentleman from New York'' are
more than offset by Hodgson's research, his insightful journalistic
compressions, and the enthusiasm with which he describes the rich
life, times, and ideas of his friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
