<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CELEBRITY SPLIT WITH ADDED PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was about three years ago when, over a breakfast of coffee
and Camels, Anne Heche professed her love for Ellen DeGeneres.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one else I'd rather be a wife to,'' said Heche, who
was attending a New York press junket to promote her latest film,
``Wag the Dog.'' This was about seven months after DeGeneres and
Heche had made their relationship public on ``Oprah,'' and
DeGeneres appeared on the cover of Time with the headline, ``Yep,
I'm Gay,'' as her television character on the ABC comedy ``Ellen''
also came out, becoming the first openly-gay lead in TV history.
</P>
<P>
   Considering whether her relationship with DeGeneres would
undermine her burgeoning career, Heche said then, ``I think the
focus will start shifting again (to her acting). And if it doesn't,
there's nothing that's more of an honor or pleasure than to be
Ellen's wife. It's the greatest thing in the world to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the news that the much-discussed relationship has
ended.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, DeGeneres, 42, and Heche, 31, said,
``Unfortunately, we have decided to end our relationship. It is an
amicable parting, and we greatly value the 3 1/2 years we have
spent together.'' Both are said to be devastated by the break.
</P>
<P>
   In a certain sense, this is just another Hollywood relationship
come undone. Everyone knows that show-biz couples can go up in
flames faster than you can say ``Winona Ryder.'' But for those of
us in the lesbian and gay community, the news is especially sad.
For once they proclaimed their love, once they said their
relationship deserved to prosper in the light and not wither in the
shadows, DeGeneres and Heche became icons.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to singer Melissa Etheridge and her
longtime partner, filmmaker Julie Cypher, DeGeneres and Heche were
Hollywood's highest-profile same-sex couple. They quickly earned
the first names-only status of a Brad and Jennifer _ everyone knew
about Ellen and Anne, whether they wanted to or not. It was rare to
see one without the other, and they seemed to be one of the more
stable couples around.
</P>
<P>
   As if Hollywood coupledom isn't challenging enough _ heck, any
relationship anywhere can be tough _ DeGeneres and Heche shouldered
the added weight of becoming symbols of lesbian and gay America.
Yet they seemed to relish their roles. For every tony event where
they strolled the red carpet before the cameras and fans, they also
spoke against injustice and bigotry. They decried the senseless
murders of Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr., both victims of
intolerance and ignorance in 1998. They talked about raising a
family, and championed the case for lesbian and gay marriage, even
saying they intended to get hitched legally once the law allowed
it.
</P>
<P>
   Back when their love was new, Heche shrugged off the notion that
her relationship with DeGeneres might derail her career _ the
inference being that no one would accept a lesbian actress playing
a romantic lead opposite a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so strange to me that someone would say I could have my
career taken away from me because I'm in love,'' said Heche, who
starred in ``Volcano,'' ``Walking and Talking,'' and ``Donnie
Brasco.'' ``When did careers and stardom become more important than
being in love with someone? Excuse me, but I get to go home, and
dance around my house holding hands every night, sitting in front
of a fire, and having a good meal. That's what I get, and I think
I'd rather have that than another job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people think we represent a love they've always wanted to
see represented,'' Heche marveled. ``Whoa!''
</P>
<P>
   This was a landscape without gravity since no one had ever done
what Heche was doing. When ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' her film
with Harrison Ford, failed in 1998, some blamed Heche's sexuality,
although they seemed to ignore one aspect of the absurdity of Heche
and Ford as a couple was because he is old enough to be her father.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, Heche went from hot actress to ``the companion
of,'' better known for her personal life than her professional
abilities, and her career did seem to falter. She worked in small
films, and directed DeGeneres and Sharon Stone in a segment of ``If
These Walls Could Talk 2'' on HBO, as well as a documentary on
DeGeneres's return to stand-up comedy, but Heche's star had dimmed.
And once ``Ellen'' ended in 1998, DeGeneres's career stalled as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Whether their sidetracked careers had any bearing on their
decision to part, no one knows. I'm sure the details will spill out
in the weeks and days to come. But this I do know: In a nation
where lesbian and gay lives are still vilified, where famous folks
have been known to hold press conferences, appear on TV
newsmagazines, and buy full-page ads to proclaim their
heterosexuality, DeGeneres and Heche were our golden couple. It is
almost impossible to calculate how much these two women
accomplished simply by being themselves _ such a rarity in a town
built on pretense, and in a society which preciously guards its
lies.
</P>
<P>
   While we all know celebrities aren't better than the rest of us,
they do have a stage we don't enjoy. We think we know them, so
whether consciously or not, we're influenced by them, and I like to
think DeGeneres and Heche turned a few heads in a positive way.
Without question they were as important to furthering the cause of
gay and lesbian rights and visibility as Michael J. Fox has been in
bringing attention to Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Their love may have ended, but with their relationship, their
(itals)marriage,(unitals) DeGeneres and Heche blazed an indelible
trail, which said to the world what most gay and lesbian folks have
always recognized _ not only that our lives and relationships can
be beautiful, successful, and happy, but that they exist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
