<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin on Tuesday
flew to the headquarters of Russia's Northern Fleet to pay his last
respects to the 118 officers and sailors who perished aboard the
nuclear-powered submarine Kursk after it suffered a catastrophic
internal explosion in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-RACISM-TRIAL (Halle) _ Three German skinheads went on
trial Tuesday for the racist killing of a Mozambican man in the
eastern town of Dessau amid mounting concern about far-right
violence, particularly in the former East Germany. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-JORDAN (Jerusalem) _ King Abdullah of Jordan visits
Israel to push the peace process. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-HAVEL-INTERVIEW (Prague, Czech Republic) _ The Czech
president, Vaclav Havel, discusses globalization, anti-Semitism and
other issues in an interview. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-POLITICS (Lummi Reservation, Wash.) _ In this far corner
of Indian country, people see two Slade Gortons, the senator who
helped to secure funds for tribal projects and the man who has
spent much of his public life battling the Lummis and other tribes
on everything from fishing rights to the power of governing their
own affairs. Gorton has feuded with American Indians but has never
suffered a strong political backlash from the tribes. But this
year, flush with money from casino gambling operations, Indians
across the country say they are going to make him pay. By Timothy
Egan.
</P>
<P>
