<P>
   DNA-AFRICAN-ANCESTRY (Boston) _ Black Americans' hunger to trace
their African ancestry is combining with powerful new DNA
technology, and the foundations are being laid for a system that
will use genetic analysis to recover the past. This fall, some 300
African-American children here are to be sent home with swabs meant
to gather DNA samples from the cheeks or gums of their family
members, part of a local molecular biologists nascent project that
he means to extend to North Carolina and other spots with
long-stable African-American populations. Last spring, a Howard
University geneticist announced he would soon offer DNA analysis to
African-Americans. And the African Burial Ground Project in
Manhattan has been assembling a data-base of DNA from long-buried
African-Americans and living Africans. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Denver) _ An update on wildfires in the West;
Montana's governor is debating whether to bar the public from state
grasslands and forests in another 16 counties. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILD-DEPORT (New York) _ A 16-year-old boy originally from
Trinidad is to appear in federal court Tuesday for a deportation
hearing. The boy came to the United States illegally with his
parents at age 3; at some point his father left the mother and
married an American, thus naturalizing father and son. The boy was
part of a chess team that went to Russia for a tournament two years
ago, and the trip put him back on the Immigrations and
Naturalization Service radar screen. He then got a letter telling
him to appear in federal court on Aug. 22, and that he would be
deported. By John Sullivan.
</P>
