<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-DIAMONDS-BOS &LR;      08-22 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DIAMONDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONFLICT-FREE' DIAMONDS COULD BE A BOON TO CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ So you're ready to pop the question, but don't want
to present your sweetie with a diamond quarried from the killing
zones of Sierra Leone, Angola, or other blood-drenched corners of
Africa?
</P>
<P>
   Suitors trying to follow their consciences as much as their
hearts are having a tough time these days when it comes to
diamonds. In Africa, the precious stones have become a guerrilla's
best friend, with traffic in diamonds financing some of the
cruelest conflicts on that continent.
</P>
<P>
   An international controversy is building over the huge, illicit
trade, and _ as diamonds become increasingly linked in the public
mind to the hideous atrocities of rampaging rebels _ the sparkling
symbols of love might become as politically unacceptable as
slave-labor sneakers or whale soup.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing an opportunity as well as a potential problem, the
rapidly growing diamond mines of Canada's Northwest Territories
have responded with a first-of-a-kind program to guarantee to
consumers that a diamond has been mined, cut, and polished in the
only diamond-producing region of North America, and is thus
untainted by conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Microscopic polar bears and other northern symbols laser-etched
into the undersides of diamonds from the sparsely inhabited
territory, along with government certificates and a ``gem print''
as distinctive as a fingerprint, may soon mark that a Canadian
Arctic gem is not just pure crystalline carbon, but ethically pure
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to assure people that Northwest Territories diamonds
are genuine conflict-free diamonds. . . that no one got his arm
chopped off for these gems,'' said Resources Minister Joseph
Handley in an interview from Yellowknife, the territorial capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other region in the world has put such a program in
place,'' he said. ``But with (human) rights groups targeting
diamonds, this is the way all legitimate diamond producers will be
headed, putting out stones whose pedigree cannot be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   A diamond is a diamond, its glory dependent on its size and the
skill with which it is cut and polished, not its place of origin.
Until recently, no one cared where a gem came from.
</P>
<P>
   But an international campaign against conflict gems, supported
by such high-profile human rights groups as Amnesty International,
is quickly building steam. The trade in illicit gems is fueling
bloody conflicts in at least six African nations.
</P>
<P>
   Such murderous insurgency movements as Sierra Leone's
Revolutionary United Front or Angola's Unita, or the United Nationa
Front for Total Independence of Angola, pay for hundreds of
millions of dollars worth of arms with diamonds mined in regions
under their control.
</P>
<P>
   Although highly trained geologists and diamond specialists can
usually tell the origin of rough diamonds, it is impossible for
consumers to know whether a cut and polished gem hails from Angola,
Australia, or anyplace else. Diamond buyers can count only on the
word of their jeweler, and as often as not, the jeweler has no clue
as to the true origin of a gemstone.
</P>
<P>
   DeBeers Consolidated Mines Ltd., which supplies more than 60
percent of the world's diamonds, is also considering ways of
certifying ``conflict free'' stones, but it is reluctant to brand
diamonds by place of origin because it mixes gems from Botswana,
South Africa, Russia, Australia, and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But the Northwest Territories, the new kid on the diamond block,
believes the world diamond industry needs to abandon the secrecy
with which it has traditionally done business and start guarding
its integrty with the same zeal it applies to protecting the value
of its gems. Annual world trade in rough diamonds is worth more
than $7 billion, while sales of finished diamonds total about $75
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new world out there, and we've seen entire industries _
Canada's 400-year-old fur industry is an example _ destroyed by
political activists,'' Handley said. ``Of course, most diamonds are
not blood diamonds. But the day is fast coming when the industry
will have to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials and diamond finishers in the territory also
see government certification of diamonds cut and polished in Canada
as a smart marketing move _ a way of promoting Northwest
Territories diamonds in the same way that Vermont certifies ``pure
Vermont'' maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to raise the profile of our Canadian Arctic diamonds.
We need to create a strong, special identity for Northwest
Territories stones,'' said Martin Irving, director of diamond
projects for the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The growing world controversy over so-called ``conflict gems''
is putting the spur to efforts of peaceable Canada to distinguish
its diamonds from those funneled into world markets by guerrilla
movements. The trade in so-called ``conflict gems'' is banned by
international law but very difficult to stamp out. By some
estimates, 10 percent of the 860 million diamonds cut and polished
every year are smuggled from African trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, we need a way to show consumers our diamonds are not
connected to any fighting and killing,'' said Frans Van Looy, vice
president of Alberta-based Deton'cho Diamonds, one of a handful of
Canadian companies that cut and polish gems from the Northwest
Territories.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Canada's diamond production was zero. Then in
1998 the giant Ekati diamond mine started operation, turning the
frigid Northwest Territories into a major diamond-producing region.
Ekati's annual yield is now more than 3.5 million carats of ``gem
quality'' (as opposed to industrial) diamonds. By 2004, when two
more mines are expected to open, the territory is expected to
produce 15 percent of the world's diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Ekati is already trying to project an image as a source of
uncontroversial gems. ``Dependable. Trustworthy. Pristine.
Natural,'' states an advertisement aimed at wholesalers. ``Ekati
Diamonds. A warm front just came in from Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the production flows as raw stones to Antwerp, Belgium,
center of the international diamond trade, but 10 percent of the
Canadian diamonds will be cut and polished by several small
companies in Yellowknife under an agreement forged between the
mine's corporate owners, the territory's aboriginal groups, and the
territorial government.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond producers in Canada say the mounting controversy makes
it imperative that gems from the Northwest Territories be certified
as to their origin. Tiny markings, visible only under a powerful
magnifying glass, are only part of the process; the government will
also provide a certificate and ``gemprint'' identification for each
gem under a program expected to be underway later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be able to show concerned buyers that our gems are
pure,'' said Van Looy. ``We hear all about diamonds from trouble
and turmoil. We hope to build an image of Canadian diamonds of
peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
