<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-LIVING-WAGE-HNS &LR;      08-22 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-WAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO CLOSER TO IMPOSING `LIVING WAGE' LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ILENE LELCHUK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After two years of intense lobbying and delicate
negotiating, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors moved closer to
enacting a broad living wage law that would provide higher pay,
paid time off and _ eventually _ health benefits for more than
21,500 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time for me in about 20 years that I'll be
getting paid vacation and sick leave,'' home health care worker
Bruce Allison said Monday night after the supervisors' unanimous
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which must go before the board for a final,
largely procedural vote next week, requires city contractors,
nonprofit agencies and businesses at the San Francisco
International Airport, to pay workers at least $9 per hour when the
law takes effect _ possibly at the end of September. Wages will
jump to $10 per hour next year and be followed by 2.5 percent
raises for three more years.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives workers 12 paid days off for vacations and
holidays and allows them up to 10 unpaid days forfamily
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is a scaled-down version of the $11-per-hour rate
proposed by Supervisor Tom Ammiano two years ago and is the result
of a compromise negotiated by Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet thing,'' Ammiano said before the vote.
``Everyone knows it's not a living wage. It's still a minimum
wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Hermanson, the co-chairman of the Living Wage Coalition,
said the authors were careful not to call the plan a ``living
wage'' ordinance but a ``minimum compensation'' ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage in California is $5.75 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, San Francisco officials will draft a final
piece of the legislation that requires city contractors and
leaseholders to either give workers private health insurance, join
a city-run health insurance pool or pay the city an equivalent of
$1.25 per hour per employee, which will help fund the city's public
health system.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 20,000 workers who would benefit from the
higher wages, an estimated 10,000 to 14,000 do not have health
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of political wrangling, Monday's victory was
anti-climactic. Only a couple of workers attended the board's
meeting and even the supervisors had little to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's been a difficult process and caught up in
politics and prolonged,'' said Ken Jacobs of the Living Wage
Coalition. ``We asked the mayor at the beginning of the year to
intervene and hammer out an agreement, but that was going slow.
Then we went out and collected signatures to put a measure ($11 per
hour) on the ballot, and in 2 1/2 weeks we collected 20,000
signatures. . . . Polling showed us that support for a living wage
was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty other cities and counties have living wages laws that
generally apply to government employers and contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Under San Francisco's legislation, the city will help nonprofit
agencies cover the cost of increased wages through at least the
first year. Those agencies, provide services for the homeless and
mental health patients, will be exempt from the second-year raise
if the city cannot afford to help them without cutting other
services.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of the plan to the city is highly uncertain,
although some estimates put it at $10 million per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
