<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TIMBER _ NEWHILL, N.C. _ This southern corner of Wake County,
where suburban sprawl from nearby Raleigh and a local wood chip
mill are eliminating woodlands, illustrates the conclusion of a
controversial new study by timber management researchers. Rather
than solely blaming chip and pulp mills for depleting the South's
forests, the report from Duke and North Carolina State universities
said urban growth is also a significant cause of the shrinking
forests. On the eve of an industry conference Wednesday in Raleigh,
this finding heightens the sharp debate between the timber industry
and, on the other side, environmentalists and federal officials
concerned about the rapid acceleration of logging in the South. The
region is less regulated than the Pacific Northwest and, for the
first time, is harvesting soft woods such as pines faster than they
are being replaced. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GA-EXECUTE _ Board of Pardons and Paroles hears the case of
Alexander Williams, who is scheduled for execution Thursday. No
decision is expected today. Also, an appeal may be filed with the
Georgia Supreme Court. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ John and Patsy Ramsey will meet with Boulder, Colo.,
police on Monday in Atlanta. The couple is looking to be finally
cleared in the murder of their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
