<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-AIRPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENVIRONMENTALISTS FEAR DEAL WOULD LEAD TO AIRPORT EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY and JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Powerful San Francisco politicians are
crafting legislation here and in Washington that would pay up to
$300 million to the Cargill Inc. to buy thousands of acres of
marshland in the San Francisco Bay, and possibly speed expansion of
San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill is scaling back its salt operations to concentrate on
finer-grained salt used in drugs instead of food. As a result,
19,000 acres of valuable land are for sale, and the property could
become the one of largest environmental purchases in California
history.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are excited that the government is finally
moving to purchase and restore the huge salt ponds. But they do not
want the deal used as an excuse to rush approval of the airport
expansion, which could see more than 1,000 acres of the Bay filled
for new runways.
</P>
<P>
   For months, public officials have been floating the idea of a
possible purchase and restoration of salt ponds as mitigation for
any environmental damage the airport expansion might create.
</P>
<P>
   But state lawmakers deny the possible Cargill purchase is linked
to smoothing the way for the expansion. Nevertheless, a cadre of
San Francisco politicians has become keenly interested in the
government's purchase of the Cargill acreage near Newark and San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislature is considering spending $150 million to
buy the salt ponds, home to more than 70 species of waterfowl and a
staging area for migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., is pursuing
another $150 million for Cargill _ but only if the state
legislature and Gov. Gray Davis approve California's half by the
end of next week, the final day of the 1999-2000 legislative
session.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's airport representative, Stuart Sunshine, said the
city supported the legislation not because it might speed up the
airport expansion, but because ``it's an extraordinary opportunity
for the state of California to increase wetland habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings back to the Bay what was lost,'' Sunshine said.
``This is an opportunity to bring back up to 50 percent of the
habitat that supports wildlife in the Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the Cargill ponds for birds and wildlife and expanding
the San Francisco airport have been running on separate tracks for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, public officials have linked buying and
reinvigorating the Cargill property as a way to balance the
environmental damage created by enlarging the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The bill before the legislature, sponsored by Assemblywoman
Carole Migden, D-San Francisco, would clear the way for buying the
Cargill land but does not provide money to restore the area back to
its natural habitat for shorebirds. The bill, however, requires
restoration money to come from somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say they know where the money will come from:
The airport would provide more than $200 million it has available
for environmental restoration, offering the money in exchange for
damage done by dumping soil in the Bay for the new runways.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be viewed as one more step for approval to runway
expansion,'' said Bill Allayaud, state legislative director of the
Sierra Club. ``The worst that could happen is if the bill gets
amended to say the purchase would be mitigation for impacts from
SFO runway expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, in fact, is paving the way for the airport to
restore the Cargill land _ if environmental officials decide that
is the best solution and if environmental laws are followed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Assembly approved a bill that gives legal clearance,
if needed, for the airport to pay for restoring the Cargill land to
make up for environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
   The runway expansion would reduce the existing flight delays,
accommodate larger aircraft and the projected increase in passenger
and cargo traffic, and reduce noise, Sunshine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
