<HEADER>
A9017 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-FEAST-PESTO-SFCHRON &LR;      08-22 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAST-PESTO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 The Roving Feast: The Truth About Pesto   By Marlena Spieler  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 LONDON _  I found my sunglasses today just in time. Summer has
almost ended, and today is perhaps the second day my eyes have
needed shading. London has alternated between gray and rainy this
summer, although occasionally it's gotten really hot and muggy and
overcast before the rain begins again. It's disorienting to think
about which month, let alone which season, we are in.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those tortoise-shell, rather stylish sunglasses I bought in San
Francisco last spring haven't gotten the use I anticipated when I
rationalized the price of the purchase. True, I did manage to pull
them out for a sultry couple of days in Portofino but they've been
lying around since then.
</P>
<P>
   We were in Liguria taping material about pesto for the British
Broadcasting Co. when we got an invitation we couldn't refuse:
Would we like to stay a night at the Hotel Splendido?
</P>
<P>
   The Splendido is a hotel favored by the very famous and very
rich, although its history includes pillaging by pirates and
grazing by sheep. I love sheep. There are no sheep now, just lots
of designer labels. My sunglasses were right at home, though the
rest of me felt a bit shabby.
</P>
<P>
   Portofino is one of the most beautiful spots in the world,
recognizable by anyone who has ever glanced through a lifestyle
magazine that involves well-heeled travel, Italy or ``The Good
Life.'' The hotel is perched on a hill overlooking Portofino and
its bay. Little and not-so-little boats bob in the sea, and you can
look right down to its depths _ clear, emerald and azure.
</P>
<P>
   Splendido's swimming pool sits at the edge of the cliff, the
view of the sea at its horizon. It is like swimming in the sky. At
night, after cocktails on the terrace _ the Splendido's cocktail is
a version of the Bellini but with strawberries instead of peaches _
dinner outside afterward _ grilled vegetables, marinated fish,
pasta with pesto and green beans _ a little  &LR; de rigueur &LR;  checking
out of the nightlife, we go swimming again.
</P>
<P>
   One of our party _ I'm not naming names here _ went skinny
dipping. OK, it was my very dignified producer. I might have joined
in, but for that cellulite. I don't know . . . Portofino just does
something to a person.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Portofino is very friendly. I met a man responsible
for most of the pesto in Great Britain _ his basil fields lie east
of Portofino and he exports to almost every supermarket and deli in
Britain. In Italy, he handles most of the country's pickles and
pickled vegetables. He promises to send me some. He is charming and
warm. And I know from talking to him that we must have something in
common. ``Were you in Berkeley in the '70s?'' he asks. ``I went to
the university there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pesto is everywhere these days, so much so that it is hard to
remember when it wasn't. We're so used to cilantro pesto and wild
thyme pesto and sundried tomato pesto and green chile pesto that
it's easy to forget its origins: Liguria, and basil.
</P>
<P>
   And it's easy to forget just how wonderful traditional freshly
made pasta al pesto can be. If you haven't had the real thing
lately or _  &LR; mamma mia! &LR;  _ ever, it is a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Pasta al Pesto the Ligurian Way &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My first pesto was prepared under the guidance of a basil grower
at the Alemany Farmers' Market years ago. I've been making _ and
eating _ it ever since. Here are my secrets, refined in the basil
fields of Liguria, the restaurant kitchens of Portofino and Santa
Margarita, and the kitchen of olive grower Carlo Isnardi, who
prepares lunch for his staff every day, in between running an
empire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Good basil. &LR;  Use basil with lots of flavor, preferably
Ligurian basil with its true basil flavor rather than the taste of
anise or mint. Some Genoans add a tablespoon or two of cooked
spinach, squeezed of its excess moisture. This gives color, but I
prefer a basil-only flavor for this speciality.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Don't toast the pine nuts. &LR;  The Italians don't and their
pesto can't be faulted in my opinion. If you like the flavor of
toasted pine nuts (I do!) sprinkle them over the dish afterward. In
some areas of Liguria, walnuts replace the pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Add a tablespoon or two of the pasta-cooking water. &LR;  This is
the magic ingredient for almost all pasta dishes. It connects the
pasta to the sauce and keeps everything succulent and moist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The right pasta. &LR;  Traditional shapes for pesto include
trofie, or twists that taper out to the ends with a chubby part in
the middle. They can be either small or very small, and are chewy
and delicious and perfect for pesto. Trenette, tagliatelle and
other flat fettuccinelike noodles are traditional and delicious.
</P>
<P>
   I sometimes use wonton wrappers as they are silky and delicate;
just don't cook them more than a minute or two. Gnocchi also are
terrific with pesto.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Traditional cooking. &LR;  Whichever pasta you choose, prepare it
in the traditional way with a little chopped potato and a handful
of green beans in the cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Balance the basil with a little tuft of parsley. &LR;  Also, add a
bit of pecorino cheese to the Parmesan; it's sharper and sheepier
than Parmesan.  &LR; Pecora &LR;  means sheep; the cheese is made from ewe's
milk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Don't listen to the Ligurians when it comes to garlic. &LR;  Some
Ligurians don't add garlic to their pesto. I've gone easy with the
garlic in today's recipe _ add more to suit yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Use Ligurian olive oil if you can. &LR;  It is amazing how using
an oil from a different region _ even a delicious oil that you love
for other purposes _ just takes over your pesto. A Ligurian oil
makes your pesto taste of the region in which it was born.
</P>
<P>
   The exception to this is nicoise oil _ it is light and flowery
and fragrant and quite good in pesto, as it is used in its cousin
basil sauce, the pistou of Nice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Don't worry about using a mortar and pestle. &LR;  While the pesto
will come out with a greater character and texture made by hand, it
is hard work, takes a lot longer, cannot really be made for a crowd
and will put off only the most dedicated of pestle pounders. Almost
everyone in Liguria uses a food processor these days, even the most
traditional of olive oil producers, basil growers, pesto makers and
chefs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ One last note. &LR;  Some people add a knob of butter or a bit of
crumbled Gorgonzola or goat cheese at the end. Delicious, but not
when I'm in a pesto-purity state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PASTA WITH PESTO
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 medium potato, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   Big pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces pasta: trofie, trenette, tagliatelle, gnocchi or other
pasta
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 pound very thin green beans such as French haricots
verts, or thinly sliced Blue Lake or Kentucky Wonder beans
</P>
<P>
   Ligurian Pesto (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Parmesan cheese for grating, as desired
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large pot with water then add the potato and a generous
pinch of salt. Bring to a boil over high heat. The small potato
pieces should be nearly done. If they aren't, cook until they are.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pasta to the cooking water and boil until it is about
two thirds of the way to al dente. Add the green beans and cook
until the pasta is al dente and the beans are bright green and
crisp-tender. The cooking time depends on how big your pasta is, as
well as the size of the green beans.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and beans, reserving about 1/2 cup of the
cooking liquid. Stir this liquid into the pesto, then toss it all
together with the pasta and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Serve right away in soup bowls with cheese for grating at the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 685 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 76 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 34 g fat (7 g saturated), 14 mg cholesterol, 268 mg
sodium, 1 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LIGURIAN PESTO
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 cups (packed) basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   15 parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil, preferably Ligurian
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated pecorino cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic and pine nuts in a food processor and whirr
until the nuts are well broken up. Add half of the basil and
process until pureed. Add the remaining basil, the parsley and oil.
Process until the mixture turns into a thickish green sauce. If it
is too thin, add more basil or parsley; if too thick, add more oil.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the Parmesan and pecorino, then season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Store in the refrigerator covered with a layer of olive oil for
up to 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yields enough for 4 servings of pasta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPAGHETTINI WITH BACON, SPINACH &AMP; CHERRY TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   If you're not in the mood for pesto, here's a great alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces bacon (preferably unsmoked) or pancetta, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil + olive oil to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions (white and most of the green part), thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   16 cherry tomatoes, quartered or halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken stock, or vegetable or porcini stock (water
mixed with a not-too-salty bouillon cube is OK, too)
</P>
<P>
   Several handfuls of fresh spinach leaves, coarsely torn
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghettini
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, a generous amount
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Handful of fresh basil leaves, torn
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Brown the bacon in a heavy skillet over medium-low heat, cooking
it slowly to render the fat and crisp it up a bit. Using a slotted
spoon, transfer the bacon to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Discard the bacon fat in the pan. Wipe out the pan if the bits
clinging to the bottom are overly browned; if they look crisp and
yummy, leave them in. Add the olive oil to the pan, then half the
garlic and half the green onions. Cook over high heat for a few
moments, then toss in the cherry tomatoes and cook, letting them
sizzle and saute for a few minutes. Pour in the wine and boil until
it reduces to about 2 tablespoons. Add the stock and cook a few
minutes longer, or until this cooks down to a lovely intensely
flavored sauce. Add the spinach, cover, and cook for 1 minute, then
toss together, cover again, and remove from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the spaghettini in a large pot of boiling salted water
until it is al dente, then drain, reserving the cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the drained pasta into the sauce, along with the remaining
garlic and green onions. Season with salt and pepper. Add a few
tablespoons of the hot cooking water and toss again. Top with the
cheese, basil and the reserved bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon into bowls and serve with extra olive oil for each person
to pour on as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 670 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 92 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 20 g fat (6 g saturated), 22 mg cholesterol, 471 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
