 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Colorado's Come a Long Way From Rocky Mountain 
 Kool Aid  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; In the 1970s, Colorado was an unusual outpost for
a wine writer. But there I was. Colorado had plenty of wine
drinkers then, even though ``Rocky Mountain Kool-Aid'' (Coors beer)
had a lock on the state beverage business. Wine lovers had a choice
of wine stores in Denver where prices for California wines were
better than in California.
<P>
   But there was only one winery in Colorado then, owned by an
overly confident orthodontist who was convinced that Coloradans
were ready for Colorado wine.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, in those days Ivancie Cellars wines were made from
California-grown grapes, shipped _ at great expense _ across two
mountain ranges in refrigerated trucks. Coloradans were curious
about Gerald Ivancie's wines, but not curious enough to pay more
than they would for California wines.
</P>
<P>
   Wine buffs also were interested in Colorado wines, so I wrote a
magazine story about Ivancie, which launched me from a part-time
general interest free-lance writer to a full-time career in wine
writing for magazines and the Rocky Mountain News.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Colorado's budding wine industry lurched forward
slowly, but now things are changing rapidly. Today, according to
the Colorado Wine Industry Development Board, the state boasts 27
active wineries, with two new ones soon to open. There also are
seven tasting rooms, many offering a range of Colorado wines.
</P>
<P>
   While you might think that Colorado is too cold to grow premium
wine grapes, popular varieties like Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon
and Merlot are grown. Most of the wine-grape acreage is in Grand
Valley and Delta-Montrose, two of the state's four wine regions.
Grand Valley is Colorado's only AVA (American Viticultural Area).
</P>
<P>
   In terms of wineries, the largest Colorado wine region is Grand
Valley, between Grand Junction and Glenwood Springs. The Front
Range, running along the eastern edge of the Rockies from Loveland
to Denver, is next, followed by Delta and Montrose counties in the
triangular region between Grand Junction, Aspen and Montrose.
</P>
<P>
   There also are wineries in the Central Rockies region, spread
out between Steamboat Springs and Aspen, and in the Southern
Rockies, mainly around Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest region is Four Corners, with one winery in Cortez
and one tasting room in Durango.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Colorado's wineries are small family-owned operations,
producing a range of grape wines and fruit wines such as cherry,
plum and peach. Colorado also has the Rocky Mountain Meadery,
offering a range of Meads, or honey wines.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado is a cool-climate growing area, so the grape wines are
closer in style to those of Washington than California. Chardonnays
are leaner, with refreshing crisp acidity, while the Merlots are
more robust and fruit-forward, similar in style to Washington
Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only Plum Creek Cellars and Canyon Wind Cellars ship to
the California market. For more information about Colorado wines
and a free Colorado Wine Country Tours brochure, call (720)
304-3406.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cognac Sales Up &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many wine drinkers shy away from the ``hard stuff,'' especially
grain spirits, but on occasion they enjoy grape spirits like
Cognac. Generally considered the most sophisticated grape spirit,
Cognac is popular with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Cognac Bureau in New York reports that for the sixth
consecutive year, the United States is the No. 1 market for Cognac
worldwide. A peak of 35.8 million bottles in 1999 catapulted the
United States ahead of more traditional export markets like France
and the United Kingdom. The United States is even ahead of Japan, a
blossoming market for Cognac in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dewar's New Whisky &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here's an idea for early holiday shoppers with a Scotch drinker
on their list. Dewar's, the top-selling brand of Scotch in the
United States, will release Dewar's 12 Year Old, its first new
blended whisky in 40 years with an age statement. The new Dewar's
is a unique blend of 12-year-old single malt and grain whiskies,
which is mellowed in oak casks. It will be available in early
September for $30 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kiwi Wines Looking Good &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wine Institute of New Zealand reports in its annual Vintage
Survey that the 2000 harvest is the biggest ever for the New
Zealand wine industry. The 2000 harvest came in at 88,100 tons,
just a little more than the 87,700 tons from 1999. Chardonnay,
Pinot Noir, Merlot and Riesling all saw dramatic increases in yield
in 2000, while Sauvignon Blanc, the country's best-known wine, was
off 25 percent. Early signs indicate the quality of the 2000 wines
to be very high.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ever open a bottle of wine and notice tiny crystals sticking to
the bottom of the cork? Don't worry, these wine ``diamonds,'' as
they sometimes are called, are just tartaric acid that has
precipitated from the wine and hardened. Once thought by some to be
ground glass, these crystals, or tartrates, are harmless and
tasteless. Wipe any crystals from the opening of the bottle and
enjoy the wine. Tartaric deposits from winemaking are used to
produce cream of tartar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
