EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Nabisco Nips the Rest in Cheese Cracker Test  By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Summer parties require snacks, but when we don't
have time to make them, the snack aisle at the supermarket has
plenty of choices.
<P>
   Today's panel tasted nine different baked cheddar cheese snack
crackers. They all had their favorites, but preferences varied.
Some noted their kids would like certain crackers, while they
preferred others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nabisco Cheese Nips &LR;  (13.5 ounces, $2.69 at Safeway) came in
first, though only one panelist picked it as his favorite,
describing the cheese flavor as the best of those tasted. Others
liked the salt and cheese balance, but one person felt the cheese
flavor was too mild. Three would buy it and two might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Pepperidge Farms Goldfish &LR;  (6 ounces,
$1.79 at Andronico's). Two panelists picked these crackers as their
favorite. Most of the panelists liked the cute shape and
crunchiness, but two detected a burned bitter flavor. Three would
buy it, one might buy it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nabisco Better Cheddars &LR;  (7 ounces, $2.99 at many supermarkets)
came in third. One taster described it as a good ``cocktail
cracker'' and others liked the cheese flavor and crunch. But two
panelists dissented, one saying it was greasy and the other writing
that it needed more ``bite.'' Two would buy it, one might buy it
and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nabisco Cheese Nips Air Crisps &LR;  (7 ounces, $2.99 at
Andronico's) took fourth place. One panelist loved the crunchy
thinness and the flavor, which she compared to macaroni and cheese.
But others thought the crackers were too bland, though most liked
the exceptional crispness. Two would buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place was a tie between  &UR; Sunshine Cheeze-It &LR;  (10 ounces,
$2.79 at many supermarkets) and  &UR; Pepperidge Farms Xtra Cheddar &LR; 
 &UR; Goldfish &LR;  (8 ounces, $1.99 at Safeway). Both crackers scored just
two points lower than the Air Crisps.
</P>
<P>
   Two panelists thought the Cheeze-Its tasted too sharp and
burned. One of them also noted that the cracker was flaky but not
crisp. Others liked the flavor and thought the cracker had a decent
crunch. One would buy it, two might buy it and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Three panelists disliked the saltiness of the Xtra Cheddar
Goldfish, but some liked the flavor they described as ``zesty.''
One panelist thought the crackers tasted slightly spicy, but not
like cheese. One would buy it, two might buy it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Keebler Munch 'ems, Safeway and Hain
Crispettes, but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Meryl Bennan, consultant and food writer; John P.
Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler, consultant and food
writer; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and
Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner,
Cafe Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for any prduct would be
100. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
