<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WALK-MISSION-SFCHRON &LR;      08-22 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALK-MISSION-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food Lovers' Walks is a bi-weekly column that covers
neighborhoods in San Francisco and other Bay Area cities where a
casual stroll turns up culinary treasures. &HT;     
 Food Lovers' Walks: The Mission Changes But the Flavors Remain   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Without a doubt, economic changes in the Mission
are pushing out many working-class people. And some in the
neighborhood worry that its traditional Latino culture could fade.
<P>
   Still, many parts of the district remain rich in the color and
culture that makes the Mission District one of the city's best
areas for food lovers to explore. For example, 24th Street is an
absolute mecca for lovers of Mexican and Central American foods but
remains undiscovered by many in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there are people like August &LR; i &LR; n Gayt &LR; a &LR; n to get the
word out. A chef and Mexican cooking instructor who was born in San
Miguel de Allende, Guanajuato, Gayt &LR; a &LR; n recently began offering the
culinary tours designed for his students to the public. Earlier
this month, I asked him to guide me through the neighborhood's
culinary haunts.
</P>
<P>
   Gayt &LR; a &LR; n's tour begins a few blocks away from San Francisco
General Hospital and heads west along 24th Street, ending at Treat
Street. The blocks near the walk's beginning house three of the
area's oldest establishments, evoking an era when the neighborhood
was home to immigrants from Ireland and Italy as well as Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; St. Francis Fountain &AMP; Candy Store &LR;  (established in 1918),
still serves homemade ice cream and sodas at beautiful old wooden
booths;  &UR; Roosevelt Tamale Parlor &LR;  has been steaming tamales since
it was founded by a Dutchman in 1922; and  &UR; Casa Sanchez &LR;  started as
a tortilla factory in 1924, but it now sells its fresh chips and
salsas in supermarkets around the Bay Area. For the past 35 years
it's also been a taqueria, and its sunny back patio is a great
place to eat burritos and sample chips and salsa.
</P>
<P>
   These are all popular stops, but Gayt &LR; a &LR; n's focus is on the
places that aren't as well known to people outside the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   His starting point is  &UR; La Palma Mexicatessen &LR; . One of the few
places that grinds its own corn to create fresh masa for its
delicious tortillas and tamales, La Palma is a true Bay Area gem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corn is as central to Mexican cuisine as meat is to European
cuisines,'' explains Gayt &LR; a &LR; n, striding past the back food counter
where employees keep rhythm with the slap-slap-slap of hands
forming thick, rough-edged tortillas. Gayt &LR; a &LR; n plucks one off the
 &LR; comal &LR;  (griddle) to try _ asking first, of course. It's so hot I
have to wait a few moments before biting into the grainy tortilla,
sweet with corn but smoky from the griddle.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop is  &UR; Casa Lucas Market &LR; , one of the Bay Area's best
sources for Latin-American food specialties. Inside, Gayt &LR; a &LR; n waves
a hand over a bounty of  &LR; limoncitas &LR;  _ tiny, sweet Mexican limes
that he recommends for margaritas. The wooden stalls are piled with
more hard-to-find produce _ yuca,  &LR; nopales &LR;  (prickly pear cactus
paddle) and fresh herbs like epazote (traditionally used to help in
bean digestion). Gayt &LR; a &LR; n crushes the herb in his fingers to point
out its unusual, kerosene-like scent.
</P>
<P>
   Just as impressive are the shelves of prepared products ranging
from delicacies like canned  &LR; cuitlacoche &LR;  (corn fungus), Mexican
sodas, frozen tropical fruit purees, and a rainbow of dried beans,
herbs and chiles. This is also the place to pick up cooking
equipment like tortilla presses and  &LR; molcajetes &LR;  (mortars used to
grind spices).
</P>
<P>
   Next stop is  &UR; La Gallinita Meat Market &LR; , tucked behind a small
food counter that Gayt &LR; a &LR; n says is especially popular on Sundays,
when patrons enjoy menudo at a long communal table. The market
offers Mexican cuts of meat like that for carne asada, which is
traditionally cut thinner and with the grain. It also carries
specialty items like  &LR; queso de puerco &LR;  (head cheese), Mexican
cheeses and aged, housemade sausages.
</P>
<P>
   Half a block west we take a break to wander though Balmy Alley,
lined almost end-to-end with colorful murals painted by local
artists. If you have the time, guided tours offered through
 &UR; Precita Eyes Mural Arts and Visitors Center &LR;  (around the corner on
24th Street), help explain the political messages behind the
powerful images.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while the bright paintings are interrupted by a
shock of fuchsia bougainvillea or a tall cactus poking its head
over a wooden fence. ``When people come on this tour,'' says
Gayt &LR; a &LR; n, ``they feel like they have visited another country.''
</P>
<P>
   When we sit down on the red vinyl seats at  &UR; Izalco &LR; , a small
Salvadorean restaurant with bright tropical fruit tablecloths, it's
time to eat. Soon come fruity aguas frescas and  &LR; pupusas &LR; , thick
tortilla-like cakes oozing with melted cheese and served alongside
marinated cabbage. Then comes fried yuca, textured and nutty, next
to large chunks of chicarron and a savory salsa. Crisp plantains
with refried beans and crema is a classic combination of sweet and
savory, and the sauteed shrimp are simple and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   As it nears time to leave, we hear bells ringing, and Gayt &LR; a &LR; n
guesses they must be from the newly renovated St. Peters church
across the street. A neighborhood fixture since 1885, the church
burned down in 1997. It is the first time Gayt &LR; a &LR; n has heard the
bells since the church reopened, and it's hard not imagine them as
a sign of very good things happening in the Mission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MISSION STREET WALK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; The area code for the following businesses is (415) unless
otherwise noted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORES AND SERVICES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Augustin's Taste of the Mission tours &LR; : call Agust &LR; i &LR; n
Gayt &LR; a &LR; n at (510) 465-4907 or e-mail  &LR; gaytan &LR; earthlink.net &LR; ; tours
by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Casa Lucas Market &LR; , 2934 24th St. (between Florida and
Alabama streets); 826-4334
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ La Gallinita Meat Market &LR; , 2995 24th St. (at Harrison
Street); 826-8880
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _La Palma Mexicatessen &LR; , 2884 24th St. (at Florida Street);
647-1500
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Precita Eyes Mural Arts and Visitors Center &LR; , 2981 24th St.
(at Harrison Street); 285-2287; mural tours on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESTAURANTS &LR;
