<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9026 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-ROVINGFEAST-SFCHRON &LR;      08-22 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROVINGFEAST-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
Today we begin ``The Roving Feast'' by Marlena Spieler, who has
been a frequent contributor to the Food Section for nearly 12
years. She's the author of more than 30 cookbooks, writes for many
magazines both in Europe and the United States and is a regular
contributor to BBC Radio. In her column, which will run every other
week, Marlena will lead us through her special world of food both
locally and abroad. &HT;    Michael Bauer Have Fork, Will Travel  
 A Bay Area food fanatic finds life, love and sausages on the 
 continent.  
   
 By Marlena Spieler  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; LONDON _  &LR; A number of years ago I had a brilliant idea: Let's go to
Europe for a year!
<P>
   So I packed up my daughter and moved to London for an adventure
_ sort of a grown-up exchange program. As life would have it, that
year turned into more than a decade _ so far _ and our lives became
bicontinental.
</P>
<P>
   Being based in London means that we can enjoy the varied
cultures of Europe, sometimes at a moment's notice because it's all
so close. A pilgrimage to Greece to bless the olives, to France for
truffle-hunting, Bulgaria for yogurt, Italy for anything, or to
Spain for a  &LR; matanza &LR;  (don't even ask, but it involves making
sausages and hams afterward).
</P>
<P>
   My passport is always ready; so are my knife and fork. And
everywhere I go, each person I meet, the meals I enjoy, I often
find a Bay Area connection.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, my Parisienne friend Paule teaches cooking and
leads food tours of Paris, largely filled with people from the Bay
Area who want to know the gastronomical secrets of the City of
Light. She e-mails me, ``You must meet my student _ she makes
cheese in Petaluma!'' Legendary baker Lionel Poilane walks me
through his bakery, then says: ``Ah, do you know Alice (Waters)?''
</P>
<P>
   My Genovese pesto and pickle king, Giuseppe, went to the
University of California at Berkeley _ we meet over truffled
pizzettas to discuss the Bay Area. Near Sienna a restaurateur tells
me, ``Last week I had a San Francisco doctor visiting _ I taught
him to make  &LR; malfatti &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   In Liguria, the olive presser looks up from the pressing stone
being pulled by his lovely little donkey, Valentina. ``California?
Give my regards to Daryl Corti!''
</P>
<P>
   A fellow food writer in London tells me he once worked at
Berkeley's KPFA; and in a ceramics workshop in Umbria, the owner
points to a pallet of brightly colored pottery. ``For Francis Ford
Coppola _ good movies! Good wine!''
</P>
<P>
   At a Slow Food convivium in London we meet Greek olive oil guru
Sotiris Kitrilakis, a former Bay Area resident whose oil (and
roasted peppers) for many years were the flavors of my life. He now
lives in Thessaloniki and exports exquisite Greek cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   I see Asian cooking authority Ken Hom in P &LR; e &LR; rigueux, France.
He's moved there from Berkeley, stir-frying up great dishes of
traditional Chinese with his distinctive California touch _ citrus
added to pork, tomato sauce to his spring rolls, a nubbin of goat
cheese to his wontons. He confesses he misses Mexican food. I do,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the good people of P &LR; e &LR; rigueux want me to open a
restaurant serving Bay Area food. ``It's so much fun to eat in this
style, not stuffy!''
</P>
<P>
   Paris already has the trendy Cafe Marly _ close your eyes so you
can't see the Louvre to your left or the Eiffel Tower to your right
_ go by the menu and you'll think you are in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The food-loving world out there is populated with people who
have been to and fallen in love with the Bay Area, and eaten their
way around gleefully, happily, enthusiastically. They are as
enchanted with us as we are with them.
</P>
<P>
   We, of course, have long been influenced and inspired by Europe:
cheeses, olives, patisserie and wine. Chocolate, too _ when
Scharffen Berger launched its gorgeous chocolate, co-owner Dr.
Robert Steinberg went to France to train in the art of
chocolate-making.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area French chefs are innovative and classic; our food
writers/ teachers commute between California and Europe; and,
outside of Italy, could any place be more  &LR; Italiano &LR;  than North
Beach?
</P>
<P>
   Our shops are wildly varied, too _ Greek, Armenian, Moroccan,
Spanish, Portuguese, as well as our many Asian and Latin American
ones. And Indian flavors! Not only via India, but via Great
Britain, too. Not long ago I had an excellent  &LR; masala &LR;   &LR; dosa &LR;  in
Cupertino; the turbaned waiter was from my European neck of the
woods _ Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   This cosmopolitan flair is nothing new; our traditions go back
to the Gold Rush _ sourdough bread and wonderful Italian bakeries,
Italian and French grand dining, Basque boarding houses, Italian
and Spanish family-style restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Like Europeans, we in the Bay Area not only like to eat (and
drink) well, we like to talk about food, too. Before, during and
after.
</P>
<P>
   We give careful consideration to the subject. Where is the best
place for bread? Should the salad be served first or last? Do you
prefer black or white truffles?
</P>
<P>
   When I got into my first discussion about where to eat dinner in
Paris I felt right at home. My family can argue about (``discuss'')
where to go for dinner until it is time for breakfast the next day.
</P>
<P>
   I'm doing my best to help the British develop in this
department. Not long ago it was considered impolite to show too
much interest in what was being eaten. I'm told that even now the
Queen forbids two things at the table _ the first is mention of the
food and the second is garlic. I suspect that my invitation to
Buckingham Palace will be a long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   But change is all around, even if it is taking a while to filter
down. The food revolution that gripped California several decades
ago has finally come to Britain, and people are paying attention _
sometimes quite a bit _ to what goes into their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived, no one was barbecuing vegetables. Now the
British grill vegetables and fish and chicken as quickly as they
once threw horrible ``beefburgers'' and scary sausages onto the
flames, although they often need to hold an umbrella over the
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   While I have missed certain tastes from home _ Peet's and
Graffeo coffee, tamales, garlic-stuffed olives, House of Bagels
bagels, even a roll or two of Lifesavers (though we often tuck a
box of See's into our carry-on) _ I've come to appreciate many
foods here.
</P>
<P>
   One is Marmite, that brown sticky salty paste, which many claim
is an acquired taste. We acquired it pretty easily _ I'm such a
sucker for anything salty. Oatcakes are another slightly odd treat
_ rich crackers made from oats, to be eaten with good artisanal
cheese. There are chocolates filled with violet fondant, delicious
in a perfume-y sort of way, and no one, but no one makes fish and
chips like the British.
</P>
<P>
   The bacon here is amazing, and comes in a huge variety: streaky,
lean, sweet-smoked, unsmoked. The sausages are OK if you think of
them as something completely different than sausage made from meat.
It's bread _ and lots of it _ that gives it that distinctive taste
and texture.
</P>
<P>
   But don't talk to me about the black currant drink Ribena, salad
cream (revolting); mushy peas, smoothies served kind of warm,
tasteless baked goods and stodgy puddings, gravy that tastes only
of salt.
</P>
<P>
   Living in Britain I have discovered many things, some nice and
some not so. I noticed that unlike Americans, there was no bias in
Britain against the overweight. As a lifelong plump person, I found
this utterly delightful.
</P>
<P>
   Any bias against Americans doesn't extend to the table, at least
not after the first (sometimes skeptical) bite. Then they are
usually hooked. When British food writers and broadcasters gather
at my table I dazzle them with olive oil and salad leaves, crusty
bread, artichokes and crab, pastas and arugula, new wave sushi and
Pacific Rim pesto, big salads and stewy braises _ foods that have
traveled far and wide, ending up in California where they have
become intrinsically, distinctly and deliciously our own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't what I expected,'' they always say. ``Have some
more,'' I reply.
</P>
<P>
   In November, we have made expatriate Thanksgivings, inviting
both homesick Yanks and curious Brits. But for Fourth of July we
try to make it home, for fireworks and tomato season.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes for holidays we have headed off in a different
direction, such as the Christmas we went to Cyprus and baked
gingerbread men and women with frosting bathing suits, or the
Easter we spent in France's southwest, lazing by the Canal du Midi,
shopping and cooking and eating our way through the week.
</P>
<P>
   But you know, I'm never really far from California.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago I was visiting Melnick, Bulgaria, sampling
exquisite preserved figs in honey. The figs tasted floral,
delicate, enchanting. ``These would be delicious with goat
cheese,'' I exclaimed. ``And maybe a little tuft of arugula, mizuna
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   My fellow (British) journalists laughed, ``You can take the girl
out of California but you can't take California out of the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is. Wherever I go I see a little of the Bay Area in my
destination, and I take a little of the Bay Area along with me,
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   In this column, I hope to share my adventures in Britain, in
Europe, wherever I find myself. And you're all invited to come
along, and feast at my table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
