<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIST-ADVISORY </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 19 August 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLLAPSING OF IRANIAN REFORM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GASPING-IRAN-REFORM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago a loose grouping of reformists, committed to the
rule of law and democratic accountability, won Iran's parliamentary
election. The future looked uncertain but promising. Even though
the conservatives still controlled all the effective instruments of
state power _ the judiciary, the police, the army, the media _ it
was fair to hope they would feel obliged to pay heed to the
strength of the people's voice. So they did _ but only to shut it
up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HUGS FOR KOREANS, BUT NOT YET FOR NORTH KOREAN LEADER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REUNITING-KOREAS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's reunion of divided Korean families was an
emotionally charged affair, but also an important step in
dismantling one of the last frontiers of the Cold War. All the hugs
and tears were a welcome sign that, after some 50 years, the two
Koreas are continuing to make progress towards unifying their
divided peninsula. Yet the small number who made the journey shows
just how wide the gulf still is.
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONCORDE: INCREDIBLY BEAUTIFUL, INCREDIBLY ILL-CONCEIVED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PIE-IN-SKY-CONCORDE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever an airplane so beautiful to look at? No wonder
the fate of Concorde, now indefinitely withdrawn from service by
both British Airways and Air France, inspires a twinge of regret
even in the sternest critic of this ludicrous airborne indulgence.
Alas, Concorde's commercial life is clearly drawing to a close;
even if flights eventually resume following the recent
crash-induced suspension, it will be difficult to rebuild lost
confidence among passengers. At the risk of saying, ``We told you
so,'' it is worth examining the lessons to be gleaned from the
remarkable airplane's history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A REALITY CHECK FOR GAGA GURUS OF THE INTERNET &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO-INTERNET-PANACEA-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New technologies often bring new, wild claims of their
potential: Biotechnology is said to be the cure for world hunger.
The sequencing of the human genome will supposedly eradicate cancer
and other diseases. The wildest optimism, however, has greeted the
Internet. A whole industry of cybergurus has enthralled audiences
(and made a fine living) with exuberant claims that the Internet
will prevent wars, reduce pollution, and combat various forms of
inequality. Poppycock. The Internet is not the first technology to
have been hailed as a panacea _ and it will certainly not be the
last. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two optional trims, totaling 375; 1,275 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON'S HOLLYWOOD: WIZARD OF AAHS AND THE YELLOW BRICK ROAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTINSELTOWN-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It is fitting that Bill Clinton should have given
his valedictory performance at a Democratic National Convention in
Los Angeles. No group has stood more solidly behind the boy from
Arkansas than the Hollywood crowd. And no group better symbolizes
both the attraction and the ultimate hollowness of his presidency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim; story uncut is 1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIO GRANDE ISN'T GRANDE ENOUGH FOR THIRSTY SOUTHWEST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FADING-RIO-GRANDE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE AND SANTA FE, N.M. _ The Rio Grande starts life
majestically, cutting deep through the volcanic canyons of the
Colorado plateau. But by the time it reaches the desert plains of
southern New Mexico it is a shade of its former self, depleted by
irrigation channels that feed the state's thirsty crops. Now the
river faces a new challenge: fast-growing cities increasingly
desperate for water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: New Mexico, Texas and Colorado) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SHHH!': RETREAT FROM LIFE'S MADNESS TO A MONASTERY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLESSED-SILENCE-SC-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONCKS CORNER, S.C. _ Visitors who drive over the Wadboo Bridge,
30 miles from downtown Charleston, S.C., soon come upon a majestic
alley of ancient live oaks, the entrance to the monastery of our
Lady of Mepkin. Twenty-eight Trappist monks live at Mepkin Abbey,
following the simple Cistercian routine of prayer,
scripture-reading and manual labor that was laid sown 900 years ago
in France. To this serene abbey comes an increasingly steady stream
of visitors these days, men and women of all faiths exhausted by
the punishing pace of life and work in 21st-century America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: South Carolina) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KURSK DEBACLE EXPOSES RUSSIA'S BROADER MILITARY WEAKNESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEEP-SIXED-RUSSIA-NAVY-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ One can only imagine the profound embarrassment that
the Russian leadership, civilian and military, must be feeling over
the disaster which befell the Kursk, a nuclear-powered (though
apparently not nuclear-armed) submarine in the Barents Sea, near
Norway, on Aug. 12. With more than 100 sailors, over half of them
officers, trapped in a dark, bitter-cold, unventilated metal box on
the ocean floor, the navy found itself struggling _ and failing _
to cope not just with a human disaster but a public-relations
fiasco as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 125-word optional trim; total uncut is 900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUR GRAPES: THE FRENCH WINE RESISTANCE VS. ROBERT MONDAVI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRAPES-DE-WRATH-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANIANE _ ``Jose Bove is my friend,'' declares Aime Guibert, the
75-year-old maker of Daumas Gassac wines, the finest of the
Languedoc region. And his role model? While Bove, the media-savvy
leader of France's small farmers, targets McDonald's as the symbol
of the evils of globalization, the silver-haired Guibert has in his
sights a Californian wine giant, Robert Mondavi. In particular,
Guibert wants to block Mondavi's plan for a winery in the beautiful
garrigue, or wooded scrub, right next to his own vineyard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Northern California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DO SADDAM'S SINS JUSTIFY WEST'S WHIMS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZAPPING-IRAQ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Historians studying turn-of-the-century events may
be baffled by the Iraqi element. Why, they might ask, did American
and British aircraft bomb a warehouse, and perhaps a railway
station too, in southern Iraq in mid-August 2002? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Attn: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &QL;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUSTRALIA'S STOLEN GENERATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STOLEN-ABORIGINES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ When Lorna Cubillo was seven, she and 15 other
aboriginal children were put into a truck by white officials at an
outback settlement in the Northern Territory. ``As the truck left
Phillip Creek, everyone was crying and screaming,'' she says. ``I
remember seeing the mothers chasing the truck. And then they
disappeared in the dust of the track.'' Peter Gunner had a similar
experience when he was six. Mrs. Cubillo is now 62 and Mr. Gunner
is 52. They are members of Australia's ``stolen generation'':
aboriginal people, estimated to number at least 55,000, who were
removed from their families as children and put in foster homes,
many run by churches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARE FEMALE MANAGERS WEAK? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WIMPY-FEMALE-BOSSES?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Bad news for female managers: Their subordinates
resent being disciplined by them. Men and women alike would far
rather be scolded by a male boss than a female one. Indeed, a study
of gender and discipline at work finds that women dislike being
told off by another woman even more than men do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASBESTOS CLAIMS: STILL KILLING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASBESTOS-US-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Johns Manville corporation agreed to be
acquired by a buyout firm and thus return to private ownership in
early July, a painful chapter in corporate history came to an end.
From the 1920s until the 1970s, Manville had been the largest
American producer of asbestos, a product belatedly discovered to be
extraordinarily dangerous. Ensuing claims led to a bankruptcy in
1982 that penalized existing shareholders in favor of a trust fund
for victims. Yet if Manville's time in purgatory is drawing to a
close, it looks likely that others will be forced down the same
path by increasingly virulent asbestos-related litigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
