<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT23-COX     08-22 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT OPPOSES DIRECT HIGH COURT REVIEW OF ANTITRUST CASE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. urged the U.S. Supreme Court on
Tuesday to derail a proposed ``fast track'' review of its antitrust
conviction and again accused the judge who tried the landmark case
of being biased against the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   The company, entitled to the final word in a battle of the
briefs with the government, said ``the benefits of comprehensive
review by the court of appeals far outweigh whatever time, if any,
might be saved by direct review'' by the high tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   When the nine justices return from their summer break on Oct. 1,
they must decide whether to follow the three-stage legal course
favored by Microsoft or to bypass the middle layer, as advocated by
the government and U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denied as ``unfounded'' a charge by the Justice
Department and 17 state attorneys general that it wants to drag its
legal feet over the appeal, waiting for a possibly improved
political climate in Washington for its claims of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But the company reserved its sharpest criticism for Jackson, who
in June ordered Microsoft split in two after ruling that it had
broken the nation's antitrust laws. In his decision, Jackson upheld
the government's claim that Microsoft had unfairly used a monopoly
choke hold on the Windows personal computer operating system to
stifle competition and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings in this case are not the product of even one
level of impartial decision-making,'' Microsoft said, adding that
Jackson's ``extensive extrajudicial comments'' and his ``imposition
of draconian relief without holding a hearing ... cast serious
doubt on the reliability of the district court as finder of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft brief responded to a counter-filing by the
government last week which had argued that the case had ``immense
importance to our national economy,'' and therefore should be heard
directly. Since 1974, when the current ``fast track'' antitrust
exception was enacted, the top court has used it only twice.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two involved the breakup of the regulated Bell System
telephone monopoly under a consent degree. That was ``a very
different case'' which did not ``bear the 'close similarities' to
(this appeal),'' as the government contended.
</P>
<P>
   Legal opinion on how the justices will proceed remains divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the Supreme Court doesn't like to deal with lots of
messy issues,'' said Bill Kovacic, an impartial antitrust professor
at George Washington University School of Law who has followed the
case closely. ``The court prefers cases with just one or two issues
that are easily laid out,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   By an overwhelming margin, some 100 lawyers queried by Kovacic
who regularly practice before Supreme Court were of the view that
the high court would not handle the case directly.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Lande, an antitrust professor at University of Baltimore
Law School and a former Justice Department lawyer, said, ``I am now
convinced the Supreme Court will take this case at this time,''
noting that ``friend of the court'' briefs filed by high-tech trade
associations that favor the direct appeal had persuaded him.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.microsoft.com/presspass/legalnews.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
