<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BOUNCER-ARRESTS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUNCER-ARRESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOUNCER HELPS APPREHEND FUGITIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Ariz., Maine)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco bouncer with a discerning ear
made the bounce of a career, the police said, and in the process
may have halted a violent, coast-to-coast crime spree that in part
targeted patrons of gay bars.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cuneo, 35, is a Golden Gate Transit bus driver by day, but
at 8:30 p.m. Saturday he was watching the door of The Cafe on
Market Street when two young men with Boston accents tried to enter
the bar without identification.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Monday, Cuneo said he recalled seeing a
police brochure in the bar's office warning of two men with thick
Boston accents suspected of beating and robbing a patron of another
San Francisco bar a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, Cuneo thought, matched a picture on the
brochure, which officers had distributed widely in gay bars. So he
calmly told the men to go elsewhere, then dialed 911 as they
strolled away down Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never let on that I knew who they were,'' said Cuneo, who
vacationed in Boston last year and remembered the accents. ``But I
also didn't want them in the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuneo's cool demeanor, the police said, led to the arrests two
blocks away of two Massachusetts fugitives _ John Lydon, 27, and
Paul Devlin, 28 _ each of whom has ``Irish Blood'' tattooed on his
chest. They were wanted by the U.S. Marshals Service.
</P>
<P>
   Their flight from the law, according to a published report,
included a taxicab ride away from the police at Tucson
International Airport on July 26. An alleged accomplice, Richard
McDougall, 29, was arrested that day while trying to board a plane
to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco police believe that Lydon and Devlin arrived
in the city the night of Aug. 12 aboard a Greyhound bus from
Fullerton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The men allegedly attacked Herbert Poteet, 63, of Fairfield, who
had agreed to give them a lift after meeting them over drinks.
Poteet told the police the men had claimed to be brothers who had
come to San Francisco after losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The men also are suspected of picking up a man in a gay bar in
Santa Monica on Aug. 7, then robbing his house and stabbing him
repeatedly. Officers found the victim outside his house, screaming
for help, said Santa Monica police Lt. Frank Fabrega. The man's car
was taken and later dumped in Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, Lydon, Devlin and McDougall are wanted in connection
with the armed robbery of $25,000 in cash and merchandise from a
jewelry store in York, the Portland Press Herald of Portland
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The three also are suspected of robbing a motor inn and
burglarizing a house in York, and robbing two outlet stores in
nearby Kittery, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Lydon and Devlin were being held at the San Francisco Hall of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Monday that Cuneo's involvement in the arrests
was an example of the best kind of public crime-fighting: not
taking physical action, but calmly guiding officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
