<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN PREPARES TO MEET WITH FAMILY MEMBERS OF KURSK CREW 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir Putin on Tuesday flew to the
headquarters of Russia's Northern Fleet to pay his last respects to
the 118 officers and sailors who perished aboard the
nuclear-powered submarine Kursk after it suffered a catastrophic
internal explosion in the Barents Sea on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader was also scheduled to meet with naval
commanders and the families of crew members. Before he left Moscow,
Putin declared a national day of mourning Wednesday and ordered
flags to fly at half staff. Russian officials said he would fly to
the deck of the cruiser Peter the Great to cast a memorial wreath
of flowers onto the Arctic waters where the twin-reactor submarine
went down.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling without his usual contingent of Russian news media,
Putin was due on Tuesday night and Wednesday to undertake the
sensitive and politically volatile task of meeting with
grief-stricken widows, mothers, fathers and other kin who have a
lot of questions about why the Russian government and its military
command were not able to assure the safety of their loved ones and
why it could not rescue them when tragedy struck.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Russian television reported that
representatives of the families had asked the navy to allow them to
leave Severomorsk, the closed military city where the fleet
headquarters is located, so they could make a public statement. For
Putin, avoiding a public or emotional confrontation with angry
family members is likely one of the major tasks of this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Though public opinion polls over the last several days have
showed that 60 percent of Russians in the Moscow region have not
changed their attitudes toward Putin for his handling of the
crisis, about 75 percent of respondents to polls have said they
either disagree or strongly disagree with Russia's four-day delay
in accepting Western assistance with the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   When Putin meets the families, the session will be tightly
controlled by Putin's advisers, who fear that emotional outbursts
and recriminations directed at Putin and broadcast to the nation
might prolong the sense of crisis and the raucous attacks in the
press that threaten to derail the president's busy economic and
political reform plans this fall.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin arrived in Severomorsk, Norwegian and British deep sea
divers abandoned their search and rescue work on the wrecked and
flooded hull, where the bodies of the crew remain in 350 feet of
water. They said they might return with different equipment if they
can conclude a contract with Russian officials. That contract would
cover the cost of penetrating the hull in a complex operation to
recover crew remains.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russian navy officials have offered to cut giant holes in the
hull of the Kursk in order to make entry to the vessel easier and
safer for divers involved in evacuating the victims' remains.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, the navy chief of staff, Adm. Viktor
Kravchenko, said the navy was committed to ``carrying out this
operation until the last seaman's body has been recovered from the
submarine's compartments.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Aleksei Kudrin said the Russian government
was prepared to finance the full cost of the crew recovery and a
complex and dangerous salvage operation whose estimated cost
already has ranged up to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an executive of the Norwegian firm, Stolt Offshore,
whose divers finally managed to open a rear hatch on the Kursk,
said in Oslo that the company would help the Russian navy study
options to raise the 490-foot vessel, which displaces 14,000 tons
of water on the surface and 25,000 tons submerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have agreed to help the Russians look at ways of recovering
the bodies and of salvaging the Kursk,'' Julian Thomson of Stolt
told reporters Tuesday. On the difficult task of raising a vessel
whose superstructure is severely damaged, he said, ``There are
dangers.'' He added that it would be very hazardous due to
unexploded munitions, internal damage and potential radiation
leaks. Planning was likely to take weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With winter approaching in the Arctic, there were conflicting
estimates of whether Russia would be able to accomplish the crew
recovery before fierce storms and ice flows set in.
</P>
<P>
   The on-going effort to solve the mystery of how the Kursk sank
also continued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Alexsander Rutskoi, Russia's former vice president and now
governor of the Kursk region, for which the submarine is named,
asserted Tuesday that the attack vessel was carrying an
experimental torpedo that was to be test-fired by the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk had on board a ``new torpedo and two civilian
engineers,'' said Rutskoi, who is a war hero and leader of a 1993
parliamentary uprising against former President Boris Yeltsin. ``It
is necessary to investigate this aspect, and if a new torpedo was
really being tested on the submarine, it is a crime,'' he
continued, arguing that test firings of new weapons should not be
conducted during crew training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership of the Chechen rebellion in southern Russia
offered its own explanation Tuesday, suggesting that a ``kamikaze''
fighter from the Northern Caucasus was among the crew and had
triggered the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who is
heading the official investigation into the disaster, lashed out at
critics for their ``cynicism'' and for ``trying to make a cheap
sensation out of this common tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``the only truth today is that a powerful and
dynamic external blow'' remains the most likely explanation for the
sinking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
