r a BC-INCOME-CALIF-HNS &LR;      08-22 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCOME-CALIF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FED REPORT HINTS AT WIDENING INCOMING DISPARITY IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Income for California families is declining
against average family incomes for the nation as a whole, according
to a report released by the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited the lasting impact of the cutbacks in the
aerospace industry and a large influx of immigrant laborers who are
generally younger and less educated. It found that the economic
picture for Californians was not as rosy as it was typically
perceived, despite its newly minted dot-com millionaires, movie
moguls and real estate barons.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the report also adds to a growing body of work that
appears to show the income gap between rich and poor is growing
wider and more stark all the time, and may become a factor both as
an election-year issue and as a consideration in whether to raise
the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislative Analysts Office, a think tank for the California
Legislature, issued a report last month finding that income for the
top 20 percent of the state's wage earners had risen while wages
for the bottom 80 percent had fallen, in real terms. And the Public
Policy Institute of California concluded last year that the growing
gap between rich and poor had increased at a rate faster in the
Golden State since the 1980s than it had in the nation at large.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Daly, a senior economist at the Federal Reserve Bank, said
the purpose of the report was to add some context to the growing
debate over the increasing economic stratification.
</P>
<P>
   Though her report found that wages were increasing, in real
terms, for families in the 70th income percentile but declining for
those below that level, she maintained the report was more about
California compared to the rest of the nation, not the widening
distance between top and bottom earners in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't confirm that, but it explains to a certain extent
why we see this divergence,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   The news comes even as California's economy has grown at a rate
faster than the rest of the nation's over the last five years. The
report found a greater number of state residents lived in poverty,
the middle class was shrinking, and a majority of families had
incomes below the level of their counterparts nationwide. While
income growth for median families outside of California grew by
more than 8 percent between 1989 and 1998, median income inside the
state declined by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the statistics show that California families had
higher incomes than families elsewhere in the United States until
the 1990s, but that relative gains outside the state began to
surpass those of residents inside the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance, the income statistics on California suggest
that seven years of economic expansion have left state residents
worse off than those residing elsewhere in the U.S.,'' the report
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1527EDT &QL; 
