<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9086 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-FALLEN-IDOLS-NNS &LR;      08-22 2480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLEN-IDOLS-NNS </SLUG>
  
 NFL's Felonious Off-Season Renews Debate over Role Modeling for
Kids  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Aug. 22, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: With seven photos, of Mark Chmura (NNS1), Rae
Carruth (NNS2), Paul Krumberger (NNS3 and NNS4), Brett Favre
(NNS5), Antonio Freeman (NNS6) and Darrell Green (NNS7). 
 By MARK O'KEEFE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Chmura wasn't just a Green Bay Packers tight end, outspoken
critic of Bill Clinton's sexual misconduct and United Way example
of what's supposed to be good and noble and true about the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura was a child's hero, riding 11-year-old Paul Krumberger's
bicycle between the Lambeau Field locker room and the Packers'
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Green Bay tradition for players to accept bike rides from
kids during summer training camp, and Paul got all the autographed
leather receiving gloves, signed them, and gave them to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Paul returned this summer to offer rides to players, but his
former hero wasn't there to pedal. Subsequently cut by the Packers,
Chmura awaits trial on criminal charges in another blow to the
image of what has been dubbed the National Felony League.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, in Paul's words, ``did something really bad to a woman
when he was drunk.'' A district attorney deemed it third-degree
sexual assault, and since the woman was a 17-year-old girl, child
enticement. If convicted, Chmura could face up to 40 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of players in handcuffs and orange jail jumpsuits --
even players innocent until proven guilty -- have prompted concern
over a serious public relations injury to one of America's most
popular sports.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Paul, and thousands of children like him,
vulnerable to around-the-clock media hype of football players
marketed as mythic figures? If kids copy the on-the-field moves,
flamboyant celebrations and excessive trash talking of their Sunday
heroes, will they also imitate their off-the-field behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Many players dismiss the connection, saying they don't want to
be role models. But the league reluctantly acknowledges a
responsibility to kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our players to be exemplary citizens,'' NFL
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said in an interview. ``We want them to
set high standards on the field as well as off the field. I think
the reality is that they are role models, whether we like it or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chmura case is made richer by the former player's longtime
criticism of President Clinton. Chmura refused to attend the
traditional visit to the White House after the Packers won the
Super Bowl in 1997. After the Monica Lewinksky scandal, he
lambasted the president's morals and the message they sent to
children.
</P>
<P>
   But the charges against Chmura are only one pro football crime
story among several that have tarnished the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Others involve Rae Carruth, the former Carolina Panthers
receiver awaiting trial on first-degree murder charges in the
shooting death of his pregnant girlfriend, and Denver Broncos
linebacker Bill Romanowski, who faces felony charges in a
prescription drug case involving diet pills. The Baltimore Ravens'
Ray Lewis, the NFL's leading tackler last year, had murder charges
dropped in May in exchange for a guilty plea to obstruction of
justice in connection with a stabbing death after an Atlanta Super
Bowl party. The NFL subsequently fined Lewis $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists say there is little doubt that in this era of
around-the-clock sports coverage and slick marketing of stars, NFL
players have some effect on the millions of children who idolize
them. But the degree of influence is difficult to measure, and
varies from child to child, dependent in part on their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe strongly in the power of modeling behavior. That's
been demonstrated for years,'' said Leonard Zaichkowsky, director
of sports psychology at Boston University and a past president of
the Association for Applied Sports Psychology for North America.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that he has seen no research establishing a
link between NFL and childhood behavior. Zaichkowsky said it's
similar to trying to prove that violent films make people violent.
The best evidence may be anecdotal.
</P>
<P>
   In Green Bay, child psychologist Bonnie Nussbaum said she hasn't
seen cases of post-Chmura trauma, but the story has been a
stressful undercurrent for many of the children she counsels. She
said it especially triggers old fears and responses of girls who
have been victims of sexual abuse and tells boys, if at a
subconscious level, that women are objects of domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids have the ego strength to resist that type of
behavior,'' Nussbaum said. ``But other kids are more vulnerable and
might follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Connor, a professor of psychology at California State
University in Long Beach, where he teaches a class on sport
behavior, said children will turn cynical as NFL players continue
to let them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could very easily turn kids against the entire sport, the
entire process and the NFL altogether,'' Connor said. ``The way
kids think, they will generalize. They'll say if Rae Carruth did
it, everyone has done it, they just haven't been caught yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my biggest concern is the disillusionment won't stop with
the football. Kids may think you bend the rules to do whatever you
can get away with in society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Such cynicism was evident this summer in Green Bay, where
muscled behemoths have been riding the bicycles of children since
the 1960s. Ten boys sat on their bikes, waiting for the objects of
their football worship and rattling off the Packers' recent rap
sheet. In addition to Chmura, four other Packers have been arrested
since December, on charges of obstruction of justice (Antonio
Freeman and Rodney Artmore), drunken driving and speeding (Marco
Rivera) and possession of marijuana (De'Mond Parker).
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on Chmura, Jason Wassenberg, 11, said, ``I think he's
sick. That's gross to do that. It's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Chad Van DenLangenberg, 13: ``I'm glad he got under
arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone,'' said 13-year-old Jacob Stalberger, ``gets in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason: ``That's because some players think they can get away
with anything because they're pro football players and big
namers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They do get away with it,'' retorted Scott Wick, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob: ``Look at De'Mond Parker. He had 7 grams of marijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the charges were dropped,'' said Luke Parlow, referring to
an arrangement that had Parker completing a court-approved drug
course. ``They shouldn't have been.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boys eagerly approached other players after practice,
asking for autographs and offering rides.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay quarterback Brett Favre downplayed his influence on
children. ``I don't think NFL players should be role models for
someone else's kids,'' Favre said. ``The parents should be their
own role models. It's not our responsibility. We try to live life
the right way, but nobody's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Freeman, ``My role models are my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   After the obstruction of justice charge in a December traffic
accident that injured a woman, Freeman was sentenced to a year's
probation, $1,000 fine and 50 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman was a Wisconsin Department of Transportation spokesman
for wearing seat belts, his likeness on 15,000 posters with the
words, ``Football is a game. Your life is not. Buckle Up.'' Police
found that he wasn't wearing his seat belt in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his conduct has hurt children, Freeman said no.
``We all make mistakes,'' he said. ``We're human.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   To what extent NFL players make criminal mistakes is in dispute.
In their often-cited 1998 book, ``Pros and Cons, the Criminals Who
Play in the NFL,'' authors Jeff Benedict and Don Yaeger said their
study of 509 players -- about one-third of the active NFL roster at
the time -- showed ``an eye-popping 109 (21 percent) were found to
have been formally charged (arrested or indicted) with a serious
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   But a year later in CHANCE, a magazine of the American
Statistical Association, Benedict joined another author in
re-evaluating NFL arrests. They studied FBI figures for the general
population -- in this case only for assaults -- and concluded that
``the NFL rates are less than half the general population rates.''
</P>
<P>
   For players critical of what they consider distorted media
coverage, that clarification is evidence that NFL players are
better people than they are portrayed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disturbing to me that there are only one or two
incidents they seem to focus on and they don't see the good that
we're doing as far as raising and generating money for different
organizations that help people less fortunate,'' said veteran
defensive end Bruce Smith of the Washington Redskins. ``They don't
see us being mentors for children and being positive role models.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Darrell Green is such a mentor. After a two-hour
summer practice in Ashburn, Va., \roMDRV\ &UR; -in 90-degree heat and
high humidity, Green stood on a plush, green practice field wearing
a sweat-soaked T-shirt and Redskins football pants, talking to 14
children involved with the Darrell Green Youth Life Foundation.
When the kids seemed restless, the defensive back called them to
attention with a firm, ``Stay with me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he retires, Green, 40, said he wants to set aside $10
million for the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you take care of things they can't take away from
you,'' Green told the children. ``In sports, you can break a leg.
But no one can take your honesty away from you. No one can take
your integrity away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking to the locker room, Green said it is foolish to see Nike
spend millions of dollars on athlete endorsements to persuade
children to buy expensive shoes and not believe that NFL players
have a powerful influence on other types of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that thing called celebrity fame,'' Green said. ``I'm not
exploiting it from the standpoint of making dollars. But I'm
exploiting it from the standpoint of trying to access the hearts
and minds of youths and trying to turn them toward what is right,
what is honest and what is respectable.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) \roMDUL\ &UR; - But for every moment of
attention from a Darrell Green, there seems to be a counter-moment
from a Plaxico Burress, first-round draft pick of the Pittsburgh
Steelers\roMDRV\ &UR; -, which gave him a $5.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   While children asked for autographs after a practice
\roMDRV\ &UR; -this summer in Latrobe, Pa., Burress ignored them and
walked to his new, shiny Hummer, the wide-bodied vehicle based on
the military's Humvee. He drove through a sea of kids without
establishing eye contact, leaving several holding pens with
confused looks on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Fasano, 19, a ``die-hard Steelers fan'' for as long as he
can remember, witnessed the scene, which fueled the distaste he
feels for what money has done to the NFL and the tradition
established by gritty, not greedy, players like Joe Greene and
Rocky Bleier, leaders of the ``Steel Curtain'' Steelers of the
1970s, a team that won four Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   \roMDRV\ &UR; -\roMDRV\ &UR; -``That's gaudy, flamboyant and out of touch
with the world,'' said Fasano, a University of Florida student.
``That Hummer was a microcosm of what I'm talking about. It didn't
even stop for the kids. It sped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fasano traces his distaste to when his favorite Steeler, Barry
Foster, held out for more money, teaching then 12-year-old Fasano
that ``the players don't give a damn about me. They just care about
their paychecks.'' He'd have been emotionally scarred, Fasano said,
if he'd seen his hero on national television as the subject of a
criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   Around the NFL, there seems to be a growing consensus that big
money in the hands of 20-something men with an adoring entourage
can be the root of some evil, sending a bad message to kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I can browbeat the guys into doing the right
thing,'' said Nesby Glasgow, the Seattle Seahawks' director of
player programs, a full-time position every team is required to
have. ``But we do sit down and talk about goals and aspirations,
and I may tell these guys I don't see your behavior reflecting your
goals and aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL also requires rookies to attend a symposium designed to
teach life skills. One of this year's speakers was Lewis, who in
the aftermath of his murder trial warned about carefully choosing
friends. The NFL says past statistics suggest that four rookies are
likely to be arrested this year, along with 12 second-year players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league for eight years and the programs have
increased 500 percent,'' said Baltimore Ravens quarterback Trent
Dilfer. ``The hardest thing for me was that I was only 21 years old
when they handed me $4.5 million. I had great parents and good
people around me, but that amount of money is overwhelming. I still
made mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   How can parents prevent the mistakes of millionaire athletes
from adversely affecting their children? When an incident hits the
news, they should talk to their sons and daughters about it, giving
them an opportunity to vent while discussing their family values,
psychologists say.
</P>
<P>
   Nussbaum, the Green Bay therapist, said it was unfortunate that
she had to discuss graphic aspects of the Chmura and Carruth
incidents with her young daughter. But that, she added, is what
life is about in our society -- not just the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter just couldn't comprehend someone shooting a woman
who was pregnant. Yuck,'' said Nussbaum. ``I mean, I don't really
want to be talking to my 7-year-old about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krumberger doesn't want to be talking about what Chmura may
have done, either. But like many well-adjusted children, he is
capable of realizing that good athletes can make bad decisions that
kids should avoid.
</P>
<P>
   When Paul plays football with his buddies, he no longer imagines
that he's No. 89 cutting across the end zone for a touchdown. He's
considering selling those once-cherished Chmura gloves, as if
someone would want them now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good influence on me,'' said Paul, ``until he did
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
