u a BC-NO-SURVIVORNNS &LR;      08-22 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-SURVIVORNNS </SLUG>
  
 `Survivor' Addicts Wonder How They'll Spend Their Wednesday
Nights  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Aug. 22, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After this week, Wednesday nights will never be the same for
them.
</P>
<P>
   They are the addicts, the obsessed. They are not mere
``Survivor'' fans, they are sheer ``Survivor'' fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   They do things like videotape each episode so they can later
analyze minutiae they missed. They turn off the telephone,
reschedule dates, rush home in a frenzy just so they can have their
Wednesday night fix.
</P>
<P>
   All that for a CBS-TV show featuring a bunch of sweaty people on
an island backstabbing their way to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But to many ``Survivor'' addicts, the money isn't the point.
</P>
<P>
   For Enrique Rojas, a computer programmer in Toronto, it's the
sheer unpredictability. You never know who will betray whom, who
will suddenly strip naked, who will explode in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know what to expect,'' said Rojas, 26. ``With
sitcoms and other shows, you pretty much know what's going to
happen. But with this, well, actors could try, scriptwriters could
try, even the proverbial million monkeys at typewriters could try,
but none of them could come close to creating `Survivor.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas recently auctioned off a charcoal portrait he sketched of
Colleen, a favorite contestant who recently departed the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``To whoever wins the auction please take care of her. The
drawing I mean,'' Rojas wrote to bidders on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   If ratings are any indication, Rojas is one of a massive number
of fans that has steadily grown through the summer's run. According
to A.C. Nielsen, last week's ``Survivor'' had 28.7 million viewers
-- more than the other five major networks combined (20.7 million).
And that number was up 670,000 viewers from the previous week. The
Daily Variety industry newspaper has dubbed it a ``summer smash.''
Industry analysts say that as many as 38 million may watch
Wednesday's finale.
</P>
<P>
   Lea Ann Martin of Topeka, Kan., finds ``Survivor'' so
enthralling that it has become a central part of her life. ``It's
sort of like watching a car wreck ,'' she said. ``You know it's
wrong to stare but you just can't help yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I set my schedule by it,'' added Martin, 30, who describes
herself as ``between jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My boyfriend works nights, and I wake him up to see it,'' she
said. ``It is the only thing he'll wake up for. I think it's a
super good thing. Everybody I know talks about the show. That's our
way to have a connection, through TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas has noticed the same phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the people who aren't fanatics have opinions and
theories, and know the characters,'' he said. ``Once at work I was
talking about it with a guy for 15 minutes, and he had never even
seen the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Radio personality Alpha Trivette, 46, regards the
program as a case study in human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this show will be used in future sociology and
archeology classes,'' he said from the studio of WBS. ``It has a
little of everything: The human instinct to survive by employing
all tactics, skills and treachery. There's sex, race relations,
conflict. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Trivette and his wife, Kim, once rushed home from a restaurant
when they realized what time it was. ``We were saying, `10 minutes
to `Survivor,' 10 minutes to `Survivor,''' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should envy these addicts, said Robert Thompson,
professor of television, radio and film and at Syracuse University
in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know how when you really get into a book or TV show or
soap opera, nothing beats that feeling,'' said Thompson, director
of the university's Center for the Study of Popular Television.
``Maybe these people have an ability to go even deeper. I watch the
show all the time and tape it and go back over it, but I get paid
for it, it's my job. Here you've got people doing it for love.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who hasn't ``looked forward to a show this much since
`Twin Peaks,''' has his own theories as to why ``Survivor''
inspires such obsession: It is well-cast with strong, engaging
characters. And it's essentially a cliffhanger soap opera, ``with a
guarantee of the best soap-opera payoff each week: A character gets
killed off.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``Survivor'' does what the best miniseries can do, because
within its 13-episode run it has a definite beginning, middle and
end. ``Each time a character leaves, you've built up more emotional
equity,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Put all that together and you have potent and irresistible
television.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, fans hold little hope for ``Survivor II,''
which begins in September and will take place in the Australian
outback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will be as good as the first one,'' Rojas
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was so intriguing about this one,'' Martin said, ``is it
was something super different. I'm not really interested in seeing
it again, just with new players.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Trivette, ``I don't know that it will have the same
draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson agreed. ``I'm not looking forward to the second one,''
he said. ``It's this particular group of people and all its
naivete, we got to see them learn the game. In the outback, that
group will know every intricacy of how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   So true ``Survivor'' addicts will resort to watching reruns and
reliving those 13 Wednesday nights in Internet chatrooms, around
office water coolers and on the telephone with friends.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no need for concern about their sanity, Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, a fan is someone who names their pets
Spock and Kirk,'' he said. ``Now if they name their KIDS Spock and
Kirk -- that's the time to consult a therapist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
