<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-22 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T TOSS OUT THE COBS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When corn is very young, you can eat it whole; the cob has as
much flavor as the kernels. But once it reaches four or five
inches, the cob is inedible. Still, all that flavor remains, and
it's a shame not to take advantage of it. The best way to do that
is to use the cobs as the base for a corn chowder.
</P>
<P>
   It's so easy that it should inspire you to move beyond the basic
soup and experiment with flavors from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   After stripping the kernels off a few ears, you can use the cobs
to make a quick stock. All it needs are something like potatoes to
add substance, seasonings and the corn.
</P>
<P>
   The entire process takes just about half an hour, and the result
is a thick, satisfying vegetable stew.
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, chowder contains little more than corn, onion,
potatoes and milk; a couple of chopped tomatoes and a handful of
parsley add flavor and color (if you left out the milk, you might
think of this as Manhattan corn chowder). Starting with bacon and
finishing with cream makes a richer version of the dish.
</P>
<P>
   But leaving the traditional flavors behind is more fun.
</P>
<P>
   I add curry powder and ginger and finish the chowder with sour
cream and cilantro for a more exotic taste. When the potato is
replaced by rice and the cream with coconut milk, Southeast Asian
seasonings can be added to make a chowder that has little in common
with the original, yet still has intense corn flavor.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of chili powder, lime juice and cilantro, again
with sour cream, will give the chowder a Mexican character; you
might thicken it with corn tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   My technique for stripping the kernels from the cobs is simple:
after shucking the corn, stand the ears up in a shallow bowl, and
run a paring knife down the sides.
</P>
<P>
   For maximum efficiency, strip the corn and get the cobs
simmering in water first; then chop the onion while the oil is
heating, and peel and chop the potatoes as the onions are cooking.
At that point, almost all of the work is done.
</P>
<P>
   As long as your corn is young and tender, the kernels should be
held out until the chowder is just about ready, so they don't
overcook. But the new super-sweet hybrids, which will retain much
of their flavor for a few days, are not as tender, and their
kernels should be cooked for a few minutes at least. Just keep
tasting, and stop cooking when their texture seems right.
</P>
<P>
   BASIC CORN CHOWDER
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 to 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 ears of corn
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or neutral oil, like canola or grapeseed
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium potatoes, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tomatoes, cored, seeded and chopped (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole or low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped parsley (optional).
</P>
<P>
   1. Shuck corn, and use a paring knife to strip kernels into a
bowl. Put cobs in a pot with 4 cups water; bring to a boil, cover
and simmer while you continue. 2. Put butter or oil in a saucepan,
and turn heat to medium-high. When butter melts or oil is hot, add
onion and potatoes, along with a sprinkling of salt and pepper.
Cook, stirring occasionally, until onion softens, about 5 minutes;
add tomatoes and cook, stirring, for another minute or two.
</P>
<P>
   3. After corncobs have cooked at least 10 minutes, strain liquid
into onion-potato mixture; bring to a boil, then lower heat to a
simmer. When potatoes are tender, add corn kernels and milk, and
heat through. Taste, and adjust seasonings. Garnish with the
parsley, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Corn chowder with bacon and cream: In Step 2,
substitute { cup chopped bacon for butter or oil; cook over medium
heat until it renders some of its fat, then add onion. In Step 3,
use heavy cream or half-and-half in place of milk.
</P>
<P>
   Curried corn chowder: In Step 2, use oil, and add 1 tablespoon
each curry powder and peeled and minced ginger to the onions. In
Step 3, use sour cream in place of milk; garnish with cilantro in
place of parsley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
