</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STASH SHORT-TERM INVESTMENT CASH
</P>
<P>
   SHORTTERM-INVEST-SMARTMONEY _ The market's gut-wrenching ride
this year should serve as a reminder to us all: Big investments in
stocks (tech or otherwise) simply aren't for people with short time
horizons. If you have near-term goals such as saving for a home, a
child's upcoming college education or a once-in-a-lifetime
vacation, you really should set up a separate portfolio that's
geared to protect your assets so they'll be there when you need
them. By Richard ten Wolde. (North American rights only.)
</P>
<P>
   BRING ME THE HEAD OF ALAN GREENSPAN
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-SMARTMONEY _ Henry Johnsen, Hoyt Brown and Pete McDade
belong to a growing (and highly vocal) minority of individual
investors who truly detest Alan Greenspan. They don't understand
why the Federal Reserve Board chairman fears inflation; they think
he's overreacting to the so-called wealth effect caused by rising
asset prices; and most of all, they are furious about what his
latest interest-rate hikes have done to their tech-heavy stock
portfolios. By Landon Thomas Jr. (North American rights only.)
</P>
<P>
   FIVE SECRETS THE GAMING INDUSTRY WON'T TELL YOU
</P>
<P>
   GAMING-INDUSTRY-SMARTMONEY _ Everyone knows the house has an
advantage. But most casino patrons don't realize just how heavily
the odds are stacked against them. Games like keno give the house
an advantage of about 25 percent. Slot machines are popular, but
also the biggest moneymakers. Casinos play by design and market
heavily in ways the consumer never knew. By Brian O'Keefe. (North
American rights only.)
</P>
<P>
   WHO WANTS TO BE A THOUSANDAIRE?
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-STOCK-OPTION-WEALTH-SMARTMONEY _ Andrew Malgieri got
rich earlier this year. And for that he can thank his stock options
in an Internet company called NaviSite. The options he got when
coming on board allowed him to purchase stock for $26. The stock
skyrocketed, reaching a high of $159. Then it started to fall,
plummeting to $31. By late June it had bounced back to $46. He's
like a lot of people who chased dot-com dreams, tasted fantastic
riches and are now coming back down to earth with a thud. By Vera
Gibbons and Gerri Willis. (North American rights only.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
