<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f BC-INTERNET-STOCK-OPTION     08-22 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STOCK-OPTION-WEALTH-SMARTMONEY-1,200-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO BE A THOUSANDAIRE?
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This ``separate-buy'' article from the August
issue of SmartMoney magazine can be purchased - the rate is not
prohibitive _ by contacting New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 1-732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697. 
 By VERA GIBBONS AND GERRI WILLIS
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
 North American rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andrew Malgieri got rich earlier this year. And for that he can
thank his stock options in an Internet company called NaviSite.
Malgieri, a 32-year-old network engineer, joined the Andover,
Mass., company this past December. NaviSite was an incredibly hot
company _ for a while. The options he got when coming on board
allowed him to purchase stock for $26; a week after he joined,
shares were already trading at $35. Then the stock skyrocketed,
reaching a high of $159 in April. Malgieri started dreaming of
early retirement, buying a house out West in Snowbird or maybe
Vermont, so he could ski in the winter. He told his buddies, ``I'll
be skiing while you guys are working.'' At the peak, Malgieri was
worth $35 million _ on paper, of course. It was a far cry from his
modest upbringing. His father is a guidance director at a public
high school; his mother is an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   He and two friends who joined NaviSite at the same time started
acting the role. One night the trio, on their way to a charity
ball, stopped at the posh Boston Harbor Hotel to celebrate their
options, which had now put them past the multimillion mark. The
three of them, dressed in black tie, toasted their most recent
milestone with champagne as they waited for a limo to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stock was trading high, there was a three- or
four-week period where I was impervious to anything,'' he says. ``I
felt like I was flying on top of the world and nothing else
mattered. Nothing bad could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the stock started to fall and finally plummeted to $31. By
late June it had bounced back to $46, which means his options are
now worth about $500,000. Malgieri took to checking the share price
twice an hour _ sometimes every 15 minutes _ and recalculating the
impact on his stake.
</P>
<P>
   Today Malgieri is still living in Billerica, the same
blue-collar Boston suburb he called home before he joined NaviSite.
Now he's thinking about leaving the company altogether before his
first option share even vests.
</P>
<P>
   He's like a lot of people who chased dot-com dreams, tasted
fantastic riches and are now coming back down to earth with a thud.
For a brief, shining moment, options held the promise of limitless
affluence. Now, except for the lucky few who got in early with the
right companies, they seem like a macabre tease.
</P>
<P>
   According to the San Francisco Federal Reserve, Silicon Valley
IPOs created option wealth of some $68 billion, or $500,000 each
for roughly 134,000 employees, between 1997 and 1999. But then the
market capitalization of those companies declined one-third from
mid-February to early May, and some $22.7 billion of wealth
disappeared into the Ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if you bought a lottery ticket and you have the
winning numbers, and then you take it to the store to cash it in
and they're like, 'Sorry, there were forgeries going around and you
got one,''' says Moira McGarvey Black, 39, vice president of ad
sales for the Seattle-based OnHealth Network, who held thousands of
options with a strike price as low as $4. She watched the shares go
as high as $21 last year _ ``I would say I was close to being a
millionaire'' before they went underwater this spring.
</P>
<P>
   At least some relished their 15 minutes. Dan Hurwitz's options
may be underwater, but he'd already lived it up after the stock of
his online media company, whose name he requested not be published,
peaked at $106 in January: He installed a pool in his Long Island,
N.Y., home and bought a new two-seater Mercedes. He also stashed
some money away for his kids' education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' the 35-year-old sales executive recalls. ``Your
attitude changes. You're like, 'I'm worth X amount, and I'm so
proud. 'Everyone started treating me differently. I would go out to
dinner and when the check came, friends would say, 'Give it to Dan,
Mr. Money Bags. He's the rich guy.' In my own head, I'm like, 'Wow,
I'm on top of the world.' You can't not like the attention.'' But
the attention vanished when the stock tumbled 83 percent and stayed
there.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible dreams die hard, but die they will. The romance of
working for startups _ the 80-hour weeks, the fast-food diets and,
above all, the chance to strike it rich _ has begun to sour. If
anything, there's a sense of bitterness in the air. ``No one wants
to hear another story about the 23-year-old who started the company
from his dorm room and is now worth $10 million,'' says Bill
Lessard, 34, a New York startup veteran and founder of the gripe
site NetSlaves.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lessard gave up chasing options after a couple of bad stints.
One example is when he joined AirMedia, a wireless media company,
when he had only $3,000 in his bank account and was desperate not
only to make some money, but to make a lot of money. ``I'd be lying
if I said I didn't want to strike it rich,'' he says. ``You get to
the point where you think, 'There must be something wrong with me.
How come everyone's rich but me? What am I doing wrong?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hired as a manager for AirMedia's Web site in 1996, Lessard says
he was lured not by the $50,000 salary, but by the options. ``They
said they were going to go public and that I was going to get a lot
of options and be rich. They also said that when I finished with
their site, there would be plenty more for me to do, lots of
opportunities. They said that I would have my own department and
that I would have all these responsibilities. All this
entrepreneurial bullshit.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, after wrapping up just one project for the
company, Lessard was fired.
</P>
<P>
   For all the disappointments, though, there are still a few
headstrong souls who are sure that their big break is right around
the corner. Michael Perhaes, 40, who lives in Manhattan's trendy
Chelsea district, is one. He turned down a job offer (with 15,000
options) from America Online in 1997 for one reason: He didn't want
to work in ``the middle of nowhere,'' he says. ``AOL is located at
the Dulles airport. Literally. It's a groovy space, but I mean the
employees go to like the Wal-Mart cafeteria for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a grave mistake. ``I figure if I took the 15,000 shares
at the 1997 price, which was like eight splits ago, I'd be totally
vested and I'd be worth well over $1.5 million today. We would be
having this conversation in Bermuda. Or Tahiti, where I'd be
drinking heavily and bragging about how rich I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaes erred again when he left digital information provider
Wave Systems, where he was creative director, that same year.
Again, he didn't like the location: Lee, Mass. Plus, he thought the
company was going to go under. ``A couple of years later, the stock
came around,'' he laments. ``Went up to like $50, and now it's
about $15. I had a $2.75 strike price _ about a million bucks of
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he refuses to give up. Now Perhaes is placing all bets on
digital broadcaster Wavexpress, which plans to go public in about a
year. (Ironically, it's co-owned by Wave Systems.) Perhaes has a
huge number of options, and while the strike price hasn't been set,
he's exhilarated. ``This is the last job I am ever going to have.
It is,'' he says. ``I am just not going to strike out a third
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
