<HEADLINE>
HOW IT'S DECIDED WHO CAN BE IN THE DEBATES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How can I contact the Commission on Presidential Debates to
register my opinion about including third-party candidates in the
debates?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.T., Ocean City, Md.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Executive Director Janet Brown, Commission on
Presidential Debates, 1200 New Hampshire Ave. N.W., Box 445,
Washington, DC 20036 or call (202) 872-1020.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Presidential Debates, a not-for-profit group
formed in 1987 to produce and sponsor presidential and vice
presidential debates, determines which candidates are eligible to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible this election year, a candidate must average at
least 15 percent support in five polls: ABC News/Washington Post,
CBS News/New York Times, NBC News/Wall Street Journal, CNN/USA
Today/Gallup and Fox News/Opinion Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Under current polling totals, only Vice President Al Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush would be invited to the presidential debate.
Ralph Nader and Pat Buchanan, the third-party candidates included
most often in polls, average less than 5 percent support each.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I enjoy the computer versions of mah jongg. Where can I buy a
real tile set?
</P>
<P>
   _ V.K., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: The retailer Mah Jongg Maven in Augusta, Ga., sells sets,
tiles, racks and jewelry devoted to the game.
</P>
<P>
   For a free brochure about the company's products, call (888)
860-1981 or write to Mah Jongg Maven, 404 Fifth St., Suite 100,
Augusta, GA 30901. You can also shop online at
www.mahjonggmaven.com.
</P>
<P>
   One thing to note when buying a set is the number of tiles it
contains. ``If you want to play American rules, you need an
American-style mah jongg set: 152 tiles,'' recommends Tom Sloper,
developer of Activision's ``Shanghai'' mah jongg game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the standard 136 suit tiles and dragons and
winds, you need eight Flowers/seasons and eight jokers, four racks,
and chips.'' Activision publishes a Web site for players at
www.activision.com/games/shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the baby on the cover of the Nirvana album
``Nevermind?''
</P>
<P>
   _ A.M., Grapevine, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The child swimming underwater is Spencer Elden, who was 4
months old at the time of the photo shoot, according to
``Entertainment Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   Elden was one of five infants hired by underwater photo
specialist Kirk Weddle, who set up a studio in a Los Angeles
swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   To get him to make a face, an assistant blew air bubbles at
Elden after he was tossed in the pool. ``Spencer was like, `Whoa,
what was that?' '' his father, Rick Elden, a film prop maker, told
``EW.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevermind,'' released in 1991, sold more than 3 million
copies. Elden earned $250.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
