<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON AREA FARM SHARES ITS HARVEST WITH THE NEEDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of Texas farmers are in a tough spot this year _ there
hasn't been enough rain to settle the dust, let alone raise a crop
_ but on one small pasture in southeast Texas enough surplus food
is being produced to help feed the needy throughout the state and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sent a half-a-truck-load to Fort Worth,'' said Becky
Finch of Share The Harvest in Brazoria County. ``That's about
22,500 pounds of rice. We also sent some to Austin and San Antonio.
That's what we try to do: Take care of people in our area first,
then the rest of Texas. If we've got some left, we reach out as far
as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the 58-acre rice pasture southeast of Houston near
Danbury will produce about 350,000 pounds of rice to be distributed
to food banks all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The pasture is donated, the cultivation is donated, and so is
the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Share The Harvest, a foundation established by Garret
Farms _ the local company that provides much of the volunteer labor
and equipment for the pasture _ said they joined with other local
farmers last year to donate ]one and a half million pounds of rice.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, the office manager at Garrett Farms, and Share The
Harvest, said that about 60 percent of the donated rice crop is
going to the Houston Food Bank, the surplus will reach as far as
Africa and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Brazoria County farms have joined in the harvest
again this year. Mowery Farms of Rosharon is among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just for a great cause,'' owner Curt Mowery told The
Facts, a Brazoria County newspaper. ``We've been pretty fortunate
the past two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mowery couldn't participate last year, he didn't get his own
harvest finished in time, but this year he arrived early and
brought some neighboring farmers with him.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko Garrett, who owns Garrett Farms, has always donated a part
of his harvest to charity, Finch said, but Share The Harvest has
made collection and distribution more organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Jacko's idea from a long time ago,'' she said. ``Now
we're trying to come up with some other ideas as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other ideas is a plan to swap some of the surplus rice
for other crops. ``We'd like to get together with farmers around
the country and maybe swap a truck load of rice for a truck load of
pinto beans,'' Finch said. ``You can feed a lot of people with rice
and beans. We just need to get the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   Finch said she is certain that Texas has enough caring people to
help feed the needy. Farmers throughout Texas have responded,
despite their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you mention the donations to them, they ask what
they can do,'' she said. ``We've even had some high school kids get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Finch said that several local high school students were working
for Garrett Farms. They were helping with the rice harvests in
other fields.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to harvest in the donated field, however, they
all punched out on their time cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us they saw everyone else donating their time and
equipment to harvest in that one field,'' Finch said. ``They said
they wanted to do something, too. So they punched out and went off
the clock before they started working in the pasture.''
</P>
<P>
   Finch said that several corporate donors have been involved in
the program. Chemical companies have provided the fertilizer and a
local trucker has furnished transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to deliver the crop off of this 58-acre
pasture to the food banks with little or no charge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some costs involved. Bags, palettes and the
milling process takes money, and Finch said Share The Harvest is
hoping that people who are not farmers, will get involved by
offering cash donations.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write Share The Harvest Foundation,
P.O.Box 603, Danbury, 77534. Or, call Share The Harvest at (979)
922-8405.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
