<HEADER>
A9123 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-GORE-NEWHOUSE &LR;      08-22 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-GORE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE THE UNHAPPY WARRIOR FINALLY FINDS A SHTICK THAT STICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 22, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore was down so far in the polls that his campaign resembled
one of those media vigils for a tot that tumbled down a well. Now
he beats George W. Bush to a thin red film on the floor in every
poll. How did this happen, exactly?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the convention that no one watched? Perhaps it was his
famous ``I will not let you down'' speech, which certainly set him
apart from those pols who promise to thwart your trust at every
opportunity. Maybe it was the big smooch he dealt the Tipper -- aw,
the big lug loves her! Let's give him control of domestic policy
and our nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the news, leaked on Gore's night of triumph, that
the reanimated corpse of Ken Starr had clawed its way from the
grave and announced it might indict Clinton. Everyone was outraged.
Outraged! Have the Republicans no shame? Politics as usual!
Partisanship! Sex-crazed vindictive hypocritical
work-of-the-American-people-thwarting lunatic zealots!
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was a Democrat-appointed judge who made the leak,
but that amplification appeared on page 28Z in most papers, next to
the kindergarten kickball tourney scores. Damage was done: Elect
Bush, and people might actually get indicted for wrongdoing. Can't
have that.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's bump might be due to all of this. None of it. Maybe the
bounce is exaggerated. Perhaps it's underestimated. What's clear is
that Gore has found his voice, his style, a shtick that sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Clintonesque-But-Moral-Gore didn't work. Cyber-Gore didn't work.
Eco-Gore still horrifies most -- there's residual suspicion that
Gore would shed the suitcoat, smear himself with peat and spend his
term squatting over a fire roasting gourds and praying for the
Earth Goddess to forgive her hairless parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's now the Unhappy Warrior, railing against the Corporations
and Special Interests. He slam Big Drugs for big profits. He
fastens his jaws on the glutes of Big Oil, which has the fabulous
gall to pass along the cost of government mandates. Big Tobacco,
Big Media, Big Liquor -- Gore demonizes them until the CEOs
themselves expect to see cloven hooves when they take off their
shoes. Why? Because they all make Obscene Profits.
</P>
<P>
   Odd: Let Big Government overtax you and rack up Obscene
Surpluses, and it's cause for a parade.
</P>
<P>
   Those surpluses, however, need spending, and Gore's the man to
do it. Bush, too. No matter who's elected, we'll have a
prescription drug benefit. It's hard to oppose the thing now
without sounding as if you favor seniors keeling over into their
evening mush. Opponents of the prescription-drug benefit program
call it the ``Viagra for Larry King'' concept. They figure that the
image of a capering priapic King wearing naught but suspenders,
glasses and a wanton grin is enough to make people vote no. If not
put out their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But most people will vote yes on drugs for seniors, because
everyone envisions a kindly Grandma with a cat on her lap and a pie
on the sill, impoverished by Pfitzer's usurious pricing strategy
for their anti-lumbago pills. Can't we spend a little of the
surplus on Grandma?
</P>
<P>
   It's odd: We can spend the surplus on drugs for the old. We can
spend it on Medicare, and Social Security, and smaller class sizes,
and alternative energy credits, and targeted tax cuts to provide
gas subsidies for gay former Scout leaders with smoking-related
illnesses who drive pregnant teens to the Planned Parenthood
clinic. We can spend the entire surplus nine times over, and
nothing bad will happen. But pass George Bush's tax cuts, and the
economy collapses into the Dark Ages and everyone gets paid in
piglets and seed corn.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work for Gore? Well, it gets the crowd excited. You can
sense Gore's righteous wrath when he's slamming the HMOs. It galls
him that people's access to medical care should be denied by some
HMO bean-counter.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting access and denying care should be the job of a
GOVERNMENT bean-counter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
