</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Whether or not an investigation
proves that the Kursk was sunk by a collision with a foreign
submarine, or by a misfired torpedo or a World War II mine, the
lasting image from the surface of the Barents Sea will be the
hapless attempts by otherwise heroic Russian rescuers to reach the
Kursk's escape hatch in outdated mini-subs powered by batteries too
old to hold a charge. A news analysis, wrapping in the latest
developments, by Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TWA-CRASH (Washington) _ Trying to discredit the conspiracy
theorists who say a bomb or missile brought down TWA Flight 800
four years ago, government investigators said Tuesday the crash
that killed 230 people was nothing more or less than a terrible
accident. The breakup of the Boeing 747 off the coast of Long
Island was caused by an explosion of fuel vapors in the center wing
tank, most likely because of an electrical short, National
Transportation Safety Board officials said. (Early summary) By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (St. Louis, Ill.) _ Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday moved to
defend his sweeping tax cut proposal as both responsible and easily
affordable in light of federal surplus projections, tossing around
figures to show that his budget plan would not require any slashing
of government spending. ``I've got to do a better job of making it
clear,'' Bush told reporters in a surprising admission aboard his
campaign plane. The remark came just one day after Vice President
Al Gore, suddenly resurgent in the polls, detailed his own
suggested tax cuts, which were less than half the size of the Texas
governor's. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT10.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MILITARY (Washington) _ Ever since President Clinton
appointed him in 1996 as the only Republican in a Democratic
Cabinet, Secretary of Defense William Cohen has often claimed he
represents the bipartisanship needed to manage matters of national
security. Now Cohen is at the center of a highly partisan debate
over the state of the American military. And the debate has left
him in a highly unusual position: defending the administration, on
one hand, while at least indirectly underscoring some of the
Republican criticisms leveled against it. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT8, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Washington) _ Reassured by evidence that wage and
price increases remain under control despite robust economic
growth, the Federal Reserve voted to leave interest rates unchanged
but warned that it could resume tightening monetary policy later in
the year if inflation creeps up. The decision seemed intended to
give the Fed more time to assess whether its campaign of rate
increases over the last year is slowing the economy to a rate that
would keep inflation in check. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI-SAFETY (Tokyo) _ The Mitsubishi Motors Corp.
acknowledged that it had systematically concealed customer
complaints about tens of thousands of defective automobiles over
the last three decades. The admission by Mitsubishi, Japan's No. 4
automaker, came a month after its top executive had denied
allegations that it had covered up repeated instances of problems
that included faulty gas tanks, gas caps, clutches, crankshafts and
brakes. As part of the admission, the company announced recalls
based on defects found in 88,000 cars and trucks, adding to a
recall of 532,000 vehicles announced last month. The recalls
include 50,000 vehicles exported to the United States. By Miki
Tanikawa.
</P>
