The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, August 27, 2000. If you have questions about stories, call
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECTION COVER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAUSCHENBERG-ART (Captiva, Fla.) - For his high school
graduation present, Robert Rauschenberg wanted a ready-made shirt,
his first. A decade or so later he made history with assemblages of
junk; sculptures and music boxes made of packing crates, rocks and
rope, and red paintings like ``Yoicks'' sewn from fabric strips.
Art sometimes has its roots in odd places, no? At 74, he is also an
American institution, the paradoxical fact of an anti-orthodox
career. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-TELENOVELLAS (Rio de Janeiro) _ When a television serial
about an 18th-century courtesan went off the air here two years
ago, few at the struggling network that had produced the drama,
called ``Xica da Silva,'' expected it to have much of an afterlife.
But then 150 episodes were dubbed into Spanish and sold to a dozen
other countries in Latin America, where the series quickly went on
to become a ratings phenomenon everywhere it was broadcast. Now the
United States, or at least the growing portion of it that watches
Spanish-language television, has succumbed to the same spell. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSICALS-THEATER (Undated) _ If the 2000-01 Broadway season has
any unifying theme right now, it might be the youthful tilt in the
range of ages among the composers and lyricists whose work will
soon be on view. A look at the resurgence of youth in American
musical theater. By Barry Singer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIJINSKY-DANCE (Undated) _ Just over 50 years after his death in
London on April 8, 1950, events on three continents reaffirm the
apparently boundless fascination with the legendary Polish-Russian
dancer-choreographer Vaslav Nijinsky, whose brief career
(1907-1917) ended at 29 with mental illness that gripped him the
rest of his 61 years. The most comprehensive Nijinsky exhibition
ever assembled began touring European museums in March,
Nijinsky-themed stage plays ran this winter and spring in Tokyo,
London and Scottsdale, Ariz., and in May, for the first time, the
Royal Ballet performed ``L'Apres-Midi d'un Faune,'' his 1912 debut
work, and a controversial re-creation of his 1913 ``Jeux.'' The
never-ending Nijinsky season continued on July 2 when the Hamburg
Ballet gave the premiere of John Neumeier's homage, ``Nijinsky.''
By Daniel Gesmer.
</P>
<P>
   BALLET-DANCE (Undated) _ Today's ballet world has two poles, and
both are in danger of freezing over. Plotless, or abstract, ballets
are at one pole; narrative ballets are at the other. By Jack
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DVD-MOVIES (Los Angeles) _ Occupying two sides of a
high-capacity disc called an 18 (for 18 gigabytes), ``Superman''
joins a fast-growing breed of fully loaded special editions that
stand stacked up like jumbo jets on fall and winter release
schedules. As demand increases, studios are taking more care to
rummage their archives and, as is the case with ``Superman,''
putting a level of effort into producing their major DVD's that in
some ways emulates the kind of attention directors themselves give
to their films. What viewers get out of this depends on their
degree of interest, of course, but even as amusements the
supplements reveal much about filmmaking. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   TAVERNIER-FILM (Paris) _ Bertrand Tavernier's latest film did
not begin with the ``big idea'' of denouncing poverty and
unemployment hidden behind France's stolidly bourgeois facade.
Rather, its genesis was an anecdote heard one evening over dinner
with his 33-year-old daughter, Tiffany, and her husband, a poet who
had taught in public schools in run-down communities. ``Dominique
told the story of a woman who couldn't afford the monthly
contribution to her children's school because she needed the 30
francs'' _ $4.50 _ ``for food,'' Tavernier, 59, recalled. ``From
this conversation, then, was born ``Ca Commence Aujourd'hui,'' or
``It All Starts Today,'' Tavernier's 19th feature film which opens
Sept. 8. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   DARK-DAYS-FILM (Undated) _ In 1994, a scruffy pod of homeless
people were sitting around a fire in the dank, dark Amtrak tunnel
they lived in underneath Manhattan when a thin, animated man named
Ralph had an idea. ``Someone should be making a film about this
stuff,'' he said. Marc Singer still finds it hard to believe that
an idle remark inspired such an odyssey that led a 20-year-old who
had never picked up a camera to live underground himself, enlist
his fellow outcasts as his crew and put together ``Dark Days,'' a
documentary that won three awards at this year's Sundance Film
Festival. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOULEZ-SALZBURG-MUSIC (Salzburg, Austria) - Pierre Boulez's
``Structures,'' Book 2, for two pianos is music of uncompromising
complexity. At the time of its premiere, in 1961, the work
galvanized composers in the avant-garde and in academic circles. No
one, including Boulez, could have thought it would reach outside to
mainstream audiences. So it must have been deeply satisfying for
Boulez when, at the conclusion of the third of four recent concerts
at the Salzburg Festival in honor of his 75th birthday, an audience
that nearly filled the 1,500-seat Felsenreitschule burst into
cheers after hearing a brilliant performance of that very work, the
gnarly ``Structures,'' Book 2. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   BAYREUTH-MUSIC (Bayreuth, Germany) _ On the morning of
`Goetterdaemmerung,'' Wolfgang Wagner, 80 years old and a grandson
of the man who composed it, was fighting off a twilight of his own.
Wagner is no god. Small, combative, prolix and not without humor,
he sparred with a press corps eager to know more about the star
defections and family squabbles that have encroached on his 25-year
regime here. Founded 124 years ago by Richard Wagner, the Bayreuth
Festival is under siege from several directions. By Bernard
Holland.
</P>
<P>
   WEBERN-MUSIC (Undated) _ The complete recording of Anton
Webern's output just released by Deutsche Grammophon does very much
more than refute old and sterile arguments against serialism. But
that it does, and overwhelmingly. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ACCIDENTAL-ART (New York) _ When Jackson Pollock first lifted
his brush from the canvas and allowed paint to drip in tangled
skeins across the surface, or Jean Arp and Marcel Duchamp began to
experiment with chance procedures, they sought in the accidental
and unpredictable the means to shatter the stale conventions of art
making. So, too, surrealists like Andre Masson and Juan Miro, who
allowed their pens to wander over the page in the belief that they
would discover in those doodles the ghosts of their own repressed
imaginations. What these artists _ all currently featured at the
Museum of Modern Art as part of the show ``Making Choices'' _ hoped
to attain was freedom, from the past, from academic formulas and
the random act was their declaration of independence. By Miles
Unger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-PHOTOGRAPHY (Undated) _ Since the 19th century, Maine has
represented an accessible wilderness: America's idea of itself.
Photographers played an important part in inventing this idea of
Maine, though their role is less well-known than that of writers
and painters. With an ambitious, two-part survey, ``Photographing
Maine: 1840-2000,'' the Maine Coast Artists/Center for Contemporary
Maine Art documents the themes and variations of photographers'
rich and complex reactions to this landscape and its inhabitants.
By Deborah Weisgall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-SPACES-ARCHITECTURE (Undated)) _ Horror vacuui _ fear of
emptiness _ is the driving force in contemporary American taste.
Along with the commercial interests that exploit this fear, it is
the major factor now shaping attitudes toward public spaces, urban
centers and even suburban sprawl. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH-HOUSES-ARCHITECTURE (Stockholm) _ Some people collect
Hula Hoops, cookie jars, Japanese screens or even racing cars; Lars
Sjoberg collects houses. What began as a childhood fancy, became a
reality when he needed places to live and evolved into a compulsion
when he saw old houses about to be torn down. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS, PAPERBACKS and BESTSELLERS-CHILDREN have all moved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Coded `t') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OREGON-BLUEMOUNTAINS (Undated) _ Driving at leisure
through the lovely Blue Mountains of Oregon. By Denise Fainberg.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OREGON-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ The Pendleton Round-Up in
Oregon has been the biggest, rowdiest four-day rodeo anywhere for
90 years. By Susan G. Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VIETNAM (Hanoi) _ Twenty-five years after the end of the
Vietnam War and a month after the United States completed an
historic trade agreement with its former enemy, tour organizers in
both countries hope that American travelers will finally start to
make their way to Vietnam in large numbers. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Home delivery, for foreign
currency ordered on the Web. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers about prehistoric
caves in France; finding accommodations in Scottish castles; tours
of Belize and Guatemala. By Suzanne MacNeille.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: The opening of the American
Discovery Trail, the first coast-to-coast, nonmotorized trail, will
be celebrated on September 2 in San Francisco, at Crissy Field in
the Presidio. The 6,356-mile trail runs from Cape Henlopen State
Park in Delaware to Limantour Beach in Point Reyes National
Seashore, about 45 miles north of San Francisco. In the Midwest, it
splits into two branches _ a northern route through Indiana,
Illinois, Iowa and Nebraska, and a southern route through Indiana,
Illinois, Missouri and Kansas. All told, it traverses 15 states and
the District of Columbia. Along its route, the trail passes through
hundreds of small towns and urban centers like Kansas City, Denver
and Cincinnati, and it leads to 14 national parks, 16 national
forests and 10,000 sites of historic, cultural and natural
significance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
