<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS RULE OUT SABOTAGE IN TWA FLIGHT 800 CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to discredit the conspiracy theorists who
say a bomb or missile brought down TWA Flight 800 four years ago,
government investigators said Tuesday that the crash that killed
230 people was nothing more or less than a terrible accident.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of the Boeing 747 off the coast of Long Island, New
York, on the evening of July 17, 1996, was caused by an explosion
of fuel vapors in the center wing tank, most likely because of an
electrical short, National Transportation Safety Board officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   That conclusion, reiterated Tuesday at the start of a two-day
session as the safety agency prepares its final report on the
tragedy, was anticlimactic and totally expected. Investigators have
been saying much the same thing for more than three years, since
the original theories of sabotage began to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that our investigation confirmed that the
fuel-air vapor in the center wing tank was flammable at the time of
the accident,'' Bernard Loeb, director of aviation safety for the
safety board, said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that an explosion in that center tank _ a space roughly
the size of a two-car garage _ was ``more than capable of
generating the pressure'' needed to break up the enormous aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The board chairman, Jim Hall, said the crash ``graphically
demonstrated that, even in one of the safest transportation systems
in the world, things can go horribly wrong.'' He added, ``It should
stand as a reminder to us all of the need for diligence and
aggressive action in identifying and eliminating potential safety
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the crash, a number of measures to reduce the chance of
electrical shorts have been put into effect, the officials said,
and still more will be tried. Detailed findings of the Flight 800
investigation are available on the agency's Web site: www.ntsb.gov
</P>
<P>
   Hall said it was perfectly understandable that many people
initially thought a bomb or missile had knocked the jet from the
sky. That summer there was a bomb explosion at the Olympic Games in
Atlanta, and trials of those accused in the 1993 World Trade Center
bombing were under way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Federal Bureau of Investigation worked with the
safety board for more than a year before concluding in November
1997 that there was no evidence of a criminal act.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The remains of all 230 victims were recovered, as was more than
95 percent of the aircraft, Hall noted. Examination of the bodies
and of the aircraft parts showed no telltale signs of a bomb or
missile, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses reported seeing a ``streak of light'' in the sky
shortly before 9 p.m. the night of the crash, prompting some people
to wonder if a missile had been shot toward the 747. There was
speculation later that the streak might have been fuel burning as
the plane broke apart.
</P>
<P>
   Hall asserted that the most irresponsible conspiracy theorists
have ``their own agendas'' and that they ``do a disservice to us
all _ but most especially to you, the TWA 800 families, who have
suffered so much in this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He tacitly acknowledged that theories of various kinds will
persist and that his agency has been urged to look for criminals.
``Our people are aviators, engineers and scientists, some of the
very best in the world,'' he said. ``They are not criminal
investigators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
