<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JACQUES OF ALL TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sauvignon blanc, the most versatile of white wines, comes in
many guises. It can be an aperitif, light, sharp and refreshing; it
can be a dinner wine with good body and lovely texture. It can be a
magnificent, naturally sweet dessert wine, either on its own or, as
it is in Sauternes, artfully blended with grapes like semillon and
muscadelle.
</P>
<P>
   A self-effacing grape, it often hides under other names. All
Bordeaux white wines, both dry and sweet, use some sauvignon blanc;
the rare Pavillon Blanc of Chateau Margaux is 100 percent sauvignon
blanc, and the white of Chateau Haut-Brion is usually two-thirds
semillon and a third sauvignon blanc.
</P>
<P>
   In the Graves region of Bordeaux, sauvignon blanc is the
predominant white grape. Once it was routinely blended with
semillon, a grape that makes a softer, honeyed style of wine, a
style that was ignored by most of the world's wine markets. In
recent years, sauvignon blanc has become more dominant in the
Graves; the wines are fresher and more vibrant, and they have
restored Bordeaux's reputation for good white wines.
</P>
<P>
   In the Loire Valley, along with chenin blanc, melon de Bourgogne
(which is the grape of Muscadet) and gros plant, sauvignon blanc
produces some of the world's best-known white wines. Sancerre is
entirely sauvignon blanc, as are Pouilly-Fume and a host of wines
from smaller communities like Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Cloudy Bay in the early 1990s, sauvignon blanc
has become New Zealand's best-known wine. South Africa, too, has
begun to produce top sauvignon blancs, beginning with Mulderbosch
and Neil Ellis' Groenkloof Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, sauvignon blanc has followed two paths. The
most successful American sauvignon blancs are, to me anyway,
fashioned in the Bordeaux style _ the older Bordeaux style, which
emphasizes softness and fullness and plays down the more acidic,
vegetal style of Sancerre and Pouilly-Fume.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known American sauvignon blanc goes under a different
name. Robert Mondavi makes it and it's called fume blanc. One of
Mondavi's signal achievements was the revival of sauvignon blanc in
California. In the mid-1960s, he took what had been a sugary, bland
wine with no varietal character, fermented it completely until it
was dry, aged it in oak and then gave it its new name. A name, by
the way, that he never registered, so that anyone could use it.
When he started working with the grape, there were about 700 acres
of it in California; now there are well over 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the Mondavi sauvignon blanc line is the Reserve Fume
Blanc made from grapes from his most famous vineyard, To-Kalon in
Oakville, Calif. All sauvignon blanc except for about 6 percent
semillon, the wine is barrel-fermented and aged for about a year in
French oak. The result is a complex wine with intense flavors and a
rich texture, full-bodied for a sauvignon blanc and with a long
finish.
</P>
<P>
   It is a beautiful wine, diametrically opposed to what I like in
a sauvignon blanc, which is lightness, no oak and plenty of vibrant
acidity. I recently tasted six Mondavi sauvignon blancs, including
three from California and three from Chile. Tasted blind, it turned
out that my favorite was from the Mondavi ``Coastal'' group because
it had at least some of the herbaceous characteristics of the wines
from the Loire, New Zealand and South Africa but from hardly anyone
in California.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a question of right and wrong, or of good and bad. Two
distinct styles of sauvignon blanc have emerged and each has its
passionate advocates. To me, the lighter, herbaceous style is
perfect with broiled fish and oysters, while the fuller California
style is best savored as a sipping wine on a warm summer afternoon.
But others prefer the more acidic style as an aperitif and the
heavier, oakier style with food.
</P>
<P>
   The oaked versions, like Mondavi's fume blanc, Caymus Vineyards'
Conundrum and Dry Creek Vineyards fume blanc, match well with
almost any dish that normally calls for chardonnay. The more acidic
versions, like the French and New Zealand wines, will enhance most
kinds of seafood and make perfect companions for a variety of
cheeses. Red wine and cheese is the traditional combination. But
many red wines are overwhelmed by sharp or pungent cheeses. Not so
sauvignon blanc, particularly when matched with goat cheese. Loire
goat cheeses like crottin de Chavignol seem to have been invented
to go with the local white wines.
</P>
<P>
   Sancerre and Pouilly-Fume are easy to find in the United States,
but domestic sauvignon blancs with the same mineral, herbaceous
elements are in short supply. Even so, there are sauvignon blancs
out there that display good varietal character. Philip Togni, in
the Napa Valley, makes a bone-dry version; others to look for
include J. Rochioli, in the Russian River area of Sonoma; Matanzas
Creek in Sonoma; Brander Vineyard in Los Olivos; St. Supery in the
Napa Valley; and Navarro Vineyards, in the Anderson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In California, there are as many interpretations of the
sauvignon blanc theme as there are wineries producing it. The trick
is to find one you like. If nothing suits your fancy, do join me in
the Loire Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
