<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S ITALIAN ACCENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The triumph of French grapes in California has been
so complete that cabernet sauvignon, chardonnay and the rest seem
as integral to the state as San Francisco fog and Malibu mud. When
California winemakers want to turn to exotica, they experiment with
Italian grapes, like sangiovese or barbera.
</P>
<P>
   By historical standards, at least, the French grapes should have
been the interlopers. Italian immigrants started many of
California's early winemaking dynasties, and their names live on
today: Martini, Gallo, Mondavi, Foppiano and Pedroncelli, to
mention a few. Yet, when the industry came of age its focus was
almost wholly on French grapes, perhaps because Italian wines were
held in such low critical esteem.
</P>
<P>
   But appreciation for Italian wines has risen in the last 25
years, around the world and in California. Barbera, the most widely
planted grape in the Piedmont, has most often been used in
California as an anonymous blending grape. Now it is being grown
more seriously and bottled on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Sangiovese, the prime grape of Chianti, took up only 186 acres
in the whole state in 1990. By 1997, though, that figure had risen
to almost 2,500 acres, the highest rate of increase of any red
grape in that period, according to ``California Wine,'' by James
Laube (Wine Spectator Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Just because Californians have planted sangiovese grapes it
doesn't mean they are producing Chianti. Most of the vines are
young and will need years before they can produce top-quality
grapes. Just as it has taken Californians decades to figure out how
and where to grow pinot noir, it may take some time to learn how to
treat sangiovese.
</P>
<P>
   While California sangioveses can vary widely, from soft, fruity
mouthfuls to oaky blasts of tannin, I found many to be enjoyable,
though overpriced, and very good with food. Some of the best
versions are made in small quantities. Bruno d'Alfonso, the
winemaker for Sanford Winery in Santa Barbara County, makes the
excellent Di Bruno as a side project. It is sold in a few stores,
but is more likely to turn up in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Italians have been experimenting with nontraditional
blends of grapes to create the wines known as super-Tuscans, so
have the Californians. Brewer-Clifton, which makes fine pinot noirs
and chardonnays, makes a super-concentrated blend of sangiovese and
merlot under the Palmina label, while La Famiglia, Robert Mondavi's
label for Italian varietals, recently released its 1997 Colmera, 80
percent sangiovese blended with five other grapes. It, too, is
impressive, and will be even more so after it ages a few years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DI BRUNO , SANTA BARBARA COUNTY , STOLPMAN VINEYARD 1998 $21 &QL; 
Rich and concentrated, full of earthy fruit and dusty tannins.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BABCOCK VINEYARDS, ELEVEN OAKS, SANTA YNEZ VALLEY 1995 $23 &QL; 
Aromas of tar, dried oranges and rose petals; juicy, dense
flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWANSON , NAPA VALLEY 1997 $28 &QL; 
Sweet aromas, fruity with firm tannins.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FLORA SPRINGS , NAPA VALLEY 1998 $18 &QL; 
Spicy aromas, with fruit and a spine of acidity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GALLO -SONOMA, ALEXANDER VALLEY, BARRELLI CREEK VINEYARDS 1997
$17 &QL; 
Dusky and earthy, chocolate aroma with mouth-filling tannins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RABBIT RIDGE, CONIGLIO SELEZIONE, SONOMA COUNTY 1997 $16 &QL; 
Orange and smoke aromas, full of fruit but not much depth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
