u f BC-EXTREME-TELECOMMUTERS     08-22 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-TELECOMMUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EXTREME TELECOMMUTERS, THE OFFICE CAN BE FOUND ON THE OPEN
ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Sid and Kristanne Heaton, ``manifest destiny'' first called
in spring 1997. Recently engaged, the couple discovered that they
had an entire unplanned summer before she was to begin a master's
program at the University of Washington. Hoping to see more of the
United States and Canada, the couple hopped into their Volkswagen
camper for three months of touring, all while he telecommuted full
time as a technical writer for a California software company.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six states, two provinces and a wedding later, the couple
took their lust for working-while-traveling to Europe, in March
1999, after she was accepted in an art history program in Rome.
Over the next 12 months, Heaton continued to telecommute for his
employer. But the Heatons also managed to live in five countries,
see seven others and post their travels online at
www.officeodyssey.com.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of the extreme telecommuter, a term that
Heaton says he coined to describe people like himself who hold down
full-time salaried positions, complete with benefits, and yet are
no ordinary 9-to-5, cubicle-inhabiting drones. The goal of an
extreme telecommuter, he says, is to happily blur the line between
working and having an adventure, whether it is touring Europe,
scaling a mountain or pedaling a recumbent bike across the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Extreme telecommuters are not bleary-eyed corporate road
warriors nor are they garden-variety telecommuters who work from
home. Nevertheless, they maintain they are no less dedicated to
their jobs. Heaton, for example, said that he had managed to get
bonuses and raises as an extreme telecommuter.
</P>
<P>
   Such telecommuters are still rare. According to workplace
experts, few jobs _ let alone employers _ lend themselves to such
potentially chaotic mobility. Still, some experts suspect that the
ranks of extreme telecommuters may slowly swell the next few years,
especially if the labor market remains tight and mobile computing
and wireless technology continue to bolt along.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of thing that so many people go through life
saying _ if only I had followed my wanderlust,'' said Gil Gordon of
Monmouth Junction, N.J., a telecommuting consultant who counsels
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fuchs is certainly following his impulse to travel.
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs, a former Time Warner executive, is now the chairman of
Autobytel.com, an online auto retailer based in Irvine, Calif. But
he is also the interim chief executive of MyTurn.com, an e-commerce
products and services company in Alameda, Calif. Fuchs has an
office in New York but often works elsewhere _ Brazil, New Guinea
or, every February, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is a real passion,'' he said. ``I was at Time for 20
years, and when I left, I told myself I would have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments do not surprise Tom Miller, vice president for
Internet strategies at Cyber Dialogue, a technology research firm
in Manhattan. ``When we first studied telecommuting in 1984, it was
a pretty structured thing,'' Miller said. ``But telecommuting has
unfolded in much more of a guerrilla warfare fashion, driven more
by individual, rather than corporate, needs.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is one company that says it is becoming increasingly open
to variations on traditional telecommuting. ``The shift we're
seeing is one where work becomes much more integrated into the
fabric of your life, but in a way that's manageable,'' said Brad
Allenby, who oversees the company's so-called telework efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Allenby said that 25 percent of his company's managers worked
from outside the office one or more times a week, and 10 percent
worked from virtual offices, at home or elsewhere. ``I've got a
manager who reports directly to me _ she's in a virtual office in
Ohio _ but she has family in Las Vegas,'' he said. ``Do I care if
she's in a cafe in Paris? No, I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Berg appreciates that kind of latitude and has adopted
what could be considered a subset of extreme telecommuting. She
lives in Bethesda, Md., but works as a computer programmer and data
processor for a public opinion polling company in Colorado. Every
six weeks, Berg hits the road for a week with her
four-and-a-half-pound notebook computer and cell phone to visit a
large network of college friends who live as far away as
California.
</P>
<P>
   Still, extreme telecommuting is not always one happy road trip.
Phil Montero, an independent consultant in North Andover, Mass.,
who trains mobile workers (his Web site is
www.youcanworkfromanywhere.com), estimates that only about a third
of employers give their mobile telecommuters any training to work
outside of the office, and that only half of those workers have
thorough training in the technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Gail Martin, executive director of the International
Telework Association and Council, says extreme telecommuting can
also raise potentially confounding liability issues. What happens,
she asks, if a telecommuter falls while mountain climbing or bike
riding? Also, who is responsible for the equipment and the security
of information?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the drawbacks, extreme telecommuters are thrilled with
their choices.
</P>
<P>
   The Heatons, for example, estimate that in their two
telecommuting sojourns they managed to do more traveling than they
would have in 15 years of conventional vacations, even though it
also meant that Heaton had to endure hardships like sending early
morning e-mails from Polish truck stops and having teleconference
calls from a piazza in Rome. He is now telecommuting from Nevada
City, Calif., a tiny town in the Sierra Nevada foothills. But the
Heatons are thinking of spending the winter in Hawaii. ``We don't
want having a career to get in the way of having a life,'' he said
in an e-mail message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
