<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PERMARITAL-PACTS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERMARITAL-PACTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT GIVES BASEBALL STAR A BREAK ON PREMARITAL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Barry Bonds' wife-to-be didn't need a lawyer to
understand what she was doing when she signed a premarital
agreement in 1988 giving up her right to half his baseball salary,
the California Supreme Court says.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's unanimous ruling was a strong statement in favor of the
binding nature of prenuptial agreements, which have become
increasingly common as divorce rates rise and prospective spouses
look for a way to protect the property they bring into a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   A state Court of Appeal had cast doubt on thousands of such
agreements in California by ruling in the Bonds case that judges
must take a close look at the possibility of coercion in any
premarital agreement in which only one party was represented by an
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's high court said the absence of a lawyer was
``only one of several factors'' to consider in deciding whether the
agreement was voluntary, along with such things as the parties'
understanding of their rights, disclosure of assets and the
pressure placed on each by time and circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of state law, said Chief Justice Ronald George, is ``to
enhance the enforceability of premarital agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he said, before Barry and Sun Bonds married in
1988, she was told by his lawyers that she had the right to her own
attorney. She replied that she didn't need one and showed she knew
that she was waiving her right to community property during the
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   There was substantial evidence to support a San Mateo County
judge's findings that the agreement was voluntary, George said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ``treats people like adults as opposed to little
children,'' said Robert Nachshin, a lawyer for the San Francisco
Giants' star outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   But Sun Bonds' lawyer, Paige Wickland, said the court had
brushed aside the pressures that could be brought to bear on an
unsophisticated spouse-to-be with little awareness of her rights _
for example, giving Sun Bonds a draft of the agreement only a day
before the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ruling, ``we will have more agreements enforced,''
Wickland said. ``Many will be unfair, but this opinion will allow
that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A law professor who has written some of California's family law
statutes was troubled by what the court did not say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was plenty of room for them to interpret the term
`voluntary' to make sure you were not improperly cajoled, persuaded
or ensnared,'' said Professor Carol Bruch of the University of
California at Davis. ``They missed that opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, the court should have declared that
prospective spouses have a legal obligation to treat each other
fairly, a duty that already applies to husbands and wives. Also,
she said, the lawyer for one prospective spouse should be required
to tell the other party, in writing, that their interests may
conflict and that both sides should have their own attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The case illustrates California's ``dreadful law on premarital
agreements,'' which offers fewer protections than unmarried
cohabitants get under case law, Bruch said.
</P>
<P>
   The court also bolstered the validity of premarital agreements
in a second case Monday, ruling 6-1 that couples could agree before
marriage to forgo the right to claim alimony if they divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Courts have traditionally struck down such agreements on the
grounds that they encourage divorce, reasoning adopted by
California's high court as recently as 1973. But a majority, led by
Justice Marvin Baxter, called those rulings out of step with modern
views of marriage, the changing roles of women and the reality that
divorce was frequent.
</P>
<P>
   The cases were the court's first look in many years at
prenuptial agreements. The Bonds case represents the typical
agreement, in which the spouses-to-be forgo the right to community
property _ the equal division of all earnings during the marriage _
and promise to claim only their own separate property at divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds was a young outfielder with the Pittsburgh Pirates
in 1987, making $106,000 a year, when he met his future wife, a
Swedish immigrant who was studying to be a beautician. Both were
23.
</P>
<P>
   The prenuptial agreement was signed the day before their wedding
in February 1988. Barry had two attorneys and a financial adviser;
Sun, whose English was limited, was attended by a Swedish friend.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bond's attorneys said later that they had told Sun Bonds
that they represented their client's interests, that she had the
right to her own lawyer and that the agreement would eliminate her
right to share in his earnings during marriage. Sun Bonds testified
that she had understood none of those things and that she had
signed because Barry Bond's financial adviser told her the wedding
would be canceled if she refused.
</P>
<P>
   When the couple divorced in 1994, Barry Bonds was making $8
million a year with the Giants. Sun Bonds was awarded $10,000 a
month in support for each of their two children and $10,000 a month
in alimony through the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But she also sought to invalidate the prenuptial agreement and
claim a share of his salary.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo County Superior Court Judge Judith Kozloski upheld the
agreement after a non-jury trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
