<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-RACISM-TRIAL-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FORMER EAST GERMANY, A MURDER TRIAL TAKES ON POLITICAL
IMPORTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLE, Germany _ The German widow of an African man killed by
neo-Nazis broke down Tuesday after silently facing the three young
men accused of his murder on the opening day of their trial.
</P>
<P>
   The widow, Angelika Adriano, 43, was ushered from the courtroom
in visible distress after sitting opposite the generally impassive
men for about an hour and hearing a prosecutor charge that they
``assumed that Alberto Adriano could die from their attack, but
their hatred of foreigners made them indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Adriano, a 39-year-old Mozambican, in the eastern
town of Dessau has become a powerful symbol of the virulence of
rightist, anti-immigrant sentiment, particularly among youths in
the former East Germany where unemployment is at twice the level of
the west of the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the trial has assumed a particular political
importance. Germany's chief prosecutor, Kay Nehm, who usually
handles cases of terrorism, has taken a leading role, and Manfred
Puchel, the interior minister of the state of Saxony Anhalt,
Tuesday took the unusual step of issuing a statement calling for
severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without wishing to put the independence of the judiciary into
question, the culprits must feel the full force of the law,''
Puchel said, describing the killing as a ``sad and repugnant
example of what xenophobic views can lead to.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Richter and Frank Miethbauer, both 16, and Enrico
Hilprecht, 24, have been charged with the murder of Adriano, a
meatpacker who had been in Germany for 12 years. They have admitted
attacking Adriano on June 11 and leaving his body in the city park.
He died three days later.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its Nazi past, and the importance it has attached to
a post-war commitment to providing asylum for anyone threatened
because of their race or beliefs, Germany is particularly sensitive
to anti-immigrant violence.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has come under growing
pressure to stop racist provocation and murder. The issue has
abruptly cast a cloud over an administration that had appeared
serene with the opposition Christian Democrats in disarray and
economic reforms giving business a boost.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder embarked this week on a 10-day tour of the east,
urging ``civic courage against rightist extremism.'' But his visit,
after almost two years in office, is widely viewed as belated, and
the weekly Der Spiegel mockingly portrayed the chancellor on its
cover setting out in a safari hat for the unknown desert around
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after unification, the formerly communist part of
Germany still bears deep scars that even more than $400 billion in
federal investments has been unable to heal. Schroeder, having
promised to be the chancellor who made German unity a reality,
appears to have realized that his vow looks empty for now.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp swing away from the Christian Democrats that partly
benefited Schroeder's Social Democrats helped the chancellor get
elected in 1998. With one fifth of the German population, the area
has the power to damage his prospects at the next federal election
in 2002 if nothing changes.
</P>
<P>
   The tour has something of the air of a publicity stunt, but
Schroeder has proved shrewd in gauging the mood of Germans and his
demonstration of concern may bear fruit. He also knows that more
racist violence could cause serious international demage to
Germany's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Schroeder sees himself as the head of a corporation called
Germany that is competing internationally for the best minds,''
commented the Tageszeitung. ``The problem is that certain of those
best minds can only enter the eastern door of the corporation at
high personal risk.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That risk was on display in court Tuesday in the form of three
young men in t-shirts from the region around Dessau where the
collapse of the East German chemical industry has caused
unemployment of over 20 percent. They showed no sign of remorse for
the killing, although Richter appeared ill at ease and occasionally
smiled awkwardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three showed absolutely no contrition,'' said Ronald
Reimann, a lawyer representing Mrs. Adriano. ``That was so shocking
to me and my client that she had to leave the courtroom early.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Adriano, dressed in black, declined to make any comment as
she walked out shortly after the judge ruled that the press and
public, who were initially admitted, should be barred from the
court because two minors are involved.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under Germany's juvenile law, Richter and Miethbauer face a
maximum of 10 years imprisonment. Hilprecht could be imprisoned for
life. The death sentence does not exist in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
