<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEREST RATES TO REMAIN STEADY, FEDERAL RESERVE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reassured by evidence that wage and price increases
remain under control despite robust economic growth, the Federal
Reserve voted Tuesday to leave interest rates unchanged, but warned
that it could resume tightening monetary policy later in the year
if inflation creeps up.
</P>
<P>
   The decision seemed intended to give the Fed more time to assess
whether its campaign of rate increases over the last year is
slowing the economy to a rate that will keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent data have indicated that the expansion of aggregate
demand is moderating toward a pace closer to the rate of growth of
the economy's potential to produce,'' the Federal Open Market
Committee said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the policy-making committee said, ``the risks
continue to be weighted mainly toward conditions that may generate
heightened inflation pressures in the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision meant that the Fed was likely to remain on the
sidelines for the duration of the presidential campaign. The
committee will meet again on Oct. 3, but the Fed has historically
tried to avoid taking any action on interest rates in the weeks
leading up to Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the meeting had been widely expected by analysts
and investors.
</P>
<P>
   The decision left the Fed's benchmark federal funds target rate
on overnight loans between banks at 6.5 percent, where it has been
since May, when the central bank raised the rate by half a
percentage point. The Fed held rates steady at its subsequent
meeting in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also left unchanged, at 6 percent, its discount rate on
loans to banks from the Federal Reserve system.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has pushed the federal funds rate up by 1.75
percentage points since June 1999 in an effort to tamp down
inflation pressures without snuffing out what earlier this year
became the longest business expansion on record.
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a 5.2 percent annual rate in the second
quarter after expanding at a 4.8 percent rate in the first three
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures were well above what most economists believe can
be sustained over the long run without igniting a destabilizing
upward spiral in wages and prices. Yet inflation has edged up only
slightly from very low levels, in large part because the strong
economic growth has been accompanied by a surge in business
efficiency, or productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Even as companies are forced to pay more to attract workers in a
labor market where unemployment is at just 4 percent, or to pay
more for raw materials or equipment, they are managing to cut costs
in other areas or improve efficiency by investing in new
technology.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Within the Fed, there is a long-running debate about whether
productivity improvements can continue to outrun inflation
pressures. In keeping rates unchanged Tuesday, the Fed seemed to be
deferring the issue rather than settling it.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the open market committee noted that economic
indicators are showing ``that more rapid advances in productivity''
have been forcing economists to revise upward their estimates of
how fast the economy can grow without igniting inflation. At the
same time, the committee said, productivity improvements have been
``containing costs and holding down underlying price pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   But the committee suggested that productivity improvements were
not a panacea, and that the combination of very low unemployment
and strong growth still had to be viewed as an inflationary
tinderbox, especially to the degree that strong demand for goods
and services outstripped the economy's ability to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, the statement said, ``remains concerned about the
risk of a continuing gap between the growth of demand and potential
supply at a time when the utilization of the pool of available
workers remains at an unusually high level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
