<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATIN-AMERICA-INTERNE     08-22 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-AMERICA-INTERNET-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA WEB VENTURES RELY ON START-UP CAPITAL FROM ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starmedia, one of the biggest and most successful Internet
companies in Latin America, has branch offices in seven countries
and millions of subscribers throughout the region. But its
headquarters are in New York. Its $450 million in financing came
from investors in the United States. Its stock is listed on the
Nasdaq but not on any exchange in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   El Sitio, another Internet service provider with millions of
Spanish and Portugese-speaking users in Latin America, also raised
money by selling shares on the Nasdaq. But El Sitio is not traded
on any stock exchange in the region where it does most of its
business.
</P>
<P>
   And when Yupi Internet Inc. raised start-up money, it too
bypassed local financial markets in the Latin American countries it
serves, seeking investors in the United States instead. Yupi's
plans for further expansion through a stock offering were postponed
in April when the Nasdaq nosedived, but the company intends to sell
shares to the public only in the United States, not Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet revolution has definitely come to Latin America.
But whether the businesses and jobs spawned by that revolution have
helped the region begin to wean itself from economic dependence on
the United States and other outsiders is considered a matter of
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This keeps us more dependent on outsiders all the time, but
the fault is ours,'' said Paul Singer, a professor of macroenomics
at the University of Sao Paolo. ``It is a deficiency which should
be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Starmedia and El Sitio contend they are not only
truly Latin American but also helping create a pan-Latin market
because Latin America's 500 million people are their main audience.
These companies also say they would not even exist if they had
sought to raise start-up money in the countries where their
customers live and work.
</P>
<P>
   But critics contend that these companies have unwittingly helped
create a kind of cyber colonialism in which the major architects of
the region's Internet access are foreigners, backed by foreign
funds, with offices in foreign lands, just like in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   There is widespread agreement that the remote-control companies
and off-shore financing that made them possible underscores the
persistent weakness of Latin America's financial world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we do have a dependency on the more sophisticated foreign
equity markets,'' said Jorge Errazuriz a partner in Celfin, one of
Chile's largest investment banks, and a member of the board of the
Santiago Stock Exchange. This ``inferior position,'' he said, means
that ``the real initial impulse for developing fiber optics,
telecommunications and the Internet will have to come from the
equity markets up north.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just startup companies that are diverting strength
from the domestic stock exchanges and extending dependency. When an
aggressive international corporation like Telefonica of Spain
purchases phone systems in Argentina, Brazil and Peru, it deprives
local exchanges of some of their biggest companies. After such
acquisitions, the local companies are removed from the domestic
stock exchanges, while Telefonica stock is listed only in Spain and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American exchanges have been hit hard. Over the last
decade, for example, the number of listed domestic companies on
Brazil's main exchange dropped by about 18 percent, from 581 to
478. In Argentina the decline was even steeper, nearly 30 percent,
with local companies on the exchange dipping to 129 from 179.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very troubling to see these markets, which are already
weak, get weakened further,'' said Roger S. Leeds, director of the
Center for International Business and Public Policy at the Paul H.
Nitzke Center for International Studies at Johns Hopkins
University. ``And I don't think that's at all healthy for the
development of the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   From Mexico to Argentina, political leaders in the new Latin
America have promised to improve the standards of living in their
countries by unleashing private enterprise and completely engaging
in the global economy. But while the biggest Latin companies
already have access on either the local or international markets to
the money they need to expand, for small and startup companies _
which generate most new jobs _ the search for funds is often an
impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   Even when local money is available, taking a company public on a
Latin America exchange can be more trouble than it's worth,
considering that most local exchanges lack the pool of capital and
investors willing to take the kind of risks a big regional Internet
company needs to start up. Besides, some require years of operating
experience before a company's stock can be publicly traded, and in
some instances they must show real profits, which few Internet
startups are able to do.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's economic development has always depended heavily
on outsiders. Big corporations _ many of them American _ set up
branch plants in Central and South America that provided jobs and
some growth. But they did little to develop a financial and
economic self sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The newest Latin American companies operate, in effect, the same
way, critics such as Leeds contend. ``There are benefits to the
local economy in terms of jobs and investment,'' he said. ``But the
benefits to the local financial sector are zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to the United States to raise money is not unique to
Latin America, not even for Internet companies. Jesse E. Reyes,
vice president of global product management for Venture Economics,
a private equity research firm, said that Israeli and French
Internet and software companies have raised generous amounts of
capital on Wall Street lately.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, he said, is that they enter the U.S. market not
just to raise money but to sell their products and services here.
Their growth then translates into profit that is repatriated and
re-invested in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin companies that raise money here, by contrast, are not
doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it from the Latin American businessman's point
of view, if they can take American money and get in on the ground
floor of a terrific opportunity, then so what does it matter?''
Reyes said. ``But the sociologists might say, `Isn't this just
another example of American colonialism?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The companies that have successfully crossed borders to raise
funds certainly do not see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our inability to raise capital in Latin America says is
that you cannot shift 500 years of monopoly control and monopoly
orientation all at one time,'' said Fernando Espuelas, chairman of
Starmedia. ``Until very recently, if you wanted to finance a
company in Latin America you got a bank loan, at 30 percent
interest, and for a very short term. Obviously, you'd never be able
to finance an Internet company that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Uruguay and raised in Connecticut, Espuelas realized
early on that Latin American investors, especially wary of risk,
would not support his dream of creating a regional Internet
company.
</P>
<P>
   Basing his company in New York reinforced its identity as truly
regional, Espuelas said, and giving it an English name helped win
over American investors. He knocked on the doors of nearly 50
American venture capitalists. Even hearing a sophisticated New York
financier refer to Latin America as ``that blob there below the Rio
Grande'' did not dissuade him.
</P>
<P>
   With flawless English and a cool confidence, he won over big
backers, including Chase Capital Partners, and raised nearly $100
million in private capital.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May 1999, Starmedia issued its initial public offering
on the Nasdaq, raising $110 million. A subsequent offering in
October raised another $200 million. Starmedia stock, which first
sold for $15, escalated to more than $60 at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   The American investors who bought in early and sold at the peak
enjoyed the kinds of gains that would have gone to Latin investors
had it been possible for Starmedia to go public in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Espuelas said he was aware of the drawbacks but felt the region
could eventually overcome the cycle of dependency.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm already re-investing money into companies in Latin
America,'' he said, though he declined to name his investments.
``Our success is demonstrative of what can happen but also of the
challenges and the road that remains to be travelled.''
</P>
<P>
   While small local companies will continue to struggle,
StarMedia's early success set loose a herd of regional Latin
companies that beat a similar path to the doors of American venture
capitalists
</P>
<P>
   El Sitio, based in Buenos Aires, raised $130 million in its
public offering in December. Impsat Fiber Networks, an Argentine
telecommunciations firm in Wilton Manors, Fla., went public on the
Nasdaq with a $195 million offering in February.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Jofre, chief financial officer of Impsat, said the
lack of adequate financing is one of the most severe limitations
Latin America faces. ``Right now there's simply no significant
amount of local financing available in Latin America,'' Jofre said.
``And this presents a big handicap when compared to most other
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But the global marketplace for capital has its drawbacks too.
Yupi Internet Inc., a Latin American Internet service company in
Miami, planned to go public in the United States last spring. Then
the Nasdaq crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed our initial public offering in January and we were
completing our road show on April 14, the day of the debacle,''
said Oscar Coen, president of Yupi. That day the Nasdaq lost 355
points, its worst ever session to end its worst ever week. Yupi may
have been in some trouble anyway because it was comparatively late
to a market already served by Starmedia, El Sitio and others. But
when the Nasdaq went into a tailspin, the company's executives and
backers changed plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that it was in the best interest of the company to
postpone the IPO until there was a more favorable environment,''
Coen said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other companies, both American and foreign, Yupi's IPO
remains postponed. The delay has meant that Yupi has not expanded
as rapidly as originally planned, Coen said. Yupi won't open shop
in Paraguay or Uruguay, while Chile, he said, ``is borderline.''
Yupi has also pared back its advertising budget.
</P>
<P>
   AOL.Latin America, a spinoff of the original AOL, is also
finding it tough to raise money in the United States. The Latin
venture between AOL and the Cisneros Group of Venezuela originally
filed its initial public offering in January but has been waiting
for the right moment to move ahead. With both Internet companies
and Latin stocks out of fashion right now, few investors have shown
an interest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a long line of Latin American startups is waiting to make
the trip to the United States. ``That is clearly the final
objective for most of us,'' said Marcos E. Galperin, president of
Mercado Libre, an Internet auction site in Latin America. He
launched his company less than a year ago, with American backing.
One of his earliest investors was an American financier who
addressed Galperin's M.B.A. class at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``From day minus one on this project I knew we wanted to get
funding in the U.S.,'' Galperin said. ``For us, it's a big stamp of
approval.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
