r e AUTHORTOMCLANCYONCELEBRI PLOTLINESANDRUNNINGFORPR   08-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 AUTHOR TOM CLANCY ON CELEBRITY, PLOTLINES AND RUNNING FOR (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixteen years after Ronald Reagan's offhand endorsement to
reporters brought attention to his first novel, ``The Hunt for Red
October,'' Tom Clancy remains one of America's most popular
writers.
</P>
<P>
   His 19th book, ``The Bear and the Dragon,'' debuts this week at
the top of every national bestseller list. The latest adventures of
Clancy alter ego Jack Ryan are both lengthy (1,028 pages) and
convoluted (too many subplots to count), in keeping with Clancy's
traditional writing style.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with the Fort Worth Star-Telegram by phone, Clancy, 53,
had lots to say between bites of breakfast, offering rare
reflections on his career and his strengths and weaknesses as a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As ``The Bear and the Dragon'' proves again, you're a master
of complex themes and subplots that somehow all come together in
the end. How do you manage it?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't remember. It's true. I write books and forget about
how I wrote them. I never use outlines. I just start writing. At
some point in each book, I panic. How is all this ever going to
work? It's like having a baby. It's painful, but somehow in the end
it all works out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You spend endless pages in every book explaining things, how
a missile works or a virus spreads. Doesn't each book require
months of research?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I have a big library, and friends in different fields
who can tell me about things. There is no pattern to what I do,
except that for each book I get money and have an agreed-on
delivery date with my publisher. When I do write, I write fast.
``The Bear and the Dragon'' took about six months.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You make it sound painless.
</P>
<P>
   A: It isn't. It's the hardest work I know. People think every
time out the muse kisses me on the ear. I've never met the muse.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some portion of each book seems to be a lecture, about
economics or national defense or what your characters, at least,
see as the interfering, ill-informed media. Is it your goal as an
author to educate readers as well as entertain them?
</P>
<P>
   A: I try to take readers into worlds most readers don't know,
and let them see what those worlds are like in a realistic way. I
believe what I'm telling them is right. About government, the
economy, the media and the way they present the news.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You, as an individual, make the news almost as much as your
books. You recently changed agents and there was a big story in The
New York Times about it. Would you rather not be a celebrity
yourself, and have any press attention confined to what you write?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, as a matter of fact. I don't see why anything I do is
newsworthy. I mean, People magazine ... the trouble with People
magazine is, it's the National Enquirer on good paper. It's what
you read in a doctor's office while you're waiting to have blood
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think whatever you have to say is reflected in your
books? Are you Jack Ryan?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jack Ryan is me. No doubt. When President Ryan says
something, that's what I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As president yourself? Are you thinking of running for
office?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Choking, possibly spewing coffee): Dear God, I hope not! I'm
not the least bit politically correct. I have a tendency to trip
over my own tongue. And I've got a big enough ego already. I don't
want it getting any bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Well, critics bash you frequently, for writing too long and
offering too many personal, conservative opinions in your novels.
Does that help keep your ego under control?
</P>
<P>
   A: I read the reviews. I'm so successful that people often envy
me and try to gain status by attacking me. That's human nature. As
a practical matter, when a reviewer reads a book, he or she likes
it or doesn't like it. Then the reviewer selectively picks out
passages to back up that opinion. True objectivity is hard to
accomplish for anyone, including me. But I'm not going to let
reviews affect me. I know what I'm trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your own opinion, how well do you do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have a good narrative sense. My characters are improving. I
don't have much trouble with editors at my publisher, because I
turn in pretty clean work. My weakness is that I work so fast, I
don't use language as elegantly as I'd like. I could write better.
But my style isn't to take a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your opinion, which are the best books you've written and
which are the weakest?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Without Remorse'' is my favorite. It's not my best book,
though. I think ``Executive Orders'' is my best. Now, I frequently
look at the books I've written and see how they could have been
better. ``The Cardinal of the Kremlin'' was my first long-term No.
1 bestseller, but it's really my least favorite. I compacted the
plot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What book do you have coming next?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know yet. I haven't made a deal for my next book, but
it will be some kind of departure from the usual style. I don't
have any additional ambition _ I enjoy the life I have now. I do
work for which I'm very well compensated. I know I'm a successful
writer. Whether I'm one of the most popular writers in America, I
don't know. I don't think in those terms. What I do think about is
that real people pay real money to buy my books, and I want to give
them their money's worth. Could I get tired of writing and the
media attention and just stop doing what I do? Possibly _ but not
for a while yet.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
