<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-SPACE-NYT &LR;      08-22 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-SPACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MANY NEW YORKERS CAN DESIGNERS FIT ON THE HEAD OF A PIN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's that special something that makes dining in New
York City unlike dining in any other place.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it energy. Some call it buzz.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers call it crowding.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just their imagination. With real estate at a premium
and an economy that's enabling more people to eat out more often,
many restaurants have begun to feel like subway cars at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal building code hasn't helped. Nor have an army of
designers and restaurant managers who have finessed the art of
squeezing more people into their seating plans. Now, strange as it
seems, New York City restaurant crowding has become a brand of its
own, sought after by restaurateurs in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the public spaces in a restaurant must allow 12 square
feet per person, including diners and staff. Maximum occupancy is
calculated depending on the square footage, the number of fire
exits, their location and their width.
</P>
<P>
   This seems fairly generous until you compare it with cities like
San Francisco and Atlanta, where the limit is 15 square feet per
person, or even Philadelphia, where it's 13 square feet per person.
Bar areas are much tighter. In Philadelphia, a bar must allow 9
square feet per person; in Atlanta, it's 7. In New York, the space
is measured by counter length: 18 inches of it per person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of restaurants out of state,'' said Warren
Ashworth, a partner in Bogdanow Partners Architects, a Manhattan
design firm, ``and I never see a place that's packed the way some
places are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramped restaurants have long been a signature of New York
dining. The ``21'' Club, which opened in 1929, has always had its
back wall of banquettes. Lining walls with banquettes increases the
number of tables that can fit in a room. What's remarkable about
the tables at ``21'', though, is how closely they are arranged. In
order for diners against the wall to get up from the table, a
waiter must come by and pull the table out into the room. Now it
seems every bistro in town has the same plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers are much more sophisticated, much more tolerant,
and docile actually,'' said Jeffrey Beers, a Manhattan architect
who designed China Grill and Calle Ocho. ``They don't mind being
bumped around a little bit; in fact, they enjoy it.'' That jab to
the back of the head when you're taking a bite of your crab cakes
might even be a sign of warmth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason you're not eating at home, where you have all
the privacy you need,'' said David Rockwell, a partner in the
Rockwell Group, whose designs include Nobu, the Monkey Bar and
Vong. ``You're eating out as much for the social experience as for
a dining experience.''
</P>
<P>
   New York diners are also sensitive and, as Rockwell added,
designers are constantly struggling to find that elusive place
between ``sardines and Siberia.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs spend a lot of time searching for it, too. In the
process, walkways get narrower, corners are maximized, and
breathing room is kept at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   A dining room laid out too generously can feel dead. If the
tables are six or seven feet apart, Beers said, ``It's difficult to
get a buzz going. It yields a quiet sit-up-straight kind of
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy in a restaurant has become a kind of commodity. Many New
York designers working in other cities have been asked to come up
with a ``New York feel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They associate that with a slightly tighter table spacing than
you might get if you were following an industry standard,'' said
Paul Bentel, a partner at Bentel &AMP; Bentel Architects/Planners in
Locust Valley, N.Y. By industry standards, Bentel said, tables for
four may be spaced five or six feet apart. In New York, he would
reduce that to as little as 24 inches, ``to get the kind of energy
they associate with a New York restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, though, these same designers are not trying to
crunch space down to the limit of 12 square feet per person. If a
room is too tight, people will feel uncomfortable and won't want to
come back, Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockwell Group and Bogdanow Partners both said their
restaurants average 16 to 18 square feet per person. The industry
standard, Bentel said, is 20 to 22 square feet per person.
</P>
<P>
   The bar area is more of a wild card _ and a tighter squeeze. The
trouble with many new designs is the mingling of bar areas with
eating areas. Often, they collide.
</P>
<P>
   New York City building codes dictate that smoking areas at the
bar can be just six feet from dining tables. Which is why in many
restaurants, like Bottino and Babbo, you often feel as if you are
eating in the bar and getting bumped by all the traffic flowing
through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, you would have to say it's unavoidable in some
cases,'' Ashworth said. But design can play a part. At Verbena, the
bar has just five seats and is set into a dark area with a low
ceiling. It sends out a clear message that it is just for waiting
for your table, not for lingering.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bar any larger would have probably affected the restaurant
dining experience,'' said Glenn Forley, a partner in Fizer Forley,
which designed the restaurant, ``because you would have had more of
an overlap. Now the bar is pretty much separate from the tables.''
The same is accomplished at Eleven Madison Park, where the bar is
set off to the side in a small dim room with low ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid crowds forming in more open restaurants, designers have
taken to adding communal tables in the bar area, which break up
crowds and form boundaries. ``By definition,'' Rockwell said, ``it
doesn't allow the bar to become too much of a bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Rosa Mexicano immediately attracted a big bar crowd,
making it impossible to navigate at times. Rockwell, whose company
designed the restaurant, has recently added bar-height tables. ``It
felt just too open,'' Rockwell said, ``and there's a lot of people
and making them a little more comfortable made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the long and narrow restaurants with bars up front that
have the most difficulty with traffic jams. At Town, a restaurant
under construction in Midtown, the bar itself and the equipment
behind it are very shallow. A small lounge is positioned at the end
of the bar, so people will be drawn through the area rather than
encouraged to linger in it. Other designers add features like a
carpet or a rail to signal which areas are for circulation.
</P>
<P>
   But there is only so much that can be done by a designer. The
rest is up to the management to control. If crowds get out of
control, as they do in many restaurant bars, it's the neighbors who
step in. The New York City Department of Buildings does not have a
task force out enforcing occupancy compliance. Most complaints are
filed by residents to the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Fire Department will send an officer to take a head
count at the restaurant, said Brian Dixon, a department spokesman.
(For occupancies over 75 or restaurants with more than 750 square
feet, a sign must be posted and there is an annual inspection,
including a review of the seating plan.) If the occupancy limit is
exceeded, diners will be asked to leave until it is met. The
restaurant can be fined a maximum of $2,500. The unlucky, randomly
chosen diners go home hungry.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York this series of events is rare. So rare that when
the Fire Department was asked, it could not dig up a single case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
