A9170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FACIALHAIR0823-COX     08-22 0118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACIALHAIR0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new cream called Vaniqa suppresses growth of unwanted facial
hair
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Unwanted facial hair is a condition that
is rarely spoken about, even among women who suffer from it.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, women tweeze and wax and pluck unwanted whiskers, but
the growths on the chin and upper lip that affect more than 20
million American women are nearly impossible to destroy
permanently. Like men, women must be vigilant about removing
unwanted hair or it just grows back.
</P>
<P>
   And this can lead to discomfort in social situations, making
women ashamed of their appearances and driving them into spending
loads of time
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BILINGUAL-AMERICA-$AD     08-22 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-AMERICA-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS TORN BETWEEN EMBRACING, RESTRICTING OTHER LANGUAGES
 &HT;    With BILINGUAL-BOX. Moving in (a) national and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ ``Bienvenidos. Se Habla Espanol.'' The sign welcoming
customers to a hair salon in a suburban shopping mall assured them
Spanish was spoken there.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, the sign disappeared from the shop
window. Soon after, according to Hispanic former employees,
managers of the Regis Hairstylist Salon in North Riverside, Ill.,
ordered them to speak only English, even on their breaks and to
Spanish-speaking customers.
</P>
<P>
   Several hairstylists allege that they lost their jobs in 1997
for defying the rule and speaking their native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) has made
a federal case out of it, filing a class-action discrimination
lawsuit last year against Minneapolis-based Regis Corp., which
operates salons in malls across America.
</P>
<P>
   As immigrants from non-English-speaking countries flow into the
United States, businesses and institutions increasingly face a
foreign-language test: How best to cope with new workers and new
customers whose first language is not English?
</P>
<P>
   The question is laden with obstacles and opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of English as the sole language of American business
and political life is being challenged, swamped by new demographic
and market realities. More than 16 million legal immigrants have
entered America since 1980. One in five children in America is
either an immigrant or the U.S.-born son or daughter of an
immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   The largest group, native Spanish speakers, represents an
important labor pool and a rapidly expanding economic force, with a
buying power last year of $383 billion, up 84 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller in numbers, but more affluent, Asian-Americans saw their
buying power leap 102 percent in the decade, to $228.6 billion,
according to estimates from the Selig Center for Economic Growth at
the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``At issue here isn't just a legal question. It is: How does
American business manage a diverse work force? How do you balance
new realities and historic assumptions, many of them unflattering,
about immigrants?'' said Christopher Ho, a senior staff attorney at
the San Francisco-based Employment Law Center, a national worker
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. efforts to penetrate the global marketplace, and keep pace
with the new diversity in America, have companies big and small
scrambling to hire bilingual employees.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal police forces, hospitals, congressional offices and
other government organizations also seek out bilingual employees or
provide language training for existing workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sense that we need it more to succeed in the economy than
we did before,'' said Pat DiCerbo of the National Clearinghouse for
Bilingual Education at George Washington University in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the work place diversifies and the need for bilingualism
grows, so too has the imposition of English-only rules by companies
claiming that the restrictions are necessary for workplace safety
and rapport.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Gomez, 39, a Mexican native and one of the Chicago
hairstylists who claims she was forced from her job, speaks English
at home with her three American-born children. But she felt it only
natural to speak Spanish at work with clients from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seemed silly to me, because we're in a free country and
my clients speak Spanish, too. It just doesn't make sense,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Regis, which operates 5,000 salons in the U.S.,
Canada and the United Kingdom, declined to comment on the case when
reached by telephone at their corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law does not prohibit employers from requiring their
workers to speak only English. But EEOC regulations can require
companies to demonstrate that the English-only policy is necessary
for conducting business or maintaining safety and that it does not
discriminate. Courts have ruled that an employer's language policy
must be reasonable and justifiable, and not a blanket policy that
extends to off-work activities.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, English-only is acceptable among air traffic
controllers or in a hospital, and perhaps even in a business
setting to maintain continuity, but not to prevent workers from
chatting in their native language at the water cooler.
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC only began tracking complaints about English-only rules
in 1996 and has seen them rise. In 1996, the agency filed 77
English-only charges, compared to 253 last year. Likewise, cases
involving discrimination based on national origin have increased as
employers take advantage of workers' unfamiliarity of the U.S.
workplace and ignorance of their legal rights. Allegations of
harassment have risen tenfold between 1986 and 1999, according to
the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has grown significantly,'' said David Grinberg, a spokesman
at the EEOC's Washington, D.C., headquarters. ``The trend we see
are immigrants in low-wage jobs who become the target of egregious
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho believes many employers enact English-only rules in the
mistaken belief that they are sanctioned by the wave of largely
symbolic English-only resolutions. About two dozen states,
including Georgia, Florida, North Carolina and Colorado, have
passed measures or ballot initiatives making English the official
language over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the U.S. House of Representatives voted 259-169 to make
English the nation's official language. But the measure has failed
to advance to a vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as English-only efforts persist, corporate marketing
efforts in Spanish and other languages are at an all-time high,
according to Raoul Lopez, senior vice president of Strategy
Research Corp. in Miami. The marketing research firm founded in
1971 is having its best year ever supplying data on Hispanic buying
trends to Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, $1.7 billion was spent on Spanish-language
advertising in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inevitable. It's the fastest-growing minority group in
the United States with enormous buying power,'' said Lopez. ``There
is a growing momentum in the market for companies to expand their
efforts under an umbrella of the top three minority groups _
Hispanics, African Americans and Asian-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Prudential Atlanta/Georgia Realty opened a
bilingual office to serve suburban Hall County's booming Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, the consumer products giant, last fall
launched a multicultural marketing effort including a magazine
called Avanzando con tu Familia (Advancing With Your Family).
Debuted last fall, it is distributed free to 4.5 million Hispanic
households and includes a blend of advertising and helpful tips for
mothers and homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which also spends heavily on Spanish-language radio
and television, is testing similar grassroots efforts to build
relationships with Asian American and African-American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, as the demographics of our customers change, we
want to change with them,'' said Maria Molina of Procter &AMP; Gamble's
multicultural marketing division. ``It's the right thing to do, and
it makes business sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In large cities like Los Angeles, Houston and Miami, native
Spanish speakers can live their everyday lives without the need for
English.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all ATM cash machines in the United States offer
English or Spanish options as the first selection of any
transaction. This year, in an effort to count everyone in America,
the Census Bureau offered questionnaires in six languages: English,
Spanish, Chinese, Korean, Vietnamese and Tagalog.
</P>
<P>
   Yet polls show that a majority of immigrants consider learning
English or improving their English skills is a top priority to get
ahead in America. Census figures show that more than 60 percent of
Spanish-speaking immigrants are fluent in English.
</P>
<P>
   Market studies show that the rate of assimilation among
Hispanics is accelerating as their affluence is growing. About 75
percent of Hispanic households in the United States are classified
as middle or upper class, according to market researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a market study by Strategy Research Corp. showed that
for every Hispanic adult identifying more with the general U.S.
population, seven were aligned more with the Hispanic culture and
market. By this year, the ratio had dropped to 1 to 3, with
substantially more Hispanics were moving toward the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, immigrants will assimilate over time. But
will employers ease up on English-only rules?
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is always tough,'' said Ho, the worker-rights advocate.
``But as we're faced with the reality that we need these people to
fuel the current economy, perhaps it will propel employers to
rethink these kinds of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, www.eeoc.gov
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Census Bureau, www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   University of Georgia's Selig Center for Economic Growth,
www.selig.uga.edu
</P>
<P>
   American Civil Liberties Union, www.aclu.org
</P>
<P>
   U.S. English, Inc., www.us-english.org
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
