<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0823-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   IF YOU'VE GOT THE CAP, WEAR IT
</P>
<P>
   War veterans embraced Al Gore as one of their own Tuesday as he
swatted back at George W. Bush's assertion that America's military
is in decline. Emphasizing his military and foreign affairs
experience _ in the Army in Vietnam, and service on intelligence
and armed services committees in Congress _ Gore told the Veterans
of Foreign Wars convention in Milwaukee that his is no election
year conversion. Wearing his cap from VFW Post 5021 in Carthage,
Tenn., Gore said it ``makes me so concerned when others try to run
down America's military for political advantage in an election.''
His $127 billion in military proposals include higher pay,
equipment modernization and more money for veterans hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   GOING NATIONAL WITH TEXAS READING PLAN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was completing a two-day tour through the Midwest
by pushing a $5 billion program _ copied from one he started three
years ago in Texas _ that would encourage states to teach children
to read by third grade. ``Reading is the building block, and it
must be the foundation, for education reform,'' was the message he
was delivering in visits to schools in Peoria, Ill., and
Chesterfield, Mo. States that use this fund, Bush said, would be
required to establish a reading test for students to determine who
needs extra help, a curriculum and teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE . . . THIS IS YOUR CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Telling his life story with millions of dollars in TV spots, Al
Gore returned to the airwaves Tuesday, trying to capitalize on
momentum from last week's convention. Almost state for state and
dollar for dollar, the effort matches rival George W. Bush's ads on
education and making tough choices, which began running Monday. The
Gore ad, playing in 17 battleground states, begins the story with
his decision to enlist in the Army despite deep misgivings about
the Vietnam War and goes on to chronicle Gore's entry into
politics, his accomplishments in Congress and as vice president,
and his main policy goals. Democrats estimate that the Bush
campaign is spending nearly $5.5 million this week, with Gore
spending about the same.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD REVERSAL IN ANOTHER POLL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has climbed to a narrow lead following the Democratic
convention by easing doubts about his leadership ability and
personal style while establishing himself with voters as the
candidate best able to deal with the economy, education and health
care reform, according to a new Washington Post-ABC News poll. Gore
currently holds a 50-45 percent advantage over George W. Bush among
registered voters _ the first time he has clearly led in a Post-ABC
News poll. Bush led Gore by 9 percentage points less than two weeks
ago. The poll has a 3.5 percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   OK, START CONVINCING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush acknowledged Tuesday he hasn't convinced voters
that the nation can afford his $1.3 trillion tax cut plan after
shoring up Social Security. ``I have got to do a better job of
making it clear'' that expected budget surpluses in the next 10
years will allow for the tax cuts, even after Social Security is
rescued, Bush said. He was responding to new criticism from Al Gore
alleging his plan would squander the surplus. Bush said he was
standing by his proposals: ``I am not changing my opinion. I think
it is the absolute right thing to do for America.''
</P>
<P>
   DOING WHAT HE'S REALLY GOOD AT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was attending a pair of lavish fund-raisers in
suburban Detroit private homes, the latest effort to boost the
Senate campaign coffers of Rep. Debbie Stabenow. She trails her
opponent in dollars raised, but appears to be in a dead heat with
Republican Sen. Spence Abraham. Clinton was guest of honor at a
$1,000-a-person reception in Bingham Farms and a $10,000-a-person
dinner in Bloomfield Hills. Money from the events _ organizers hope
to raise $500,000 _ will be split between the Democratic National
Committee and Stabenow's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSIVE
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Defense Department has done its best to defend
its capabilities, while not appearing to take sides in a political
spat. ``We're still the finest force in the world today,'' said
Defense Secretary William Cohen, a Republican. Cohen admitted,
however, that one area in need of improvement is compensation and
benefits _ a major issue of contention between George W. Bush and
Al Gore. ``We've had the largest pay raise in a generation,'' Cohen
said. ``Can we always do more? Sure . . . I think there's always
room for criticism.'' But Cohen denied Bush's assertion that, if
elected, Bush would inherit a military ``in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   AN ARMY TRAVELS ON ITS STOMACH
</P>
<P>
   The quality of life for military families was popularized as a
campaign issue by Arizona Sen. John McCain, whose failed
presidential campaign called attention to the fact that thousands
of service members are on food stamps. But some military analysts
don't necessarily think that's a bad thing, regarding food stamps
as just another military benefit. But it has become a mark of
shame, and both Al Gore and George W. Bush say conditions must be
improved. Gore says the number of active service members receiving
the coupons has dwindled by two-thirds in a decade, to about 6,000,
and reminds everyone that food stamps in the military date back
well before the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   BIG ELECTION, BIG MONEY
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush raised seven times more money than Al Gore in
July, according to monthly filings with the Federal Elections
Commission. While Gore raised $771,000 from individuals, Bush
reported receipts of $5.4 million, including contributions from
political action committees. With both party conventions over, the
candidates no longer can accept campaign contributions. Instead,
both will receive a $67.56 million federal subsidy. Both political
parties, however, can still raise unlimited amounts in ``soft
money'' donations.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER FATHER-SON COMBO?
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said he thinks his eldest son,
HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo, will run for governor of New York in
2002. But the elder Cuomo said that ``unless Andrew is lying to
me,'' his son has not yet completely committed to running.
Nonetheless, Mario Cuomo said, ``We're doing everything possible to
get him ready for when he says it. I'm talking to people about
money, and that's coming fairly well. . . . We're doing that kind
of thing and he's moving around.'' The father lost the job in 1994
to Republican George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   POPULIST PITCH PUMMELED
</P>
<P>
   Green Party candidate Ralph Nader challenged Al Gore's populist
credentials and urged him to reject campaign money from industries
he criticized during his address to the Democratic convention last
week. ``He challenged and criticized the giant drug companies, the
oil companies, the pharmaceutical industry, the HMOs. . . . He
talked populist, but buys into corporate power,'' Nader said in Los
Angeles. ``Give the money back, Mr. Gore, or stand condemned of
deceiving and misleading the American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BUT SHE'LL LET THEM ENDORSE HER, THOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton declined to offer her backing for Rep. Eliot
Engel, a five-term Bronx Democrat facing a September primary
challenge. Black and Hispanic leaders have thrown their support
behind a black state senator, Larry Seabrook. ``I am not getting
involved in that campaign,'' Clinton said in Yonkers as Engel, who
is Jewish, stood stiff and expressionless at her side. ``This is a
local situation. I'm not going to have anything to say about
that,'' she said. Clinton has generally steered clear of taking
sides in any primaries, even those involving incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER SPRAY PEPPERS CLINTON RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents removed Hillary Clinton from a community
center in Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y., after a supporter accidentally
released pepper spray into the meeting hall. Clinton apparently was
unaffected by the incident, which occurred as she was posing for
photos with children. But dozens of others left the hall and went
outside coughing. ``I was putting something in my bag and I must
have knocked the safety off,'' said an embarrassed Ka'ttie Coleman,
a Clinton supporter, pulling out the small black canister attached
to her keychain. ``I feel very, very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS TIME'S MANAGEMENT'S THE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   In a municipal election in Selma, Ala., longtime Mayor Joe
Smitherman, a white ex-segregationist who was in office during the
civil rights violence of 1965, faced challenges from three black
candidates. Smitherman, 70, barely won re-election in 1996. During
his first term, the city became infamous for the armed response to
the Selma voting rights march. Later, he welcomed blacks into his
government and has won nine consecutive elections in a city that is
now 65 percent black. Most opponents _ including businessman James
Perkins, who nearly beat him four years ago _ criticize him for his
management of the city.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
