<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-STRATEGY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATING THE BAR WHEN IT'S THREE DRINKERS DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How a concerned drinker might ask, is a person
supposed to get a margarita at the new Rosa Mexicano on Columbus
Avenue? The place is huge: two floors across from Lincoln Center.
The bar, for some reason, occupies approximately 0.01 percent of
this vast space. It's like a trading post on the floor of the New
York Stock Exchange, everybody shouting and waving their arms
about, frantically trying to place orders. Drop in there after
work, and witness the sad sight of two attractive women shuffling
back and forth on the periphery of the crowd, trying to get the
bartender's attention.
</P>
<P>
   A terrible spectacle, but not an unusual one. Manhattan's
restaurants are the most congested in the country _ and seem to be
getting more so by the minute. Going out has become a battle of
inches, from securing the edge of a bar stool to steeling yourself
against the jostling of waiters, busboys and fellow diners in
restaurants prized for having 13 tables. Even for hardened night
life decathletes, walking into the new now place induces a
fight-or-flight response.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I subjected myself to a week of heat-seeking
throngs. My hope was to learn how to navigate Manhattan's most
mobbed bar scenes, where restaurant congestion reaches critical
mass.
</P>
<P>
   For the first outing, last Tuesday, I brought my friend Doug, a
writer and photographer who does not exaggerate when he says he
spends every night of his life in a bar. Our first venue:
Balthazar.
</P>
<P>
   The bar was bustling. A phalanx of skinny young things and the
men who prey on them blocked access to a tantalizing wall of wine
and liquor. We saw two empty stools, but a man sporting a
blazer-T-shirt look was standing proprietorily over one of them.
Doug, not a shy person, asked the fellow if he would mind moving to
another vacant stool, further down the bar, so we could have his.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sit here, but I'm not giving up my position,'' the
fellow said, leaning into a conversation between two young women on
the other side of him.
</P>
<P>
   So Doug sat and I stood. We immediately asked for drinks and a
menu. Ordering food is an excellent way to claim a beachhead: the
moment the cutlery and napkin arrive, you've doubled your real
estate. By the time the steak frites came, we'd squeezed our friend
out and over to a second-row spot facing the two women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done this guy a major favor,'' Doug said, going on to
offer a few recommendations for prompt bar service, in order of
advisability:
</P>
<P>
   --Seek out the shortest people and get behind them _ same
strategy as at a rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   --Wave a large wad of cash _ crass but it still works in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   --Do the one-finger slam dunk, as if tipping a basketball in
with the index finger, making yourself as tall as possible and
gesturing at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   --Say: ``My wife's pregnant. She needs a Guinness.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Dechais, one of the women sitting next to us, revealed
that she works on weekends as a bartender in Queens. Her advice?
``Anyone who leans over the bar and aggressively tries to get my
attention will be the last person I will serve,'' she said. ``The
best way is to be polite, like, `I know you're really busy but when
you have a moment ... .'''
</P>
<P>
   I tried out her technique the following night at Rue 57, the
57th Street version of Balthazar. I arrived, alone, at 7 o'clock. I
sidled up to a stool occupied by a purse and shopping bag that
belonged to a nearby quartet of French-speaking women. I hovered by
the stool, adopting a sideways stance and planting one hand on the
edge of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender, who seemed older than his bottle-blond hair and
gold hoop earring would indicate, was deep in conversation with two
female patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Married is single in my world!'' he said in a Down Under
accent, clasping one of their ringed fingers in his hand. I
considered asking him if this was something Bryan Brown had said in
``Cocktail.'' Then I remembered the polite approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me. ... When you get a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. I sensed I was not a member of his favorite gender. I
locked onto the more approachable-looking bartender, resolved not
to take my eyes off him till they made contact. (If a bartender
looks at you and you're not looking back, prepare to wait another
20 minutes.) I'd been Hoovering edamame from a bowl on the bar, so
I used this as my witty ice-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good!'' I said, furiously popping the soy beans into
my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said. ``Can't stop eating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Connection made! It got me a beer and a menu. I was then free to
focus on how others around me did it. One guy tried shouting over
the row of people in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a chardonnay!'' he declared, as if to indicate
confident familiarity with the grape.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind?'' my bartender asked with what sounded like a hint
of irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you like.''
</P>
<P>
   Another bartender would later tell me that her pet peeve is
people who don't know what they want.
</P>
<P>
   I was then treated to the opposite approach, aggressive
hostility. A short dark-haired woman charged the bar with such
violence that my hand slipped on my pint glass, splashing her with
a few droplets of beer foam. She shot me a death glare and fanned
theatrically at the cigarette smoke coming from the woman on the
other side of her. (Lighting up is a surefire way to expand your
perimeter.) But I couldn't help but admire how fast she managed to
get a menu in one hand, a fistful of edamame in the other and a
round of drinks for her friends. This is New York. Sometimes,
bartenders have also told me, pushy works.
</P>
<P>
   Being Canadian, I can't do pushy. Canadians are personal-space
fanatics (we invented the white line on the highway), but we're too
deferential to do much about it but fume and call it patience. This
paid off when the French foursome finally left. I took their
bag-storage stool and ordered a plate of oysters and littleneck
clams. From my perch I could now watch a poor sap in a powder blue
polo shirt, who'd been there as long as I had, wander aimlessly
around a crowd that was now three deep. After a while, Powder Blue
Man slammed his empty glass down in front of me and stalked out, as
if I had somehow stolen his rightful place.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was getting the hang of this. Thursday night would be
the true test. The TGIT crowd, out in force. I'd heard that when
Guastavino's first opened under the 59th Street Bridge, people were
turned away from the bar on Thursday nights unless they had dinner
reservations. That was where I brought my friend Tad, a producer
and program host on the Metro Channel.
</P>
<P>
   We were not denied. The bar was filled with very short, very tan
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo, Rich! When ya get a chance.'' This was the voice in my ear
mocking our own futile stabs at getting a drink. Knowing the
bartender, or at least able to address him by name, is the ultimate
weapon. It doubles, maybe triples, your range. You could be 20 feet
from the bar and still get an order through with a ``Yo, Rich!'' in
your arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and saloon scholar from Chicago had e-mailed me to this
effect. ``Curry the favor of all bartenders in the joints you
frequent,'' he advised. ``The key is to be well known for tipping
generously and thus establish yourself as a beloved regular who
knows a thing or two about the server. This limits your power to
all but a handful of hangouts _ but I find it's always better to be
treated with deference in your favorite haunts than to explore new
ones and be made to feel like a loser all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tad likes to go for ``the pocket,'' the spot at the end of the
bar under the television often left vacant by people who like to
watch. No good here, as there is no TV. His other tactic is to scan
the bar like a parking lot, looking for the equivalent of a brake
light: anyone who looks as if he or she is settling up. We found
one such opening, a narrow one, which I tried to enlarge by
sticking out my chest and elbows. (A friend calls this maneuver
``fatting.'') After one beer and too many chicken wings, we left
for more challenging territory.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
