<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-STRATEGY-N     08-22 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: challenging territory.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We found it at Red Rock West. This West Chelsea theme dive _
Hogs 'n' Heifers meets Coyote Ugly _ makes no delineation between
bar and nonbar space, just an alcoholic mosh pit. In short, not an
easy place to get a drink.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you happen to be 6-foot-6 and built like a professional
wrestler. This was ``Land of the Giants'' territory, and we, a
couple of average-size media guys, had made the mistake of bringing
our womenfolk. Tad knows one of the Red Rock bartenders, Anne, who
if she doesn't like the way someone asks for a drink will use the
bar microphone to publicly abuse that person. (What sets her off is
people who address her as ``Hello-o-o!'') Anne wasn't working that
night, making Tad just another loser trying to get a round of
tequila shots.
</P>
<P>
   We were one layer away from the bar when I became aware of a
huge forearm reaching over my head and a voice growling, ``Get me
an Amstel Light and a vodka-tonic.'' A curt nod and it was done.
The drinks were passed back over my head and handed to our dates.
</P>
<P>
   Things could have gotten ugly _ I might have had to rough some
dudes up _ but it was at this moment that my date discovered that
her ankle was bleeding. Enough bottles and glasses explode here _
on the floor, over someone's head _ that you write it off as
background noise. Ambience. But she'd caught enough shards that we
had to leave to assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a place for mules,'' she observed as we fought our
way upstream toward the door.
</P>
<P>
   Our shots had just arrived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
