<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SLUG-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-22 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATS! WHAT TO SERVE FOR A `SURVIVOR' PARTY?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to `Reality bytes' main story. Second of 2
sidebars.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sabina Steinmetz of Burbank is planning a ``Survivor'' party
with tapioca treats, immunity challenges for her guests and a
tiki-themed jungle decor that would do Elvis Presley proud. She's
even serving up her own variation of rat-on-a-stick, with barbecued
chicken standing in for the rodent.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Rhodes of Studio City has an even more elaborate soiree
planned _ partygoers will be divided into teams and be allowed
different qualities and quantities of snacks, much as the Tagi
tribe went hungry as the Pagongs feasted after winning goofy
challenges on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have normal stuff _ rice, tapioca, fish, rats, grub
(actually gummi) worms,'' Rhodes promises. ``After the first
challenge on the show, everyone's gonna draw numbers out of a hat.
We'll have sushi and sake and nice food for the winning group;
everyone else eats rice with sand in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Partygoers will be dressed as their favorite survivors _ ``I'll
have failed if at least one guy isn't naked,'' he says. ``I'm
coming as Colleen. I've had parasites in my legs for the past four
days so the scarring will be authentic,'' he jokes. At least, we're
pretty sure he's joking.
</P>
<P>
   Both Steinmetz and Rhodes also know who they're rooting for to
take home the million-dollar prize with their tattered apparel:
Rudy, the 72-year-old former Navy SEAL who couldn't start a fire
and couldn't catch a fish, but still seems more worthy of winning
than the other finalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I think everybody pretty much despises the rest
of them,'' Steinmetz says. ``I thought Kelly would've been gone
several episodes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes concurs: ``Anyone who eats at the Olive Garden, even if
she's using someone else's credit card'' _ as Kelly is accused of
doing by North Carolina authorities _ ``doesn't deserve anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinmetz continues, ``I don't despise Sue _ she's up-front
about things, but crude in a way. I think Richard has a shot in the
final two, but then it becomes a matter of who the castaways hate
less, and the others really resent his manipulations in getting
that far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants want to see Snidely Whiplash win,'' Rhodes
echoes.
</P>
<P>
   And Steinmetz is already looking ahead _ albeit a smidgen
reluctantly _ to the Australian sequel, scheduled to debut in
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Says Steinmetz, ``I'll watch the next one, but there'll never be
another like this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
