   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   Editors: Deletes iFilms;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE _ The Firestone tire models voluntarily recalled Aug.
9 are also failing on sport utility vehicles other than the Ford
Explorer, but when an Explorer loses its tire tread it is six times
as likely to roll over and kill someone, federal accident data
shows. An analysis of the of 642 Firestone and Explorer-related
accident reports that the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration has collected since early this year shows that the
rate at which tire treads are coming apart are comparable whether
the Firestone tires are on Ford's popular Explorer or on other
sport utility vehicles. However, the analysis indicates that what
happens after the tread peals away is strikingly different. The
results of the analysis, which was performed by the American
Statesman, appeared to support the allegations of lawyers and
safety advocates who have claimed that the Explorer has played a
role in the catastophic tire failures being reported nationwide.
(Carmody, Austin American-Statesman). 45. WITH CHARTS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE-SIDE _ The Blossie family of Austin lost their
11-year-old daughter in an Explorer/Firestone accident last month
in Arizona. The accident fits a pattern emergeing nationwide. We
talk to that family and other Explorer owners. (Carmody, Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CANE-MAIN _ Debbie is headed toward South Florida, if the
islands don't detour it along the way. It could hit San Juan soon.
The utilities and Water Management District are gearing up.
(O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post). 25.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ M ILWAUKEE, Wis. _ Vice President Al Gore, rebutting
Republican charges that the U.S. military has grown weaker under
the Clinton administration, told the Veterans of Foreign Wars on
Tuesday that America's fighting forces are ``the strongest and the
best in the entire world,'' and he would keep them that way.
(Shepard, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Politics.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FLORIDA _ Al Gore and Joe Lieberman will visit South
Florida Wednesday for the first time since the Democratic
Convention. They will visit Kings Point community in Tamarac and
address an audience of senior citizens, middle-class families who
are caring for an elderly parent, and local caregivers. They will
discuss their plans to provide targeted tax cuts to help families
pay for long-term care. George W. Bush arrives Thursday. (Crowley,
Palm Beach Post). 12.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TIMBER _ NEWHILL, N.C. _ This southern corner of Wake County,
where suburban sprawl from nearby Raleigh and a local wood chip
mill are eliminating woodlands, illustrates the conclusion of a
controversial new study by timber management researchers. Rather
than solely blaming chip and pulp mills for depleting the South's
forests, the report from Duke and North Carolina State universities
said urban growth is also a significant cause of the shrinking
forests. On the eve of an industry conference Wednesday in Raleigh,
this finding heightens the sharp debate between the timber industry
and, on the other side, environmentalists and federal officials
concerned about the rapid acceleration of logging in the South. The
region is less regulated than the Pacific Northwest and, for the
first time, is harvesting soft woods such as pines faster than they
are being replaced. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GA-EXECUTE _ Board of Pardons and Paroles hears the case of
Alexander Williams, who is scheduled for execution Thursday. No
decision is expected today. Also, an appeal may be filed with the
Georgia Supreme Court. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ John and Patsy Ramsey will meet with Boulder, Colo.,
police on Monday in Atlanta. The couple is looking to be finally
cleared in the murder of their daughter. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ If Bill Clinton is indicted and faces potential
prison time after he leaves the presidency for lying under oath
about going too far with Monica Lewinsky, so be it. After all, the
president got himself into this fix and there is no reason why an
ex-president should be cut any legal slack the rest of us wouldn't
get. And that is precisely why Clinton shouldn't be charged. Almost
no one else would be in the same circumstances.(Teepen, Cox News
Service.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg's column is not available
today. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ With summer's end, the pace in Pelee Island,
Ontario slackens as ferries from the Canadian and U.S. mainlands
cut back their shuttles to a sparse winter schedule that lasts
until the lake freezes over. Life on the island slows to a pleasant
walk. I know because I've been reading all about it in some back
issues of the local newspaper - The Grapevine. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKMAN-COLUMN _ While the GOP may officially oppose what it
calls ``quotas,'' there's no question that party leaders wanted a
certain number of minority faces broadcast on the nation's TV
screens from the convention in Philadelphia, and that those faces
were far out of proportion to their actual number and influence in
the party. Rather than an expression of hypocrisy, however, perhaps
it's best to look at that radiant picture of diversity from
Philadelphia as the stating of a goal. (Bookman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ The arrival of another school year brings to mind
contraband. Not drugs, but the more benign goods of another time.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ An eye problem keeps columnist Joe Murray
home from the Democratic convention and reminds him of a childhood
game with cousin Bubba. (Joe Murray, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   KOOP _ Anatomy of a rescue plan: who gets what in what is likely
a reprieve more than a bailout. Venture capitalists spend $20
million to get two-thirds of a company that a year ago was valued
at $500 million, 4 of the 6 board seats and a presumably valuable
Internet brand name. They also get 7 shareholder lawsuits and an
SEC investigation. CEO Don Hackett is out, but stays on the board.
Who wins, who loses, what's next. (Park, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp., in a final rebuttal
brief to the Supreme Court, renewed its argument that a federal
appeals court should hear its appeal of the antitrust case that
threatens to break the computer software giant in two. (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-STATION _ WHDT, which used to be Channel 55, has become
the first television station to go exclusively digital in the
United States, and has petitioned the FCC to force South Florida
cable systems to carry it. The case is being watched closely
nationwide, putting a new twist on the whole digital transition,
cable must-carry dispute. (Stephanie Smith, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   INTEL _ SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Maybe Intel Corp. should change its
slogan from Intel Inside to Intel Online. For years, Intel has been
the almost-untouchable leader of semiconductors for the PC
business. But as PCs become passe and the Internet rules, Intel is
refocus itself on providing chips for everything Internet-related,
be they wireless Web phones or high-powered Internet servers. No
where is Intel's Internet emphasis more present than at its annual
developer's conference, which begins Tuesday in San Jose, where the
theme is ``Powering the Net.'' (Keefe, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FIBER-OPTICS _ Scientific-Atlanta and other technology
infrastructure companies are looking to optics as the way to send
data farther, faster and more efficiently. Optic technology could
cut cost of cable and telco upgrades by allowing the companies to
decrease new fiber installations and do more with the fiber they
already have in the ground. (Brister, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-PROMOTIONS _ Sprite and teen e-commerce site Rocket Cash
partner for online promotion. Lift off the cap, win cash to spend
on the Rocket Cash site. Promotion is set to run indefinately.
Pepsi has a similar promotion running now as well. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-WIRELESS _ NTT DoCoMo, the most valuable wireless
compoany in the world, the wireless arm of the largest phone
company that has reportedly been talking with BellSouth about an
investment. A biz overview of why we are talking about them and why
they matter. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   FIBERWORKS _ Fiberworks is announcing a $60 million equipment
deal with Nortel meant to power its ambitious plans to install
all-fiber, all-optical ``last mile'' metropolitan local access
networks in Atlanta, Charlotte and other large cities. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   IPHONE _ A a look at the i-mode phone that went from zero to 10
million subscribers in 18 months by letting people email, get
weather reports, train schedules and otherwise use the Internet --
doing it all more efficiently than can be done with wireless phones
in the U.S. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK-COLUMN _ Banks and retailers are eager to issue credit
cards to college students, because they know most of them will keep
their first card for 15 years or more. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MASE _ Almost two years ago at the height of fame and commercial
success, former rapper and close Sean ``Puffy'' Combs sidekick Mase
abruptly left hip-hop music to pursue the ministry. And he
basically hasn't been heard from or seen since. But now that his
``Hell Is Not Full'' crusade is coming to metro Atlanta, we get one
of the first interviews with him to discuss his departure, his
religious plans and life in his new hometown. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   FACIAL-HAIR _ One of the most difficult problems a woman can
face is the growth of unwanted hair, especially facial hair.
Waxing, electrolysis, tweezing, and new prlm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE _ The teacher, in our society, is expected to
produce positive results, often without the tools that are
essential for success. Many parents simply enroll a child in school
at the appropriate age and sit back and wait for expected results.
Parents, and society in general, are often oblivious to the
stresses felt by educators.(LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAiNMENT-ARTSSURVIVOR-MAIN _ What started as a simple
summer fill-in has become a record-breaking summer phenom: What has
drawn us to Survivor, a show that picked up ratings each week as
one of the 16 castaways got the boot? And where do we suddenly
reality-based viewers go from here?. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 27.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-FINALFOUR _ A final look at who will be the surviving
Survivor. We'll look at the pros, cons of each one, what he/she has
contributed, etc. Somewhat like a tale of the tape feature.
(Kloer/Jubera, Atrlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-GLANCE _ Episodes at a glance: We track Survivor from
the May 31 premiere through episode 12 (8/16). Basically a graph
each with that show's ratings at the end. (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-GUIDE _ Viewer's guide to Wednesday's finale; plays
better with the living package. Immunity challenges, etc. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 5.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   CANTALOUPE _ Most months of the year picking out a good
cantaloupe is a risky roll of the dice. We heft it because we know
it should feel heavy. We eyeball it, looking for errant traces of
green. We sniff it, hoping for sweet fragrance. We take it home.
Cut into it. And it is tasteless. In August, the odds switch to our
favor. That's when farmers bring America's favorite melon to
market. (Dayton Daily News). 27. WITH PHOTOS, RECIPESSPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-CUTS _ Recap of cuts as the grim reaper strikes at NFL
camps. Looking for the bigger names, but will include as many as
possible. (Segiura, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGESFBC-AGGIES _ Evan Perroni will be replacing
Rocky Bernard as the starting defensive end this fall. Perroni has
been a career backup. He challenged Bernard for the starting job in
the spring. He's a junior who has played a lot, 22 tackles in two
years. (Riggs, Austin American-Statesman). 20. WITH PHOTOS OF
PERRONI.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL/COLLEGESBKC-SIGNEE-ARRESTED _ Georgia signee John
Toombs, who didn't score high enough on the SAT to be eligible at
Georgia, was arrested and charged with underage drinking and simply
assault. He was released on his own recognizance into the custody
of coach Jim Harrick. May include update on Kenny Brunner. (Atlanta
Journnal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
