<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB (Moscow) _ The last time a Russian sub was lost,
mothers were notified by mail, in letters that listed their sons'
cause of death as: death. Russian officialdom has gotten more
respectful of public opinion since then, and the uproar over the
inept handling of this sub disaster has been a study in the
contradictory and clumsy way the power structure deals with its
people. By David Filipov. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MANGLE (Des Moines) _ For the second time this year, the
Republican presidential contender goes to Iowa and gives a stump
speech that mystifies his listeners and mangles some of his
phrases. By Glen Johnson. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   QUADRUPLE-TRANSPLANT (Boston) _ Brigham and Women's Hospital
hits a grand slam, taking four organs from a single patient and
transplanting them into four patients, all within a few hours. It
may be the first such surgical manuever anywhere. More important,
it's the wave of the future, when hospitals will be geared up to
make the most of every donor. By Larry Tye. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FED-RATES (Undated) _ Federal Reserve decides strong
productivity and a moderating economy are good signs and decides to
leave interest rates alone -- for now. The decision was expected.
By Kimberly Blanton. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Undated) _ Firestore's voluntary recall is gobbling
up so many SUV tires that dealers' supplies are nearly exhausted.
By Bruce Mohl. 650 words.
</P>
