<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-NNS     08-22 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CAMPAIGN RHETORIC IGNORES CORE DEFENSE PROBLEMS, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Aug. 22, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By DAVID WOOD  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hot on the campaign trail, presidential candidates
George W. Bush and Al Gore are trading accusations and boasts about
U.S. military readiness. So far, at least, what passes for a debate
on this critical issue is more likely to confuse than to inform.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon analysts and defense experts dismiss much of the
rhetoric so far as empty political blather.
</P>
<P>
   It glosses over very real problems inside the military, they
say, and fails to address the central issue of readiness: ready for
what?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an issue neither side has really explored because,
quite frankly, it's not something you can get into in 10 seconds or
less,'' said Andrew Krepinevich, executive director of the
nonpartisan Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Monday to the annual convention of the Veterans of
Foreign Wars, Bush, the Texas governor and Republican nominee, said
that the armed services' recruiting difficulties, spare parts
shortages and other problems ``are signs of a military in decline
and we must do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Vice President Gore returned fire, telling those
attending the convention in Milwaukee that it is ``wrong ... when
others try to run down America's military for political
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who claimed the Democratic nomination last week, told the
VFW convention that ``our military is the strongest and the best in
the entire world. ... I pledge to keep it that way with whatever it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   In common with most analysts, Krepinevich, a retired Army
lieutenant colonel, said the basic strength of U.S. forces is
sound, and that many of the arguments over readiness amount to
fussing over the fine print, ``tiny red flags'' that could signal
significant readiness problems in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin C. Spinney, a senior Pentagon analyst, said the
candidates are ignoring deeper problems than the military's
day-to-day readiness.
</P>
<P>
   One such problem, he said, is that the Pentagon's financial
books are in such disarray that ``we don't have the information to
sort things out.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Spinney said in an interview Tuesday, ``This thing
has become totally politicized. Neither (candidate) has a clue what
to do because the basic information isn't there ... and if they
just throw more money at it, that will make things worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States already spends roughly $300 billion a year on
its military. Adjusted for inflation, that's about what it was
spending at the height of the Cold War in 1980 when U.S. forces
were prepared to fight a global war against the 5 million-man
Soviet armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   That $300 billion a year also is more than the next 10 largest
military powers spend combined, including Russia, China and the
NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that sizable budget goes to a military significantly
smaller than the force that Bush's father commanded a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   This year, candidate Bush has accused Democrats of squandering
U.S. military power. He has charged that in sheer numbers of
soldiers, jet fighters, combat ships and tank divisions, U.S.
military power has slipped seriously in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   But these reductions were set in motion in 1990 by
then-President Bush and his defense secretary, Dick Cheney, the
younger Bush's running mate. Their rationale is applicable today:
With the Cold War over and the Soviet military shrunken to a shadow
of its one-time power, there is no need for the United States to
maintain a large, standing combat-ready force.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that the U.S. would realize savings from
developments in Europe was popularly referred to as the ``Peace
Dividend.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1990 State of the Union speech, a few months after the
Berlin Wall was torn down, President Bush proposed deep cuts in
U.S. troops based in Europe. Cheney went on to press Congress to
authorize a 25 percent across-the-board cut in U.S. military
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Army Gen. Colin Powell, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff at the time, said the cuts were not only justified because of
the vastly reduced global threat, but were necessary because
Congress would cut even deeper if the administration didn't hold
the line at 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Today there is still no sizable conventional military threat to
the United States, according to recent assessments by the Central
Intelligence Agency and such independent groups as the U.S.
Commission on National Security in the 21st Century, a
Pentagon-chartered panel set up by former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For the immediate future, at least, threats to the United States
will be terrorism, political destabilization, small regional
conflicts such as Kosovo, and perhaps missile attacks against U.S.
or friendly forces and facilities abroad.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, it is difficult to see why the U.S. Army should
maintain at high combat readiness the five tank brigades currently
stationed at Fort Riley, Kan., and Fort Carson, Colo., for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Should war break out in the Persian Gulf region or Korea, these
tanks would eventually arrive by ship, a process that would take
months. Rather than paying to keep these 580 tanks constantly
manned, gassed up and loaded with combat ammo, it might make more
sense for the Army to keep them clean and oiled but idle. It could
afford to take a week to bring them up to full combat readiness.
Meantime that money could be used for other purposes _ say,
research on a new generation of tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But that kind of readiness trade-off, however, might leave the
Army open to criticism that all its tanks are not ``combat ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for example, cited the reported non-readiness of two Army
divisions as one example of what he says is an alarming decline in
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are signs of a military in decline and we must do
something about it,'' he told the Veterans of Foreign Wars.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Army did report that two of its 10 combat
divisions were not, by Army standards, combat ready. The two
divisions in question, the 10th Mountain Division and the First
Infantry Division, each had one of its three brigades deployed
overseas on peacekeeping missions in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Every unit in those two divisions, down to nine-man squads, was
in fact ready for combat, division officers said. Had war broken
out somewhere, they were ready to go. But Army regulations require
any division with units deployed away from home be reported as not
combat ready.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush vowed that as president he would boost
military spending significantly, including a $1 billion military
pay increase. Previously, Bush has called for increases in spending
on military research and development and investment in a new
generation of high-tech weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   But defense budget analysts believe that anything short of
massive new funding could backfire and actually make readiness
worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the per-unit cost of weapons systems has risen as
fast as or faster than defense budgets. Congress might fund 100
airplanes, for instance, but get only 60 for the money initially
appropriated.
</P>
<P>
   This means that today's weapons cannot be replaced as they wear
out. As a result, Spinney said, the arsenal is getting older and
smaller at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Today, for example, the average Air Force jet fighter is already
14 years old. Many of the F-15s based at Langley Air Force Base in
Virginia, for example, are battered and patched and increasingly
difficult to maintain in flight status.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15, which costs $58.3 million, is due to be replaced by
the F-22, which costs $254.6 million, according to the most recent
Pentagon estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the F-22 program proceeds without any cost overruns or
schedule disruptions _ unlikely, given recent history _ the Air
Force will be unable to replace each F-15 with an F-22. In the
meantime, existing squadrons of F-15s and other fighters will wear
out.
</P>
<P>
   Without enormous increases in the budget for aircraft, or huge
cuts in the size of the tactical fighter force, the average age of
fighters will rise to 20 years in the latter part of this decade,
Spinney said. That means the Air Force may eventually have to keep
some of its fighters in service as long as 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like buying a Spad in 1918 and retiring it in 1960,''
Spinney said. ``This is the worst case, but it is a general pattern
for virtually all our weapons systems. And that's not giving our
boys the best.''
</P>
<P>
   And the cycle can't be broken without a level of defense funding
that would be politically unacceptable _ even to Gore and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's Inspector General's office identified a
compounding problem this spring: the Defense Department's books are
in a mess.
</P>
<P>
   In a report dated February 25, the inspector general said it had
identified a total of $6.9 trillion in data entries in the Pentagon
budget bookkeeping system. Of those, it found $2.3 trillion were
``unsupportable,'' meaning the auditors could find no link between
what Congress authorized and what was actually spent.
</P>
<P>
   The reported said that financial statements for the general
funds of the Army, Navy and Air Force ``were unauditable'' because
of fiscal irregularities and lack of supporting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this boils down to is, Job One is we gotta get better
books,'' said Spinney. ``We just don't have the detailed
information we need to sort out the real choices in readiness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9209 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-NNS     08-22 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CAMPAIGN RHETORIC IGNORES CORE DEFENSE PROBLEMS, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Aug. 22, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By DAVID WOOD  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
