<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FIBERWORKS0823-COX     08-22 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIBERWORKS0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiberworks to announce $60 million equipment purchase
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Powered with local investor cash and riding an
ambitious plan to connect office buildings with high-speed lines,
Fiberworks today will announce a $60 million deal to buy the Nortel
equipment needed to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   That deal, the purchase of optical networking equipment from the
telecom giant, is aimed at a potentially huge part of the market:
the so-called last mile to user desktops.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with metro Atlanta, where Fiberworks plans to install
about 400 miles of lines, the company means to provide ``last
mile'' service in scores of cities.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-employee, Lawrenceville-based company _ which plans to
move its corporate headquarters to Alpharetta _ has been installing
fiber lines around the Southeast, selling their use to a host of
carriers. Fiberworks has seen 100 percent-a-year growth _ from near
zero five years ago to about $6 million now.
</P>
<P>
   Among customers are Enron, Allied Riser Corp. and Urban Media
which, in turn, sell high-speed access to businesses and Internet
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the company looked at studies showing that 70 percent
of the data traffic going in and out of metro Atlanta was generated
by just 10 percent of the area's 19,000 office buildings.
Fiberworks is embarking on a five-year plan to hook fiber to
another thousand of those buildings, which average 75,000 square
feet and 300 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Fiberworks is operating in a crowded field, but Don Smith,
president of Optical Internet at Nortel Networks, dismissed the
industry buzz about a ``bandwidth glut.'' Conventional wisdom has
it that the demand for high-speed services can't keep pace with the
scores of providers installing thousands of miles of high-capacity
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been very rapid ramping increases, massive growth,
year after year,'' said Smith. ``And at the end of the day, it's
about bandwidth _ how much is needed? How much will be used?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the supply of high-speed connections has soared.
</P>
<P>
   Entrenched phone companies like BellSouth, in addition to using
copper wires for digital subscriber lines, have also installed
thousands of miles of fiber, especially in new neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Others like WorldCom, Qwest Communications, Williams and Level 3
are pushing ``the fat pipes,'' fiber that can handle huge amounts
of data. And companies like Winstar and Teligent are selling a
high-speed wireless solution. Meanwhile, cable companies like
Comcast and AT&AMP;T-owned MediaOne are upgrading their networks to
handle high-speed transmissions of phone, data and video.
</P>
<P>
   Fiberworks doesn't share Wall Street nervousness about a crowded
field, said Scott P. Burkholder, president and chief executive
officer of the 5-year-old company. ``The demand for services is
insatiable right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, in the fight for the last mile, fiber is way behind.
Copper goes into every building. Wireless can be quickly deployed.
But while thousands of miles of fiber have been installed through
metro Atlanta and around the United States, most of it is between
cities or through the heart of business districts. Connections
still must pass that last mile over copper. Maximum data rates on
copper are about 1.5 mbps (the installations that are later bought
or leased and resold by big names like Qwest or WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   All those builders and carriers lease to each other even as they
compete. In the cities of the Southeast, the biggest purveyor of
fiber is BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The company has put down about 68,000 miles of fiber in metro
Atlanta, said Bill Carver, spokesman for BellSouth. While much of
that is ``backbone'' down main streets and through densely
populated areas, more of it all the time connects to customers, he
said. ``There is fiber run into some buildings, and we expect
continued growth in the number of buildings we build fiber to.''
</P>
<P>
   Small fish often feel they can outmaneuver the big ones, of
course. Burkholder acknowledged that BellSouth's resources dwarf
those of the minnows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to wiring, we think of buildings. They think of
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
