<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-1st-LEDE-     08-22 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-1st-LEDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A `SURVIVOR' FAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Eds: Minor editing throughout)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you imagine? A recent supplicant on ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' had no idea that the Tagi and Pagong tribes on
``Survivor'' had merged and become the Rattana tribe. True, Rattana
sounds like something from the Martha Stewart Designer Fescue
Collection, but how could someone not know? Was she (A) a part-time
hermit, (B) a cloistered nun, (C) a pop-culture illiterate or (D) a
complete doofus?
</P>
<P>
   None of the above. Turns out she has a life and doesn't watch
``Survivor.'' Such a charming concept.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a life that cost her some serious cash on
``Millionaire.'' Cash that the rest of us nimrods could have put to
good use on, say, a big-screen, plasma-screen, you-screen,
I-screen, we-all-screen home entertainment system _ something to
lend proper gravitas to Wednesday night's mother of all tribal
councils: the season finale of ``Survivor,'' the Borneo chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Or we could have cornered the market on presto logs and built
one honkin' bonfire. As Jeff Probst, the king of khaki, the caliph
of the camp shirt, likes to say, fire represents life on the
island. I figure as long as there's a Duraflame going in my Weber,
I have a life.
</P>
<P>
   What? You were expecting rational thought?
</P>
<P>
   'Scuse me, but I've been listening to Richard Hatch's
pseudo-intellectual bushwa for 12 weeks. I came this close to
offering up novenas so Susan Hawk might be banished from this
planet (and the ones to our immediate left and right, just to be
safe). I considered hiring a few Cuban-Americans still hopped up
over the Elian Gonzalez thing to stage a little insurrection and
have Gretchen Cordy installed as queen of Pulau Tiga.
</P>
<P>
   So don't expect a logical argument, Bunky. My name is John, and
I'm a ``Survivor'' fan. The logic chromosome went tapioca about the
same time the Tagis decided they could do without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has been the greatest escape since Steve McQueen's
motorcycle ride through the German countryside. And Wednesday's
finale, likely to be watched by more than 30 million Americans with
nothing better to do, is the millennium's first entry in the ``Who
Shot J.R.?'' collection of don't-miss episodes. It's got fire. It's
got suspense. It's got the big payoff.
</P>
<P>
   It's also got wacky characters. People we sorta like, people we
sorta don't, people we'd like Tony Soprano to whack if he's ever
vacationing in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, right. We're not in Borneo anymore, Toto. This whole thing
was filmed months ago, and the ultimate survivor has probably
already spent his/her million dollars at Sylvan Delearning Center,
trying to unremember Richard's naked avoirdupois.
</P>
<P>
   What makes me think Richard isn't the big winner, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. It just can't be. Sure, oil rises to the top, but
come on! Richard seems like the standard slab of USDA Slime who
becomes a consultant because he's a good blatherskite and not much
else. OK, he can catch slimy things on the ocean floor. Whaddya
expect? Slime knows slime.
</P>
<P>
   As for Susan, well, don't get me started. Just because she's a
self-proclaimed redneck doesn't give her permission to be a boor.
And don't give me this twaddle about her being feisty and
independent. She's Richard's lap dog. She gives rednecks a bad
name. And remember: They both lied to Mr. Probst, the fuehrer of
the flame, the bailiff of the ballots, when he asked if there was a
voting alliance in place.
</P>
<P>
   Do we want a toad or his toady taking a chunk of CBS's millions?
(A 30-second commercial on Wednesday's finale cost $600,000.) Do we
want to reward duplicitous behavior? (Sonja Christopher, the first
person voted off the island, says this is her biggest fear.)
</P>
<P>
   I say nay! Let's give it to Rudy Boesch, the ex-Navy guy. He's
not someone I'd want to spend 39 days with, or even 39 minutes. But
at least he's honest. And his laconic performance in last week's
immunity challenge _ ``I dunno, I dunno, I dunno'' _ was the
highlight of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if Rudy wins, CBS will be able to say it hasn't
abandoned its core audience of viewers older than 50 who are a tad
uncomfortable among homosexuals. What a coup that would be. While
celebrating the victory of a homophobic septuagenarian, the network
would have a whole new bloc of younger viewers absolutely atingle,
practicing for ``Survivor II'' by noshing on the flora and fauna in
their crisper drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the next ``Survivor,'' which will take place in
the Australia bush and debut after the Super Bowl on Jan. 28, may
not be as much fun as the first, or even as much fun as
Australian-rules football. You can bet your last Sacajawea that
everyone will be forming factions from the get-go, which should
make ``Survivor II'' seem pretty much like another day at the
office. At least Wednesday night's final four has one semilikable
person in it: the waffly Kelly Wiglesworth. Come next winter, the
final four will look like everyone you never liked in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Nosirree, Bob. There may never be anything to match the
unbridled goofiness of this first ``Survivor.'' It was new. It was
different. And if you'll allow me to go all existential on you
here, it was the perfect exercise in determining what's right and
what's wrong in a universe with no rules. It was a soap opera with
people who don't look like soap stars. They didn't even have soap.
And don't think for a minute that producer Mark Burnett, the new
golden boy of television, hasn't been manipulating us like a bunch
of soap fans by carefully choosing which footage to use on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, ``Survivor'' is like good junk food, the stuff you
know you shouldn't eat but still consume on special occasions: the
milkshakes at Dick's, the french fries at McDonald's, the hot dogs
at Costco. They won't kill you if you only eat them now and then.
Like, say, once a week.
</P>
<P>
   That's where ABC went wrong with ``Millioniare,'' and CBS with
``Big Brother.'' They're on way too often. That sort of diet will
inevitably take you down. Indeed, Wednesday's two-hour finale of
``Survivor'' plus an hourlong ``town meeting'' with Bryant Gumbel
and the complete cast at 10, could cause some serious bloating.
</P>
<P>
   But we ``Survivor'' survivors can handle it. Just toss a few
more larvae on the barbie, would you?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-WEB-CONFERENCING-HARV     08-22 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CONFERENCING-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB CONFERENCING: A NEW WAY TO CONNECT VISUALLY WITH CUSTOMERS,
EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., June 22, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Managers used to have only two choices when it came to getting
employees from distant locations together to discuss information:
Send them by plane, train or automobile to meet in person, or set
up an audio conference.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's another alternative. A Web conference _ essentially
an audio conference with visuals _ enables managers to communicate
visual information to a group and yet never ask them to leave their
offices.
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT WORKS
</P>
<P>
   To launch a Web conference, the manager who's organizing it just
asks interested parties to log onto a URL. at the same time,
participants dial into an audio conference. (Putting out both audio
and visual information simultaneously on computers is possible but
still considerably more primitive and unreliable.)
</P>
<P>
   What the participants see is a screen that the meeting
coordinator controls. He or she can present visual information in
any format, from streaming video to PowerPoint slides to notes in
Word. Other optional features include chat lines, group white
boards and note-taking devices.
</P>
<P>
   As with any relatively new technology, there are glitches. First
is the Web itself. It can go down at the user end, be maddeningly
slow or annoy users with its sometimes sophomoric interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Web conferencing technology is still imperfect. The more
complicated the visuals, the slower and jerkier they can appear.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, to be successful in this new genre, the meeting
organizer must coordinate the smooth delivery of the visuals with a
successful audio conference. Either one of these tasks can be
daunting for the average stressed-out businessperson. Doing both at
once may be beyond the grasp of many.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite these hazards, the use of Web conferencing is
spreading rapidly. For example, brokerage houses are beginning to
use it to hold analysts' briefings.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a quarterly basis, they used to do a teleconference and now
they'll do a Web-based meeting. The presenter will send out a slide
show and the audio to maybe 300 to 400 analysts and investors
around the country,'' says Mike Archer, president of PresentPLUS, a
Web conferencing company based in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those people will not interact very much,'' Archer adds.
``They won't use any of the interactive tools that are available
even in a Java (Web) format. It's one-way communication.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, other companies are beginning to do training with
smaller groups of employees using Web conferencing with interactive
features.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Web conferencing is so inexpensive,'' Archer says,
``Hewlett-Packard and Rockwell Automation both do training shows
twice a month. That way, even though the information is not
terribly critical, they can get it out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Reed Hoke III, publisher of Direct Marketing, identifies
another use for Web conferencing: ``The small businesses that I
deal with belong to direct marketing clubs that sponsor regional
meetings with phenomenal speakers,'' he says. ``But people can't
get there. This technology is going to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales presentations similarly become much more cost-effective
when delivered over the Web, if only because salespeople can reach
many more customers without leaving the office. It remains an open
question as to how many new customers can be brought in using the
relatively impersonal Web format, but the Web can be used to
communicate regularly with well-established customers.
</P>
<P>
   The economics are often compelling. For somewhere around $5,000
per site per hour-long event, companies can set up fully
interactive rooms for their employees to hear the latest strategic
thinking or fiscal year plans.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive Web conferencing may never completely replace the
dynamics of a face-to-face meeting. The technology is still in its
adolescence and has its awkward moments. Links go down, screens are
small, the video can be blurry depending on the available bandwidth
and the quality of the equipment. Moreover, we humans are animals,
and we learn to trust each other by getting physically close
together.
</P>
<P>
   But after contemplating the time or expense involved in yet
another round of travel to distant places for a meeting with work
colleagues, remember that there is an alternative to the meeting
... and it's virtual.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
