<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMPLOYEE-REVIEWS-WITH-TEETH-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMANCE APPRAISALS WITH TEETH: CAN THEY WORK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Aug. 22, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At most companies, giving or getting a performance appraisal has
all the appeal of a trip to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers often loathe doing appraisals. If they thought they
could get away with it, they'd skip the repulsive chore entirely,''
observes a new study of best-practice performance management by the
American Productivity &AMP; Quality Center, or APQC, in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies are finding ways to abolish formal these
unpopular evaluations. Even so, most organizations grit their teeth
and plow ahead, if only because they feel a need for some way of
assessing employees' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants the results and outputs that a reliable
performance appraisal system can deliver,'' APQC says.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is changing on the appraisal front. In the past,
performance appraisals were often treated as a charade in which
employees, like the children of Lake Wobegon, were all rated above
average.
</P>
<P>
   No more. According to the APQC, best-practice companies now
believe that ``too few employees are terminated each year for poor
performance,'' and so are focusing their performance-management
systems specifically on weeding out noncontributors. These
companies are also beginning to single out star performers for pay
increases and other rewards not available to the majority of
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, performance-appraisal systems are now likely to
have teeth _ and employees are increasingly likely to be graded and
ranked like students in high school.
</P>
<P>
   This development presents managers with a dilemma, and not just
because assessing job performance is harder than grading answers on
a math test. The most successful work environments are those in
which people feel a sense of teamwork _ ``we're all in this
together'' _ and do whatever is required at the moment rather than
sticking to rigid job descriptions. Stratification and rankings
don't exactly encourage this collaborative attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the fear of losing your job because you're rated in
the bottom tenth. If politics creeps into the rankings _ and it may
_ the resentment will fester like mold on last week's vanilla
pudding.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a manager to do? One solution is to work with the
company's human resources department to ensure that the appraisal
system is perceived as fair.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the APQC says, many companies actively solicit
employee involvement in shaping the system, and then make a point
of surveying employees to assess its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   A second solution: Make sure the employees' performance reviews
focus on variables within their control. People are responsible for
their attitudes and work habits. They can't be held accountable for
performance problems caused by poor training, inadequate equipment
or conflicting instructions from management.
</P>
<P>
   Putting teeth in performance appraisals won't necessarily make
them more popular. So long as they're perceived as fair, though, it
may make them more effective.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
