<P>
   JUDGES-CAMPAIGNS (Undated) _ Alabama's judicial discipline panel
has filed charges against an incumbent justice of the state Supreme
Court, charging he falsely said in TV ads during the primary
campaign that his opponent ``let convicted drug dealers off'' at
least 40 times. Judicial campaigns in quite a few of the 40 states
that elect judges have recently become mudslinging matches. As a
result, judicial disciplinary panels are regularly trying to do
something unique in American politics: forcing candidates to stop
calling each other lazy, corrupt or soft on crime, unless they can
prove it. Across the country, judges are being fined, censured and
even threatened with removal for practicing that venerable
political art: exaggerating or outright lying during a campaign. By
William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI-SAFETY (Tokyo) _ The Mitsubishi Motors Corp.
acknowledged that it had systematically concealed customer
complaints about tens of thousands of defective automobiles over
the last three decades. The admission by Mitsubishi, Japan's No. 4
automaker, came a month after its top executive had denied
allegations that it had covered up repeated instances of problems
that included faulty gas tanks, gas caps, clutches, crankshafts and
brakes. As part of the admission, the company announced recalls
based on defects found in 88,000 cars and trucks, adding to a
recall of 532,000 vehicles announced last month. The recalls
include 50,000 vehicles exported to the United States. By Miki
Tanikawa.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL (New York) _ While most political debate over
education involves tweaking existing programs, charter schools
present a chance for teachers, parents, management companies and
bright young idealists to sit around a blank blackboard and imagine
a school from scratch. Charter schools, which get public funds but
are run without regulation from the local school district, have
been embraced by conservatives and liberals alike as an outlet for
innovation, what many see as the most dynamic and important
education reform movement in decades. Times reporter Jodi Wilgoren
looks at the opening of one such school in New York, Bronx
Preparatory, one of 380 new charter schools opening across the
country this fall. (1500 words)
</P>
