<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE TEST NYC TEACHERS MUST TAKE _ AND PASS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was pouring rain and I was seriously sleep-deprived the
morning I took the Liberal Arts and Sciences Test, New York state's
main certification exam for teachers. I had signed up for the
four-hour test on a whim, but when my alarm clock blared at 6:45
a.m. on July 15 _ a Saturday, no less _ I rued my bright idea.
</P>
<P>
   I was not looking to switch careers. As an education reporter
covering New York City schools, I had grown curious about the test,
which I had written about several times in my first year on the
beat. In one front-page story, I had reported that nearly a third
of the city's teachers had failed the certification exam at least
once. Yet several experienced teachers had told me the test was
ridiculously easy.
</P>
<P>
   I yearned for the truth. So on that rain-soaked morning, I
dragged myself to Edward R. Murrow High School in Brooklyn to see
for myself. For the record, I had not taken a standardized test
since 1986, as a high school senior hoping to boost my College
Board scores.
</P>
<P>
   At Murrow, I waited in line behind hundreds of other New Yorkers
anxious to prove they were fit to teach. Some, I knew from my
reporting, had failed the test repeatedly yet were still working as
uncertified teachers, the kind the state is pressuring the city to
get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   But at least they came prepared. Everybody but me, it seemed,
had a fistful of sharpened No. 2 pencils. I had just one, which I
unearthed in a frantic search of my apartment the night before.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only way I was poorly prepared. While others
spent weeks poring over test prep manuals, I took a single practice
exam. The questions had rattled me. You needed to remember the five
pillars of Islam, understand osmosis and know whether barbed wire
was invented before the telephone, to name a few. The math was so
beyond me that I skipped five questions altogether; it harked back
to trigonometry class, which I had not thought about since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Arts and Sciences Test is the most general of three
exams that teacher candidates have to pass to get a state teaching
license. It supposedly measures your knowledge of basic math and
science, history and the arts and humanities. It also asks you to
read and answer questions about literary passages and newspaper
articles, makes sure your grammar is correct and tests your writing
skills with an essay assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. As it turned out, though, the real thing was
considerably less taxing than my practice test. The exam was
tedious and long, with 80 multiple-choice questions plus the essay,
and more than a little frustrating. I can't reveal the actual
questions, because the state asked me not to. But I will say that
some questions _ especially those that asked me to interpret works
of art or literary passages _ seemed to have more than one right
answer. On others, I was convinced that none of the supplied
answers was right.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the math was much more manageable than I expected.
You basically had to know how to multiply, divide, read graphs and
do simple algebra equations. Determining the original price of a
sale item given the rate of discount, for example. Or calculating
someone's wages based on a sales commission.
</P>
<P>
   I also breezed through the section testing communications
skills. Analyzing newspaper excerpts, weighing objectivity,
interpreting figurative language and identifying grammatical and
structural errors came easily. But by the time I got to the essay
section, I was thoroughly burned out and my pencil was worn to the
nub. Moreover, the assignment _ to opine on whether the rich should
be taxed at a higher rate than the poor _ made my eyes glaze over.
</P>
<P>
   I ignored the test booklet's instructions to carefully outline
my essay on scrap paper first. I just started writing, breathlessly
making the case for a higher tax rate as if I was dashing off a
newspaper article on a crushing deadline. Afterward I sped home for
a long nap, and put the rather dismal experience out of my head
until my scores arrived in the mail this week.
</P>
<P>
   The good news: I passed, with a scaled score of 284 out of a
possible 300. (You need at least a 220.) But on closer examination,
my results made little sense. I got a perfect score, 300, on the
science and math section _ bizarre, considering that I failed out
of pre-calculus in high school and never took another science
course after 10th-grade chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I am mortified to report that my worst score _ a 260
_ was on the essay.
</P>
<P>
   What all this says about the state certification exam, I'm not
sure. If my experience is any indication, it's not the best measure
of someone's academic strengths and weaknesses. And, as with all
standardized tests, your performance might depend more on your
state of mind the day you take it than on your intellectual
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not a bad idea to make sure teachers can figure
percentages, form a scientific hypothesis, recognize symbolism in a
a short story and, yes, write a well-organized essay. If I were in
charge of the test, I'd probably make it a little tougher _ there's
just no excuse for someone like me to get a perfect score in math.
</P>
<P>
   But that could prove disastrous. Of the 4,315 people who took
the exam on July 15 in New York City, a whopping 41 percent failed,
according to the state. That compares with a 26 percent failure
rate for the 3,170 people who took the test elsewhere in the state.
Although it is not perfect, the exam seems a necessary gatekeeping
device for a profession whose purpose, after all, is imparting
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   I approve, and hope that I never have to take it again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1840EDT &QL; 
