<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday will be more humid than recent days in the Northeast
as breezes from the southwest increase ahead of a cold front.
Sunshine will fade behind increasing afternoon clouds in coastal
areas. Clouds and a broken band of showers and thunderstorms will
prevail from northern New England to the Ohio Valley. The showers
will shift to the Northeast and Middle Atlantic coasts Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will linger from the southern and central Plains to
the interior Southeast. Scattered thunderstorms will erupt near the
coast of the Gulf of Mexico, especially from northeastern Texas to
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be hot. Moist air at 10,000 feet will
promote numerous afternoon thundershowers from southeastern
California to the central and southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SUPER STORM
</P>
<P>
   Super Typhoon Bilis hit the southeast coast of Taiwan on
Wednesday with central winds estimated at 160 mph. Typhoon is the
name given to hurricanes that form over the western Pacific, where
the warm waters typically produce more frequent and powerful storms
than than their Atlantic counterparts. A typhoon or hurricane is
called ``super'' once its wind speeds exceed 150 mph. In the
Atlantic, Hurricane Debby is expected to stay off the north coast
of Hispaniola Wednesday as it moves west-northwest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
