<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9251 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-IPHONE0823-COX     08-22 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPHONE0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Japanese Internet phone technology a fit with the U.S.?
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Japan could be the future of wireless, or then again,
maybe it's just an interesting sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic and consumer culture that mass-marketed Pokemon,
Walkman and the videocassette recorder to the world has also
embraced some things _ minidisc players, high-definition
television, bullet trains _ that have not exactly caught fire in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So what to make of how Japan has taken to the i-mode Internet
phone from NTT DoCoMo? What are the chances of metro Atlanta seeing
something like it _ and would it become as universally loved here
as it is in Japan?
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo certainly seems to want to bring its technology
stateside _ it is reportedly in talks to make a major investment in
a joint wireless venture being formed by BellSouth and SBC.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Net phones have not taken America by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Net service offered by phone carriers in the United
States is generally slow, limited and costly _ a sad experience
compared to the Internet experienced by users from their desktops.
Wireless in this country is at least a year behind Europe, which is
as far behind Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan, where i-mode is king, 10 million users have signed
up since early last year. They send e-mail. They check train
schedules, the weather forecast and movie listings. They read
newspapers, play games, make airplane reservations, transact
banking business and have their fortunes told.
</P>
<P>
   And they are paying billions of dollars to NTT DoCoMo for the
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, unlike in the United States, home computers are
not common in Japan, where only about 13 percent of homes are wired
to the Internet via a desktop machine. For most people there, the
i-mode offered their first e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   For another, it's remarkably easy to use the i-mode from a
financial point of view. A user may pay a Web site a subscription
fee _ say $1 a month to have access to weather predictions or for
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Those fees appear on the user's monthly bill from NTT DoCoMo, as
do bills for purchases from Web sites that have deals with NTT
DoCoMo.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo takes a cut _ 9 percent _ from all those transactions
and charges the user based on how many packets of data he or she
transmits.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo has deals with scores of Web sites whose names appear
on the phone screen. Using the list, a user need only punch a
button to be connected. You can get to other sites, but it's not so
easy. And fees from those sites are billed separately.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that's the key. When the Americans mimic that
model, there will be similar enthusiasm, they say.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S., however, there are other ways to weave the wireless
Net into consumer lives, such as the Palm Pilot, and the nearly
ubiquitous desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in countries may mean that the i-mode culture
won't translate across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Without desktop monitors to compare it to, the Japanese do not
find viewing the Internet on a tiny screen so inherently
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   And Japan also has a longstanding culture of Gameboys and other
hand-held computer games. It has long workdays and long commutes in
which employees strain to find a way to use their time _ and the
stylishly designed i-mode fits right in.
</P>
<P>
   And Japanese have also long suffered with a sluggish banking
system. The i-mode made transactions possible anytime from
anywhere. Hundreds of the DoCoMo-approved sites are banks.
</P>
<P>
   The people might have ended up playing games and hitting the
Web, but they started off paying their bills, said Carlton Hill,
director of Internet initiatives for BellSouth Wireless. ``I
believe they bought the i-mode to answer a true practical need in
their lives. That is something that is unique to Japan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
