<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED STANDS PAT ON INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board, showing greater confidence that the
economy has begun to slow, have decided not to raise interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong campaign in which rates were boosted by a total
1.75 percent in an attempt to cool an overheated economy and
prevent a spiraling in inflation, Fed members voted Tuesday to
stand pat, instead letting their prior rate hikes do their work and
letting the economy run its course.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second meeting at which the Fed left the federal
funds rate unchanged at 6.5 percent, a level first set in May.
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers said the board's statement, which accompanies each
decision, was more upbeat about the prospects for a slowdown than
was its last statement, after its June 28 meeting. The Fed said
that growth ``is moderating'' toward a more reasonable pace. In
June, the Fed had said growth ``may be moderating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message (sent by the Fed) is we're headed in the right
direction _ toward an end to the tightening,'' said Allen Sinai,
president of Primark Decision Economics in Boston. ``But we're not
quite there.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, there was no use of the word ``slowdown,'' and
board members remained concerned about the potential for inflation
if the economic growth were to resume its torrid, early-year pace.
The Fed said the ``risks'' of inflation have not been removed yet,
and they adopted a bias toward future rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed is not expected to raise rates at its next meeting,
scheduled for Oct. 3, analysts said. Some economists, looking to
the presidential election in November, said the central bankers
would not take any action that would open them to charges of being
political. Others argued the Fed would abstain because it would not
yet have enough new data by then to make an informed decision.
</P>
<P>
   David Kresge, senior vice president of PrimeStreet.com, a Boston
company that matches small businesses to lenders, said the inaction
confirmed that Fed policy over the past year appears to be a
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are moderating about as well as the Fed could've
hoped,'' Kresge said, ``yet the economy isn't tightening up
abruptly'' and falling into recession, which often is a risk of
aggressive Fed interest-rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's decision was no surprise to those familiar with the
testimony given by Alan Greenspan in a July 20 speech to Congress.
The Fed chairman said he was encouraged by a possible
``acceleration'' in worker productivity, which tends to temper
inflationary pressures. He also said a ``flattening in equity
prices'' and a rise in consumer debt were dampening consumer
spending and a fall in housing starts would cut into demand for
such manufactured products as kitchen appliances.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's inaction also comes days after a report that the
consumer price index in July rose only 0.2 percent _ and 3.5
percent during the past year. There have been spotty signs of
slower growth in the data, particularly in industries sensitive to
interest rates, such as housing construction and car sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent data have indicated that the expansion of aggregate
demand is moderating toward a pace closer to the rate of growth of
the economy's potential to produce,'' the Fed said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite positive signs, Fed members said in a boilerplate
sentence similar to those in prior statements that they remained
``concerned about the risk of a continuing gap between the growth
of demand and potential supply at a time when the utilization of
the pool of available workers remains at an unusually high level.''
In other words, they are concerned that rising wages would spark
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Glen Migliozzi, who heads the bond group for Fleet
Investment Advisors, saw a subtle but important shift in the Fed's
thinking about the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been raising rates all along to be preemptive about
inflation picking up,'' Migliozzi said. ``Now, I believe they will
shift to being reactive,'' raising rates once inflation becomes a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan's Fed watcher in New York, Mark Wanshel, said the
Fed's inaction ``was no surprise in any respect. There was very
little reaction in the markets to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose only 59.34 points, to 11,139.15, though the Blue
Chip index's slight gain continued the rally that has occurred in
recent days. The Nasdaq index of technology stocks rose just 5.06
points, to 3958.21.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Fed give any clues to its course of action to a Wall
Street that has watched every move. The Fed's comments, Wanshel
said, ``were not strong enough to give the market any new
information about the probabilities for Fed action down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1852EDT &QL; 
