<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BELSOUTH-WIRELESS0823     08-22 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELSOUTH-WIRELESS0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Japanese phone giant NTT looking at U.S. market
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - It took longer than expected, but the world's largest
telecom wallflower has finally started to dance.
</P>
<P>
   And that shuffle by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan and
its wireless subsidiary NTT DoCoMo could lead them to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are reportedly under way on a major investment by the
Japanese firms in the company being created by combining the
wireless units of SBC Communications and BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials all around decline comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's intent seems clear, said Perry Walter, analyst
with Robinson Humphrey. ``They have been very vocal about their
interest in the United States. They consider the U.S. a strategic
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover the technology used by NTT DoCoMo to connect wireless
users to the Internet is far better than what is offered in the
United States, he said. ``I think people would find it easier to
use, more graphically appealing and more feature-rich.''
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo is in talks aimed at arranging purchase of a 10 to 15
percent stake in the still-unnamed company, according to the
Financial Times. Injection of that cash _ probably between $5
billion and $10 billion _ would help SBC and BellSouth buy licenses
or companies needed to fill out the national footprint of the new
unit. The joint venture would be the second largest wireless
company in the U.S., behind only Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more intriguing is the implication that the
arrangement might include use of i-mode _ the wildly successful NTT
DoCoMo technology.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the SBC-BellSouth unit will have nearly 18 million
subscribers. But the future is not just voice. No one can say with
certainty exactly what wireless will look like in a few years, but
clearly the technology and the economics are driving the market
toward using wireless devices for a variety of jobs, including
Internet access and transactions. Neither BellSouth nor SBC has
done much yet in the consumer market with wireless Net access.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where i-mode shines.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of NTT DoCoMo's i-mode can send e-mail, check train
schedules and movie listings, read newspapers and are expected soon
to be able to download music off the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers generally consider the United States to be
far behind Japan in wireless Internet use. Since its launch in
early 1999, the i-mode has amassed more than 10 million users in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But success in Japan is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications is moving toward a world dominated by a
handful of global companies. The largest companies are supposed to
lead that trend and get ever-larger. In Europe, France Telecom,
British Telecom, Telefonica and Deutsche Telekom have been actively
expanding. In the U.S., AT&AMP;T has poured more than $100 billion into
buying cable networks, while WorldCom bought MCI and a host of
others before being stymied by regulators in its bid for Sprint.
SBC Communications now extends from the Pacific to its Northeast
border with the turf of Verizon, itself an amalgam of Bell
Atlantic, Nynex and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo needs to spread its influence _ and its investments.
And the company has the deep pockets to play catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a dramatic stock slide since the spring, NTT DoCoMo
shares are worth about a quarter of a trillion dollars _ more than
four times the stock value of BellSouth. The company has revenues
of $25.9 billion and earnings of $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, NTT has made investments in Europe and Asia, bid for
one U.S. company and is reportedly in talks aimed at taking a stake
in another.
</P>
<P>
   In its U.S. bid, NTT DoCoMo has been interested in buying a
piece of VoiceStream only to be shut out when Deutsche Telekom
agreed to pay $56 billion for the whole thing. That defeat could
work to its advantage _ if the Germans take all the heat during a
politically touchy moment.
</P>
<P>
   A group of U.S. Senators led by Ernest Hollings (D-S.C.) is on
record as opposing the Deutsche Telekom bid. Moreover, NTT DoCoMo
is apparently only shooting for an investment in BellSouth-SBC, not
a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   And the relationship would not be built from scratch. NTT DoCoMo
already has a 15 percent stake in KPN Mobile. The wireless unit of
KPN Telecom has been BellSouth's partner, and the three companies
last week were one of the winning bidders for a license to provide
new wireless services in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arrival of the Japanese on the U.S. wireless scene
could change the dynamics at BellSouth and SBC where there have
been no foreign investors. It would also potentially challenge the
technology being used by other U.S. providers for Net connections.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. carriers insist their technology is the equal of i-mode and
that DoCoMo's advantage has more to do with enlisting hundreds of
Web sites to tailor their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The most creative advance is in putting Web use and various
services all on the same i-mode bill, said Paul Reddick, vice
president for product management development at Sprint. ``That is
one thing they've done that is unique in Japan. But that is not
specific to i-mode, and just because it's not happening with U.S.
carriers doesn't mean that it can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
