<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-SUPER-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE: MY JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (Marek Ponichtera is a building superintendent in New York City;
this was written with Marchin Skomial)  
 By MAREK PONICHTERA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I set out for America 10 years ago with my new wife
and $500 that I had borrowed from friends.
</P>
<P>
   My wife's uncle picked us up at Kennedy Airport. He was the only
person we knew in this country _ and he was unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   My wife soon got a part-time job as a cleaning lady for a family
in Brooklyn. I couldn't find work, so I helped her out. I did
whatever I was told to do: sweeping the walk, washing windows,
changing bulbs. As payment, we received free room and board, but no
money. The family didn't speak Polish, but somehow we were able to
communicate through sign language and an English-Polish dictionary
that I always carried with me.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a year later, I got a job as a mason's helper at a
construction site. I carried 50-pound loads of bricks around _ not
easy, as I weigh about 140 pounds _ and I put in 10 hours to 12
hours a day, six days a week. My poor English was a worse
disadvantage than ever. Once, a worker asked me to bring him a
hammer. I nodded and fetched a screwdriver. He burst out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It was about then that I enrolled in a class to learn English. I
also picked up other trade skills, and in 1992 I got a job doing
carpentry, electrical work and painting.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, I was hired as superintendent of a residential
building on West 85th Street. The pay and free housing seemed like
a good deal, but I quickly realized I had my work cut out for me. I
was responsible for the whole building, and anyone who needed
something done in his apartment called me to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Once, on a Sunday evening when I was getting ready to go out to
a movie with my wife, my intercom started ringing. Someone had a
leak in his apartment and the water had dripped into the apartment
underneath. It took me two hours to solve that problem, and when I
got back to our apartment, my wife handed me a sheet of paper with
two other assignments: In both cases, a toilets had gotten clogged
and the tenant was in desperate need of a plunger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, my boss asked me to supervise the renovation of
apartments at a much larger building he owned on West 90th Street.
Although my title was still superintendent, I no longer had to deal
with leaks and clogged toilets. I hired a porter to take care of
those chores, while I sat in my office in the basement, ordering
paint and sheetrock and hiring workers, mostly newly arrived Poles
who couldn't speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Once, my boss started shouting at a group of them _ unloading
steel pipes from a truck _ to work faster. They ignored him. When I
saw what was happening, I hurried to explain to him that none of
them understood a word he was saying.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I am surprised at how rude people can be. Perfect
strangers will make disdainful comments about my work clothes,
which are often spattered with paint, for example.
</P>
<P>
   One Sunday, when my porter was off duty, a lady asked me to come
to her apartment immediately to fix her air conditioner, While I
was working, she asked me about my family and background. At some
point, she started to express dissatisfaction with my Polish accent
and the fact that I came from a formerly Communist country. It
didn't seem to matter to her that she herself came from Romania _
and had a Romanian accent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-BOS &LR;      08-22 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH TO REPLACE SUV TIRES DEFLATES DEALERS' SUPPLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Firestore's voluntary recall is gobbling up so many sport
utility vehicle tires that dealers say their supplies are nearly
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The tire shortage not only means more scrambling for owners of
Ford Explorers covered by the Firestore recall, but also means
anyone with an SUV using the same-size tire is going to have a hard
time finding replacements. The shortage is driving up the cost of
tires as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have virtually nothing left,'' said Benjamin Kravetz,
president of Summit Tire of Massachusetts, a major tire wholesaler
in the state. ``There are literally millions of these tires on back
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bird, the owner of Marshfield (Mass.) Tire, said he's out of
name-brand sport utility tires and his suppliers are telling him he
could have a long wait before he gets new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like running an ice cream stand without ice cream,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage began developing shortly after Aug. 9, when
Firestone voluntarily recalled 6.5 million 15-inch ATX, ATX II, and
Wilderness AT tires. The tires, most of them sold as original
equipment on Ford Motor Co.'s best-selling Explorer SUV and the
Ford Ranger light truck, were linked to accidents, many involving
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone initially tried to phase in the recall, focusing on
southern states first. But it then allowed customers across the
country to pull into Firestone tire centers and have replacement
tires from Firestone and other manufacturers put on at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone subsequently allowed customers to purchase
similar-size tires directly from any tire dealer and be reimbursed
up to $100 per tire, including mounting, balancing, and taxes.
Local dealers say the $100 doesn't always cover the entire
replacement cost, particularly for more expensive tires such as
Michelins.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for tires has been so strong many dealers say they
are running out of the type of tires that go on most midsize SUVs
and light trucks. The size is identified as P235/75R15.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone and other tire manufacturers are ramping up production
of the SUV tires, but officials say it may be a while, possibly
many months, before the shortage begins to subside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making and shipping tires as fast as we can, but we
can't keep up with demand,'' said Chuck Sinclair, a spokesman for
Goodyear Tire in Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear's Web site (www.goodyear.com) offers information on
replacement tires and suggests consumers call their local dealer
and place an order.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sinclair at Goodyear said the company isn't raising its
prices, dealers locally say most tire prices are going up. Several
dealers said the prices they are paying for tires have increased at
least 5 percent, a hike that is being passed along to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are getting very upset,'' said Nicky Cerundolo,
manager of Arlington (Mass.) Tire and Auto Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cerundolo said he has sold more than 200 replacement tires since
Firestone announced its recall Aug. 9. He was down to his last four
Uniroyals Tuesday and doesn't know when he'll get more in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to consumers is to move quick,'' he said. ``Nobody
has them in stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Kravetz said he believes the heavy emphasis by manufacturers on
the production of SUV tires will eventually result in shortages of
tires in other sizes. ``There's going to be shortages of other tire
sizes in a couple months,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Tire industry officials say many consumers affected by the
recall are demanding tires of similar quality, but with the
shortage many who want new tires immediately are being forced to
consider non-brand name tires or tires not designed specifically
for SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come to a point where people are going to say,
`I don't care what it is, put it on,' '' said Bob Laroche,
wholesale manager at Maynard and Lessieur in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
