<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY CENTER HONORS 5 PERFORMERS, 3 OF WHOM ARE FOREIGN-BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts
announced the recipients of its annual honors for outstanding
American performers Tuesday, and for the first time since the
awards were established 22 years ago, most of the recipients are
foreign-born.
</P>
<P>
   They are the dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov, born in Riga, Latvia;
the tenor Placido Domingo, born in Madrid; and the actress Angela
Lansbury, whose London roots are probably little known to millions
of television viewers who remember her mainly as an all-American
amateur detective in ``Murder, She Wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   They are to receive their awards in December with two recipients
born in the United States: the rock 'n' roll legend Chuck Berry,
born in St. Louis, and the actor and director Clint Eastwood, born
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When the abundance of foreign-born recipients was mentioned to
Baryshnikov, he said: ``Isn't that the tradition of this country?
It is so wonderful to immigrants, and I am one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by telephone in the Dominican Republic, where he is
vacationing, he added: ``I am very excited and honored, but
accepting this award makes me uncomfortable because so many artists
I have worked with in the past 25 years deserve this recognition
more than me. I will hold a place in line for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov, now 52, defected in 1974 from the Soviet Union,
where he had been a member of the Kirov Ballet, and joined American
Ballet Theater in New York. He shifted to the New York City Ballet
in 1978 to work with George Balanchine and Jerome Robbins, who have
also been honored by the Kennedy Center. He rejoined American
Ballet Theater in 1980 as principal dancer and artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   Domingo, 59, has sung 115 roles in the works of Verdi, Wagner,
Puccini and others. He has also conducted widely and has taken on
administrative roles at the Washington and Los Angeles Operas.
</P>
<P>
   Lansbury, 74, has had several distinct chapters in her career,
including her early roles in Hollywood movies like ``National
Velvet'' with Elizabeth Taylor and ``The Long Hot Summer'' with
Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   At 22 she played a woman in her 40s who tries to come between
Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracey in a classic Washington
political movie, Frank Capra's ``State of the Union.'' Then she
shifted to the Broadway stage, where her performances included the
roles of the eccentric aunt in Jerry Herman's ``Mame'' and the
barber's murderous accomplice in Stephen Sondheim's ``Sweeney
Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   She then turned to television detective work, solving a killing
every week for 12 years and finding an entirely new audience on
``Murder, She Wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 73, the singer-songwriter and guitarist regarded as an
originator of rock 'n' roll, has been cited as an influence by the
Beatles, the Rolling Stones, Bob Dylan, Bruce Springsteen and
countless others. John Lennon once said, ``If you tried to give
rock 'n' roll another name, you might call it `Chuck Berry.'''
</P>
<P>
   His first recording, ``Maybelline,'' was a hit in 1955. Other
big sellers include ``Roll Over Beethoven,'' ``School Days'' and
``Johnny B. Goode.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry is the first Kennedy Center honors recipient to have
served time in prison; in 1959 he received a two-year sentence on a
morals case that involved a teen-age girl in his St. Louis club.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood, 70, appeared in a string of B-movies in the 1950s
before landing a role on the long-running television series
``Rawhide.'' He went from there to the spaghetti westerns directed
in Europe by Sergio Leone that made Eastwood a star: ``A Fistful of
Dollars,'' ``For a Few Dollars More'' and ``The Good, the Bad and
the Ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the United States and played many tough-guy
roles, becoming the leading box office draw by 1969, and following
up with ``Dirty Harry'' in 1971, his most popular role. Eastwood
has directed many films, including ``Bridges of Madison County.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign-born performers have received many Kennedy Center Honors
in the past, and in 1986 three of the six recipients were from
abroad. They are being cited, in the words of James A. Johnson,
chairman of the Kennedy Center, ``for the unique and extremely
valuable contributions they have made to the cultural life of our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners are to be honored on Dec. 3 at the Kennedy Center
Opera House in a gala performance that is the center's principal
fund-raising event of the year. The program will be taped and
broadcast on CBS later in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
