<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHARK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-22 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SHARK NET': MURDER AND OTHER GROWING PAINS IN PERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perth _ the most isolated city in the world, or so they like to
say there out there on the western coast of Australia _ sits facing
the Indian Ocean, which stretches endlessly to Africa. Robert
Drewe, the Australian novelist and playwright who grew up there,
makes the place sound a bit like Albert Camus' North Africa,
blinding in its brightness and dominated by the maritime elements:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing in the straight white coastline to give your
eyes a rest _ no bays, few trees to break the line and the glare
and the shuddering mirages. Often on hot days the smell of
something dead rose from the dunes and filled your head. ... You
became dizzy and got a headache if you looked toward Africa too
long.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that smell of something dead that is the suggestive
element in ``The Shark Net,'' Drewe's spiced and savory memoir of
his boyhood years in Perth, when the rampages of a serial killer
mingled with the more normal events of a young life, making them
all seem like threads of the same tableau. Or perhaps these other
events are not so normal after all. They only seem that way in
comparison with the murders committed by one Eric Cooke, a possibly
insane man who shot or stabbed eight strangers to death in Perth
between 1959 and 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Drewe treats all of this, normal and not, with a kind of
quizzical power of observation that gives his book a whiff of
mystery and plenty of charm.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with a description of the light in the courtroom in
which Cooke was convicted of murder: ``harsher, dustier, more
ancient looking'' than normal light. He lets us know early on that
the trial, somehow, would be an instrument in the transformation of
his own life. He was on the scene as a reporter for The West
Australian, the newspaper that Drewe, still only 19, had begun
working for shortly before. But he soon lets us know that the
trial, taking place amid the ordinary artifacts of conventional
suburban life, was affecting him deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The murders had stopped,'' he writes. ``Life would go on. But
it was clear that my life wouldn't continue as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Drewe's memoir in a sense explains why this was so,
though he doesn't provide a full explanation until he returns to
Cooke's trial near the end of the book. In the meantime he provides
a chronicle of growing up in a normatively dysfunctional family in
sun-stroked, sea-dazzled Perth, a chronicle wherein the mature man
attains a kind of bemused control over the eager foolishness of his
earlier self.
</P>
<P>
   Drewe's father was a state manager for Dunlop, the rubber
company, in which he invested emotions that he did not bestow on
his family. His mother suffered quietly and yearned for more, which
Drewe, the oldest of her three children, discovered when he went
with her to hear a speech by the evangelist Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   The series of murders that terrified Perth during Drewe's
teen-age years were personal to him because he knew one of the
victims _ a boy named John Sturkey, shot in the head while he slept
on the porch of his rooming house _ and he knew Cooke. Drewe
provides telling glimpses of Cooke as a misfit who was ridiculed
growing up because of a harelip and a speech impediment. He
remembers him lurking at Saturday night parties and approaching
young women, who spurned him, even as his wife and seven children
stayed at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shark Net'' is not what you would call a true crime story;
its purpose is not to delve deeply into the minds of a killer and
the police officers who caught him. But as Drewe recounts his young
man's wonderment at the criminal and the evil he wrought, he does
cast some doubt on a legal system that, first, convicted two other
men of two of the crimes that Cooke committed and gave only the
most passing consideration to the possibility that he was insane.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Drewe was growing up, forced to do so quickly when his
girlfriend got pregnant and, not long after that, his mother died
of a cerebral aneurysm. Drewe marvelously evokes the residual
Victorian primness of his childhood in a conversation he had with
his family's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably been wondering whether you killed her,'' the
good doctor begins, referring to the shock Drewe's mother
experienced when she learned that he had a girlfriend (of a
different religion no less) and that she was pregnant. It is not
certain, the doctor goes on. Then, prescribing phenobarbital to the
young Robert, he reduces this searing moral question to a handy
piece of arithmetic: ``I think we're looking at a 60-40
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Drewe, though young, is happy in his marriage and with the son
who soon comes along. He works hard as a reporter, hoping, as he
looks for stories of shark attacks along the Perthian coast, that
an attack will happen and that he can become a hero by leaping into
the waves and saving someone. But then he is scooped by a rival
reporter who learns that Drewe's friend has drowned in the heavy
surf that Drewe had swum in the same day, which leads him to a
brief disquisition on the shark nets of his title, those screens
the authorities put up to protect swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Drewe does not seem to be in favor of shark nets: you've got a
better chance of dying in a plane crash or from just plain
foolishness than you do being attacked by a shark. Sharks here
represent the human imagination, how we organize the data of
experience in our minds as we react to the presence of a mad killer
among us, or perhaps to the death of a mother or to some of the
lesser accidents of life. In the deepest sense Drewe's affecting
memoir is the story of how one man comes to terms with the absence
of ultimate protection, with the reality that for some things the
only safety net comes from within.
</P>
<P>
   THE SHARK NET  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Drewe  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   289 pages. Viking. $24.95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A retrospective on the career of George V. Higgins is available
with a review of his posthumous novel, ``At End of Day,'' at The
New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
