<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GILLETTE-STATIONERY-B     08-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-STATIONERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE DIVESTS STATIONERY DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Looking to focus on core product lines such as razors,
batteries, and oral-care products, Gillette Co. has agreed to sell
its struggling stationery division to Newell Rubbermaid Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Though a sales agreement had been expected, terms of the
transaction were not disclosed Tuesday, nor would Gillette publicly
discuss the fate of roughly 4,000 employees who work in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still confidential,'' said Nicola Pugliese, Gillette's
director of financial communications.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stationery business, which includes such brands as
Paper Mate, Parker, Waterman, and Liquid Paper, accounts for about
10 percent of Gillette's total work force.
</P>
<P>
   Only one plant making stationery products is in the United
States, and that plant is in California, Pugliese said; others are
in such countries as England, France, and India.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gillette chairman and chief executive Michael C.
Hawley said, ``Our resources will now be devoted to the three core
businesses of grooming, portable power, and oral care.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the proposed sales price ranged from $500 million
to $750 million. Over the years, Gillette paid a total of about
$572 million for various pen brands it bought.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to be relieved that a sales agreement finally
had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very logical,'' said Fredric E. Russell of Fredric E.
Russell Investment Management Co., an Oklahoma firm that owns
Gillette shares. ``This is very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, as investors complained about Gillette's subpar
performance, Gillette hinted that it might sell its stationery
division and some Braun appliance lines. In June, it announced it
had entered talks to sell its stationery business to Newell.
Gillette recently said it plans to hang onto its Braun small
household appliance lines.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Gillette's strategy has been to take household
products that some might regard as commodities and improve them
with technical innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette then uses aggressive marketing campaigns to convince
consumers that its improved products are worth a premium price.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has worked splendidly with razors such as the
Mach3, but less well with pens, and some Wall Street analysts have
recently begun to wonder whether this game plan can work long-term
for Gillette's Duracell batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stationery sales have declined sharply, perhaps in
part because the company isn't as dominant in the pen business as
it is in some of its other product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gillette reported stationery sales of $743 million
and a divisional profit from operations of $18 million. In 1997, it
said it had $156 million in profit from operations on stationery
sales of $924 million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Gillette had total sales of just under $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette put together its stationery portfolio bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, it bought the Paper Mate brand for $15.2 million. In
1979, it bought Liquid Paper for $69.9 million. In 1987, it bought
Waterman pens for $39.4 million. And in 1993, it bought the Parker
pen brand for $447 million.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, Gillette had a phenomenal run.
</P>
<P>
   But about two years ago, economic problems in some key foreign
markets combined with a strong dollar to slow Gillette's momentum.
More recently, investors have fretted about fierce competition in
the battery market, which has hurt Duracell.
</P>
<P>
   Of the stationery brands, Ariel Capital analyst Todd Griesbach
said: ``These are good brands that have been undermanaged by
Gillette. Newell is much more focused on stationery products,
including writing instruments. There will also be a lot of
manufacturing synergies.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Illinois, Newell had 1999 sales of $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette shares closed at $31.13 up $1.31. Newell shares rose 50
cents to $26. Both companies trade on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
