<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXCERPTS FROM GORE INTERVIEW ON MILITARY POLICY
 &HT;    With GORE.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Here are highlights from an interview with Vice
President Al Gore following his speech earlier Monday to the
Veterans of Foreign Wars national convention in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In your speech to the VFW today, you said you were ``so
concerned'' by ``others trying to run down America's military for
political advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   A. (Laughs) You're not going to make me say who, are you?
</P>
<P>
   Q. I think reasonable people can conclude that you're talking
about Governor Bush. But let me ask you this: military policy is
certainly a legitimate political issue for debate in a presidential
campaign. But at what point does criticism of military policy cross
the line?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have long since begun the increased investments in
modernization and readiness that are needed. And therefore, I would
never say that it's not legitimate to raise questions about how
much investment of that sort is needed. I've pledged to continue
the increases. In fact, it was an issue in the primary contest,
where I called for increased defense spending and my opponent did
not.
</P>
<P>
   But to go beyond that and to say that two divisions can't even
respond to a call to deploy, or to imply that our fighting forces
are not the most capable in the world by far, that's mistaken. And
I don't think that it's helpful to the country to put an inaccurate
impression out there.
</P>
<P>
   I think people probably take it with a grain of salt. So I don't
want to overstate how much damage is done by it. I don't think it's
a lot. But it's just the kind of thing that ought to be accurate if
you're going to say it. The Pentagon immediately set the record
straight.
</P>
<P>
   And look, we picked a Republican to run the Defense Department,
partly to take military policy out of the political arena. I
strongly recommended Bill Cohen. I had served with him in the
Senate. He and I served on the Armed Services Committee with Sam
Nunn. And he and Sam and I were a threesome in working with Norm
Dicks in the House (a Democrat from Washington state first elected
in 1976) to advance the strategic forces modernization agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary Cohen offered my opponent a briefing on some of these
issues and he turned it down and accused Bill of partisan politics.
Well, Bill hasn't even endorsed me. In fact, he's said publicly
that he would probably vote for my opponent because of his party
affiliation, although _ and I haven't talked to him _ I doubt very
seriously that he would say that now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Today's newspapers include accounts of a new team of arms
inspectors being sent into Iraq, possibly setting the stage for
another confrontation with Saddam Hussein. And that raises the
question of what kind of commander-in-chief George Bush was. Also,
it's an issue in the context of the military the Clinton-Gore
administration inherited from the Bush administration and the fact
that he left Saddam in power. And you voted with Bush on the Gulf
war.
</P>
<P>
   A. I did. I have always defended former President Bush's
decision to pull back when he had the knife at Saddam's throat. I
think it was a mistake, and I've said that I thought that decision
was a mistake. But I also know the pressures that he and our
country faced at the time, having put together an international
coalition that included Egypt and Syria and other Arab countries.
And I understood how, having achieved the narrow objective he
established for Operation Desert Storm. So while I have said it was
a mistake, I've also said it was an understandable mistake.
Therefore, it does not in my view fall into the category of huge
blunders that greatly damaged our national security. I think it was
a mistake, but I think we ought to cut him some slack on it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Nearly every presidential candidate in my lifetime has talked
about improving benefits for veterans. And yet, conditions at VA
hospitals are often deplorable. And benefits seem inadequate. So
why should a voter think you would do any better?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have brought about some significant improvements, but the
challenge continues to grow with the aging of the veterans
population, particularly the aging of the World War II vets, who,
like all the rest of us, have increasing medical needs as they age.
Therefore, we have to make this a decision to make this a priority,
and I will.
</P>
<P>
   I've been involved through the reinventing government work in
getting to know a lot of the most effective regional VA
administrators. We've actually implemented some of the ideas out of
the Reinventing Government Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   I've had some experience with how to listen carefully to the VA
employees and make some of the changes that can improve the quality
of life for veterans seeking health care.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Because you're a veteran, do you feel a special obligation to
them?
</P>
<P>
   A. I sure do, especially since I've a veteran who, as I said
today, didn't do the most or run the gravest risk. I know the guys
who did that. I want to make sure that our country, by God, does
right by them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Sometimes this election sounds like it's taking place in the
1980s, about ``Star Wars'' and other expensive weapons systems.
Haven't we had this debate before?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. But there certainly are disagreements and I think they
should be debated, because a lot is a stake, both in terms of the
astronomical costs involved and, more importantly, the dangers of
restarting an arms race with Russia and kindling a new one with
China if we don't approach it in the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
