<HEADLINE>
THE (UN)FROZEN NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 23, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By EDMUND BLAIR BOLLES    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 19th century's dream of an open polar sea has become the
21st century's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend's news that an icebreaker arriving at the North
Pole had found open water instead of ice means that the fantasies
of 19th century explorers are now a reality _ one with potentially
dire implications for the environment. A hundred and fifty years
ago, such a discovery would have been a cause for celebration. In
1853, for example, the American explorer Elisha Kent Kane sailed
north to Greenland, determined to find an open polar sea and with
it a shortcut to China. The details of his journey inspired Jules
Verne's novel of 1866, ``At the North Pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Were pioneering arctic explorers like Elisha Kent Kane crazy?
Didn't they know the North was frozen? Sure, they knew that the
Arctic was frozen; whaling ships had been hunting in Baffin Bay for
centuries, and sailors had seen the ice packs. But no one had yet
been to the North Pole. The explorers were hopeful that, like a
lake whose shores are frozen but whose middle is not, the Arctic
Ocean might contain open water at its center.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th century's optimism about finding a Northwest Passage
through the pole was founded on ignorance about climate change. In
1837, when the Swiss naturalist Louis Agassiz proposed that much of
the geology of northern Europe was the result of a geologically
recent Ice Age, he was greeted with shock and disbelief. To his
contemporaries, the idea of a glacier extending from the Arctic to
the Alps was inconceivable, as were the cold temperatures necessary
to sustain it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, optimism and ignorance have again gotten in the way of
understanding, this time in the debates over global warming. The
evidence of accumulating greenhouse gases in the earth's atmosphere
is indisputable, but optimists have insisted that this change does
not necessarily bode ill for the climate. Meanwhile, hard-nosed
experts have had to admit that they do not know enough to predict
precisely how global warming will affect life on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the broad implications are clear enough. A temperature
increase great enough to melt the northern icecap means a massive
reorganization of the earth's heat and water patterns. Some places
that have been able to support millions of inhabitants may in the
future be able to support only thousands. Some formerly
uninhabitable areas may eventually become suitable for farms and
cities, but settling and developing those areas will take
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, many people resist the notion that such a brutal
future is possible. The Rev. Jerry Falwell recently said on
late-night TV's ``Politically Incorrect'' that he thought global
warming was nonsense. Of course, he does not believe in evolution
or the Big Bang either, but he expresses an optimism about
Providence that many share.
</P>
<P>
   General acceptance of the Ice Age began only when Elisha Kent
Kane returned from his ill-fated search for an open polar sea. He
published a richly illustrated account of his experience that
enabled people to understand for the first time what arctic ice was
like. His discovery and account of the Humboldt Glacier, the
world's largest, astonished and impressed the world. Modern
Greenland became a popular metaphor for the old Ice Age.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the recent photographs of the open waters at the North
Pole will do the same for global warming theory. They show clearly
and unmistakably what so many experts had once thought impossible.
For the first time in 50 million years, we now have an open polar
sea.
</P>
<P>
   (Edmund Blair Bolles is the author of ``The Ice Finders: How a
Poet, a Professor and a Politician Discovered the Ice Age.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
