<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-AMERICA _ CHICAGO _ ``Welcome. We speak Spanish,''
said the sign in Spanish beckoning customers to get a haircut at a
suburban Chicago salon. But somewhere along the way, former
employees allege, the Regis Hairstylist Salon decided that Spanish
spoken among employees made its English-speaking customers
uncomfortable. The sign disappeared and employees were ordered to
speak only English. Several hairstylists allege that they lost
their jobs for speaking their native tongue. As immigrants from
non-English-speaking countries flow into the United States,
businesses and institutions increasingly face a foreign-language
test: How best to cope with new workers and new customers whose
first language is not English. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-BOX _ Data for a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Tuesday. WAN: Location Atlanta, category National,
subcategory Social Issues.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BATTLEMAP _ Al Gore began a new ad campaign this week,
and almost state for state and dollar for dollar, the ad buy
matches presidential rival George W. Bush's new ads on education
and making tough choices, which also began running this week. From
the ad buys, a map of 17 battleground states emerges. We look at
the map and its significance. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   SC-POLITICS _ Party preferences change over time. Demographics
shift, and politicians come and go. But century over century, some
features of a state's body politic persist and give it a special
personality. In South Carolina, the old political worry lines can
be traced in the difference between Upcountry and Lowcountry
Republicans. (Baxter , Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. (WITH
Politics in the South sig).
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CENTAM _ TAPACHULA, MEXICO _ Baby-faced Sonia Marlene
Lopez, 15, said she was willing to do anything if she could just
get to the United States. ``Wash dishes, clean hotel rooms, take
care of babies,'' the Salvadoran teenager said earnestly, her eyes
as wide as saucers. But Lopez never made to Houston or El Paso, her
dream cities. Instead she, her sister and a cousin _ all teen-age
girls _ ended up in a jail cell here for undocumented migrants
crossing into Mexico's southernmost Chiapas state. While U.S.
officials conduct their own battle to stem illegal crossings,
Mexican officials here say they've seen a 30 percent increase over
last year in the number of undocumented immigrants they're
</P>
<P>
   catching along the southern border with Guatemala. Although
they've taken South Americans into custody, too, the vast majority
detained are Central Americans bound for the United States. An
increasing number appear to be willing to take perilous journeys to
avoid capture, suffocating in cargo trailers or drowning at sea.
Those captured often say they're looking for a way out of poverty
that hasn't abated after years of civil war and 1998's Hurricane
Mitch. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH box attached at end of story.
</P>
