<HEADER>
A9275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LINCOLN-AD-COLUMN-NYT     08-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: `IMMERSION' PLAN KEY TO LINCOLN'S ADS AT U.S.
OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While there are plenty of sponsors at the U.S. Open
tennis tournament, which begins on Monday, one sponsor intends to
stand out _ quite literally _ among visitors to Flushing Meadows in
Queens County, N.Y., where the event is held.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Sept. 1, Lincoln Mercury, the Ford Motor unit based
in Irvine, Calif., will usher visitors through elaborately staged
exhibits in a pavilion the size of four tennis courts to promote a
more contemporary image.
</P>
<P>
   In creating the unusual exhibits, Lincoln is embracing a new
idea in marketing called experience marketing, made popular in
books like as ``The Experience Economy,'' by B. Joseph Pine and
James H. Gilmore (Harvard Business School Press, 1999). Experience
marketing tries to appeal to consumers through the senses
experience the brand, often through show-businesslike techniques
that appeal to the senses. Retailers like Niketown and DKNY in
Manhattan are examples of brands that use similar techniques to
create an experience intended to move beyond just shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Wahl, Lincoln Mercury's marketing communications
manager, said Lincoln was intrigued with the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message in the experience economy is to combine education
with sensory experience and entertainment,'' Wahl said. ``We took
that cue, and made it relevant to Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln American Luxury Immersion exhibit is part of the
automaker's strategy to align itself with its belief that there is
a new idea of American luxury. Based on consumer research, the
company describes the new luxury as casual, energetic and
optimistic. One example: a generation ago, a nice evening might
have included driving a Lincoln to a formal restaurant where diners
had to dress accordingly and use the right fork, Wahl said. Today,
Lincoln's key consumer audience _ drivers 30 to 50 _ would probably
prefer skewering jumbo shrimp on an expensive gourmet grill while
dressed in shorts and a T-shirt, with _ Lincoln would hope _ a
Lincoln Navigator in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boils down to luxury without rules,'' Wahl said. ``It fits
into the new trend. All the new affluence is redefining how we
define luxury; it's a different way of approaching it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln pavilion, situated inside the grounds' former indoor
tennis courts, is a series of interactive sensory experiences that
juxtaposes old definitions versus new definitions of luxury. Upon
walking into the pavilion, for instance, visitors will experience
the sights and sounds of tennis from the past, with real grass
courts, still photography from the 1940s and '50s and video and
audio evoking that era, followed by the sights and sounds of
today's more causal and energetic U.S. Open. In the last stage of
the exhibit, Lincoln unveils its newest vehicle, a sporty truck
called the Blackwood.
</P>
<P>
   Impiric, the customer relationship unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam in
Irvine, Calif., is overseeing the project for Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like building a set: It's a cross between
Broadway and a sound stage,'' said Allan Finehirsh Sr., vice
president-director of event marketing and promotions, at Impiric.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln exhibit is the largest to ever appear at an Open,
said Pierce O'Neil, chief marketing officer for the U.S. Tennis
Association, the nonprofit group that owns and operates the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln recently signed a five-year agreement as exclusive
sponsor of the United States Tennis Association, which makes it the
exclusive auto sponsor and a year-round sponsor of USA League
Tennis, the world's largest recreational tennis league.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln will run commercials during the Open on CBS and USA
Cable.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil said the sponsorship was a perfect match for the
association. After reaching a peak in popularity in the early
1980s, fan interest waned and the Open's television ratings
declined. But in the last few years, the USTA has been working to
attract a younger, more diverse crowd. The group believes it is in
the early stages of a resurgence: ratings climbed in 1998 and this
year it began attracting a variety of sponsors, from newcomers like
Lincoln and Elle magazine to longtime supporters like Heineken and
Fila.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many similarities between the demographics, but it's
more about the image,'' O'Neil said of the Lincoln sponsorship.
``Optimistic, inviting, friendly _ those are all words and concepts
that Lincoln uses and those are words and phrases that certainly
describe the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jack Trout, a marketing consultant and author in Greenwich,
Conn., said Lincoln has a way to go to change its image.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's undermining their image is that the biggest way you
experience the Lincoln is when you are going to the airport,''
Trout said. ``They kind of dominate the limo market, and to me that
is a big factor in their image problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Lincoln sales are up this year because of its newer
vehicles, the sporty LS, and the Navigator, a sport utility
vehicle. According to J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, a market research
firm in Augura Hills, Calif., Lincoln sold 101,024 vehicles for the
year ended June 30, compared with 81,131 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   To attract visitors to the exhibit, Lincoln will begin running
advertisements on Aug. 23 from Young &AMP; Rubicam that ask questions
like ``Have you heard about it?'' and ``Are you living it?''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements will also appear throughout the 50-acre Flushing
Meadows site.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of Lincoln's efforts to attract visitors are
contemporary. Lincoln possesses one of the oldest summertime
marketing ploys: Immersion, Wahl said, is the only site open to all
visitors that has air conditioning _ a fact the company will not
advertise but knowledge of which is sure to get around, especially
if temperatures rise during the two-week event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
