<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9276 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-ART     08-22 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTING A COURSE TOWARD MAKING STUDENTS WANT TO ACHIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is an abridged version of a story that appears on Page 1
of The New York Times. The full version is available upon
request.)  
 (EDS:: In 1st graf, please replace (plus) and (equals) with the
symbols, no parentheses)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The word of the day was ``preparatory.''
</P>
<P>
   As in, Bronx Preparatory Charter School, the name stitched in
blue and gold on the patches decorating the children's white polo
shirts. As in, Preparation (plus) Focus (equals) Success, the motto
posted on the wall in the cafeteria, in the hallway, at the front
of every classroom and at the bottom of teachers' letters to
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission, the reason, the be-all and end-all of why we are
here, is to prepare you for college _ and for life,'' Kristin
Kearns Jordan told the 100 black and Hispanic youngsters seated
around the tables she and her husband spent the Saturday before
putting together. ``Everything that happens here happens to help
get you prepared. But you're never going to be prepared if you
don't do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 31, had been preparing for this moment for 18 months, or
maybe for her entire life, but especially throughout this summer of
14-hour workdays filled with assembling computer tables,
negotiating staff contracts, collating student binders and soothing
parental worries. It was the first hour of the first day of the
first year of a new school.
</P>
<P>
   While most political debate over education involves tweaking
existing programs, charter schools present a chance for teachers,
parents, management companies and bright young idealists like
Jordan, who had never before worked in a school, to sit around a
blank blackboard and imagine a school from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools, which get public funds but are run without
regulation from the local school district, have been embraced by
conservatives and liberals alike as an outlet for innovation, what
many see as the most dynamic and important education reform
movement in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Prep started with 102 fifth and sixth graders on
Wednesday, Aug. 16, three weeks before almost every other New York
City public school, part of its regimen of extra class time and
rigorous discipline. With plans to add a grade each year until it
stretches through high school, Bronx Prep is one of 380 new charter
schools opening across the country this fall, including 18 in New
York state, 11 of them in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A movement that began with three schools in Minnesota and
California in 1992 now stretches across 34 states and the District
of Columbia, with nearly 520,000 students _ 1 percent of the
nation's schoolchildren _ enrolled in 2,069 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Though more than two-thirds of the schools have waiting lists
and some have posted remarkable achievement gains, the freedom
granted to charter schools has also created new opportunities for
corruption, with some schools shuttered after officials discovered
dangerous facilities, the illegal teaching of religion or financial
irregularities. Over all, 79 new charter schools have closed.
</P>
<P>
   As Bronx Prep begins its first year, promising to prepare
students for the nation's top colleges through a tightly controlled
environment and an extended school day and year, the looming
question is whether independence and innovation can transcend the
problems plaguing children from one of the nation's poorest and
most troubled neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question yesterday was, will we be able to pull it off?
The question today is, how good can we get?'' Jordan said last
week, on Day Two. ``Everyone can perform for the first day. Now our
challenge is to sustain it and build it and make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   29, New York's charter law, passed in 1998, dictates that
enrollment be determined by lottery. Technically, the school is
open to any student in the state, but Bronx Prep's 155 applications
came from within a few miles of the school, where recruiting was
focused.
</P>
<P>
   Charters cannot hand-pick high-quality students, but the fact
that their families sought out the school suggests a certain
commitment to education.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who turned up for the 10 information sessions this
spring had once applied to the School Choice Scholarship
Foundation, an organization Jordan used to run that sends
low-income students to private schools. Some of the children were
bright and unchallenged in the local schools. Others had behavior
problems, lagging years behind grade level. A few parents were
lured by Bronx Prep's promised schedule: 7:55 a.m. to 5 p.m., 200
days a year, or some 50 percent more time in class than the Board
of Education requires.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Prep was born out of frustration with the educational
desert that dominates the South Bronx, combined with Jordan's
yearning to work more closely with children after years in
educational nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   By March 1999 _ more than a year before the charter would be
formally issued _ Jordan had told her bosses she planned to open a
school. Unlike most charter-school operators, for whom obtaining
facilities is the biggest challenge, Jordan quickly secured a
$75,000-a-year lease _ cheap at $5.75 a square foot _ from Our Lady
of Victory, a Catholic church, for the school next door, which had
stood vacant for five years. Bronx Prep was chartered by the State
University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, the school's director, hired as the principal Marina
Damiba,29, a Haitian-born dynamo who was one of the founding
teachers at KIPP Academy, a school a few miles away that has
received national attention for outstanding performance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a charter school, Bronx Prep can ignore city and state
mandates regarding curriculum, testing, staffing and spending,
though it has promised to administer the same standardized tests as
the New York City Board of Education so that its progress can be
compared with that of its competitors. The school will also be held
accountable for lengthy standards described in the charter, . which
SUNY can renew or revoke after five years.
</P>
<P>
   Tidbits like ``the word of the day,'' the hand-rung bell to
signal class-switches, and the achievement agreement that all
students, parents and teachers must sign are borrowed from Exeter,
Catholic schools, other charters, and, especially, from KIPP, the
Knowledge is Power Program, which itself is converting this fall
from a branch of the Board of Education to a charter school.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Prep will have daily 90-minute blocks of reading and math,
plus separate classes in grammar/writing and novel reading, along
with science and social studies. The afternoons are devoted to
``enrichment'' _ 42 students are in the orchestra, the rest will be
split among African dance and drumming, step dancing and chess.
Each teacher will also meet daily with a small group of students
for discussions and activities like community service; plans for
recess and physical education remain sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be a place of rigid discipline, filled with rituals,
where students are called ``scholars,'' drilled in basic skills and
nitpicked about decorum _ girls endlessly reminded to close legs
under the plaid uniform skirts, boys admonished to keep hands out
of the pockets of their khakis. Over and over again, students are
told to ``practice their STEPS'': S means sit up straight; T, track
the speaker; E, enrich the class; P, pay attention; and S, show you
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has never taught a class. She has not designed a
curriculum. She has no degree in education, no teaching
certificate, little hands-on experience with children.
</P>
<P>
   What she has is a thick Rolodex, with relationships in the world
of education and the Bronx community, organizational savvy and
newly discovered skills like shopping for industrial-size food
warmers, operating a power drill and sewing curtains for the
doorless women's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   She also knows how to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $900,000 to date, much of it before the charter was even
granted, from foundations, corporations and, friends. Expenses for
the first year are estimated at $1.1 million, plus $400,000 in
pre-opening costs. The state's per-pupil allocation of $6,630 adds
up to $676,000, with other revenues of $150,000 in federal and
state startup grants; $125,000 in aid for programs for poor
students; and $8,000 from the state for materials.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening day, about half of Bronx Prep's students had
already logged hours in its classrooms, summer's sun glinting
through arched windows.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty children struggling academically or socially were ordered
to attend a two-week preparatory session, which served as a trial
run for everything from bathroom procedures (children must sign a
log) to Scholar Dollars, a point system to monitor attitude.
Orchestra auditions _ students had to mimic a series of clapping
beats _ began in late July; a week after receiving their
instruments, the violinists were playing harmony for ``The Star
Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, too, trickled in. Three of them, like Damiba, are
alumni of Teach for America, the national program that places
recent college graduates in impoverished classrooms. One just
returned from the Peace Corps in Zimbabwe, another spent the last
two years teaching in a San Francisco group home for emotionally
disturbed teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran of the group is 32, with a master's degree in
teaching English as a second language, the baby a 1999 Yale
graduate facing the front of a classroom for the first time. There
are two men and five women; four are white, two black, one Puerto
Rican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
