<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WALLEYE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-22 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLEYE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDISCOVERING WALLEYE, AKA PIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to fish, geography seems to dictate
consumer tastes. New York's markets and menus are dominated by
ocean-going varieties, not fish that spend their lives in rivers
and lakes. Chicago and other Great Lakes cities are where
freshwater fish are more in favor.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, several European-trained chefs here have been
delighted to discover walleye from the Great Lakes. The fish is
extremely meaty, with firm snowy flesh of uncommonly satiny
succulence and a sweet, mild flavor.
</P>
<P>
   For one of these chefs, Laurent Tourondel of Cello, on the Upper
East Side, it has been a reunion of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Troisgros, in France, we would get sandre from
the Loire, and I didn't think it was available here,'' he said.
``But your walleye pike is the same. It's a wonderful, big,
firm-textured fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Gutenbrunner, the chef and owner of the new Wallse in
Greenwich Village, named for his hometown in Austria, is also
serving the fish, which is called zander in German. He calls it
yellow pike on his menu, which is another common name.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Gras at Peacock Alley in the Waldorf-Astoria and Daniel
Boulud at Daniel are also using walleye now. Jean-Georges
Vongerichten, though, says he has been familiar with it for several
years but does not have it on the menu regularly because supplies
are not guaranteed. He offers it as a special, often poached in
butter with a caramelized shallot broth.
</P>
<P>
   Walleye is actually not a member of the pike family at all, but
is related to perch. Pike-perch is another of its confusing
aliases, which explains why the translation of the French sandre is
sometimes given as both pike and perch. In Michigan, walleye is
also known as pickerel. In the northern Midwest, it's popular at
fish fries.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, walleye is often sold as yellow pike, which is one
of the classic ingredients of gefilte fish.
</P>
<P>
   Walleye range in size from about 5 to 10 pounds and have a shape
like salmon but with a fierce-looking jaw. They rarely have the
slightly muddy taste typical of some freshwater fish. The name
walleye refers to its wide-set eyes, which, because it forages at
night, never have the clarity and brightness characteristic of the
freshest fish.
</P>
<P>
   Walleye can be found in rivers and lakes from New York to
Montana, as far north as Hudson's Bay in Canada and as far south as
North Carolina. In 1812, walleye were introduced into a branch of
the Susquehanna River near Elmira, N.Y., and they thrived so
abundantly throughout the Middle Atlantic river system they were
called Susquehanna salmon. But they were highly prized on the
plate, and by the end of the 19th century had been overfished in
this region nearly to extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the walleye on the market comes from the Great Lakes,
especially Lake Erie. It's available fresh in markets here from
spring through early fall. During the rest of the year it is
usually available frozen, though sometimes fresh walleye shows up
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Citarella on the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan
sells the whole fish for $5.95 a pound. Jake's Fishmarket on the
Upper West Side has it for $6.99 a pound. Wild Edibles in the Grand
Central Market is selling fillets for $13.95 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Tourondel of Cello sears the fillets and serves them with a
red-wine butter sauce, often on a bed of Swiss chard stems.
``That's the classic way it's done in Burgundy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SEARED WALLEYE WITH MERLOT SAUCE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Cello &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups merlot
</P>
<P>
   10 finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   Pinch sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic: 1 whole, 1 minced, 3 crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   4 black peppercorns, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Stems from 2 large bunches red Swiss chard
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces slab bacon in {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons unsalted butter in {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2{ pounds walleye fillet, in six portions, with skin.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place merlot in saucepan with shallots, sugar, 1 sprig thyme,
whole garlic clove, bay leaf and crushed peppercorns. Cook over
medium heat until wine has nearly evaporated but shallots are soft
and moist, but not brown. Set aside in saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, trim Swiss chard stems in 3-inch lengths. (Reserve
leaves for another purpose.) Bring large pot of salted water to a
boil, add stems and blanch 2 minutes, until tender. Drain and place
in ice water.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat large skillet and add bacon. Fry until crisp. Drain
excess fat and remove bacon. Add 2 tablespoons butter. When butter
starts to brown, add minced garlic. Drain Swiss chard and add.
Stir-fry a couple of minutes, return bacon to pan and stir in
parsley. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove garlic, thyme and bay leaf from the saucepan that
contains the wine and shallots. Place pan over medium heat. Whisk
in 6 tablespoons butter bit by bit, until smooth. Remove from heat
and season with salt and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Lightly score skin of fish. Season with salt and pepper. Heat
remaining butter in large cast-iron pan. Add remaining garlic and
thyme. When butter starts to brown, add fish, skin side down, and
sear until crisp, 2 to 3 minutes. Turn and sear until done, another
5 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   6. Reheat Swiss chard mixture and place a portion in center of
each of 6 plates. Place fish, skin side up, on top. Gently reheat
sauce and spoon around the fish, then serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
