<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE23-COX     08-22 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH CRITICISM OF MILITARY OUT OF BOUNDS, GORE SAYS
 &HT;    500&AMP;add. With GORE-Q&AMP;A.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Vice President Al Gore suggested Tuesday that Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas went beyond the appropriate boundaries of
political debate by creating an ``inaccurate impression'' of U.S.
military forces.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made the suggestion in an interview as he expanded on his
remarks earlier in a speech to the national convention of the
Veterans of Foreign Wars (VFW) in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, wearing the military-style cap of VFW Post 5021 in
Carthage, Tenn., told the group that ``an unshakable national
commitment to our veterans'' has been a hallmark of his 24 years in
politics, rooted in his service as an Army journalist in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that year-after-year commitment to a strong American
defense that makes me so concerned when others try to run down
America's military for political advantage in an election year,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president did not mention Bush by name, but his meaning
was clear. The day before, Bush, the Republican presidential
nominee, used the VFW convention as a forum for accusing the
Clinton administration of allowing the U.S. military to ``decline''
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the subsequent interview with Cox, Gore cited Bush's earlier
criticism of the administration's military policies _ which he
called inaccurate _ to suggest that the Texas governor has stepped
beyond what is appropriate for a political debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long since begun the increased investments in
modernization and readiness that are needed,'' Gore said. ``And
therefore, I would never say that it's not legitimate to raise
questions about how much investment of that sort is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to go beyond that and to say that two divisions can't even
respond to a call to deploy, or to imply that our fighting forces
are not the most capable in the world by far, that's mistaken,'' he
added. ``And I don't think that's helpful to the country to put an
inaccurate impression out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said Gore's comments were
``reactionary and defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, speaking to the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia, Bush charged that two divisions of the
U.S. Army were not ready for combat duty. He was immediately
corrected by Defense Secretary William Cohen, a Republican and
former member of the Senate Armed Services Committee with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a Republican to run the Defense Department, partly
to take military policy out of the political arena,'' Gore said in
the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, received a rousing reception from the nearly 7,000
veterans at the VFW convention, especially when he vowed to ``make
sure our military continues to be the best-trained, best-equipped,
best-led fighting force in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He also promised military pay raises and improvements in
veterans benefits. But he cautioned that a $1.3 billion tax cut
proposed by his Republican rival would ``wreck our good economy and
make it impossible to modernize our armed forces and keep them
ready for battle.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore is one of 1.9 million members of the VFW by virtue of his
service in Vietnam, in contrast to Bush, who served stateside n the
Texas Air National Guard during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your military experience makes a little difference to this
group, but not much,'' said Dale Hundt, a 69-year-old conventioneer
from Madison, Wis., who was a paratrooper in Europe during World
War II. ``The important thing is where you stand on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a 10-year, $127 billion defense package that
includes the 3.7 percent military pay increase enacted this year,
investments to modernize equipment and more funding for veterans
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore's proposed spending on defense
would probably be increased in a fall revision of his budget to
reflect bigger surplus projections.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed pumping $1 billion a year more into military
pay over the next five years and spending $310 million to fix
schools on military bases.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with Cox, Gore said he feels a special
obligation to veterans because of his noncombat service in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure do, especially since I've a veteran who, as I said
today, didn't do the most or run the gravest risk. I know the guys
who did that,'' he said. `` I want to make sure that our country,
by God, does right by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
