<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRED-WRITERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IS IT TIME TO HANG UP THE PEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There comes a moment in the twilight of literary careers when
some popular authors feel compelled to reveal plot twists in their
own lives that lead to unlikely denouements: pensions and
retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   As summer beckoned, the self-described airport author Maeve
Binchy declared to headlines in London that her 12th book,
``Scarlet Feather,'' was her very last big novel. So millions of
loyal readers should expect no more sprawling page-turners from
this Irish bard of heartache, humor and transcontinental
house-swapping.
</P>
<P>
   Ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all a Frank Sinatra person who can be lured back,''
warned Binchy, 60, a former teacher and journalist whose best
sellers, like ``Tara Road,'' have earned her Oprah Book Club
celebrity, advances in the $10 million range and sales in her
homeland that outstrip those of William Butler Yeats and Oscar
Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Binchy was followed by Rosamunde Pilcher, 75, who revealed that
she was shaping the final chapter of a 50-year career that has
produced several cozy best sellers about English hearth and home.
Her latest, ``Winter Solstice,'' with 600,000 copies in print,
soared to the top of the fiction best-seller list of The New York
Times after St. Martin's Press published it this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could write another,'' Pilcher, whose latest
book commanded an advance of more than $6 million, said in an
interview. ``I hate publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Such open declarations raise a delicate issue in the literary
world, where there are no standard tribal retirement rituals. It is
a long way from the universe of sports, which lavishes attention on
its pensioners. Computer keyboards are not retired. Career
best-seller records do not lead to teary stadium send-offs. The
creative force that drives writing may still burn, but the energy
to promote a book fades like the pitching arm of a middle-aged
hurler. In some ways, mulling a writerly finale seems a bit morbid;
or, as Pilcher put it in a polite British accent, ``I don't think I
thought about it anymore than my own death.''
</P>
<P>
   The retiring literary set is a group usually overlooked in favor
of writers like Saul Bellow, who this year, at 85, delivered
``Ravelstein,'' his first major novel in more than a decade. The
very notion of a pension is not suitable publishing-party
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've only discussed this with one other author,'' said
Sidney Offit, 71, the author of more than a dozen books and the
president of the Authors Guild Foundation, the educational arm of
the Authors Guild. He added: ``Retirement depends on why people
need to write. For some people, writing is the only world they
control; it satisfies a therapeutic aim. Other people have a
message they want to deliver and when they're done, they're out.
Then there are people who write under the Sam Johnson dictum:
`Anyone who writes for anything other than money is a blockhead.'''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is so touchy that some writers refuse to discuss it.
Sidney Sheldon, for example, declined to be interviewed for this
article. At 83, he is publishing his 17th novel, ``The Sky Is
Falling,'' next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bradbury, who just turned 80, keeps writing despite the
effects of a stroke he had months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote part of my novel while I was in the hospital, and I
wrote a screenplay,'' he said in an interview. ``You want to live,
don't you? If you don't give up, you don't die.'' Bradbury
continues to deliver lectures from a wheelchair, and in the fall of
2001 he will publish a novel about a friendly vampire family called
the Elliots, a work that he has been laboring on sporadically for
about 55 years.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Kurt Vonnegut, 77, insisted that his 19th book,
``Timequake,'' was the last in his almost 50-year career. Back
then, he confessed relief that he had crossed the marathon finish
line. But now his retirement is an issue that he declines to
address. ``Well, I don't want to talk about that,'' he said from
his summer home in Sagaponack, N.Y., a Hamptons retreat on Long
Island's South Fork that is the literary parallel to a Florida
retirement community.
</P>
<P>
   Many older writers decide at some point to devote more time to
their lives than to their characters. A prosperous Shakespeare is
said to have retreated in perfect health to Stratford in his last
two years and produced nothing, leaving others to finish his
incomplete plays.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, even some middle-aged authors have felt compelled to
seek short forms of semiretirement. At 45, the Scottish author Iain
M. Banks, whose first novel was ``The Wasp Factory,'' announced a
few months ago that he was taking a year off from a relentless
writing schedule that has resulted in an annual novel or science
fiction title for the last 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``His wife wanted him to spend some time with her,'' explained
Mic Cheetham, Banks' literary agent in London, who called the break
a sabbatical. ``I don't know why some writers say they are
retiring. Maybe to get people not to phone them? One of the things
about writing is that it's such a very private business. But when
you become a best-selling writer, it becomes very public, and
everyone keeps asking, `When's the next one?' Then everyone is
completely astonished when you say you're taking a year off. It
seems to me very normal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The increasing rigors of a public literary life are often the
deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   Maeve Binchy's epiphany came as she was sitting at a book event
beside another successful writer whom she would identify only as
``a very bad-tempered woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was drumming her fingers on the table,'' Binchy recalled.
``She kept saying: `This food is terrible. There should be more
people. This is too tiring. It's going on too long.' I thought,
this discontented lady has written books, which is what we've
always wanted to do. She's allowed this to get into her soul. And I
said to myself, `A little voice of warning, Maeve. Leave before you
become like that.' I was really afraid that I would become one of
the people to whom this was a treadmill.''
</P>
<P>
   Roaming the world on an international book tour was not easy on
Binchy's arthritis; the unending airport corridors tested her
joints. Her readers seemed to be getting younger as she gazed out
at them at book events. She wondered if she could keep up her
appeal. And she and her husband, Gordon Snell, an author of
children's books, were content with the state of their bank
accounts and pensions and with their homes in London and a village
outside Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terribly young, and I feel 23 in my heart,'' said
Binchy, who is published in the United States by Delacorte. ``But I
have to realize that the world has changed very much, and so have
people's dreams and aspirations. I think a sensible woman would
realize that it's hard to keep a finger on the pulse of the young
today. It's quite a different lifestyle. They're so much more
traveled, so much less insular.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tara Road,'' for example, one of her most popular books in the
United States, explores the fates of two young women who change
their lives by swapping their homes in Ireland and America for the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Binchy added that she would write some short stories, which did
not produce the same sort of publishing pressures as her
bread-and-butter full-length novels, like ``Circle of Friends,''
which was made into a movie starring Minnie Driver. She has also
dropped a column that she had been writing for The Irish Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my publishers very honestly, from the start, that I was
going to do this,'' said Binchy, who has since retreated on an
Alaskan cruise. ``I gave them six months' notice, but they didn't
really believe me. I think the thinking is that I could be
persuaded to go back. I couldn't go on in this kind of way, and I
don't want more money.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that publishers and editors prefer to consider
retirement announcements as figments of fertile imaginations and to
believe that ultimately writers will be unable to resist the muse,
and the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for a born storyteller like Rosamunde Pilcher or
Maeve Binchy not to tell a story,'' said Thomas Dunne, Pilcher's
editor of more than 20 years. ``At least, that's what the
publishers hope, and there are millions of dollars at stake for
them, of course. If you ask Ros Pilcher right now, she'll tell you
that she doesn't see another book on the horizon. I think that is
entirely possible, but I also believe that she will return to
writing after a bit, if only because she enjoys the process.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Dunne who patiently persuaded Pilcher to write another
book after she finished ``Coming Home,'' which sold more than
500,000 copies and provoked their first discussions about
retirement. Dunne called the author at her home in Perthshire,
Scotland, in 1997 to suggest an idea for a novel set at
Christmastime. Eventually, the idea took hold, and Pilcher
delivered ``Winter Solstice,'' which happens to include a 60-ish
character, a former actress who is seeking retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I started to think about the characters, I had them in my
mind and I had to write their story,'' said Pilcher, whose daily
efforts would take up part of her morning and afternoon, as well as
her dog walks, in which she would mull over plot and character.
``Writing is work, but it's also a compulsion, and once you get
your characters on paper, you can't abandon them. You have to
respond to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The creative process was stimulating, she said, but she doesn't
consider writing a pleasurable pastime. ``It's a job that you have
to do,'' she said. ``But it's still demanding and draining, and I'm
very tired at the end of a day's work.'' She vowed that with the
completion of the book she would retreat into a ``world of
domesticity'' populated by her husband, Graham; their four
children; their grandchildren; their friends; and their dachshunds,
Daisy and Polly.
</P>
<P>
   She is not touring the United States to promote her latest
novel, adding that the task of selling a book is wearing. ``I'm
really quite a private person, and I find it intrusive,'' she
continued. ``My husband has a new hip, and all of this happened
while I'm trying to juggle 24 balls. I never found it this way
before. I suppose when I was younger, I had more energy, and I
wasn't looking after a sick husband. This time I think the time has
come to hang up the hat, but I'm not going to say that
definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years ago, Carl H. Klaus, the founding director of
the University of Iowa's nonfiction writing program, decided that
he also needed a break after a four-year effort on his latest book.
</P>
<P>
   He treated his literary exhaustion with a regimen of reading,
traveling, and tending his prized vegetable garden of cherry belle
radishes and Oregon giant snow peas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the urge to be writing again returned before the year was
out,'' said Klaus, 68, who suspects that retiring authors are more
fatigued by publishing pressures than by writing itself. ``It's
irrepressible and comes from the same deep well that I drew upon
when a student asked if I had any last words at the end of my last
course at Iowa _ and without thinking, I told her, `Just keep
writing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Klaus is back at the keyboard, pounding out the chapters
of a book of essays. He is fully recovered from the rigors of
writing his last title, a memoir called ``Taking Retirement: A
Beginner's Diary.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
