<SLUG> BC-MAINE-PHOTOGRAPHY-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGENIC MAINE: WILDERNESS THAT'S EVERYONE'S 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
 By DEBORAH WEISGALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKPORT, Maine _ Maine is a place of lakes and bays, hills and
islands, weathered people who live in plain and weathered
buildings; a place eroded to the bone, both hard and tender. Since
the 19th century, when Hawthorne and Thoreau published accounts of
sojourns there and Thomas Cole and Frederic Church sent paintings
of its coast and mountains south to the cities, Maine has
represented an accessible wilderness: America's idea of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers played an important part in inventing this idea of
Maine, though their role is less well-known than that of writers
and painters. With an ambitious, two-part survey, ``Photographing
Maine: 1840-2000,'' the Maine Coast Artists/Center for Maine
Contemporary Art documents the themes and variations of
photographers' rich and complex reactions to this landscape and its
inhabitants. Bruce Brown, the gallery's curator, organized the
exhibitions with John Chandler, a former curator. The first
installment, covering the years 1950-2000, runs until Oct. 1, and
the second, called ``1840's-1940's: The First Century,'' from Oct.
21 to Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they form a short course in American photography.
Almost everybody visited Maine, and many stayed. Ansel Adams,
Walker Evans, Gertrude Kaesebier, Paul Strand _ all have work in
Part 2 of the show, while Berenice Abbott, Eliot Porter, Ernst
Haas, Arnold Newman, Rudy Burckhardt and William Wegman are among
those represented in the current installment. One of its surprises
is the number of photographers who came from Maine: Kosti Ruohomaa,
for instance, one of Life magazine's great regulars in the 1950s,
was born in Rockland. His ``Monhegan Light, January 1957,'' with
the lighthouse beacon shining like the low sun, catches the
bleakness and exhilaration of a Maine winter, its daily
chiaroscuro.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Peterman, a young photographer whose photographs of ice
fishing huts were recently shown in New York, grew up in Camden; in
``Long Lake,'' the painted, recycled boards of a shack acquire the
minimal elegance of a Mondrian.
</P>
<P>
   For year-round Mainers, winter dominates, but to most visitors
Maine represents summer. Abelardo Morrell, who began studying
photography at Bowdoin College, pinpoints the season's elusive
magic in his ``Camera Obscura Image of a Pine Tree in Bedroom,
Little Deer Isle.'' The picture superimposes a ghostly state symbol
on the interior of a motel room like those where so many passing
tourists sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Despite motel corridors and the poverty of many of its citizens,
Maine appears desirable and beautiful, always pristine. Many of the
images, like Morrell's pine, locate their poetry in this
contradiction. Haas' ``Maine, 1960'' draws lyrical patterns with a
road's white dividing line, the flaking white spokes of an
abandoned wagon wheel, the fading white geometry of a decrepit
farmhouse and the bent dark figure of the old farmer. In Patrisha
McLean's ``Brandy in a Bathing Suit,'' a little girl grins and
arches her back as she leans against a windowsill; she looks like a
saucy ripening bean. Observing her balefully through the glass from
his chair just inside is an obese and coarsened man, obviously the
child's father, and her future.
</P>
<P>
   In Burckhardt's ``Bunchberries, Deer Isle, 1955,'' delicate
leaves float like paper boats on light rippling the forest floor.
Bunchberries and their clumps of red fruit, like Haas' native
farmer, have almost vanished in the last half century. But Judy
Ellis Glickman's ``Reflections, Great Diamond Island,'' made in
1999, shimmers with a sense of solitude no different from the
feeling of George Daniell's ``Portrait of John Marin,'' taken in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   With 135 pieces, each by a different photographer,
``Photographing Maine'' emerges as a brilliant play on the changing
nature of place, on what vanishes and what remains. We come here to
this ideal place that promises innocence, hoping that what we see
will illuminate that quality in us.
</P>
<P>
   In Paul D'Amato's ``Girl in Pew, Peak's Island, 1997,'' a girl
turns her head, caught in the camera's flash like a deer in
headlights. She seems innocent, shot in the plain church where she
thought herself safe. ``Photographing Maine'' snares these living
moments: Subjects vanish, wilderness diminishes, but the images
endure, imprinted in the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
