<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9287 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BRAZIL-TELENOVELLAS-$     08-22 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TELENOVELLAS-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL BUILDS BIGGER AND BETTER TELENOVELAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 27)  
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ When a television serial about an
18th-century courtesan went off the air here two years ago, few at
the struggling network that had produced the drama, called ``Xica
da Silva,'' expected it to have much of an afterlife. But then 150
episodes were dubbed into Spanish and sold to a dozen other
countries in Latin America, where the series quickly went on to
become a ratings phenomenon everywhere it was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Now the United States, or at least the growing portion of it
that watches Spanish-language television, has succumbed to the same
spell. Since going on the air seven months ago, this tale of a
Brazilian slave who uses her quick-wittedness and sexual prowess to
gain freedom and wealth as the mistress of a powerful colonial lord
has revived the fortunes of Telemundo, the country's perennial No.
2 Spanish-language network.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the success of ``Xica'' (pronounced SHE-kah) undoubtedly
stems from the saucy performance of Tais de Araujo, the 21-year-old
actress who plays the title role and who was recently included in a
list of the 25 most beautiful people in Latin America published by
People magazine's Spanish-language edition. But the international
popularity of ``Xica'' also demonstrates that in the genre known as
the telenovela, as in soccer, nobody plays the game with more skill
than Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novela is a form of entertainment that has developed into
one of the best products of Brazilian show business,'' said Joao
Carlos Daniel, who, working under the stage name Daniel Filho, is
one of this country's most successful directors in the genre. ``It
is not an exact science and there is no sure-fire formula for
guaranteed success, but without a doubt, we do it better than
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The telenovela, usually referred to simply as novela, is often
described as a Latin American version of the soap opera, and while
there are many similarities, there are also important differences,
beginning with structure. While some American soap operas have been
running for more than 40 years, a novela always has a beginning and
an end, which here normally comes after about 180 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the novela consigned to the ghetto of daytime
programming. The United States has had prime-time soaps such as
``Dallas'' and ``Dynasty,'' but in Brazil, as in the rest of Latin
America, novelas are glossy entertainment on the air five or six
nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   As such, they attract the biggest audiences, demand the highest
rates of advertisers and thereby are entitled to the biggest
production budgets, with the cost of making a single episode often
exceeding $100,000. Novelas are so popular that nighttime
broadcasts of soccer, Brazil's other great passion, are delayed
until the last one is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that in the United States the soap opera is not a
prime-time product and so less investment and effort goes into
it,'' said Walter Avancini, who directed ``Xica da Silva'' and more
than 20 other novelas. ``That's not the case here. The novela is
the backbone of prime time, and so it has assumed a tremendous
level of importance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Hollywood's biggest stars would view a
role in a soap opera as beneath their dignity. Not so here: because
even Brazil's most distinguished actors and actresses find it all
but impossible to make a living just from films or theater, they
are often recruited to play choice roles in novelas, performing
alongside whoever the latest teen-age heartthrob happens to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a good script comes along, why should I refuse to
participate just because it is a telenovela?'' asked Fernanda
Montenegro, who was nominated for an Academy Award in 1999 for her
role in ``Central Station'' and is usually cast as an elegant
upper-class matron when she works in novelas. ``Why limit myself?
After all, Balzac, Dumas, Dickens and Dostoyevsky all wrote
serials.''
</P>
<P>
   The novela originated more than 50 years ago in Mexico as a
radio melodrama, but when television appeared the genre was quickly
adapted to the new medium and soon spread all over Latin America.
Every country from Argentina to Mexico now makes novelas, but
Brazil's tend to have larger casts and more elaborate plots and
sets _ thus attracting the biggest audiences, even though, as in
the case of ``Xica da Silva,'' they have to be dubbed from
Portuguese into Spanish for the rest of Latin America and for the
Spanish-language networks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Brazilian novelas more than any others because they
are so beautiful to look at,'' Maria Dolores Faundez, a Venezuelan
housewife, said in an interview in Caracas early this month. ``The
stories are wonderful too, but everything always looks so
luxurious. I especially like the way the characters dress and the
magnificent apartments they live in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the popularity of Brazilian novelas may also stem from a
willingness to tackle controversial social and political themes
such as agrarian reform, racism, abortion, environmental
degradation, homosexuality and corruption, mixed in, of course,
with classic themes of jealousy, intrigue and betrayal. That
tendency has in large part been implanted by scriptwriters with
leftist sympathies who came to television in hopes of addressing a
mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telenovela is basically a distraction, and no one watches
it in order to be educated,'' Brazil's leading author of novelas,
the playwright and former Communist Party member Alfredo Dias
Gomes, said in an interview shortly before his death in an
automobile accident last year. ``But it is an instrument through
which you can denounce and point out the errors in a society, and I
have often done that and felt the public respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a striking boldness on sexual matters, including
generous doses of nudity, has also proved to have universal appeal.
``Brazilian television is the most liberal in the world,'' said
Daniel, who has worked in the medium since the 1960s. ``In terms of
open sexuality, nobody in the world shows what is shown on
Brazilian television. It is extremely bold, perhaps because of our
Carnival tradition and the procession of nudity and raw sexuality
that people have come to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the American market is the final frontier for
Brazil: since 1978, more than 80 different Brazilian novelas have
been exported to 119 different countries. A novela produced here,
``Isaura the Slave,'' is said to be the most popular television
program ever shown in China, and Brazilian novelas today are
broadcast as far afield as Indonesia, Russia, Chad, Turkey and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian television executives say that period costume dramas
that touch on themes of slavery or other social abuses tend to do
the best abroad, and ``Xica da Silva'' certainly fits that
description. A movie version directed by Carlos Diegues had already
been an international success in the 1970s, largely as a result of
the perforamnce of Zeze Motta, who ended up being cast as Xica's
mother in the novela.
</P>
<P>
   So for an unproven newcomer like Araujo, who was only 17 when
``Xica da Silva'' began taping, the chance to play a figure so
important in Brazilian folklore was both an unusual opportunity and
a daunting challenge. ``I turned the role down at first, because I
was scared and didn't think I was ready for it,'' she said in a
recent interview at her home here, shortly before heading off to
New York to study English. ``Xica is a legend in Brazil, and here I
was, just a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ``Xica da Silva'' was a conscious attempt to break
down an imposing social barrier. The majority of Brazil's
population may be of mixed race, but the ideal novela star, male or
female, is still someone who is light-skinned, preferably with
blond hair and blue or green eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first time that Brazilian television had a black
woman as the protagonist of a novela, so we were up against some
deeply ingrained prejudices,'' Avancini said. ``But Xica is one of
the first symbols of feminine liberation in Brazil and has become a
mythical Afro-Brazilian figure, and Tais had just the right
temperament, naughty but gutsy, to win over the public.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Xica da Silva'' was also unusual in that it was made by the
Manchete network and not by Rede Globo, which is both the largest
television network in Brazil and the largest privately owned
commercial network outside the United States. Globo's Projac
production center on the outskirts of Rio de Janeiro is a vast $125
million facility that churns out programming at a pace and on a
scale that rivals a Hollywood studio.
</P>
<P>
   At any given moment, three of Globo's four giant soundstages are
being used to tape novelas that are currently on the air, using
props and sets that have been manufactured at shops on the
premises. The fourth stage is usually reserved for novelas that are
in the pre-production phase, comedy and variety programs or for
somewhat shorter versions of novelas called ``mini-series'' that
can run as many as 100 episodes, and there are also buildings on
the premises set aside for editing and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to producing novelas, Globo functions like a
Japanese factory that uses the just-in-time principle,'' said
Avancini, who now works for the network. ``Normally you like to
work well in advance, finishing an episode a couple of weeks before
it goes on the air, but sometimes you end up taping things that are
going to be broadcast in just a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   By working so close to broadcast date, Globo's novelas
department gains unusual flexibility. The network makes extensive
use of focus groups, whose recommendations are taken into account
in expanding roles of minor characters who suddenly become popular,
eliminating altogether characters that viewers do not like and even
extending particularly popular novelas beyond their original
length: ``Terra Nostra,'' about Italian immigrants in Sao Paulo,
ran a record 233 episodes before ending early this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 321-acre facility, which opened in 1995, also includes
outdoor areas for settings that tend to recur from one novela to
the next, such as the typical Latin American town square and church
or a big city at the turn of the century. When an Indian village
was needed for a series that was broadcast earlier this year,
Indians were even brought from the Amazon to build it.
</P>
<P>
   A visit one day earlier this month to Avancini's current
production, a costume drama called ``The Thorn and the Rose,''
found one unit shooting on an outdoors set made up to look like a
Sao Paulo street in 1927 while another was indoors on a soundstage
that recreated a rustic hacienda. For the actors involved, that can
mean a routine that is taxing and frantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have 29 scenes to shoot, and I am in almost all of
them,'' Eduardo Moscovis, who plays the male lead in ``The Thorn
and the Rose,'' said as he hurriedly ate a plate of cold pasta
during a short break. ``That's the way it is when you're right in
the middle of making a novela, but you learn to get used to that
rhythm, intense as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Avancini, Araujo is now under contract to Globo, and
quickly noticed the difference in atmosphere from her days at
Manchete, which recently declared bankruptcy. ``With `Xica da
Silva,' we had four months of readings and rehearsals before we
even began shooting, which is very unusual in Brazilian
television,'' she recalled. ``Globo doesn't have time for that.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than 30 years of experience and a total of 203
novelas produced in-house, the Globo formula and schedule contain
few surprises. The network's evening programming begins at 6
o'clock, often with a period piece like ``The Thorn and the Rose,''
which is a Brazilianized version of ``The Taming of the Shrew''
that is set in Sao Paulo in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 7 o'clock comes a comedy, the frothier the better. The
current offering, in which Araujo plays a small role, is called
``Uga Uga'' and tells the Tarzan-inspired tale of a handsome young
man raised in the jungle who returns to civilization, clad only in
a loincloth that allows him to continually show off his muscles to
a mainly female audience, in order to claim a family inheritance at
the behest of the Indian tribe that has sheltered him.
</P>
<P>
   The most prestigious piece of prime time, or ``the noble hour,''
as it is called here, comes at 9 p.m., after the nightly news _
which is broadcast at 8 p.m., several hours later than in the
United States _ and is reserved for a melodrama. At the moment,
``Lacos de Familia,'' or ``Family Ties,'' holds down the slot every
evening except Sunday, and on a good night, more than half the
television sets in this nation of 170 million people are tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Ties'' stars Vera Fischer, Brazil's leading sex symbol,
as a rich and glamorous Rio widow competing with her daughter for
the affections of a 25-year-old hunk. But according to the numerous
gossip magazines that track every detail of every novela, the
daughter will soon come down with leukemia and will need a bone
marrow transplant that can only be obtained from her father, who
she has been told died when she was 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novela is what it is,'' Daniel said. ``You can change the
characters, but the stories remain basically the same, and the only
novelty you are likely to see is that today's novelas are more and
more technically polished. That is why I tend to agree with Peter
Bogdanovich when he says that the best movies have already been
made. The same is true of novelas.''
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, as new forms of entertainment such as the Internet
and satellite television emerge, critics predict the decline or
even disappearance of the genre. But Dias Gomes disagreed, saying
the novela ``cannot be substituted'' because it is too deeply
rooted a habit in Latin America, and Daniel agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the novela talks about things that are truly ours,
and the people identify immediately with the characters,'' he
explained. ``The novela is part of the daily routine of the
Brazilian people, and there is no way to deprive them of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
