<SLUG> BC-NASD-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: NO IMPACT FROM BROKER'S REPORTING FAILURE, REGULATORS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every month the National Association of Securities
Dealers compiles the short interest table for Nasdaq stocks, a
table that shows just how popular _ perhaps unpopular is a better
word _ a stock is with investors who bet on a decline in price. The
numbers are avidly scanned by investors and by the companies
themselves. Some investment strategies are based in part on those
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But how good are those numbers? Only as good as the reports from
brokerage firms, which are required to add up short positions of
their customers on all trades that have settled by the 15th of each
month. And it appears that the NASD is doing something less than a
stellar job of riding herd on the brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, NASD Regulation, the regulatory arm of the
association, announced that ETrade Securities, a large online
brokerage firm, had been fined $20,000 because it failed to file
such reports for 28 months, from June 1996 through September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   How did ETrade manage to go for more than two years without
reporting? The firm called it inadvertent and an NASD official
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Luparello, a vice president for market regulation of
NASD Regulation, said ETrade, like many other brokerage firms, had
arranged for the brokerage firm that clears its trades to do the
report.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, ETrade began to clear some of its own trades, but did
not realize that it had an obligation to make the reports, he said.
Nobody at the NASD noticed until 1998, when an examiner spotted the
failure during a routine examination of the firm, and referred the
matter to NASD Regulation, which began an investigation in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Luparello said that the NASD does make sure that every firm it
knows has an obligation to file such reports does so every month.
But any firm that is newly required to file will only be caught
during an examination, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sort of a technical administrative failure where they
didn't realize the obligation they had,'' Luparello. He added that
the numbers, which ETrade supplied after reviewing its records,
were ``not material'' to the Nasdaq short interest figures.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures show the number of shares in each stock that have
been borrowed and sold short, but not yet repurchased, by the
reporting date.
</P>
<P>
   One reason to short a stock is to bet on its decline; others
include arbitrage involving differing securities issued by the same
company or involving two companies that are planning to merge.
</P>
<P>
   Luparello said that in the first month ETrade failed to file,
its customers had a short interest of 314,000 shares in 298
securities. By September 1998, the final month it failed to make
the report, the figure had grown to 1.4 million shares involving
749 companies, while the overall figure for all brokers was 2.15
billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Luparello said that NASD had decided not to update its
historical records after concluding the figures were not material
for any stock. He said that the NASD would not release the figures
for individual stocks because it had decided there was no need to
make the information public.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for ETrade could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty is the second in a few months that indicates ETrade
had a great deal of trouble in dealing with its explosive growth.
In May, NASD Regulation fined the brokerage firm, a subsidiary of
ETrade Group, $20,000 because it had failed to respond to NASD
requests for information concerning customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade shares rose 13 cents to $17.25 in Nasdaq trading Tuesday.
The company went public in August 1996 _ a month after it began
clearing some of its trades without complying with reporting
requirements _ at $2.63 a share, adjusted for subsequent splits,
and rose to a high of $72.25 in April 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
