u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-BOS &LR;      08-22 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN FACES FAMILIES OF DEAD SUBMARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When an accident on the Soviet nuclear submarine K-19
killed 28 crewmen in 1972, the Kremlin never let on. Only months
later did the victims' families received a terse, one-line letter
announcing their demise, and it listed their sons', husbands, and
loved ones' cause of death as: death.
</P>
<P>
   That was it.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to 2000. Tuesday Russian President Vladimir Putin
flew to an Arctic naval base Tuesday to face, and try to console,
the families of the crew of the submarine Kursk, which sank after
suffering a large explosion on August 12.
</P>
<P>
   The president's trip is one clear sign that the leaders of
today's Russia cannot ignore public opinion the way Soviet leaders
once could. So are the actions of several military commanders, who
have reacted to the startingly public outflow of anger and grief
with equally surprising public apologies.
</P>
<P>
   These gestures may mean little to relatives who were kept in the
dark about the fate of their loved ones during the bungled nine-day
rescue effort. But they provide a clue as to how much Russia has
changed, and how the Kursk tragedy may change it still more.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians, however, are inclined to see the government's
actions as a marker of what has not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Many saw the accident as an object lesson on how little the
state cares about ordinary people's lives, and there is a segment
of the population who will always believe that the authorities are
covering up some terrible crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The navy is hiding the reason for the explosion, and delayed
the rescue so that none of the crew memebers would be alive to say
why the Kursk sank,'' said Viktor Sokirko, defense correspondent
for the Moskovsky Komsomolets newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   When the navy balked at Western offers of help, Sokirko and many
others saw it as a continuation of another old Soviet tradition:
the secrets of Russia's most advanced submarine were more important
than the lives of some of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be hard to raise the nuclear submarine from the
bottom,'' wrote Vitkor Loshak in Moscow News. ``But it will be even
harder to return the trust between society and the authorities that
has drowned in the Barents Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   But other commentators do not believe that trust in Putin, which
was well over 70 percent just a few months ago, will suffer that
much.
</P>
<P>
   They point out that Putin's image makers have shown they can use
public opinion to their advantage _ they managed to turn an
unwinnable quagmire in Chechnya into a rallying cry that carried
Putin to the Kremlin. The president's meeting with the grieving
relatives could pull off a similar result.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way, Putin will show that he is not a heartless `Black
Colonel,' but a sincerely begrieved man, who understands that he
made a serious mistake,'' commented the Moscow daily Kommersant.
</P>
<P>
   The process began Tuesday. Russian television showed Putin,
dressed in a somber black suit with black shirt but no tie, meeting
with Irina Lyachina, the wife of the Kursk's commander, Captain
Gennady Lyachin. Later, the president had a long private session
with more than 500 victims' family members.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, which Putin has decreed an official day of mourning,
he is scheduled to sail to the area where the Kursk went down in
354 feet of water to commemorate the memory of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Putin's subordinates have followed his example by
publicly expressing their regret, a remarkable event in a country
where officials traditionally never say they are sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral Vyacheslav Popov, commander of Russia's Northern Fleet,
begged forgiveness Thursday night for his failure to save the crew.
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev all but asked to be fired by
acknowledging that he had waited 12 hours before informing the
president of the accident in the crucial period when perhaps some
crew members still could have been saved.
</P>
<P>
   Russians are often cynical about the intentions of their
leaders, and it is too early to tell whether the belated reaction
to the Kursk sinking will change the way the authorities respond to
future disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that ``Black August,'' as this month has
become known because of the Kursk, the ongoing violence in
Chechnya, and a deadly bombing in central Moscow, has merely shown
that the state continues to be indifferent towards, and unable to
protect, its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more afraid about their lives, the worth of their
lives, the degree of protection against any kind of disaster,
whether it is an explosion in Moscow or a sub that sinks,'' said
Yevgeny Volk, director of the Moscow office of the Heritage
Foundation think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The television images of a mother who had sent her son to the
navy so that he would not have to fight in Chechnya, only to have
him die on the Kursk, have added to a general negative mood about
the military in a country where all young men are obliged to serve
at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to go to jail than to give your son to the fleet
or the army,'' commented Moscow News.
</P>
<P>
   It was Russia's mass media, which has complained of increasing
pressure from Putin's Kremlin to toe the party line, that gave
voice to the public anger. ``It was after all public opinion, about
the absence of which we have always complained, that forced the
president to break off his vacation and accept aid, from NATO of
all people,'' wrote Inna Rudenko in the newspaper Komsomolskaya
Pravda. It remains to be seen whether Putin will respond by
fostering more openness in government and the military, or with new
restrictions on the vulnerable media.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators expressed dismay that the former superpower
could not send its own divers to open a hatch on a Russian
submarine, and in the end had to ask Norwegian divers to do the
job. But another Komsomolskaya Pravda commentator said the Kursk
underlined a larger reality about post-Soviet Russian society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't have the right wrench,'' said Vladimir
Mamontov. ``It's that we don't have a country. One ended, and the
next one hasn't yet been built.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
