<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WILL GORE'S BOUNCE CARRY HIM TO DEBATES?
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrat Al Gore struck flint, but no great
political fire, when he accepted the Democratic presidential
nomination at his party's national convention here last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, as is expected for all pols coming out of their
conventions, he bounced up in the polls. Thus, at long last, he got
the joy of leading his Republican opponent George W. Bush in some
of the better known polls.
</P>
<P>
   And, as those polls indicate, he recaptured a great chunk of the
traditional Dem base of liberals and women, which had been less
than enamored with him before his speech, widely billed as ``the
most important'' of his political life.
</P>
<P>
   But, that he had to devote so much of his effort to
accomplishing that does not bode politically well for Gore.
Especially if those who warmed to him because of his super-long
litany of political promises ever snap to wonder how those promises
will be kept _ a question many in the hall here apparently had.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if that crowd's acceptance of the speech Gore and many
of his operatives contend was filled with substance had only
approximated the passion demonstrated in the onstage embrace
between Gore and his wife, the veep would have greater cause for
political contentment.
</P>
<P>
   There is a peculiar trend growing in presidential politics this
year _ a trend strongly supported by many in the political press
and one the candidates simply love. In essence, it causes any mere
mention of any subject _ especially those of Gore's choosing _ to
be deemed substance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, of course, hardly is alone in playing that the promise to
favor positions is substantive. Bush seems to do it as well _ if
not nearly as extensively as Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But, not only is promise-making far from the truly substantive,
what Gore achieved with his promises is too restricted to be
considered far on the road to winning. For example, many think he
scored so well with women because he promised so many things that
appeal to them, such as prescription drug benefits for senior
citizens, affordable health care for all and his promise to
continue to provide Social Security benefits with no changes.
</P>
<P>
   Topics such as these do not become substantive until the
candidate reveals how he will achieve them and at what cost. That
is why it is, to use a word he favors, risky for Gore to base his
campaign on promises and in his derision for candidates with
personality and likability _ his allusion to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting to not being able to sustain a display of strongly
convincing leadership and likability ultimately is quite likely to
wear too thin to serve Gore well. For example, though he evidently
played fairly well on the tube, the veep failed to genuinely excite
those in the hall with his rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest signals of this came in the comments of delegates
leaving even as the Democrats' version of a four-day
infomercial/political extravaganza was gaveled to a close.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of their plans for the evening ahead, their
transportation schedules home, the parties they attended, the basic
thrill of a political convention for political junkies and of their
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was one lone man who announced to the clutch of
friends with whom he was walking, ``Listen, for Gore, that was
really pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was this sentiment that prevailed when folk were questioned.
Some were more enthusiastic, several quite emphatic, most rather
calmly observant, in thinking the veep's delivery was quite good _
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most ardent of Democrats, however, were inclined to
think Gore's speech was considerably longer than it actually was
and much lacking in comparison to the one delivered by Bill Clinton
the opening night.
</P>
<P>
   To Gore's rhetorical credit, however, it can be said he did
about as good a job as possible of trying to associate himself with
the great economy the country has experienced in Clinton's tenure,
yet working to disassociate himself from the many peccadilloes
associated with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it is the latter that has caused the Gores to engage in
a fantastic number of displays of ardent affection _ as though such
will convince the American electorate this year's Democratic ticket
absolutely is committed to unwavering monogamy.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a far greater fool than even a ragtag political writer
stuck in the smog of California to flatly _ thus, madly _ predict
the outcome of a presidential election weeks down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one can't help but wonder: How many more of the most
important political moments of his life can Al Gore have this year?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was his convention speech. This week, the Dems are
looking toward the presidential debates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XX END OF STORY
</P>
