<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9295 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PENCIL IT IN: CONVENTIONS ALL SUMMER 2004
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luckily for them, most politicians and journalists left for home
Friday after the Democratic National Convention. A headline on the
front page of Saturday morning's Los Angeles Times would have sent
many of them back to bed with a migraine.
</P>
<P>
   It said: ``2004 Conventions May Run Longer as Focus Shifts to
Cable, Local TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight nights of primarily pre-scripted pablum (four in
Philadelphia for the Republicans, four on the West Coast for the
Democrats) hadn't been enough? An extension of the exquisite
torture was not what many in the political class had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Network coverage hit a historic low and viewership, too,
cratered _ the worst for the quadrennial wingdings since Nielsen
started keeping score back in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   But taking their cue from the glut of weightlifting, cookware
and cosmetics informercials flooding the airwaves, some party
leaders see merit in making the national conventions lengthier,
even more packaged and increasingly targeted. It's called
``narrowcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Add in the Internet and you have the new frontier in convention
planning.
</P>
<P>
   The national parties as well as the state and local political
honchos (especially candidates who have to fight for television
attention back home) like the largely uncritical coverage served up
by many local television reporters and even some of the national
cable broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Cable plays along because it has a gaping maw of a schedule to
fill, and many local TV stations and their correspondents don't
seem to know any better.
</P>
<P>
   But why just add a night or two to the current schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Why go to bed at all? Run those sessions round the clock. Surely
there's a big insomniac vote. Make conventions look like a Jerry
Lewis telethon. There are some politicians who will get up at any
hour to go on TV. (Note to Sen. Phil Gramm and Rep. Sheila Jackson
Lee: Don't set your alarm clocks. I'm just joking about this.)
</P>
<P>
   But don't laugh. The L.A. Times caught Democratic Rep. Ron Klink
of Pennsylvania, who's after a Republican-held Senate seat, getting
up one morning last week at 1:30 a.m. and hitting the convention
center at 3 a.m., California time, just so he could do a 6 a.m.
morning show back in Johnstown-Altoona, one of his home state's
medium-sized media markets.
</P>
<P>
   And why just one city? If Republicans this year had a rolling
roll call of the states, why can't there be a rolling convention?
Start about Memorial Day in Portland, Maine, hit the population
center of the nation (some burg in Missouri) around July Fourth and
then wrap up Labor Day weekend on the beach in Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   And because fund-raising is such an integral part of the
convention landscape, it may be time to revisit the idea of having
corporately sponsored events, such as the General Motors Pledge to
the Flag, the Boeing Co. Attack Night or the American Federation of
Teachers Acceptance Speech.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties quickly cottoned to the voracious needs of cable as
well as to the increasing (and, remember, uncritical) appetite of
many local network affiliates around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Andrew Card, the architect of the Republican show,
sensed there was a synergistic prospect in blending the
pre-convention, convention and post-convention show, and the Bush
campaign signed off happily.
</P>
<P>
   Card played what became known as a four-four-four strategy:
planning a largely repetitive four days of warm-up, four days of
convention and four days of postlude. It was a variation on the old
drum-it-in dictum of radio news: Tell 'em what you're going to tell
'em. Tell 'em. Then tell 'em what you told them.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans updated the design of the media stands in First
Union Center to provide plenty of positions for local TV stations.
Stanley Stiffhair could do his live shot back to Keokuk with the
GOP podium in the background, and it wasn't obvious to homefolks
that he was two inches from Gloria Goldentonsils who was warbling
for viewers in Ketchikan.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats zapped the heavens with multiple satellite uplinks to
beam local candidates back up to hometown television stations.
</P>
<P>
   And we just thought that the biggest smooch at the conventions
was Tipper's and Al's.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
