<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-MUSLIMS-ART-5     08-22 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-MUSLIMS-ART-570(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA'S RELIGIOUS DIVISIONS SHARPENED BY ADOPTION OF MUSLIM LEGAL
CODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUSAU, Nigeria _ When Yusuf Oumar saw early this year that this
state's politicians were adopting Islamic Shariah law and planning
to enforce it by segregating schools and taxis, not to mention
caning drinkers and amputating thieves, he made the only sensible
decision he could think of: He moved here.
</P>
<P>
   Oumar, a 37-year-old petty trader, packed up his goods and his
family, leaving the center of this West African nation for Gusau,
the capital of the small, formerly obscure state of Zamfara, in the
dusty northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Delighted with this place, he has recently built a house here
and set up shop in the middle of town in a new market populated by
recent arrivals like himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Shariah,'' Oumar said the other day, behind a table
laden with gadgets with seemingly familiar names like ``Suny'' tape
recorders and ``Naiwa'' radios.
</P>
<P>
   Oumar explained that no one cheated, stole or haggled in the
market thanks to the Islamic legal code. ``But even now our Shariah
is not yet like the one in Saudi Arabia. But in time _ by the grace
of God _ it will be like that. Small, small.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Zamfara, seven other states have embraced the laws of the
Koran in predominantly Muslim areas of northern Nigeria. The latest
one, Borno, held a ceremony to adopt it on Saturday, a week before
President Clinton's scheduled visit to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   If this state is a harbinger, this country of 36 states divided
uneasily between Muslims and Christians seems likely to experience
a hardening of those divisions. In a development that risks further
undermining the fragile unity of Nigeria and its 15-month-old
democracy, Muslims have been moving into the Shariah states and
Christians moving out, according to interviews here and with
officials from other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Since a series of deadly religious clashes in the north
recently, many Christians have relocated to Jos, a traditionally
Christian city and geographically the closest to the predominantly
Muslim north, said Rima Shawulu, an aide to the House speaker, Umar
Ghali Na'Abba. The influx was raising rent and land prices, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of the Christian population is widening the
Christian-Muslim gulf,'' said Shawulu, who commutes to Jos on
weekends from Abuja, the capital. ``Increasingly, it's becoming
difficult to have common ground. That is why it is fearful when we
think of national integration in the context of this gulf.''
</P>
<P>
   It was late last year that the ambitious politicians in this
state, backed by powerful northerners fallen out of favor in the
government of President Olusegun Obasanjo, began calls for Shariah.
The move proved so popular that other Muslim politicians, who had
initially dismissed Zamfara, could not but follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are using Shariah to create problems for the
Obasanjo government, either Muslims who have lost relevance in the
north or Christians who are calling for sovereignty in the south,''
said Yahaya Mahmood, the lawyer for a Muslim organization in the
north.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim leaders have politicized Shariah, Mahmood said, while
the Christians have used it to inspire fear among their followers
and stoke separatist sentiments. Nigeria's desperate poverty,
resulting from successive governments that have stolen the
country's oil money, provided the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was enough to eat, nobody would riot,'' Mahmood said.
``What we need is good government and sincere leadership.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nigeria has been blessed with little of either. In the
religiously mixed state of Kaduna, where thousands were killed in
riots after the state's leaders said they were considering Shariah,
Christians have gravitated to the south and Muslims to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard this area was all Christian,'' said Simon Tyonongo, a
new arrival to a neighborhood called Sabon Tasha. Tyonongo, a
jobless 40-year-old, who said he had lived until recently in a
mixed northern neighborhood, sat recently by a roadside in front of
two gutted houses. ``You see the Muslim houses there. They are all
burned and they are no longer staying here. It's better here for
me. I feel free.''
</P>
<P>
   Shariah has long been in effect among Muslims in the northern
states, as local religious leaders referred to it to decide on
personal matters like marriage and inheritance. While governments
played little role in its enforcement in the past, they are the
ones pushing it forward today.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Gusau, the government of Zamfara state has implemented
policies that now affect all areas of life: schools,
transportation, hotels, restaurants and criminal matters. In the
most famous case, a man who stole a cow was convicted in Shariah
court and had a hand cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He confessed, so there was no doubt at all,'' said Mahmud
Aliyu Shinkafi, the state's deputy governor, in an interview inside
his office here.
</P>
<P>
   Like all politicians who have moved toward Shariah, Shinkafi
emphasized that the law would apply only to Muslims, never to the
Christian minority living in Zamfara. This, he said, was not a move
toward an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, just outside his office, construction workers were
building a mosque with public money. A couple of miles away, in the
compound of the deputy governor's official residence, workers were
doing the same. The deputy governor's aides said they simply needed
a place to pray.
</P>
<P>
   Under Shariah, Shinkafi said, gambling, prostitution and crime
had nearly vanished. ``We had no armed robbery for 4 months,'' he
said, adding that it was only robbers from neighboring Kaduna state
who had recently slipped inside state lines to commit an offense.
``This is a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews in Gusau suggested that most Muslims shared his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   At the market, Abdulmmounu Mohammed, 35, was another trader who
had moved here after Shariah. ``We're enjoying it _ we have
peace,'' Mohammed said, explaining that in Kaduna, where he had
lived previously, his business had suffered. ``There were armed
robberies and stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   About the amputation of the cow thief, he added: ``People were
happy over it. The majority of the people here supported it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At another market, traders said Shariah had raised sales by
raising morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before when men collected their salary, they would spend it on
prostitutes or beer,'' said Ahmed Salis, 27, who sells plastic
containers. ``Now they come here with their wives and buy things
for the family.'' His sales had at least doubled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another trader, Ibrahim Lawal, 25, said he himself had turned
over a new leaf. ``This Shariah encouraged me to get married,''
Lawal said, adding that in another year or so he expected his
15-year-old wife to bear him a child.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of town, Halima Mamman, 55, was walking along
Gusau's biggest street, with her 7-year-old grandson in tow. Mamman
had moved from a village in the state to the capital here six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come here to the headquarters of Shariah,'' she
said. She strongly supported changes such as forbidding women to
ride on motorcycle taxis, called kabu-kabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision against kabu-kabu,'' she said, ``is in order for
the simple reason that Islam forbids women from touching any man
apart from her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred feet away, a group of girls had been waiting for
at least half an hour for a women-only taxi to pass by. The girls,
students at the government's Girls Arabic Secondary School, covered
their heads and faces with their shawls and hands. ``It has no
effect on us,'' one of them said of Shariah.
</P>
<P>
   Moving around town had become even harder for Christian women.
Forbidden from entering public taxis or buses, as well as
women-designated taxis unless they covered their heads, they relied
mostly on Christian kabu-kabu drivers. But they were often
difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we trek,'' explained Victorian Jonathan, a waitress here.
``I want to leave. I don't like the state. It's not good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Christians had already left, not only from this state, but
also from the others that have taken up the Koran, said officials
in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has bedeviled us, particularly at this time of
democracy,'' said Barminas Yilkes, 45, a congressman from Plateau
state, which include Jos, the city where many Christians had moved
to in recent months. ``Really, the effect is bad. You cannot live
in isolation and develop properly in a modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim generals who ruled Nigeria for most of its
post-colonial history had understood the divisiveness of Shariah.
And they had quickly suppressed calls for it in the past, viewing
it as challenge both to them and national unity.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Shariah seems to be weakening several of the policies
that had been undertaken to stitch together Nigeria after the
Biafran war, in which 1 million Nigerians were killed when the Ibo
tried to secede.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, university students have been required to spend
their first year after graduation serving in an area of the country
other than their own. In recent months, though, many Christian
graduates have left the Shariah states, or simply refused to go
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow my daughter to serve in the north,'' said
Dorcas Odujinrin, a Congresswoman from Lagos. ``It does not make
sense to train her and then send her to the den of the lion.''
Shariah, she added, ``is an infringement on the rights of women. It
is an oppressive system against everybody, especially women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
