<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9300 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ACCIDENTAL-ART-$ADV27     08-22 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCIDENTAL-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING ART IN RANDOM IMAGES IS AS OLD AS ART ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 27)  
 By MILES UNGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Jackson Pollock first lifted his brush from the
canvas and allowed paint to drip in tangled skeins across the
surface, or Jean Arp and Marcel Duchamp began to experiment with
chance procedures, they sought in the accidental and unpredictable
the means to shatter the stale conventions of art making. So, too,
Surrealists like Andre Masson and Juan Miro, who allowed their pens
to wander over the page in the belief that they would discover in
those doodles the ghosts of their own repressed imaginations. What
these artists _ all currently featured at the Museum of Modern Art
as part of the show ``Making Choices'' _ hoped to attain was
freedom, from the past, from academic formulas, and the random act
was their declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption was that the old masters were a more plodding
bunch, perfecting their craft only through years of patient study.
But a closer examination of the art of the past reveals that
artists _ and writers on art _ have long recognized the importance
of the unintended and unexpected in the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier centuries placed a greater emphasis on discipline, but
sometimes a masterpiece was born with an inadvertent splash or in a
moment of aesthetic pique. The first-century Roman writer Pliny the
Elder tells the story of the artist Protegenes, who became
frustrated with his efforts to paint a dog foaming at the mouth:
``Finally he fell into a rage with his art . . . and dashed a
sponge against the place in the picture that offended him . . . and
chance produced the effect of nature in the picture!''
</P>
<P>
   Here, the rage-induced splatter achieved what no amount of
careful planning could, a faithful rendering of animal fury.
Similar stories abound in other traditions. A ninth-century Chinese
treatise on painting describes the artist Wang Mo, ``who excelled
in splattering ink to paint landscapes.'' The chronicler continues
with a description that will sound familiar to audiences acquainted
with the biographies of more recent artists: ``There was a good
deal of wildness in him, and he loved wine. Whenever he wished to
paint a hanging scroll, he would first drink, then after he was
drunk he would splatter ink. Laughing or singing, he would kick at
it with his feet or rub it with his hands ... According to the
forms and appearances, he would make mountains and rocks, clouds
and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like this _ or another told of the 12th-century painter
Cheng Kang-chung, who also preferred to make his ink-blot paintings
after a few stiff drinks _ show that the myth of artist as savage
is not an invention of the Romantic era.
</P>
<P>
   For the Chinese chronicler, as for more modern biographers,
vitality of expression is often the gift of the untamed soul. But
it need not be the product of uncontrolled passion. One artist who
tried to systematize the use of the fortuitous mark was the English
landscape painter Alexander Cozens, whose 1785 how-to manual, ``A
New Method of Assisting the Invention in Drawing Original
Compositions of Landscape,'' recommends covering the page with
random ink blots, ``to draw forth ideas of an ingenious mind
disposed to the art of designing.'' The ink blots suggest new forms
to the mind in a manner similar to the Rorschach test, whose
deliberate ambiguity serves to draw out the patient's own fantasies
or obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   While Cozens' goal was not to probe the psychology of the
artist, he knew that indeterminate forms could unlock the inner
workings of the mind. ``There is a singular advantage peculiar to
this method,'' he declared, ``which is, that from the rudeness and
uncertainty of the shapes made in blotting, one artificial blot
will suggest different ideas to different persons; on which account
it has the strongest tendency to enlarge the powers of invention.''
</P>
<P>
   Cozens, like the Surrealists a century and a half later,
understood that ambiguity gave rise to individuality. In its
dismissal of convention and promotion of idiosyncratic invention,
this treatise is an important early salvo in the nascent Romantic
revolt.
</P>
<P>
   E.H. Gombrich, who wrote extensively on the role of the accident
in his book ``Art and Illusion,'' stressed that ambiguity is the
main ingredient in all such techniques. But mere ambiguity is not
enough to explain the efficaciousness of these forms, which suggest
profound affinities among the psychological, the natural and the
creative. Leonardo da Vinci, whom Cozens cites as the inspiration
for his own pedagogical technique, uses similarly muddled forms for
the purpose of ``arousing the mind to various inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo's preferred method was not to hurl and splatter at
random but to find suggestive forms in nature itself. In a famous
passage from his ``Treatise on Painting,'' Leonardo encourages the
aspiring landscape painter seek inspiration in natural forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at any walls spotted with various stains or with a
mixture of different kinds of stones,'' he wrote. ``If you are
about to invent some scenes, you will be able to see in it a
resemblance to various different landscapes adorned with mountains,
rivers, rocks, trees, plains, with valleys and various groups of
hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo's method differs from Cozens' in that he seeks out the
accidental in the world around him rather than improvising it on
the page. But, as Gombrich asserts: ``It matters less whether the
initial form into which the artist projects the image is man-made
or found. What matters is what he can make of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``found accident'' shifts the focus from the world of the
mind to the world of nature. Gombrich finds a remarkable parallel
to Leonardo's method in a passage by an 11th-century Chinese
artist, Sung Ti, who recommended that to achieve a ``natural
effect'' in landscape, the painter should throw a piece of silk
over an old wall and study its bumps and hollows. It is not
surprising that the found landscape plays a central role in Chinese
art, which, heavily influenced by Taoist beliefs, proclaims the
unity of all nature. The purest embodiment of these beliefs is the
so-called scholar's rocks, naturally occurring stones _ sometimes
minimally ``improved'' through human intervention _cherished for
their capacity to conjure in their crags and hollows whole
landscapes or mythical beasts. Robert Mowry, writing in ``Worlds
Within Worlds: The Richard Rosenblum Collection of Chinese
Scholars' Rocks,'' explains: ``Like a landscape painting, the rock
represented a microcosm of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a single stone standing as a cosmos-in-miniature
is intimately bound up with the Taoist world view, but this feeling
for the indivisibility of nature is not confined to the Eastern
tradition. An intriguing echo can be found in a treatise on
painting an the early 15th-century follower of Giotto, Cennino
Cennini.
</P>
<P>
   In a chapter titled ``The Way to Copy a Mountain from Nature,''
Cennini advises. ``If you wish to acquire good style for mountains,
and to have them look natural, get some large stones, rugged, and
not cleaned up; and copy them from nature, applying the lights and
the darks as your system requires.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this passage is often quoted as an example of the
artificiality of medieval studio practice, it reveals an
understanding of how a single set of principles runs through all
nature, from the microscopic to the monumental, a belief that
Leonardo would certainly have found congenial. Like the Chinese
scholar, the medieval Italian painter was able, to borrow William
Blake's famous line, ``to see infinity in a grain of sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the mottled forms of the ink spatter or the
convoluted topography of a water-carved stone are suggestive enough
to stimulate the imagination and open-ended enough to allow for an
almost infinite variety of readings.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are not made deliberately they do not come with
assigned meanings. Rather, it is we _ artist and viewer _ who must
make sense of them, bringing our own experience and personalities
to bear.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the accidental form as both a diagnostic tool in
psychology and a creative tool in art testifies to the mind's need
to organize random data into meaningful configurations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether deliberately fashioned, sought out or merely stumbled
upon, such forms traffic simultaneously in the universal and the
deeply personal. They are both liberating in their capacity to
stimulate our creative faculties and tyrannical in their insistence
that wherever we look, we will only see ourselves reflected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
