<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BALLET-DANCE-$ADV27-N     08-22 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-DANCE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BALLET STYLES WITH SOMETHING IN COMMON, ALAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
 By JACK ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's ballet world has two poles, and both are in danger of
freezing over. Plotless, or abstract, ballets are at one pole;
narrative ballets are at the other.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued that because there are two different but
valid types of ballet, each would theoretically complement the
other, thereby enriching company repertories. Unfortunately,
however, both abstract and dramatic works often suffer from a
deadly chill.
</P>
<P>
   These days, abstract ballets dominate many repertories. It was
George Balanchine who popularized the genre. Indeed, his
abstractions proved so remarkable that during the '50s and '60s
some dancegoers argued that it was aesthetically necessary for
ballet to discard plot and characterization, just as certain
artistic and musical authorities had argued that painting was
destined to become abstract and that historical necessity had
propelled music toward serialism.
</P>
<P>
   At their weakest, abstract painting and serial music developed
academic conventions. So, too, at times has abstract ballet. Thus
one currently popular choreographic recipe seems to be: Take a
piece of classical music and plow your way through it with fast
steps to the allegros and slow ones to the adagios. Few
choreographers have come close to equaling Balanchine, perhaps
because they have failed to realize that his abstractions, though
devoid of narrative, can be kinetic revelations of love, longing,
fear, struggle and aspiration. In contrast, other abstract
choreographers merely string steps together.
</P>
<P>
   Surely choreographers who have tired of abstractions ought to
revel in emotional confrontations, swashbuckling derring-do or
comic misadventures. Unfortunately, recent dramatic ballets can be
as tepid as the abstractions. One reason is that they tend to be
full-evening creations, and the longer they are, the duller they
grow.
</P>
<P>
   In the past season, for instance, American Ballet Theater danced
John Cranko's full-evening version of Shakespeare's ``Taming of the
Shrew.'' It has boisterously funny moments. It also has lots of
choreographic padding and is less ebullient than another Cranko
comedy, ``Pineapple Poll,'' a nautical romp in the style of a
Gilbert and Sullivan operetta that the Joffrey Ballet used to
perform. But ``Pineapple Poll'' is in only one act.
</P>
<P>
   Too many choreographers now appear to assume that dramatic
ballets ought to be multi-act productions. But consider some of the
distinguished dramatic pieces of the past century: Michel Fokine's
``Petrouchka,'' ``Firebird'' and ``Scheherazade,'' Leonide
Massine's ``Three-Cornered Hat'' and ``St. Francis,'' Balanchine's
``Apollo'' and ``Prodigal Son,'' Ninette de Valois' ``Job,''
Frederick Ashton's ``Wedding Bouquet,'' ``Enigma Variations'' and
``A Month in the Country,'' Antony Tudor's ``Jardin aux Lilas'' and
``Pillar of Fire,'' Eugene Loring's ``Billy the Kid,'' Jerome
Robbins' ``Fancy Free,'' and Agnes de Mille's ``Rodeo'' and ``Fall
River Legend.'' All are in one act. And their economy helps make
them enthralling.
</P>
<P>
   How many comparably admirable multi-act ballets can be set
beside them? The list is ominously short. Some balletomanes might
choose ``Romeo and Juliet,'' as choreographed by Ashton, Cranko,
Kenneth MacMillan or Leonid Lavrovsky, or Balanchine's adaptation
of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' But ``The Dream,'' Ashton's own
treatment of that fantasy, is equally worthy _ and in only one act.
We also have Ashton's fine personal versions of ``La Fille Mal
Gardee,'' an 18th-century comedy, and ``Ondine,'' a 19th-century
Romantic ballet. And what else?
</P>
<P>
   Repertory lists might suggest that a lot else exists. In recent
seasons, choreographers have based multi-act works on such literary
and historical figures as Cinderella, Camille, Peer Gynt, Anna
Karenina, Cleopatra, King Arthur, Peter Pan, the Three Musketeers,
the Great Gatsby and Dracula. Shakespeare is always popular source
material, ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' and ``Romeo and Juliet''
especially but others as well, including ``Othello.'' Yet the most
potent choreographic retelling of that tragedy remains a one-act:
Jose Limon's ``Moor's Pavane.'' And once Tudor also created a
poignant one-act ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   A curious thing about some of the multi-act productions is how,
after receiving their premieres and attracting attention (for they
are often scenically elaborate), they soon drop out of repertory. A
few return in a season or two, only to vanish once more; many are
never seen again. They have had their moments of fame.
</P>
<P>
   One would have to inspect companies around the world to come to
a definitive conclusion on this matter, yet it sometimes seems as
if choreographers turn to ``Romeo,'' ``Cinderella'' or ``Dracula''
not because they are deeply interested in those characters and
their stories but because they think such familiar titles will sell
lots of tickets. There's nothing wrong with selling tickets, but
marketing should not take precedence over creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographers should ask themselves, and managing directors and
board members should allow them to ask, ``What do I want _ what do
I really want _ to do?'' Balanchine's love of bodies moving to
music through intricate patterns in time and space gave us
``Agon.'' Tudor's concern for the quiet desperation of lonely
people gave us ``Pillar of Fire.'' Both works were considered
unconventional when new. Neither is tied to a well-known story or
an easily hummable score. But as audiences began to sense their
passion and realize their excellence, these ballets grew popular.
</P>
<P>
   Let marketing experts take care of the marketing. Choreographers
burning with passion ought to be encouraged to express that passion
in whatever dramatic or abstract form they think appropriate.
Otherwise, there may be no thaw at either balletic pole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
