<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BAYREUTH-MUSIC-$ADV27     08-22 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYREUTH-MUSIC-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE CRACKS IN THE WALLS OF VALHALLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany _ On the morning of a recent performance of
``Goetterdaemmerung'' (``Twilight of the Gods''), Wolfgang Wagner,
80 and a grandson of the man who composed the opera, was fighting
off a twilight of his own. Wagner is no god. Small, combative,
prolix and not without humor, he sparred with a press corps eager
to know more about the star defections and family squabbles that
have encroached on his 34-year regime as sole director of the
Wagner Festival here.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 124 years ago by Richard Wagner, the festival is under
siege from several directions. This press conference, accompanying
Juergen Flimm's new production of ``Der Ring des Nibelungen,'' had
art as its advertised subject matter, but so quickly did it veer
toward internal politics that Wagner threatened to call the
proceedings off scarcely after they had begun.
</P>
<P>
   This is a country accustomed to command and control on one side,
and order and acquiescence on the other. In what other culture
would an opera audience allow itself to be locked in (literally) to
a performance? My enduring image from a week spent in this small,
dull but not disagreeable Bavarian city was of two well-dressed
women standing at a curb late one evening. Not a car or a
pedestrian could be seen in any of four directions, yet patiently
they stood waiting for the ``Don't Walk'' sign to turn green. For a
Manhattanite it was an eerie picture.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner took every question not to his liking as an insult. He is
accustomed to command, and there was a palpable sense of a man who
no longer had the energy to exercise it fully. His 11-year-old
production of ``Parsifal'' had begun the week. It was a dreary
affair, rescued only by his grandfather's breathtaking music. The
principal props were giant crystalline stalagmites, shuffled into
different formations. In matters of staging, Wagner leaned toward
the emotive stagger, the beaten breast and the well-wrung hand.
</P>
<P>
   Decently sung and eccentrically conducted by Christoph
Eschenbach, this ``Parsifal'' should have been the anchor of the
festival. It is the one opera Wagner wrote specifically for the
distinctive qualities of his Festspielhaus. He did so with the
muffled glow of the orchestral sound and the easy resonance
provided singers already in his ears. The Bayreuth production of
``Die Meistersinger,'' I am told, is just as forlorn.
</P>
<P>
   Other factions of the Wagner family want Wolfgang out, but he is
virtually unfireable. His niece Nike Wagner has joined Elmar
Weingarten, the general manager of the Berlin Philharmonic, in a
manifesto proposing that the festival widen to different locations,
introduce theme seasons and add early Wagner pieces like ``Die
Feen'' and ``Das Liebesverbot.'' Intriguing is their idea to
commission site-specific operas gauged to the peculiar qualities of
the Festspielhaus.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Bayreuth is human nature at work: the good and the
bad of tradition versus the good and the bad of change. Wagner's
widow, Cosima, ran the early years in stern homage to her husband's
specific wishes. These were, of course, wishes as interpreted by
her, and Cosima was careful to get rid of adjutants who had been
around and might have had a different version of the ``facts.''
Cosima-induced rituals of gesture survived well into the 20th
century, as did some of the painted scenery. Yet her son,
Siegfried, began the modernization of Bayreuth productions (often
at odds with written directions) as early as 1908.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt a conspiracy, but the defection this summer of two
longtime Bayreuth stars lines up alongside the Nike Wagner forces.
The bass Hans Sotin, after 29 years at the festival, withdrew as
Gurnemanz in ``Parsifal'' following the dress rehearsal, citing
``unbridgeable differences'' with Eschenbach; the administration
line was one of puzzlement and disappointment. Eschenbach was on a
plane to the United States on the morning after the opener, leaving
Wagner to fence with the press.
</P>
<P>
   The more glamorous accuser was the mezzo-soprano Waltraud Meier,
who, in an interview with the local newspaper the Nordbayerische
Kurier, described the festival's course as ``sad and aimless,''
expressed horror at the Sotin affair and announced her withdrawal
from future festivals. This year she sang Sieglinde in the
``Ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, in an eight-and-a-half-minute response at the press
conference, said that Sotin's decision to quit was purely his own
and that the Meier affair involved the singer's competing
commitments in Munich and Salzburg, which overlapped her rehearsal
times at Bayreuth. Wagner had a point, but Sotin and Meier can
sing, and he can't. What was offered this summer at Bayreuth was
Gabriele Schnaut, coarse and deafening as Bruennhilde, and Wolfgang
Schmidt, a vocal disaster as Siegfried.
</P>
<P>
   American money is coming in bigger amounts to Bayreuth, which,
like other European arts institutions, is no longer smug in the
knowledge of heavy government support. With levels of federal and
local underpinning altered in Germany, the nurturing of ``Friends
of'' societies in foreign countries is becoming as important in
Bayreuth as it has been at the Salzburg Festival in Austria. One
major gift is from Alberto Vilar, an investment manager whose name
and checkbook are already writ large at the world's prestigious
opera houses. Vilar will pay for a new ``Tannhaeuser'' production
in two years, and ``no artistic influence'' will accompany the
money, Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Munificence like this has become crucial to the changing economy
of opera. Yet it will arrive in the middle of a political war for
control of the festival (with other members of the family also
candidates to succeed Wolfgang, including Gudrun Wagner, his second
wife; Eva Wagner-Pasquier, his daughter by his first wife; and
Wieland Lafferentz, a nephew of Wagner); and whether intended or
not, it lands squarely in Wagner's camp. One image that Bayreuth
does not need is American money versus European art.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
