<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DARK-DAYS-FILM-ART-$A     08-22 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARK-DAYS-FILM-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME WAS A TUNNEL AND NEIGHBORS WERE HIS CAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 27)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By PETER APPLEBOME  
 .2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One October evening in 1994, a scruffy pod of
homeless people sitting around a fire in the dank, dark Amtrak
tunnel they lived in beneath Manhattan heard a thin, animated man
named Ralph come up with an idea. ``Someone should be making a film
about this stuff,'' he said. The others nodded or laughed or agreed
or shook their heads at the absurdity of the thought, and the
conversation moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Singer still finds it hard to believe that such an idle
remark could have inspired his odyssey, one that led a 20-year-old
who had never picked up a camera to live underground himself,
enlist his fellow outcasts as his crew and put together an
84-minute, black-and-white documentary that won three awards at
this year's Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   But when Singer's ``Dark Days'' opens for a two-week run at the
Film Forum in New York on August 30 _ with bookings in six other
cities set after that _ it will mark the culmination of six years
of work that in almost every way mirrored the life-on-the-edge
existence of his compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   The film was cobbled together through grit, guile and an ability
to rummage through society's detritus and spare parts. It was done
in utter isolation from anything resembling the mainstream world of
film. It was a project whose survival was always not just in doubt
but highly unlikely. In the end, it reached an improbably
redemptive conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   If the documentary is unlikely to change too many minds about
the nature of the homeless, it allowed Singer, who grew up in an
upper-middle class family in London and came to New York with hopes
of becoming a fashion model, to succeed in his aim of making not
just visible, but thoroughly human, New York's invisible people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal, crazy as it sounds, was to make enough money to
get everyone out of the tunnel,'' said Singer, 26, whose restless
energy, close cropped hair, white T-shirts and cargo pants, summon
up the street more than the runway. ``But the other goal was to
just let people see the homeless as they are, so maybe they'll look
at them with less hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to go on a mission with this film. I never
wanted to convert anyone into helping the homeless. But we look at
them as if they're not human. It's like there's an invisible wall
there. But you go and meet them, and it turns out they're just like
me and you; they just don't have a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer's unlikely journey began when he was living in the East
Village, shortly after he moved to New York from Miami. He came to
know some of the street people in his neighborhood and through them
learned about the subculture of ``mole people'' living in the
railroad tunnels from 72nd Street to 125th Street underneath the
West Side Highway. There were from 50 to 75 of them in the winter
and perhaps 150 to 200 in the summer, and soon he found himself
spending most of his time with them by the plywood shacks,
makeshift shanties and nightly campfires they built alongside the
railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than thinking of Ralph's idea as a stray pipe dream, he
took it on _ first as a quixotic project, then as something close
to an obsession. He began by getting Cinevision, the downtown
camera shop, to give him the use of what became the first of four
Arriflex SR2 16-millimeter cameras he used to make the film. He
sold most of his belongings, and finally even his own bed, to buy
film and supplies. When he ran out of film and money, Kodak gave
him much of what he needed free of charge. He took to living
underground with his subjects and eventually became homeless too. A
friend went to the bank and gave him his last $10,000. He did not
have a print to take to Sundance until the day he got on the plane
and carried it with him.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the homeless people _ identified in the credits
only by their first names _ became not just his subjects but his
collaborators. Singer and the tunnel people all trooped off
together to see the documentary ``Hoop Dreams'' and decided they
could make a film, too. They became Singer's film crew, learning
and improvising as they went along, much as he did. When they
needed a dolly, they built one using an old grocery cart and an
abandoned stretch of rail. They ran cable underground, hooked up to
whatever power source they could find, and for lighting used
hand-held floodlights mounted on metal crosses. He gave a dozen of
the homeless _ three of whom died before the film could be released
_ part ownership in the film, so they stand to profit if it makes
money.
</P>
<P>
   What he captured was a life underground that was at once
entirely alien and oddly familiar. Singer's friends cooked over
fires and small stoves. They listened to radios and watched
television, using electricity tapped illegally from aboveground.
They sat in their shacks in T-shirts emblazoned ``Bank of America''
or ``Republican National Convention,'' with a dog at their feet and
pictures on the wall, discussing favorite recipes, long-lost pets
and sometimes horrific family tragedies. They got food from
scavenging through garbage and showered under a leaky water pipe.
</P>
<P>
   But through much of the film they seem not so much homeless as
people whose home happens to be 50 feet underground, one that can
be torn down with a sledgehammer in about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting portrait is tantalizingly complex: at one moment
there are rats scurrying around; in the next, it all seems vaguely
homey. While the subjects come across for the most part as
articulate hosts and raconteurs, they are also capable of
lacerating confession and crack-addled delusion.
</P>
<P>
   Singer's unconventional film concludes with the most
conventional of scenes, one depicting the bliss the homeless people
ascend to when, after being evicted from the tunnel, they find
themselves in clean, private apartments paid for with Section 8
government-subsidized housing vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of romanticizing the homeless or vilifying the Amtrak
officials who evicted them, the film reminds us that the people on
the street _ or under it _ want nothing so much as a home.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Singer takes pains to point out that his subjects
aren't stand-ins for ``the homeless,'' a more-or-less homogeneous
group of society's victims. ``People on the street get lumped
together, but there are so many types,'' he said. ``There are
people who are mentally ill and people on the street fleeing
abusive homes, there are runaway kids on drugs, there are people
who've been burned out of their house and have nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a million ways that people can get on the street,
and there are bad people there. But there are a lot of good people,
too. And I ended up with enormous respect for everyone in the
tunnel, because they just wouldn't give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put myself in that situation, and I wonder what would I have
done? Would I have given up, because it would have been easy to do.
I mean out of sight, out of mind, and how much further out of sight
can you get than living in a tunnel?''
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, the making of the film was very much a process
of clawing in the direction of survival. ``Marc's incredibly
confident and incredibly determined,'' said Melissa Neidich, the
film's editor. ``If he wants to learn something, he'll learn it
completely. If he wants to do something, he'll do what he has to do
to master it. That's the way he was able to get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   But after devoting six years to the film, Singer views its
theatrical release with mixed feelings of excitement, trepidation
and, finally, an urge to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so ready to let go of it, mate,'' he said. ``Six years is
a long time to think about something seven days a week, often 20
hours a day. I can't get past it yet, but I'm looking forward to
when I can. What I'd like to do is get away, sit on a beach and
think the bloody ocean is a lovely color blue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
