<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: ROYAL PEACE TRIP
</P>
<P>
   On the first visit to Israel by an Arab leader since the failed
Camp David talks, King Abdullah II of Jordan met Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, and Prime Minister Ehud Barak. Arab diplomats
said the king's aim was to try to find common ground on the issue
of Jerusalem, but the talks appeared to have produced no break in
the impasse. It was the second meeting between the king and Barak
in a week; the two also held talks in Amman, the Jordanian capital.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: 23 HELD AS TERRORISTS
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian security officials have arrested 23
Arabs suspected of planning a series of terror attacks to disrupt
peace plans, and said at least one suspect had links to Osama bin
Laden, the FBI's most wanted terrorist suspect. Security officials
said the arrests, over three months, involved radicals with links
to the Hamas and Islamic Holy War groups active in Gaza and the
West Bank, as well as the Al-Qaeda movement led by bin Laden from
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: DROUGHT HITS 37 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   The drought that has devastated large areas of southern and
western Asia, from India to the Middle East, has affected 37
million people in Iran, a U.N. relief official said. Vladimir
Sakharov, who toured Iran for 17 days with a team from Unicef, the
World Health Organization and the office of the U.N. coordinator
for humanitarian affairs, said drinking water was scarce and many
people had lost crops and livestock for the second year. He said it
was the worst drought in Iran since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: AWOL OFFICER LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Army Reserve intelligence officer who was declared absent
without leave in Israel denied reports he was a spy and returned to
the United States. ``First of all, I'm on vacation here,'' Lt. Col.
Jeremiah Mattysse said. ``I'm not a spy. I've given no classified
information to anybody.'' Mattysse, 50, denied allegations he had
fled the intelligence unit he had headed in Texas with confidential
information.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: ARMS RING UNCOVERED
</P>
<P>
   The government announced the uncovering of an international arms
trafficking ring that smuggled 10,000 assault rifles from Jordan to
the Amazonian jungles of Peru for delivery to Marxist guerrillas
fighting in Colombia. Six people were arrested, including two
Peruvian military officers.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: BRIBERY INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua promised to cooperate with an
investigation into charges that a labor reform bill he proposed
passed the Senate in April after opposition senators received
bribes and other personal favors. Several officials, including the
labor minister, have volunteered for questioning by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN, NORTH KOREA: ROCKY TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Japanese and North Korean negotiators vowed to try to set up
diplomatic ties, but hopes for a breakthrough looked dim as the
longtime foes stuck to entrenched positions on key issues. On the
first of two days of talks in Tokyo, North Korea repeated its call
for Japan to apologize and pay reparations for its 1910-45 rule
over the Korean Peninsula. Japan replied by raising the issue of 10
Japanese citizens Tokyo believes were kidnapped by North Korean
agents.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: REVEALING PREMIER'S PAST
</P>
<P>
   A court decided to ask the police to make public whether or not
they apprehended Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori in a brothel more than
40 years ago _ an allegation by a weekly magazine that Mori has
denied. News organizations said the Tokyo District Court, holding
hearings on a suit filed by Mori against the magazine, Truth of the
Rumor, had made the unusual decision in response to a request by
the magazine's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: LIBYA INCREASES RANSOM
</P>
<P>
   Libya has agreed to pay $1 million for each of the 12 foreign
hostages held by Muslim rebels in the southern Philippines since
April 23, clearing the way for their release ``fairly soon,''
officials close to the negotiations said. The hostages were to have
been freed last weekend but the Abu Sayyaf guerrillas delayed the
release after Libya haggled to lower the ransom to $700,000 per
captive, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
   MONGOLIA: HELD IN '98 KILLING
</P>
<P>
   The police have detained a leading opposition politician,
Erdeniin Bat-Uul, as a suspect in the 1998 killing of the country's
leading democracy figure, Bat-Uul's wife, Delgertuyaa, said. She
said her husband was first arrested on charges of disturbing public
order, but then prosecutors said he was being held as a suspect in
the murder of Sanjaasurengiin Zorig, minister of infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: PEACE TRIP OFF
</P>
<P>
   President Pierre Buyoya canceled a trip to South Africa and a
meeting with Nelson Mandela, and instead focused on calming Tutsi
opposition to a peace accord intended to end the country's civil
war, which started in 1993. Tensions between Hutu and minority
Tutsi have increased as an Aug. 28 deadline neared for signing a
power-sharing pact. Mandela, the former South African president,
has been mediating talks and has invited President Clinton to
witness the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERIA: BRITISH TV CREW HELD
</P>
<P>
   A judge rejected a request to grant bail to a British television
crew charged with spying, saying the accusations were too grave.
Two Britons, a Sierra Leonean and a South African say they were
working on a documentary for Channel 4 in Britain, where Foreign
Office minister Peter Hain called the arrests ``an attack on
international press freedom.'' Liberia says the crew was trying to
link President Charles Taylor to diamond smuggling and gun-running
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PIG BAN NARROWED
</P>
<P>
   The European Union recommended the narrowing of a ban on
importing live pigs from England to cover only animals from an area
in southeast England where an outbreak of swine fever is said to
have been contained. A European panel said there had been no new
reports of the disease in Suffolk, Norfolk and Essex since Aug. 12.
The United States has also banned English pork products and China
said it would do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
