<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION (Peoria, Ill.) _ Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush, on a two-day swing through the Midwest,
pushes a $5 billion program aimed at encouraging states to teach
children to read by the third grade. He says reading is the
foundation for education excellence. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-VETERANS (Milwaukee) _ Vice President Al Gore tells the
convention of the Veterans of Foreign Wars that America's fighting
forces are the strongest and most modern in the world. On Monday,
Republican George W. Bush told the same gathering that the military
had been neglected by the Clinton-Gore administration. By BENNETT
ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-KIDS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas leads the nation with the
highest percentage of uninsured children but is moving faster than
others to solve its problem, a state health official tells
lawmakers. In the first five months of the Children's Health
Insurance Program, Texas enrolled 17 percent of 428,000 eligible
children and has set a goal to enroll all in the next year. One
lawmaker, however, says the state is behind in helping the poorest
children get Medicaid coverage. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLICS-PILL (Undated) _ A pill used to treat nausea in
chemotherapy patients may help early-onset alcoholics reduce their
drinking, or stop it altogether, according to a new study. By LEIGH
HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEA-CHIEF (Undated) _ The recently confirmed head of the Drug
Enforcement Administration began his career in the early 1970s
fighting Mexican drug cartels in Texas. After 30 years in law
enforcement, DEA Administrator Donnie Marshall says some things
have not changed. By MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Washington) _ Network coverage of the Republican
and Democratic conventions hit a historic low and viewership, too,
cratered. But taking their cue from the glut of weightlifting,
cookware and cosmetics informercials flooding the airwaves, some
party leaders see merit in making the national conventions
lengthier, even more packaged and increasingly targeted. It's
called ``narrowcasting.'' By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ELY-COLUMN (Houston) _ Al Gore may be up in the polls, but he is
still struggling. He's appealing to voters by selling promises as
substance, but George W. Bush is selling personality, which will
probably attract more voters. By JANE ELY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means is on vacation. The MEANS-COLUMN will resume
Monday, Aug. 28.
</P>
