<HEADER>
A9315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HUDSON-BRADY-NYT &LR;      08-22 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDSON-BRADY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `NO' TO `YO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Katherine M. Brady is chief executive of the Brady Corp., a
manufacturer of identification and material-solution productions;
this was written with Julia Lawlor)  
 By KATHERINE M. HUDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had planned to be an economics professor. I went to graduate
school at Cornell University on a fellowship, but in 1969, the
school fell apart. There were student demonstrations against the
Vietnam War, the administration lost control of the university, and
the campus shut down for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   I was studying; I wasn't demonstrating. I'm a conservative
Republican. So I took a leave from the fellowship, packed up my VW
Beetle _ that part of me was a little avant-garde _ and headed home
to Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   I knocked on the door at Eastman Kodak, where my dad had started
as a messenger boy at 18, and got a job as a systems analyst in the
logistics area.
</P>
<P>
   I was paid $10,206 a year, an awesome salary. So awesome, I said
to myself, ``Why would I go back to school to be an economics
professor?''
</P>
<P>
   After six years at Kodak, I had a goal: to be the first woman
corporate officer in a job that was not OK for a woman to be in.
That meant not human resources, not public relations, not
advertising. Something that was where the guys were.
</P>
<P>
   I ended up being talked into taking a job in corporate
communications. That led to a job as director of community affairs,
where I got to work with the Kodak's chairman, Walter Fallon.
</P>
<P>
   He was tough. The first time I went to his office with my boss,
he looked up and said, ``What's she doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   But he taught me how to think like the boss.
</P>
<P>
   After that, I turned around the instant photography division. We
went from losing $35 million to making $5 million a year. And in
1988, I became chief information officer, the first woman corporate
officer of Kodak. In the summer of 1993, the board of directors
fired the CEO, Kay Whitmore, and held a meeting of 50 Kodak
managers.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Goizueta, who was the chairman of Coca-Cola at the time,
told a story at the meeting about his grandfather, who raised boxer
dogs. He said if the dogs were more than 30 percent white, they
were considered defective and had to be destroyed. He said that was
the problem with Kodak management: it was too inbred, and we had to
bring new people in. Those of us in the room who'd been trying to
make changes all along were fuming. After you're accused of being a
dog, when the phone rings and it's a headhunter, you listen. Next
thing you know, I was CEO of a $240 million company.
</P>
<P>
   At Brady, our mission statement talks about creating a
challenging and fun work environment. We're going from a culture of
``No'' to a culture of ``Yo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo'' is our cheer. We give out yo-yo's as awards. My first
license plate on my Dodge Ram pickup truck said ``No2Yo.''
</P>
<P>
   We try to have fun. A few years ago, we would shoot each other
with Batman guns at our meetings. Every year we hold the ``Martha
Stewart Good Housekeeping Tour.'' I play Martha, and I go around
giving out the seal of approval to everyone who's done a good job
cleaning their office.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm proud that I've been able to sustain a family life. I
have a really great kid, a wonderful husband. A week before we were
supposed to get married, he was rushed to the hospital with a
blocked intestine. He almost died. So we held the ceremony in the
hospital. The bride wore a red business suit, the groom wore blue
pj's and a robe, and after 20 years of marriage, he can still get
in his wedding outfit, and I can't. We live on a farm with two dogs
and a cat. The problem with being a CEO is that you're always
thinking about work. I try to get home for dinner most nights so I
can spend time with my 12-year-old son. But if you'd talk to him,
he'd say Mommy works all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      08-22 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FLIGHT ATTENDANT SINGS PRAISES OF CORPORATE
FLYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moving in ``t'' category) 
 By JOE SHARKEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rene Foss, a flight attendant, jokes about flying ``around the
world in a bad mood.'' In fact, she's written a musical revue with
that title. More on that later. But first, a good word for business
travelers from Foss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business traveler is my favorite passenger, mainly because
they're used to the system,'' said Foss, who is 38 and has worked
for Northwest Airlines for 16 years. ``As a rule, they're usually
the best dressed, the best behaved, and the most sympathetic when
there's a problem,'' she said. ``They're the most sophisticated of
the travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait, though. Let's not get carried away with the compliments.
You know those self-important bozos you often see with a
first-class upgrade and an attitude? (I recently watched a
businessman waving his first-class ticket literally push a woman in
a wheelchair out of the way so he could be the very first in line
to board a flight to Phoenix.) Flight attendants encounter
customers like that every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, with some business travelers, their demands have
increased,'' she said. ``There is a sense of entitlement. They
expect a little more, maybe because they're paying a higher price
for the ticket, or they're angry because they've had a horrible
experience on the previous flight, or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, don't get her started. This is a woman who sends out
information about her theatrical revue tucked in an airline barf
bag. A woman who has written ditties called ``The Ballad of Jed
Clampett,'' which describes the bewildered hordes of infrequent
fliers who fly during the summer-sale season, and ``The Hello
Song,'' in which overburdened flight attendants start out warbling
sweet hellos that soon descend into a cacophony of fulminating
rage. A woman who says modestly, ``I have written a musical comedy
based on my rotten life, I mean, my glamorous life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, referring to her day job in the sky, ``you get some
of these young guys in first class, they think they're kind of hot
shots,'' she said. ``They'll get done with their meal and then they
want to get their computer out right away, so they'll just put
their garbage on the floor. They don't even look up when we come by
to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The abilities to ``take abuse and collect trash in confined
areas'' are, in fact, prime job requirements for becoming a flight
attendant, as an employment supervisor for Wafti (We Apologize for
the Inconvenience) Airlines explains it to the bright-eyed
job-seeker played by Foss in her show, ``Around the World in a Bad
Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical revue has a cast of five, including one other
working flight attendant. Originally produced in New York two years
ago, it was a hit this summer at the Minneapolis Fringe Festival, a
program of off-beat theater. The show, which is popular with
off-duty flight attendants and other airline employees, returns to
New York for four Saturday night performances next month at Rose's
Turn, a Greenwich Village cabaret (212 712-8702).
</P>
<P>
   Foss' mother was a flight attendant in the 1950s, when air
travel was considered to be an elegant way to go. But she doesn't
have any illusions about the way women were once treated as
stewardesses who were there to pamper and flatter business
travelers, who have always been the airlines' prime customers and
whose ranks were overwhelmingly male until the 1980s. Remember
those pouty, suggestive ``Fly Me!'' airline commercials?
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother was flying the stewardesses wore white
gloves,'' Foss said. ``But they also had to wear a girdle. They
would come to work and have to be checked. Yes, the airlines had a
girdle checker. And do you know what else? They had a weight
checker. And if you were five pounds over what your weight was
supposed to be, you were grounded till you lost the weight.
Stewardesses would go on these awful diets, not eat for three days
to try to lose five pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said: ``They had to quit when they got married, which
is why my mother left the business. They had a rule that at age 32,
you had to quit, no matter what. So the life was glamorous in a lot
of ways. Airline crews used to stay at much better hotels and enjoy
longer layovers, for example. But at the same token, there was a
dark side. There was a girdle checker.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we hear a song coming on there?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Other possibilities for new material in the show
include the prospect of passengers being able to use cell phones in
the air, with all the ensuing drama, resentment and fury.
``Actually, that could be an opera,'' said Foss, who is always
working on new material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I'm any big writer or anything, but for me the
airline experience is fascinating to try to capture because it's
sometimes so much like a drama or a comedy,'' she said. ``Honestly,
it's like watching a play. You just stand there and observe
quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd never know she was a wise acre, at least not on the job.
``I'm really not much of a smart aleck,'' she confided. ``I'm too
afraid I'll get in trouble. I try to keep my mouth shut as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Just remember, though. That flight attendant up there by the
galley might well be taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
