<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GOV-LAWSCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOUISIANA, LAWYERS' ARCHRIVAL STUDIES LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For five years, Gov. Mike Foster of Louisiana has made
no secret of his contempt for the state's trial lawyers, calling
them ``bad guys'' who played too large a role in picking judges and
influencing legislation. He pushed through changes to Louisiana's
legal system that reduced damage awards, and accused lawyers of
driving jobs out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday morning, demonstrating the assured singularity that
has become his trademark, the 70-year-old governor walked into a
classroom at Southern University in Baton Rouge and began his first
day of law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a lifelong ambition,'' he explained to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   That ambition has been well-hidden from the public, which has
watched with some amusement as he made his battles with lawyers a
foundation of his successful campaigns for office in 1995 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial lawyers always hide behind the working people, but
they are the biggest enemy of the working people,'' Foster said
last year. ``The lawyers will run business out of the state and
that means they run jobs out of the state. They've done it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marsanne Golsby, Foster's press secretary, said the governor
has been talking about studying law for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes a challenge, and he's had to put up with lawyers all
of his professional life,'' Golsby said. ``It just eats at him that
an area of expertise that he runs across, a big area of knowledge
that's very very important, he doesn't know himself. He doesn't
like it when they know something he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Golsby said the governor will begin with three courses _ torts,
civil procedure and legal writing _ and will continue taking a
half-load of courses as long as he has the time. She described him
as ``a little nervous'' when he realized how much reading he would
have to do, but said he was willing to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Foster has not said whether he would actually become a lawyer
after his term expires in three years, but he does not appear to
need the extra income. Before entering public office, he became a
wealthy businessman with interests in construction and his family's
sugar plantations. But several law-school graduates said he was
welcome in their profession, hoping it might ease some of the
tension between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased education always allows people to make better
decisions,'' said Sam Gregorio, president of the Louisiana Trial
Lawyers Association. ``I applaud his intellectual interest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2014EDT &QL; 
