<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-VETERANS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VETERANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TELLS VETS BUSH IS WRONG IN CRITICISM OF MILITARY READINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore told a
veterans group Tuesday that his Republican opponent was not only
wrong in his criticism of the nation's military readiness, but was
risking the nation's security.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the Veterans of Foreign Wars national convention that
the Clinton administration has worked to reverse the decline in
defense spending and has successfully lobbied for military pay
raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that year-after-year commitment to a strong defense that
makes me so concerned when others try to run down America's
military for political advantage in an election year,'' Gore said.
``That's not only wrong in fact _ it's the wrong message to send
our allies and adversaries across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was referring to Bush's speech to the veteran's group
Monday, when the Texas governor said the ``next president will
inherit a military in decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore rebutted Bush's claims, saying the Army's 10 divisions are
combat ready, the Navy has more than twice as many surface ships as
China and ``our Air Force is by far the largest and most modern in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his critics, Gore said, ``Let them remember our
overwhelming victory in Kosovo _ without a single American life
lost in battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore pledged to modernize weapons systems, lobby for another pay
increase, improve military housing, and reduce the number of
soldiers on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will insist that we follow this simple rule: We must never
send our service men and women to do what they are not equipped to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also drew a subtle contrast with his opponent by noting
that he had served as an Army reporter in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Bush served in the Texas Air National Guard. Neither man went
into combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do the most or run the gravest danger,'' Gore said.
``But I was proud to wear my country's uniform. And my own
experiences gave me strong beliefs about America's obligation to
keep our national defenses strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's military credentials were on display when he entered the
convention hall wearing his VFW Tennessee chapter cap.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett called Gore's comments ``reactionary
and defensive,'' proof that Bush's point was having an effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore says he's committed to helping veterans, but this
administration has continually offered budgets that made huge cuts
in veterans programs,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore launched a series of campaign ads Tuesday that detail his
Vietnam experience, congressional career and family life.
</P>
<P>
   The ads begin by looking back to 1969. ``America in turmoil,'' a
narrator says. ``Al Gore graduates college. His father, a U.S.
senator, opposes the Vietnam War. Al Gore has his doubts, but
enlists in the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent biography, Gore enlisted to help his
father weather attacks by his Republican opponent during his
re-election campaign in Tennessee. The senior Gore lost anyway.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore may hope his Vietnam stint will give him an advantage
over Bush, his boss, Bill Clinton, proved that military service is
not prerequisite to winning the White House. Clinton beat George
Bush and Bob Dole, both of whom saw action in World War II.
Republicans were unsuccessful in derailing Clinton by portraying
him as a draft dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was received warmly by the veteran's group, a number of
whom said they liked the fact that he served in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   However, others said they saw little differences between the two
candidates when it came to strengthening the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on most issues both candidates are the same. They tell
you what you want to hear,'' said Kenneth Ricciardi, 54, who served
in the Marine Corps in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Ricciardi, who works for the city of Milwaukee, said he is
tempted to write in on the presidential ballot the name of Sen.
John McCain, the former Vietnam POW who unsuccessfully challenged
Bush in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Korean War veteran James Klug, 69, was puzzled how Bush and Gore
could offer such different assessments of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush was telling us we are in a decline. Today we heard the
opposite,'' said Klug of Omaha, Neb. Klug said he liked the more
``positive'' outlook saying ``as of today I'm voting for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Kobluck, 49, a Vietnam War veteran from Chicago, said
that while military experience is important, it was not the only
factor he weighed in voting for a president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say the economy is the best it's ever been. My
pocketbook tells me at the moment to vote Democrat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
