<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Martha Shares a Tip With Oprah 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR;  talks turkey with  &UR; Martha Stewart &LR;  in the latest
issue of O. Both women admit to being perfectionists. Both admit to
being taskmasters. ``You can't be a taskmaster?'' asks Stewart.
``Forget it. You can be a taskmaster and you can uphold your
standards. And you can create standards of perfection and quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a book called `American Standard of Perfection' by the
American Poultry Association. Most associations have standards of
perfection that they adhere to. So when they look at a chicken,
they can look at the picture in the book, then look at the chicken
and see if it is an example of perfection. . . . You can do that in
other parts of life, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After comparing standards for poultry to ideals for people,
Stewart insists that she knows how to let down her guard and have a
good time with friends. She shares her special technique to help
them get over any awe they might have of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going to people's houses. My friends all invite me out.
I'm actually setting all my silverware out backward now! Dyslexic
table settings, so some people don't get intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MUGGLES IS &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; AND MUGGLES WAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle reported last week that  &UR; J.K. Rowling &LR; , author of
the Harry Potter books, is fighting with  &UR; Nancy Stouffer &LR; , a
Pennsylvania children's book author, over the word ``Muggles.''
Muggles are people without magical powers in the Potter books; in
1984 Stouffer published ``The Legend of Rah and the Muggles.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter publisher Scholastic's response to Stouffer's suit
includes mention of trumpeter  &UR; Louis Armstrong &LR; 's 1920s blues tune
called ``Muggles,'' a familiar jazzman's word for marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Iman &LR;  was carrying her baby  &UR; Alexandria &LR;  when she walked into
a New York hotel a few days ago, and  &UR; David Bowie &LR; , the papa, was a
few steps behind, the New York Daily News reported, carrying an
infant car seat.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Paul Sorvino &LR;  couldn't fit comfortably behind the wheel of a
Cadillac while shooting ``Plan B,'' so the seat was taken off its
tracking to accommodate him. His representative,  &UR; Leslie &LR; 
 &UR; Sloane-Zelnik &LR; , told New York magazine that it wasn't surprising.
``Paul's like 6-foot-2. He's all leg.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dan Kerrigan &LR; , a welder who the Boston Herald says worked
extra jobs to pay for the skating lessons of his daughter,  &UR; Nancy &LR; 
 &UR; Kerrigan &LR; , has won $1 million on a $5 Massachusetts lottery ticket.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HERE AND NOW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen.  &UR; Charles Robb &LR; , D-Va., an advocate of gay rights, and his
wife, the former  &UR; Lynda Bird Johnson &LR; , stopped by last week at
PlanetOut, a gay media company in San Francisco. Mrs. Robb's
statement of support seemed to refer to her own family history,
including the hotel-room massage her husband received from a beauty
queen that made headlines nine years ago. ``It doesn't matter
whether your partner is the same sex or the opposite sex,'' said
Lynda Bird, ``all of it is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I'm not that book smart. I talk with small words. People &LR; 
 &UR; don't have to use a dictionary. They understand me.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Anna Nicole Smith &LR;  in Us Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
