<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALL-STAND-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE: EXPERIENCE IN SELLING FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Gerard `J.J.' Carelli is a basketball stand operator at Rye
Playland in Rye, N.J.; this was written with Amy Zipkin)  
 By GERARD `J.J.' CARELLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I sell fun. I work six days a week, 10 hours a day,
all summer long.
</P>
<P>
   Park rules are you can't call out, so I lure people by making
eye contact and smiling. They come over to see me. I can tell by
looking at somebody if they are interested. I started 10 years ago,
when I was 15. My first game was setting up milk bottles on the
shelf. It was back-breaking. We didn't get the little kids. We got
the macho guys who weigh a ton and wanted to throw cannons. I got
hit in the head a lot. They think it takes might, but the softer
touch is better.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I moved on to a stock job. I walked around the park for
two years carrying large plastic bags of toys and delivered the
prizes to the different booths. It wasn't much fun.
</P>
<P>
   This is my fourth year at the minibasketball game. Three in a
row for $2 gets you any prize you want. If you miss, you can still
win. I have 14 levels of play. One basket gets you a ball. Two
baskets gets you a Yankees or Mets bear. Three balls wins a framed
picture or rubber Playland ball. Derek Jeter and Britney Spears are
the most popular. I have 22 prizes that change every year. Last
year, Pokemon was big. The year before that it was Tweety in a
cage. My largest prizes, for 14 balls, are Taz, Scooby and
Sylvester stuffed animals and a black inflatable WWF chair. It's
the coolest.
</P>
<P>
   I get about 1,000 players on an average day. Most of them are
teen-agers. It's kids that have the touch. The ratio of kids to
adults that win is about 10 to one. The adults tend to rationalize
it and think how it works.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can get abusive because they feel a lot of pressure
playing this game. I had one customer who kept on playing and
playing because the kid he was with kept telling him what prizes
she wanted. When he didn't win, he started to take it out on me. He
started screaming, ``This game is a rip-off.'' Then he started in
on me. ``No wonder you work in a minimum-wage job.''
</P>
<P>
   I just try to keep my cool when that happens. That's where the
experience comes in. I take a ball and toss it through the hoop. I
don't count it in the scoring, but I tell him, ``Throw the ball up
higher, you get a better chance.''
</P>
<P>
   One day last summer, I had three girls about 15 playing with
their father. One of the balls they were using rolled out into the
midway. A bystander picked it up, and from a distance, aimed it at
one of the baskets. Instead of hitting the basket, he hit the light
up above. The glass from the light shattered and went into the hair
and the eyes of one of the girls. Nothing like that had ever
happened in the booth before. I was frightened, but there was
nothing I could do except call my boss and tell him to get first
aid.
</P>
<P>
   I have my regular customers. I have one older couple that live
in Yonkers, Jean and John. They come about three times a year and
always leave with something big.
</P>
<P>
   I always give free shots. If they're little kids, I let them
stand on the counter for their last shot. If they miss I give them
a smiley face. No kid goes away empty-handed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
