A9327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VISA-ANTITRUST-NYT &LR;      08-22 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISA-MASTERCARD ANTITRUST CASE MOVES CLOSER TO RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   by ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The two-month trial of the government's landmark
antitrust case against Visa and MasterCard limped to the finish
line Tuesday with both sides expressing satisfaction with their
arguments and independent observers reluctant to predict the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of testimony and evidence, the heavily lobbied case
headed toward the day, slated for late October, when it will go to
U.S. District Court Judge Barbara S. Jones for a decision. That
could lead to a restructuring of the giant, highly profitable
industry or, at the other extreme, to what in effect would be a
ratification of current practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have presented strong evidence,'' said assistant
attorney general, Joel I. Klein, in a statement, ``that Visa and
MasterCard engaged in conduct that stifled competition and harmed
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard, for its part, contended: ``The absence of evidence
is glaring. To make matters even worse, its proposed remedies would
likely harm consumers, not help them.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, filed by the Justice Department nearly two years ago
and which went to trial June 12 in the federal courtroom in lower
Manhattan where IBM fought monopoly charges in the 1980s and where
Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were convicted of spying in the 1950s,
centers on two main accusations.
</P>
<P>
   One is that both credit card associations are controlled by the
same group of large banks whose representatives sit on both boards.
The government contends that this dual governance lessens
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The other target is the practice by the associations, which
serve banks that are the actual issuers of credit cards, of
forbidding members to also offer those of rivals like American
Express or Discover, which is owned by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
Visa and MasterCard control about 75 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the evidence showed that if Amex were allowed to
issue its cards through MasterCard and Visa banks, consumers would
be harmed,'' said Noah Hanft, deputy general counsel of MasterCard
in a statement at the end of the trial. ``This is because Amex
would only seek to partner with select banks from these networks,
which would undermine the associations and their ability to
continue offering competitive pricing and advantages to the benefit
of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But after 36 witnesses, 18 on each side, and millions of pages
of documents, impartial observers, including some who called the
government's case unpersuasive, were cautious when asked to predict
how Jones will rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tossup,'' ventured Bradley Ball, an analyst at Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``It's very difficult to assess where she ultimately
will come out,'' he said, pointing to what he said was a
concentration of testimony on whether consumers were being harmed
rather than on the more technical legal questions.
</P>
<P>
   Anita L. Boomstein, a credit card specialist at the law firm of
Hughes, Hubbard &AMP; Reed, declined to predict that Judge Jones would
side with the defendants but said she thought the government's case
was ``weak'' and over reliant on academic theory.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which did not spell out specific remedies it
seeks until mid-trial, wants to require banks that sit on the
MasterCard board to begin issuing only MasterCards and such Visa
board members to issue only Visa cards. This would end dual
governance, which the government has likened to a big shareholder
in Procter &AMP; Gamble sitting on the board of Kimberly-Clark, which
makes similar products.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial's final defense witness Tuesday, professor Robert
Pindyck of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, contended
that this would limit, not enhance, competition between the two
networks as well as among other card issuers and other forms of
payment.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the defendants have said, barring joint
governance would mean that board members could not issue both kinds
of cards, which both parties agree is to be encouraged. And it
would restrict banks' ability to play the two card associations
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Visa is less interested in preserving dual governance than is
MasterCard, however, because as the larger network it would more
likely prevail if issuers were forced to choose a single partner.
Indeed, some testimony has called MasterCard's very survival into
question in this situation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
