<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS &LR;      08-22 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CLARIFIES TAX RELIEF PROPOSALS; DENIES PLANS HARMFUL TO
FEDERAL PROGRAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. _ As he hopscotched across the Midwest in search of
undecided voters, Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush on
Tuesday defended his tax cut proposals by reassuring the public
that he wouldn't decimate existing federal programs or exhaust
projected federal budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he'll have to try harder to explain his tax
relief plans, the Texas governor sought to counter criticisms that
his plan to grant across-the-board income tax breaks and bolster
the Social Security system is potentially harmful to important
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied he was reacting to claims by his Democratic
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, that his plan was too risky. Bush
said he was responding to distortions of his plan's impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do a better job of making it clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under his plan for $1.3 trillion in tax cuts over 10 years, Bush
said, ``we're going to give you some of your own money back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not changing my opinion on it because I think it is the
absolute right thing to do for America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once voters ``buy into the tax relief package even more,'' Bush
predicted, his campaign will capture wide support in several
Midwestern states where the GOP faltered in the last two
presidential elections. That's why he has spent two days this week
stumping in Wisconsin, Iowa, Illinois and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's proposal, the dollar amount of tax relief would
depend on income _ prompting Gore's claim that the rich would
benefit the most. But Bush insists that his goal is to help every
taxpayer. He said a two-income family of four earning $50,000 a
year would get a tax cut worth $2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even some Republicans have raised questions about the plan.
U.S. Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., who warmed up a Peoria airport rally
crowd of 4,000 people, told reporters the Bush plan was ``very
ambitious,'' to the point of being ``problematic.'' He said Bush's
proposal has appeal, but some voters would prefer to see more
surplus funds applied to decreasing the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed cutting $500 billion over the same 10-year
period, closely targeting his reductions for specific areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane ridiculed Bush's effort to step up
his sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The P.R. people who tried to sell the Edsel could only go so
far because at the end of the day, the American people determined
the Edsel was a lemon. George W. Bush is having the same problem in
selling his tax plan,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush emphasized the feasibility of his tax cuts to
reporters, in his public appearances he touted the importance of
reading and education. His visits to a public school in Peoria and
another in the St. Louis suburb of Chesterfield were the 94th and
95th of his campaign. His goal is to top 100 school visits.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to third-graders in Chesterfield's Wild Horse
Elementary School, Bush encouraged the students to forgo television
and pick up books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching TV can be fun sometimes, but it's not as good as
reading because reading is how you learn,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He told educators and parents that he would take $1 billion a
year from the projected surpluses to operate a ``reading
initiative,'' mimicking a Texas program that helps schools pay for
teachers, special training and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is scheduled to be in Austin Wednesday, but returns
to the campaign trail on Thursday in New Orleans and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
