u s BC-OLY-ARBITRATION-NYT &LR;      08-22 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARBITRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE OLYMPICS: ATHLETES ARE TAKING TRIALS FROM ARENAS TO THE
COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most American athletes are preparing for events like
swimming, gymnastics and track and field at the Summer Games next
month in Sydney, Australia, a number of them are preparing for the
burgeoning Olympic sport of arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Code of conduct and grievance procedures that govern American
Olympians allow athletes to take disputes to binding arbitration.
Generally, it is a good idea for athletes to have this avenue
available to seek redress from unnecessarily subjective methods by
which various sports federations choose their Olympic teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the arbitration process appears to have been abused in two
prominent cases. The Greco-Roman wrestler Keith Sieracki and the
cyclist Christine Witty were both named to the American Olympic
team, only to have their selections challenged by other athletes
who did not qualify. However, both Sieracki and Witty say that they
were never notified of the arbitration hearings or given a chance
to defend themselves. Because their rights of due process were
violated, they say, the subsequent rulings against them should be
invalidated.
</P>
<P>
   At the Greco-Roman Olympic trials in June, Sieracki, an Army
sergeant, defeated the four-time national champion Matt Lindland,
2-1, in the deciding third bout of the 167{-pound category.
Lindland filed an immediate protest, saying he had been illegally
tripped. Greco-Roman wrestling prohibits use of the legs to conduct
a maneuver, but incidental contact is allowed. Lindland filed two
protests with the U.S. wrestling federation, the sport's national
governing body, and both were denied.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland then took his case to an arbitrator, who ordered a
rematch. This time, Lindland won, 8-0. Sieracki said, however, that
he thought the rematch was simply part of training for the
Olympics. He filed a counterclaim, saying that the arbitration
ruling should be meaningless because he was not invited to
participate. A second arbitrator ruled in his favor in a
preliminary hearing. The case will continue Wednesday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Equally troubling in the Sieracki case is the idea that a
referee's decision could be grounds for arbitration. Carried to the
extreme, every ball and strike called in a baseball game could be
subjected to review. Imagine the chaos in figure skating, which
combines artistry with sport and carries a great deal of
subjectivity in the judging.
</P>
<P>
   The great attraction of sport is that, unlike in everyday life,
victories and losses are clearly defined. Perhaps the officials
made an error in the Sieracki-Lindland match at the Olympic trials.
People make mistakes. But that should not be grounds for
arbitration. There is no quicker way to kill spectator interest
than to have a game played and the outcome decided a month later by
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three officials were there,'' said Sieracki's lawyer, Lt. Col.
Dan Shaver, referring to the referees at the Olympic trials. ``The
integrity of the officiating has to rely on those three officials.
If not, why not videotape every match and let arbitrators make the
decision?''
</P>
<P>
   Witty, who won silver and bronze medals in speedskating at the
1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, is attempting to become the
fourth person to win medals at both the Winter and Summer Games. In
the Olympic cycling trials in April, she finished second to Tammy
Thomas in the 500-meter time trial. But Witty was named to the
American team instead of Thomas because the U.S. cycling federation
used the criterion of international performance over the past two
years. Witty won the 1998 national championship and finished fourth
at the 1998 world championships in the 500-meter time trial, a
two-lap race against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas protested to an arbitrator, who ordered a ride-off last
Sunday in Frisco, Texas Witty did not show up, and Thomas circled
the track alone. Because she had never been invited to the
arbitration hearing, Witty contended, she was not bound by any
order for a rematch. She has filed her own arbitration case,
scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was never invited to defend herself,'' said Witty's
lawyer, Jeff Benz. ``There was no due process.''
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger, Benz and the cycling federation said, the
arbitrator's ruling did not say that the winner of the rematch
should be placed on the Olympic team. Like Thomas in Sunday's
ride-off, the case continues aimlessly around in circles.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cast members of ``Survivor'' could also determine
the outcome of these Olympic cases in Wednesday night's finale. At
least a couple of anonymous sports would get enormous television
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have athletes deciding the Olympic teams
instead of lawyers,'' said Rich Wanninger, director of
communications for USA Cycling. ``We're going to have to start
including bios of the lawyers in our media guide.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
