<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore-Lieberman visit kicks off the start of rapidly growing
state campaigns
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Already peppering the state with new
campaign ads, the presidential candidates are making live
appearances in South Florida this week beginning with a trip to
Broward County today by Vice President Al Gore and his running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   They will be followed by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who is
scheduled to campaign Thursday and Friday in Miami-Dade County. It
will be the first visit for both campaigns since the national
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman are going to Kings Point, a largely Jewish
and politically active condominium community in Broward County.
Lieberman, a former Connecticut attorney general, has caused a lot
of excitement among South Florida's more than 500,000 Jewish voters
because he is the first Jew on a national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   During the Democratic National Convention, some members of the
Florida delegation cried during Lieberman's speech overcome with
joy at the fact that someone of the Jewish faith could be the next
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   After the event at Kings Point, where the candidates will
discuss plans for tax cuts to help families pay for long-term
health care, Gore and Lieberman will raise money for the Democratic
National Committee at the home of Mitchell Berger, a Fort
Lauderdale attorney. Cost is $10,000 per couple. Then they return
to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrives in Miami on Thursday. He will go to the Coral
Gables home of former Arvida Co. chairman Chuck Cobb where he is
expected to raise more than $1 million. On Friday, Bush will have
an early morning event, topic still to be determined, at Florida
International University.
</P>
<P>
   With each campaign describing Florida as a key battleground
state, the visits this week are just a small part of rapidly
growing Florida campaigns. Both sides are beefing up staff and
increasing their spending on television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began a new ad Tuesday that touches on various aspects of
his life building to a theme that ``Al Gore decided that to change
what was wrong in America, he had to fight for what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has two ads running. One is primarily about education and
Bush's ideas for solving learning problems by focusing on reading
and giving more control and accountability to local schools. The
second ad talks about the nation's ``deficit in values.''
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns are running the ads in key states.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
