<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-INTEL0823-COX     08-22 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel aiming at improving its presence on the World Wide Web
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Maybe the world's biggest semiconductor maker
should change its slogan from Intel Inside to Intel Online.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since IBM Corp. picked Intel Corp. to supply
microprocessors for its first personal computers in 1981, the
company has made its bread and butter _ and billions in profits _
from selling semiconductors to the PC industry.
</P>
<P>
   But with PC sales on the wane, and the World Wide Web on the
rise, Intel is betting its chips on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more obvious than at Intel's annual developers
forum, which runs through Thursday here. Traditionally, the
conference has been the place where Intel gives details about its
latest and greatest PC chips _ past stars have been the 486 and the
Pentium lines.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Intel unveiled its Pentium 4 to a ho-hum audience of
about 5,000. The spotlight at the conference _ where the Intel
slogan ``Powering the net. Connecting the net'' is everywhere _ is
clearly on the company's Internet initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the PC is dead yet _ but our other businesses
are growing faster than our core business,'' said Intel Chief
Executive Craig Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Intel plans to show off new chips for cell phones and handheld
computers and to introduce the latest version of its
Austin-designed StrongARM chips, which are made for Internet-ready
cell phones and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which dominates the PC chip business, finds itself in the
odd position of underdog in the fast-growing business for wireless
Internet semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   Before it began buying its way into the industry two years ago,
Intel's share of the wireless chip business was virtually nil _
something that could make it tough for it to catch up with bigger
players such as Texas Instruments Inc. and Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Although PC chips will remain Intel's core business in the near
future, Barrett said that its wireless and Internet-related chip
business could surpass its PC chip business within five or 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Even the new Pentium 4 is being ballyhooed primarily for its
ability to quickly handle Internet video and pictures, not complex
computing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw that the Net would become much more visual,'' said
Albert Yu, general manager of Intel's chip business.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of the new chip, Yu and an assistant filmed
video and sent it seemingly flawlessly over the Internet, capturing
938 frames in a matter of seconds. A similar demonstration using a
Pentium 3 chip captured only 530 of 940 frames, resulting in jerky,
hard-to-see video.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium 4 is expected to run at speeds of up to 1.4
gigahertz when released later this year, which would let Intel
recapture the title as the world's fastest chip maker from
arch-rival Advanced Micro Devices Inc. Yu also demonstrated a
Pentium 4 that ran at speeds of up to 2 gigahertz, but declined to
say when that chip, which also is being developed with the Internet
in mind, might be available.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Barrett has been touting the wonders of the
Web, but in recent months, the company has seriously stepped up its
efforts. It has been buying, investing in or otherwise doing deals
with companies that do everything from online videoconferencing to
making chipsets and software for wireless Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Through June, Intel had made more acquisitions than any other
company in the electronics industry, according to figures from
merger specialist Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin Inc. And that was
before it went on a real buying binge earlier this month, spending
more than a half-billion dollars to pick up three companies in the
Internet wireless business (see chart). Monday, Intel was part of a
group that invested $9 million into Austin-based Banderacom, which
makes chips for high-speed connections for Internet servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been acquiring companies like crazy,'' said Will
Strauss, whose consulting company, Forward Concepts Inc., follows
the chip business. ``It's pretty clear they want to move into the
wireless market _ and they want to be among the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's metamorphosis makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   After dizzying growth in the 1990s, the growth rate of PC sales
is starting to decline. Meanwhile, sales of wireless goods that
connect to the Internet _ everything from Web-ready telephones to
personal digital assistants _ are booming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the market for wireless chips) is the fastest-growing
segment of the semiconductor business and the only market bigger
than that for PCs,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Intel's minor role in the wireless chip market, its
semiconductor sales grew by about 17 percent during the first half
of this year, compared with Texas Instrument's 26 percent, Motorola
Inc.'s 25 percent and STMicroelectronic's 55 percent, according to
figures from research company IC Insights.
</P>
<P>
   Look for that to change as Intel digests its recent acquisitions
and gets its new products rolling, analysts and company officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year is when we start to see its whole revenue structure
start to change,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel stock closed up 16 cents to $72.13 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Email: bkeefe(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
