<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-640&AMP;A     08-22 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE TIRES' WEIGHT CAPACITY MAY BE INADEQUATE FOR FORD
EXPLORER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Firestone tires that have been failing on Ford
Explorers have fairly low weight-carrying capability for a vehicle
of the Explorer's size, particularly at the low inflation pressure
recommended by Ford Motor, publicly available technical
specifications for the tires and the Explorers show.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone officials have said several times over the
last two weeks that the recalled 15-inch tires are losing their
treads at high speeds partly because drivers are overloading their
vehicles. But this can be easy to do in an Explorer: its
recommended maximum payload for passengers and cargo is 750 to
1,310 pounds, depending on the model. Four people, plus luggage,
can exceed the lower end of that range, particularly if they use
the roof rack and the rear cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer is at least as heavy as any of its main rivals in
the mid-sized sport utility market, and has been several hundred
pounds heavier in some model years, notably 1996, the vintage that
has produced the most crash claims. Yet Ford's rivals typically use
either larger tires or recommend higher tire pressures for their
models.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the size of a tire or its pressure allows it to carry
more weight safely, provided motorists do not exceed the maximum
pressure recommended by the tire maker.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevrolet Blazer, for example, uses the same size tires as
the Explorer. But General Motors recommends that the tires on all
its mid-sized sport utilities be inflated to 35 pounds per square
inch, compared with just 26 for the Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the combined weight-carrying ability of the Blazer
tires is 1,100 pounds greater than the Explorer tires. The
recommended maximum payload for a Blazer is 930 to 1,330 pounds,
which four adults and their luggage are less likely to exceed.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda Passport, Nissan Pathfinder and Mitsubishi Montero
Sport have the same recommended tire pressure as the Explorer. But
the Passport and the Pathfinder use larger tires, allowing them to
carry more weight. The Montero Sport has even smaller tires than
the Explorer, but Mitsubishi recommends that its customers raise
the pressure in the rear tires before carrying heavy loads _ a
recommendation that Ford has not made for the Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has chosen larger tires with higher pressures for its next
generation of Explorers, which will go on sale in January. The new
tires, chosen several years ago, will be able to carry considerably
more weight than the current ones, and will give the new Explorer a
recommended payload of 1,100 to 1,500 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials defend their choice of the recalled tires, saying
they meet tire industry guidelines for carrying weight. Ford also
questions Bridgestone/Firestone's assertion that overloading has
contributed to tire failures in the United States, although the
automaker acknowledges that tires did fail on Explorers overseas
that became overloaded when owners installed third rows of seats
and used the vehicles as shuttle buses.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also contends that with the Explorer or any other truck, it
is the responsibility of owners to check weight labels posted on
the inside of the doors and then limit the weight put inside, with
particular attention to not putting too much weight at the back of
the vehicle. ``It provides you on the label the gross vehicle
weight rating _ you can't load it so that you exceed 3,000 pounds
on the rear axle either,'' said Lee Carr, a vehicle dynamics
engineering consultant on the Explorer and former Ford engineer to
whom Ford referred questions on the Explorer tires.
</P>
<P>
   But safety experts have long questioned how many sport utility
customers think of their vehicles as trucks, much less check the
weight ratings on the label. Carr acknowledged that people who
switched to Explorers from cars might not be accustomed to checking
weight ratings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jon Harmon, a Ford spokesman, said the best evidence for the
adequacy of the current tire size and pressure lay in the
performance of Goodyear tires that were installed on nearly half
the Explorers built in the 1995, 1996 and 1997 model years.
Goodyear has not had any reports of problems with these tires, said
Bill Hopkins, Goodyear's vice president for global product
marketing and technical planning. Harmon said Ford had received
just one report of a tread separation involving a Goodyear tire on
an Explorer, but the incident did not result in any injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials have been consistent in pointing to quality
problems in the Firestone tires, while contending that their design
decisions did not cause the failures. Reluctant to antagonize their
biggest customer, Firestone officials have said little to question
this.
</P>
<P>
   But John Lampe, an executive vice president of
Bridgestone/Firestone, said this evening that concerns about the
tires' ability to carry the Explorer's weight safely had been one
reason for the tire maker's recommendation two weeks ago that
Explorer owners begin inflating their tires to 30 pounds per square
inch. Ford has since said that a range of 26 to 30 pounds is
acceptable to the automaker's engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's decision on Monday to temporarily close two Ford Ranger
pickup factories to make more replacement tires available for
Explorers highlighted the unusual fact that the Ranger and the
Explorer still use the same tires.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer was introduced as a variation of the Ranger in late
1990, and was an immediate best-seller. Over the years, the
Explorer has grown bigger and heavier, because many people use it
as a luxury family car and choose practically every option,
including four-wheel drive even if they plan no off-road driving.
Yet most Explorers still share the tires of a small pickup that
weighs half a ton less.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Ford executives expected only a few customers to
choose four-wheel drive, and were taken by surprise that most
drivers want the option, which adds 220 pounds to the vehicle's
weight. Ford makes the key components for the four-wheel-drive
systems at a factory in Bordeaux, France, that has been so
backlogged that the automaker has maintained a charter fleet of
jets for years just to ferry them to its Explorer assembly plants
in Louisville, Ky., and St. Louis, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice problem to have,'' said Steve Von Foerster, the
chief program engineer for the Explorer. ``People want it so bad
that you have to rent your own fleet of 747's.'' With a profitable
model, airlifting heavy auto parts is cheaper than shutting down
the assembly plant, but an automaker does it only as a last resort,
after greatly underestimating demand for an option.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles need tires that can support considerably more than
their own weight plus the payload because they lean on the tires on
one side when going around curves, and because the weight of cargo
and passengers is seldom evenly distributed.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Ford Explorer weighs 4,000 to 4,400 pounds. Four
15-inch tires of the type and inflation pressure now being recalled
can support a total of 7,012 pounds at a pressure of 26 pounds per
square inch, according to the tire industry's Tire and Rim
Association guidelines. At a pressure of 30 pounds per square inch,
which Firestone now recommends, the tires can support a total of
7,525 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the similarly sized Chevrolet Blazer weighs roughly
4,000 pounds or a little less. It has the same size tires but,
because of a higher inflation pressure, the tires can support a
total of 8,112 pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
