<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     08-22 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ASKS SUPREME COURT TO SEND ANTITRUST CASE TO APPEALS
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. made a final plea Tuesday to the Supreme
Court to send its antitrust case to a federal appeals court for the
``onerous task'' of reviewing the record instead of hearing the
appeal directly.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's plea came in a legal brief that answered a filing
last week by the Justice Department, which urged the Supreme Court
to hear the appeal directly. A fast-track appeal directly to the
top court, the government said, was in the national interest
because waiting for the appeals court to act could ``irreparably
harm competition'' in the computer industry and could result in
justice being ``denied through delay.''
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Tuesday, Microsoft focused on the arguments that
the case is extremely complex and that the trial judge made a
series of factual and procedural errors.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who heard the
lawsuit, ruled earlier this year that Microsoft was a monopoly that
had repeatedly violated the nation's antitrust laws. He ordered
that the company be split in two, an order he later shelved pending
appeals. Microsoft is appealing both Jackson's ruling and his
breakup order.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft clearly plans to ask that Jackson's work be given a
detailed review on appeal _ a task, the company says, that would be
handled best by the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings in this case,'' Microsoft stated, ``are not the
product of even one level of impartial decision-making.'' In its
filing, Microsoft said that Jackson's handling of the trial and his
ordering of a breakup without separate hearings on sanctions ``cast
serious doubt on the reliability'' of his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it is difficult to assess whether the Supreme
Court will hear a direct appeal of the Microsoft case. The court
will decide by the opening of its next session, in October, if not
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the stewardship of William H. Rehnquist, who became chief
justice in 1986, the Supreme Court has been aggressive in limiting
its case load, legal experts say. In the late 1970s and early
1980s, they note, the court routinely decided nearly twice as many
cases as in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Microsoft lawsuit, they add, is an extraordinary case.
The antitrust Expediting Act of 1903, which was amended in 1974,
permits direct appeals to the Supreme Court of antitrust cases
brought by the government. Until the 1974 amendment, such appeals
always went straight to the Supreme Court, but the revision of the
Expediting Law let the court decide whether to take an appeal
directly.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, the government has rarely asked for a direct appeal.
The last time it did so was nearly 18 years ago, when the Supreme
Court agreed to hear two appeals to the AT&AMP;T antitrust ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts point to the ``institutional forces'' in the
Microsoft case that might prod the Supreme Court to take a direct
appeal. The U.S. solicitor general and the Justice Department have
made the request, and Jackson has certified the case for fast-track
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be hard for the court to say no,'' observed Andrew
Gavil, a professor at the Howard University law school.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, however, says that saying no would be the appropriate
choice. Although the company's brief said that ``no one is more
anxious than Microsoft to see this case brought to a prompt
conclusion,'' it went on to explain why it thought its case was
different from the AT&AMP;T case.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T case, Microsoft said, did not involve a review of a
complex factual record _ a sharp contrast, in the company's view,
from what would be required in the appeal of its own case.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing last week, the Justice Department made a spirited
argument for direct appeal. ``The stakes in this case for the
national economy are immense,'' the government said. ``If this case
does not qualify for direct review under the Expediting Act, it is
difficult to imagine what future case would.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft addressed those statements in its reply Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is: a case in which the nature of the issues
presented and the state of the record make it suitable for direct
review by this court,'' the company said. ``AT&AMP;T was such a case;
this case is not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
