<HEADER>
A9339 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     08-22 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR DODGERS TO REBUILD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time has come for the Los Angeles Dodgers to take that
difficult, humbling and controversial step, one that will raise the
hackles of some fans and is always accompanied by a white flag.
</P>
<P>
   Fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   It's come to that point. A dozen reasons can be cited for the
team's malaise, but the statute of limitations on kvetching about
Pedro Martinez, Mike Piazza and the Dodger Blue massacre of 1998 is
about to run out. It's time to move forward, and the reality is
that this team as currently assembled isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   That means retrench, putting the biggest names on the ballclub
in the showcase window -- 2000 MVP candidate Gary Sheffield, lone
wolf pitcher Kevin Brown, longtime Dodger Eric Karros and
first-year Dodger Shawn Green -- and not just the usual suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be tough seeing Sheffield leave, now that he's finally
comfortable in L.A.? Yes, but no tougher than seeing Piazza traded.
Isn't it risky trading a No. 1 pitcher like Brown? Yes, but perhaps
not if one can get three pitchers in return. Would it hurt to see
Karros move on, the last remnant of five straight rookies of the
year? Yes, but we're used to that pain.
</P>
<P>
   These are the toughest kind of decisions, and also the most
controversial. Teams like the Padres, Marlins and White Sox were
scorched by fan and media criticism of their fire sales, but the
reality is that they have all survived and built a new foundation
from the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   What's more enjoyable, watching a team with a $90 million
payroll floundering around .500 and sharing space in baseball's
middle ground with the Marlins (payroll: $19 million), or watching
teams like Oakland ($32 million) and Chicago ($31 million) emerge
as playoff candidates a few years removed from their own fire sale?
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, watching a team crumble from the expectations of
high-priced players with long term contracts, or a team rebuilding
around a nucleus of young players with upside?
</P>
<P>
   There's no guarantee that opponents will step up boldly for any
of the four highest-priced Dodgers. Thanks to the generous Kevin
Malone, three of the four players make more than the going rate for
superstars, and all have multiyear contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But they would draw some interest. And baseball's recent past is
encouraging for those teams willing to take this step.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, for example. No one projected a Mariners division title
or playoff berth without Randy Johnson and Ken Griffey, but the
young players they received in trade -- pitchers Freddy Garcia and
John Halama, outfielder Mike Cameron -- have contributed, and they
used the salary savings to sign free agents Aaron Sele and John
Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   The A's weren't expected to overcome losing Mark McGwire. But
while the three pitchers Oakland obtained haven't contributed
directly, the A's used their pitching depth to make subsequent
deals for Terrance Long and closer Jason Isringhausen. They also
had a plan, what with young players like Dirtbag Jason Giambi, Eric
Chavez, Miguel Tejada, Ben Grieve, Tim Hudson, Ramon Hernandez and
Adam Piatt all maturing at about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox and owner Jerry Reinsdorf were condemned for
trading Roberto Hernandez and Wilson Alvarez to the Giants in 1997
for prospects. But one of those prospects is White Sox closer Keith
Foulke, one of six players obtained in minor trades that have
contributed to the White Sox's A.L. Central lead -- Jon Garland,
Bobby Howry, ex-Dodger Paul Konkero, Sean Lowe, Bill Simas (Angels)
and Chris Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres were roasted for their distress sale in the early
'90s, but they rebounded and made it to the 1998 World Series. Even
the Marlins, who discarded every member of their 1997 World Series
champs -- Charles Johnson, Gary Sheffield, Edgar Renteria, Robb
Nen, Moises Alou, Livan Hernandez, Kevin Brown -- have emerged from
their fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   They're a credible .500 team with a modest $19 million payroll
and good, young pitchers eberywhere, like Ryan Dempster, A.J.
Burnett, Brad Penny, Braden Looper, Jesus Sanchez and several
others waiting in the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, of course, have no farm system, or so CEO Bob Daly
and Malone will tell you. They said Fred Claire and Tommy Lasorda
left the team bare of products, a specious argument considering the
team turned out five rookie of the year winners in the mid-90s. If
the Dodgers are so bare, then why did Malone trade the franchise's
best minor league lefthander, Randy Dorame, in the Tom Goodwin
deal?
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the first products of the Malone regime are
two-to-three years away from contributing, that suggests a target
date of 2003, and I can't imagine fans tolerating two more seasons
of 2000-brand baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So if it's tough decisions that need to be made, giving up ten
games in 2001 to gain 20 by 2002, then so be it. Let the changes
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Shop the Fantastic Four to Boston, Cleveland, St. Louis, Texas
and both New York clubs. Several of those teams could use a
left-fielder like Sheffield. Cleveland and St. Louis would love a
Kevin Brown. Trade at least one of them for a three- or four-player
package of prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Send good guy Todd Hundley where he belongs, to the A.L. where
he can DH, in exchange for a solid prospect. Make whatever deals
necessary to move Devon White, Tom Goodwin, Mark Grudzielanek,
Carlos Perez, Terry Adams, Gregg Olson, Chad Kreuter, Kevin Elster,
Antonio Osuna, Jim Leyritz, F.P. Santangelo and other
Malone-acquired dross on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Keep Jeff Shaw after testing the market. Give the catching job
to Paul LoDuca and/or Angel Pena and shortstop to Alex Cora. Keep
Adrian Beltre. Keep Darren Dreifort and Chan Ho Park, and maybe
even Ismael Valdes because he's too young to quit on. Promote all
of the young pitchers at Albuquerque. And reassign Malone to player
development, where he belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Is this tough? Yes. But no tougher than watching the Dodgers of
2000 stumble around baseball's equator. If a fire sale would help,
then let's break out the matches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
