<HEADLINE>
THE ULTIMATE `SURVIVOR' SURVIVAL GUIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, a little perspective: When ``Survivor'' debuted May 31 on
CBS, the Dallas Stars were still alive in hockey's Stanley Cup
playoffs, ``Mission: Impossible 2'' was the No. 1 movie at the box
office, and Walter Matthau and Sir Alec Guinness were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, time flies when you're vicariously stranded on an island.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night brings the two-hour finale of ``Survivor,''
along with a cast reunion/post-mortem that is likely to give CBS
its biggest ratings bonanza since Hawkeye said goodbye to B.J. in
the closing episode of ``MASH.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, maybe bigger. This has been the show of the summer,
dominating TV and dividing the country into two camps, the fanatics
and people who insist that they'll never watch the show _ but even
the latter group probably has some idea who Kelly, Richard, Rudy
and Susan are.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the show-avoiders will probably break down Wednesday,
their curiosity getting the better of them, and check out what all
the fuss is about. But walking into ``Survivor'' at this juncture
can be like trying to understand the rules of, say, cricket. So,
with both fanatics and newbies in mind, we present the ultimate
``Survivor'' survival guide.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OUR STORY THUS FAR ...
</P>
<P>
   Back in the spring, CBS dumped 16 people on Pulau Tiga, an
island in the South China Sea. They were allowed some material
luxuries _ including, apparently, makeup and razors _ but were
largely stripped of the necessities like, say, a roof, a fridge and
a bed. They had to make their shelters and forage for most of their
food.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 were divided into two tribes of eight, the Tagi
(portrayed as squabbling, back-stabbing, devious) and the Pagong
(friendly, mellow, good-timey). Each week, the tribes were issued
two challenges, often in the form of elaborate, Rube Goldberg-style
games: a reward challenge (for a home comfort) and an immunity
challenge. The tribe that lost the immunity challenge gathered in a
``tribal council'' and voted one of its members off the island.
</P>
<P>
   When the island members dwindled to 10, the tribes were merged
into one and given the Pottery Barn-esque name Rattana. The
challenges became individual events, and immunity ensured that a
contestant survived till the next episode. For example, Kelly, the
22-year-old river guide, has dodged bullets for two consecutive
episodes by winning the immunity challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's episode starts with the Final Four, who face two
more immunity challenges and three more tribal councils. In the
final tribal council, the last two plead their cases to a ``jury,''
made up of the last seven people voted off the island (including
Wednesday's two evictees). The person who makes the most convincing
case wins and snags a million bucks. The rest go home a few pounds
lighter, unless a diet consisting of rice, bugs, rats and manta
rays makes you gain weight. Don't cry too hard for the losers,
though; they get consolation prizes that would pay off most
people's credit-card debts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE FINAL FOUR
</P>
<P>
   KELLY
</P>
<P>
   Full name: Kelly Wiglesworth
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22 (during filming; turned 23 June 24)
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: River guide
</P>
<P>
   Annoying trait: Two-faced _ although you could say that about
almost everyone left, except for Rudy
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Young and athletic
</P>
<P>
   Weakness: Wishy-washy; remaining competitors believe she has
betrayed them
</P>
<P>
   Odd factoid: She can touch her nose with her tongue _ and she's
proud of it!
</P>
<P>
   Survival odds: 10-to-1 against
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD
</P>
<P>
   Full name: Richard Hatch
</P>
<P>
   Age: 39 (celebrated birthday during filming)
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Corporate trainer
</P>
<P>
   Annoying trait: Tendency to walk around naked
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: The very deviousness that makes many viewers hate
him; the best fisher and food-gatherer on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Not many _ which makes him vulnerable to other
competitors, who may vote him off in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Odd factoid: Unintentionally sparked an Internet rumor that he
is really former ``Battlestar Galactica'' star Richard Hatch,
fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Survival odds: Even money.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RUDY
</P>
<P>
   Full name: Rudy Boesch
</P>
<P>
   Age: 72
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Retired Navy SEAL
</P>
<P>
   Annoying trait: Chronic grumpiness, although it's kind of
endearing if you're in the right mood.
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Individualism (despite his participation in an island
``alliance''); thinks the whole thing is bull and just wants the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Age, although he has held out better than previous
over-50 islanders; burns food; thinks the whole thing is bull and
just wants the money.
</P>
<P>
   Odd factoid: A painting of Rudy slathering sunscreen on Richard
went for $530 on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Survival odds: 2-to-1 against.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN
</P>
<P>
   Full name: Susan Hawk
</P>
<P>
   Age: 38 (during filming; turned 39 Thursday)
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Truck driver
</P>
<P>
   Annoying trait: She can't help it, bless her heart, but her
Midwestern accent is so broad, she makes the people in ``Fargo''
sound like the British Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Strengths: Almost as devious as Richard; aside from Rudy, may be
the most macho person left on the show; the second best
hunter-gatherer remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Weaknesses: Grating, back-stabbing personality may have other
contestants gunning for her.
</P>
<P>
   Odd factoid: Has the same name as a Dallas County assistant
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Survival odds: 5-to-1 against.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
ttx-z r abx nt06 nt07 nt26 &QL; 
rabx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-`SURVIVOR'-FINALE-2ndTake-TEX &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: 5-to-1 against. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVE YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few audience-participation tips to get you in the
spirit for Wednesday's ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   What to wear: Women should favor bikinis, tankinis, sarongs,
scarves, occasional gimme caps _ and good running shoes. For men,
the style is much simpler: shorts, T-shirts, tank tops, gimme caps
_ and good running shoes. For men, shirts are optional; if you want
to be like the recently ousted Sean _ although we can't fathom that
_ sport a nipple ring. If you want to emulate Richard, walk around
almost naked _ but retain your black dress socks. Clothes from
Target, one of the show's sponsors, are preferred.
</P>
<P>
   What to eat: Rice, bland seafood. Other items are suggested for
immunity challenges below.
</P>
<P>
   What to drink: Water _ and none of that fancy bottled stuff,
either. We'll accept beer, but only if it's Bud Light, one of the
show's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating tips: Remove all furniture from your TV room and sit
on logs, or stretch out on hammocks. Occasionally throw water on
guests to simulate island storms (it's even better if you do it in
front of a high-speed fan). Tiki torches and mosquito netting are
optional.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGE YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   You can use these games for reward challenges or immunity
challenges. For reward challenges, we suggest that you have
prepared a slice of pizza, a barbecue sandwich, one beer or some
other similar food item that only the winner can eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turn off the air conditioner. Last person to complain about
the heat wins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sit through the Reebok commercials. The last person to laugh
or express shock at the envelope-pushing humor wins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give everyone remote controls programmed for your TV set. The
last person to channel-surf wins. Women have an unfair advantage,
but hey _ life's not fair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drink a full glass of the beverage of your choice during each
commercial break. The last person to use the restroom wins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shoot suction-cup darts at host Jeff Probst when he shows up
onscreen. The person who comes closest wins _ although in a way,
everyone does.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS FOR: Eating a bug or a fried rat. Or watching
someone else do it.
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE-EXTRA POINTS FOR: Correctly guessing the people who will
be kicked off, in order.
</P>
<P>
   POINTS OFF FOR: Walking around naked, having an irritating
voice, being lazy or sporting a nipple ring.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
