<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Acknowledges It Concealed Complaints
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors acknowledged that it had systematically
concealed customer complaints about tens of thousands of defective
automobiles since 1977. The admission by Mitsubishi, Japan's No. 4
automaker, came a month after its top executive had denied
accusations that it had covered up repeated instances of problems
that included faulty fuel tanks, fuel tank caps, clutches,
crankshafts and brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade Stock Rises on Rumors
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, the fifth-largest online brokerage firm, was
contending with a deep slump in its stock price when its new chief
executive, Thomas Lewis, abruptly resigned two weeks ago. Since
then, Ameritrade's stock has been driven up by speculation that the
company will be acquired. That rise accelerated yesterday as shares
climbed $1.13, to $17.06, fueled by a rumor that American Express
might buy Ameritrade.
</P>
<P>
   Management School of Hard Time
</P>
<P>
   Attica prison, home to many of the most violent felons in New
York, may seem like a dangerous place to teach lessons about
effective management. But each month, a group of executives and
inmates share insights and learn about communicating.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Card Antitrust Trial Ends
</P>
<P>
   The two-month trial of the government's landmark antitrust case
against Visa and MasterCard limped to the finish line with both
sides expressing satisfaction with their arguments and few
reluctant to predict the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Fines ETrade $20,000
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities
Dealers announced that ETrade Securities had been fined $20,000
because it failed to file reports adding up the short positions of
its customers for 28 months, from June 1996 through September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Partial Verizon Walkout Continues
</P>
<P>
   Two days after more than 50,000 employees of Verizon
Communications ended a 15-day strike in New York and New England,
representatives for thousands of their colleagues continued to
haggle with the company over details of a contract proposal,
prolonging the walkout in several Eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   An Executive Moves From No to Yo
</P>
<P>
   When Katherine Hudson entered the corporate world at Eastman
Kodak some 30 years ago, she was determined to open for herself
some doors that until that time were tightly shut to women. Now she
is the chief executive of Brady Corp., where ``yo'' _ not ``no'' _
is the company cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Makes Final Plea
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft made a final plea to the Supreme Court to send its
antitrust case first to a federal appeals court for the ``onerous
task'' of reviewing the record instead of hearing the appeal
directly.
</P>
</TEXT>
