<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NIJINSKY-DANCE-$ADV27     08-22 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIJINSKY-DANCE-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL GRASPING FOR NIJINSKY'S ELUSIVE LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANIEL GESMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Just over 50 years after his death
in London, events around the world are reaffirming the apparently
boundless fascination with the dancer and choreographer Vaslav
Nijinsky, whose brief career ended at 29 because of the mental
illness that gripped him the rest of his 61 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In March, a comprehensive Nijinsky exhibition, including his own
drawings and paintings, began touring European museums.
Nijinsky-themed plays ran this past winter and spring in Tokyo,
London and Scottsdale, Ariz., and in May the Royal Ballet performed
``L'Apres-Midi d'un Faune,'' his 1912 debut as a choreographer, and
a controversial re-creation of his 1913 ``Jeux.'' The Nijinsky
season continued on July 2 when the Hamburg Ballet gave the
premiere of John Neumeier's homage, ``Nijinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The mental illness that culminated in a breakdown in 1919 froze
Nijinsky's image in perpetually radiant youth, an
early-20th-century Jim Morrison or Bruce Lee. A virtuoso of
unprecedented caliber, an unabashedly erotic interpreter of
gender-bending roles, a choreographer of revolutionary ballets, a
scandalously open bisexual, a self-styled ``philosopher of
feeling,'' a madman _ Nijinsky left a rich yet enigmatic legacy
that still eludes full understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Nijinsky created his own system of dance notation, which was
finally deciphered in 1984, but he recorded the steps only for
``Faune.'' Before being dropped from the Diaghilev Ballets Russes
repertory, ``Jeux'' and ``Le Sacre du Printemps'' (1913) received
fewer than 10 performances each in Paris and London, and ``Till
Eulenspiegel'' (1916) received just 23 during the 1916-17 United
States tour. Despite numerous imaginative reinterpretations over
the decades, these last three ballets were long presumed lost,
leaving scant evidence for assessing Nijinsky's choreography, which
was largely dismissed until books by Lincoln Kirstein and Richard
Buckle in the 1970s gave it an elevated and, according to some,
inflated stature.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1971, Millicent Hodson, an American student who wanted
the exercise of choreographing ``in the style of'' Nijinsky, began
efforts to reconstruct ``Le Sacre.'' Ten years later she met and
married the British art historian Kenneth Archer, an authority on
the Russian painter and pantheistic philosopher Nicholas Roerich,
whose original costumes and set designs for ``Le Sacre'' he
subsequently recreated. Seven companies have produced the
Hodson-Archer reconstruction of ``Le Sacre,'' starting with the
Joffrey Ballet in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Hodson and Archer mounted their first (and so far only)
reconstruction of ``Till Eulenspiegel'' with the Paris Opera
Ballet, and in 1996 they presented a ``reconstruction after''
Nijinsky's ``Jeux'' with the Opera Ballet of Verona in Italy. But
their efforts had never been seen in England before the Royal
Ballet's staging in May of ``Jeux,'' alongside ``Faune,''
Bronislava Nijinska's 1924 ``Les Biches'' and Michel Fokine's 1910
``Firebird.''
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with this ``Diaghilev Legacy'' program, a reworking
of David Pownall's play ``Nijinsky: Death of a Faun'' was presented
at the Royal Opera House's Linbury Studio Theater. It starred the
dancer Nicholas Johnson, who commissioned the one-man drama and was
its original interpreter in 1991 and previously performed many of
Nijinsky's roles with the Royal and English National Ballets. He
also danced Nijinsky's ``soul'' in the 1975 BBC Omnibus documentary
``God of the Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nijinsky's journal, a quasi-mystical and undeniably disturbed
document written on the eve of his 1919 breakdown, said that
``Jeux'' was a veiled portrayal of Diaghilev's fantasy of a gay
threesome. But a nocturnal tennis match at Lady Ottoline Morrell's
London home in July 1912 also purportedly inspired the
``poeme-danse,'' the first ballet to treat contemporary life and
bisexuality and to resolve a love triangle as a menage a trois. His
imagistic scenario of a three-way courtship, drawing on
Bloomsbury's libertine manners and mores, also marked the first
time a choreographer had commissioned a score; Claude Debussy's
18-minute masterpiece was only recognized as such decades later.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jeux,'' a lost ball draws a man and two women from an
offstage tennis court into a secluded garden, where shifting games
of jealousy and desire are played out in ambiguous couplings and
triplings. The figures were possibly based on the painter Duncan
Grant and the Stephens sisters, the novelist Virginia Woolf and the
painter Vanessa Bell, who would later vie for Grant's attentions.
Another source may have been Nijinsky's three-way tennis games in
1908 with his sister, Bronislava, and his early lover, Prince Lvov.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary reviews did not disparage Nijinsky's morals, but
attacked instead his cinematically abrupt choreography with its
pioneering neoclassical juxtapositions of sportive movement,
Edwardian walks, conversational gestures, mothlike arm flapping and
period social dances like the waltz, tango and turkey trot. In the
end, the riotous scandal of ``Le Sacre,'' whose hotly anticipated
premiere followed two weeks later, overshadowed the more subtle and
sophisticated ``Jeux,'' which was later labeled Nijinsky's most
modest work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven years after the fact, how much credence should we
give a ballet reassembled from fragmentary evidence?
</P>
<P>
   Like other arts, choreography is exactingly detailed and
precise, but the methods of recording and reconstructing it remain
controversial and poorly understood. Critical assessments of the
Nijinsky restorations, typically focusing on the choreographic more
than the design aspects, often trip on these issues.
</P>
<P>
   This was certainly the case with the reviews in Britain, which,
unlike the more positive 1996 Verona notices, underplayed the
psychological incision and striking modernity of the revived
``Jeux'' in favor of superficial dismissals of its viability or
desirability. Some observers appreciate the Hodson-Archer
reconstructions as impressionistic interpretations, despite
questioning their authenticity; Judith Mackrell of The Guardian and
Jann Parry of The Observer were among those who applauded a
``Jeux'' that may be only partly genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I don't care if it wasn't 100 percent Nijinsky,''
said the Royal Ballet soloist and choreographer William Tuckett,
who set his own second ballet to Debussy's ``Jeux.'' ``This was not
a dryly intellectual or self-aggrandizing exercise. The
reconstructors were dedicated and meticulous in their research and
analysis but used feeling and intuition, too. They created
something genuine and valid in the spirit of the original. It was
completely fresh and stood absolutely in its own right, defying
historical categorization.''
</P>
<P>
   Using all available evidence _ in this case period photographs;
drawings by Leon Bakst, who designed the sets, and contemporary
artists; the Debussy piano score with Nijinsky's libretto notes;
accounts in the news media and memoirs, and conversations with
relatives and proteges of original participants _ the two ``ballet
archaeologists'' fix steps and positions to musical passages where
they can. To bridge gaps in the trail of evidence, Hodson uses the
logic of dance technique, her scholar's knowledge of the
choreographer's stylistic proclivities, exhaustive experimentation
and old-fashioned intuition.
</P>
<P>
   She carefully calls this process intervention as opposed to
invention, while stressing the need to breathe living stage appeal
into what might otherwise be museum pieces. The drawings she makes
(she is also a visual artist) to aid the reconstruction process
have been widely published and exhibited, most recently in May at
Gallery K in London. Hodson and Archer also assemble dossiers of
reading and visual materials to help the creative team _ for
``Jeux,'' the Royal Ballet principals Bruce Sansom and Deborah Bull
and the soloist Gillian Revie _ soak up the social and cultural
atmosphere of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nijinsky's time is on display in the exhibition ``Nijinsky:
Legend and Modernist,'' which is intended to demythologize him and
clarify his career. It is a collaboration between the Dansmuseet in
Stockholm, where it was on view this spring, and the Musee d'Orsay
in Paris, where it will be shown from Oct. 23 to Feb. 18. Two
Nijinsky documentaries will have their premieres during the Paris
show.
</P>
<P>
   Nijinsky inspired more artistic interpretations than any other
dancer, and the exhibition showcases examples of these from public
and private collections, along with memorabilia and previously
unknown works. Also on display are many of Nijinsky's haunting,
circle-based drawings and paintings, made by the hundreds between
1916 and 1919 and resembling nonobjective Russian art of the same
period. The catalog essays, and the exhibition as a whole, argue
that Nijinsky's enigmatic diary and visual works, previously
dismissed as pathological, should be regarded as important
continuations of his modernist creativity once circumstances
separated him from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Neumeier, the artistic director of the Hamburg Ballet, has had a
longtime enchantment with Nijinsky. He began gathering the
memorabilia collection that forms the centerpiece of ``Nijinsky:
Legend and Modernist'' in 1975. A version of the exhibit opened at
Hamburg's Museum fur Kunst und Gewerbe on July 2, the same day the
Hamburg Ballet presented the premiere of Neumeier's ``Nijinsky.''
The homage begins with Nijinsky's last performance, set on a
meticulous re-creation of the actual recital hall, which was
recently torn out of the Suvretta Hotel in St. Moritz, Switzerland.
Characters from the dancer's life on and off the stage then
interact in a free-association of time, space and identity
comparable in form to his diary.
</P>
<P>
   Neumeier presents a Nijinsky gala every year, and the 25th was
given on July 16 with the Royal Ballet's ``Jeux'' cast as invited
performers. The Hamburg run of the Nijinsky exhibition ends
September 2.
</P>
<P>
   Two new plays and two forthcoming films signal that the
fascination with Nijinsky will not subside anytime soon. In
February, William Luce's ``Nijinsky,'' featuring leading Japanese
actors and the Tokyo Ballet principal Yasuyuki Shuto, had a
critically acclaimed, sold-out three-week run at the Parco Theater
in Tokyo, where it will return next year. An English translation
and European productions are planned for the play, which has
choreography by Gary Chryst.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-June at Arizona State University's Kerr Cultural Center
in Scottsdale, Kinga Nijinsky-Gaspers played her grandmother Romola
in Terry Earp's ``Madame Nijinsky _ Married to a God.'' Earp, the
wife of Wyatt Earp's great-grandnephew, based the one-woman play on
family recollections and Romola Nijinsky's books and letters. It
runs in Phoenix through Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   In film, the Australian director Paul Cox (``Vincent'') has in
production an abstract, 85-minute homage to Nijinsky featuring Sir
Derek Jacobi narrating pasages from the dancer's diary. The
American screenwriter Eva Burch's independent film, tentatively
titled ``Nijinsky's War,'' is scheduled to begin production next
year.
</P>
<P>
   For all the ferment, the direct record of Nijinsky's artistry
consists solely of black-and-white photographs, made with leading
photographers and aglow with an otherworldly quality. No film of
him performing is known to exist, but an intriguing concurrence of
anecdote, rumor and circumstance suggests that footage may someday
be found. Perhaps only then can Nijinsky's overpowering myth be
grounded in reality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
