u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-ART     08-22 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MILITARY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN WALKS FINE LINE IN DEBATE OVER MILITARY READINESS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ever since President Clinton appointed William
Cohen secretary of defense in 1996, Cohen, the only Republican in
the cabinet, has claimed to represent the bipartisanship needed to
manage matters of national security.
</P>
<P>
   Now he finds himself _ by all accounts reluctantly _ at the
center of a highly partisan debate over the state of the American
military. And it has left him in a highly unusual position:
defending the administration while at least indirectly underscoring
some of the Republican criticisms leveled against it.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cohen, who represented Maine in the Senate, launched
what amounted to a preemptive strike against criticisms by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas that the Clinton administration was
responsible for a weakened, over-extended military.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen noted not only the budget increases approved by Clinton,
including the biggest pay increases for service members in a
generation, but also the fact, rarely mentioned by the Bush
campaign, that defense budgets started falling rapidly as the Cold
War ended _ when another Bush was president and the governor's
running mate, Dick Cheney, was secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts that followed, Cohen went on to say, reflected a strong
bipartisan demand for a ``peace dividend'' since the United States
no longer faced a threat from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``My constituents from Maine were demanding it, as were people
around the country,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at the annual convention of the Veterans of Foreign
Wars in Milwaukee on Monday, only hours before the governor, Cohen
offered a rebuttal _ of a sort _ to the criticisms that Bush has
repeated throughout his presidential campaign and accentuated since
the Republican convention three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Bush by name _ or for that matter Clinton or
Vice President Al Gore _ Cohen launched a lengthy, detailed defense
of the nation's armed services, arguing that they remained strong
and ready and had proved it during last year's war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Cohen left open the need for
improvement, suggesting that more work, and money, was needed to
meet the pressures on an ever busier military engaged in operations
from the Persian Gulf to the Balkans _ something Bush said he
intended to rethink, if elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can always do better,'' Cohen told the audience, ``and
national security is certainly a subject matter that is open to
debate and improvement. Hopefully that will be the case whatever
administration comes in next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the same audience Tuesday, Gore made that point
in a more overt, more partisan, more full-throated way. Gore went
so far as to say that Bush's repeated attacks on the state of the
military ``for political advantage'' threatened to undercut
American credibility in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not only wrong in fact _ it's the wrong message to send
to our allies and adversaries across the world,'' Gore said,
thrusting defense issues to center stage of the presidential
campaign for a second day.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's remarks, by contrast, have been more subtle _ and more
conflicted.
</P>
<P>
   While his remarks defending the armed services have sought to
counter some of Bush's criticisms, they have also highlighted
shortcomings in spending and readiness that have long been the
subject of complaints from Republicans in Congress and even some
uniformed leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As a Republican surrounded by Democrats, Cohen has always been
an oddity in Clinton's cabinet. He caused a minor stir when he told
Barbara Walters in April that he and his wife, Janet Langhart
Cohen, a Democrat, would ``in all probability'' vote for different
candidates. He later said, ``I indeed did not surrender my
Republican credentials when I agreed to serve in the
administration.'' Now he just declines to say whom he plans to vote
for.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he accepted Clinton's offer to be defense secretary,
Cohen had a reputation as an independent willing to cross party
lines to build consensus, particularly when it came to defense.
Aides in the Pentagon said he took seriously the president's
gesture of choosing a Republican, hoping to renew a bipartisan
spirit with his colleagues who control the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen himself once said in an interview that he had never sat
through a purely political meeting with Clinton and his advisers;
the discussions had always been on the substance of the issues. The
political discussions, presumably, began after he left the room.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's success as a bridge to the Republicans has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Working with the Joint Chiefs of Staff two years ago, he
persuaded the administration to agree to a $112 billion increase in
defense spending over six years. He has also been the leading
administration advocate for building a limited national missile
defense.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he has failed to win over Republicans in many
areas, like closing more military bases, and Republican criticisms
of Clinton's defense policies have only intensified in Cohen's
years as secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Cohen invited Bush to the Pentagon for a briefing on the
state of the nation's strategic nuclear arsenal after Bush pledged
to reduce the number of American nuclear warheads. The invitation
was curtly rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   However proud Cohen is of his accomplishments at the Pentagon,
he is clearly reluctant to weigh in on the political debate over
them now that the campaign is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   He winced when asked at a news conference at the Pentagon last
Friday to respond to Bush's criticism that morale in the ranks was
low. When reporters cornered him on Monday to ask about Bush's
remarks, he began by saying, ``Well, I want to keep my comments
strictly on the facts and the record and to stay out of the
politics as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House official insisted that no one had asked Cohen to
respond to Bush's criticisms, although Cohen's remarks clearly had
the criticisms in mind. ``When we think of somebody who can speak
for the vice president or the Democratic Party on military issues,
Bill Cohen is not the first name that pops in our head,'' one Gore
aide said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Gore's campaign aides sought a defense expert to
brief reporters on the issues the vice president raised Tuesday,
they had to reach back to Cohen's predecessor as secretary of
defense, William J. Perry.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was added to the list of Tuesday's VFW convention speakers
relatively late, defense officials said, and only because his wife
was receiving an award from the veterans. ``I am not here as a
Republican,'' Cohen himself said on Monday. ``I am not here on
behalf of the Democratic administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's posture reflects the fine line walked by men and women
in uniform, who are prohibited by law and by policy from
participating in overtly political events and thus carefully couch
any discussion of political points as strictly factual.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cohen's defense of the armed forces _ from noting the
increase in weapons procurement and to highlighting pay raises that
officials said have led to rising re-enlistment rates _ are seen by
some as an effective counter to Republican critiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't assail Cohen,'' one person in Gore's campaign said.
``He's a great surrogate for us. No one can accuse him of
politicizing the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   But that has a double-edge.
</P>
<P>
   When Cohen says that more can be done _ and spent _ it supports
arguments made by Bush's supporters. The same thing happened when
the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry H. Shelton,
rebutted Bush's assertion during his presidential acceptance speech
in Philadelphia that two of the Army's 10 divisions were not ready
to fight a major war.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said that was not true, then pointed out that Clinton's
approval of a $112 billion budget increase fell far short of the
$148 billion the chiefs had said they needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
