u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-22 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE STRIKE CONTINUES IN SIX EASTERN STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after more than 50,000 employees of Verizon
Communications ended a 15-day strike in New York and New England,
representatives for thousands of their colleagues continued to
haggle Tuesday with the company over details of a contract
proposal, prolonging the walkout in six Eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for Verizon employees in New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia and Washington, D.C.,
discussed details _ like limits on mandatory overtime and the
definition of certain jobs _ with officials of the company, which
was formed by Bell Atlantic's acquisition of the GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the strike has dragged on in this region
is the structure of the union. Most of the employees who returned
to work Monday are in the territory of the former Nynex, which Bell
Atlantic acquired in 1997, while the employees in the six-state
region stretching from New Jersey to Virginia are in Bell
Atlantic's original territory.
</P>
<P>
   In these states, customer service representatives have greater
representation in union locals, and one of the main concerns of
these employees heading into the strike was the large amount of
mandatory overtime. So while union negotiators from New York and
New England were pleased for the most part when Verizon agreed to
limit mandatory overtime to eight hours a week, negotiators in
these other states have pushed for an even lower amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply trying to arrive at the best possible
agreement,'' said Candice Johnson, a spokeswoman for the
Communications Workers of America, the union to which who have not
returned to work belong.
</P>
<P>
   About 14,000 members of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, the other union that was on strike, are mainly
in New England, while the bargaining unit for about 40,000
Communications Workers is rooted mainly in New York and New
England. The union put the number of remaining strikers at about
40,000, while Verizon said the number is closer to 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the strike's protracted conclusion is the
priorities set by regional union leaders, like the definition of
cable splicers' jobs in Pennsylvania, which is where Vincent
Maisano, the lead negotiator for the remaining unit, is from.
Maisano has apparently made this issue and other details of the
proposed contract crucial, people close to the talks said. Maisano
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of support for Maisano and his fellow negotiators, the
union's national office in Washington asked union members in New
York to respect the picket lines formed by striking employees sent
there to put pressure on Verizon. But it appeared that most union
members in the region had returned to work as picket lines thinned
in New York, New Jersey and other states.
</P>
<P>
   As it tried to resolve the remaining issues in the strike,
Verizon, the nation's largest local and mobile telephone company,
also worked to complete orders for repairs and new service that
swelled during the strike. The company had about 73,000 outstanding
repairs and 200,000 orders for new service to fill as of Tuesday,
said Eric Rabe, Verizon's spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
