<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-22 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Chancellor master at button pushing
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Here come Van Chancellor's Comets, poor souls. They
don't stand a chance. Give the WNBA trophy to the New York Liberty
right now. Start engraving the names of the new champions. Gather
up confetti and ticker tape and get ready for the parade.
</P>
<P>
   It's all over but the crying. But of course, these are all
crocodile tears we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets are neither underdogs nor overrated on the way to
their fourth crown, but why let details get in the way of a good
sound bite and a bit of motivation? This is a three-time
championship team that looks more than capable of winning a fourth,
even with a couple of ring fingers tied behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Having swiftly dispatched the one team that seemed capable of
beating them _ the Los Angeles Sparks _ to win the conference
title, the Comets are playing their best basketball at the best
time. Superb efforts from point guard Janeth Arcain and inside
force Tammy Jackson have come at the right time. The Big Three _
Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia Cooper and Tina Thompson _ have been huge.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it won't be a walk in the park against the Liberty
when the Comets open the WNBA Finals on Thursday night, because it
never is when a title is on the line. But neither will it be the
doomed midnight walk through Central Park _ thugs and muggers at
every turn _ that Chancellor makes it out to be.
</P>
<P>
   But such has been Chancellor's way throughout the 2000 season,
sometimes even with good reason. The Comets had to begin the year
with a new point guard and a new center _ only the two most
important players on the floor for most teams. It was the perfect
opportunity for others to dismiss their chances and for Chancellor
to find a rallying cry: We're the underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were considered champions in waiting. The Sacramento
Monarchs were considered huge threats to the Comets' reign.
</P>
<P>
   It's just what Chancellor wanted, much like this series against
the Liberty, which the Comets have defeated two times for the title
but against whom they've lost once this season.
</P>
<P>
   No opponent serves as better material for Chancellor to hem, haw
and poor-us his way to the crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, (the Liberty) have a big advantage over us,''
he said Tuesday. ``They think they can beat us. We've kept them
from getting the rings, and they know that. It's going to be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, whatever works.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because Chancellor spent 19 years trying to win
Southeastern Conference championships at Mississippi while in the
same league as the dominant Tennessee Lady Vols. He's had practice
playing the role of underdog, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   But knowing what to say and when to say it has proved to be
Chancellor's greatest talent as a coach. Without Chancellor's
confidence-building and stroking, would Cynthia Cooper have become
the league's Most Valuable Player in 1997 and 1998?
</P>
<P>
   Rave all you want about Cooper's great talent, which is
undeniable. But when Coop began playing the game under Chancellor,
she was not destined for the Basketball Hall of Fame. Now, she is.
</P>
<P>
   And without Chancellor's handling of tragedy and heartbreak a
year ago, would the Comets have won the WNBA championship in the
wake of Kim Perrot's succumbing to cancer?
</P>
<P>
   He realizes when to be fiery, when to be compassionate, and when
calm waters need to be boiled into motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Through much of this season when the scepter of team leader was
being passed from Cooper to Swoopes, Chancellor handled the
transition and all the tensions that went with it directly and
honestly. Cooper and Swoopes' feelings for one another, or lack
thereof, could have dismantled hopes. But the drawling amateur
psychologist kept it all together.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Comets are getting along as well as ever, the
challenge has been finding a fire that could sweep Chancellor's
team through the playoffs yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Done. He spent much of Tuesday's post-practice media session
outlining all the things stacked against the Comets in this title
series, but he was talking as much to his players as reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The long trip by commercial airline: ``Man, that's just tough on
you. It takes seven hours to get there by the time you're through
traveling. It's exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   The first game being on the road: ``It makes (the Liberty) a
whole lot better. There's 15,000 people, 19,000 people it gets
their adrenaline flowing. I'm telling you, they're going to think
they're just a better team than us.''
</P>
<P>
   The officiating: ``(New York's) rebounding is what worries me
most. In a series like this, the longer you play, the less they
call.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Chancellor talk, you would think the Comets have to come
up with some kind of spectacular effort if they're going to again
wear the rings. But don't worry; they should. He always seems to
know which buttons to push.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
