<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ART-415&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      08-22 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFENSIVE BUSH INSISTS HIS TAX-CUT PLAN IS SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas aggressively defended
his sweeping tax-cut proposal Tuesday, saying it was both
responsible and easily affordable in light of federal surplus
projections. Bush produced an assortment of figures to show that
the plan would not require cuts in government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do a better job of making it clear,'' Bush told
reporters in a surprising admission aboard his campaign plane. The
remark came just one day after Vice President Al Gore, suddenly
resurgent in the polls, held an extensive discussion of his own
suggested tax cuts, which are less than half the size of the ones
proposed by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed to projections by the Congressional Budget Office
that the federal government would run a surplus of about $4.6
trillion over the next 10 years, a figure that includes the Social
Security surplus. He said voters needed to know that the projection
represented money left over even after an expected growth in
government spending of about $3.3 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that after setting aside the Social Security
surplus to shore up that program for the future, he would have
roughly $2.3 trillion for tax cuts, new spending and debt
reduction. Bush's proposed tax cut would cost $1.3 trillion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as voters understand that, he said, ``People will buy
into the tax-relief package even more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not changing my opinion on it,'' he added, a defiant
declaration that, like the rest of his comments to reporters about
the surplus and tax cuts, was largely unprompted. ``It's the
absolute right thing to do for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's uncharacteristic decision to revisit calculations that
his campaign had previously outlined seemed to be an
acknowledgement of a potentially troubling political reality for
him. Many polls show that American voters by and large are not
hankering for an enormous tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore, who has proposed only about $500 billion in tax cuts
over the next decade, has been hammering Bush on the issue,
repeatedly claiming that Bush's plan unnecessarily coddles wealthy
Americans at the expense of fiscal prudence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said on Monday that Bush's tax cut would plunge the country
into deficits, and Tuesday, in a speech to veterans in Milwaukee,
the vice president added that it would ``wreck our good economy and
make it impossible to modernize our armed forces and keep them
ready for battle.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The burden on Bush to convince voters that his tax cut is
affordable was clear not only in his own remarks today but also in
those of Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., who fielded questions from
several reporters after a Bush rally in Peoria, Ill. LaHood had
introduced Bush at the event, a campaign stop that the governor
made on his way from Des Moines, Iowa, to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood said that while ``there's some appetite'' among voters
for Bush's suggested tax cuts, ``I think he should also be talking
about, `I want to be able to pay down the debt, too.' I think that
is problematic for people.''
</P>
<P>
   When LaHood was asked if Bush's proposed tax cut was too large,
both politically and practically, he said merely that it was ``an
ambitious proposal'' and that ``Congress will have some say about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's very ambitious, there's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the 14-month course of his campaign, Bush has said
repeatedly that he is committed to paying down the federal debt,
but more often, when he talks about tax cuts, he simply tells
people that he wants to return their hard-earned dollars to them.
It is a pledge that predictably draws roars of approval from his
Republican base.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the numbers that Bush and his aides used today for
surplus and growth projections had been rounded off, they were
essentially valid, in line with estimates from the Congressional
Budget Office, and some economists and political analysts consider
Bush's tax cut to be reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   But others note, among other criticisms of his plan, that if he
succeeded in enacting the tax cut, it would be extremely difficult
to take it back and raise taxes in the event that the projected
surpluses did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers, for their part, say that Gore is the
candidate who is potentially endangering the economy by outlining
significantly more new spending than Bush has.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, they cited a report released recently by the National
Taxpayers Union, a conservative group, that estimated that Gore's
spending programs over the next 10 years would exceed the surplus,
at least if Gore did not touch the portion of that surplus
generated by Social Security taxes, as both he and Bush have
promised.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign's concern about charges that the
governor's tax cut is too large was evident both today and on
Monday in the aggressiveness of their responses to criticism by
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Karen P. Hughes, the communications director for the Bush
campaign, said that Gore had gone ``completely overboard'' and
grossly distorted the substance and effect of Bush's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes added that the vice president was ``trying to muddy the
waters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want the American people to know how much money's
available,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that while Bush was calling for tax cuts for
Americans at every income level, Gore's plan, targeted more
specifically at less affluent Americans, would leave 50 percent of
taxpayers, totaling 50 million people, without any tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan would reduce federal tax rates across the income
spectrum, lowering the highest rate to 33 percent from 39.6 percent
and the lowest rate to 10 percent from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth between the Bush and Gore campaigns about tax
cuts, spending and fiscal responsibility reflected a larger aim:
each candidate wants to be seen as the better, more prudent steward
of the economy, an issue forever at the top of many voters'
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers have long reveled in how well Bush did in polls
that asked voters which candidate they trusted more on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the recent surveys that showed Gore getting an
enormous _ and possibly temporary _ bounce out of the Democratic
National Convention also indicated that voters had at least
temporarily reassessed his ability to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released on Sunday, 50 percent of
adults surveyed said that Gore would better handle the economy,
while 40 percent said Bush would. Before either party's convention,
a poll by the same organizations showed Bush with a 47 percent to
40 percent lead on the issue. The margin of sampling error was four
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of which candidate would better handle the
federal surplus, Gore led Bush by 48 percent to 41 percent in the
recent poll. In the one before the conventions, Gore trailed Bush,
38 percent to 49 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
