u a BC-MIAMI-STILTSVILLE-NYT     08-22 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-STILTSVILLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPRIEVE OF SORTS FOR LAST 7 OF MIAMI'S FAMOUS STILTSVILLE
HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ On a clear, hot day, with the sunlight
glittering off the water, the houses of Stiltsville seem to float
on a liquid horizon. A cluster of seven ramshackle houses built on
weathered pilings, the structures dot the shallow waters of
Biscayne Bay like shipwrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Cursed by environmental advocates, praised by others as a symbol
of a dying, free-spirited way of life, they have endured 70 years
of mildew, rot and hurricanes, and assaults by federal parks
officials who want them torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the beginning of the end of Stiltsville, just inside
Biscayne National Park, seems finally here.
</P>
<P>
   The occupants of the weather-beaten wooden structures, weekend
renters who use them mostly for parties and getaways, are being
evicted, federal parks officials said. The renters, some who have
been coming to the old houses for decades, have until Dec. 1 to
move out.
</P>
<P>
   The structures themselves will not be torn down but will be
opened to the public, perhaps as environmental education
facilities. But it is only a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   The houses would not be rebuilt if substantially damaged by
weather, said Linda Canzanelli, superintendent of Biscayne National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   That, say the people who want to keep them in the bay, means it
is only a matter of time until a storm wipes them from the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels awful,'' said Gail Baldwin, an architect who has had
a house in Stiltsville since the early 1970s. ``I feel sad for me
and very sad for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The houses are woven into the skyline and lore of Miami, a
romantic symbol of the region's waterfront culture _ and its
weirdness _ since the 1930s, when Eddie Walker, a local fisherman,
turned a barge grounded in the shallows into a one-story home.
</P>
<P>
   Other houses followed, and the community became a getaway for
the affluent. It has appeared in television shows including the
``Miami Vice'' series of the 1980s. Carl Hiaasen, a novelist and
columnist at The Miami Herald, used the house as a backdrop for one
of his popular novels, ``Skin Tight.'' In that book, the hero stabs
a man to death with the bill of a fish he had mounted on the wall
of his Stiltsville house.
</P>
<P>
   Once, there were as many as 25 houses, but fires (all the houses
were wood) and storms whittled their number to the remaining seven.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials have long regarded the houses as a nuisance. When
the section of Biscayne Bay containing Stiltsville became a
national park in 1968, homeowners signed long-term leases, some of
which have changed hands many times.
</P>
<P>
   Canzanelli said the decision to remove the renters but not the
houses was a compromise in the dispute between park officials and
the renters, who wanted the houses left alone.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a case of the federal government running longtime
homeowners who have nowhere else to go off the water but an
eviction of people who use the structures to tie up their boats,
watch the sunsets and lie under the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Their use of the houses contributes to the fouling of the
shallow water, and endangers a fragile ecosystem coral and
seagrass, environmentalists have argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lease is up,'' Canzanelli said. ``They don't own the
structures and they never owned the structures. There was always an
intention that, at the end of this lease, these structures would be
removed. We've gone an extra step to keep them for public use.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who lease the houses say it is just a ploy to prevent them
from keeping up the structures, which require regular maintenance,
and one that dooms the houses to destruction after the first strong
wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they eventually see the National Park without
Stiltsville,'' said Baldwin. ``My feeling is the whole thing is a
ruse to put the houses on hold, and get us out of there, They're
just going to let them deteriorate to the point that they're
unsafe, and then they'll have to tear them down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canzanelli said the park service must maintain the houses to
keep them safe for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have made the offer if there wasn't serious
interest in protecting the structures for public use,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
