<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-KOOP0823-COX     08-22 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOOP0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing drkoop.com gets $20 million cash infusion
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN - Ailing Internet company drkoop.com Inc. has negotiated
a $20 million cash infusion from venture capitalists that will keep
it alive for perhaps another year but comes at a steep price.
</P>
<P>
   The investors have replaced the founders with a new management
team, will control the board of directors and could eventually hold
nearly three-fourths of the stock. They inherit a battered health
information site that last week attracted 680,000 visitors but
whose name is now associated with the this year's tech stock swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, who gave his name
to the company but never took an active management role, will
remain chairman of the board. Founder Donald Hackett, who owns 20
percent of the stock, stays on the board but is out as chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The new team will be headed by venture capitalist Richard
Rosenblatt, 31, who becomes CEO and a board member. The new
investors will be able to appoint up to four new directors.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt's firm, Prime Ventures of Santa Monica, Calif.,
invested $3.5 million in drkoop.com, with the balance coming from
other firms, including J.F. Shea Ventures, Cramer-Rosenthal-McGlynn
Inc. and RMC Capital. Drkoop.com said the investment could rise to
$27.5 million if all options are exercised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Koop and I are extremely pleased to have recruited in
top-notch Internet talent to lead the company in its next phase,''
Hackett said Tuesday. ``We're just real happy that the expenses
have been reduced substantially and the cash infusion really will
provide a significant momentum for the business to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Prime Ventures executives are also taking top
positions: Edward Cespedes, 34, president, and Stephen Plutsky, 31,
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hackett nor Prime Ventures would comment on the
company's direction. The company didn't say what will happen to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million should solve drkoop.com's most pressing need,
though. On Monday, the company said it had run through the cash it
had left at the end of June and had tapped a line of credit for
$400,000 more last week.
</P>
<P>
   The company is spending between $1.5 million and $2 million a
month, meaning the new investment could last between 10 and 13
months.
</P>
<P>
   But significant challenges remain, including reviving a stock
that has flat-lined around $1 a share, defending against a raft of
shareholder lawsuits and an inquiry by the Securities and Exchange
Commission, and redirecting its strategy to reflect the new demands
of the stock market. Simply put, investors have put Internet
companies that rely on advertising on the critical list.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a new corporate strategy,'' said Eric Brown, an
e-health analyst for Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``To
just to take the same goal of (providing) health content to
consumers online . . . isn't going to work any better this time
than it worked the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the company should look for opportunities to merge
its health content with other Internet health care ventures, such
as new sites that allow consumers to shop for health plans and
health care a la carte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this happened early enough that people aren't
completely distrustful of the content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock market has been unfriendly to e-health companies
recently. Shares in Healtheon/WebMD Corp., the biggest and
best-funded Internet health venture, are trading at a fraction of
their 52-week high and the company has begun layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Any new strategy could also involve cutting expenses. Last week,
Austin's mall.com Inc. received an infusion from a new venture fund
dedicated to rescuing troubled Internet companies, and immediately
cut half of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt started Prime Ventures after selling iMall, an
e-commerce services business, to Excite(at)Home for stock worth
$565 million.
</P>
<P>
   In just 10 months, Prime Ventures has invested in about 15
companies.One company in its portfolio, Boise, Idaho-based
sweepstakes site webMillion.com Inc., was sold in July for $20
million after less than a year in business.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Adcock, one of webMillion's founders, said Rosenblatt's
direction made the difference in landing the buyer, online
advertising firm L90 Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the breakthrough there,'' Adcock said. ``He really has
the ability to see value in things and really make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The new investors are well-protected if they can't make it
happen. In addition to getting control of one of the best-known
names on the Web, they will receive a hefty amount of preferred
stock that can't be traded now but which they ultimately will be
able to convert into about 57.1 million shares of common stock at
35 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The investors, drkoop.com's placement agent and merchant bank,
Commonwealth Associates, and the new management team will also
receive warrants to buy up to 40.7 million more shares at 35 cents.
</P>
<P>
   If all of those purchases take place, current shareholders _ who
hold about 34 million shares _ would see their investments
significantly diluted.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, other prominent dot-coms that have flirted with
bankruptcy have negotiated better rescues. Online grocer Peapod
Inc. received a $73 million bailout from Royal Ahold in June and
Bertelsmann agreed to buy online music retailer CD Now Inc. for
$117 million in July.
</P>
<P>
   But as the summer has dragged on, drkoop.com has looked more and
more distressed. Most of the top executives have left, quarterly
results have fallen way short of expectations, and the company has
faced legal and regulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pretty much over a barrel,'' said Mark Mulcahay, an
analyst who follows drkoop.com for Pacific Growth Equities in San
Francisco. ``I don't think they were negotiating from a position of
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
