<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9371 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-STOCKS-ART-4     08-22 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-STOCKS-ART-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC DECIDES NOT TO ACT AGAINST LAZIO ON STOCK TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Securities and Exchange Commission has said it
will not take action against Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican Senate
candidate in New York, after conducting a two-month preliminary
investigation into whether he used inside information to make a
series of lucrative securities trades.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign released a two-sentence letter from the SEC on
Tuesday informing him that it had closed its inquiry and that ``no
enforcement action has been recommended.'' The SEC, which sent the
letter on Monday, would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Lazio said he was ``pleased that this matter has
been quickly settled.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, the commission opened its inquiry into Lazio's trading
in securities of Quick &AMP; Reilly, a brokerage whose executives are
among his biggest campaign contributors. Lazio spent $2,300 on
speculative options trades in the company's stock in 1997, and in
less than seven weeks earned a profit of roughly $13,500, or nearly
600 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that Lazio, who has regularly bought and
sold stocks in recent years, engaged in such high-risk trading.
Lazio also made a 53 percent profit, or $6,900, in Quick &AMP; Reilly
stock in 1997 and 1998. Over all, he was far more successful in
Quick &AMP; Reilly securities than he was in any other since he became
a congressman in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said in June that he had not obtained inside information
from executives of the company. He said he was a modest investor
with average returns, and had put money in Quick &AMP; Reilly
securities because he believed the company was undervalued. Soon
after Lazio's investments, the company's stock soared when word
leaked out that Quick &AMP; Reilly was putting itself up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I think that it was a good company and one that
got batted down, and I thought that was an opportunity,'' Lazio
said at the time. ``I never had a single discussion'' about the
stock with Quick &AMP; Reilly executives.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Quick &AMP; Reilly have given a total of at least
$35,000 to Lazio's campaign since 1995. Two of those donors, Peter
Quick and Christopher C. Quick, said they had never discussed the
company's stock with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Besides prompting the SEC inquiry, Lazio's profits also focused
attention on whether a member of Congress with influence over Wall
Street _ Lazio serves on both the House Banking and Commerce
committees _ should be trading in the stocks of financial-services
companies. Lazio has also bought and sold stock in others with
business before his committees, including Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides have said he votes solely on an issue's merits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When word of the S.E.C. inquiry was disclosed in June, Lazio's
aides attacked it as politically motivated, noting that the
commission was controlled by appointees of President Clinton. The
aides pointed out that the state comptroller, H. Carl McCall, a
Democrat, had called for an inquiry, citing an article about the
trades in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the commission, while declining to confirm the
inquiry, said then that the commission was an independent agency.
Lazio did not repeat that allegation in his statement yesterday.
After the commission notified Lazio about the inquiry in June, he
said he would cooperate and provide the documents it was seeking.
Neither Lazio nor the commission would describe the documents or
detail any negotiations that were part of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The commission generally does not discuss investigations while
they are ongoing, but when it closes one without taking action, it
customarily sends a short letter to the subject. The letter is not
made public, though in this case, Lazio chose to disclose it.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is not required to finish its preliminary
inquiries within a specific time period. Still, it was undoubtedly
mindful that if the inquiry dragged on into the fall, it might
increasingly affect the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's trading recalled that of several other prominent
politicians whose securities profits have come under scrutiny,
including his Democratic opponent in the Senate race, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, Senator Robert G. Torricelli, the New Jersey
Democrat, and former Senator Alfonse M. D'Amato, the New York
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband was attorney general and then governor of
Arkansas in the late 1970's, Clinton turned a $1,000 investment
into nearly $100,000 over 10 months by trading in risky commodities
futures. An executive of Tyson Foods, which is regulated by the
Arkansas government, assisted her in the trades.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have cited those profits as an example of what they
called a pattern of questionable ethical behavior by Clinton.
Democratic leaders had sought to use the SEC inquiry to neutralize
any attempt by the Lazio campaign to criticize her over the
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate tried yesterday to portray the other as bringing
down the tone of the race. ``I hope Clinton will now join me in a
campaign about issues and finally abandon her tactics of personal
attacks and innuendo,'' Lazio said in his statement. ``New Yorkers
deserve better than her distortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Dunn, a spokeswoman for the Clinton campaign, said:
``Hillary has been running a campaign of issues and ideas for over
a year. Now that the SEC probe is over, maybe Congressman Lazio
will come out of hiding and begin defending his record.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about the Quick &AMP; Reilly trades was gleaned from the
financial disclosure forms that Lazio is required to file with
Congress. Lazio has declined to release copies of his trading
records and tax returns, which would provide more detailed
information.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides, who have promised the tax returns for several
weeks, say they expect to release them in the coming days, and say
they are unremarkable.
</P>
</TEXT>
