<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-KEY CHENEY TALKS IN CLASS, BUT DOESN'T MENTION VOUCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDLANDS, Calif. _ When Dick Cheney came to an elementary school
here on Tuesday to discuss the education policies of the
Bush-Cheney ticket, he brought along a secret campaign weapon: his
wife, Lynne Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Her role became clear almost the moment they arrived, as they
were ushered into that classic campaign photo-op: a classroom full
of eager children. But it was Mrs. Cheney who gamely worked the
crowd of fourth graders as she and her husband, the Republican
vice-presidential nominee, toured a computer laboratory in front of
the cameras. ``Looks like Windows, huh?'' she asked a student,
before rooting for several others who were playing a math game.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cheney, meanwhile, stood quietly in the center of the room,
his hands in the pockets of his pinstripe suit, smiling. After a
few moments, he turned to the teacher, Viola Perez, and made his
own brand of small talk: he asked her about the federal Title I
program for disadvantaged students and training for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cheney came to the school Tuesday to promote Gov. George W.
Bush's ideas on education: he called for maintaining high
educational standards and high expectations, keeping control of
schools at the local level and more resources for schools. The
campaign chose Kingsbury Elementary School as a backdrop because
school administrators from there traveled to Bush's home state of
Texas several years ago to study its education system and, in some
respects, to emulate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think education this year is probably going to be the single
most important issue that is likely to be addressed in the national
campaign this year, and that is as it should be,'' Mr. Cheney told
an education forum in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not address one of the more contentious education
issues: Bush's call for using vouchers to send children in poor
public schools to private schools, a move that Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate, opposes. The issue was
seized upon by a small band of protesters who stood outside the
school.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief news conference, Mr. Cheney was asked about whether
voters concerned about rising oil prices would be concerned that he
had worked for an oil company (``I was running an energy services
and engineering and construction company, not an oil company''),
whether he was too conservative to win in California (``Some of my
best friends are California conservatives'') and his views on
immigration (``We welcome legal immigrants.'')
</P>
<P>
   At times on Tuesday Mr. Cheney displayed some of the dry sense
of humor that he is known for. As he introduced Rep. Jerry Lewis, a
California Republican who joined Congress the same year Mr. Cheney
did, he said: ``I would also point out now Jerry has real influence
as the chairman of one of the key appropriation subcommittees, and
I'm striving to find a position of somewhat lower significance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
