<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SURVIVOR0823-COX     08-22 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survivor winds up stunning summer tonight
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Lisa Sheehan-Hicks is saying a sad goodbye to her
summer fling tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like a first love. You never get it again,''
says the 26-year-old doctoral candidate in community counseling
from Carrollton.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS series ``Survivor'' has been like a summer romance:
short, intense, a little overheated and obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd find myself walking around, just thinking about
strategies, what everyone's odds are,'' says Ted Friedman, who
includes the show in his Media and Popular Culture class syllabus
at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who've never seen ``Survivor'' are aware of the
premise, so thoroughly has the series defined the summer of 2000.
Sixteen contestants _ a cross-section of applicants _ were left on
the South Pacific island of Pulau Tiga to fend for themselves and
every week vote off one member.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tonight at 8, the two-hour finale will reveal the
final ``Survivor,'' who earns $1 million. The finale is expected to
draw 35 million to 40 million viewers, many of them at special
viewing parties.
</P>
<P>
   That's nowhere near Super Bowl levels but way ahead of TV's top
series such as ``ER'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' CBS is
charging $600,000 per 30-second spot, more than than any series
earns during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' like last summer's ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' is a phenomenon that has sent shock waves through
the TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality shows,'' as they're called, are hotter than ever and
more legitimate. CBS has tried to piggy-back ``Big Brother'' _
based on a group of strangers living in a home amid a 24/7
Web-watching audience and five hours of primetime TV exposure each
week _ onto ``Survivor'' with limited success.
</P>
<P>
   And more reality clones are on the way, including ``The Chain,''
an NBC show in which a woman is chained to five men for a week and
eliminates them one by one (the genders are then switched).
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works are ``The Mole'' on ABC (10 contestants travel
the country doing different tasks as an undercover colleague tries
to sabotage their efforts) and ``Boot Camp'' (20 people endure
military-like training while competing for cash) on Fox. Both held
auditions in Atlanta recently.
</P>
<P>
   Finding players for such shows is easier than you'd think. Some
6,200 people tried out for ``Survivor;'' the sequel premiering Jan.
28 lured 50,000 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Shows like ``Survivor,'' which pays big bucks to a few but don't
offer large salaries for cast members, are cheaper to produce than
traditional sitcoms (``Becker'') and dramas (``Providence'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people watch 'Frasier' but they don't talk about
it a lot,'' says Robert Thompson, director of the Center for the
Study of Popular Television at Syracuse University. `` 'Survivor'
is something you talk about, fantasize about what you would do on
the island.''
</P>
<P>
   And something that attracts a large online audience. Fan sites
sprung up like summer mosquitoes, and one, www.survivorsucks.com,
became ground zero for Sherlock-wannabes studying clues, trying to
figure out who would be the next castaway to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a moment in time,'' says Paul Sims, the Dallas-based
Webmaster of survivorsucks.com. ``It will never be like this
again.''
</P>
<P>
   How do we love ``Survivor?'' Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   1. We love it as a mystery. Although the show was taped in the
spring and the winner's identity is known to about 100 people, the
secret has not leaked. (Players' contracts say they can be sued by
CBS if they blab and spoil the ending.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the loose-lipped competitive journalistic environment we
have today, it's nothing short of a miracle,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few mysteries left in the world and this is one
of them,'' says Sims. ``Even with the Internet, there's been no
Deep Throat.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's a whodunit _ a whowonit, perhaps _ every bit as
compelling as ``Who shot J.R.?'' 20 years ago on ``Dallas'' and
``Who killed Laura Palmer?'' 10 years ago on ``Twin Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Figuring out the mystery angle is the biggest thing for me,''
says Jason Kotz, 29, a computer programmer in Kennesaw.
</P>
<P>
   2. We love it as a metaphor. ``It's kind of like the
workplace,'' says Friedman. ``What's most compelling is the
conflict between the need to work collaboratively and, at the same
time, compete as individuals. I've also seen people on the Web
discussing how graduate school is like 'Survivor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Says Mike Halterman of Pensacola, Fla., a 14-year-old who
created one of the many Internet fan sites: ``I just survived my
first week of ninth grade. Pulau Tiga? Bring it on!''
</P>
<P>
   3. We love it for its people. ``They did a brilliant job of
casting the show,'' says Jimmy Baron, a morning host on rock radio
station 99X, one of several Atlanta stations which talk about the
show incessantly. ``The characters are very well-defined, very
unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk on the Web and around water coolers has
centered on Richard Hatch, the manipulative corporate consultant
from Rhode Island whom viewers love to hate, and one of the final
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so interesting that a lot of the characteristics our
society seems to admire, they're bashing the heck out of Richard
for,'' says Sheehan-Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our office is rooting for Rudy,'' says Amie Brown,
a recruiter for Management Recruiters of Cartersville, referring to
Rudy Boesch, 72, the show's ex-Navy SEAL. ``We go around talking
about 'Rudy sayings.' ''
</P>
<P>
   4. We love it for its insidiousness: ``We started out thinking
this was voyeurism, we were all peeping toms,'' Thompson says.
``But we all started grudgingly saying it's a good show. It's a
good old-fashioned soap opera with elements of a sporting event.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Atlanta fan Hilary Copp: ``When I first heard about it, I
was kind of horrified by its 'Lord of the Flies' aspect. Now I'm
ashamed of how drawn into the show I am.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling of being sucked in has led to a certain ambivalence
in many fans' obsessiveness. ``You know when you're screaming at
the TV and your spouse won't come in the room with you, there's
something really wrong,'' says Sheehan-Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it's time to say goodbye. Baron, of 99X, says he can
relate to the idea of ``Survivor'' having been our national summer
romance. ``You try to rekindle that during the year and it just
falls flat,'' he says. ``It was at the right place at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Thompson: ``I've talked to maybe 300 die-hard fans, and
almost everybody has the same response about 'Survivor II.' It's
not going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
