<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9377 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-EPA-ASBESTOS-SPI &LR;      08-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-ASBESTOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT VOWS MAJOR EFFORT TO PROTECT VERMICULITE
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government says it will begin an ``all-out effort''
to protect tens of thousands of workers who handle vermiculite from
exposure to asbestos, which often is found in the ore.
</P>
<P>
   They ``are determined to follow vermiculite products from the
earth to the final occupational use and to intervene if necessary
to assure that workers are not at risk,'' the Occupational Safety
and Health Administration and the Mine Safety and Health
Administration said in a joint statement issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement came on the same day that the Environmental
Protection Agency issued its report on the risks to consumers who
use vermiculite in garden products.
</P>
<P>
   As the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported three weeks ago,
testing by EPA investigators in Seattle and contract scientists in
Washington, D.C., found small amounts of asbestos in 17 of the 38
products tested. Five samples ``contained levels that could pose a
potential for exposure,'' the agency reported. The health hazard to
home gardeners who use vermiculite material only once a year is
minimal, the report said, but risk could increase depending on the
frequency of use and the amount of asbestos in vermiculite being
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vermiculite may present more serious risks in an occupational
setting where the duration and frequency of exposures is likely to
be significantly greater,'' the report said, but later added,
``Occupational exposures were not evaluated as part of this
study.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement puzzled and angered some union officials and
researchers who read early drafts of the report that clearly showed
the EPA scientists had done preliminary evaluations of worker
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The occupational exposure calculations in the draft report
reflected extremely high risk. The early drafts cautioned that
workers using vermiculite daily faced an increased risk of cancer
from two additional cases for each 1,000 workers to one cancer per
100 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went down this road with EPA 20 years ago when they
concealed and ignored risks to vermiculite workers, and their
inspector general is investigating that absurdity. Now we've got it
again. The agency finds that workers are at significant risk of
contracting deadly diseases, but they pull it from the report they
made public,'' said Donald Judge, head of the AFL-CIO in Montana,
where the nation's largest vermiculite mine operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell is going on with this agency? How much do we
have to study the issue of asbestos? How many thousand more workers
will have to die before the EPA does something to stop it?'' Judge
asked.
</P>
<P>
   EPA's Stephen Johnson says the scientists doing the study ``did
make some attempt to characterize the workers' risk,'' and those
risk assessments were present in the earlier drafts that were sent
to OSHA and other agencies for peer review of the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told that our preliminary analysis on workers were
based on calculations that were not based on (OSHA's) methodology,
and so we agreed, and we deleted it from the report,'' said
Johnson, who is deputy assistant administrator for the Office of
Prevention, Pesticides and Toxic Substances.
</P>
<P>
   EPA's preliminary examination of occupational exposure was
crafted on how nursery and laboratory workers might use
vermiculite, but according to Commerce Department and industry
estimates, 200,000 or more other workers use vermiculite on a
regular basis, many in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of factories make fire-resistant wall board and sheet
rock using hundreds of tons of vermiculite. Every day at
construction sites throughout the country thousands of workers mix
bags of vermiculite with cement and plaster. Raw vermiculite is
poured into holes and stomped down by workers installing liners for
swimming pools. Smaller amounts are used by hundreds of other
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``OSHA and MSHA are committed to ensuring that workers' exposure
to asbestos in vermiculite is identified and addressed,'' the
agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA has asked the National Institute for Occupational Safety
and Health to evaluate worker exposure to asbestos in vermiculite
in processing operations and other work sites. MSHA is evaluating
worker exposure to asbestos in vermiculite mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we do not know if there's a hazard to workers, it is
important that we work together to assess the magnitude of
potential exposure to asbestos from working with vermiculite,'' the
statement said. ''What's more, it is not known if the problems
associated with vermiculite from the former Libby mine in Montana
are present in vermiculite found in other mines today, and this
will be investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, OSHA offered suggestions for concerned workers:
</P>
<P>
   _ They can first talk to their employers to determine whether
the vermiculite they're using has been tested for asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   _ If they're in a union or other worker's organization, they can
talk to the group's safety representatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ If they're still not sure, OSHA suggests that workers ``wet
the product down, don't work in closed areas without good
ventilation and avoid the dust which settles in the bottom of the
bags of vermiculite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The levels of asbestos varies considerably from one batch to
another,'' an OSHA spokesperson cautioned. ``Workers may be using a
batch of vermiculite that has absolutely no asbestos in it and
tests clean. But the next day, using the same material, they might
be working with vermiculite that is highly contaminated. The
asbestos contamination is so variable, and that's why it's so
important that more work be done on this problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
