<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ELCHIBEY-NYT &LR;      08-22 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ELCHIBEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABULFAZ ELCHIBEY, 62, FIRST DEMOCRATIC PRESIDENT OF AZERBAIJAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Abulfaz Elchibey, a former history professor
who became the first democratically elected president of Azerbaijan
before fleeing into internal exile, died early Tuesday in a Turkish
hospital where he was being treated for advanced prostate cancer.
He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey's death was announced by his doctors at Gulhane
military hospital in Ankara, where he had been a patient for two
weeks. The doctors said he was also suffering from diabetes and
infections. Officials in Azerbaijan said his body would be flown to
the capital, Baku, for a state funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was elected president in 1992, a year after the
collapse of the Soviet Union brought independence to the small
country on the Caspian Sea. Elchibey's yearlong tenure was marked
by his insistence that Russian troops and bases be removed from the
country and that a national currency, the manat, be introduced.
</P>
<P>
   But his brief term was also marred by economic upheaval and
military losses in the breakaway region of Nagorno-Karabakh, where
Armenian-backed forces claimed 20 percent of Azerbaijan and turned
about 1 million Azerbaijanis into refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey himself was forced to flee Baku in June 1993 when a
small uprising at a military base threatened to plunge the country
into civil war. He was succeeded as president by Geidar Aliev, the
country's communist boss under Soviet rule. Aliev cemented his
control later that year in an election that Elchibey denounced as
fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last month in Baku, Aliev said he had agreed to
assume the office of president at the personal insistence of
Elchibey.He quoted Elchibey as saying that Aliev was the only
person who could hold the country together and avoid a blood bath.
</P>
<P>
   Aliev was dismissive of his predecessor, describing him as a
professor who lacked the experience to run a country and deal with
the political complexities of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was born on June 24, 1938, in the small town of Keleki
in the enclave of Nakhichevan, a section of Azerbaijan cut off from
the rest of the country and surrounded by Iran, Turkey and Armenia.
His original surname was Aliev, which he later changed to Elchibey,
which means envoy. The surname Aliev is shared by a great many
Azerbaijanis, and the two men were not related.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Baku as a 19-year-old student and studied Arabic at
the university. He later became a history professor. He was also an
active dissident and was jailed briefly in 1975 after protesting
Soviet policies in the region.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the national Popular Front party, he was swept
into office by anti-Soviet sentiment in June 1992. Unlike leaders
in neighboring Georgia and Armenia, he was successful in forcing
the removal of most Russian troops and bases from his country and
moving Azerbaijan away from Russian dominance. He realigned the
country with Turkey, an alliance that remains strong today. He also
changed the alphabet from Cyrillic to Roman.
</P>
<P>
   But Elchibey faced insurmountable difficulties in the heavily
Armenian section of western Azerbaijan known as Nagorno-Karabakh.
The military suffered stunning defeats at the hands of
Russian-backed Armenian troops and lost the region.
</P>
<P>
   Elchibey was driven from office in June 1993. He spent the next
four years in internal exile in Nakhichevan, coincidentally the
same province where Aliev went after the country's independence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Elchibey returned to Baku and tried to regain his
influence as a leader of the opposition movement. Though he
remained chairman of the Popular Front, he had little real power,
and opposition to Aliev has remained weak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
