<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CANE-MAIN0823-COX     08-22 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANE-MAIN0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1,000 miles out at sea, Debby has a straight shot at South
Florida
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Hurricane Debby began stair-stepping up the Caribbean
Islands Tuesday, sparing the Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico the
brunt of its 75 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   And that left the fast-moving storm 1,000 miles of open sea on a
straight shot that would bring it near South Florida by Friday
morning, eight years and a day after Hurricane Andrew barrelled
into Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm or hurricane watches could be posted in South
Florida by late afternoon today, National Hurricane Center
forecasters said. A watch means tropical storm or hurricane-force
winds are possible within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do feel the effects of Debby, it would probably be
Friday morning,'' said hurricane center meteorologist Krissy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Debby is likely to be a Category 2 storm, with winds of 105 mph
by late afternoon Thursday as its projected path reaches Andros
Island in the Bahamas, about 200 miles southeast of West Palm
Beach, Williams said. Hurricane force winds of 74 mph or more are
likely to extend 80 miles north of the center of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The official forecast track puts the hurricane anywhere from
Melbourne along the central Florida coast to south of Cuba by 5
p.m. Friday. But not all of the computer models agree on a track.
</P>
<P>
   One has Debby continuing on a more westerly path into the
Florida straits. Another has it turning north over the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The storm is being guided by a high pressure ridge over Florida
and the eastern Atlantic Ocean, steering Debby on its
west-northwest path under the ridge. But a weakness in the ridge
over the Bahamas could allow the storm to veer more northward by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too early to tell,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Local and state emergency management officials moved to a state
of watchful waiting Tuesday, advising South Florida residents to
begin thinking of what last-minute preparations they should make.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it stays on our track, we've got Wednesday and Thursday to
prepare.'' said National Hurricane Center Director Max Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching real closely,'' said Palm Beach County
Emergency Management Director Bill O'Brien, who met with and made
calls to the Palm Beach County School Board, American Red Cross and
state officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Partial activation of the emergency operations center could come
today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida Water Management District opened low pre-storm
water releases from canals in Miami-Dade County Tuesday. Water
levels in primary canals in counties farther north, including Palm
Beach, Martin and St. Lucie were within seasonal ranges so gates
were not opened yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Okeechobee is below normal level so no releases are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Power &AMP; Light will not position crews until after the
storm hits. ``We've found it's better to wait until we really know
where it's going,'' said FPL spokesman Bill Swank. ``All the heavy
hurricane season preparation has been done and we did a dry run
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon Tuesday, local residents were keeping an eye on
Debby and beginning to make preparations for a possible landfall in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At the Publix supermarket on Southern Boulevard in West Palm
Beach, workers were stocking extra cases of bottled water that had
been shipped to the store earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the water business right now, that's a good
business to be in,'' one employee said. ``I'd hate to see what it
looks like'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Franz of West Palm Beach was one of the few people
stocking up, buying 12 bottles of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left work early so I could beat the 5 o'clock rush,'' Franz
said. ``People are going to get home, watch the evening news and
come out here. It'll be packed.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the Home Depot on Lake Worth Road, Efrin Valle was
buying plywood to cover his carport. He said he and his family are
watching the storm, but aren't nervous, yet.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the reaction of most people Tuesday, said Jerry
Hester, Home Depot's sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been selling panels and plywood, but there's no panic
yet,'' Hester said. ``It's not anything more than an average day
right now. I would think the next day or two will be the big
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Caribbean islands escaped with little damage. With winds up
to 75 mph, the storm was a Category 1 hurricane when it struck
Antigua, Anguilla and other small islands Tuesday morning. It then
made a slight _ but crucial _ turn to the north that meant populous
Puerto Rico and the vulnerable Dominican Republic could be spared
the worst.
</P>
<P>
   A 78-year-old San Juan man died Tuesday, Puerto Rican police
reported, when he fell off a roof as he tried to dismantle a
television antenna.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. Virgin Islands, the storm caused a few power outages
but little damage. Airlines canceled flights, schools and banks
closed, storekeepers nailed plywood to windows, cruise lines
diverted ships and a major oil refinery was partially shut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
