<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pope unseats Costello as punter for Cincinnati
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Daniel Pope couldn't punt for Milton High in
Alpharetta, Ga. But he will be punting for the Cincinnati Bengals
this fall. Pope, who graduated from Milton in 1994 and went on to
punt for Alabama, won a job Tuesday, the deadline for teams to trim
their rosters to 65 players. When the Bengals released incumbent
Brad Costello along with three others, Pope was the only punter
left on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was my consistency,'' said Pope, who averaged 41.9
yards on seven punts this preseason. ``Plus, the fact that I can
hold (on field-goal attempts) helped.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals also will have a new kicker. They let go Doug
Pelfrey, who was the most accurate kicker in team history but was
18-for-27 last season. Instead, Cincinnati kept sixth-round pick
Neil Rackers from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have kept them if we didn't think they were pretty
good,'' coach Bruce Coslet said.
</P>
<P>
   Pope's path to an NFL job was not easy. He played linebacker and
long-snapped at Milton, then walked on at Western Kentucky but left
before the start of classes. He stayed home for a year, then walked
on at Alabama and waited three years before winning the starting
job.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he averaged 41.8 yards per punt as a rookie for
Kansas City before being let go in July. Costello averaged 33.8
yards last season for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams, including the Falcons, made their moves during the
weekend or Monday. The biggest name Monday was probably Buccaneers
defensive tackle Brad Culpepper, who started the past four seasons
for Tampa and had 23.5 sacks the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Saints cut 13 players, and the Bears cut 14.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Bears' cuts was veteran defensive lineman Chris Mims,
who missed Monday morning's practice after reportedly oversleeping.
Offensive lineman Gannon Shepherd, an undrafted rookie from Duke
and Marist High, also was cut.
</P>
<P>
   Another notable cut was Broncos running back John Avery, who was
the Dolphins' first-round pick in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins placed wide receiver Lamar Thomas on injured
reserve with a fractured and dislocated hip. It is the second
consecutive season Thomas will miss with an injury. He suffered it
Monday night in a game against the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco placed running back Garrison Hearst, coming off
ankle surgery, on the physically unable to perform list. He must
sit out at least the first six games.
</P>
<P>
   The next deadline is Sunday, when teams must cut from 65 to 53
players.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
