<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIRES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE FORCES LIMITS IN ACCESS TO MONTANA COUNTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs to change `close' counties to `restrict access' or
limiting movement in lede, grafs 5, 6 and 7, for clarity.) 
By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With some of the summer's worst wildfires burning vast
stretches of Montana, Gov. Marc Racicot is preparing to restrict
access at least 16 counties in the western part of the state, a
decision that would put some of Montana's most popular recreation
areas off limits until the fires are brought under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an extremely serious situation for us to be addressing
it in these terms,'' Racicot said Tuesday in an interview,
referring to an announcement he expected to make on Wednesday.
``It's so incredibly difficult for people who rely, in so many
ways, on this area for recreation and their livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana is one of several Western states in which officials have
taken unusual precautionary measures because of wildfires that have
now consumed 4.1 million acres in 11 Western states, and some 5.7
million acres in the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming last week declared his state a
disaster area because of wildfires and drought. On Monday, the
Forest Service closed the Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness Area, a part
of Clearwater National Forest in north central Idaho, and the
Bridger-Teton National Forest in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The expected decision by Racicot could include as many as 19
counties, which would effectively reduce access to the entire
western third of Montana to all but those who live and work in
areas that fire officials have determined are not in immediate
danger.
</P>
<P>
   It would also bring to 28 the number of counties that he has
restricted access to this month _ or half the state, which has 56
counties _ following an order two weeks ago to shut off all or part
of nine counties in central Montana. The Bureau of Land Management
has already closed federal land it controls in those counties.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions are intended to minimize the risk of injury
from wildfires that have been spreading rapidly by persistently dry
weather conditions and, for the most part, temperatures in the
upper 80s and low 90s. Racicot's orders so far have made exceptions
for some recreational areas, and the ones he is expected to issue
Wednesday are expected to do the same. Several major national
parks, like Yellowstone and Glacier, remain open.
</P>
<P>
   But limiting movement in areas like the Lolo National Forest and
the Bitterroot National Forest is one of several unusual elements
that reflect the seriousness of wildfires that are making this one
of the worst years in decades. There were 20,364 wildfires in the
West on Tuesday morning, with 79 large fires still burning across
almost 1.4 million acres in nine Western states.
</P>
<P>
   Resources have been so strained that for the first time, fire
management teams from other countries are assisting. Two
supervisory teams from Canada are at work, and a team from
Australia is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unprecedented,'' said J.D. Coleman, a spokesman for the
Northern Rockies Coordinating Center in Missoula, Mont. ``Never
have we been stretched so thin that we've had to bring in fire
management teams from other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Parman, a spokesman for the National Interagency Fire
Center in Boise, Idaho, said that the firefighting force included
20,000 to 25,000 people, with about 1,200 more soldiers expected to
arrive later this week to join about 2,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   But the fighting force is comprised of more than veterans of
past fires and even scores of retired fire fighters who have joined
the efforts. Officials at the Fire Center estimate that as many as
9,000 college students may be on the lines, many of whom will have
to depart in the weeks ahead to return to classes. And in Wyoming,
42 prison inmates are working alongside professional firefighters
as part of a program that has been in effect since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are inmates who are about to be released or who have
earned the right to less security and are not a threat to
society,'' said Melinda Brazzale, a spokeswoman for the Wyoming
Department of Corrections. ``They are professionally trained by
another firefighter and go out and fight fires all over Wyoming and
in South Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazzale said the program had proved beneficial to both the
inmates and the state, which had saved more than $125,000 this year
by using them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a savings to federal and local agencies,'' she said.
``It's also a real benefit to the inmates to learn a saleable
skill.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to personnel needs, fire-fighting efforts this year
have been compounded by the growing number of private homes that
have been built inside forested areas, a trend that Racicot and
other officials said reflects the nation's vibrant economy. Many of
the houses are owned by retirees; others are second homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have completely changed how we go about fighting fires,''
Coleman said. ``So many people have come out West to burrow into
woods, draws and creek beds. They like being a modern-day pioneer.
But now we have to protect their homes, and with the volume of
fires and their complexity, it makes for such an unpredictable
situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
