<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ME, MYSELF AND WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Great balls of fire!
</P>
<P>
   Alpha Al, you the man. You got your mojo. You are looking
 &UR; goooood &LR; !
</P>
<P>
   Hey you, handsome front-runner in the mirror, give me a high
five! Yesssssss! You've got the cool, clear eyes of a seeker of
wisdom and truth.
</P>
<P>
   All right, enough kudos for me and my five-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the bench press. I want to buff my pecs and ridge my
abs. By the time I meet the Austin airhead at the first debate _ if
he even has the nerve to face me _ my shoulders will be twice as
broad as his.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody had written me off _ even my ``loyal'' hired guns and
my ``loyal'' Oval Office cheerleader. Everybody figured I was an
apple-polisher and W. was apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   But now 74 percent of the American people know I Have the Right
Kind of Experience to Be President. And 62 percent are convinced I
Understand the Problems of People Like Them. And 56 percent say I
am a Strong Leader. (Margin of error: 3.5 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Bounce that, W.!
</P>
<P>
   Bush thinks a St. Alban's boy like me can't win on class
warfare. He can't even pronounce it! He calls it ``class warfore.''
I can't believe I ever trailed a free-trader who can't even spit
out ``tariffs and barriers.'' For awhile he was saying ``terriers
and bariffs.'' The other night in Des Moines he abbreviated it to
merely ``terrors.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he tries to talk about the budget, he trips on his
trillions.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a relief not to have to pretend anymore that I
relished being the underdog and that I didn't care about the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I love polls more than anything _ even my Palm
Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   I am feeling so empowered today, I'm going to do an extra set of
reps. Man, those biceps are looking especially chiseled today!
Watch out, rural waitress moms, suburban soccer moms and
18-to-24-year-old single female urban dwellers! This stud is coming
to a town meeting near you!
</P>
<P>
   I will be  &UR; (huff) &LR;  humble  &UR; (puff) &LR;  as I claim my rightful place
as Master of the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   President Ego can march through convention hall basements till
noon on Jan. 20, when I'll show him the door. There's a new
gladiator in town.
</P>
<P>
   I've had it with him. My pal Marty Peretz told the BBC that
Clinton had been ``a big burden'' to me, and that he had a ``deeply
flawed'' and ``loathsome character.'' I'm glad Marty said what
Tipper and I really think.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch! I feel as if I pulled a muscle. I'll stop pumping iron for
a moment and strategize. To keep the bounce going, I have to figure
out what I did in Los Angeles that changed voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   What do I have now that I didn't have before? Which new me works
best for me? Were they wowed by Wednesday's earth tones or
Thursday's business attire? Do they prefer Al the Lover to Al the
Fighter? L.A. Al must not revert to D.C. Al!
</P>
<P>
   I must focus-group myself. The important thing is not to panic.
There's a throb in my deltoid. I'll pop an Altoid. But I need a
factoid.
</P>
<P>
   I'm calling Stan Greenberg. ``Stan? Al. Convene a group ASAP. It
is of the utmost urgency that we find out, right now, once and for
all, who on earth I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I want you to find out:
</P>
<P>
   ``DidtheylikeitwhenItalkedfast? Do they want more specificity,
less liberalism, more Nashville, less condescension, more Hadassah?
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out if it was The Kiss that swayed independent women my
way. Was 4.398 seconds of lip-locking and 18.901 seconds of hugging
sufficient? Do they want to see me nibble Tipper's neck? Shall we
save a 10-second kiss for our October surprise?
</P>
<P>
   ``See if they saw me as My Own Man because we leaked that stuff
about our deep disdain for the future First Couple of Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out if they want me to keep campaign finance reform as my
first Oval Office priority. Check if they noticed that I promised
reform on Thursday night one hour before scooping up five million
at Barbra's fund-raising concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to have cottoned to Joe. Do they want  &UR; me &LR;  to walk
to work on Saturdays too?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask if they still notice The Spot now that my hair's moussed
up like Reagan's. They're not comparing the size of my Spot with
Joe's spot, are they?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just ask them who they want me to be and if I'm bouncing or
slipping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
