</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS RULE OUT SABOTAGE IN TWA FLIGHT 800 CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for rewriting thruout, new byline; story is now 200 words
longer)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opening the final chapter in the longest and most
expensive crash investigation in its 33-year history, the National
Transportation Safety Board began a two-day meeting Tuesday to
review a draft of its final report on the cause of the crash of
Trans World Airlines Flight 800 over Long Island four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the five-member board, investigators said they had
reached the inescapable conclusion that the Boeing 747 was ripped
apart in midair when its center wing fuel tank exploded minutes
after it departed from Kennedy International Airport bound for
Paris on July 17, 1996. All 230 people aboard were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, James Hall, chairman of the safety
board, said there was no evidence of a criminal act, despite
initial suspicions and trace amounts of explosive residue found on
three of the tens of thousands of pieces of the plane's wreckage.
He strongly condemned critics who maintain that the government is
hiding the fact that Flight 800 was downed by a missile or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take exception to those who consistently distort the record
and persist in making unfounded charges of a cover-up,'' he said,
addressing spectators who included family members of the victims.
``They do a disservice to us all but most especially to you, the
TWA 800 families, who have suffered so much in this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Summarizing the conclusions of the four-year investigation,
Bernard Loeb, the director of the board's office of aviation
safety, said that the atmosphere in the fuel tank at the time of
the accident was easily capable of exploding with enough force to
bring down the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite extensive research and testing, investigators could
not determine exactly what ignited the fuel vapors in the nearly
empty tank, which had been heated to an explosive state while the
25-year-old jet sat baking in the sun for nearly three hours before
taking off. After ruling out several possible ignition sources,
Loeb said that investigators now believe that a short circuit sent
a surge of electricity into the tank through the wiring of a fuel
gauge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot be certain that this in fact occurred, but of all of
the ignition scenarios that we considered, this scenario is the
most likely,'' Loeb said.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the meeting, which was open to the public under a
federal sunshine law, was to let board members question
investigators about their 684-page draft report and make revisions.
The meeting is expected to conclude on Wednesday, when the board is
scheduled to vote to approve the final report and its safety
recommendations. The board plans to release abstracts of the report
immediately on its Web site, www.ntsb.gov. Internet users can
monitor the board meeting live on the site. The full report will be
made public in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the board's safety recommendations, relating to fuel
tank flammability, potential sources of ignition and the
maintenance of electrical wiring in older jets, were previously
proposed to the Federal Aviation Administration, which was closely
involved in the crash investigation. Indeed, the FAA said it had
already issued 37 directives to operators of a variety of aircraft
models in the wake of the crash, the most sweeping actions in its
history, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is now evaluating ways that the center fuel tank can
be kept cooler. It is also studying how to formulate a rule that
would direct aircraft operators to inject nitrogen into nearly
empty fuel tanks to prevent combustion. Investigators say that this
is the best way to prevent future explosions regardless of the
source of ignition.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the questioning by board members at Tuesday's meeting
seemed intended to try to dispel suspicions of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they considered the possibility of a bomb or
missile early on but ruled it out because none of the wreckage
showed the characteristic damage present after a high-energy
explosion. In addition, there were no holes in the fuselage large
enough to have been made by the impact of a missile, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators theorize that the traces of explosives found
on the three pieces of wreckage could have been placed on the jet
when it was ferrying troops during the Persian Gulf War, during an
explosive-detection exercise with bomb-sniffing dogs that occurred
about one month before the crash, or after the crash during the
salvage operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
