<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS CONSIDER BILL CAPPING ELECTRICITY RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mounting political concern over what many are
describing as deregulation run amok in the electricity market in
San Diego, which prompted a battle in the state Assembly Tuesday
over a bill that would place a broad cap on power costs in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the state utility commission narrowly approved a
partial rate cap for San Diego, the first city in California to be
deregulated, but many people said they believed it was too little
to help customers being hit with bills that have doubled or tripled
in just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, the bill, which was passed previously by the
state Senate by 28-0, had still not been voted on, and it was
facing resistance because of the expected costs to the state,
perhaps many hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But several legislative aides said late Tuesday that it appeared
that supporters of the measure did not have enough votes yet to
pass it, and that its fate was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, skyrocketing power rates in San Diego, the first
city in a pioneering state program, has suddenly become a source of
concern because of the unexpected rate increases. Deregulation was
undertaken because the Legislature believed it would prove an
antidote to what were already high power rates in the state,
roughly 50 percent above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deregulation plan, passed in 1996 with the expectation
that it would be phased in over many years, utilities had to sell
off their power generating plants and then purchase electricity
through a state-controlled exchange. San Diego was opened before
other cities because of a merger of its various utilities to form
Sempra Energy.
</P>
<P>
   But many critics have complained that the market was opened
before there was a sufficient supply of electricity available,
skewing prices upward. The strong economy and the added burden of
people turning on their air conditioners during summer added to
demand, and correspondingly, the jump in wholesale power rates,
which in turn have been passed along to retail consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the state, from Gov. Gray Davis to the chairman
of Sempra Energy, have accused some of the wholesalers of price
gouging, and the government has written President Clinton urging
him to initiate a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is of the essence, Mr. President,'' the Davis wrote in
his letter dated Aug. 10. ``San Diego consumers have paid an
enormous price for deregulation in a market that no one believes is
functionally competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Golding, San Diego's mayor, said in an interview that she
supported deregulation, but that the timing had been so badly
planned that some sort of market intervention by government was
necessary to spare the city's economy major problems in what had
been its best economic expansion after suffering through a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, it takes a very long time to go from a bad
economic climate to a good one, but almost no time to go the other
way, and that's what I'm afraid could happen here,'' said Golding.
``I don't think this bill is the right long-term solution, but I
chose to support it because it is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the California Public Utility Commission narrowly
approved a measure that would cap power costs in the city, but only
for small businesses and residents who used 500 kilowatt-hours of
electricity per month or less. That left many people unsatisfied,
particularly since a variety of users, from public schools to high
technology companies that have boosted San Diego's economy in the
last decade, would see no improvement in their power bills.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted the State Assembly to resume its debate of the new
bill, which is sponsored by two San Diego area legislators, state
Sen. Dede Alpert, and Assembly member Susan Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would rollback prices to their levels in June, before
rates began to skyrocket, order the state utility commission to
place a firm cap on rates at that level, and create a mechanism for
passing along excess profits to consumers. The bill would also
require an investigation of the increase in rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
