<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE'S SEASON TO END EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, in the
midst of treatment for bone marrow cancer, returned to the team
Tuesday but said he would probably not be able to finish the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre has been preparing for a stem cell transplant, in
which cells cleansed by chemotherapy are reintroduced into his
body. Doctors have not told him exactly when that procedure will
take place, but whenever it does _ and Stottlemyre wants to have it
done as soon as possible _ he will not be able to return to his job
for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll make it through the season,'' he said.
``Everything they've done so far, I've been on the upper scale, on
the plus side. The things that have bothered me have bothered me a
lot less than they've bothered other people. The stem cell
collection, instead of taking three days, they probably had enough
in one day. I've just been lucky; I've reacted very favorably to
all the medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre intends to serve as pitching coach for the next
couple of days and to go on the Yankees' coming road trip, assuming
that his latest blood tests, scheduled for Wednesday, produce the
expected results. ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I came here today
with the doctors' blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who last coached Aug. 5, has watched all but one of
the Yankees' games on television and has spoken to manager Joe
Torre regularly. ``The game looks easier on TV,'' Stottlemyre
joked. ``There's been a lot of good things. A couple of negatives,
I guess _ the bullpen in a couple of games. The starters have been
pitching well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough sitting at home, watching on television. You're
used to watching the game from the dugout, and all of a sudden
you're confined to watching the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Connors, who has been filling in during Stottlemyre's
absence and will accompany the Yankees on the coming road trip, has
been keeping Stottlemyre's records in the same manner Stottlemyre
does; typically, each pitching coach keeps records in a style that
suits only him. ``Billy's been pretty much keeping me up to date,''
Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre decided not to talk to anyone who has had a stem
cell transplant until he was actually on the verge of having one
himself. Now, he said, he's ready to take that step of discussing
it with someone like Roger Neilson, the former coach of the
Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm curious about how some people rebound,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre believes that working helps Stottlemyre _ ``He was going
stir crazy,'' Torre said _ and that having Stottlemyre around helps
the Yankees. ``Any time you think of griping, you look around and
see Mel and all of sudden what you're griping about seems very
insignificant,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's Nagging Injury
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch continues to go through rehabilitation for his
right elbow at the Yankees' minor-league complex in Tampa, Fla.,
and could join a minor league team later in the week. But the pain
that has bothered him for almost a month continues to nag at him.
</P>
<P>
   With time running out on the season, there is a chance Knoblauch
will not be able to throw pain-free again before the playoffs. The
question, then, will be whether Knoblauch, who can hit without a
problem, can play second base with the pain.
</P>
<P>
   It is a question that Joe Torre will likely ask Knoblauch in the
next few days. ``I think that's probably the next step, to give him
a call and try to figure it out,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   If Knoblauch does feel that he can play with the pain, he could
be activated within a week. If he feels he needs relief, the
Yankees could pursue more substantive medical treatment, like a
cortisone shot, before he continues with his rehabilitation. If he
feels he cannot play with his current level of pain, then he could
be relegated to the role of pinch-hitter, pinch-runner and
part-time designated hitter _ sharing time with Glenallen Hill and
Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is obviously hoping Knoblauch can play second base,
because of his importance as the Yankees' leadoff hitter; Knoblauch
would presumably be replaced in the late innings any time the
Yankees have a lead.
</P>
<P>
   Williams Ailing
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center
fielder, will join Knoblauch on the disabled list. Williams
strained the right side of his rib cage, and the Yankees intend to
be extremely cautious about his return, because if he comes back
too soon and exacerbates his injury, it could affect him deep into
October.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he hoped to play Wednesday. Torre said he did not
expect Williams to play for the rest of the homestand, which ends
Thursday. ``They've got me on a snail's pace,'' said Williams, who
was to play catch before Tuesday night's game against the Texas
Rangers at Yankee Stadium. ``If I take batting practice tomorrow
and I think I can hit, I might be able to convince them I can
play.''
</P>
<P>
   There are statistical goals within reach for Williams, if he can
play. With another 23 runs batted in, he will tie Mickey Mantle's
single-season RBI record for switch-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   No Justice
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also played their second consecutive game Tuesday
night without David Justice, who strained his neck, an injury that
is not considered serious. Ramiro Mendoza, on the disabled list
because of stiffness in the back of his shoulder, played catch
again Tuesday. The Yankees hope he will recover in time to rejoin
the team by the middle of next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
