<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION SERVICE DROPS BID TO DEPORT BRONX STUDENT, 16 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Immigration and Naturalization Service on Tuesday
abruptly backed off an effort to deport a 16-year-old Bronx high
school student to Trinidad after an apparent mix-up involving his
family's residency papers.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Ricky Ramoutar, who moved to the United States at
age 3 with his family, received a terse INS notice at his Bronx
home in April ordering him to appear before an immigration judge.
If he failed to show up, the notice warned, he could be arrested
and jailed.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager had come to the agency's attention after playing
on an American junior chess team at the World Youth Games in Moscow
in 1998. The trip required permission from the INS.
</P>
<P>
   When he received the notice, Ricky Ramoutar said in an
interview, ``I was crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, his family's application with the INS for
permanent residency was pending, but the paperwork had been stalled
for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went in for the appointment, they told me they would
write me,'' said Ricky's father, Barminth Ramoutar. ``They never
told me there was any problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murtha, the boy's lawyer, said in an interview that after
the Ramoutar family came to the United States, the parents split
up. Barminth Ramoutar, a welder, married a U.S. citizen. In 1997,
based on that marriage, Barminth applied for permanent residency
status, seeking what is known as a green card for himself and his
two sons.
</P>
<P>
   When Ricky traveled to Moscow with the chess team from Middle
School 118 in the Bronx, he received written permission from
immigration officers. But that also brought the young man under
scrutiny. In April, they sent the ``notice of removal'' to his
apartment. Oddly enough, it applied only to Ricky, not to his
father or brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they said was, `Show us a reason he should not be kicked
out,''' said Murtha, an immigration lawyer. ``The reason he got
stuck in court was the trip to Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramoutars appeared for two interviews with INS officials,
and after that heard nothing about their application. Green-card
reviews typically take about 15 months to process, Murtha said.
</P>
<P>
   After he received the immigration notice, Ricky called Marley
Kaplan, the executive director of Chess-in-the-Schools, a New York
City program that had captured his interest. She said she was
shocked that the INS wanted to deport him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible thing that is happening to a great kid,''
Kaplan said. ``He goes off to represent the United States as a
champion, and this is what happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man had been on the Middle School 118 team that won
the national championship in Arizona two years ago. Kaplan has also
sponsored Ricky at the Roman Catholic high school he attends now.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about Ricky's plight, Kaplan swung into action,
calling Sen. Charles Schumer's office and the news media. When the
Ramoutars appeared in immigration court in Manhattan on Tuesday
morning, the tiny courtroom was crowded with reporters and family
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha conferred with the INS lawyer, and the judge adjourned
the case until immigration officials could check on the status of
the Ramoutars' green-card application. By late afternoon, the
agency had changed its position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been looking into the specifics of the case,'' Mark
Thorne, an INS spokesman, said in an interview. ``We have asked the
immigration court to terminate these proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said the case was not over. The Ramoutars' application
for permanent residency was rejected on Aug. 16 because they did
not appear for another meeting with immigration officials, Murtha
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Ramoutar never received notice of a meeting or of
the denial of the green card. Murtha said he hoped that the INS
would reopen the review.
</P>
<P>
   Thorne said he could not comment on whether the INS would
reconsider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
