<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER NBA MEGA-TRADE COLLAPSE, EWING'S FATE IS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing is not battling only his aching joints
anymore. Public opinion is posting him up, telling him to leave
town. His own organization even planned a conference call on Monday
night to announce the separation.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Ewing, the Knicks' franchise center,
survived yet another coup to his 15-year reign Tuesday. How long he
remains in New York is unclear, but the four-team, 13-player swap
that would have sent the 38-year-old veteran to Seattle is
officially dead.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Knicks, the SuperSonics and the Los Angeles Lakers
all entertained possibilities of separate deals that could
eventually cause Ewing to land in Seattle and Vin Baker and Glen
Rice in New York. The Lakers would secure a power forward to help
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant defend their title.
</P>
<P>
   But barring late-night negotiations among the clubs, nothing
seemed imminent Tuesday night. Ewing, moments away from ending his
long association with the Knicks on Monday and the subject of a
tabloid headline Tuesday that blared ``Good Riddance,'' remained a
Knick for another evening.
</P>
<P>
   A club spokeswoman said the organization had nothing to announce
late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with the Knicks trying to salvage a deal with the
SuperSonics, who were prepared to send Baker to New York for Ewing
in the proposed trade, which would have been the largest in NBA
history.
</P>
<P>
   But New York's interest in parting ways with Ewing was tied to
acquiring Rice from the Lakers, a Knicks team official said Tuesday
on condition of anonymity. Rice was one of two other prominent
players in the deal, along with Detroit's Christian Laettner, whom
the Lakers were trying to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors led to the demise of the four-team deal, none
more important than the Pistons' refusal on Monday night to take on
the contracts of seven marginal role players moments after the
Knicks, the Lakers and the SuperSonics had begun plans for a
conference call to announce the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Division among Pistons executives over adding at least three
contracts that had more than one year remaining on them led to
Detroit's pulling out of the deal. According to an Eastern
Conference official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, the
Pistons yesterday asked Scott Layden, the Knicks general manager,
to include Marcus Camby in a package. But Layden, the conference
official said, was not willing.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons, who spent much of Tuesday completing a trade that
would send Lindsey Hunter to Milwaukee for Billy Owens, showed
little inclination to get back involved in a four-team swap.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ewing was beginning to have mixed feelings about
ending his association with New York, a person close to him said.
The 12-time All-Star waived the no-trade clause in his contract
recently, essentially giving the Knicks approval to move him to
another team of his liking.
</P>
<P>
   After all the innuendo and speculation, it is not inconceivable
that Ewing will return for a 16th season in New York at age 38. The
Eastern Conference official implied that if the Knicks did not
receive what they believed was fair value for Ewing, a future Hall
of Famer, the club would most likely enter training camp with Ewing
on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not impossible,'' the official said. ``Would they welcome
Patrick back if things fell through? From what I hear, they would
do it with open arms. They're not letting him go for one player
who's not going to help them out as much Patrick already does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
