<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SENDING TROOPS TO TRAIN NIGERIANS FOR U.N. DUTY IN SIERRA
LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first American soldiers will arrive in Nigeria
Thursday to train Nigerian troops as peacekeepers for Sierra Leone,
though some contend there are concerns about instructing troops
from an army known for human rights violations that include
executions.
</P>
<P>
   The American soldiers, who are being rushed to Nigeria to be
there when President Clinton arrives for a visit Saturday, will
immediately start training and equipping a Nigerian battalion of
about 800 men, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, several hundred Americans are to train about 3,000
Nigerians, who will then be sent to serve under the United Nations
in Sierra Leone, in the throes of an eight-year civil war where
rebel guerrillas have specialized in chopping off the limbs of
civilian victims.
</P>
<P>
   But because Nigerian troops in Sierra Leone were accused by the
United Nations and human rights groups of executing alleged members
of the rebel Revolutionary United Front and that group's civilian
sympathizers last year, administration officials said they are
aware that training Nigerian soldiers will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration was criticized for its failure
provide support for the U.N. peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone
when, despite a peace pact signed in July 1999 to end the conflict,
peacekeepers ran into trouble against rebels earlier in May. As a
result, the Clinton administration recently decided to help build a
regional force to fight under U.N. command.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's shift has been largely welcomed in Congress
as a sign of backing words of sympathy for Africa with some
military muscle. But some members of Congress have asked how the
American public would react if American-trained Nigerian troops,
using American equipment, commit human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels in Sierra Leone have proven particularly vicious, and
are skilled at using women and children as human shields, making
the task for forces fighting them complex, considering possible
temptations for troops to kill civilians to get to rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A report last year by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan detailed
some abuses by Nigerian troops in Sierra Leone, including the
execution of an 8-year-old boy for possessing a pistol, an
execution at a hospital and other ``summary executions of alleged
rebels or rebel sympathizers.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official who worked on the
decision to send the American troops said that there would be ``a
significant component'' in training the Nigerians that would
emphasize the rules of war. Referring to the Nigerian troops, he
added, ``The aim is not to de-toughen them, but to keep them
legal.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House International Relations Committee,
Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., said he was pleased that the
administration had decided to take an active role against the
rebels. But, he said, ``In the past the R.U.F. has attacked women
and children and used them as human shields. Are we prepared for
the prospect of U.S.-trained and equipped forces facing that
situation?''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that Clinton was not planning to meet
with the American troops in Nigeria. About 14 American soldiers
will arrive Thursday in Nigeria from their base in Germany. The
training will occur near Lagos, officials said, and Clinton will be
in Abuja, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian army's past human rights abuses in Sierra Leone
presented ``a sensitive issue,'' an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fight to save the Sierra Leone capital, Freetown, from
being overrun by the rebels in early 1999, Nigerian troops were
known to have gone on a ``rampage'' when one of their soldiers was
killed, and soldiers had sought revenge by killing civilians, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon acknowledged the need to make training in human
rights a part of the mission, the official said, and one of the
most important elements in the American training would be to
instill discipline in the Nigerian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council recently strengthened the mission of
the peacekeepers in Sierra Leone, which should help define the
military goals of the Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian troops chosen to be trained by the Americans are
being closely monitored to weed out soldiers who have violated
human rights, another administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations will monitor the soldiers' activities in
Nigeria, but the senior U.N. representative in Sierra Leone,
Oluyemi Adeniji, is a Nigerian. That could make it difficult to get
unbiased assessments of the Nigerian soldiers, a State Department
official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
