<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-865&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `SURVIVOR' COUNTS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 14 weeks in which it became not only a huge television
hit, but also a real cultural phenomenon, ``Survivor,'' the CBS
summer reality program, comes to an end Wednesday night with a
special, two-hour finale.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday evening's program, one of the four contestants
who still remain in the competition on the Southern Pacific island
of Pulau Tiga will survive a vote by his or her island compatriots
to win a $1 million prize.
</P>
<P>
   The final episode of ``Survivor'' will be the culmination of a
stunning run in which it smashed ratings records, drew an audience
much younger than the one CBS normally does and turned many of its
original 16 castaways into stars. It has also launched a host of
imitators that are to be shown on other networks.
</P>
<P>
   As its castaways competed with each other under harsh island
conditions in which they dodged snakes, ate rats and bugs and built
their own shelters, ``Survivor'' became one of the few programs
that tens of millions of people made a point of being home for.
</P>
<P>
   Considering competition from the Internet and cable, that is a
rare feat for television, let alone during the lazy days of summer,
when viewing levels are at their lowest.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, ``Survivor'' was the most-watched series to be
shown during the summer in television history. Since its May 31
debut, it has been watched by a weekly average of 24.5 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Its audience has steadily grown. The first episode was watched
by 15.5 million people. Last Wednesday, ``Survivor'' was watched by
28.7 million. That episode's household audience was 23 percent
larger than the combined household audience of its five broadcast
network competitors combined. For CBS, the show's household rating
was more than double the one for an episode of ``Martial Law'' that
ran during the same time period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor's'' ratings have even dwarfed last summer's ratings
of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the ABC game show with Regis
Philbin as host that took the television world by surprise last
August by drawing an average audience of 14.3 million people. (Now
`Millionaire' draws close to 20 million viewers on a regular
basis.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS would not estimate how large its audience would be Wednesday
night. But the program is widely expected to draw its largest
audience yet. That expectation has allowed CBS to sell 30-second
advertisement spots for $600,000 each, more than those on ``ER,''
NBC's top-rated hospital drama.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS is apparently doing all it can to ensure that the
sponsors of Wednesday night's finale are not disappointed, with
much of today's schedule devoted to the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' will factor heavily in the ``Early Show,'' with
Bryant Gumbel as host, and CBS's ``Late Show With David
Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 p.m., CBS will run a half-hour ``Survivor'' preview
special on many of its owned and affiliated stations. The
``Survivor'' finale will itself be shown from 8 to 10 p.m. It will
be followed by a one-hour special in which Gumbel will interview
the 16 original contestants.
</P>
<P>
   That Gumbel will be host of the special reflects the show's
phenomenal status. Gumbel is an employee of CBS News, yet
``Survivor'' is managed by CBS's entertainment division.
</P>
<P>
   Girding for criticism that CBS is blurring the line between
entertainment and news, executives pointed out that plot twists
were being treated as legitimate news by other media organizations
throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's role in the program has raised some eyebrows within CBS
News as well as in other network news divisions, especially because
the special is being directed by the two men who direct his morning
program. What's more, it is being produced by a former producer of
``Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has often been featured by ABC's ``Good Morning
America'' and NBC's ``Today'' and has been the focus of the covers
of Time and Newsweek. Some newspapers have followed developments on
the program the way they would any other news.
</P>
<P>
   ``News is partly what interests people, and you can't be above
the news,'' said Steve Friedman, the executive producer of Gumbel's
``Early Show.'' ``This is what America's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Early Show,'' a production of CBS News, has seen its own
ratings fortunes grow along with those of ``Survivor'' by
interviewing contestants and running features on the program.
Wednesday morning it will again focus heavily on ``Survivor,'' with
profiles of the remaining contestants and a recap of the program's
highlights. Tuesday's ``Early Show'' also included segments about
``Survivor,'' including one in which a professional social planner
doled out advice for those who are giving parties celebrating the
program's finale.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that ``Survivor'' has been able to hold that kind of
audience interest is because the identity of the winner has been
closely guarded and has not leaked to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 contestants who initially began competing on the
island, four are left. They are: Richard Hatch, 39, a corporate
trainer from Rhode Island; Kelly, 23, a white-water guide from Las
Vegas; Rudy Boesch, 72, a retired Navy Seal; and Susan Hawk, 38, a
truck driver from Wisconsin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   CBS had hoped to build on ``Survivor's'' success with ``Big
Brother,'' another reality show in which contestants are forced to
cope with each other in a fabricated house. As in ``Survivor,''
contestants vote each other off the program. The last person
remaining when the program concludes next month will collect a cash
prize of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not enjoyed comparable success. Although it has often
done better for CBS than other shows that have run during its time
periods a year ago _ especially among younger people _ it is in no
way considered a runaway hit. ``Big Brother'' has been criticized
for lacking the sort of personal dynamics featured in ``Survivor,''
which is often praised by critics for a good mesh of strong
personalities, including Hatch, the corporate trainer who openly
plots with fellow contestants and has paraded on the beach naked.
</P>
<P>
   `Nightly News' Change
</P>
<P>
   NBC News has named a new executive producer for ``Nightly News
with Tom Brokaw,'' which had been without one last month when David
Doss departed for what were said to be opportunities in new media.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw's new producer is Jonathan Wald, who was the senior
producer for the program. It is said that Wald has news in his
blood. His father is Richard C. Wald, a longtime senior vice
president at ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Wald is taking over at a good time for the program,
which has been gaining against its closest competitor, ABC News'
``World News Tonight.'' For the week of August 14-18, the NBC
program was watched by 9.65 million people and the ABC program by
8.2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
