<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVOKING SUFFRAGISTS, MRS. CLINTON COURTS FEMALE VOTERS UPSTATE 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also NY-LAZIO-STOCKS, NY-MRSCLINTON-ADBOX) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Invoking the legacy of the suffragists at
every turn, Hillary Rodham Clinton sought Tuesday to portray
herself as a champion of women and working families and to bolster
her support in this city, where Susan B. Anthony once fought for
the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the Democratic Senate candidate, toured Anthony's
red-brick home, boasted of her own efforts to promote women's
issues like breast cancer and child care, and even appeared with
Ruth Dyk, 99, who once marched alongside the suffragists and
likened Clinton to them. ``If I've learned one thing, it's this:
New York needs a woman's touch,'' Dyk said while endorsing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In her latest campaign swing through this key electoral county,
Clinton seemed determined to show female voters that she was their
candidate. At a meeting with union members, she said she was a
working mother like many of those in the room. ``I know what it's
like when you have to worry about whether or not you're going to
make it to that school play because you're in one of those
interminable meetings,'' she said to laughter and clapping.
</P>
<P>
   Some polls have shown Clinton in trouble with various pockets of
female voters, particularly white women, and she has sought out
issues to shore up support. At the same time, her Republican
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, has aggressively pursued these same
groups of voters. Just last week, for example, he visited the
Women's Rights National Historic Park in Seneca Falls, the
birthplace of the women's suffrage movement.
</P>
<P>
   Although she never mentioned Lazio by name, Clinton Tuesday
repeatedly tried to distinguish herself by stressing her plan for
economic development in upstate New York and her support of issues
traditionally important to women, like education and health care.
She also advocated a woman's right to choose an abortion, and
further pledged that she would never vote to confirm a judge who
would try to make abortion illegal. ``I want you to know my
opponent does not have the same view of reality, the same vision of
the future, the same positions on the issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also supports the right to an abortion but is opposed to a
form of late-term abortion called partial birth by opponents and is
against public financing for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's efforts to focus on substantive issues,
several women continued to bring up personal details about
President Clinton's extramarital affair in the White House that led
to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lowenstein, a registered nurse, said that she intended to
vote for the first lady but that many of her female friends would
not. ``I think the issue is the problems with Bill,'' she said. ``I
think, unfortunately, some women can't forgive her for not leaving
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Bredes, director of the Susan B. Anthony Center for Women's
Leadership at the University of Rochester, said that Clinton's
candidacy might make some women uncomfortable because it reflects
their own struggles to be both leaders and nurturers in a modern
world.
</P>
<P>
   And while Clinton was surrounded by a number of women Tuesday,
some of her most effusive supporters were men.
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Noto, a retired railroad worker, could not wait to line
up at the Marketplace Mall to shake her hand. ``She's a strong
woman, because she stuck by him,'' he said. ``A lot of people
wouldn't have had the courage and the strength. I told her that
four years from now, I'll vote for her for the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0381 </DOCNO>
