<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HACKETT-PATERNO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL HACKETT FINALLY BEAT PATERNO?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ The last time USC coach Paul Hackett faced Joe
Paterno was the last time he saw Paterno face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   It was eight years ago in State College, Penn., and the Nittany
Lions had just thumped Hackett's University of Pittsburgh team
57-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our butt,'' Hackett said. ``Simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   But things are never quite that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any coach in the country that wouldn't
be upset when you lose to a big rival,'' said USC director of
football administration Larry Petroff, an assistant to Hackett at
Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   That 1992 blowout is remembered as a symbolic final straw for
Pitt fans. Hackett was fired by Pitt shortly afterward, and the
Panthers fell off Penn State's schedule for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett says he isn't worried about flashbacks when USC
faces Penn State on Sunday in the Kickoff Classic. He believes he
has a fighting chance against the coaching legend this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett met Paterno three times in the heated Pitt-Penn State
rivalry and lost three times. But in all of those meetings, Hackett
felt like the junior varsity coach against the varsity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were far better than we were,'' Hackett said. ``He's the
king, because he's beaten everybody's butt for a long time. But all
three of my teams (at USC) were better than any of those Pitt
teams. It's a different time and place.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about all Hackett wants to say about his former nemesis.
While at Pitt, he never felt he had a chance on or off the field.
The fact more Pittsburgh-area players chose Penn State over their
hometown team was a source of frustration for Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Pittsburgh, there are more Penn State graduates than Pitt
graduates,'' Petroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the game was played at home, Hackett didn't feel as if
he had an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game was played in Pitt, the crowd was like 50-50,''
Hackett said. ``It's a huge rivalry so it's more than just a game.
And what's always painful for Pitt is watching those people play
for Penn State who are players from the Pittsburgh area.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all forgotten, Hackett insists. This week, Hackett
stresses the Kickoff Classic is about ``the players, not Joe
Paterno.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to believe that he wouldn't gain an extra measure
of satisfaction from beating Paterno at least once in his coaching
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a very good relationship,'' said ESPN college
football analyst Beano Cook, who has lived in Pittsburgh for 46
years. Joe Paterno is sanctimonious. With Paterno, he had
everything going his way. Pitt was going through what they do every
so often. Hackett was a little over his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paterno likes to lecture all the other schools. Coaches do not
like coaches who are sanctimonious.''
</P>
<P>
   As proof, Cook cites Penn State's 12-0 season in 1994, in which
the Nittany Lions didn't even earn a share of the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches didn't want to vote for him,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hackett has not spoken to Paterno in eight years, he
was briefly miffed last season when Penn State refused to send USC
tapes of its game with Arizona, a common courtesy between schools
that are scheduled to meet.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Hackett has discovered how difficult it is to obtain
information on the Nittany Lions, who are secluded in Happy Valley,
away from the press and pretty much anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the last school in the country that doesn't get
scrutinized,'' Cook said. ``They've got a docile press west of
Philadelphia. They're rooters as much as journalists. It's really
the last media in the country that's as much rooters as
reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a contrast to USC's practices at UC Irvine, where
fans can walk up and watch workouts on the campus' wide-open
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always the way he's been. He runs a tight boat and we
should take a lesson. We all can learn from that,'' Hackett said.
``He's been doing what he's doing for a long, long time. But we
also think it's important to allow our fans to come to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The seclusion of Penn State, which is about 80 miles northwest
from the state capitol of Harrisburg and 120 miles east of
Pittsburgh, definitely makes it easier for Paterno to answer
questions on his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Hackett on Tuesday, he said, ``I think he was a very
good coach at Pitt but wasn't there long enough to have the impact
on the program he could have had. Paul's a very innovative coach
and has been his whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   That qualifies as an in-depth interview around State College.
</P>
<P>
   But Petroff, who was Pitt's recruiting coordinator, said it's a
misconception that Paterno is resented because of his stature or
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're battling against him in recruiting and on the
field, you can get that feeling,'' Petroff said, ``but coaches I
know that know him think he's a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So will it be any more special if Hackett gets to shake
Paterno's hand as the winning coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. This team needs to go back and win for this program,''
Hackett said. ``Joe Paterno is the opponent, but he is not the
issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
