r k BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CLINTON PARDON WOULD BEST SERVE NATION(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ROBERT ROBB(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - While the presidential candidates debate the future,
whoever wins may find that he must first close a chapter on the
past by pardoning President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The disquieting disclosure last week that a new grand jury has
been impaneled in the Clinton-Lewinsky affair felt like a new act
in a Greek tragedy that just will not end.
</P>
<P>
   This is not, however, prosecutors run amok, as the Clintonites
would have us believe. From the beginning, prosecutors have just
been doing their job, as defined by the courts and the Department
of Justice. And it will be hard for Clintonites to pin the partisan
Starr on new independent counsel Robert Ray, who until recently was
a registered Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is assumed to be still investigating whether Clinton
committed perjury. Based upon the public record, it would certainly
seem that he did. You don't even have to get into the dirty details
of what precisely Clinton did with and to Lewinsky, and whether it
fit the definition of sexual relations he was handed, to reach that
conclusion. The man said he could not remember being alone with the
woman, for gawd's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Ray has apparently decided that he has to wait until Clinton
leaves office to prosecute him. But if the evidence so dictates, he
has no choice but to proceed. That's his job.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ray has not closed this and all other open matters when
the next president takes office, whoever it is should pardon Bill
and Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The primary objection to such a pardon is that no man should be
above the law. But the entire purpose of giving the president and
the state governors pardon and clemency authority is to change the
course and outcome of criminal proceedings. Those who believe that
the law should always run its course should be advocating that
these powers be stripped. But, of course, there is no movement to
do that.
</P>
<P>
   The president and state governors are given the power to pardon
and grant clemency when, in their sole and unreviewable judgment,
either justice or a larger public purpose require it.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Clintons, the case for a pardon is justified
in some small part by the former, and in strong measure by the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton were simply citizen Clinton, and not President
Clinton, he would not now be under investigation. The Lewinsky
investigation derives from the Whitewater investigation. The feds
went hard after the owners of failed savings and loans and
deep-pocketed developers with defaulted loans to recover federal
losses from deposit guarantees. But the Clintons were minor,
passive investors in Whitewater, and had no deep pockets. And
Whitewater was only a marginal contributor to the failure of the
savings and loan in question. In ordinary circumstances, no federal
attorney would have given the role of the Clintons a second look.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was president, which triggered the execrable
independent prosecutor statute, with its endless resources and a
legal mandate to pull every string to see where it leads. And it
led to the president lying under oath about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason to pardon the Clintons, however, is to serve a
larger national purpose. The Clintons produce an unusual amount of
vitriol within the body politic. The hate of them far exceeds any
rational reaction to what they have done. And there isn't, really,
a pro-Clinton faction any more; there are simply those who hate
those who hate the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal trial of either Clinton would bring the nation to a
boil. Bringing them to justice, given the nature of the charges
that likely would be brought against them, just isn't worth the
price the nation would pay in the process.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Robb at bob.robb(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8472.
His column appears Sundays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Robb &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic
</P>
</TEXT>
