<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ADBOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLINTON AD REVISITS LAZIO-GINGRICH TIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 30-second commercial, called ``Won't See,'' that
the Hillary Rodham Clinton campaign began broadcasting statewide
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: The Clinton Team
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: This is a hard-hitting advertisement from
Clinton's campaign, intended to mock an advertisement Lazio
released last week heralding his record in Congress on housing and
education issues. This one, like Lazio's, opens with white text
against a black screen, with the printed words echoing what the
announcer is proclaiming, to the same patriotic music Lazio
employed. It shifts to a fuzzy, vaguely ominous picture of Lazio
with Newt Gingrich, the former House speaker _ the quality is akin
to that of a bank camera that has captured a bank robbery in
progress. It moves to a photograph of Lazio standing alone, as the
announcer, with a sharp, snide tone, lists votes Lazio cast
against, among other things, federal financing for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``The end to nursing home standards. The largest
education cuts in history. The slashing of Medicare by $270
billion. Who voted for all this? Rick Lazio. Four years as Newt
Gingrich's deputy whip. You won't see that in his ads. And you
won't see his recent votes against investing in 100,000 new
teachers and against guaranteed prescription drug coverage under
Medicare. With Rick Lazio, the more you know, the more you
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The nursing home standards refers to 1995 legislation,
sought by some governors, to eliminate federal control over nursing
homes, handing control to the state. Lazio voted with House
Republicans for the largest tax cuts in education spending imposed
in the nation's history, though Lazio countered Tuesday by saying
that President Clinton had proposed even larger ones. The Medicare
cut is a question of what the definition of the word ``cut'' is:
Democrats call it a flat-out cut, while Republicans, more
accurately, call it a cut in the rate of growth in Medicare
spending. Lazio voted against a Democratic bill to provide
financing for 100,000 more teachers, but voted for a Republican
bill that did pretty much the same thing. He voted against a
Democratic bill that would have provided prescription drug coverage
under Medicare, though he supported a far more limited Republican
bill.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: With this ad, Clinton officially brings Newt
Gingrich, the former House speaker, back into her campaign arsenal.
She had initially invoked him when Lazio got in the race, and then
stopped trying to associate the two after her aides determined that
it was showing no sign of traction. After two months of using
various other attacks on Lazio, Clinton has come back to using
Gingrich as a way of portraying Lazio as conservative. The
advertisement is intended to turn Lazio's voting record, which he
has presented as a way of reminding voters of Clinton's lack of a
voting record, against him, on issues that polls have shown could
be decisive in the campaign ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
