<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEBATES; BUSH BLOOPERS; REFORM'S $12 MILLION QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEBATES: LET'S TALK
</P>
<P>
   In a brief telephone call on Monday, the chairmen of the Bush
and Gore campaigns began tentative negotiations on debates. Chris
Lehane, a spokesman for Al Gore, said the vice president's
chairman, William Daley, former commerce secretary, had spoken with
Donald Evans, an oil entrepreneur and longtime friend of Gov.
George W. Bush. They plan to speak again later this week. Bush has
said he is willing to debate Gore three times, but has not accepted
the dates, sites or formats of the October events proposed by the
bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates. Gore's aides have
said he will accept those debate invitations as well as numerous
others. Daley has asked Alexis Herman, the labor secretary, and
James Johnson, the chairman of Fannie Mae, to help him in
negotiations with the Bush campaign, Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: BUSH BLOOPERS
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, it happens to just about every candidate,
especially after long hours out on the campaign trail. And Monday
night, during a campaign stop in Des Moines, it happened to George
W. Bush. Just about every other sentence he uttered in a 15-minute
speech at a fund-raiser seemed to have a blooper in it. His first
slip of the lip came when he told his audience, ``When we carry
Iowa in November, it'll mean the end of four years of
Clinton-Gore.'' (He meant eight years, of course.) Next, outlining
his trade policy, he promised, ``I will work to end terrors,'' only
to catch himself and hastily make it ``tariffs and barriers.'' His
policy on national security: ``We cannot let terrorists and rogue
nations hold this nation hostile or hold our allies hostile.'' His
audience seemed not to mind the bloopers. He was cheered
repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY: THE $12.6 MILLION QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Asked to referee a Reform Party fight, officials of the Federal
Election Commission are preparing to decide, reluctantly, who
should get $12.6 million in federal presidential campaign funds,
Pat Buchanan or John Hagelin. Both candidates claimed the Reform
mantle at a raucous convention this month that ended with the party
dividing into two factions that nominated separate candidates:
Buchanan to represent the conservatives who have recently flooded
into the party, and Hagelin to represent believers in the kind of
governmental reforms that Ross Perot called for when he founded it.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this week, both men are expected to have formally
applied for the money, and the FEC will rule on each application
separately within 10 days of receiving it. It is possible that both
candidates will be eligible for the money, Darryl Wold, the
commission chairman, said Tuesday. He added, however, that federal
law did not provide any guidance in that regard, and so ``agency
attorneys are now analyzing what should be done in that case.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the six-member commission eventually rules, both sides
say the next stop will probably be in court. In fact, the two
factions are already in litigation. On Tuesday the chairman of the
Buchanan faction, Gerry Moan, sued Hagelin for claiming to be the
party's ``proper'' presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY _ Bakersfield and Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE AND JOE LIEBERMAN _ Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER _ Santa Barbara, Salinas, Santa Cruz, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
