r s BC-GAHOOPS0823-COX     08-22 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAHOOPS0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arrest helps derail Toombs' Georgia hopes
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - Georgia was prepared to accept basketball recruit
John Toombs as a partial qualifier until his arrest early Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs, from Carver High in Columbus, was arrested at McWhorter
Hall on misdemeanor charges of underage possession of alcohol and
simple assault. The dormitory houses mostly student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia announced only hours after Toombs' arrest that he
wouldn't enroll at the school this fall, even though he could have
been admitted as a partial qualifier under SEC rules.
</P>
<P>
   According to a UGA Police report, an officer found Toombs
``covered in blood'' from cuts on his arm. The report said Toombs
was standing in front of a broken window in a dormitory room.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs, 6 feet 10, 250 pounds, was taken to a hospital for
treatment and was later booked in the Clarke County Jail. He was
released on his own recognizance.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Hesprich, a Georgia sophomore from Snellville, was
dismissed from the women's basketball team for her involvement in
the incident. Hesprich had intended to walk on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs, who signed with Georgia April 22, learned over the
weekend that he hadn't scored high enough on the SAT to be admitted
to school as a full-qualifier. He had earned a qualifying SAT score
more than a year ago, but the Educational Testing Service flagged
it because of an excessive increase. Toombs retook the test Aug.
15.
</P>
<P>
   A school official said Tuesday that Georgia had initiated
paperwork to accept Toombs as a partial qualifer. As a partial
qualifer, he could have practiced with the team this season, but
could not play in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That decision is made by the university,'' Georgia athletics
director Vince Dooley said. ``Whether (his arrest) entered into
that or not, I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs was expected to add depth to Georgia's frontcourt. Last
year, Toombs attended Crispus Attucks YouthBuild in York, Pa., a
prep school where he averaged 16 points, 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
