<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HAS FOUR CONTENDERS AT RUNNING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alan Taylor insists that it's business as usual in
the Cal State Northridge backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor - a returning sophomore - is one of four running backs
competing to be the Matadors' starting tailback. Taylor, Bruce
Molock, Terrelus Wright and Matt Hicks - who hasn't practiced yet -
are trying to catch the attention of first-year running backs coach
Daniel Escalera.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no tension back there,'' Taylor said. ``Everybody is
out there having a good time and trying to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Escalera readily discusses the attributes of each running back.
But at some point in the next 10 days, one must be singled out.
CSUN opens the season Sept. 2 at Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Escalera isn't worried about that. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of keeping the door open, so to speak,'' Escalera
said. ``I'm not looking for anybody now. I want to make sure the
guys know the offense. We'll sit down and talk about their
performances based on the scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to make sure the offense is installed and
we're able to execute it. The reps have all been about equal, to
tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as mastering the offense, Taylor probably leads that
category. Taylor saw limited action last season with 141 yards on
32 carries as one of two backups to Jaumal Bradley. Taylor thinks
CSUN could benefit from using more than just one featured back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a real strong backfield and a lot of talented
guys with different running styles,'' Taylor said. ``I think it
will be a stronger part of our offense. Once a defense gets used to
a certain runner, we know we can throw in another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is experienced, quick and changes directions well. He had
the longest run - 27 yards - in Saturday's scrimmage. Molock has
speed and the ability to get up field. Wright is tabbed as a hard
worker who's learning the offense quickly. Hicks, who transferred
from Air Force, is expected to make an impact once his paperwork is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We commented the other day that as a group, the running backs
performed the best in the scrimmage,'' CSUN coach Jeff Kearin said.
''Everybody brings something different to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: The Matadors made it through Saturday's scrimmage
without major injuries. However, defensive lineman Andy Zaldivar is
out with a high left-ankle sprain he suffered Friday and likely
won't play against Air Force. ... Offensive lineman Keith Kincaid
also is nursing a sprained ankle but is expected to return to
practice today. ... Defensive lineman Jason Nicastro sat out
Wednesday with a minor groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Double duty: It's possible quarterback Marcus Brady could punt
for the Matadors - but only in an emergency situation. CSUN should
excel in the special teams department with preseason All-American
Ethan Beck - who averaged 43.4 yards per punt last year. Ruben
Gomez - a transfer from Santa Barbara City College - is the backup
punter, and Brady and kicker Derek Brown practiced punting Tuesday.
Brady hasn't punted since high school but Kearin said he's
qualified to fill in if needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
