<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-RENO-1STLD-WRITE     08-22 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RENO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO AGAIN REJECTS NAMING A PROSECUTOR IN GORE FUND-RAISING
INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 15th graf, But Conrad reminded ... to fix typo in
1997.) 
By NEIL A. LEWIS and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rejecting the recommendation of a top Justice
Department investigator, Attorney General Janet Reno has decided
not to name a special prosecutor to investigate Vice President Al
Gore's political fund-raising activities in 1996, government
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the department's campaign finance unit, Robert J.
Conrad, told Reno in June that she should appoint a special counsel
to investigate whether Gore had been truthful with investigators
about his fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said Tuesday that Reno has apparently sided
with others in the department who have argued against choosing a
special prosecutor, a move that would have given momentum to the
criminal inquiry just as Gore's presidential campaign enters the
final months.
</P>
<P>
   One Justice Department official said that Conrad was alone in
his recommendation. ``No other prosecutor in this matter thought
that there should be a need for a special counsel,'' said the
official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Reno, which may be announced as early as
Wednesday, is the latest chapter in a long-running and often bitter
internal debate in the Justice Department over how to deal with
Gore's role in raising money for the Democratic Party and the
national ticket in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be the third time that Reno has rejected a
recommendation to seek the appointment of a special prosecutor to
investigate Gore. In 1997 and again in 1998, Reno declined to ask a
special federal judicial panel to appoint an independent counsel.
She did so on those occasions over the strong objections of FBI
Director Louis Freeh and several senior Justice Department
officials. Reno also faced pressure to appoint an independent
counsel from Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, a career federal prosecutor from North Carolina who was
appointed last December to lead the Justice Department's campaign
finance unit, made his recommendation after a four-hour interview
with Gore conducted on April 18. It was the fifth time Gore was
questioned under oath about fund-raising issues.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Conrad was dissatisfied with some
of Gore's answers in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's recommendation for the appointment of a special
prosecutor was based on Gore's responses in two areas: a
fund-raising appearance by Gore at a Buddhist temple in California
in April 1996 and fund-raising coffees for Democratic campaign
donors at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the vice president will no longer face a criminal
inquiry comes at an especially good time for the Gore-Lieberman
campaign. Buoyed by his performance at the Democratic convention
last week, Gore leads Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
presidential nominee, in several national polls by margins ranging
from 1 or 2 percentage points to 5 points, even though none is
statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Conrad's recommendation was disclosed in June by
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., Gore decided to release the transcript
of the April interview, saying it demonstrated he had been truthful
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the truth is my friend in this,'' Gore said after
releasing the transcript on June 23. ``The truth, the full truth
and nothing but the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcript showed that Conrad, who posed most of the
questions, was clearly skeptical about some of the responses. And
it demonstrated that Gore bristled at some questions and showed
flashes of anger at others.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the interview, Gore insisted that the 103 coffee
sessions with campaign donors held at the White House in 1995 and
1996 were not ``fund-raising tools'' used to raise money for the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Conrad reminded Gore that an inquiry in 1997, found that
those at the coffees from November 1995 to October 1996 contributed
a total of $7.7 million within one month of having attended them.
</P>
<P>
   During the questioning, Gore also said that he thought he had
attended only one of the coffee sessions. The Senate panel reported
that he had played host at 23 coffees and attended eight with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   When Conrad confronted the vice president with that
contradictory information, Gore said, ``That seems inaccurate to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, who was assisted in the interview by two FBI agents,
devoted most of the time to Gore's understanding of the principal
purpose of the Buddhist temple event.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad asked Gore about numerous memorandums from aides
suggesting that it was widely known that the April 29, 1996, event
at the Hsi Lai Temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif., was intended to
raise money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were aware in late February, were you not, that there was
a goal of raising $108 million by the DNC?'' Conrad asked,
referring to the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Gore replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a couple of months later there is a DNC-sponsored event
at the temple, and it didn't raise any fund-raising issues in your
mind?'' Conrad went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know this was a fund-raiser,'' Gore replied.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seemed to bristle at the line of questioning, snapping at
one point, ``I sure as hell don't recall having _ I sure as hell
did not have any conversations with anyone saying this is a
fund-raising event.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the interview, Gore inadvertently referred to the
temple luncheon as a ``fund-raiser.'' The vice president's personal
lawyer, James F. Neal, quickly advised Gore that he had misspoken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
