u s BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     08-22 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' RALLY IS WASTED AGAINST RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees and the Boston Red Sox have become like an
old married couple; the longer their race goes on, the more they
resemble each other. Every time the Yankees lose, it seems, so do
the Red Sox, and when the Yankees win, so do the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees just cannot seem to divorce themselves in the
American League East from the Red Sox. Their lead over Boston
remained at three games after they lost to the Texas Rangers, 5-4,
at Yankee Stadium Tuesday night and Boston was an 11-4 loser to
Anaheim at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro broke a 4-4 tie with a home run in the eighth
inning off Denny Neagle after the Yankees came back from a 4-0
deficit. John Wetteland pitched a perfect ninth for the save
against his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees won on Aug. 4; Boston did, as well. Each team
lost the next three games. The Yankees lost on Aug. 18 and the Red
Sox won, but the next day, the Yankees won and Boston lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Red Sox have had the same result on 13 of 18
days since Aug. 4, their records almost identical: Yankees 10-9,
Red Sox 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 4-0 before they even batted Tuesday night, the
Yankees tied the game with three runs in the sixth and one in the
seventh. Having thrown 119 pitches, the left-handed Neagle went out
to start the eighth inning and fell behind the left-handed-hitting
Palmeiro two balls and no strikes before Palmeiro launched a high
drive to right.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill backed against the wall, looked up, only to see
Palmeiro's 32nd homer carry over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle struggled with his mechanics in the first inning, often
pausing after bad pitches to repeat what his motion should have
been, how his right shoulder is supposed to turn or how he should
release his changeup. He fell behind in the count, kept getting the
ball up in the strike zone and generally needed his defense to bail
him out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees outfielders only hurt Neagle in the first
inning. Texas had runners at first and third with one out when
Palmeiro laced a line drive to center field, where Clay Bellinger
has been filling in capably for the injured Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinger came in on the ball unsteadily as it fell in front of
him _ and then it skipped quickly past him, rolling almost to the
center-field fence. Both runners scored and Palmeiro reached third.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler pulled a hit to left-center to drive home Palmeiro,
and when left fielder Luis Polonia took a cautious route after the
ball, Kapler hustled into second base. Kapler subsequently scored
when Ricky Ledee pulled a single through the infield.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' 4-0 lead appeared insurmountable early because Rick
Helling was dominating the Yankees, throwing only 40 pitches in the
first four innings, retiring 17 consecutive batters after Polonia
doubled to lead off the first.
</P>
<P>
   There were two outs and nobody on in the Yankees' sixth, nothing
happening. But Polonia crushed a homer over the right-field wall,
waking the crowd. Derek Jeter walked and O'Neill hit a line drive
to right, the ball requiring about 1.1 seconds to reach the
screaming fans, the Yankees' 22nd home run in their last 10 games.
Three batters, three runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees resumed their comeback in the seventh, Tino Martinez
dumping a double into left-center and eventually scoring on Luis
Sojo's double to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees loaded the bases with two out. Tim Crabtree relieved
Helling and fell behind Jeter three balls and one strike. But
Crabtree came back, throwing a fastball past Jeter's swing to keep
the game tied at 4-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
