<HEADER>
A9436 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WESTERN-FIRES-SPI &LR;      08-22 2010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-FIRES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORST FIRE SEASON IN YEARS FUELS DEBATE ON FORESTRY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT McCLURE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WENATCHEE _ Blame Smokey Bear. Blame the U.S. Forest Service.
Blame the timber industry. Blame environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of blame to go around as the West sizzles
through its worst fire season in decades.
</P>
<P>
   And now the public faces some difficult choices in a
long-contentious debate. After nearly a century of mismanagement,
millions of acres of federally owned forests are dangerously full
of sick, spindly trees in unnaturally thick stands. Over the years,
federal investigators concluded in 1999, fires feeding on these
manmade forests have grown ``increasingly unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it: The cataclysmic blazes that charred
over 5 million acres this year _ plus another 25 million over the
past decade _ are no mere act of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncontrollable wildfire should be seen as a failure of land
management and public policy,'' the National Commission on Wildfire
Disasters warned. ``The fire situation will become worse rather
than better unless there are changes in land management... at all
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1994, the same year that the cocoa-colored hills here
by Wenatchee, at the eastern edge of the Cascades in central
Washington, got mauled by some monster fires.
</P>
<P>
   Those blazes taught a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   They are proving this year to be a forerunner of the
conflagrations raging across 10 states. Now managers of the
Wenatchee National Forest are striving to set things right with
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been successful in doing the right things,'' said Sonny
O'Neal, supervisor of the Wenatchee National Forest. ``We just
haven't been able to do them on a large enough scale.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an arduous and expensive job that researchers say must be
taken on across the West. They say it will take decades _ and that
it must start right now.
</P>
<P>
   As she lay in bed one night in 1994, Christine Mallon was
bothered by the weird red glow over a distant ridgeline.
</P>
<P>
   The reddish cast to the night sky came from a day-old fire near
her home some 15 miles north of Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is eerie,'' she recalls now of the hellish halo caused by
1994's Tyee Creek fire. ``It draws your attention.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, as the blaze descended on the Mallon household, the
family grabbed a few precious items _ photo albums, a guitar,
hard-to-replace tractor parts _ stashed them in the root cellar and
sped away, hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, the fire would singe more than 200 square
miles, making it the biggest blaze in Washington in six decades. It
disgorged walls of flame that approached the height of the Space
Needle, sent columns of smoke as high as the cruising altitude of
some airliners, generated hurricane-force winds that snapped off
treetops. It spawned fire ``tornadoes'' that tossed embers a
half-mile or more, sparking more flames.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighting cost $44 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The Mallon home wasn't among them. In the years before the Tyee
Creek fire, the Mallons had cleared out many of the dinky trees
around their house and pruned lower branches on those that
remained. They removed fuel from the forest floor. An intentional,
highly controlled ``prescribed burn'' by Forest Service workers
finished the job.
</P>
<P>
   On a small scale, they had done what the Forest Service needs to
do on a massive scale. And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire break worked to textbook perfection,'' Mallon
recalls. ``The fire was (burning treetops) and when it got to the
fire break (around her home), it went to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tyee Creek fire sprang from the very same pattern that
foresters say still endangers more than nearly 40 million acres of
low-elevation forests across the West:
</P>
<P>
   First, starting in the 1800s, the really big trees were taken by
loggers. Most of these were fire-resistant ponderosa pines.
</P>
<P>
   In their absence, sunlight penetrated to more of the forest
floor. Many more trees sprouted. Quite a few were firs, which are
less resistant to fire.
</P>
<P>
   Then, early last century in the face of blazes that killed
hundreds of people and wiped out billions of board-feet of timber,
the U.S. Forest Service adopted an unyielding policy: Extinguish
all fires as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   What this strategy ignored is that some forests need fire.
</P>
<P>
   The low-elevation forests of the interior West grew for
millennia with blazes occurring every 10 to 15 years, on average.
Those fires killed off small trees. They consumed dead needles, old
decaying limbs and other fuel that accumulated on the forest floor.
They killed off saplings struggling to grow among the giant pines,
but left the older and more resilient trees alive.
</P>
<P>
   Today's blazes are different. In a forest where flames have been
unnaturally excluded, fire behaves in a whole different way.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1900s, many forest patches grew incredibly thick with
trees, all competing with each other for sunlight, nutrients and
water. Most, like half-starved humans, are a little unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Where you might have found 30 or 40 trees to an acre at the turn
of the century _ each two feet or more in diameter _ today you'll
see between 200 and 300 trees with an average width of perhaps five
inches.
</P>
<P>
   Because fire has been kept out of the forest for so long, the
forest floor is littered with fuel. The groundfire burns long and
hot.
</P>
<P>
   As it moves through the overcrowded, sickly forests, the blaze
engulfs the lower trunks of the thin trees, climbs up their limbs
and finally shoots out their crowns, killing the forest. In the
original forests, most fires bolted through quickly at ground
level.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what happened at the Mallon home in 1994. Ditto for
a section of woods up Mud Creek from there, where the Forest
Service had done thinning and burning work across a thin stretch of
forest. Today, an aerial photo shows a sliver of green running
through acres of trees that look like spent matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good stewardship,'' Mallon concludes, ``doesn't mean don't
touch it. Using a chainsaw isn't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Hoffman looks around: Charred stumps. Blackened tree
trunks. The brown needles of a dead ponderosa pine.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Hoffman is pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The district ranger for the Lake Wenatchee and Leavenworth
disticts of the Wenatchee National Forest also sees deer tracks,
rodent burrows with fresh trails and a raven swooping through the
open forest.
</P>
<P>
   Just 15 months ago, following selective removal of some trees,
this once-overcrowded forest was burned by Forest Service crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of trying to dismantle the risk,''
Hoffman explains. ``It's like there's a time bomb, and the clock is
ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the two districts he supervises, Hoffman figures, some
135,000 acres are counted as dangerously overcrowded.
</P>
<P>
   So far he has managed to work through a cumbersome approval
process to thin 14,000 acres and burn 6,000 acres. Hoffman ticks
off a list of the checkpoints he must satisfy for each project:
Will it harm endangered species? Has the public had an adequate
chance to comment? Will the smoke violate the Clean Air Act?
</P>
<P>
   In several cases here, Forest Service plans to reduce forest
fuel loads were halted by environmentalists who _ like many across
the West _ support the concept but don't trust the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   One factor is administrative. The cash-strapped Forest Service
has trouble paying for the thinning work. But timber companies will
actually pay to do the work if enough large trees can be removed.
However, as federal auditors pointed out last year, that defeats
the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sweeten the pot with big trees to entice the big timber
corporations,'' says Pat Rasmussen of Leavenworth Audubon Adopt A
Forest, who has challenged plans for several timber cuts around
Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   In a backcountry area call Devil's Gulch, Rasmussen says, she
took the Forest Service plans and hiked up to the area to be
``thinned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they had circled to do `thinning' was more of these
clumps with huge ponderosa pine trees,'' she recalls. ``We put up a
big fight... They were planning to take a whole bunch of really big
trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service spokesman Al Matecko said environmentalists
sometimes have been right on this count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dispute that,'' he said. ``That has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, fire ecologists say, some ``zero-cut'' groups
have challenged timber sales that, on balance, would have proved
helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Timber interests, for their part, would like to get more work in
the woods. The problem: Many or even most of the trees that need to
be removed to end catastrophic wildfires have little or no
commercial value. They argue for more thinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake we made wasn't to suppress fire,'' said Chris West
of the Northwest Forestry Association. ``But because we were
removing fire from the ecosystem, we needed to do a better job at
removing the fuel loads.''
</P>
<P>
   James Agee, a University of Washington researcher and leading
fire ecologist, says both the timber industry and environmentalists
share some of the blame for today's mess.
</P>
<P>
   For environmentalists, ``It's a simple message and it's been
very successful in fundraising _ demonize the timber industry,''
Agee said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in surveying loggers' work, ``I've seen what
they call `forest health' cuts that did not do what they were
supposed to... (creating) land that, after they got done with it,
looked worse than before from a fire standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   All involved agree that before the Forest Service can do this
job, it will have to win back public trust.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help any when the prescribed fire near Los Alamos
swirled out of control in the spring, grabbing national headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue is heating up politically. Presidential candidate
George W. Bush, House Speaker Dennis Hastert and other Republicans
have accused the Clinton administration of failing to allow enough
logging.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials respond that the crisis comes
from decades of mismanagement. It will take decades of bipartisan
effort to fix, they say.
</P>
<P>
   And environmentalists point out that the vast majority of this
year's fires happened in areas that were previously logged, not in
pristine backcountry wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as the mid-1980s, national forests' plans were
geared mostly to satisfy timber companies by allowing them to take
big logs, said Bob Freimark, northwest director of The Wilderness
Society and a trained forester.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not rocket science. They wanted the big trees and they
wanted a higher level of them,'' he said. ``They were continuing
the strategy that got us into the situation where we are today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even under the current schedule for making forests safer, 10
million acres will remain at high risk of fire by 2015, the General
Accounting Office projected last year.
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators quoted fire ecologists' warnings from the
early 1990s that there was a window of only 10 to 25 years left
before ``widespread, long-term damage from such fires occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Senate has included $240 million in next year's
proposed budget, up from $70 million this year. And after President
Clinton's visit to see fires in Idaho earlier this month, his
administration started work on a new package that is bound to ask
for even more.
</P>
<P>
   Doing nothing also would prove expensive. In just eight years,
firefighting costs increased from average of $134 million a year in
1986 to $335 million a year in 1994. As of Tuesday, officials
reported they were spending about $16 million a day on firefighting
costs.
</P>
<P>
   It was only three decades after the Forest Service instituted
its no-burn policy that some foresters began questioning its
wisdom, said the UW's Agee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known about this for 60 years,'' he said, ``but it's
taken essentially 60 years of watching that old policy fall apart
to recognize that we went the wrong way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT &LR;      08-22 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO HOW BAD WERE METS? EVEN BELL GOT TO PITCH
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The first pitch came in at 47 mph, looping like a
rainbow, and Joe Vitiello let it go by. This was a pitcher he had
never seen before _ nobody in professional baseball ever had _ and
there was no scouting report.
</P>
<P>
   The next pitch came in at 78, also for a ball, and then Vitiello
looked at a strike. With a 3-1 count, he could not resist a 79-mph
heater, pulling it down the left field line, just foul. Finally,
ball four came in at 66 mph. Say this for Derek Bell, the Mets'
mop-up man in a 16-1 loss to the San Diego Padres: He knows how to
change speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Bell allowed five runs in the bottom of the eighth inning,
although one of them was unearned, coming when catcher Todd Pratt
dropped a pop-up. When Vitiello popped up to end the inning, Bell
lifted his cap to the Qualcomm Stadium fans, who saluted him. It
was absurd, and appropriate for a crazy day at the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, an outfielder, became only the third position player ever
to pitch for the Mets. As bad as his inning was _ five runs, three
hits, three walks _ Pat Mahomes had two that were worse. Bell
needed 36 pitches to get through the eighth; Mahomes needed 34 in
allowing five runs in the second, and 43 in giving up five more in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo and Mike Piazza had the day off, and Bell _
another starter _ was also supposed to. The game became a lost
cause early.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the fourth inning, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
started pulling the starters who did crack the lineup. Robin
Ventura and Mike Bordick hit the bench. The Padres just hit,
period. San Diego, last in the National League West, has won six of
eight games this year against the wild card-leading Mets.
</P>
<P>
   No Mets starter in three years had allowed 10 runs in a start,
but Mahomes did Tuesday, and his performance spiraled out of
control in a hurry. With two outs and two runners on in the second,
Mahomes walked catcher Wiki Gonzalez to bring up the pitcher, the
rookie Adam Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   But Eaton is a good hitter, the only pitcher in the National
League with 30 at-bats and a .300 average, and he fouled off two
pitches with a 2-2 count. Mahomes lost the battle, walking Eaton to
force in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Dave Wallace came to the mound. Mahomes threw a
high fastball to Damian Jackson. Jackson pounded it into the
left-field bleachers for a grand slam. Padres 5, Mets 0, and more
to come.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, after Bordick had singled home a Mets run, Mahomes
walked leadoff man Ryan Klesko. The next batter, Phil Nevin,
launched a pitch into the second deck at Qualcomm Stadium, a perch
reached only by Mark McGwire this season and by just 14 Padres in
the stadium's 32-year history.
</P>
<P>
   One batter later, John Mabry whacked a ball into the second deck
in right field, the first hit to land there in the four years since
that deck was built. It was 8-1, and Mahomes still had a few
extra-base hits to allow. Ruben Rivera, Gonzalez and Eaton, the
pitcher, doubled in succession to bring in two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes allowed 10 runs on seven hits, walking five in four
innings; he has 57 walks in 80 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, who left his start last Thursday with a stress
fracture in his right ribs, threw on flat ground Tuesday and will
do so again on Wednesday. He will throw a bullpen session on
Friday, and while the Mets have no plans to put him on the disabled
list, General Manager Steve Phillips said, they also are not sure
when he will start again. In the meantime, the Mets' bullpen will
be thin.
</P>
<P>
   After Mahomes left, Turk Wendell pitched the fifth, John Franco
the sixth and Armando Benitez the seventh. The two remaining
relievers _ Rick White, who was used as a pinch-hitter, and Dennis
Cook, who had worked two innings in losing Monday's game _ were
unavailable. The Mets were out of pitchers, and Bell started
warming in the right field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Bell pitched in the final game of the Little League World Series
for his Tampa, Fla., team, but he had never pitched in professional
baseball. Only three times in their history had the Mets used a
position player as a pitcher: Last season, on July 2 and Aug. 8,
when Matt Franco pitched against Atlanta and Los Angeles, and on
Sept. 26, 1992, when Bill Pecota pitched against Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
