<SLUG> BC-`SURVIVOR'-WHO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL BE REALITY SHOW'S SOLE SURVIVOR?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the night we get our lives back.
</P>
<P>
   That's an exaggeration, of course _ it only seems like
``Survivor,'' CBS' phenomenally popular ``reality'' game show, has
dominated our lives since its May 31 debut on CBS. Really, most
people have lost only 12 hours _ less, if they taped the show and
fast-forwarded through the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But the show reaches its two-hour finale Wednesday night, and an
hourlong reunion of the 16 ``Survivor'' contestants follows, as CBS
devotes its entire prime-time lineup to the show of the summer.
This is when the show provides, to paraphrase another game show,
its final answer to the question: Who outplayed, outwitted and
outlasted the other contestants and scored a million bucks?
</P>
<P>
   Many of you may say the show never affected you at all _ that
you never watched it, and probably never will. Still, you couldn't
avoid it _ the players are on magazine covers, they're on talk
shows, they're making TV deals, they're considering offers to pose
for ``Playboy,'' they're making headlines when they get in trouble
with the law _ they're doing everything but bugging you during
dinner with telemarketing calls.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations imitate the show, and their morning jocks yak
about it the next day. Web sites celebrate the show or denigrate
it, going as far as trying to spoil the ending. TV critics either
sing the show's praises or trash it as junk. Pundits pontificate
about voyeurism, reality TV and their own superiority to those of
us who have been suckered in. TV producers scramble to recapture
the show's magic, in shows like CBS' own ``Big Brother'' and NBC's
upcoming ``Chains of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals protests the show's
rat-eating scenes, advertisers drop $300,000 for a 30-second spot
on the show _ and $600,000 for a spot on the finale, which is
expected to earn CBS $35 million, according to ``Advertising Age.''
And the Nielsen rating service apparently has to reset its dials
every week, as the show averaged nearly 29 million viewers during
last week's episode. The other five networks combined drew only
20.7 million, according to Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   So for the holdouts who haven't jumped on the bandwagon, it's
time to break down and watch the final episode, like some people
only watch the World Series or the Super Bowl. And yet football and
baseball are easier to understand the first time around than
``Survivor,'' and they don't require the cumulative effect that
``Survivor'' needs to draw you in. Watch one episode of
``Survivor,'' and you're embarrassed; watch it over and over, and
you begin to root for certain people and decide which ones are
worms. And if the responses to our ``Survivor'' polls have been any
indication, everyone has picked a different worm.
</P>
<P>
   So let's go over this again, quickly, for the uninitiated. Back
in March, the show's producers dumped 16 people on an island in the
South China Sea, where they were to spend up to 39 days. During a
series of ``immunity challenges'' _ elaborate games of physical and
mental endurance _ and tribal councils, one contestant was voted
off the island every week (the series, based on a Swedish game
show, compressed three days of island living into every episode).
</P>
<P>
   And through the votes, we got to know the players on a
first-name basis. The first two episodes provided the ouster of
Sonja and B.B., both gone in a youthful rebellion against people
over 60; Ramona, who encountered illness, was ejected; competitive
women named Stacey, Gretchen, Jenna and the deceptively sweet
Colleen got bounced; Male contestant Gervase, charming but often
accused of laziness, was removed, along with the eccentric Greg,
the goofy Sean, sexist Joel and religious Dirk.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves four people who _ let's be honest here _ aren't very
nice. Or at least that's the way the show portrays them; former
players have often said that the show was edited to show only their
bad sides. But the four remaining players are Kelly, a duplicitous
23-year-old river guide; Susan, an abrasive 39-year-old truck
driver; Rudy, a grumpy 72-year-old retired Navy SEAL; and the most
Machiavellian of them all, Richard, a scheming 39-year-old
corporate trainer who has become the Survivor whom viewers most
love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the final four face two more immunity
challenges and three tribal councils. During the final tribal
council, the last two ``survivors'' remaining will plead their
cases to a jury made up of the past seven people voted off the
island _ including Wednesday night's two evictees. The jury has
been growing during the most recent episodes, and frankly, they
look a little ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   The winner gets the million bucks, and we get our lives back _
at least until January, when ``Survivor II'' plops another group of
contestants in the Australian Outback. Whether CBS can repeat the
initial ``Survivor's'' success is doubtful _ it resulted from one
of those happy collisions of an empty summer-TV landscape, a unique
premise and a more-charismatic-than-expected ``cast.'' But after
Wednesday night, many of us can say that we survived ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   (This report contains material from the Kansas City Star. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
