<SLUG> BC-AMERITRADE-RUMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERITRADE TAKEOVER RUMORS, POSSIBLY BY AMERICAN EXPRESS, FUEL
SPIKE IN SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is supposed to be the slow season in the online brokerage
business, but this one has not been quiet in Omaha, Neb., the home
of Ameritrade Holding Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, the fifth-largest online brokerage firm, was
contending with a deep slump in its stock price when its new chief
executive, Thomas Lewis, abruptly resigned two weeks ago. Since
then, Ameritrade's stock has been driven up by speculation that the
company will be acquired. That rise accelerated Tuesday, fueled by
a rumor that American Express Co. might buy Ameritrade.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, shares of Ameritrade rose 20 percent, to more
than $19, on the Nasdaq stock market. But without any sign of a
buyout, they dropped back to close at $17.06, up $1.13, or 7
percent, in the heaviest volume in five months.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for American Express and Ameritrade declined to
comment on the speculation, although Dow Jones Newswires reported
that an Ameritrade spokesman had said that the company was not for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were skeptical about the likelihood of an imminent
buyout by American Express, but several have said that they
consider Ameritrade a takeover target, especially in the wake of
Lewis' departure. The company has said little about the
resignation, except to describe the reason for it as personal. J.
Joe Ricketts, the company's founder and chairman, is acting as
chief executive while the company searches for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Appleby, an analyst at Robertson Stephens, said he
considered American Express a possible buyer because it had shown
interest in an another online brokerage, ETrade Group. Neither
American Express nor ETrade would comment on whether they had
discussed a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby said he expected Ameritrade to earn about 85 cents a
share next year. The company's stock is trading at 20 times that
estimate and Appleby said American Express could pay as much as 30
times earnings in a stock-for-stock acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But Appleby said he did not see American Express, a
premium-brand company better known for its charge cards than its
brokerage operation, as an ideal match for Ameritrade, which
heavily advertises its trading commissions, which are as low as $8.
``I would prefer to see consolidation within the industry, rather
than from outside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What American Express and Ameritrade do share is a willingness
to give away stock trades to attract customers. Late last year,
American Express began offering free online stock purchases for
people who keep at least $25,000 in an account. Earlier this year,
Ameritrade quietly matched that offer by creating a separate,
pure-electronic brokerage firm called Freetrade, which does not
charge commissions on some online trades. Both companies are also
running investing contests on their Web sites this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those similarities, some analysts said they thought
Ameritrade was a better fit for a bank or brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm of the opinion that three to five years from now, most
banks, if not all banks, will have some sort of online brokerage
capability,'' said Matthew Vetto, an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``If you're looking for critical mass in a pure-play
broker,'' he said, Ameritrade is the most attractive choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
