<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-SCHOOL-TESTS-NYT &LR;      08-22 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOL-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
NEW JERSEY OFFICIALS TO REVIEW 4TH-GRADE TEST  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey officials released a new round of standardized test
scores Tuesday for public school students in the fourth- and
eighth-grades, but would not disclose the results for fourth-grade
language arts literacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the writing section of the test, students' scores were so low
that the state Education Department's Language Arts Literacy
Assessment Committee will review the test scores and the grading.
</P>
<P>
   In the language arts test as a whole, students appeared to be
able to read and comprehend the material and answer multiple-choice
questions, said David C. Hespe, the state's education commissioner.
But in the writing portion, where students could score from zero to
four points, almost 75 percent scored one point or less on several
items, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few students received a score of three or four on a scale of
zero to four,'' Hespe said. ``This is not what we expected this
year, and it signals a potential problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The test, known as the Elementary School Proficiency Assessment,
was taken by 80,000 fourth-graders during the 1999-2000 school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and administrators have criticized the test, saying it
is too long and its instructions are not always clear.
</P>
<P>
   Some teachers have also expressed concern about the grading of
the tests. The writing portion is scored by Measurement Inc. of
Durham, N.C., whose employees are college graduates but are not
required to have a teaching background.
</P>
<P>
   The department plans to release the language arts scores, with
modifications if necessary, in September.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-grade science scores did not change significantly
from the previous year, with 57.3 students ranked as proficient,
32.3 ranked as advanced proficient and 10.4 percent as partly
proficient, the lowest category. Fourth-grade students improved in
math, with 49.6 percent in the proficient category in the 1999-2000
school year, compared with 47.5 percent in the previous year.
Students in the advanced proficient category rose from 18.2 percent
in 1999 to 21.7 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 75,000 eighth-graders in public schools scored well
in science and language arts, with more than 80 percent scoring in
the proficient or advanced proficient categories. In math, 67.3
percent demonstrated proficiency, scoring in the proficient or
advanced proficient categories, compared with 68.5 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A complete district-by-district breakdown of the scores will be
released in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2319EDT &QL; 
