A9562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-QUAKE-NYT     08-22 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-QUAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR QUAKE GIVES NEW YORK TOWN MAJOR SCARE, BUT NO DAMAGE  
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, N.Y. _ The dogs knew it was coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the night, Michael McDonough's three Maltese
terriers began barking frantically. McDonough, who had been sound
asleep in bed, rolled over and looked at the clock, which said
1:45. And that is when it hit _ an earthquake in the suburbs north
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like thunder, but not quite thunder,'' McDonough said.
``I woke up, looked at the clock, and heard that noise like a bang,
a big, loud bang or a rumble and then a little rumble after that,
and you could feel the house shaking and the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   For miles around Putnam County and across the state line in
Fairfield County, Conn., Tuesday morning's tiny earthquake _ with a
preliminary magnitude of 2.5, according to the National Earthquake
Information Center _ jarred people with a few brief seconds of
terrifying sound and force.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of frightened people called 911, local police
departments or the county sheriff. But officials said Tuesday that
there were no injuries and no reports of damage. Many people
thought their boilers had exploded. Several said they had looked
out a window to see if a car had crashed into their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Buck, who works at the Carmel public library, was
awakened by the jolt. In the fuzziness of sleep, she said to
herself, ``If I didn't know better, I'd think this was an
earthquake.'' Her four daughters, also stirred out of bed, thought
someone was setting off fireworks at a farm down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing of it is, at that time of morning, everybody was
probably kind of asleep,'' said Waverly Person, a geophysicist at
the earthquake center. ``And waking people up, it was probably kind
of frightening, even thought it was what we call a really minor
earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Minor earthquakes are from 3.0 to 3.9,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes are unusual in the New York area, large quakes even
rarer. But numerous small earthquakes have occurred over the years,
including one in 1985 that was 4.0 on the Richter scale, a
measurement of magnitude no longer widely used by seismologists.
Several people who remembered that earthquake said that this one
did not even come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that one,'' said Schweitzer. ``I lived in an
apartment building in Mount Vernon. My dresser danced across my
bedroom in that one. That was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   This quake has been the talk of Carmel, a town of more than
31,000 people that is the Putnam County seat, and of neighboring
towns like Kent and Patterson. The shock was even felt in Danbury,
Conn., about 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a big topic of conversation,'' said Eric Schweitzer,
the night manager of the Carmel Diner Restaurant downtown. ``I went
to the supermarket. Everybody was talking about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0399 </DOCNO>
