A9564 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     08-22 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY LOOKS FOR BIG-GAME VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is a pattern developing over the years that
has Los Angeles Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri concerned.
</P>
<P>
   His team's resume includes two MLS title-game losses and a
setback in the U.S. Open Cup quarterfinals last season.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Galaxy had a chance to draw closer to Western
Division-leading Kansas City at the Rose Bowl but allowed the
Wizards to escape with a 1-1 draw.
</P>
<P>
   Against Chicago on Saturday, the Galaxy had a chance to
strengthen its grip in the MLS playoff race, but the Fire walked
away with a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at Cal State Fullerton, the Galaxy will meet Chicago for
the second time in five days, this time in the U.S. Open Cup
semifinals. Another big loss in a big game is something the Galaxy
needs to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows we've never won a championship, but we get so
close,'' Caligiuri said. ``Again this season, we've shown signs of
not winning the big games when we have had the opportunity. Our
last two against K.C. and Chicago is just another example.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Galaxy wins tonight, it will advance to the U.S. Open Cup
final Oct. 22 against either New York/New Jersey or Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big test,'' Caligiuri continued. ``We want to use
this U.S. Open Cup to change our fans' minds and our minds that we
can win big games and ultimately a championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-NEWARK-ARENA-NYT &LR;      08-22 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-NEWARK-ARENA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR LIMITS AID TO NEWARK ARENA TO $75 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Story is also moving on sports wire.)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ The long-awaited bargaining over state aid for a new
sports arena here has begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gov. Christie Whitman said Tuesday that state and other
taxpayer assistance should not exceed $75 million. That figure is
well below the $123 million in state aid that the YankeeNets, owner
of the New Jersey Nets and New Jersey Devils, has said in recent
weeks is the minimum needed.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the teams' owners have said they would also need
$25 million in aid from the city to relocate from the state-owned
Continental Arena at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The $325 million arena for the two teams is to be built in
downtown Newark; officials hope it will impell the city's
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the Whitman administration's view on the limits of
public contributions, Mike Torpey, her chief of staff, said in a
letter to the YankeeNets owners that any contributions from city
and county government would result in an equal reduction in other
state aid to those municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   But what many characterized in private as a tough opening stand
by the governor, was nevertheless viewed with gratitude in public
by the Newark, Essex County and YankeeNets officials who support
the arena proposal; they applauded it as a first sign of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a step in the right direction, and the right direction
for us is Newark,'' said Harvey Schiller, the chairman and chief
executive of YankeeNets.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe James, the mayor of Newark, said the governor had taken
``a leadership role in keeping professional sports in New Jersey,''
and James Treffinger, the Essex County executive, called Torpey's
letter ``a very positive first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Torpey, in an interview, said the letter set ``the parameters of
further negotiations,'' although he cautioned that the $75 million
in assistance alone was likely to run into trouble in the
Legislature, which he characterized as not eager to support
professional sports complexes in Newark or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was released on the day that the YankeeNets completed
the $176 million purchase of the National Hockey League's New
Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   One of the intentions of the letter from Torpey, said other
officials familiar with the politics of the arena negotiations, was
to serve notice to the YankeeNets that they should not try to use
local elected officials to help wring more money out of taxpayers,
and to confine their negotiations to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Since the New Jersey Nets were acquired three years ago by a
group led by Raymond Chambers the group has hoped to help
revitalize Newark by relocating there. But Whitman had said that
the state would not contribute anything unless the arena had two
sports teams to make it economically viable, a condition that was
met with the acquisition of the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter to the YankeeNets, Torpey held out yet another
opportunity to the two teams to remain at the Meadowlands arena,
saying that the teams could be housed in a new arena there for less
money: $250 million that would include the same $75 million in
state assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no harm in us keeping the alternative of the
Meadowlands on the table,'' he said in an interview. ``But
ultimately they have made it clear that it is their desire to go to
Newark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9567 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HEALTH-KIDS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Texas touts increase in insured children
 &HT;    Critics say state still has a long way to go
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By POLLY ROSS HUGHES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas leads the nation in uninsured children, but a
children's health official told lawmakers Tuesday that it is
catching up faster than other states.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80,000 children _ 17 percent of those eligible in the
state _ have enrolled during the first five months of the
Children's Health Insurance Program, state CHIP director Jason
Cooke told the Texas House Appropriations subcommittee on health
and human services. Of those, 12,500 were from Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five months, that compares very favorably with other
states,'' Cooke said, ``both in terms of where they were after five
months and in terms of how many months it took them to get to where
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with nearly 1.4 million uninsured children in Texas, the
state has much further to go, two Houston Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Census data released in March shows 25.4 percent of the children
in Texas are uninsured compared with 15.4 percent for the nation
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we've actually lost the most ground was kids who were
covered by Medicaid,'' said Eva de Luna, analyst at the
Austin-based Center for Public Policy Priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Medicaid rolls for children have fallen mostly because the
family lost some other kind of public assistance and they thought
that meant Medicaid as well,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, a member of the committee, said
``extreme barriers'' make it hard for families who erroneously fell
off the Medicaid rolls to restart the insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike CHIP, which requires filling out an application and
mailing it in, the poorer families eligible for Medicaid must make
appointments for face-to-face meetings every six months and prove
they don't own a car or have other assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've accomplished our goal until we've enrolled
people who are eligible for Medicaid, which is the lower income
group,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 600,000 children in Texas eligible for Medicaid but
not enrolled in it. The state has enrolled only 2,000 of them
during the last five months, Cooke said.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP is for children of the working poor who do not qualify for
Medicaid. Texas lawmakers in 1999 passed CHIP legislation to cover
children in families that earn up to 200 percent of the federal
poverty level. That's $33,600 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Participating states share the cost of the Children's Health
Insurance Program with the federal government. Texas is using
proceeds from its settlement with the tobacco industry to pay its
share of the program costs.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston on Tuesday, state Sen. Rodney Ellis joined Republican
Harris County Judge Robert Eckels to unveil 400 billboards
promoting CHIP. Ellis said he believes Texas should &UR;  &LR; use its own
funds to increase coverage for children of the working poor who are
not yet eligible for CHIP.
</P>
<P>
   Of the state's 1.4 million uninsured children, about 300,000 are
not covered by either Medicaid or CHIP because their families earn
more than 200 percent of the federal poverty level, state officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to join about 10 other states around the
country to do better than that,'' Ellis said. ``In Texas, because
we have the youngest population of the 50 states, it's incumbent
upon us during the best of times to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooke told lawmakers, however, that the state is making
considerable progress in drawing uninsured children into the
program.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas has 17 percent enrolled in CHIP after five months,
California had 7 percent, Florida 8 percent and Michigan less than
1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile it took California more than twice as long _ 11 months
_ to reach 17 percent of its goal and Florida reached that
percentage after a full year, he added.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
