<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX     08-22 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG BULLPEN, PALMEIRO'S CLUTCH BLAST LIFT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every once in a while, almost out of the blue, the
Texas Rangers put together one of those games that provide, as
Diana Ross used to sing, reflections of the way life used to be.
</P>
<P>
   They'll get a well-pitched game from their starter, a flash or
two of great defense, a clutch hit from one of their big hitters
and, perhaps most importantly, their once dominant relievers will
come in and shut down the other team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got a little bit of all that Tuesday night,
combining it into a 5-4 victory against the New York Yankees at
Yankee Stadium. The victory was only the Rangers' second against
the Yankees this year, but it gave them a reminder of that almost
forgotten feeling of a pennant race and playoff pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we haven't played well all year, but this isn't like
we're running a high school team out there,'' reliever John
Wetteland said. ``We all know what to do. It's a matter of putting
things together. Tonight we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro broke a 4-4 tie with an
eighth-inning home run off Yankees starter Denny Neagle, and
Wetteland closed it out with a 1-2-3 ninth inning. That finished
off 21/3 scoreless innings from the bullpen that started with Tim
Crabtree blowing away Derek Jeter with a full-count fastball with
the bases loaded, two outs and the game tied in the seventh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the key right there,'' Palmeiro said. ``That's the game
right there. If he gets a walk or a hit, we lose that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, coming with nothing but fastballs, got behind 3-1 in
the count before coming back and striking Jeter out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some pretty good battles in the past,'' Crabtree
said. ``That was one of those moments that reflected back to the
last couple of years to being in the playoffs against them. You've
got the game on the line and the stands are really loud. It was a
real exciting atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   One the Rangers once knew but only rarely to get to feel again.
Usually it's on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (trainer) Danny Wheat about that before the
game,'' Wetteland said. ``I've never pitched for myself and I've
never really thought about personal stats and numbers. But
career-wise, August and September are usually my best months, but
that's usually because of the pennant race. It's an intangible you
can't reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   This night appeared to belong to Rick Helling, who gave up a
leadoff double to Luis Polonia in the first, then retired 17
consecutive hitters. Armed with a 4-0 lead, Helling looked
unbeatable. But Polonia got him with a two-out home run in the
sixth, then Jeter walked and Paul O'Neill ripped a two-run shot to
make it a 4-3 lead. Doubles by Tino Martinez and Luis Sojo in the
seventh tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty close to as good as I can pitch for 52/3
innings,'' said Helling, who was helped by some excellent defense
from third baseman Mike Lamb and shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree helped out Helling by striking out Jeter, and then
Palmeiro put the Rangers ahead leading off the eighth with his 32nd
home run of the year. Palmeiro also had two singles and is 6-for-12
in his past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he may be getting into a groove where he really
gets hot,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a few spurts, but they've lasted short,'' Palmeiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers know the feeling. Glimpses of the past usually don't
last long. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-T     08-22 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDS: FIXES SLUG LINE 
STRONG BULLPEN, PALMEIRO'S CLUTCH BLAST LIFT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
