r s BC-OLY-TABLETENNIS-LADN     08-22 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TABLETENNIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EXPATRIATES GIVE U.S. MEDAL HOPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former President Richard Nixon mixed table tennis
and politics with his famous ``Pingpong Diplomacy'' tour to China
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first, let's differentiate between pingpong and
table tennis. Better yet, let U.S. Olympic team member David Zhuang
explain it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pingpong is a game, table tennis is a sport,'' said Zhuang,
who represented the U.S. at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and is headed
to the Sydney Games as one of America's top players.
</P>
<P>
   Pingpong is a tranquil way of spending an afternoon in the
garage with a friend or family member. Table tennis is a fast-paced
game of chops (backspin hitting), loops (topspin hitting) and
blocks (a defensive technique against topspin attacks).
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends say, `Oh, you play pingpong, I grew up playing
pingpong. I can beat you,' '' Zhuang said. ``But then they'll see
me playing at my club, and they realize that table tennis is a
whole different sport.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a sport that's been dominated by the Chinese since
table tennis made its Olympic debut at the 1988 Seoul Games. Of the
12 medals awarded since in men's and women's singles and doubles
since 1988, China has won nine golds.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world has a long way to catch up, though the
world's No. 1 men's player, Vladimir Samsonov, is from Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has never medaled in the Olympics, and its best hopes
for Sydney are with Chinese-born athletes who have become U.S.
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Representing China in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, Gao Jun was a
silver medalist in doubles with her partner Chen Zihe.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1992 World Cup doubles tournament in Las Vegas, she met
an American citizen named Frank Chang. They fell in love and were
married in 1993. She was granted citizenship in 1997, but her
release from the Chinese Olympic Committee took more than two years
to be finalized, keeping her out of the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult because I couldn't participate in so
many events,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gao became eligible to represent the U.S. shortly before the
1999 Pan American Games in Winnipeg, Manitoba, and promptly won
gold in singles and helped the Americans to a team gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Now 31, Gao ended 1999 ranked 24th in the world, tops among U.S.
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gao could medal on the men's side,'' said U.S. men's
player Todd Sweeris.
</P>
<P>
   Gao has been a boon to USA Table Tennis. She has worked with
younger players to help the U.S. develop a stronger program.
</P>
<P>
   Now she seeks another Olympic medal representing her new
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard (watching the Atlanta Games on television),''
Gao said. ``I kept hoping and hoping until I was there. Now, I can
go to Sydney. I'm very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BROOKLYN-STADIUM-8     08-22 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BROOKLYN-STADIUM-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI: ECONOMIC REHABILITATION JUSTIFIES OVERRUNS ON CONEY
ISLAND STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Story is also moving on sports wire)  
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's new Coney Island stadium for a
minor-league Mets franchise will cost up to $8 million more than
previous estimates, and the project continues to provoke bitter
sniping between its biggest booster, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and
its most vocal opponent, Howard Golden, the Brooklyn borough
president.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremonial groundbreaking Tuesday on Surf Avenue, where
construction of the 6,500-seat ballpark is well under way in the
shadow of Coney Island's storied parachute drop, Giuliani said the
city would spend as much as $39 million on the project _ more than
25 percent above its previous budget of $31 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani defended the additional cost, saying it was necessary
to ensure completion by the scheduled opening day in June. That
deadline, a year earlier than previously set by the city, means the
Coney Island stadium, like a counterpart on Staten Island, will be
completed before the mayor leaves office at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn stadium has been a longstanding matter of
contention between the mayor and Golden, who for years strenuously
promoted a grander sports and recreation complex for the site. And
Tuesday's ceremony brought them no closer together. Several top
City Hall aides and Guy Molinari, the Staten Island borough
president, joined Giuliani at the ceremony, but Golden was not
invited and did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that the city administration continues to
implement a sweetheart deal that offers little economic benefit to
Brooklyn, but is a windfall to professional baseball,'' Golden said
in a statement released immediately after the event. ``Taxpayers
deserve more for this huge public investment than an outrageous
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coney Island and Staten Island minor-league ballparks, which
are being paid for with more than $100 million in city money, have
been championed by the mayor to foster economic development in the
boroughs outside Manhattan. The Staten Island stadium, budgeted at
$71 million and under construction along the St. George shoreline,
just west of the Staten Island Ferry Terminal, is to be used by a
minor-league franchise of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Staten Island project will be the most expensive
minor-league ballpark in the country, it has caused little upset,
while the battle over the Brooklyn stadium has nettled Golden for
more than a year. He has also maintained that its price is too high
and that the caliber of baseball it will bring, with a Single-A
minor-league franchise, to the home of the Brooklyn Dodgers, is
beneath the dignity of the borough.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Golden was not invited to the event, Giuliani angrily
replied: ``Why wasn't he here? Because he is against this project.
I can't imagine why.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of a 20-year lease between the city and the Mets,
the minor-league franchise will pay up to $520,000 a year, based on
attendance, for use of the stadium. While the current home of the
Mets' minor-league team in Queens sometimes draws fewer than 1,000
fans, the mayor said that he hoped a new stadium would attract
larger crowds, and that if the stadium were at least half full for
each game next year, he would be satisfied. In addition to lease
payments, the city would receive half the advertising revenues that
are generated by the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani also sought to dismiss the points raised by Golden
and other critics who say that the Coney Island project will
provide a windfall for the Mets. Giuliani insisted that it would
lead to sweeping economic development along the neighborhood's
tawdry beachfront and commercial blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark will do for Coney Island what Disney did for
42nd Street,'' Giuliani said, referring to the investment by the
Walt Disney Co., backed by city tax incentives, in a Times Square
theater and store in the early 1990s. He said the city would prompt
further Coney Island development by paying for a Little League
field close to the new stadium, for repairs on the rusting
framework of the parachute drop, and for incentives to lure new
stores to the quarter-mile stretch of Surf Avenue between the
stadium site and the historic Nathan's hot dog emporium.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani declined to say which of those projects, if any,
would be completed before he left office.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Michael Carey, the president of the city's
Economic Development Corp., which is in charge of the stadium
projects, said that the cost of the Coney Island field had grown
because advancing its deadline meant bringing in more workers and
materials at a time when both are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   He said the city and the Mets had agreed to seek a corporate
sponsor for the stadium, embracing a model of corporate support
established by several professional sports organizations around the
nation as well as on Staten Island. Although no such sponsor has
been found, Carey said he expected a company to pay for the right
to include its name in that of the new Coney Island stadium, and
that the arrangement would probably yield as much income as the
$400,000 a year that the Richmond County Bank has agreed to pay to
have the field in St. George named the Richmond County Bank
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Carey also said that the city and the Mets would select a name
for the minor-league team from ideas submitted by the public.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One suggestion was made immediately Tuesday at the ceremony by
Joan Hodges, the widow of Gil Hodges, the former Brooklyn Dodger
first baseman and Mets manager. ``I respectfully submit the name of
Gil Hodges,'' said Hodges, whose presence was apparently intended
by City hall to evoke the splendor of professional baseball in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who followed Hodges to the microphone, was effusive in
his praise of her husband, who died in 1972, but stopped short of
seconding her nomination. Without referring to the naming process
of Coney Island's new club, he said that Gil Hodges ``truly
deserves to be in the Hall of Fame,'' an honor not yet bestowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0407 </DOCNO>
