<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HOLLYWOOD-POSTMARK-LA     08-22 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-POSTMARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S MOST FAMOUS NEIGHBORHOOD GETS STAMP OF APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood hasn't had a cancellation like this
since ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States Postal Service is earning raves for giving
Tinseltown its own postmark, or rather, giving much of L.A. a
Hollywood postmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted. I've always felt that the most famous community
in the world should have its own postmark,'' said Johnny Grant,
honorary mayor of Hollywood. ``We haven't had one in about 52
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant expended a considerable amount of shoe leather trying to
convince the Postal Service, which is more fond of lumping places
together, to recognize the entertainment capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The marking, approved by the service's L.A. District Manager Al
Iniguez, will read, ``Los Angeles/Hollywood, CA'' with a cluster of
five stars and an overlay reading, ``Home of the Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite unique,'' said Larry Dozier, spokesman for the
Postal Service in Los Angeles. ``Many cities and neighborhoods have
requested their own postmark'' but residents of those places
usually have to be content with a postmark named after the big
sorting facility the mail goes to after it leaves their local post
office.
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley mail usually is postmarked ``Santa
Clarita,'' the sorting facility where Valley mail is sent.
Residents of Beverly Hills, 90210, and most coastal communities get
a ``Marina del Rey'' postmark.
</P>
<P>
   But after Thursday's unveiling ceremony at the Roosevelt Hotel
on Hollywood Boulevard (``It's in Los Angeles,'' said a directory
assistance operator), mail from all ZIP codes beginning with 900
will get the new LA/Hollywood postmark. That, of course, will
include Hollywood's 90028 code, Dozier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious to us that the federal government and the U.S.
postmaster realize that Hollywood exists and it's leading the way
to cityhood,'' proclaimed Gene La Pietra, founder of the movement
to separate Hollywood from the city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was pleased with the new postmark, he said it
wouldn't be enough to stop the secession movement.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist of the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp., said the new mark would help promote business
all over the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a cute thing. `Hollywood' definitely has some
zip.''
</P>
<P>
   x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000822.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-22 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9582 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MISS-DEAF-AMERICA-LAD     08-22 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-DEAF-AMERICA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST MISS DEAF AMERICA HAS PASSION FOR PRINTED WORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRENT HOPKINS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To win the Miss Deaf America crown, Lauren Teruel
drew on her lifelong passion: reading.
</P>
<P>
   The California State University, Northridge, graduate won the
coveted crown from a field of 25 national competitors after
translating into American Sign Language a book from her childhood,
Shel Silverstein's ``The Giving Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to read me a different story every night,'' she
said Tuesday through an interpreter. ``And I mean literally every
night. He'd sit down and sign it to me, making sure I understood.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the 22-year-old Teruel is scheduled to make her
first local appearance since winning the Miss Deaf America title
last month. She'll present ``The Giving Tree'' to children during
Sign Language Story Time at Borders Books and Music in Northridge,
not far from her alma mater in the suburban San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to serve as an example of how the hearing-impaired can
succeed in any situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show the older generation in the deaf community that
they're leaving things in good hands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teruel graduated in May from CSUN with a degree in English. She
now works at the school's National Center on Deafness in a program
to improve post-secondary school education for the
hearing-impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NCOD opened in 1962, CSUN has been a magnet for deaf
and hard-of-hearing students, drawn to its educational outreach for
the hearing-impaired. Through the work of NCOD, the university has
grown to be the pre-eminent mainstream institute of higher learning
in the country, offering services to nearly 300 students, according
to Nina Treiman, a counselor at NCOD.
</P>
<P>
   While studying there, Teruel made use of both a sign language
interpreter and a closed captioner, as well Internet chat rooms to
interact with her classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning Miss Deaf America's vivacious personality leaves a
lasting impression on those who cross her path. Treiman remembers
fondly how Teruel stood out from the rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We draw some of the best and brightest students from all over
the country, and Lauren was definitely one of them,'' Treiman
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   While she was studying at CSUN, Teruel first became interested
in the pageant. She attended the National Association of the Deaf's
1998 conference as a member of CSUN's College Bowl team, and
watched another Northridge alumna, Amy Wong, win the crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired a woman who could stand up in front of a crowd like
that with so much poise,'' Teruel said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she entered a preliminary competition, and won the
Miss Deaf Illinois title in her native Chicago. From there, she set
her sights on going all the way. To do so, she had to perfectly
polish herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women are judged across a broad spectrum of categories
including community service, academics, current events, knowledge
of deaf culture and more,'' said Jennifer Yost, youth programs
coordinator for the NAD.
</P>
<P>
   After securing the crown in a July 8 ceremony held in Norfolk,
Va., Teruel plans to continue her work at NCOD. She also hopes to
apply to graduate school to study new media in the coming year and
continue her writing and endeavors in performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
